<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DIPLOMATIC PRINCIPLES FOR KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, April 8:
</P>
<P>
   As Serbian forces continue to advance across Kosovo in a brutal
campaign of ethnic cleansing, talking about the terms of a
political settlement may seem premature. But with diplomatic
activity stirring and NATO's air strikes starting to undercut
Slobodan Milosevic's military base, it is not too early for the
Clinton administration to start thinking about the broad shape of
an acceptable peace deal. President Clinton has led the way this
week by forcefully enunciating some core principles that are likely
to be at the center of discussions between the United States,
Russia and other nations now pursuing a diplomatic track.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's idea of a reasonable resolution is deformed but
cunning. In recent days Belgrade has tried to create the illusion
that the conflict is winding down by saying that refugees can
return safely to their homes, that Serbia can work with ethnic
Albanian leaders to develop their own plan for political autonomy
in Kosovo and that three captured American soldiers may soon be
freed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO cannot accept on trust such Serbian assurances. It must, as
Clinton has said, aim for an outcome that effectively insures the
security of Kosovo, shields the resettlement of the hundreds of
thousands of ethnic Albanians who have been evicted and guarantees
a high degree of autonomy for Kosovo. Montenegro, another part of
Yugoslavia, should also be assured that its autonomy and democratic
government will not become the next target of Serbian aggression.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely how those objectives can be achieved will depend in
large part on how much damage NATO can inflict on the Serbian
military before a cease-fire is put in place. The greater the
damage, the more leverage NATO will have in negotiations. Given the
uncertainties on the military front, it would be unwise for
Washington and its allies to spell out a detailed peace plan in
advance of negotiations. If Russia is to play a productive role in
ending the conflict, something the White House is now wisely
encouraging, Clinton will have to persuade Moscow to accept NATO's
conditions, or a close approximation.
</P>
<P>
   With his murderous assault on Kosovo, Milosevic has shown that
in the future Kosovo should be democratically self-governed and
free of Serbian intimidation. But it ought not to be an independent
country. Though many of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians might prefer
outright independence, the creation by NATO of a sovereign nation
in Kosovo would invite further conflict there by humiliating the
Serbs. It would also create an unrealistic and potentially
dangerous model for resolving ethnic disputes elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Whether autonomy comes through partition, the creation of a NATO
or United Nations protectorate or some other arrangement remains
uncertain. But it is abundantly clear that a substantial
international peacekeeping force will be needed to insure that
autonomy is preserved and Serbian forces cannot again terrorize the
people of Kosovo. To make such a force more acceptable to Serbia,
it ought to include Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian political and military leaders should be held
accountable in some fashion for the killing they sanctioned in
Kosovo. If international investigators confirm refugee accounts
that Serbian forces have executed thousands of ethnic Albanians,
the men responsible for these atrocities should be indicted by the
war crimes tribunal in The Hague and eventually brought to justice.
The Serbian government should help pay for the reconstruction of
villages burned by Milosevic's forces. This war may not end any
time soon, but when it does, Serbia must give up its destructive
role in the Balkans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
