<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-WATERSHED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: POLITICS AND THE WATERSHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, April 8:
</P>
<P>
   There is no higher environmental priority for New York City than
protection of the watershed around the upstate reservoirs that
supply 10 million people with high-quality drinking water at
remarkably low prices. But in recent months there have been
disturbing signs that the city's devotion to this vital task is not
as strong as it ought to be. There have also been charges from the
environmental community that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has allowed his
statewide political ambitions to compromise his commitment to
watershed protection.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's people insist that his interest has not wavered, and
we hope they are right. Whatever happens to him politically,
Giuliani will surely not want to be remembered as the mayor who
betrayed a historic opportunity to preserve one of the city's great
assets. Nor will he wish to be remembered as the mayor whose
inattentiveness or ambition saddled the taxpayers with a $6 billion
filtration plant that the city will be required to build if it does
not keep the watershed clean.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one recent decision is profoundly suspicious. Late last year
a deputy commissioner of the city's Department of Environmental
Protection, Dr. William Stasiuk, asked the Army Corps of Engineers
to help the city prevent development on thousands of acres of small
wetlands that are vital to the health of the watershed. After
various upstate officials and developers complained, Stasiuk's
boss, Commissioner Joel Miele, withdrew the request, saying that
the watershed needed no special protections. His decision
astonished the Corps and the Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Miele says that politics was not involved and that his
department has sufficient powers to protect small wetlands. But his
and the state's authority over wetlands under 12.4 acres is very
shaky. Only the Corps can block the destruction of these smaller
wetlands, where a lot of development and damage to the watershed
actually occurs.
</P>
<P>
   A historic 1997 agreement to save the watershed empowered the
city to regulate its development. In exchange the city had to
provide funds to upgrade sewage treatment plants in the watershed,
repair many of the region's 128,000 septic tanks, acquire thousands
of acres for buffer zones around the reservoirs and underwrite
innovative conservation programs. There has been progress on many
fronts.
</P>
<P>
   But there have also been glitches. The EPA was distressed to
learn last fall that the city had allowed developers to build
septic tanks on steeply sloping hills, contrary to its own rules.
An environmental group, the Natural Resources Defense Council, has
accused the city of not moving aggressively enough to protect the
Kensico Reservoir, a vital basin near White Plains that funnels 90
percent of the water from upstate to the city. Now comes the city's
rebuff to the Corps of Engineers on the wetlands question. If these
concessions keep adding up, the watershed could be lost, and with
it a legacy that Giuliani should be proud to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
