<SLUG> BC-NY-POLITE-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI AND SAFIR TRY TO PUSH POLITENESS CARDS AT A ROLL-CALL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard
Safir went to a roll call at a Harlem station house Wednesday
morning to bring their campaign for a more polite police force to
officers on the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   As a platoon of officers from the 32nd Precinct stood at
attention at 7 a.m., the mayor and the police commissioner
explained their plan to try to improve relations between the police
and the public, which have been strained since the fatal shooting
of Amadou Diallo on Feb. 4. Under the initiative, all officers are
being given wallet-sized cue cards reminding them to call people
``Sir'' or ``Ma'am,'' and to say ``Hello'' and ``Thank You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not meant to insult you; it's not meant to tell you that
you don't know how to say `Sir' or `Ma'am' and to say, `Thank
you,''' Safir said. He said the cards would remind officers that
``as you're doing your job and a lot of things are going on and
people are losing their heads, you need to keep yours.''
</P>
<P>
   The police officers listened politely, in the way that members
of paramilitary organizations are obliged to listen when their
commanders speak: They stood at attention, ramrod straight with
chins up, shoes polished to a shine.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that the plan was a simple one. ``I think on
purpose it's a very, very transparent campaign,'' he told the
officers. ``We want you to go the extra mile to act nicer; we want
you to go the extra mile to act more respectful. Go out of your way
so people can see that. Because we want to get them to do the same
thing with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the cards _ much like the ones officers now get to
remind them of the Miranda warnings _ has not exactly been popular
with officers on the beat. Interviews with a half-dozen officers
yielded polite, but off-the-record, criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has got to carry a card to deal with the public
shouldn't be on the job,'' said one Brooklyn detective with 18
years of experience. ``You've got to give respect to get respect.''
</P>
<P>
   A police officer in Manhattan joked about the new insistence on
honorific titles: ``You mean I can't say, `Hey mope, get over here'
anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor's and the police commissioner's visit to the
station house had another purpose: to heighten the department's
morale, which has sagged in the two months since the shooting of
Diallo led to intense scrutiny _ and criticism _ of the Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the job of the mayor is described as the second
toughest job in America,'' Giuliani told them. ``It isn't. In fact,
your job is more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor told the officers that when he had to make a decision,
he usually had the luxury of time and a team of advisers to help
him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can think about it,'' he said. ``I can reflect on it. But
even with all that, as you read in the newspapers, a fair number of
times I make the wrong decision. You've got to make decisions on
the spur of the moment and it's difficult. And very, very often
it's under circumstances that most people don't have to face in
their entire lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the mayor, the police commissioner and the assembled
commanders left the small muster room to the more routine aspects
of a morning roll call. A lieutenant took attendance and gave the
officers their daily instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Then the officers were sent out to pick up their radios and hit
the streets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
