<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT SAYS HE'S `FINE' WITH BEING BENCHED TUESDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ If it hadn't already happened twice to Shaquille
O'Neal, it might have been a surprise to see Kobe Bryant lifted in
the fourth quarter of a close game Tuesday night. But Los Angeles
Lakers coach Kurt Rambis is showing no hesitancy to remove his
stars if it's the right move, and in this case, Bryant knew exactly
why he was called to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz forward Shandon Anderson, Bryant's defensive assignment,
had just rattled off three layups while Bryant strayed from the
game plan. The Lakers fell to a double-digit deficit and then a
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple bad decisions, bad judgment on my part and a couple
of other players,'' Bryant said Wednesday. ``I just made a couple
mistakes, and that's it. They were huge mistakes. It's good to get
them out of the way now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Bryant was the only culprit, and not that those were
his only mistakes. The coach also pulled him in the first half
after Bryant got a little out of control on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine with it,'' Bryant said. ``I told Kurt, I continuously
tell him, `I'm with you. Whatever decision you want to make, I'm
with you.' Obviously, I don't like being taken out of games at any
point, because you always wanna play. But I'm always with Kurt
whatever he wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rambis doesn't bother lecturing Bryant on why he pulled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Bryant said sheepishly, ``he pretty much knows that I
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Ty's time?: Tyronn Lue thrilled the Lakers faithful and
teammates alike with his 12-point debut against Utah, but Rambis
won't say yet if the rookie point guard will have a continuing role
in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens,'' Rambis said. ``I didn't do it (play
Lue) for any other reason than a feel-thing, pick up the tempo a
little bit and see how the game goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lue ended up playing 23 minutes, more than starter Derek Harper
or ailing backup Derek Fisher. That wasn't necessarily the plan,
but Rambis said he planned to play Lue even before Fisher's knee
tendinitis flared up and sidelined him.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, for one, wouldn't mind a regular dose of Lue in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not? The more he plays, the more his confidence is gonna
go up and the better he's gonna play,'' Bryant said. And his play
Tuesday? ``Loved it, loved it, loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Fisher recovered from his tendinitis Wednesday and
played the majority of the first half in relief of Harper against
Sacramento.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
