A0139 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-POW-LADN     04-08 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-POW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE LIFTS POW'S EX-NEIGHBORS, FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY YVETTE CABRERA AND LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After seven anguish-filled days since Serbians
captured her son, Vivian Ramirez clung to a message of hope
Wednesday that he could be freed shortly with two other American
POWs.
</P>
<P>
   Word that the acting president of Cyprus could win the soldiers'
release as soon as today raced through Ramirez's East Los Angeles
neighborhood, as hundreds added signed cards to the growing tribute
of yellow flowers, candles and balloons outside his home.
</P>
<P>
   With the possibility that her son, Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez,
could be released soon, Vivian Ramirez prepared to fly to Cyprus to
meet him. Still, she expressed cautious optimism that the days of
prayer might be over for her and for the mothers of Spc. Steven M.
Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas; and Staff Sgt. Christopher J.
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a mother, I can only share with you the deep concern I have
not only for my son, but the other two mothers and how they feel
about their sons as well,'' Vivian Ramirez said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely hopeful the negotiations will begin immediately
and the entire world will join in praying for peace and the release
of our POWs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Defense and the U.S. Army were ready to escort
Ramirez's mother to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's actually in very good spirits,'' said Dina
Tank-Schoettlin, an aide to Bob Archuleta, Los Angeles County
commissioner for military and veteran affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's hopeful that she'll be joining Andrew soon. She
expressed her deep gratitude to the nation for not forgetting the
POWs.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Ramirez family and concerned strangers alike
gathered outside the East Los Angeles home to offer their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a mother, I understand how hard it must be and I wouldn't
wish this on my worst enemy,'' said Leticia Mendoza, a Montebello
resident who last year moved away from Andrew Ramirez's block, but
returned Wednesday to try to talk to the family. ``We're with them
in spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Ramirez's cousin, Olivia Rodriguez, said the family
understands the obstacles that stand in the way of a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully the president will do what he's capable of doing.
But he's dealing with unrealistic people. The people you're dealing
with are the same ones exiling their own people,'' Rodriguez said
from the family's St. Alphonsus Church in East Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said President Clinton called the soldier's mother,
Vivian Ramirez on Easter to console her. Vice President Al Gore
called Ramirez on Tuesday to wish her well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave her optimism that (Andy's) going to return ...
Basically, he told her to hold on and to have faith and continue
her prayers,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the sergeant's parents are in contact with Pentagon
officials and are on standby to travel to Germany. If efforts
succeed, that's where they would meet their son, who would travel
through the Mediterranean island nation of Cyprus upon his release,
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, family members keep updated with the latest news
reports, poring over newspapers, checking the Internet and flipping
through TV channels for newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just waiting to see if it's true,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad Perez Garcia, who once baby-sat Andrew Ramirez when he
was a youngster, said she was saddened by the news of his capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God that soon all of this will be resolved,'' said Perez
Garcia, who tied a yellow ribbon and U.S. flag to her front porch.
``I go to Mass and pray to God for him and his family because we're
all family.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Rios, a longtime Ramirez family friend, said she plans to
organize the neighborhood's first block party when Ramirez is
released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been just heartbroken and very worried because he's so
far away, and how do we know that he has not been mistreated?''
said Rios, who was pleased to learn of his possible release. ``It's
good news, but at the same time ... I won't believe it until I see
it. We've never had a block party before, but it will be the first
and hopefully the biggest.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
