<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS STILL RATTLED BY BRUSHBACK PITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson doesn't
know what the Arizona Diamondbacks' beef is with the pitch Chan Ho
Park threw Tuesday behind Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona right-hander Todd Stottlemyre, who opposed Park, was
lamenting on his decision not to bean any of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day after the benches cleared in Tuesday's sixth
inning, but nothing had calmed down. In fact, Stottlemyre talked
about a sleepless night he experienced after not brushing back, or
plunking, one of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to look in Matt Williams' eyes,'' Stottlemyre said
before the teams completed their three-game series Wednesday. ``It
still keeps me up all night. These are the guys, in the locker
room, you go to war with, they become part of your family. What
upsets me is you have a decision to make and you have to be real
responsible for the decision you make, and what keeps you up all
night is, does Matt Williams know I'm going to get his back.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams homered earlier in the game, then hit a long foul ball
off Park. The next pitched sailed behind Williams, but Park
maintained it was unintentional. Johnson, as expected, backed up
his pitcher, saying there was no reason to hit a batter late in a
tie game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Diamondbacks are emphatic in their belief that the pitch
was thrown with purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Park) can say it slipped,'' Stottlemyre said. ``I just know I
never threw a ball behind a person when I wasn't trying to. What
kills me is Davey said we shouldn't take it that way. I guess we
should take our (butt) kickin' and like it.... We took it
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson also said the incident may not be over, especially
since the teams meet Monday in Phoenix to begin a four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything to retaliate,'' Johnson said.
``If they blatantly try to drill one of my guys, I don't think our
guys are going to react to that with kid gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Speaking of beanballs: &UR; !off! &LR;  While he was on the topic
of brushback pitches and the such, Johnson talked about former
Dodgers right-hander Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The all-time head-hunter is now in Boston. Pedro Martinez,''
Johnson said. ``He was the worst. He had a no-hitter in Montreal
and hit Reggie (Sanders) twice. It wasn't with leg shots, it was
high up.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!HR king's anniversary: &UR; !off! &LR;  It was 25 years ago tonight
Hank Aaron hit his 715th career homer off L.A.'s Al Downing to
break Babe Ruth's home run record. Johnson was Aaron's teammate on
the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the memories I have are of the man, not so much the
event,'' Johnson said. ``Once you got to know him, you just knew it
was inevitable. When he wanted it to happen, it was going to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what a great individual. All through it, he did everything
he could to lessen the media hype because he didn't want it to
affect the team. He was adamant about that the whole time, that it
was an individual accomplishment, but what was important is the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Johnson was also a teammate of Sadaharu Oh with the
Yomiuri Giants when Oh hit his 715th career homer.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Extra innings: &UR; !off! &LR;  Todd Hundley caught his third
straight game, but was moved from second to fifth in the Dodgers
lineup while Devon White was moved from fifth to second. Hundley
was 1 for his first 10 at the plate, and Johnson said Paul Lo Duca
will make his first start of the season today.... Right-hander
Antonio Osuna (right elbow soreness) will begin a rehab assignment
with Single-A San Bernardino on Saturday against Lake Elsinore....
The Dodgers had six stolen bases in seven attempts through their
first two games. They recorded their sixth stolen base last year in
their sixth game. &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
