<SLUG> BC-MILK-PRICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILK PRICES DECLINE AS GROCERY CHAINS PASS ALONG SAVINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Even as gasoline prices soar, the cost of one
semiprecious fluid has dropped dramatically this week.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a state-mandated cut in prices charged by California
dairies, the retail price for a gallon of milk has fallen by about
50 cents at the state's largest grocery chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just reflects the price decrease we're getting from
suppliers,'' Terry O'Neil, a spokesman for Ralphs Grocery Co., said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ralphs has reduced the price of its milk by 50 cents per gallon
across the board, O'Neil said. At Lucky stores, prices have dropped
between 35 cents and 55 cents per gallon, with whole milk
experiencing the biggest decline to $3.44 per gallon. A Vons
spokesman said his chain has cut prices by up to 57 cents per
gallon, with a half-gallon of whole milk currently on sale for 99
cents.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread cuts originated with the state Department of Food
and Agriculture, which April 1 trimmed a record 50 cents per gallon
off the regulated minimum paid to state dairy farmers -- from $1.71
per gallon to $1.21 per gallon. Department officials cited a
nationwide increase in the supply of milk for the drop.
</P>
<P>
   While the state intervened to reduce wholesale prices, it's up
to retailers to pass on the savings to consumers. And for the most
part, that appears to be happening. Even smaller mom-and-pop stores
have cut prices. At Dale's Junior Store in Sherman Oaks, for
example, manager Don Plautz said the market has cut its price for
one gallon of whole milk by 40 cents to $3.59.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it awesome?'' said Myrlys Williams, a spokeswoman for
the California Department of Food and Agriculture. While prices
typically drop in early spring, the current decline is the biggest
in the state's history, Williams said. ``And we owe it all to the
very kind-hearted and gracious retailers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   California, the nation's biggest milk producer, also has the
most expensive milk, which critics blame on a combination of state
price regulations, higher quality standards and alleged gouging by
big grocery chains. State agricultural officials and dairy farmers
counter that the price is higher because state law requires milk to
be fortified with vitamins, driving up costs.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the high cost of California milk is a separate state
law that mandates that the product can't be sold for less than it
cost to produce. In other states, retailers often sell milk as a
``loss leader,'' hoping it will draw in shoppers who end up buying
other groceries. A state senator from San Francisco recently
introduced a bill in the Legislature that would allow retailers to
sell milk below what it cost to make.
</P>
<P>
   Mad About Milk, a group of out-of-state dairies lobbying for
access to the California market, claims that because of
protectionist barriers against milk imports, California consumers
pay $650 million more per year than their counterparts in
neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
   The group is trying to get state lawmakers to lower California's
standards for milk to meet the U.S. Food and Drug Administration
nutritional guidelines used by the country's 49 other states.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
