<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH VAUGHN OUT, WHO'S ON FIRST?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn's tumble into the Cleveland Indians'
dugout Tuesday left the Anaheim Angels' $80-million first baseman
limping on a sprained left ankle, forcing some shifts in the Angels
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad, who did not play a single inning at first base
during spring training, started Wednesday night in Vaughn's place.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Palmeiro gave up his seat on the bench to play Erstad's
spot in left field and bat leadoff. Erstad last played first base
during the final week of last season against the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like riding a bike. You don't forget,'' Collins said of
Erstad. ``I watched him take ground balls today. He'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad wasn't so sure about how he'd do after being away from
first. ``I don't know ... we'll find out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Railing removed: The Indians offered no help for Vaughn as he
approached the top of the dugout steps. He never looked down to see
where he was for fear of losing sight of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame anybody in that situation,'' Vaughn said. ``It's
my responsibility to take care of myself.
</P>
<P>
   When Anaheim Stadium was renovated and became Edison Field in
1997, the dugouts initially had railing about three feet high with
netting, separating the playing field from the dugout. But manager
Terry Collins asked that the railing be removed because ``I didn't
like 'em. But I never felt we were going to have an $80 million
first baseman either.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoulder worries Edmonds: Center fielder Jim Edmonds plans to be
ready to come off the disabled list when he's eligible Wednesday.
His biggest problem now is not the strained groin, but the cyst
buried in the muscle of his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds has had a sore shoulder going back to last season, but
he aggravated the condition lifting weights last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like if Gary (DiSarcina) didn't show up to spring
training early, he'd be in the lineup right now,'' Edmonds said.
``And if I had a lazy Saturday afternoon and didn't work out, I'd
be in the lineup. (Stuff) happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds said it hasn't been determined if he'll have the cyst
drained or will allow it to heal on its own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0145 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--Astros-Cubs-HNS &LR;      04-08 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Cubs-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Control belongs to Cubs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The Astros never got the fuse lit on their explosive offense, and
the pitching staff was a time bomb waiting to detonate.
</P>
<P>
   The undesirable combination of poor pitching and scarce hitting
caused the Astros to implode en route to a 9-2 loss against the
Chicago Cubs on Wednesday night at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd all like to think we could get everything out of our
system and it only cost us one loss in the standings,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said. ``Hopefully, we'll find out (today)
that it really is out of our system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly had enough things go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of it occurring on the pitcher's mound, where the Astros
issued nine walks and hit two batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the hardest thing to watch,'' Dierker said. ``It's
frustrating when you don't even give your fielders a chance. The
two things you can't defend are walks and home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Starter Mike Hampton avoided the home-run portion of that
equation; not so the walks. Hampton struggled with his location,
walking five batters in a brief 3-inning stint that forced an early
appearance by the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``My (pitches) were moving like I wanted them to, but my
location just wasn't there, and I never got into a rhythm,'' said
Hampton, who allowed seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just disappointed that I put us in a hole so early and put
our backs against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros trailed 4-1 when Hampton left, and it was painfully
obvious the offense was not in the comeback mode that defined the
team's success in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs starter Kevin Tapani had quite a bit to do with the
inefficiency Wednesday, holding the Astros to four hits in six
innings. Tapani, who won 19 games in 1998, got plenty of support
from his offense, which banged out 12 hits _ five for extra bases.
</P>
<P>
   Astros killer Glenallen Hill had four RBIs and Mickey Morandini
had three despite sitting out the first four innings in favor of
Jeff Blauser, who started at second base.
</P>
<P>
   The first five hitters in the Cubs lineup produced eight of the
12 hits and drove in all nine runs. The Astros scratched out five
hits _ none coming from the top three spots in the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those games where Tapani was on and we were
off,'' said Astros right fielder Derek Bell, who hits second _
sandwiched between Craig Biggio and Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Tapani was stingy with the hits, but he did give the Astros a
few breaks, walking five batters in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, you can't get away with that kind of stuff,'' Tapani
said. ``I was hoping to get out of there before they did get to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took a 1-0 lead in the second inning on a single by
rookie catcher Mitch Meluskey, who collected his first career RBI.
Richard Hidalgo and Bill Spiers also had hits for the Astros in the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Little did they know that would represent 60 percent of their
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of (the second) inning, we never put
anything together,'' Spiers said. ``You usually don't see a pitcher
be on like Tapani was this early in the season, but he was. Any
time you don't put any hits together, you know the pitcher is on.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (0-1) struck out three of the first nine batters he
faced, but the Cubs struck back in the third inning, scoring three
runs on five hits, two on a single by Hill. Sammy Sosa had a RBI
double in the inning on his first hit of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs pushed the lead to 4-1 in the fourth when Tapani scored
on Mark Grace's sacrifice fly. Hampton issued three walks in the
inning, the last of them prompting Dierker to summon Brian Williams
from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs were 1-for-9 against Hampton on their first trip
through the order and 6-for-13 in their subsequent at-bats against
the Astros lefthander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you one thing,'' Hampton said. ``I've got to challenge
the hitters a lot more than I did. I've got to take it to them
rather than letting them take it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams bailed Hampton out of trouble in the fourth but created
a bit of chaos in the fifth when he hit two batters, threw a wild
pitch and issued a walk. Williams managed to limit the damage to
one run; Benito Santiago scored when Williams hit Morandini with
the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``My adrenalin was flowing,'' Williams said. ``The thing that
frustrated me was hitting the guy after I had got ahead in the
count. I got a little upset with myself after that, but I still
feel like I kept us in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros pulled within three in the fifth when Bell scored on
a two-out single by Carl Everett. But it was only a tease. The Cubs
scored two runs in each of the last two innings, courtesy of a
two-run homer by Hill and a two-run triple by Morandini.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who feasts on Astros pitching, put the game out of reach
with his blast off reliever Doug Henry. Hill has a .299 career
batting average with nine homers and 28 RBIs against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Henry's conclusion: ``It was just an ugly game all around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
