<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0146 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-COLUMN-HNS     04-08 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Nothing to salvage from Astros debacle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now that the stadium formerly known as the Ballpark at Union
Station has a new name _ Enron Field _ sooner or later we're going
to have to change the Killer B's nickname to something more
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it will be the Gashouse Gang _ Y2K version.
</P>
<P>
   But after Wednesday night's 9-2 Astros debacle at the hands of
the free-swinging Chicago Cubs, obviously it's going to have to be
later. By any name, this one stunk.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it was one night. Just one night out of 162.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night the Astros surely will be able to forget, and
apparently many fans forgot even before the first pitch was thrown
_ just 23,381 fans showed up after the 51,000-plus crowd of opening
night.
</P>
<P>
   But the B's, the Astros pitching and the game were anything but
a gas, gas, gas, unless you count the kind that usually begins with
all-you-can-eat hot wings and ends with plop-plop, fizz-fizz.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those games,'' said Astros second-baseman Craig Biggio,
who was hitless for the second day in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to talk about anything negative,'' outfielder
Derek Bell said, pausing long after making that pledge as if
searching for something good to cull from the night.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's silence was perhaps the best thing you could say about
this sluggish, sloppy night, on which the B's went 0-for-10,
starter Mike Hampton struggled to find the plate, and the Cubs
played wall ball from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   A purging performance
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us would like to think we can get everything
out of our system and only take one loss from it,'' Astros skipper
Larry Dierker said. ``We got a lot of bad things out of our system
tonight. It was an off night.''
</P>
<P>
   On the hill, Astros pitchers walked nine batters and hit a pair,
including Mickey Morandini by Brian Williams in the fifth inning to
bring in a run.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton never found the plate, and relievers Williams and Doug
Henry were not nearly as sharp as they showed in the spring. The
only 1-2-3 inning for Astros pitchers came in the seventh, after
the Cubs already had comfortable control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't even give your fielders a chance when you walk that
many,'' Dierker said. ``Compared to last night, it was a dull
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was at the plate where the usually dependable Astros
bats went silent against Cubs starter Kevin Tapani.
</P>
<P>
   The best dribblers in the house proved to be not the various San
Antonio Spurs and Rockets players who showed up for Wednesday's
game, but the Astros batters. For the second night in a row, the
best Astros offense came only from the players with the most to
prove _ Carl Everett, Richard Hidalgo and rookie Mitch Meluskey.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the ball just dribbled off Astros bats. The Killer
B's were not in midseason form, or even preseason form. It was more
like postseason form, like a cross between Atlanta two seasons ago
and San Diego last year.
</P>
<P>
   Counting Tuesday night, the B's now are 2-for-21.
</P>
<P>
   Two out of three are bad
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a lot of guys on base and took advantage, and we
didn't swing the bats very well,'' Biggio said. ``We didn't do two
of the three most important aspects of the game. Hitting and
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   And really, Astros fielding got the gold star on this night only
by default.
</P>
<P>
   The scorebook said the Astros committed only one error, an
eventual two-run blunder by Ricky Gutierrez in the ninth. But all
night there were plays that on most nights, normal nights, the
Astros would have made.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo sailed a throw to the plate trying to throw out Sammy
Sosa that not even David Robinson, seated behind home plate, could
have reached.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell could have saved at least one run with a tailor-made
double-play line drive by the Cubs' Mark Grace, but could not
convert. Bagwell later ho-hummed a grounder down the first-base
line that looked foul, but was called fair and wound up being a
two-run triple by Morandini.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have games like that,'' Bell said. ``Tapani
was on and we were off.''
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed panicked over it all and, really, why should they?
It's a long season, another title could be on the way and a year
from now at the Gashouse, when the gang is slamming doubles and
triples all over the place, Wednesday night's misery will be a
distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   But it was indeed miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad night,'' Dierker said. ``Just throw it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
