<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-INMATES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN FELONS GET RICH ON PAPER WITH INVESTING GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time for the Stock Market Game at Black Canyon School, and
student teacher Charlotte Scott is prodding students to put some
thought into their picks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of buying stocks just because they went up the day
before, she suggests they zero in on hot trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss, we haven't been out in a while,'' piped up 16-year-old
Janie. ``I don't know what's popular.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules are a little different when teenage criminals play the
popular investing game.
</P>
<P>
   Black Canyon is a juvenile detention center in north Phoenix, a
last resort for judges who run out of patience and options for the
most troubled kids.
</P>
<P>
   Janie, who's from Mesa, has been here for 11 months for
violation of probation and drug abuse. She sits next to Melissa, a
16-year-old from Phoenix in the third month of her second stint,
this time for violating parole.
</P>
<P>
   They are on one of two Black Canyon teams playing the game, in a
class not called economics or math, but life management. The game's
been played in tough places before, schools in gang havens and
slums, but this is believed to be the first instance of players who
must be escorted to class and locked up at night.
</P>
<P>
   The streets most of these kids grew up on couldn't be farther
from Wall Street, but they've mastered the game on their first try.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the Black Canyon School boys' team had the
fattest portfolio of the 835 teams in the state. The team still is
in the running to win its division, ranking second after seven
weeks. The girls' team is poised to place in its division, sitting
in fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so excited,'' said Toni Erman, the Black Canyon
teacher who brought the game to campus and directs the winning
teams.
</P>
<P>
   There are already plans for a party if the students prevail,
with David Gaspar, director of the Arizona Department of Juvenile
Corrections, on the guest list and non-institutional food on the
menu. The students won't be able to go to the official awards party
at Ed Debevic's diner in Phoenix because they can't leave Black
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Erman heard about the Stock Market Game a couple years ago and
waded through the state bureaucracy to get the OK to play it at the
school because she thought it would teach valuable lessons to the
troubled kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're figuring out they can earn money in an honest way,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids resisted, arguing they could earn more selling drugs,
but many have come to like the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's risky _ and they like risk,'' Erman said.
</P>
<P>
   That the boys have turned $100,000 into $151,000, the girls into
$141,960 _ 51 percent and 42 percent returns, respectively, in
seven weeks _ would seem to suggest some stockpicking secrets, but
the inmates play the game much like other students.
</P>
<P>
   The goal: gun for gains. The competition, which uses play money,
lasts 10 weeks, so the emphasis is on quick hits, not long-term
successes.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy, one of the boys' first picks, wasn't moving up, so they
quickly dumped it.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year or so, the way to riches in the national game
has been Internet stocks, which often move more in a day than most
stocks move in a year.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper article tacked to a bulletin board in Erman's
classroom talks about how Yahoo!, America Online and other ``.com''
wonders propelled students to the top places in last fall's contest
in Arizona. So that's where the Black Canyon kids _ who share one
computer with Internet access, outside Erman's classroom _ started.
</P>
<P>
   The boys' and girls' teams each bought Amazon.com, AOL and
Yahoo!.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just all looked at what was going up. We just went from
there,'' said Brian, a lanky 17-year-old from Tucson who's been at
Black Canyon for three months for violating parole and possessing
drug paraphernalia. He dropped out of high school in 10th grade for
``lack of interest'' but is due to take the high-school equivalency
exam later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Brian is one of the team leaders, taking charge along with Karl,
a 17-year-old who used to attend Alchesay High School on the Fort
Apache Indian Reservation in Whiteriver, the school where Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar served as volunteer assistant basketball coach this
past season. Karl was sent to Black Canyon two months ago for
cocaine possession.
</P>
<P>
   Brian slides into the desk by Erman's desk the second he enters
the classroom, flipping open the newspaper's business pages to the
stock tables. He and Karl, a husky teen with a buzz cut, search the
listings for the team's stocks, not sure whether they're traded on
the New York Stock Exchange or Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare chance to read the paper; inmates aren't allowed to
read or listen to the news for fear of keeping up with gangs and
other trouble lurking on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of my only contacts with the outside world,'' Karl
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both say they've had some exposure to investing. Brian's
stepfather occasionally talks stocks at the dinner table and Karl's
grandfather invests in stocks and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   One day last week, Karl suggested they look into buying Pfizer,
the giant pharmaceutical company. His interest was piqued by a new
estrogen product he heard about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll see an increase in their stock price,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They ask Erman to research Pfizer and IBM on her home computer.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely they'll just end up buying more Amazon or Yahoo! or
AOL, however. When a classmate reads an article on Iridium, the
maker of the global satellite-telephone network with a beat-up
stock price, Karl suggests they can't afford a turnaround stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would maybe be a good stock to buy for the long term,''
he said. ``We've got to stick with the active stocks and see if
they do it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   With the contest drawing to a close, the girls also talk about
dumping everything else and buying more Internet stocks. Janie and
Melissa, who sit slumped in their desks in the back of the room,
recommend selling Harley-Davidson, Xylan and Ameritrade and bulking
up on Amazon, Yahoo! and AOL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't be wasting our money on things that aren't doing
good,'' Melissa said.
</P>
<P>
   Janie has more selfish reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want first place,'' she said. ``I want a party.'' &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson may be reached at 444-8617 or
dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
