A0155 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-REVOLT-LADN     04-08 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-REVOLT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE MAKERS LEAVING L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Movie production off studio lots in Los Angeles
County fell dramatically in the first three months of the year,
reflecting the lure of lower-cost locations such as Canada and
tighter Hollywood budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lot production was down a whopping 21 percent in the first
quarter of 1999 compared with '98, according to figures released by
the Entertainment Industry Development Corp. March shoots alone
plunged 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter decline in movie activity follows a 12.7
percent decline for all of last year. The Motion Picture
Association of America underscored the trend last month when it
reported that the average cost of a 1998 major studio film declined
1.3 percent to $52.7 million after jumping 34 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thompson, owner of the Van Nuys-based Real to Reel
location-scouting service, said Wednesday that leakage to foreign
locations has become a major concern for Hollywood's core work
force, those performing ``below-the-line'' tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense that I get is that it's a big problem because it
seems like the foreign market is really starting to boom,'' he
said. ``Canada and Australia are really doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers say studios have decided it makes more
financial sense to produce modestly budgeted movies with
blockbuster potential such as ``There's Something About Mary'' than
to commit to a nine-figure movie like ``Godzilla'' that might not
live up to its hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``The activity is very much as we anticipated,'' said Cody
Cluff, president of the Entertainment Industry Development Corp.
``Studios are cutting back on the number of features and the size
of budgets. The big difference is that in 1996 and 1997, we saw a
lot of $85 million and $100 million projects; now we're seeing a
lot of $40 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller budgets mean shorter production schedules, Cluff noted.
``If you're a producer, you still spend the same amount on talent,
but not as much on the bottom line,'' said Cluff, whose agency
issues about 80 percent of off-lot permits in Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson agreed. ``Budgets are getting tighter,'' he said. ``It
used to be 60 percent was spent below the line; now it's
reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same story in Orange County, normally the recipient of
spillover shooting from Hollywood. ``We're seeing a lot of
big-budget projects put on hold and a lot more lower-cost films
from independents,'' said Debi Hausdorfer, managing director of the
Orange County Film Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The squeeze on dollars also means that producers continue to
succumb to the lure of out-of-state locations, dazzled by such
come-ons as lower labor costs, tax rebates and freebie permits and
police.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Canadian province of Manitoba tripled its
production revenues to $50 million for its fiscal year ended March
31 after it instituted a stunning 35 percent rebate for use of
Canadian labor.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Vivier, Manitoba's film commissioner, predicted the
province will double that total this year. ``Our locations are
different from Los Angeles, so it's hard to say what we're taking
away,'' she added. ``We're getting two or three inquiries a day and
scouting a project a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Cluff said feature activity in Los Angeles County has picked up
recently with several prominent projects under way including ``End
of Days'' with Arnold Schwarzenegger, ``Town and Country'' with
Warren Beatty and Diane Keaton, and ``Hanging Up'' with Meg Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent projects scheduled locally: Warner Bros.'
``Space Cowboys'' with Clint Eastwood and Tommy Lee Jones;
``Fifteen Minutes'' with Robert De Niro; ``The Next Best Thing''
with Madonna; Universal's ``For the Love of the Game'' with Kevin
Costner; Sony's ``What Planet Are You From''; and New Line's
``Magnolia.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cluff admitted that even an upsurge probably would leave
1999's feature activity even with last year's total at best. ``I
would expect we would track fairly closely to 1998 numbers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Entertainment Industry Development Corp. said the
movie decline was mostly offset by increases in TV activity, with
overall production sliding just 2.9 percent in the first quarter.
Television, particularly one-hour episodic programs, gained 9.4
percent in the quarter as production days in March jumped from 970
to 1,280.
</P>
<P>
   However, Thompson noted, Canada appears to have supplanted Los
Angeles as the favored site for movies of the week. ``I haven't
seen an order for movie-of-the-week work in months,'' Cluff added.
</P>
<P>
   Local commercial activity, which has been erratic, also surged
in March with a 70 percent gain to 798 days. As a result, March's
overall commercial activity rose 12.1 percent after successive
declines of 10.7 percent and 10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Orange County, overall activity fell more than 23 percent for
the first two months of the year, then picked up in March.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
