u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT &LR;      04-08 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SHUT OUT MARLINS, 6-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There is a sound this time of year that Rickey Henderson
hears. It is the sound of a bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time the bell rings, we're ready to play,'' Henderson
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the bell first rings, it's opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It rang,'' Henderson said. ``I heard it solid.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still ringing. Henderson, who has obviously shrugged off a
dismal spring (just as he predicted he would), went 4 for 4 on
Wednesday night with two solo homers, two doubles, a walk and four
runs scored to lead the New York Mets to a 6-0 victory over the
Florida Marlins at Pro Player Stadium as Bobby Jones pitched seven
shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's 12 total bases were one off the team record, held by
Darryl Strawberry, Claudell Washington and Jim Hickman. And for the
opening series of the season, Henderson was 6 for 11 with 3
doubles, 2 homers, 3 walks, 1 stolen base, 5 runs scored and 4 runs
batted in, as the Mets took two of three from the low-budget
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson led the way in both Mets victories, just as the team
hoped he would when it signed him during the off season to be the
leadoff hitter they never really had last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ageless,'' Mike Piazza said of the 40-year-old Henderson.
``There are very few players in the history of the game who can
dominate a game from the leadoff spot. He's one of them, if not the
only one.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the 10th time in his career that Henderson has hit two
home runs in the same game, but the first time since July 22, 1993.
When asked if he could remember having four extra-base hits in one
game, Henderson said he could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can't remember half the things I do in this game,''
baseball's career stolen base leader said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Elias Sports Bureau, Henderson's previous high
was three extra-base hits in the same game, something he has done
three times in his 20-year major league career, the last time on
July 16, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Through six innings, the Mets' lineup was 0 for 9 with runners
in scoring position, one night after it had been 7 for its first 8
with runners in scoring position in a 12-3 rout of the Marlins, two
nights after it had been 0 for 14 in a 6-2 opening-day loss.
</P>
<P>
   About the only constant was the lineup itself. Last year,
Manager Bobby Valentine did not field the same lineup in three
consecutive games until the final week of the season. This season,
Valentine has not changed a thing over the first three days.
</P>
<P>
   There has been little reason to. Not only did Edgardo Alfonzo
and Robin Ventura each extend their hitting streaks to all three
games, Henderson also seemed to be on the bases _ or circling them
_ all series long.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the Mets left fielder walked to start the
game, although he was picked off. It turned out to be the only
mistake Henderson would make on the night.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Henderson blasted his first homer as a Met, 417
feet to straightaway center field off the former Met left-hander
Jesus Sanchez. And in the fifth, after he had pulled a double to
left, Henderson evened things with Sanchez on the basepaths to
create another run. Sanchez balked.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud followed with a sacrifice fly. And the Mets were up,
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The book on Henderson is to pitch him inside. But Henderson led
off the seventh against Brian Edmondson by pulling his second
double of the game to left. And when he later scored on Piazza's
one-out ground-ball single to left off Antonio Alfonseca, Henderson
_ who hit .130 this spring _ had scored the first game's first
three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, had a 6.30 earned run average this spring. But tonight,
the 29-year-old right-hander, who scattered five hits with one walk
and two strikeouts, looked more like the pitcher who tossed six
shutout innings on opening day a year ago than the one who went 9-9
the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is striving to be more consistent this season. On
Wednesday night he outdid last season's debut by one inning, and
departed with a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, the final run belonged to Henderson, who belted his
second solo homer of the game, this time off Alfonseca, with two
out in the eighth. The ball traveled an estimated 375 feet. And
like the doubles, it too was pulled to left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
