<HEADER>
A0168 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      04-08 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DER FICKLE FUROR OVER DER FUEHRER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm having trouble keeping my Hit lers straight.
</P>
<P>
   I work in the news business. I read the papers every day and
watch the network broadcasts every night. I can find Kosovo on a
map by drawing a line over the Adriatic Sea from above the heel on
Italy's boot.
</P>
<P>
   I understand the evils of ``ethnic cleansing'' and go along with
NATO's decision to bomb the hell out of Yugoslavia as long as its
government continues to terrorize and kill its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm confused by all the politi cians _ from President
Clinton on down _ who want us to think of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milo sevic as another Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, in that same part of the world,
politicians every where were calling Bosnian Serb dictator Radovan
Karadzic the next Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   That was confusing enough, particu larly since for much of the
1990s leaders of the Western world had been referring to Iraq's
Saddam Hussein as the world's most Hitler-like figure.
</P>
<P>
   Especially after he gassed the Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Moammar Gadhafi, the Libyan dictator who's not
even smart enough to elevate himself above the rank of ``colonel''?
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1980s, when President Reagan sent war planes to bomb
Gadhafi's house, we were told that Moammar was an awful lot like
Adolf.
</P>
<P>
   THEY'RE EVERYWHERE
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, politicians were making Hitler comparisons to
Chi na's Deng Xiaoping, who sent troops and tanks to kill his own
people in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago in Rwanda, when the Hutu majority started
killing thousands of men and women in the Tutsi minority, many
called it the worst example of genocide since World War II and the
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that every newly de clared Hitler must run with a
crowd of newly declared Nazis, who invari ably are said to employ
``Gestapo tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 years ago, people were saying things like that about
the Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Before that there was Pol Pot in Cambodia, Nicolae Ceausescu in
Romania, Augusto Pinochet in Chile, Idi Amin in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   North Korean dictator Kim Il-sung was spoken of in the same
breath as Hitler for nearly 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   There are even alleged Hitlers that most Americans have never
heard of, like Nigerian ruler Gen. Sani Aba cha.
</P>
<P>
   And there are guys who get Hitler-like reputations although they
don't rule any country. For instance, the terrorist and billionaire
Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   None of it's true.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hard the wicked SOBs of this generation try to
match him, there will never be another one.
</P>
<P>
   He was the Michael Jordan of dictators. The Babe Ruth. The Bee
thoven. The Picasso. The Shake speare. The Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   He was the perfection of evil. &QL; 
LEVEL OF ATROCITY
</P>
<P>
   But, in this age of squeamish politi cians and skittish
citizens, there's an unwritten rule that says we must convince
ourselves a miscreant has risen to Hitler's level before we try to
stop him.
</P>
<P>
   It's like saying you shouldn't consult a doctor until your body
tempera ture reaches 105. That you shouldn't call the fire
department until flames are shooting 50 feet above your roof. That
you shouldn't trip the burglar alarm until the thieves are speeding
off in the getaway car.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavian army is said to have displaced more than half a
million ethnic Albanians from their homes in only the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The White House supposedly has a document claiming the Serb
military and police have emptied and burned villages, and carried
out mass execu tions.
</P>
<P>
   That's more than heinous enough for most of us, no matter whose
name the politicians attach to it.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, our Hitler Parade is topped by Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   He's No. 1 on the charts.
</P>
<P>
   With a bullet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NY     04-08 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNETS TOP KNICKS, 106-82 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ It was time to give up and usher an end to
this miserable night by turning the floor over to the Knicks'
reserves. Crestfallen and drained, Coach Jeff Van Gundy waved Larry
Johnson off the teal-trimmed court with about 7 long minutes left
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   As Johnson shuffled by Van Gundy, he shook his head and
whispered, ``I let you down.'' Van Gundy patted him as he passed
and must have wondered if the rest of the players knew how much he
needed them to respond.
</P>
<P>
   So after the 18-17 Knicks lost their seventh game in 10 tries on
Wednesday night, after they watched a lower-echelon team like the
Charlotte Hornets make fun of them during their 106-82 defeat at
the Charlotte Coliseum, and after they fell to 4-12 on the road and
a half-game out of playoff position, Van Gundy made a plea to his
unraveling team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them this is my responsibility and that I also need
their help in putting more into it,'' Van Gundy said. ``I'm
disappointed in myself and in the team. It's my responsibility to
get them to play better. I haven't done my job well the last couple
of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has had the assurances of management and the support
of his players, however hollow and fleeting those may be. But after
absorbing another painful night for his team of misfit talent, he
may be driven to a career counselor _ and soon.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing he preaches is getting through. Nothing he shouts is
heard. Buried beneath the rubble of an unthinkable collapse in
front of the Hornets (13-20) _ a team that was on a five-game
losing streak _ is a confused team in total disarray.
</P>
<P>
   How else can you explain this? In desperate need of a victory, a
team that Van Gundy had said was teetering fell off the cliff in
the first quarter tonight. In 12 minutes the Knicks were down,
29-12, and had turned the ball over five times. The shock of it
didn't even rattle the Knicks, who were down by 58-38 at the half
after allowing the Hornets to hit 63.9 percent from the field.
Before the four-minute mark of the fourth quarter, the Knicks were
down by 29 points and ended the game with players like Herb
Williams and Ben Davis on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Not once did the Knicks mount a threat. Out of sorts, Sprewell
played his game of one-on-one and came up with a 5-of-16 effort and
13 points, while the shrinking Allan Houston made just 1 of 8 shots
for 5 points. Only Sprewell seemed the least bit optimistic for a
quick turnaround, though his reasoning was curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played on losing teams, whereas other guys here
haven't,'' Sprewell said. ``I know what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   He does? Sprewell failed to lead Golden State to the playoffs in
his last four seasons there. His logic aside, the Knicks are not
going to find a silver lining unless they respond to Van Gundy. He
has urged his team to defend, and yet one after another _ Charlie
Ward, Allan Houston and Chris Childs _ left his man wide open on
the perimeter while the Hornets hit 8 of 14 3-pointers. Van Gundy
had implored his team to take care of the ball, and yet Ward had 5
of the Knicks' 15 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   One turnover led to Houston's benching. With four minutes left
in the third quarter, Houston lost the ball as he pulled it up over
his head. With a hangdog look on his face and a lazy stride, he
watched as Eddie Jones took his miscue and blew by him for an
uncontested layup.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was furious. He angrily he took a timeout and scolded
Houston, who stared straight ahead and did not look at Van Gundy.
Two plays later, after the Hornets took a 77-52 lead on two
straight jumpers, Houston was taken out and the seldom-used reserve
David Wingate replaced him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jeff was frustrated with that,'' Houston said. ``He
should have been. I think we're getting confused over what it takes
to win. We have to find a way to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to blame others. It takes a man to stand up and take
responsibility. We can't blame Jeff. If anyone is not to blame,
it's Jeff.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy didn't have enough room for everyone to sit on the
bench as the Knicks trailed the Hornets, 79-60, after three
quarters. Everyone, with the exception of Johnson, contributed with
senseless mistakes and panicked plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a frustrating night,'' Ewing said. ``Things are not
going well for us. I have no excuse or explanation. We're letting
ourselves down.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's frustrating,'' Johnson said. ``Early on, we
would get frustrated losing close games. It would be a critical
mistake here or there. Now, we're not close.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 0145EDT &QL; 
