<HEADER>
A0172 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBA     04-08 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBACKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SWEEP DIAMONDBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Arizona Diamondbacks talked about contending
for the National League West title, and about battling with the Los
Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Next, please.
</P>
<P>
   Extra innings weren't needed on this occasion, but the Dodgers
again broke out the long ball with two homers in a five-run fifth
inning as the Dodgers swept the three-game series with a 6-4 win
Wednesday night against the Diamondbacks at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The win marked the first time since 1995, and the fourth time
since the Dodgers moved west in 1958, they have begun the season
with three straight wins.
</P>
<P>
   And like the opener, and like Tuesday's home run heroics by Gary
Sheffield, again the Dodgers overpowered Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi, who homered twice in the opener, hit a home run
off Arizona starter Andy Benes (0-1) to break a 2-2 tie in the
fifth, and catcher Todd Hundley made it back-to-back with his first
home run as a Dodger. He lined a 3-2 pitch over the right-field
fence to give the Dodgers a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The way right-hander Ismael Valdes was pitching, that was plenty
of support.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his five-year career, scouts, general managers and
front office personnel have all said Valdes has some of the best
stuff in baseball, but he labored through 10-11 and 11-10 seasons
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, coming off a magnificent spring, is trying to
re-establish his standing and turn the talk and promise into
results.
</P>
<P>
   He did that against the Diamondbacks, limiting them to two runs
on five hits in 72/3 innings. Valdes (1-0) walked one and struck
out five in becoming the first Dodgers starter to win a game this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shaw recorded the final three outs for his first save. He
was pressed into pitching when Mel Rojas surrendered back-to-back
homers to Matt Williams and Luis Gonzalez, who homered twice, to
start the ninth as Arizona pulled within 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   As was Arizona's protocol in this season-opening series, the
only way they could get to a Dodgers pitcher was via the home run.
Gonzalez hit the second pitch he saw from Valdes in the fourth
inning into the left-field stands, a two-run shot, to give the
Diamondbacks a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   All 12 runs the Diamondbacks scored in the series were produced
by homers, eight in all.
</P>
<P>
   But following Gonzalez's homer, Valdes was nearly unhittable. He
allowed a single to Bernard Gilkey, but retired the next 11
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the first two games, the Dodgers didn't wait until the
last moment to rally, instead seizing control in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   It began with birthday boy Adrian Beltre (he turned 21) hustling
for a leadoff double on a liner to left-center field. Valdes
sacrificed Beltre to third and Eric Young, who had three hits,
doubled in the Dodgers' first run. Center fielder Devon White
blooped a single to short left field to score Young with the tying
run.
</P>
<P>
   After Sheffield flied out to left, Mondesi punished Benes' 1-0
pitch into the left-field stands as the Dodgers went ahead 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said he moved Hundley from second to fifth
in the lineup to ease the offensive burden on his catcher, and the
move paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Hundley follow Mondesi's third homer of the season
with his own, but two innings later the hustle of Sheffield got
Hundley another RBI. Sheffield singled to lead off the seventh
inning, stole second and went to third when catcher Kelly
Stinnett's throw bounced off Sheffield and into left field. After
Mondesi was intentionally walked, Hundley delivered a sacrifice fly
to left to score Sheffield and give the Dodgers a 6-2 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
