<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0173 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN     04-08 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ROUT KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ A day or two off, and maybe the Los Angeles Lakers
could have afforded a full-blown exorcism to rid themselves of the
evil spirits that haunted them in Tuesday's late collapse to the
Utah Jazz. But the NBA schedule being what it is, the Lakers had
time only to traverse the state, hold a brief team meeting and play
their third game in three nights _ against a team they had yet to
solve.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the power of the team meeting is the best mojo after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the source of inspiration, the Lakers reversed their
recent ill fortunes and trounced the Kings 104-89 at Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' first win in three tries against Sacramento came
after a slow start but an impressive finish, as they outscored the
Kings 28-17 in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They took a four-point lead into the fourth, but Kobe Bryant
rattled off seven straight points, then passed off the duties to
Shaquille O'Neal, who scored eight in a row, and the Lakers had a
91-79 lead they wouldn't relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal finished with a game-high 30 points and 18 rebounds, and
Bryant overcame early offensive struggles to score 18 points and
dish out seven assists. Glen Rice also struggled with his shot but
scored 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   The bench also came through, with Derek Fisher scoring 19 points
to go along with six assists. Rick Fox added 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with an introspective team meeting in place of the
usual morning shootaround. That was more a product of the Lakers'
heavy schedule _ they played their fifth game in six days _ than
any need to rehash the mistakes of the night before. But a rehash
was in order after the fourth-quarter debacle against the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   There was no mistaking the team's mood in the morning meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were frustrated with the way that they played, and the
mistakes that they made,'' Rambis said before tipoff Wednesday. ``I
just told them to stay positive. As well as (the Jazz) played, and
all the things they did so well execution-wise, it still came down
to a four-point ballgame with four minutes to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense was the primary topic of discussion, accompanied by
lowlight film of their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same people all the time, and it's not the same
mistakes all the time, but there always seems to be a breakdown of
somebody doing something wrong sometime,'' Rambis said. ``No team
plays perfect defense ... but you learn to cover each others' backs
and cover up those mistakes. And we just have to try and minimize
our mistakes.... They knew what our game plan was. But guys were
just, `I thought I could ...' `I almost got ...' Well, that's
great, but those resulted in baskets for (Utah), a few of them at
critical times too. You can't do that. You can't arbitrarily make
up your own thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure everyone stays aware of their
relationship between themselves, their man and the ball, so they're
ready to help on the weak side.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Fox, ``It was more of a pow wow on what we didn't do well.
I guess you could call it critiquing.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe their next meeting should focus on those mind-numbing slow
starts. They sputtered early again Wednesday and the Kings took an
early lead, extending it to 31-22 by the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was late in the second quarter before the Lakers took the
lead back, erasing a 10-point deficit with an 18-6 run. J.R. Reid
and O'Neal scored six points in the run, and the Lakers grabbed a
43-41 lead with five minutes remaining, then held on for a 53-51
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal finished the first half with 16 points on 7-of-11
shooting. Dennis Rodman sat all but nine minutes of the first half,
but O'Neal picked up the rebounding slack, grabbing nine in 15
minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
