<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL BRINGS MASTERS TOUCH TO SEASON'S FIRST MAJOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ America is waiting to get in, but David Duval
stands on the other side of the door, hearing the knocks, refusing
to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Although his golf game is on full display like the azaleas at
Augusta National, he keeps his personal side stuffed away in some
basement closet. Duval collects trophies and dust, and don't dare
try to buff him up.
</P>
<P>
   This is who he is, plain as Wonder Bread, the death of the
party. But no one can ignore the monotone man anymore. The
27-year-old enters the first round of the Masters Thursday as the
prohibitive favorite, Tiger Woods included, having won two straight
PGA tournaments and 11 in his last 34 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's batting .333,'' said CBS analyst David Feherty.
``Baseball players do it against one pitcher. He's doing it against
150 players. It's extraordinary. It's like he's saying: `Does
anybody have any hard games?'''
</P>
<P>
   Courses and conditions don't matter. Needing a boatload of
birdies, Duval won the Bob Hope Classic with a final-round 59,
tying the PGA record with an eagle on the 18th hole. Needing pars
and steady play, Duval won The Players Championship two weeks ago
in his hometown of Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in Atlanta last week, the four-time All-American at
Georgia Tech was just looking to warm up for the Masters but ended
up winning the BellSouth Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Three straight wins would appear incomprehensible for even
Duval, but he has accomplished that before with his first three
victories on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   He arrives at the Masters as the No. 1 attraction for curiosity
and autograph seekers, the whole scene making him uncomfortable.
Duval insists he is just a regular guy. But because of his uncommon
golf game and reclusive appearance on the course, reporters wield
shovels, attempting to unearth more about him, believing the public
wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   So they pry and prod and coax and David Duval sits there with a
bemused look, undoubtedly wanting to tell everyone to get the hell
out of his garden.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt from this week's press conference:
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: David, there's kind of a perception out there that
you're somewhat of a dullard.
</P>
<P>
   Duval: A what?
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: A dullard. Why do you think that is?
</P>
<P>
   Duval: You tell me. Is that your impression?
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Duval: I don't understand. ... If that's a perception, that's
fine.
</P>
<P>
   (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Observations, situations, nothing bothers the unflappable Duval,
who heightens the interest with a mysterious manner.
</P>
<P>
   For those who know nothing about golf, Duval is recognizable
because of his sunglasses. A few others on tour wear them, most
notably Fuzzy Zoeller. But Zoeller looks like an approachable guy
on the beach, whistling while he works on his tan.
</P>
<P>
   Duval appears cold. His Oakley wraparound shades cover his eyes
and a large part of his face. He wears a Titleist baseball cap, but
you rarely see any dimples: Duval doesn't smile much. He used to
have a goatee, creating an even more sinister and standoffish look.
His golf shirt is buttoned up tight to his neck, but he never
chokes.
</P>
<P>
   He reacts in the same way to bogeys and birdies. Duval is not
easily fazed or excited. If Ed McMahon showed up at his house to
tell him he won the Publishers Clearinghouse Sweepstakes, Duval
would say: ``Oh.''
</P>
<P>
   This is just his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to make it a stress-free round every time I tee it up,''
said Duval, who tied for second with Fred Couples in last year's
Masters. ``If you hit something in the water and get worked up, it
can harm you for an additional one, two or three holes. You have to
find the demeanor and personality under which you perform the best.
For me, that's not worrying about stuff. I can't re-hit a shot, I
can only move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   So he does, unimpeded, strolling along and gathering victories
at a faster rate than fans. At Augusta Thursday, there will be
larger galleries following Woods and Couples. ``You da man'' types
don't hang out with Duval; those who appreciate the game do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be something you're not,'' Duval said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may want to see more (expression), but I don't think
he's ever going to give it,'' Couples said. ``What he's giving is
great golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval has a fluid swing. It's not the same syrup Couples uses
but close. He is a feel player who relies little on mechanics. In
one unusual aspect, his head does not stay still, contrary to one
of golf's fundamentals; it follows the ball. Annika Sorenstam, one
of the LPGA's best players, has a similar swing and head reaction.
</P>
<P>
   A bad round for Duval is a 70. He averages 68.22. He leads the
tour in two of the most telling statistics, greens in regulation
and putting. He hits nearly three out of four greens and takes
about 30 putts a round. He also turns his little white ball into a
disappearing dot, ranking fourth in driving distance at 287.5
yards.
</P>
<P>
   It's methodical and brilliant if monotonous.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes in here (media room) every week,'' Couples said.
``He's got to go in and tell you: `I'm playing well.' How many ways
can you say that. It's going to be boring no matter how you say
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it remains, then, dullard Duval retaining the
misconception. As it turns out, Duval has his reasons for turning
inward. In this week's Sports Illustrated, it was revealed that
Duval's older brother died from aplastic anemia, a bone marrow
disease, when Duval was 9 years old.
</P>
<P>
   He has several stories, but the bookshelf seems empty because of
his guarded nature.
</P>
<P>
   Duval snowboards and skis and fishes and loves to read himself.
He was once a failure, Feherty remembering when Duval did not get
his PGA Tour card at qualifying school in La Quinta, Calif., in
1993. He used to pack 235 pounds on his 6-foot frame but has since
lost 40 pounds and continues to work out. It took three years and
seven second-place finishes before he finally broke through.
</P>
<P>
   Duval is understated elegance, a work in progress. The
sunglasses protect his sensitive eyes from pollen, but maybe they
are really reflecting the glare of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   When someone referred to him as a star, Duval fidgeted. When
someone else said he was the Michael Jordan of golf, Duval
blanched.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's entirely inappropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not: David Duval has become the world's best golfer.
And this weekend, he will attempt to win his first major at the
Masters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
