<HEADER>
A0201 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-AUGUSTA-SPI &LR;      04-08 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-AUGUSTA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUGUSTA DECEIVING FOR THE AVERAGE HACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Ever wonder how you would fare at Augusta?
Pretended like Bill Murray, fantasizing about being a Masters
champion?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's a Sam Perkins reach, but there are reasons to
believe that the average hack, the Seattleite who tees it up at
Jefferson or hits worm-burners at Jackson, could handle this
layout.
</P>
<P>
   If you can deal with initial intimidation and subsequent
embarrassment, there are possibilities for you here. Augusta is a
beast that no one tames anyway. But you just might fare better than
the professionals given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   That's the hypothesis presented in David Owen's book, ``The
Making of the Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1930s, the course was designed to be a test for
experts, yet playable for bogey golfers. One of the designers and a
great player in his own right, Bobby Jones, wanted members and
guests to have enjoyable rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Jones succeeded. And here's the most surprising thing about
Augusta: although you will watch pros struggle Thursday, remember
that duffers oddly shoot better than their handicaps here.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons? Fairways are wide open. Wherever you go off the
tee, you're laying one. That's not the case at McCormick Woods in
Port Orchard, where white stakes and red stakes lead to penalty
strokes and you can be laying five or seven by the time you finally
get one in play.
</P>
<P>
   If you end up in the trees, it's a minimal problem here. Unlike
dense Northwest firs, say at Battle Creek in Marysville, these
Georgian pines are spaced apart, making recovery shots possible.
</P>
<P>
   You're familiar with the water at 11, 12, 13 and 15. Penalty
strokes could add up on those holes. But there is no water on the
front side.
</P>
<P>
   On many holes, you can bump and run your ball to the green and
walk to the next tee with an acceptable bogey. In addition, there
are no waste areas to carry on tee shots, another terrifying hazard
to the hackers.
</P>
<P>
   The rough that concerns the pros would not bother you. It is 1]
inches high. A ball dropped in the rough on No. 1 Wednesday sat up
nicely. In fact, the rough here is easier for the high handicapper
to hit from than the fairways.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta mows its fairways down to .39 of an inch, lower than all
of the fairways in the Seattle area. For instance, Willows Run in
Redmond is currently at half an inch. When there is that little
grass, it is almost like hitting off hardpan or cart paths for
duffers, who are apt to hit fat shots.
</P>
<P>
   The greens would be a problem. There are so many undulations, as
you know. They are mowed to the nubbin, producing quick surfaces
and slick putts.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how fast they are because everything is so
secretive here. But it's believed to be a 12 or 13 on the
Stimpmeter, which translated is Formica fast.
</P>
<P>
   A Golf Digest survey also showed that Augusta's greens rate a
difficulty of 148 compared to 72 for your normal course.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the deal: if you're a bogey golfer, you have your
share of 3-putts anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta has never been officially rated or given a slope. But it
has an unofficial rating of 76.2 based on 6,985 yards from the back
tees. In comparison, Druid's Glen in Maple Valley rates 74.8 and
Harbour Pointe in Mukilteo rates 72.8.
</P>
<P>
   Now then, the pros shot down these Augusta hacker hypotheses
Wednesday, calling hogwash on the whole idea. They were questioned
about how an 18-handicapper would handle Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jones: ``If they played these greens like we play 'em,
they would face double the normal breaks. A 6-inch break turns into
a 12-inch break. They would shoot 30 percent higher than their
handicap here.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Azinger: ``They'd probably shoot 105. Most 18-handicappers
are awful on the greens. If they normally had two to three
three-putts a round, they'd have six to eight here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik: ``They would never get it in the hole, that's
the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   David Feherty, former pro and current CBS wise-guy analyst:
``The average 18-handicapper would be lucky to break 130 from the
back tees. There are more difficult shots under 100 yards than any
course in the world. There would be four-putts, five-putts,
six-putts. You may not finish. It could get dark. It's that
difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
