<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0203 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-08 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERENE TRAIL BLAZERS STEAL SONICS' STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Yet one more consequence of the NBA lockout: Without
permission, without warning, without ticket-refund offers, the two
longtime Northwest rivals switched team personas.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the Sonics: Sullen, directionless, underachieving
losers.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the Trail Blazers: Serene, driven, overachieving
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Watch tonight's game at KeyArena and see if the Blazers don't
resemble the Sonics of three and four years ago. And the Sonics,
after Wednesday's blowup at practice between Gary Payton and Vin
Baker, following a numbskull loss to Sacramento, are looking like
the disjointed Rose City failures who have lost in the first round
of the playoffs for five straight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chemistry is great,'' chirped Bob Whitsitt from Portland
Wednesday. ``The players really like each other, and their roles.''
</P>
<P>
   The phone conversation came a couple of hours before Payton and
Baker, supposedly close pals, broke up practice with a fractious
bout of accusations and name-calling.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Whitsitt would revel in the irony, or anything.
</P>
<P>
   Not Whitsitt, the Sonic president fired by owner Barry Ackerley
five years ago, only to see what was mostly Whitsitt's team make
the 1996 NBA Finals. Not Whitsitt, whose Blazers have been 5-14
against the Sonics during his tenure, including 0-4 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Not Whitsitt, the Seahawk president who recently hired perhaps
football's best coach, and works two jobs for the one of the
world's richest men.
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt? Gloat? Nah. Not him.
</P>
<P>
   Not out loud to a reporter, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, there has to be a little heh-heh-heh under
construction. For now, publicly, Whitsitt offers the predictably
diplomatic patter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done anything yet,'' he said of the Blazers. ``Wait
'til we get out of the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   An NBA-best record of 27-6 is nevertheless a superlative feat to
date. Whatever happens in the playoffs, the Blazers as an
organization must be credited with a plan that survived the lockout
better than any other franchise.
</P>
<P>
   From a rapidly maturing 46-36 team a year ago, they added only
reserve guards Jimmy Jackson and Greg Anthony _ who would rather
have stayed in Seattle, but the Sonics had no salary cap room for
him _ to ride out the compressed season with more horsepower than
any other club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our run really began last year with the trade,'' Whitsitt said
of the February, 1998 deal that brought guard Damon Stoudamire and
swingman Walt Williams from Toronto in exchange for Kenny Anderson,
Gary Trent and Alvin Williams. ``After the playoffs, we sent four
staffers across the country who spent a lot of time working guys
out through June 30, right up to the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, after the lockout, with two weeks of training camp, and
the injury and fatigue factor, we figured having continuity and
depth would be an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   As with Utah and Indiana, the Blazer core stayed together and
prospered, unlike the Sonics, who had six new faces that included
three rookies, plus a new coach and system.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers also filched a vital cog from Seattle _ assistant
coach Tim Grgurich, enormously popular with players, whose presence
Wednesday at Sonic practice certainly would have helped.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was a fast start under coach Mike Dunleavy that
mitigated the Blazers' biggest potential problem _ gripes about
playing time from so many talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've sold these guys on winning first, and everything
else flows from there,'' Whitsitt said. ``If they don't get a lot
of playing time, they might be upset for a few minutes, but they
realize where the team is going, and it fades.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt's favorite example is Jackson, the shot-happy guard
with his fifth team in the last three years, who has never averaged
less than 15 points a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew the deal coming in _ he was going from 35 minutes a
game as a starter to 18 off the bench,'' Whitsitt said. ``He's put
up big numbers elsewhere, but he hasn't won. He didn't want to be a
starter on a bad team.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar sacrifice was offered by Rasheed Wallace, the 6-11
fourth-year forward who was the Blazers' No. 3 scorer last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rasheed came to Mike at the end of last season and said,
`Bring me off the bench.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that a player usually does later in his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this Blazer sweetness is enough to provoke dental decay.
What isn't known yet is whether the
holding-hands-round-the-campfire business will survive a three-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   This team isn't that far removed from its Jail Blazer past that
it couldn't go postal under the right conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, a little thievery of Sonic personnel and a swiping
of a lot of Seattle swagger has made the Blazers formidable.
</P>
<P>
   Next Portland will want to steal the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   So make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
