<P>
   &UR; SERB COUGHS UP THE TRUTH: `MILOSEVIC CAN'T LOSE' &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ If you want to talk to the free press in Belgrade,
hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette smoke in Radomir Diklic's cluttered Beta news
agency office is as thick as fog, great swirling blue wreaths of it
that have the ladies banging open the windows for air above Srpskih
Vladara street.
</P>
<P>
   Diklic smokes himself, of course, a small agitated man with a
potbelly and uncombed hair who breathes through his cigarette until
I am coughing over my notes. But there is a lot to cough about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our friends from the Western embassies here,'' he says.
``We had a lot of contacts and we warned them that the day the
first bomb drops, they could count on the fact that everyone will
be for the defense of their country.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you people _ NATO _ did a good job for Slobodan Milosevic.
It was the best present he could be given. For ordinary people,
Milosevic is now a god; when you bombed, he became a symbol of our
country _ which is awful.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Note TWO OPTIONAL TRIMS, totaling 200 words; uncut
1,025) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-MILOSEVIC-CAN'T-LOSE-600&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
