<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0218 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-RE     04-08 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINUS VAUGHN, ANGELS FALL TO INDIANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins says he
focuses on the players he has on the field, not in the trainer's
room. But that can be difficult when one of the walking wounded is
Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   While Collins' healthy Angels were losing to the Cleveland
Indians 9-1 Wednesday night before 21,689 at Edison Field, Vaughn
and his sprained left ankle were the main topics of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn entered the Angels clubhouse Wednesday afternoon on
crutches, causing most of his teammates to turn their heads _
albeit briefly _ from the freeway chase on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters lurked in the clubhouse, waiting for Vaughn to emerge
from the trainer's room after treatment. Vaughn had an MRI
Wednesday, which revealed a bone bruise and sprained ligaments in
the ankle. His prognosis is officially day-to-day, but it seems
clear he's at least several days _ if not a week or more _ from
returning.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Ned Bergert said Vaughn is definitely out for the next
two games, and the next few days will allow Bergert time to test
the strength and flexibility of the ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who was injured Tuesday night falling into the Indians'
dugout trying to catch a pop-up foul, remains optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking just get the inflammation out as fast as we can
and we can get playing again,'' he said. ``As soon as I can move
around at half-speed, I'll be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he isn't concerned about the danger of coming back
too soon: ``There's danger walking down the street.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he can play with nagging pain: ``The only thing
nagging me is sitting here when I should be on the field. It's
already nagging me and it's only been one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who wore a plastic, removable cast on the ankle and
foot, has been on the disabled list only once in his career, and
doesn't plan to make it twice with this injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if there's ligament damage, it doesn't mean I won't be
able to play,'' he said. ``If it's not broken, that's a positive. I
don't know much about ligaments _ just give me some ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Ken Hill (0-1) had his arm in ice sooner than he
had hoped Wednesday, getting pulled from the game after 41/3
innings. He gave up four runs (two earned) and six hits while
walking four and striking out two. An error by shortstop Andy
Sheets resulted in two unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense, without Vaughn and Jim Edmonds, could do
little with Indians starter Dave Burba (1-0). Burba struck out 10
in six innings, allowing one unearned run and three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Collins wouldn't say whether having Edmonds and Vaughn in the
lineup would have made a difference against Burba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same (without them), but there was nothing wrong
with our lineup,'' he said. ``I'll run Orlando Palmeiro out there
100 times and he won't strike out three times in a game again. It's
why I say Burba had good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Burba) was throwing his split and I don't know if he threw
one for a strike,'' said Sheets, who struck out twice. ``But we
kept swinging and check-swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheets added that the absence of Edmonds and Vaughn might have
had a subconscious effect on the hitters. ``No one really talked
about it,'' he said, ``but maybe in the back of our minds ...''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians broke the game open with a five-run eighth inning,
scoring all five runs off rookie pitcher Scott Schoeneweis, who was
making his major-league debut. Omar Vizquel led the Indians'
offense with three hits and four RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of anticipation making my debut, it's been a
long road to get here,'' Schoeneweis admitted. ``I was excited to
get in there. It can only go up from here, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored their only run on Tim Salmon's infield single,
scoring Palmeiro from third base in the first inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
