<HEADER>
A0219 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-08 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA DELIVERS IN FIRST START; GRIFFEY HOMERS IN 4-FOR-4 NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Of all the attributes listed for Freddy Garcia this
spring _ 96 mph fastball, excellent curveball, improving changeup,
solid mental makeup _ nobody mentioned this: he knows the right
time to be oblivious.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia slept comfortably Tuesday night. Then, when he got to the
Kingdome before his first major league game Wednesday, he took a
nap. A couple of hours before game time, the big right-hander
filled out the dugout doorway with his smile, appearing totally at
ease with himself as he watched his teammates warm up.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the franchise's happiest hour. The Mariners had
just learned shortstop Alex Rodriguez would be lost 4-6 weeks with
torn cartilage in his knee, and they had been blown out in the
season's first two games. Garcia was being asked to do what
veterans Jeff Fassero and Jamie Moyer couldn't: shut down the
surprisingly potent Chicago White Sox offense.
</P>
<P>
   So that's what he did, working 52/3 strong innings to lift the
M's over the White Sox, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got poise for a young pitcher, he really does,'' manager
Lou Piniella said of Garcia. ``He's very relaxed out there,
confident. He gets the ball and throws it.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia threw it 100 times Wednesday night, allowing two runs on
seven hits and two walks. He also recorded five strikeouts _ one
against the first batter he faced, Ray Durham, and the others all
coming with runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so happy right now,'' Garcia said. ``When I'm on the
mound, I feel confident, and that's what happened right now.''
</P>
<P>
   He turned the ball over to his roommate, Jose Paniagua, who
preserved a 5-2 lead by striking out Mark Johnson with runners on
first and second to end the sixth. Paniagua lasted until two outs
in the eighth, when Jose Mesa retired Johnson on a fly ball to
strand two more runners.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa walked two, allowed a double and gave up a run in the
ninth, but did earn a save in his Seattle debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good game,'' Piniella said. ``I know one thing _ I'll
enjoy my off day (Thursday) a little better with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing mightily to the win was Ken Griffey Jr., who had a
walk and four hits, including his second homer of the year. The
home run came in the first inning off White Sox starter John
Snyder, who also allowed Russ Davis' second homer, which led off
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The M's added another solo homer in the seventh, when Matt
Mieske delivered on his billing as slayer of all things
left-handed. Mieske, a .314 career hitter against southpaws,
drilled a pitch from Bryan Ward over the left-field wall in his
first Mariner at-bat. It was the M's first pinch-hit homer since
Paul Sorrento did it in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle also got strong defensive plays from first baseman David
Segui, plus the new double-play combination of second baseman David
Bell and shortstop Carlos Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen was the first of the three Houston Astros acquired for
Randy Johnson to make an impact with the M's, impressing in a
September call-up last year. While reliever John Halama awaits his
Mariner debut, Garcia was the second member of the trade to
deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see Carlos here, Freddy here, John Halama here,'' said
pitcher Jamie Moyer. ``Not to say you wanted to see Randy go, but
when a club makes a trade, obviously you want to see people able to
contribute and help. The three players we got in return look like
they're capable of doing that. That's important.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to lose a key part of your ballclub, especially a No.
1 starter, but what did everyone say last year when that trade was
made? Everyone ridiculed everything about it. But the
organization's going to start reaping the benefits of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
