<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0220 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBA     04-08 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBACKS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SWEEP DIAMONDBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Spring was great for Ismael Valdes. He was nearly
unhittable and more importantly, was unflappable. But it was still
spring, which meant it meant nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, that was something. That's what Valdes told
himself. It was to be the beginning of his transformation from a
pitcher with great stuff to great pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The first, ever-so-slight step was fine. Buoyed by a five-run
sixth inning, Valdes and the Los Angeles Dodgers swept the
three-game series from the Arizona Diamondbacks with a 6-4 win at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so confident,'' Valdes said. ``I have experience. I
have a lot more confidence in myself and my pitches. The past is
the past. I'm working for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (1-0) allowed two runs on five hits in 72/3 innings.
Right fielder Raul Mondesi hit his third homer of the season, a
two-run line drive to left that gave the Dodgers a 4-2 lead.
Catcher Todd Hundley added his first homer of the season and had
two RBI.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time since 1995, and the fourth time since the
Dodgers moved west in 1958, they have begun the season with three
straight wins. And the Dodgers did so despite surrendering eight
homers in the series, which accounted for all 12 of the
Diamondbacks' runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's that Mark McGwire disease. The balls are really
flying out,'' said Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, whose team hit
seven homers in the series. ``There wasn't much difference (between
the teams) in the series, but we persevered.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped to get a stellar effort from Valdes, whose past
is riddled with inconsistency. After he broke through in 1996 with
a 15-7 mark and a 3.32 ERA, the 25-year-old fell into mediocrity by
going .500 the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He spent a spring talking about how different this year would be
because he had confidence, and the foresight to pitch in Mexico
during the offseason certainly helped him get ready for his debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed speeds, was hitting his spots and threw the ball
hard,'' Hundley said.
</P>
<P>
   The only magnified mistake Valdes made came on a changeup in the
fourth inning when Diamondbacks left fielder Luis Gonzalez (2 HR, 3
RBI) hit an 0-1 pitch over the left-field fence. The two-run homer
gave winless Arizona (0-3) a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Valdes had no problems after that. He gave up a single to
Bernard Gilkey and then retired the next 11 Diamondbacks before
turning it over to the bullpen, which turned interesting. Mel Rojas
yielded solo homers to Matt Williams and Gonzalez as Arizona pulled
within 6-4, but closer Jeff Shaw got three straight outs for his
100th career save.
</P>
<P>
   However, the talk was about Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can throw his breaking ball for strikes and spot his
fastball,'' Williams said. ``That's why he wins so many games. He
uses his fastball effectively and gets ahead of the count, and he
keeps you off balance with his breaking ball. Good pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Valdes needed on this night was an offensive
burst, and that came in a flash in the fifth inning off
Diamondbacks starter and loser Andy Benes.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Adrian Beltre, celebrating his 21st birthday, led
off the fifth with a hustling double on a liner to left-center
field. Eric Young (3 for 4) doubled in Beltre and center fielder
Devon White blooped a single to short left field to score Young
with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Mondesi punished Benes' 1-0 pitch into the
left-field stands as the Dodgers went ahead 4-2. Hundley followed
with a solo homer to right for the first back-to-back Dodgers
homers since last August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened very fast,'' White said. ``It was one of those
things you can't really explain, but when you have the kind of
explosive lineup that we have, it doesn't surprise me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
