 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2532 - April 8, 1999   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2532 -- April 8, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. ETHNIC CLEANSING : A 20TH CENTURY PHENOMENON ``Ethnic
cleansings'' such as the Serbian campaign in Kosovo, have exploded
in this century, claiming 40 million lives, estimates the American
historian Norman Naimark. Ethnic minorities have always been at
risk, he says, but the risks have grown as nations define targeted
groups as enemies and apply modern industrial methods to kill or
expel them. The outlook for the next century is ot a hopeful one,
Naimark says. From Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. (English translation
available.) 2. NATO'S FIRST WAR IS A REVELATION NATO's 50th
anniversary party in Washington later this month is obviously going
to be a far more difficult and sobre occasion than planned. The
Kosovo issue will not be resolved by then, though it is possible
that combat operations may stop. That depends on Slobodan
Milosevic. But NATO has both to look ahead to what is sure to be a
long, difficult involvement in the region and to look back on what
it has just learned. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
________________________________________________________ 3. ``THE
KHMER ROUGE NEVER DIE'' In Pailin, their stronghold near the Thai
border, some of the former mass-murderers of Cambodia's Khmer Rouge
now live in peace. Many run businesses and have made fortunes. Will
they be spared trial before an international tribunal? Could a
trial bring a new civil war? From Der Spiegel. 1,000 words.
(English translation available.) 4. DAN QUAYLE : STARTING OVER Dan
Quayle is back - and being left in the dust by the son of the
president he served. Why risk the humiliation again? He wants to be
taken seriously. By Melinda Henneberger. From The New York Times
Magazine. Full-length (4,800 words) + edited article available. 5.
STUDY MAY LEAD TO NEW TREATMENTS FOR DEADLY LUNG DISORDER Adult
respiratory distress syndrome is a common and often fatal
complication in seriously ill patients. The disorder is caused by
an out-of-control inflammatory reaction that destroys the lung's
ability to deliver oxygen to the bloodstream. Currently, there is
no treatment that can reverse ARDS, and doctors can only support
the patient until the reaction subsides. British researchers report
that a crucial protein in lung fluid may be being destroyed in
ARDS. The findings suggest that it may be possible to treat ARDS by
replacing the protein and giving drugs that prevent their
destruction. By Michael McCarthy. From The Lancet News Service.
1,000 words. 6. THE UNITED STATES : SHERIFF OR ROGUE? One of the
priorities of United States foreign policy is to combat what it
calls ``rogue states'' - countries whose behaviour on the
international stage is incompatible with the rules generally
accepted by the world community. The definition poses three
problems: the Americans fix the criteria themselves; they are
highly selective in the way they apply them (in what way is Cuba
less democratic than Saudi Arabia?) and, on closer inspection, the
U.S. itself could well qualify for inclusion on the list of states
that do not bother too much about rules that have been accepted by
most countries. By Pascal Boniface. From Le Monde. 800 words.
(English translation available.)
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
WHAT'S DOING IN JERUSALEM The typical tourists in Jerusalem fill
their days with official sites because, from the Yad Vashem
Holocaust memorial to the al-Aksa Mosque, there is so much history
to be seen. But the real, throbbing, conflicted city often gets
overlooked. By Deborah Sontag. From The New York Times Way To Go!
1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
SIX SPECIAL MILLENNIUM CROSSWORDS The New York Times Syndicate is
offering a special package of six Millennium Crosswords, with hard
and easy clues. Please contact us for more details. 9. FROM NATURE
NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain.) A. HAIR LOSS AND
IMMUNODEFICIENCY Hereditary baldness - in the form of male pattern
baldness - is very common. But one recently discovered form of
genetic baldness has tragic consequences, for the affected gene
causes not ony complete hairlessness from birth, but a crippling
defect in the immune system which leads to death in infancy unless
rapidly treated. By Eleanor Lawrence. 500 words. B. BANISHING
WASH-DAY BLUES Help may be at hand for the days when you forget to
sort the washing and end up with rainbow-coloured clothes. We might
soon be adding an enzyme from the ink-cap mushroom to the wash to
prevent such accidents. By Eleanor Lawrence. 500 words.. Please fax
to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81 I am interested in
