A0363 &Cx1f; tad-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV11-C     04-08 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE POINT OF NO (TAX) RETURN
 &HT;    For release Sunday, April 12.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An estimated 126 million individual income tax
forms will be filed with the Internal Revenue Service this year. If
you haven't prepared your own, be assured you're not alone:
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin confides that he too seeks help.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did my own taxes, I'd certainly be out of a job, and I'd
probably be in jail,'' Rubin said as the annual April 15 deadline
approached. Having amassed a fortune on Wall Street before moving
here, Rubin stashes his non-governmental income in a blind trust.
</P>
<P>
   But most folks have more choices than Rubin, including the
option of filing their returns via the Internet. For a modest fee,
you can even get the job done on a secure Web site.
</P>
<P>
   One such service, blessed by a cyber-friendly IRS, tells
would-be users: ``Once there, just answer a series of plain-English
questions (no tax jargon!). Based on your responses, WebTurboTax
then fills out the proper tax forms and does all the math for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic tax filing has been around for years, but until
recently it could handle only the most basic returns. Things began
to change 15 months ago when Rubin recruited Charles Rossotti as
IRS commissioner, with a mandate to shake up the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, 99.9 percent of taxpayers can use it,'' Rossotti
says.
</P>
<P>
   IRS statisticians project nearly 30 million returns will arrive
electronically and be processed that way in 1999, posing no burden
on paper mills. That would mark a 21 percent jump from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Another 6.6 million filers are expected to use their touch-tone
telephones. But that option is limited to persons with incomes of
under $50,000 and without dependents.
</P>
<P>
   One likely bonus for filing online: a fast refund, usually
within two to three weeks after the last mouse click. By contrast,
paper tax returns mailed to the IRS will take from six to nine
weeks to be processed before a refund check comes back in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic filers will collect some $60 billion from their perch
at the head of the refund line. That's their ``reward'' for
granting the feds a no-interest loan.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin likes to stress the IRS' new consumer-friendly look
because he's aghast at the alternate approach that some Republicans
in Congress have in mind: a return-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has come up with a well-thought-out alternative,'' he
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, some 40 nations, including Britain, Germany and Japan,
employ a no-return system in one form or another, for most, if not
all, of their taxpayers. Such schemes usually rely on either exact
withholding, which does away with refunds, or a reconciliation by
the collection agency, which sends taxpayers a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Treasury and Congress tinker away at the margins
of tax reform, declining to make any broad changes. One such
mini-move, enacted last year, suggests taxpayers henceforth make
out their checks to the ``United States Treasury'' instead of to
the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may improve the public's awareness of the IRS as merely
the collector of revenue for the U.S. government,'' the lawmakers
noted. However, should Rubin's trustees overlook the adjustment and
write in ``IRS,'' the check will be cashed promptly anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is glass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
