<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0364 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-BURDEN-$ADV11-COX     04-08 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-BURDEN-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE TAX MAN'S STING IS DEEPER, BUT COMPLAINTS ARE MUTED
 &HT;    For release Sunday, April 11.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans, filling out the last lines of their 1040
forms for Thursday's tax deadline, are paying the highest rate of
federal revenues in the nation's peacetime history. Of every $5
generated by the economy last year, slightly more than $1 went to
Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other time has revenue soaked up a greater share of
output, and that was at the height of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   So why aren't Americans chaining themselves to IRS offices and
staging tax revolts?
</P>
<P>
   At least part of the reason is rising personal income that has
taken some of the sting out of paying income taxes in the late
1990s. At the same time, the nation's tax burden has been shifting
sharply to the richest taxpayers. And perhaps equally important in
tempering outrage, few taxpayers have any concept of how much they
actually pay.
</P>
<P>
   Add to all of that President Clinton's vow to save the surplus
collections for Social Security, and even many Republicans in
Congress have lost their zeal for reducing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly have been more receptive times for tax cuts,''
conceded Daniel Mitchell, a senior fellow at the Heritage
Foundation, who has been disappointed at lagging interest in
tossing out the tax code and replacing it with a simple flat tax
with one low rate.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional proposals for a 10 percent across-the-board cut
quickly died, replaced by a plan for unspecified reductions of $800
billion over 10 years. The president's budget, although it includes
a variety of targeted tax cuts, calls for more tax increases than
reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a windfall of revenues continues to pour in, largely
because the rich have gotten richer and paid soaring amounts of
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Among those making $1 million or more a year, federal income tax
payments doubled between 1993 and 1997, according to a
Congressional Budget Office analysis. People with an adjusted gross
income of $200,000 or more paid 37 percent of all income taxes
collected by the federal government, although this group makes up
only 1.5 percent of taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients are paying through the nose,'' said Roger W. Lusby
III, an accountant with Frazier &AMP; Deeter in Atlanta. But he added
that annual tax complaints from clients in the upper brackets have
been somewhat muted by the booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market's been good and the retirement accounts are
good,'' he said. He added that many are taking advantage of cuts in
the capital gains tax rate to a maximum 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the income scale, many low-income families
now receive checks from the federal government at tax time. With
the expansion of the Earned Income Tax Credit since 1993, working
parents with low and modest incomes can receive up to $3,756 when
they file their tax returns this year.
</P>
<P>
   For middle class households, income taxes have remained fairly
stable. This year, many can lighten their load if they fit under
income ceilings that allow them to take advantage of child credits
($400 for dependent children under age 18), college tuition credits
(up to $1,500), and other recently enacted tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   More burdensome for these households is the payroll tax for
Social Security and Medicare, levied on a salary base that rose
this year to $72,600. The combined 15.3 percent charge (including
the half paid by the employer) is widely seen as regressive, since
it hits hardest families with less discretionary income. The
payroll tax now exceeds income taxes for the overwhelming majority
of American households.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many taxpayers have only a vague idea of the total
amount they turn over to the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``A high school student working his first job, thinking he's
earning $10 an hour for seven hours and should get $70, is shocked
when he sees his first paycheck'' after the government takes its
share, said Kathy Burlison, a tax research specialist for H&AMP;R
Block. As for the rest of taxpayers, she said, ``We just accept it
as part of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if a family adds up the tax money withheld from paychecks,
that would tell only part of the story. Various levels of
government collect dozens of less visible taxes, assessed every
time they pull up to the gas pump, buy a soda, take a trip or make
other purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Americans recognized the high level of taxation, there
might well be a second American Revolution,'' wrote Bryan Riley of
the National Taxpayers Union Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Americans for Tax Reform, a group that urges slashing revenues,
has estimated that ``hidden'' taxes add an average 35 cents to the
cost of a $1.14 loaf of bread, 18 cents to a can of soda, and
$63.60 to a $159 airline ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The Tax Foundation, a private research group, has totaled
revenues of all kinds and come up with an average cost of nearly
$10,000 for every American last year. That's more than the average
per-person cost of housing, food and clothing combined.
</P>
<P>
   So are taxes too high? That depends on your perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington's paycheck has been growing faster than America's
paycheck,'' said Scott Hodge, at Citizens for a Sound Economy
Foundation, who favors an across-the-board tax cut. ``Tax revenues
as a percent of gross domestic product is estimated to be over 20.7
percent in 1999, the highest since 1944-45. And there's no end in
sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodge estimates that since Clinton took office, 35 cents of
every new dollar of personal income created by the economy has gone
to taxes.
</P>
<P>
   However, at the liberal Citizens for Tax Justice, tax policy
director Michael Ettlinger applauded the increase in tax
collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are doing well, they pay more taxes. That's a good
thing,'' he said. ``Now's the time to pave roads and build new
school buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, more loopholes should be closed so that the
rich pay even a bigger share. Dismissing charges that government
will waste money, he said, ``I think most of the money goes to
things that help people.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
