<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    East Texas district tops target list
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The seat in the Texas Senate that has the most
chance of turning over in next year's election is East Texas'
Senate District 3. The current question is whether incumbent Sen.
Drew Nixon (R-Carthage) will seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The district, which runs from north of Houston to Tyler and east
to the Louisiana line, is at the top of the Democrats' target list.
Winning it back could reverse the 16-15 majority Republicans enjoy
over Democrats _ if Sen. David Cain (D-Dallas) survives re-election
in Senate District 2, which stretches through Northeast Texas to
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   That could determine which state senator might succeed Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry as the Senate's presiding officer, should Gov. George W.
Bush be elected president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason even the Republican establishment will be
trying to field someone other than Nixon in the general election
next year. Another is that the Texas Legislature in 2001 will
redistrict legislative and congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district's incredibly important,'' said Robert Black,
press spokesman for the Texas Republican Party. ``We have a slim,
one-seat majority in the Senate. ... We intend to maintain our
majority in the Senate _ and increase it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon gained notoriety after being arrested for soliciting a
prostitute in Austin during the 1997 legislative session. He
pleaded guilty and served out his sentence on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Several state representatives and others lined up to run if he
resigned. Nixon, 39, an accountant who also sells insurance and
real estate, had just been re-elected to a four-year term in 1996.
He decided to serve it _ though he also said he probably would not
seek re-election in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past few months, Nixon, an unpredictable
conservative with an occasional populist streak, has been talking
about running again. ``We have not totally made up our mind,''
Nixon said last week. ``We've gotten an awful lot of people who
have indicated they'd like to see us run.'' He said he'll probably
decide by August.
</P>
<P>
   Three state representatives _ second-term Republicans Todd
Staples of Palestine and Wayne Christian of Center, and six-term
Athens Democrat Clyde Alexander _ are interested but will decide
after the legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Others considering the race include former state Rep. Bob Rabuck
(R-Conroe), a dentist who retired from the House last year after
four terms; Les Tarrance, a Montgomery County homebuilder and the
brother of Republican pollster Lance Tarrance; and Democrat David
Fisher of Silsbee, a grandson of U.S. District Judge Joe Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   The slightly Democratic district had been represented by
Democrat Bill Haley of Center for years. But Haley quit the Senate
to be a lobbyist after the filing deadline in 1994. After a
squabble over which Democrat would replace him on the ballot, Nixon
became the first Republican to win the district since just after
the Civil War. In 1996 he won re-election by just 387 votes of more
than 200,000 cast _ and that was before the scandal. With observers
speculating that well over $1 million will be spent by candidates
seeking the office, Nixon may decide he's better off seeking
privacy than re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``That district is totally overlapped by Democratic
congressional and state House races that will be in play,'' said Ed
Martin, a consultant and former executive director of the Texas
Democratic Party. ``There's going to be an effort to turn out every
Democratic vote we can. East Texas is going to be a war zone this
next election, no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
