<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unfit as foster parents?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state of Texas has issued an all-points
appeal for foster parents. Hurry. Children are stacking up waiting
for homes.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says state Rep. Robert Talton.
</P>
<P>
   First, Talton wants to know if foster-parent applicants are gay
or straight. If they're the former, Talton says Texas doesn't need
the love they could supply to small refugees from shattered homes.
</P>
<P>
   Texas also needs more adoptive parents for children in its
custody. Many of these children have emotional problems,
disabilities and other conditions that mean they don't fit the
bouncing-baby, come-to-Papa, high-in-demand profile. They still
need loving parents, quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says state Rep. Warren Chisum. Straight or not? The
state should ask that first, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Talton (R-Pasadena) has authored a bill that would prevent
homosexuals from foster parenting. A bill by Chisum (R-Pampa) would
prohibit them from adopting children under the state's
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   They say it's in the best interests of the children. Better for
those children to hang in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the number of children in foster care has almost
doubled since the mid-'80s, from 275,000 to half a million.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has more than 5,000 children in foster care and a waiting
list of 2,028 seeking permanent adoption. Some of the latter are in
institutional settings. Some are in temporary foster settings. An
average of 638 additional children queue up for foster homes every
month. Roughly, Texas has about a third as many foster homes as it
has children who need them.
</P>
<P>
   It would have even fewer such homes if Talton's bill prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Under current state policies, being gay or lesbian does not
exclude a person from being a foster parent. State case workers
generally will attain a handle on facets of a foster parent's
personal life before assigning a child for foster care. But sexual
orientation alone will not disqualify an applicant. Nor should it.
</P>
<P>
   What matters to the caseworkers? Whether the foster parent or
parents will be home at night, whether the persons are dependable,
responsible and loving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for stable environments,'' said Marla Sheely of
the Texas Department of Protective and Regulatory Services.
</P>
<P>
   The assertion that a homosexual cannot meet all the state's
criteria for successful foster parenting or adoptive parenting is
bigotry most foul.
</P>
<P>
   Talton points out that sodomy is against the law in Texas (an
outrageous and unenforceable law, I'll add), and says foster
children shouldn't be in the homes of lawbreakers. This, of course,
is the essential function of the sodomy law, not to be enforced
against behavior itself but to legitimize discrimination against a
class of people.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time we had two words for this brand of lawmaking:
Jim Crow.
</P>
<P>
   Talton and Chisum will assert that their concerns are merely the
protection of the children. With considerable numbers of children
already having had gay and lesbian foster parents and adoptive
parents, I want to hear of the supposed atrocities and warped
childhoods this legislation would have prevented.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if we were to go broad-brush about sex assaults, abuse,
violence and more, we would prohibit adoption and foster parenting
by heterosexuals first, since as a class they appear to have major
problems abiding by laws and honoring the classic model of loving,
responsible, monogamous parents.
</P>
<P>
   That, in fact, is why the state is so desperate to find foster
parents. The Talton and Chisum bills would not make lives better
for any children, only place more of them in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
