<HEADER>
A0393 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCR-SMARTMICROWAVE09-     04-08 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCR-SMARTMICROWAVE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR develops `Intelligent Bin' that can shop and sort goods
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Taking a page from George Orwell's 1984 , NCR
Corp. has developed a trash can that will keep track of what you
consume and when you throw the container away.
</P>
<P>
   This smart appliance will generate a shopping list for you and
then relay the information via the Internet to retailers who can
then tailor coupons and special offers based on your consumption
patterns. The ``Intelligent Bin'' can sort your recyclables, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't some sort of gadgety kind of thing. It's based upon
fundamental research of the future of computing, the future of
networks,'' said Stephen Emmott, director of NCR's Knowledge Lab in
London.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall the Knowledge Lab came up with the Microwave Bank,
which comes with a touch screen monitor on the door and voice
recognition software. In addition to cooking food, it can be used
to transfer funds between accounts electronically and look up
recipes on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Emmott predicts such intelligent appliances will be introduced
to the marketplace within a year and widely available within three
years. Emmott said such appliances could go shopping for the lowest
price on the Web based on the shopping list generated off items
discarded into the Intelligent Bin.
</P>
<P>
   NCR researchers took four months to build the ``Intelligent
Bin,'' which uses motors to sort recyclables and an Internet
connection to relay info. The bin would require the widespread use
of radio frequency identification technology. Currently, most
products have bar codes to identify them. RFID uses a tiny computer
chip and antenna embedded into a label than can be slapped onto
products. RFID can carry more information than a bar code and can
be changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Knowledge Lab has been focusing on kitchen appliances
because studies show people spend significant amounts of time
there, said NCR spokesman John Hourigan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
