<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0395 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISABLED-ARTISTS09-CO     04-08 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-ARTISTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Creative spirit is the draw at Atlanta gallery giving the
disabled a voice in the arts
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Katie Smith cannot speak, a result of a stroke at age
15.
</P>
<P>
   But the 31-year-old Cumming resident does communicate _ through
the technology of her computer and the spirit of her art.
</P>
<P>
   A painter of large, modern abstracts with such titles as
``Enraged Abyss'' and ``Broken Wing,'' Smith has found her voice.
</P>
<P>
   And, because of a fledgling Atlanta gallery, she also has found
an audience.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into the historic Healey Building, the Arts for All
Gallery is like many in the area: understated and quiet, with
glossy hardwood floors and warm lighting.
</P>
<P>
   But its mission is virtually unique. For the past year, it has
given disabled painters and sculptors an artistic home and a small
source of income.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The gallery) allowed me to show a large number and varied
array of my work to a diverse group of potential buyers,'' Smith
said via e-mail. ``Generally, my work adorns only my walls and
isn't seen by the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, one of the gallery's best sellers, said determined and
talented artists can make it anywhere. But a gallery show is good
for the ego, she wrote, and ``everyone needs strokes every now and
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating its first anniversary on May 10, the gallery is one
small part of Arts for All, a nonprofit group that has worked for
two decades to help disabled, disadvantaged or institutionalized
people participate in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   But the gallery has been more successful than expected, making
about $10,000 in sales largely due to walk-in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone on the board envisioned it to work so
well,'' said Larry Pollard, chairman of the group's board of
directors and a partner with Ernst &AMP; Young, an accounting firm.
``We wanted a place where we could showcase the visual arts,
something to catch the public's interest, but we never expected it
to generate this kind of revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, disabled artists, often already struggling with
medical and home health bills, have a tough time finding a venue
for their work. Their efforts often are relegated to festivals or
corporate offices.
</P>
<P>
   But the gallery allows their work to be seen by art buffs of all
stripes, without bias. Large picture windows allow passers-by to
examine the displays. It's not until they enter the gallery that
they learn about its special nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, the artists are artists first, disabled, second,'' said
Jennifer Sedlack, the gallery's director.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Spriggs, the curator of folk art at the High Museum of
Art, said the gallery's approach rightly emphasizes the art _ not
the artists' disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``An ongoing frustration in this field is that the difficulties
and challenges of (an artist's) life are sometimes emphasized more
than the art itself ... and that almost becomes an excuse for the
quality,'' she said. ``In this case, I really think it's great that
I could come in there and look at the work on its own merit and not
just because I know the people are disabled.''
</P>
<P>
   For James ``Seymour'' Lunsford, the gallery's top seller, the
location gives him another venue to display his work. He already
exhibits at Lansdell Galleries, near Brookwood Station, but likes
the purpose of Arts for All.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galleries are very particular about what they will use,'' said
Lunsford, who lost a foot in a car accident. ``If they don't think
they can sell it, they won't show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this (gallery) gives artists who do nice stuff a place to
display,'' Lunsford, 50, said. ``Perhaps the standards aren't quite
as high, but neither are the prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Smith's pieces are priced from $50 to $700, with a
percentage going to the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery does require that all artists are professional, with
a staff scouting for suitable talent, said Sedlack.
</P>
<P>
   Lunsford, for example, used to be a freelance photographer
before becoming a painter. He earned a degree from the Art
Institute of Atlanta. Smith holds a degree in studio art from
Kennesaw State University.
</P>
<P>
   But those familiar with the artists say they also like the
artwork because of it represents an artistic testament of strength
and struggle against sickness. Smith, for example, has astigmatism
that causes her eyes to be in constant motion. She said that
condition helps her artwork because she never sees an object
``completely within the bounds of reality...so I create my own
world from my perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Terry O'Shea, an East Cobb dentist, said he bought pieces
because he thought they were not only pretty, but ``inspirational''
because they represent a triumph of the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers should probably balance such feelings with a basic art
knowledge in order to feel more comfortable purchasing from such a
specialized gallery, Spriggs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you decide to invest in artwork, the most important
thing is to educate your eyes,'' Spriggs said. ``And the only way
to do that is see what you can see in person, in books, in museums
and galleries. Over time, you'll be able to discern what you like
and why.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, she said, if you know you like an artist, find out more
about his or her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to invest in someone you don't really connect with
or don't respect as a human being?'' she said. ``Or would you enjoy
investing in somebody who you think is doing amazing things with
their life and their work?''
</P>
<P>
   Cassie Dillon, of Charlotte, N.C., said she bought from the
gallery because ``there's a spontaneous feel about it, an earthy
feel, that you don't see in some of the more well-known
galleries.'' Dillon most recently bought a large acrylic painting
by Lunsford.
</P>
<P>
   Another buyer, Nanalee Wegener, said she's purchased pieces by
Smith because she is captivated by the contrast between the
artist's physical presence and her artistic flair. ``When you see
her and meet her, you think she has such a quiet and gentle manner,
'' Wegener, of Cumming, said. ``But her artwork is so vibrant, so
different from that impression.''
</P>
<P>
   For the artists, it is one more opportunity to connect with
fellow human beings, without worrying about the barrier of physical
handicaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, art is created by the soul,'' Smith wrote. ``And that
in me was not touched.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
