<P>
   DISABLED-ARTISTS _ Katie Smith cannot speak, a result of a
stroke at age15. But the 31-year-old Cumming resident does
communicate _ through the technology of her computer and the spirit
of her art. A painter of large, modern abstracts with such titles
as ``Enraged Abyss'' and ``Broken Wing,'' Smith has found her
voice. And, because of a fledgling Atlanta gallery, she has also
found an audience. The mission of the Arts for All Gallery is
virtually unique. For the past year, it has given disabled painters
and sculptors an artistic home and a small source of income. (Lore,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 31. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0413 _ During 40 years in the thick of show
business, Ron Howard has been known as many things: aw-shucks star
of ``American Graffiti'' and ``Happy Days''; uber-producer and
co-chairman of Imagine Entertainment; A-list director of critical
and box office hits ... and Opie. Boyish and swell as ever, with
his ubiquitous baseball cap and pinkish skin, Howard's days as an
apple-cheeked TV star are far behind him. He has carved a spot as
one of the hottest and most efficient filmmakers of the past two
decades. He's a Hollywood rarity: mogul and mensch. (Garcia, Austin
American Statesman) Art includes 3-column color photo of Ron
Howard, an 18-pica color photo from the film ``EDtv,'' and a
1-column color photo from ``Apollo 13.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN _ A 2-column color graphic ``Countdown
to `Star Wars''' outlining the number of days remaining until ``The
Phantom Menace'' opens. (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   ON VIDEO _ You may not like every Robert Altman movie you see,
but it's unlikely that you'll forget one. The idea of an Essential
Altman is probably an oxymoron, but here are some other Altman
titles you might want to check out on video. (Ringel-Gillespie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column color photo of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS _ ``Beloved is an A-list epic that inadvertently
suggests that Toni Morrison's novels are unfilmable. Also,
``American History,'' ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer.''
(Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) With 2 column color studio
photograph from the film ``Beloved.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ On his third album, ``I Am ... ,'' Nas shows he's
the kind of material rapper who can go Gucci toe to Gucci toe with
Sean ``Puff Daddy'' Combs. Also Joey McIntyre. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0413 _ The idea was for the good guys _ U.S. Army
Rangers and and super-secret Delta Force warriors _ to buzz in
Somalia, nab a couple of the warlord's lackeys and return to the
base in time for dinner. A milk run. But mistakes, as they say,
were made. Mistakes that led to the worst firefight involving
American soldiers since Vietnam. In ``Black Hawk Down: A Story of
Modern War,'' Mark Bowden tells of the events on the streets of
Mogadishu on Oct. 3, 1993, in visceral detail. It's a lucid,
authoritative account of the raid that's great military history and
great nonfiction storytelling. (Beach, Austin American-Statesman)
Art includes 3-column B&AMP;W photo of soldiers standing by helicopter,
1-column photo of beaten U.S. soldier captured by Somali forces and
6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-JORDAN -- In ``Playing for Keeps,'' David Halberstam
documents Michael Jordan's rise as both a basketball player and as
a corporate commodity. Along the way, Halberstam reveals how the
NBA resurrected itself under Commissioner David Stern, how the
all-sports cable network ESPN came into being and how Spike Lee
found himself directing a Nike commercial _ while also creating a
basketball superhero. (Wangemann, Austin American-Statesman) Art
includes 2-column color photo of Michael Jordan and 6-pica color
photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-CRIME-- When it comes to dissecting the narrative ideal,
journalist Janet Malcolm is a top surgeon, perhaps the best. She
now turns her steely eye to the flawed narratives of trial law in
``The Crime of Sheila McGough.'' (Stuever, Austin
American-Statesman) Art includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SKUBE _ Last month, I quoted Judith Butler's sentence that
won her the 1998 Worst, Most Awful Writer Award. Recently, Butler
took to the op-ed page of The New York Times to explain why
intelligent people should not expect to have the faintest idea what
she's trying to say. No one, on the basis of that piece, would call
Butler a stylist, but you have to say she can write clearly and
forcefully when she wants to. She's not the nincompoop her award
would suggest _ but no deep thinker either. Just another leftover
leftist still living in the '60s. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-JANISJOPLIN _ Review of Alice Echols' bio of Janis Joplin.
(MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 27.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-WALTZ _ Review of Dale Ray Phillips' ``My People's
Waltz.'' (Lenhard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Anita Shreve's ``The Pilot's Wife' is Oprah's next
book club selection; the trend in ``tiny'' books; and publishers
have found thattelephone service BookTalk, which lets readers
listen to their favorite authors discuss their books, is an
inexpensive way to create buzz. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   EUDORA-WELTY _ On the eve of Eudora Welty's 90th birthday, which
is Tuesday, the house has become the writer's entire universe.
Confined by poor health alluded to only in the vaguest terms by her
friends and family, Mississippi's grande dame of literature and
Jackson's most hallowed resident is rarely seen these days.
Round-the-clock nurses tend her, and only close friends and
relatives visit. She is missed around town. Yet, even as she is
nowhere to be seen, Welty is everywhere in Jackson. By choosing to
stay here all her life, Welty is in the air, palpable in her old
haunts like the lingering perfume of someone who just left the
room. For Eudora Welty the woman, Jackson has been, quite simply,
home. For Eudora Welty the writer, Jackson has been what Oxford,
Miss. was to William Faulkner, a small but ample playground for her
imagination. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, April 11
</P>
<P>
   UGA-LITERARY _ ATHENS , Ga. _ Athens is experiencing something
of a literary renaissance, with a growing number of resident
writers of note, from Rumi translator Coleman Barks and Jim Kilgo
to fiction mainstays Phil Williams and Terry Kay; four presses
(Maypop Books, Orloff Press, Hill Street Press and UGA Press) and
subsidiary businesses like the Georgia Review that contribute
events and cachet to the scene. A roundup and who's who. (McCarthy,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, April 11.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
(Milner, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS/REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-COOKIE _ Movie Review: ``Cookie's Fortune'' directed by
Robert Altman. Ringel-Gillespie. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COOKIE-ALTMAN _ Robert Altman talks about making ``Cookie's
Fortune.'' (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-GO _ Movie review: ``Go'' Grade: B. It has the energetic,
late-night delirium of a Chinese fire drill. A three-part
comedy-drama unfolding on a single Christmas Eve, it's directed and
shot by Doug Liman (``Swingers''). You could think of it as a movie
built on ``X's.'' We get Xmas, exhilaration, exhaustion, excitement
and the drug called ecstasy, better known as X. The movie is
basically a picaresque plot machine that sends its characters
spinning through misadventures. It's a bright, shining package. And
though it turns out to be pretty empty, you can't help admiring how
cleverly it's wrapped. (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-KISSED _ Movie review: ``Never Been Kissed'' Grade: C.
Drew Barrymore, ``Kissed's'' executive producer, is Josie Geller, a
mid-20s Chicago Sun-Times copy editor and former high school dweeb
(``Josie Grossie,'' they called her) who goes back to teenville as
an undercover reporter, promptly relives high school hell and
pretty much bumbles her way to popularity. Everything about her
career is implausible, the jokes are lame, the situations looopy,
but Barrymore does her best to make a go of it. (BLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   READER-CRITICS _ Weekly You Be The Critic with reader reviews of
``October Sky,'' ``The Corruptor,'' ``Never Been Kissed'' and
``8MM.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
