<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0397 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-KERR09-COX     04-08 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-KERR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing time not a concern for Kerr
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ He had spent the entire game on the bench,
and now Steve Kerr was summoned by his coach to produce some
instant magic during the final seconds, maybe pull a three-point
shot out of his warm-up jacket sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs needed a three-pointer late in a recent
game against Toronto. Kerr never got the chance to shoot. But Kerr
believes that had he been open for even a split second with the
ball in his hands, he could have nailed the shot, despite having
come into the game cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be my role on this team _ to go in there every
once in a while and hit one shot,'' Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   Those are encouraging words for Gregg Popovich, the San Antonio
coach and general manager who signed Kerr (6 feet 3 inches, 180
pounds) in January with hopes that he could make the critical jump
shots that other Spurs missed last season. Jaren Jackson, signed by
the Spurs for his defense last season, missed important perimeter
shots at the end of playoff losses to Phoenix and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr began the season as the most accurate three-point shooter
in NBA history, having hit 47.3 percent during 11 years in the
league. Though his career average is only 6.9 points per game, Kerr
has been adept at hitting the one or two three-pointers his team,
the Chicago Bulls, needed the past five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But circumstances, particularly defensive matchups, have
dictated that Kerr receive sporadic playing time, according to
Popovich. He didn't play Monday against Golden State. Those who
watch the Spurs wonder if Kerr will be ready to make a big
three-point shot against Utah in the playoffs when Popovich could
not find playing time for him during the regular season against
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerr says he is not concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, that's what kept me in the league,'' Kerr said.
``For five seasons (mostly with Cleveland) before I got to the
Bulls, I never really played consistent minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Popovich said, ``Steve is used to playing three or 37 minutes
most of his career. He's always ready when you call on him. Steve
and I have talked about it. He's proven he can handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr scored a season-high 14 points on March 17 at Golden State
a day after he did not play at all at Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, he has struggled to find open shots
and has sometimes failed to convert the available ones. He averages
4.8 points per game. Kerr's 35.5 percent three-point accuracy is
acceptable for most players, but it's the second-lowest of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to have envisioned that Kerr would have difficulty
finding open shots when the Spurs agreed to pay him $11 million
over five years. After all, wouldn't 7-footers Tim Duncan and David
Robinson attract enough defenders near the basket that Kerr would
be wide open outside? As it turned out, opponents stick with Kerr
like a sweat-soaked jersey, taking their chances with leaving the
other Spurs open on the perimeter during defensive rotations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the league 11 years,'' Kerr said. ``Everybody
knows what I do. So I'm not going to get a lot of open shots off
double-teams, because when they double-team, they don't leave me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr was presented with a rare opportunity Saturday when the
Clippers left him open while they converged on Duncan. But Kerr
missed all five of his shots, four of them three-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a night to have my shot off,'' Kerr said. ``My first
three felt good. I thought they were in.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr had his best seasons with the Bulls, averaging between 7.5
and 8.6 points in 1994-98 while playing half a game or less.
Chicago uses the triangle offense, in which players are in constant
motion. Kerr had a knack for getting open while opponents worried
about stopping Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen. Kerr's most
famous shot was the game-winner he hit in game six of the 1997 NBA
finals against Utah to secure the second of his three championships
with the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else runs the triangle,'' Kerr said. ``So when you get
used to playing a certain way and then you have to go to a totally
new style, there's going to be a transition period. I know we're
all (the former Bulls) going through that.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason Kerr has played little in some games and not at all
in others goes beyond a lack of open shots. The Spurs already have
a small guard in the starting lineup, Avery Johnson, who is
generously listed at 5-11. So Kerr played only six minutes in a
recent game in Portland, where he would have had to defend Jimmy
Jackson (6-6, 220) or Walt Williams (6-8). Popovich usually calls
on Mario Elie (6-4) and Jaren Jackson (6-6) to guard such players.
And Elie and Jackson have hit the open three-point shots with
sufficient regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can play against bigger guards,'' Kerr said. ``But
obviously, Jaren and Mario are much stronger than I am, so we don't
have to double-team when they're guarding those guys. And they've
both played well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the way the NBA works,'' Kerr said. ``I told him
(Popovich) a month ago, `Don't worry if you can't play me against
certain guys.' I'll be ready. I'm not taking it personally. We're
just trying to win. I'm a complementary player. Anyone who thinks
they'll win a championship because of me is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr's attitude and perspective were born of his modest
background as a player. While playing at Pacific Palisades High
School near Los Angeles, he was too small and slow to become a
coddled star. The only Division I team that wanted Kerr was
Arizona. And first-year Coach Lute Olson, who took over a 4-24 team
and needed players badly, did not offer Kerr a scholarship until
two weeks before classes started. Kerr did not come highly
recommended. Having watched Kerr play, Olson's wife, Bobbi, said,
``You've got to be kidding me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lute Olson, ``Steve never stops reminding her of that.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Kerr averaged a decent 11 points a game for
his career. He and the Spurs' Sean Elliott are the only Arizona
players whose jerseys are retired.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr never envisioned a successful pro career, which is why, he
says, ``I pinch myself every day. I'm kind of shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Kerr believe he has lasted 11 years because he is
tougher than appearances suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll try to knock somebody's head off if you ask him,''
Popovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott has known that all along. As a junior in high school
living in Phoenix, he watched Kerr score 15 points as an Arizona
freshman two nights after his father, Malcolm, was assassinated in
Lebanon. Malcolm Kerr was president of American University in
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Arizona played at rival Arizona State, a group of
fans chanted ``PLO'' at Kerr and held a sign reading ``Where's your
father?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve went out and killed Arizona State, destroyed them,''
Elliott said. ``They paid a price. You could see this fire in
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Kerr tries to lend perspective to the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was five or 10 people yelling stuff,'' Kerr said. ``After
that I received hundreds of letters from ASU fans who couldn't have
been nicer, apologizing for the actions of those people. That's
just the way the world is. Wacko people. Maybe they had too much to
drink.''
</P>
<P>
   A man that forgiving, how can he complain about playing time?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
