<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   POW-MUSEUM _ Before the $5.8 million National Prisoner of War
Museum opened a year ago today in this tiny southwest Georgia town,
most visitors to Andersonville were Civil War buffs who came to
gawk at the 12,920 marble tombstones of Union soldiers who perished
at the Confederate prison whose name has become synonymous with
cruelty. But since last April 9, it's become a hallowed mecca for
tens of thousands of veterans, most wrinkled, limping on canes or
pushed in wheelchairs by aging sons and daughters through the dark
corridors of the grim museum, full of relics that point out the
horrors of life as a POW. Attendance skyrocketed more than 20
percent in just the first six months, and Park Superintendant Fred
Boyles expects 12-month figures to show a 40 percent jump over the
previous fiscal year. And an unexpected consequence has been the
donation of a flood of 1,561 relics by ex-POWs who salvaged eating
utensils, hand-made weapons, diaries and even German and Japanese
flags that flew over their camps when they were liberated.
(Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (l) Lifestyle and (a) General News categories.
</P>
<P>
   DOG-BAKERIES _ The desserts look good enough to eat, until you
take a closer look. Pup Tarts? Peanut Brindle? Ruffles? Those
fancy-looking treats arranged so prettily in the display case are
for dogs, not humans. Gourmet dog treats are hot; two bakeries for
dogs have opened in Atlanta recently, with more popping up around
the U.S., and some pet stores are starting to stock these treats,
too. Even a bakery for humans, Einstein's, carries a bagel just for
dogs. (LizLee, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 21. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   BLACKCHURCHES _ The Interdenominational Theological Center (ITC)
will hold a press conference Thursday to announce the details for a
new think tank that will become a clearinghouse for the black
church. The ITC/Faith Factor will offer technical assistance and
research facilities for urban and rural black churches. ITC's
president, Robert Franklin, will talk about the new think tank as
well as other ITC programs. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (l) Lifestyle and (a) General News categories.
</P>
