<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STADIUM-NAMES (Houston) _ The Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix is
called ``The Bob.'' Jacobs Field in Cleveland is ``The Jake.''
Qualcom Stadium in San Diego is ``The Murph.'' Now that Enron Corp.
is paying more than $100 million for the naming rights to the
baseball park under construction in downtown Houston, will people
call it Enron Field? By JOHN WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-DRINKS (Albany, N.Y.) _ They're the drinks of champions:
Gatorade, Powerade, Sportade and dozens of lesser-known
electrolyte-laden beverages. But for all the hype and promotion,
the pro and weekend athlete alike might be better off drinking ...
water. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ATHEIST-THEORY (San Antonio) _ Federal investigators suspect
atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair and her two adult children were
dismembered and put into 55-gallon metal drums after they were
murdered in late 1995, according to informed sources. By JOHN
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   TRANSGENDER-PROTEST (San Francisco) _ A coalition of transgender
people claims they are subjected to ``systematic harassment'' by
police officers and sheriff's deputies by being verbally abused
either on the street or in jail. The Police Department and
sheriff's office deny the claims. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   SEXUAL-ASSAULT (San Francisco) _ High school coaches and
athletic directors expressed shock at allegations of an alleged
incident of sexual assault by high school baseball players on
younger teammates. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   GREMLIN-CAT (San Francisco) _ Gremlin, the 2-year-old cat who
leapt into the nation's imagination when he jumped from the fifth
floor of a burning building in February, scaled smaller heights at
a ceremony marking his release from the animal hospital. By ERIC
DRUDIS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PALM-WOMEN (San Francisco) _ Does Silicon Valley have a problem
with naked women? The controversy over using the female form in the
marketing of high tech has again broken out _ this time around an
ad campaign for 3Com Corp.'s Palm Pilot. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCALLOPED-POTATOES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Some foods, such as puff
pastry and hollandaise sauce, are just not worth making from
scratch and good convenience versions are tasty enough to pass as
the real thing. Then there are other convenience products that
don't seem to make the grade. Scalloped potatoes for instance. By
RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ These are the times you wish you
had an on-off switch in your brain or lived alone in a cave or
somehow had achieved the Zen ideal of ultimate detachment. Hundreds
of thousands of people are suffering on a biblical scale, thousands
of miles away, and you can do nothing about it but wring your hands
and write checks to relief agencies. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
