<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0435 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMAICA-BEE-$ADV10-CO     04-08 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-BEE-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW RULE SPELLS TROUBLE FOR JAMAICA; ISLAND IS EXCLUDED FROM
THIS YEAR'S BIG BEE
 &HT;    With Photo
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI -- With less than two months to go before the U.S.
spelling bee, organizers are trying to stanch a flow of negative
publicity surrounding this year's exclusion of Jamaica, home to the
current champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get the word out that we are not biased
against Jamaica in any way, shape or form,'' said Paige Kimble,
director of the National Spelling Bee.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Jody-Anne Maxwell, a 12-year-old from Jamaica, wowed
bee officials by becoming the first non-American to win the
high-profile, Washington-based event in its 73-year history.
</P>
<P>
   But a new rule disqualifies Jamaica from this year's National
Spelling Bee, June 2 and 3. That has spurred several unflattering
editorials in U.S. newspapers, as well as a controversy in Jamaica
so huge it's on par with ``Monicagate'' in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Kimble has taken a whirlwind tour of the United
States, visiting newspapers in various cities to try to repair the
bee's image.
</P>
<P>
   The bee is sponsored by Scripps Howard, part of Cincinnati based
E.W. Scripps Co., which has several media holdings.
</P>
<P>
   But Kimble's effort is likely to do little to sway Jamaicans and
African-Americans who remain convinced the company is biased
against Jamaicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is blatant and persistent racism and discrimination,''
said Maurice Thomson, owner of Phillips &AMP; Phillips Stationery
Suppliers Ltd., one of the Jamaican sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability of black kids from a Third World country to win
the competition against all those white kids proved to be too much
of an embarrassment for Scripps Howard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimble said sponsors were informed three days before last year's
bee that a new rule would force entrants to qualify in contests
between Feb. 1 and April 11. That new rule would require a change
in Jamaica, which for nearly four decades has held its finals in
August and had already planned them in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Scripps Howard was forced to disqualify Jamaica this year after
it went ahead and held the finals in August in violation of the new
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Phillips &AMP; Phillips say they weren't formally
notified of the rule change until late July, too late to cancel the
finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told about the new rule over an informal brunch in
May, and there wasn't anything official said about it until late
July,'' Thomson insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Kimble said the rule was changed to create a more-level playing
field for the participants.
</P>
<P>
   She said that 80 to 90 percent of entrants qualify in March or
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a kid who qualified in April, and you're sitting
next to a Jamaican kid who qualified in August, then obviously you
would be at a disadvantage because you would have had less time to
prepare,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The national bee draws nearly 250 students from across the
United States, as well as from Mexico, the Bahamas, and the U.S.
territories of Guam, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jamaicans and African-Americans charge that the new rule
was implemented only to keep Jamaica out.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow/PUSH Coalition, founded by the Rev. Jesse Jackson,
has complained to bee officials in a letter that the rule is
``exclusionary.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jamaica -- a small Third World nation that stresses
educational excellence so much its students are introduced to
Shakespeare at age 8 -- the controversy dominates almost all
discussion shows on radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaicans say their poor island proved it could go head-to-head
with the world's richest country when Maxwell won the bee by
correctly spelling C-H-I-A-R-O-S-C-U-R-I-S-T, which means an artist
who works with shades of light.
</P>
<P>
   The win placed Maxwell in the Jamaica national spotlight
alongside Bob Marley and the country's Olympic bobsled team.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica has participated in the bee only twice, in 1997 and in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Jamaica, Jody-Anne is like a Michael Jordan,'' said O'Neil
Hamilton, a spokesman for Jamaica's embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Kimble said she hopes Scripps Howard can re-admit Jamaica to the
annual competition in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But officials with the Daily Gleaner newspaper in Jamaica, which
runs Jamaica's national competition, said no final decision's been
made as to whether the date of the finals will be changed.
</P>
<P>
   So far, this year's finals are still scheduled in August.
</P>
<P>
   If the date's not changed, Scripps Howard will continue to
exclude Jamaica from the bee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't decided anything because the way the finals are set
up now fits nicely with our school curriculum,'' said Anne-Marie
Asher, a spokeswoman for the Daily Gleaner. ``But we're considering
a change because the bee means so much to the people here, and
especially the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kimble said she hopes Jamaica's absence this year
doesn't detract from the bee's significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no ill will towards Jamaica, but rules are rules,''
she said. ``It's very important to maintain the integrity of the
bee.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
