<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0442 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSMOS-$ADV11-COX     04-08 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMOS-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENTISTS, THEOLOGIANS TO DEBATE: DID GOD CAUSE THE BIG BANG?
 &HT;    760&AMP;add. For release Sunday, April 11.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some scientists who study the universe are
beginning to ask if Something did, after all, create everything _
not in six days of cosmic spectacle a few thousand years ago, but
in the instantaneous ``Big Bang'' billions of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Facts collected by instruments such as the Hubble Space
Telescope were supposed to wipe away big hunks of the remaining
uncertainty in the strictly scientific explanation of the origins
of time and space and matter.
</P>
<P>
   That has happened, but a few cosmologists say these new
explorations also have taken them to shores they did not expect to
discover. Now, they say, they think the universe may be too
intricate, too logical, too orderly to have ``just happened'' _
there may have been A Plan to it.
</P>
<P>
   Others, such as Nobel Prize-winning physicist Steven Weinberg of
the University of Texas at Austin, see nothing to suggest a pause
has occurred in the centuries-long assault on religious belief by
science. Weinberg has no patience with talk about the appearance of
a kind of ``common ground'' at the far edges of science and
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like science to go on making religion increasingly
marginal,'' Weinberg said, ``and I'm not sympathetic to any of this
talk of a reconciliation between science and religion.''
</P>
<P>
   But the idea has taken on sufficient intellectual standing that
this week, the American Association for the Advancement of Science
(AAAS), the world's largest and oldest scientific organization,
will sponsor a three-day symposium into the religious implications
of recent scientific discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Religious scholars and scientists, including Weinberg, will
plunge into such subjects as whether anything happened before the
``Big Bang,'' whether the universe is a planned, orderly place, and
whether intelligent life exists elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   These are among ``the most provocative questions in contemporary
cosmology and astronomy,'' the AAAS said in announcing the
symposium.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium is being supported by the North American
Montessori Teachers Association and the John Templeton Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation last month awarded the annual $1.2 million
Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion to physicist-theologian
Ian Barbour, whose writings, it said, have helped to ``set in
motion the ongoing scrutiny of areas where science and religion
might meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbour, once a teaching assistant to nuclear physics pioneer
Enrico Fermi at the University of Chicago, teaches classes in
science, technology and society at Carleton College in Northfield,
Minn. Previous recipients of the prize have included Mother Teresa,
evangelist Billy Graham and Charles Colson, the former Watergate
figure who founded Prison Fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence that interest in religion is growing today
among a significant minority of scientists,'' Barbour said.
``Moreover, a new interest in science can be found in portions of
the religious community today.''
</P>
<P>
   Exquisite measurements by the Hubble telescope have lent strong
evidence to the idea that the observed expansion of the universe
will continue forever, Barbour noted. Previously, scientists who
believe the galaxies and the space between them were created in a
cosmic explosion about 15 billion years ago had wondered whether
the swelling of space would eventually stop and all matter would
reverse itself, eventually converging in the same infinitesimal
point where it all began.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Big Bang'' began to stimulate religious reflection when
British cosmologist Steven Hawking calculated that if conditions at
the moment of the hypothesized burst of creation had been different
by a factor of only one in 100 quadrillion, the universe never
would have appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Such precision does not sound, even to some cosmologists, like
something that ``just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say that the Big Bang may have been only one in an
infinite series of big bangs, each occurring again when all the
matter reconverged. The universe, they say, developed from a Big
Bang that happened to get it right.
</P>
<P>
   The Hubble data suggest that the universe ``will keep expanding,
rather than collapsing, and this does look a little bit more like
the creation story in Genesis than the other model, which offered
the idea of a succession of universes,'' Barbour said. ``This may
be providing some comfort to religious people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Barbour said differences between religious and scientific views
about creation and control of the universe have ranged from mutual
contradiction to dialogue. There is a tendency among some
scientists to ``feel a sense of awe and wonder in response to the
universe which science has disclosed to us.'' This feeling leads to
the impression that there is a design to it all that is best
explained by the will of an ``intelligent and personal God.''
</P>
<P>
   Each body of thought can instruct the other, he says. Ethical
concerns about subjects like genetic cloning, stem cell research
and the release of nuclear energy defy scientific analysis, but can
be meaningfully approached in religious contexts.
</P>
<P>
   The AAAS symposium will begin Wednesday with discussions of the
whether the Big Bang actually happened, whether anything happened
``before'' it, and what, if anything, human beings may ever learn
about the earliest milliseconds of creation.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, scientists will debate the question of whether the
universe was ``designed.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg's answer is direct: ``No.'' John Polkinghorne, former
president of Queens College in Cambridge, England, who became an
Anglican priest after a distinguished career as a physicist, will
take the other side.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium closes Friday with a session on the search for
signs of intelligent life elsewhere in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   To Barbour's description of the range of reactions between
religion and science, Weinberg adds another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my physicist friends are not sufficiently interested
in religion to even qualify as practicing atheists,'' he said. ``I
do care about it. I talk about it, and I think religion is awful.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the symposium will take up timeless questions for
which there may never be answers, Weinberg added, ``I enjoy going
into conferences like this one, where everyone is full of good
thoughts, and playing the role of the cat among the pigeons.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-UTILITY-$ADV11     04-08 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-UTILITY-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELECTRICITY SYSTEM IS A MESS, BUT MEXICANS ARE LEERY OF
PRIVATIZATION PLAN
 &HT;    For release Sunday, April 11
 &HT;    With photos
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY -- Josefina Cruz sets up her produce stand on a
street here every morning before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   To see what she's doing, she plugs a long cable into a
electrical socket and clicks on a bare light bulb.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like an ordinary sequence of events, but consider this:
the socket is embedded in a street utility pole, courtesy of
electrical workers who charged Cruz to install it.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz's arrangement is just one example of Mexico's patch-work
power system, where 10 percent -- maybe as much as 20 percent -- of
electricity is stolen or unaccounted for because of shoddy
infrastructure and jury-rigged hook-ups people here call ``little
devils.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackouts are common fare for jaded consumers, who regularly
offer bribes so their meters are fixed to understate energy use.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to make the system more efficient and to meet a 6
percent annual growth in demand -- mostly from a booming
manufacturing sector -- President Ernesto Zedillo has proposed
privatizing this state-owned industry.
</P>
<P>
   That would open the production and distribution of electricity
to private and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo says $25 billion is needed to expand and upgrade the
nation's electric industry. Without renovation, in as little as six
years it won't be able to generate enough electricity to meet
Mexico's growing needs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, private companies could build and invest in
plants and would be granted 30-year concessions to distribute
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The government would retain control over Mexico's transmission
network, as well as hydroelectric plants and its Laguna Verde
nuclear plant near Veracruz.
</P>
<P>
   If Zedillo's proposal is adopted, ``I believe there will be
fierce competition. It's an enormous and growing market,'' said
John Hushon, president of El Paso Energy International, a
Houston-based subsidiary of El Paso Natural Gas.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1992, Mexico allowed private companies to generate
electricity for their own consumption or to sell to two state-owned
companies.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the changes in 1992, El Paso Energy International
owns 40 percent of a power plant near Ciudad Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's latest proposal, Hushon said, is a ``logical next
step'' after Mexico's initial relaxation of protectionism in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But Zedillo's plan requires a constitutional amendment passed by
a two-thirds vote by Mexico's Congress. Ironically, more democracy
in Mexico -- which has accompanied economic reforms -- may torpedo
the privatization proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo is trying to sell his plan to Congress and the public as
a way to improve electricity delivery and free millions of dollars
in government funds for Mexico's desperate educational and social
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought is, `Why should we spend money on electricity when
the private sector can do it perfectly?' `` said Jonathan Heath, an
economic consultant in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in Mexico, privatization is, unfortunately, a bad word,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans are still shell-shocked from fast-track auctions of
public properties in the early 1990s that resulted in disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Fraud and mismanagement in privatized banks is costing Mexicans
$65 billion for a bailout. Companies that built some of the world's
most expensive toll highways begged Mexico's Congress for their own
$2.4 billion rescue plan.
</P>
<P>
   Caution has bred strong resistance in Mexico's Congress, which
no longer is controlled by Zedillo's party, the Revolutionary
Institutional Party, or PRI, as it has been for most of this
century.
</P>
<P>
   The left-of-center Democratic Revolutionary Party quickly
denounced Zedillo's proposal as a national sell-out. The
conservative National Action Party -- usually backers of free
market reforms -- is also leery.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo can't even count on his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Gonzalez, a PRI deputy in the lower house, said
residential fees that are heavily subsidized by the government have
to be raised to make the electricity industry more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   But he and other PRI members believe the plan must clearly
establish who in the future will pick up the tab for legions of
low-income people in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The free market is never going to bring electricity to a
community of 20 houses miles away from a plant or to the urban poor
that ring cities,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is some union resistance, which is feeding on
Mexicans' nationalistic sensibilities. The Mexican Syndicate of
Electrical Workers in Mexico City has staged a number of large
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Union members are scared they'll lose jobs as state companies
are dissolved and that Mexico will be overwhelmed by foreigners
taking control of the energy industry, including oil, which
Mexicans jealously guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``A crisis doesn't exist in the electricity sector,'' said Ramon
Pacheco, a union leader. ``The constitution should not be touched.
All other alternatives should be explored first.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
