community of 20 houses miles away from a plant or to the urban poor
that ring cities,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is some union resistance, which is feeding on
Mexicans' nationalistic sensibilities. The Mexican Syndicate of
Electrical Workers in Mexico City has staged a number of large
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Union members are scared they'll lose jobs as state companies
are dissolved and that Mexico will be overwhelmed by foreigners
taking control of the energy industry, including oil, which
Mexicans jealously guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``A crisis doesn't exist in the electricity sector,'' said Ramon
Pacheco, a union leader. ``The constitution should not be touched.
All other alternatives should be explored first.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
