<HEADLINE>
SPORTS DRINKS ABOUND, BUT WATER MAY BE THE BEST CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As spring becomes less of a broken promise and
more a reality, weekend athletes start popping up like crocuses.
</P>
<P>
   And as every man, woman and child takes to the parks and bike
paths, they're sure to take a water bottle with them. If they've
bought the hype, they have a sports drink.
</P>
<P>
   You know what we're talking about: the want-to-be-like-Mike
drinks of champions. Gatorade, Powerade, Sportade and dozens of
lesser-known electrolyte-laden beverages, such as Z'lektra Sport
from American Quality Beverages.
</P>
<P>
   None has done a more masterful marketing job than Gatorade, a
Quaker Oats Co. product and the leader of the pack. Introduced to
the American public in 1965, Gatorade now comes in more than two
dozen flavors and seems to be part of the backdrop of every sport
you can find on television.
</P>
<P>
   The company says Gatorade is used by the following pro sports
organizations: NFL, NBA, PGA, NASCAR and Major League Baseball.
When was the last time you saw a Super Bowl end and the coach
wasn't doused with a 50-gallon bucket of Gatorade?
</P>
<P>
   All Powerade, a Coca-Cola Co. product, has to show for itself is
``the official sports drink of the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Z'lektra and the other wannabes are hoping you'll be
willing to experiment.
</P>
<P>
   But should you drink any of these sports drinks, which many
supermarkets now cram together in what they call their ``isotonic
beverages'' section? And is there any difference between Gatorade
and Powerade and the others?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there are differences, and a fair rule of thumb for judging
is this: the smaller the market share, the better the product.
Consider the following: Gatorade, the Microsoft of sports drinks,
has about two-thirds of the desired calories of most of its
competitors, yet it contains more than twice the sodium.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-ounce glass of Gatorade has 50 calories (which, in the
case of sports drinks, more is better) and 110 milligrams of sodium
(which is way more than you need). By comparison, Powerade contains
70 calories and 55 milligrams of sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Z'lektra, made by a Syracuse company available primarily in the
central New York region, has no preservatives, natural colors and
both complex and simple carbohydrates, all claims Gatorade and
Powerade cannot make. It also has 40 milligrams of sodium per
eight-ounce serving.
</P>
<P>
   One nutritionist believes Adam Athlete would be better served
skipping sports drinks altogether and sticking with water.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the average person who does up to an hour or two of
exertion several times a week, the body is quite adept at
conserving chloride and sodium,'' said Jean Bigaouette, who has a
clinical nutrition practice in Albany. ``The body does a good job
of balancing itself out. You don't need the electrolytes in these
sports drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Water is the best replacement fluid,'' Bigaouette adds.
``Besides, those sports drinks don't even taste good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
