A0491 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-08 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL SUFFERING IN TODAY'S GLOBAL VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ These are the times you wish you had an on-off
switch in your brain or lived alone in a cave or somehow had
achieved the Zen ideal of ultimate detachment.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of people are suffering on a biblical
scale, thousands of miles away, and you can do nothing about it but
wring your hands and write checks to relief agencies. Every
instinct in you wants to ignore them, to shove them completely out
of your consciousness _ don't you have enough problems of your own?
_ but you can't.
</P>
<P>
   You can do nothing to help, but you can't stop thinking about
how much help is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, when you wake up in the middle of the night, you
swear you can hear fields of children crying. You can see their
mothers _ thousands of hunched-over shadows _ stretching for miles.
</P>
<P>
   Because you lie in a warm, soft bed, you try to imagine being
pulled from your house at midnight by men in black ski masks with
guns pointed at your face. You try to imagine recognizing the
voices of some of your neighbors behind the masks.
</P>
<P>
   You try to see yourself being told to run or die, leaving behind
everything you own and treasure. You try to imagine tearing
yourself from the arms of the man you love and knowing in your
heart that you may never see him again.
</P>
<P>
   You try, but your own face dissolves from the vision. You can't
imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Every comfort you have _ running water, hot food, a night's
sleep, a loving kiss _ feels like something you've stolen off a
corpse. You try to enjoy a Mozart concerto, a glass of good wine, a
book of poetry, a sunny day.
</P>
<P>
   The great imbalance won't allow the enjoyment to last.
</P>
<P>
   All that is happening in Kosovo, Macedonia and Albania has
invaded the air you breathe. It's eaten up much of the oxygen and
replaced it with an invisible, noxious gas that won't blow away.
</P>
<P>
   Are you obsessed? Perhaps. Or maybe you are simply learning what
it means today to be a member of the human family. Maybe cyberspace
and satellite communications really have built a global village,
and this is the natural result of living in it.
</P>
<P>
   Misery that weighs as much as this misery weighs can't help but
drag millions of bystanders down toward it. Even far-away
bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   You would feel better if this were not so, but would you be
better off? Do you really wish you could resist the weight? Shove
away all traces of that biblical-scale suffering with your Mozart
and your wine and your sunshine? Until you acquire an on-off brain
switch or live alone in a cave or achieve ultimate detachment,
isn't this the way it's supposed to be? When we cannot alleviate
unfathomable human pain, aren't we at least required to share just
some of it?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
