<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METROLAND-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFORMANCES THE ESSENCE OF `METROLAND'S' CHARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Editors: Note use of italics in grafs 1 and 3.  
RATING: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's nothing terribly deep or profound or even
new at the heart of ``Metroland,'' an enjoyably English comedy
about an idealist who wakes up one day and _ (ITALICS)yikes(ITALICS
END) _ realizes he has become his father.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's themes _ the sacrifice of youthful dreams for
grown-up comforts, the vexing difficulties of monogamy and the
undeniable appeal of French women to impressionable young men _
have been done to death and with better results. But ``Metroland''
isn't without its charms, chief of which is a pitch-perfect
performance from Emily Watson, reason enough to recommend this
likable movie.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Julian Barnes novel, ``Metroland'' is about two
childhood friends who have taken very different paths in life.
Chris (Christian Bale) and Toni (Lee Ross) grew up on the suburban
outskirts of London at the end of the London Underground
Metropolitan Line (the Metroland of the film's title). In the early
1960s, the two surly kids were part of the Anger Generation and
expressed complete contempt for anything that smacked of
conformity. Life, for them, was going to be
(ITALICS)different.(ITALICS END)
</P>
<P>
   And for Toni, it worked out that way. When he telephones in 1977
(after a long absence), he's writing bad poetry and jet-setting
around the globe using the credit card of his rich American
girlfriend. Their relationship is nonbinding and, best of all,
nonmonogamous.
</P>
<P>
   Chris, meanwhile, lives in Metroland with his lovely wife Marion
(Watson) and their baby daughter. He's a photographer (good) for an
advertising agency (bad). In other words, in Toni's eyes, he's sold
out. And, increasingly, during late-night, soul-searching walks
through the suburbs, Chris is starting to think that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Chris also has been fondly remembering his bohemian days in
Paris in the late '60s, highlighted by a tempestuous affair with a
beautiful French woman named Annick (Elsa Zylberstein). The
memories have caused a stirring in his loins. Sure, he loves
Marion, but it has been eight years of only Marion. And that wasn't
the way he thought his life was going to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metroland'' shifts between the present and the past, and lead
actors Bale and Ross are quite convincing playing characters that
age 15 to 20 years. The Parisian scenes are rather stock
(Francophiles will love the glowing photography) but contain an
agreeable frankness and a lovely turn by French star Zylberstein.
</P>
<P>
   As Chris struggles with Toni's barbs and his own self-contempt
about his measured, staid, oh-so English rationality, it's the
grounded housewife, Marion, who makes him see his life for what it
is. Not that she doesn't have a surprise or two up her sleeve, too.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's challenging presence gives the film its most original
and intelligent moments, playing a woman who hasn't lost her
idealism even though she has passed her 30th birthday. Dire Straits
leader Mark Knopfler adds a score that, like the film itself, isn't
particularly groundbreaking but has its small pleasures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
