<HEADER>
A0496 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KISSED-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      04-08 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KISSED-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM HAS `NEVER BEEN' DUMBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Note use of italics in two grafs.  
RATING: 2 stars 
By Glenn Whipp  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Adorably lamebrained in a distinctly Drew
Barrymore way, ``Never Been Kissed'' is so far-fetched that it
makes the actress's last fairy-tale movie, ``Ever After,'' seem
like (ITALICS)cinema verite(END ITALICS). Unfortunately, while
Barrymore remains a winning screen presence, ``Never Been Kissed''
is a formulaic fantasy whose supposedly up-with-teens spirit
amounts to nothing more than misguided drivel.
</P>
<P>
   Barrymore plays Josie, a mousy Chicago Sun-Times copy editor
assigned to go undercover at a local high school and report on what
teen-agers are really like. It's a good-news, bad-news scenario for
Josie. The good news: She has always wanted to be a reporter. The
bad: She hated high school and now she has to relive it.
</P>
<P>
   When Josie arrives at school, history does seem to repeat
itself. She shows up dressed in outdated fashions and behaving so
strangely that one student asks, ``Are you in special ed?'' The
popular kids immediately shun Josie and find a variety of painful
ways to humiliate her, bringing back memories of her geeky
adolescence when she was nicknamed Josie Grossie.
</P>
<P>
   But just as she triumphed over her evil stepmother and
stepsisters in ``Ever After,'' Barrymore again rises to the
challenges of today's savage youth with an assist from her older,
underachieving brother (David Arquette), who returns to school to
boost Josie's image and impress baseball scouts. Never mind the
fact that Arquette couldn't pass for a college student, much less a
high school senior.
</P>
<P>
   But then, that far-fetched subplot doesn't have anything on some
of the other, shall we say, improbabilities, here. Examples: As the
youngest copy editor at the Sun-Times, Josie has her own office and
her own (italics)assistant(end italics). Her newspaper has its own
surveillance truck and equips Josie with a mini-camera that
transmits her exploits back to the office. A reporter is fired
because he was scooped on a story. Work stops in the newsroom as
staffers follow each new development with rapt attention.
</P>
<P>
   The high school scenes are equally idiotic. The most misguided
aspect of the movie has Josie's literature teacher, Sam (played by
Mark Harmon look-alike Michael Vartan). Sam develops a thing for
Josie, despite the fact that he thinks she's supposed to be 17. He
flirts, he shares a Ferris wheel ride with Josie, tells her how
special he thinks she is. He even asks her to dance at the prom.
</P>
<P>
   It's handled in a wink-wink way because, after all, we know
Josie is really 25. But we also know that Sam thinks she's 17. When
Josie's editor tells her to go after Sam for his inappropriate
behavior, she's horrified. She won't betray a friend. The thing is,
her editor is right. And that makes the movie's fairy-tale romance
pretty wrong-headed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Barrymore is so darn cute that it's easy to forget
how egregiously stupid the movie is. No actress suffers indignities
better. Barrymore pours her heart into her wounded characters,
making them more sympathetic and endearing than a puppy dog in a
pet shop window.
</P>
<P>
   That's great when the movie is clever. (See ``Ever After.'') But
lip-quivering loopiness can only go so far on its own. And that's a
lesson Barrymore (who also executive produced this movie) needs to
learn before she picks her next project. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1257EDT &QL; 
