<HEADER>
A0510 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN     04-08 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO VERY DIFFERENT FAMILIES IN TURMOIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Edward Norton delivered a powerful performance as
Derek, a racist skinhead, in ``American History X.'' That role
netted him an Oscar nomination for best actor. Meanwhile teen-ager
Leelee Sobieski showed off a maturity and presence beyond her years
in ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries,'' her first major film role.
</P>
<P>
   The two films _ which hit video stores this week _ both have
stories that revolve around families, and both feature excellent
acting.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, ``American'' is the more explosive of the two, but
not the more satisfying. The film was steeped in controversy even
before it opened. Its director, Tony Kaye, took out ads in the
Hollywood trade papers decrying the fact the the studio had recut
his film. Whether it would have been a better film is anyone's
guess. As it stands, ``American'' keeps your attention despite its
flaws, but the brutally edgy film is often undercut by weak plot
contrivances and too many overly melodramatic moments.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Derek, who has been sentenced to prison for
purposely killing two African-Americans after they tried to steal
his car, has a conversion, seeing the error of his ways toward the
film's end. But this epiphany hardly seems real. Derek's hatred
stems from the slaying of his father, a firefighter who was killed
while putting out a blaze in a crack house. For a number of years,
he falls under the influence of the neo-Nazi Cameron (Stacy Keach),
carrying out the older man's agenda. It's made clear during the
film that Derek is bright, even reasonable, and you wonder how he
could be blinded so long.
</P>
<P>
   But he is, and nowhere during this time does he show any concern
for his family and how he's destroying their lives with his
viciousness, particularly his younger brother, Danny (Edward
Furlong), who is following in his footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two years of prison where he shows no remorse,
he sees that the other neo-Nazis in his cellblock are not as
``righteous'' as he because they sell drugs. This and some kindness
shown to him by an African-American inmate are supposedly enough
for Derek to have a change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``American History X,'' though, should be given credit for
addressing this country's skinhead culture with a cold eye. Besides
Norton's tour de force, Furlong and the rest of cast's strong
performances help viewers overlook some of the film's gaps in
logic.
</P>
<P>
   Sobieski is also surrounded by a marvelous cast in the
Merchant-Ivory film ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries.'' Based on
the novel by Kaylie Jones, the daughter of James Jones (``From Here
to Eternity,'' ``The Thin Red Line''), the film is somewhat
autobiographical. It's the story of novelist Bill Willis (Kris
Kristofferson) and his family living in Paris during the '60s and
'70s, told from the point of view of his daughter, Channe
(Sobieski). When Channe is quite young, Willis and his wife,
Marcella (Barbara Hershey), adopt a 6-year-old French boy, who was
born out of wedlock to a 15-year-old mother.
</P>
<P>
   The story quickly shifts to the children's adolescent years, as
Channe and Billy (Jesse Bradford) struggle through the difficulties
of gaining acceptance in schools, while their father struggles with
his writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Soldier's Daughter'' is one of those perfect Merchant-Ivory
films (``Howards End,'' ``Remains of the Day,'' ``A Room With a
View'') that probes relationships, societal manners and emotions.
It's often the characters who drift in and out of the story that
help define it.
</P>
<P>
   There's Francis Fortescue (Anthony Roth Constanzo), the boy who
befriends Channe and is set on a life of art; Candida (Dominique
Blanc), who refuses to marry though wanting to; and Billy's real
mother, whose tale haunts the film.
</P>
<P>
   And Merchant-Ivory films always feature great acting.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe how much Kristofferson seems to inhabit the
role. His earthy touches are perfect. The underappreciated Hershey
again displays her emotional juggling act _ from happy to manic in
the blink of an eye. And Sobieski is simply impressive.
</P>
<P>
   What happens in ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries,'' you may
ask? Well, you know and you don't know, and that's the beauty of
it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
