<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0538 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUMBABY-TEX     04-08 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUMBABY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLES TRYING TO DELIVER THE FIRST BABY OF THE NEW CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRY LEE GOODRICH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, Texas _ Christine Benton is preparing for a rigorous
race. She has undergone a physical and says she's in good shape.
She's taking plenty of vitamins and even has a uniform picked out.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike an Olympian hoping to bring home a medal in 2000,
Benton's trophy would be swaddled in a soft blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Benton, 32, of Haltom City wants to have a baby on Jan. 1, 2000.
So she and her husband will be off and running on Friday _ the day
given by obstetricians and gynecologists as the ideal day to
conceive a baby to be born on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be kind of neat,'' Benton said. ``It is
something that we could say years later, `This is what happened.' I
hope we have a little girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Benton and her husband are not alone in their effort to produce
the first Y2K baby. They will face competition potentially from
thousands of other couples.
</P>
<P>
   Baby races are going on across the United States. In the
Dallas-Fort Worth Metroplex, radio station KYNG/105.3 FM will put
up 20 married couples in a hotel on Friday. The couple that has the
baby earliest in 2000 will win at least $2,000, KYNG officials
said. And no inducing labor or having a Caesarean.
</P>
<P>
   The Bentons hope to be one of the contestants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will kind of be like a honeymoon,'' said Benton, who has
bought a new dress for the occasion. ``I'm hoping it will be kind
of romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   It will definitely be a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Preston, a Bedford obstetrician and gynecologist, said
``only about 5 percent of people will deliver on the due date.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone embraces the idea of trying for that Y2K baby. One
who dislikes the baby race is child psychologist Robert R.
Butterworth of International Trauma Associates in Los Angeles, who
appears frequently on national talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``As if children don't have enough to worry about growing up in
this world, parents are trying to burden them with another
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will do nothing for the child,'' he said, questioning the
parents' motivation. ``But I have to admit it will be a good
research project for developmental psychologists in 2020 to see how
these `special' babies turned out.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, there are lots of ways to boost chances of
a pregnancy, doctors and midwives say.
</P>
<P>
   One recommendation is that would-be fathers wear boxers rather
than briefs _ a valid strategy, doctors say. That means a romantic
evening in the hot tub might not be the proper warm-up for couples
who want a bun in the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, the experts say, timing is everything. Because
egg and sperm are short-lived, and there are only a few days a
month when a woman is fertile, doctors and midwives generally
consult a ``fertility wheel,'' a round device about the size of a
compact disc. It's a calendar of sorts, based on the assumption
that a woman has a 28-day menstrual cycle and that the due date
will be 40 weeks from the first day of the last menstrual period
before conception.
</P>
<P>
   Individual lengths of cycles must be taken into account, Preston
said. But generally speaking, conception for a Y2K baby should
probably occur in the first 10 days of April.
</P>
<P>
   To help women pinpoint their conception time, ovulation kits
costing about $25 abound in drugstores, most requiring urine tests.
A variation on that is Ovu-Tec, said Hurst midwife Gail Johnson of
Well Woman Health Care Associates. About the size of a lipstick,
it's a microscope that can be tucked into a purse and used as a
gauge for a saliva test.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you do is lick it and examine the dried saliva under the
microscope,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   If you see bunches of what look like little ferns _ go for it,
she advised. But shapeless blobs won't do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Ovulation kits could give false positives, and boxers don't
always work, experts say. Still, modern methods make for better
odds than fertility rites from ancient times, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In certain Latin-American cultures, a pomegranate was brought
to the altar for the moon goddess, cut in half and covered with
honey, and the name of the woman written on paper and placed
between the halves,'' said Johnson, who consulted Carol Dunham's
book ``Mamatoto: A Celebration of Birth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was that the woman became ripe like the fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancient Malayans had a more chauvinistic approach, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They regarded man as a higher rational being than woman,'' she
said. ``They thought the baby was in the brain of the man and fell
down,'' ending up inside the woman.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a smidgen of truth in that, she said. ``After all,
doesn't sex begin in the brain?''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
