<HEADLINE>
IN INDIANA, HISTORY IS SEEN FROM A DIFFERENT ANGLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRILLVILLE, Ind. _ When NATO bombs rain down on Belgrade, they
are felt here in a Byzantine church built on a former corn field,
where a perplexed priest in a black robe gives history lessons to
anyone who will listen.
</P>
<P>
   The Very Rev. Jovan Todorovich leaned forward Wednesday in his
chair and, through a thick accent of his homeland, lamented the
slaughter of 77,000 Serbs in Kosovo at the hands of the Turks in
1389. His hands shaking slightly, Todorovich told the story as
though it happened the night before, and if people only knew it,
they would realize NATO is bombing the wrong side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we an enemy? Why are we a pariah of the Balkans?
Kosovo was ours, Kosovo is ours, and Mr. Clinton better register
this: Kosovo will remain ours, one way or another,'' the Serbian
Orthodox priest said quietly, more a vow than a threat.
</P>
<P>
   It is a particularly American phenomenon that no matter whom the
United States is at odds with, there are hyphenated Americans who
hail from, or trace their lineage to, a place that has been deemed
enemy soil.
</P>
<P>
   Just as consistently, those Americans with immigrant roots have
sought to correct what they consider misunderstandings about their
homeland, while also maintaining their own stars-and-stripes
patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   In northwest Indiana along the southern edge of Lake Michigan
lies a region that by some estimates is home to 100,000
Serbian-Americans. By dint of numbers alone, that makes it the
wellspring of Serbian support on US soil and _ in light of the past
two weeks of bombing _ a slow-boiling cauldron of anger,
frustration and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Merrillville, a town of 32,000 people 90 minutes from Chicago,
is arguably the Serbian-American capitol, home to two of the
region's four Serbian Orthodox churches, as well as a Greek
Orthodox Cathedral and the oldest Macedonian Orthodox church in the
nation. Aside from those grand, domed edifices, there is nothing
especially impressive about Merrillville. It is a flat, featureless
area with car dealerships and endless strip malls.
</P>
<P>
   But to Serbs and other Eastern European immmigrants it has been
a land of opportunity. They poured into this area beginning 100
years ago, drawn by jobs at Big Steel _ United States Steel Corp. _
and Little Steel _ Inland Steel Co. _ in neighboring Gary. And just
as their fathers and grandfathers withstood the searing heat of
steel mill furnances, today's residents have resisted the cultural
melting pot, reveling in their status as Americans of Balkan
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Roknich is a retired machinist and an officer in the Loyal
American Serbian Democratic Club. Zarko Korac is a retired trucker
and president of the Serbian Republican Club. There is little about
public policy these two men agree on, but they are political
soulmates on one subject.
</P>
<P>
   In separate conversations, each proudly recalled Serbia's warm
relationship with the United States during World War II. Each
invoked Serbs' rescue of several hundred allied pilots shot down
during bombing raids. Both suggested the NATO pilots flying the
current raids have betrayed that bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are seen as the Nazis,'' said Korac, 80, an American
for nearly 50 years. ``It's not very far back we were fighting with
Germany to help get American pilots home, and now America does
this? For what? For Albanians? No, that shouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Roknich told his own version of the history, also with a sharp
jab at the Albanian Kosovars whose treatment by Serbian forces
under Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic triggered the NATO
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to America, I speak the language of this country.
But those Albanians never want to speak Serbo-Croatian,'' he said.
``Albania was poor, so they came to Kosovo, and they had 8, 9, 10
children to a family. All of a sudden they are a majority on Serb
land, and they push the Serbs out of there and they want their own
country. What if the Mexicans tried to do that in Texas or
California? We'd never allow it, but in Serbia, (NATO) supports
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Local Serbian-Americans are quick to note that warmth toward
their homeland does not extend to Milosevic, who is routinely
denounced as a communist and a barbarian. And yet, his pursuit of
total authority over Kosovo wins him grudging respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose side are you going to be on, the United States when they
bomb Serbia? We're not for Milosevic, we're for keeping what is
Serbian. If NATO didn't interfere, eventually the Serbs would get
rid of him themselves,'' said Olga Dotlich, president of the
Serbian Sisters of St. Sava, a women's group at Todorovich's
church.
</P>
<P>
   At Bronko's, a tavern in neighboring Crown Point that is a
gathering spot for Serbian-Americans, there is a general sense that
the Serbs are misunderstood and misrepresented by the media. There
have been no reported incidents of Serbian-Americans suffering as a
result, but tavern regulars wonder how long that will last.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs are being portrayed like the Palestinians were in
the '60s and '70s, as people who don't want peace,'' said Peter
Flemming, whose father was Serbian. ``The Serbs only don't want
peace if it's a peace where the Albanians get everything.''
</P>
<P>
   At Todorovich's church, the St. Sava Serbian Orthodox Church,
the bells have been rung throughout daylight hours every day since
the bombing began, in sadness and solidarity. ``I'm trying to be
forgiving, to have compassion, for the Albanians, for everyone. But
I think of Kosovo and it starts digging inside me,'' the priest
said, his voice trailing off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
