<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUANTANAMO-REFUGEES-A     04-08 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUANTANAMO-REFUGEES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS GROUPS DECRY GUANTANAMO AS REFUGEE SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Kosovar refugees being relocated to the US
naval base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba will be trading life in one no
man's land for another, human-rights advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't simply a question of conditions _ though people
familiar with Guantanamo call it a ``hell-hole'' of shadeless
concrete, steamy tents, and barbed wire that will be anything but
welcoming to the ethnic Albanian refugees who are expected to begin
arriving in Cuba by US airlift as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The key concern is that Guantanamo is not a US territory.
Refugees who come there, even under the auspices of an American
humanitarian mission, have no civil rights under the Constitution
and, unlike refugees on US soil, have no status to apply for asylum
and resettlement in the United States under immigration laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is appalling,'' said Michael Ratner, a lawyer for the
nonprofit Center for Constitutional Rights in New York. ``These
people are not prisoners, they are refugees. If this is a
humanitarian operation, then the Kosovars should be brought to the
US mainland for safe haven and not put in Guantanamo, which is
really a hell-hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratner, who in a series of court cases argued _ largely
unsuccessfully _ for the rights of Haitian refugees held at
Guantanamo Bay in the early 1990s, said he thinks the Clinton
administration chose to shelter the Kosovars on foreign land to
avoid the issue of whether they have a right to resettle in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   J. Brian Atwood, who is heading the US refugee-relocation
operation, said there is no urgency on the immigration issue
because the Kosovar refugees want to go home, not to the United
States. In fact, Atwood said he was not sure when the airlift to
Guantanamo would begin or how many refugees would depart the region
because ``a lot of people don't want to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want (the refugees) to understand where they are going and
what the facilities are,'' said Atwood, who is administrator of the
US Agency for International Development. ``We are not sure how many
will want to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced Tuesday it was prepared to accommodate
as many as 20,000 refugees from Kosovo at the US naval base at
Guantanamo. US officials stressed that the relocation would be
temporary. The Kosovars would not even be processed as refugees by
the US Naturalization and Immigration Service, an INS spokesman
said, because the mission is to provide the Kosovars a haven until
it is safe for them to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our anticipation is that they are going to be allowed to
return to their homeland,'' said Russ Bergeron, an INS spokesman.
``To create a scenario where the vast majority of the Kosovars
would be given permanent refugee status would play into the hands
of (Yugoslav President) Milosevic and would further his goal of
ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees, defined under international law as individuals
persecuted in their homeland, are admitted to the United States
under an annual quota system and once here are entitled to a host
of benefits, including food stamps, Medicaid, and job training.
Most important, they are allowed to apply to become permanent
residents after one year and to have family members join them in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But refugees outside the United States have no such rights, the
US Supreme Court ruled in 1993 in a case that tested whether aliens
outside the US territory _ in this case, Haitians intercepted on
the high seas _ were entited to protections under the Immigration
and Nationality Act.
</P>
<P>
   So the rights normally afforded refugees in the United States
won't apply to the Kosovars at a US naval base in Cuba, just as
they would not apply if the Kosovar refugees were housed at the US
air base in Aviano, Italy, Bergeron said. ``In a broad sense, these
are not legal refugees, and they have no immigration status, since
there is no intention of letting them immigrate to the United
States,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said it will inform the ethnic Albanian
refugees who volunteer for relocation to Guantanamo that they will
not be entitled to apply for political asylum in the United States.
But J. Brian Atwood, the US official coordinating the refugee
operation, acknowledged Wednesday the administration ``would have
to re-evaluate the (immigration) situation'' if Kosovars were at
Guantanamo for more than six months.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Acer, who coordinates the asylum program for the Lawyers
Committee for Human Rights in New York, said refugee advocacy
groups like hers will press the administration to allow the
Kosovars freedom to travel, to obtain legal counsel, and eventually
to be brought into the United States, either to immigrate or to
unite with family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our big concern is leaving them in legal limbo for long,''
Acer said.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Immigration Minister Lucienne Robillard announced on
Tuesday the 5,000 Kosovar refugees Canada agreed to accept would
have freedom to move around the country, live with host families,
and be allowed to stay permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Senator Susan Collins, a Maine Republican,
suggested to the State Department that 500 Kosovar refugees might
find the climate and living conditions more comfortable at the
shuttered Loring Air Force Base in Limestone, in northern Maine.
The State Department refused, according to Felicia Knight,
Collins's spokeswoman, citing its desire to keep the Kosovars
together in one place.
</P>
<P>
   But Irwin Stotzky, director of the Center for the Study of Human
Rights at the University of Miami Law School, said the decision to
confine the Kosovars to a ``detention facility in a hot, tropical
climate with nothing to do'' appears more political than
humanitarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the purpose of accepting 20,000 Kosovar refugees is to show
NATO and Macedonia that the United States is doing its fair share,
then these refugees are being used as political pawns,'' said
Stotzky, a legal advocate for Haitian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``By taking the refugees to Guantanamo, we could be put in the
embarrassing position of violating the refugees' human rights,
which is just what we are trying to protect them from,'' Stotzky
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
