<HEADLINE>
LA TIMES'S EYES ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every day the dispatches roll in from forbidden and foreboding
territory. Wednesday, there was the report _ from the checkpoint
between Kosovo and Macedonia _ of some Kosovo refugees turning
around and heading home. On Tuesday, it was an eyewitness account
of a very uncomfortable meeting in Pristina between Kosovo leader
Ibrahim Rugova and Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister Nikola Sainovic.
On Monday, the story detailed attempts to administer criminal
justice on the empty streets of Pristina, including the tale of a
``journalist'' briefly detained by local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   That journalist putting himself in harm's way by filing reports
from the hellish scene in Kosovo is Los Angeles Times correspondent
Paul Watson, believed to be the only American reporter currently
based there. As testimony to the risks inherent in such work,
Watson has already had two rented bulletproof vehicles confiscated
by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does difficult stories,'' says Times editor Michael Parks
of Watson. ``It's a real calling.'' Asked if he worries about his
reporter, Parks responded, ``all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, 39, was hired by the Times in September as its Vienna
bureau chief and has been stationed in the Balkans ever since. At a
time when other journalists have been exiled from the war zone, he
has been producing a steady stream of stories with Kosovo
datelines. (His dispatches can be read on line at
http://www.latimes.com/home/news/reports/yugo/dispatch.)
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Watson is reprising the role of Caryle Murphy, the
Washington Post reporter who spent nearly a month as the only
American newspaper reporter in Kuwait during the 1990 Iraqi
invasion. She was forced underground, hiding from the Iraqis until
she finally escaped to Saudi Arabia wearing a disguise. For her
remarkable efforts, Murphy was awarded with a Pulitzer Prize for
international reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Given the events he describes in his reports, Watson has cropped
up in public, must be known to the Serbian authorities, and has not
had to completely emulate Murphy's clandestine existence. But like
Murphy, he, too, has claimed a Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, as Africa correspondent for The Toronto Star, Watson
became the first Canadian to win the coveted award for his famous
photograph of a dead American serviceman being dragged through the
streets of Mogadishu in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers believe that the emotionally charged photo forced
America to reverse its policy and withdraw from Somalia. In a story
about Watson's Pulitzer that appeared in the Star, he was quoted as
saying that ``military people have told me to my face that (the
photo) degrades the American military . . . that it destroyed
morale and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Watson's Kosovo-based accounts of
another dangerous intervention will have the same impact.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a strange multimedia story brewing in San Diego where a
man claiming to be the victim of an aggressive TV reporter has
taken matters _ and revenge _ into his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   About three weeks ago, Colin Flaherty _ who describes himself as
a former journalist turned public relations man _ started a Web
site dedicated to harassing Mark Matthews, a reporter for station
KGTV in San Diego. In order to spread the word, Flaherty hyped the
site in e-mails he sent to ``San Diego opinion leaders'' and
members of the San Diego Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty says his action is basic tit for tat: Matthews, he
says, invaded his privacy in pursuit of a story about who wrote a
fake letter to the editor. And now he's returning the favor. The
site _ called ``Mark and Me: Tales of an Investigative Reporter'' _
includes accounts of Matthews's alleged ``ambush'' journalism,
solicits other complaints about him, and even features photos and a
map of Matthews's home.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he's worried about violating Matthews's privacy,
Flaherty responds that ``this is 100 percent the point. I want
Channel 10 (KGTV) to come back to me and define . . . what the
limits of coverage are. . . . I'm going to engage Channel 10 in a
very public discussion of what it is people can do to get a news
story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're puzzled by this. We don't understand this. Mark is an
award-winning reporter,'' says Neal Allen, a spokesman for KGTV.
``If this is intended to have a chilling effect on our news
gathering, it will not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, 70 US newspapers (from the Los Angeles Times to The
Wausau (Wis.) Daily Herald) and 43 Associated Press bureaus have
signed on for the National Time-Out for Diversity and Accuracy
sponsored by the American Society of Newspaper Editors and the
Associated Press Managing Editors.
</P>
<P>
   The Time-Out is a fresh attempt to tackle a stale problem.
America's newsrooms _ where only one in every nine desks is
occupied by a minority _ are too often bastions of demographic,
cultural, and philosophical homogeneity. Traditionally, newsroom
diversity has been considered a matter of equality and morality.
But Time-Out organizers want to reframe the issue, in the words of
Michael Dukakis, as one of competence, not ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Time-Out for Diversity and Accuracy is based on
the common sense proposition that in order for a newspaper to be
accurate, it should look like its community,'' stated ``Time-Out''
organizer David Yarnold at a March 29 press conference kicking off
the initiative in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnold says that during the Time-Out, scheduled for the week of
May 17, newspapers will conduct content audits, examine how sources
are chosen, discuss how stories are framed, and take a hard look at
the structure of beats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
