<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS STILL BANKS ON PITINO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- What happens when a company signs up a star to
represent it and the star suddenly loses his luster?
</P>
<P>
   That's a question Citizens Bank could be asking these days. In
the fall of 1997 Citizens paid an estimated $5 million for five
years and outbid its two larger rivals to become the bank of the
Boston Celtics. Citizens later signed a separate deal with coach
Rick Pitino, and made him the centerpiece of its radio and
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The move made a lot of sense. Pitino is good-looking,
articulate, and has the reputation of being a winner. There's only
one problem: Pitino and the Celtics aren't winning. In fact, they
are having a disastrous season.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago the Celtics were talked about as a playoff team.
Today they have one of the worst records in the league. The team
has lost consistently at home and there have been suggestions _
denied by Pitino _ that some of the players have quit on him. Just
this week the coach benched point guard Kenny Anderson for one game
for an unspecified discipline problem.
</P>
<P>
   Who brought underachievers like Anderson to Boston? Celtics
president Rick Pitino, one of those rare people in sports with the
power both to recruit players and coach them. In the memorable
words of football coach Bill Parcells, Pitino cooks the meals and
shops for the groceries. Based on the results, you might think
twice before sending him to the supermarket. Pitino traded the
number-three pick in the draft for Anderson. He also traded away
next year's first-round pick for Vitaly Potapenko, a 7-footer who,
so far, has come up short in the performance department.
</P>
<P>
   Off the court, Pitino has developed a hate-hate relationship
with the callers to sports talk radio. They call him ``Little
Ricky.'' He derisively refers to them as the ``fellowship of the
miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does Citizens Bank think of its poster boy?
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen any negative impact,'' says Hal Tovin, the
bank's chief marketing officer. On the contrary, the feedback the
bank has received on its Pitino ads could hardly be better,
according to Tovin. He says a recent survey commissioned by the
bank found that consumers consider Pitino credible, believable, and
likable. Even better, the Pitino commercials have helped Citizens
sell more home equity loans.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens also uses Pitino to give speeches and chat up
customers. There too, the results have been impressive, says Tovin.
``He is still very good at getting people to come out,'' Tovin
points out.
</P>
<P>
   Tovin is no rookie when it comes to sports. At Shawmut Bank he
developed relationships with all four sports team in Boston and
helped negotiate the deal that put Shawmut's name on the new
basketball and hockey arena, now the FleetCenter. ``Any time you go
into sports there will be blips up and down,'' says Tovin. ``We
take that risk. But Rick Pitino is a quality individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people around town who know sports think Citizens still has
a valuable property on its hands. ``Rick Pitino has a tradition of
winning,'' says Larry Moulter, president of Woolf Associates, a
sports marketing firm. ``He's rebuilding this team and that isn't
going to be accomplished overnight. These are just bumps in the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Pile, who owns his own marketing and consulting company,
agrees there is no reason for Citizens to panic. ``My instinct
tells me things will turn around,'' says Pile. ``This won't
negatively affect Citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one top advertising executive, who asked not to be
identified by name, sounded more like a member of the ``fellowship
of the miserable.'' As he put it, ``I think Pitino's effectiveness
is greatly diminished. I don't think the bank is getting its
money's worth right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino himself probably isn't letting all this negativity get to
him. His $6-million a year paycheck soothes a lot of pain. On top
of that, the man who comes through in his 1997 management and
motivation book, ``Success Is A Choice,'' is relentlessly upbeat.
The book lays out 10 steps for overachieving in business and life.
Some of the steps include, ``always be positive,'' ``thrive on
pressure,'' and ``learn from adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Success is not a lucky break,'' writes Pitino. ``It is not a
divine right. It is not an accident of birth. Success is a
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the obvious question: Is failure a choice too?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
