<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0550 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-08 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAGE AN ATTACK ON SERBIA'S `SOFT ASSETS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Washington Post has reported that Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic had sent his son, daughters, and grandchildren
to Crete for an extended vacation. One presumes that other children
and grandchildren of the Milosevic elite are likewise ensconced,
far away from NATO air strikes and the possibility of personal
collateral damage. Precious assets get special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the United States and its NATO allies have devoted all
of their resources to attacking ``hard'' military assets in
Yugoslavia. These include missile defense systems, communications
infrastructure, ammunition depots, and the like. Cruise missiles
and laser guided bombs rain down on these targets with stepped-up
intensity. The Clinton administration believes these attacks are
``working.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience teaches that aerial assaults will not reverse what
has already happened in Kosovo. Two weeks ago, Pristina, the
capital city of Kosovo, was a bustling community of 250,000 ethnic
Albanians. Today, it has 300, according to one news account. The
battle for Kosovo is over. The Serbs have won. The only thing that
will reverse this outcome is an allied invasion of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of 19 NATO countries agreeing to use ground
troops in the Balkans is not great. The best the air campaign can
hope to accomplish is to make Milosevic more flexible when the
inevitable ``peace conference'' is convened. So the question
arises: What should the United States and its NATO allies do to
weaken Milosevic's negotiating posture?
</P>
<P>
   First, the United States and its NATO allies should continue the
air war on Yugoslavia without interruption. Degrading the military
assets and the communications infrastructure of the Serbian army
diminishes its ability to wreak further havoc in the Balkans.
Milosevic's unilateral cease-fire was patently bogus and rightly
rejected out of hand. The air war on hard assets should increase
and intensify with each passing day.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the United States should begin to mobilize a ground
force for deployment in the Balkans. Troops can be introduced into
Albania under the cover story that they are there to help with
humanitarian and relief efforts. The United States can do this
without NATO approval. Milosevic will get the point.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the United States and its NATO allies should mount an
aggressive campaign against the ``soft assets'' of the Milosevic
elite. In the past, campaigns against ``soft assets'' have taken
the form of economic sanctions and have not been particularly
successful. But just because they haven't worked against, say,
Iraq, does not mean that a ``soft assets'' campaign won't work
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian elites see themselves as cosmopolitan Europeans. They
educate their children abroad. They travel frequently throughout
the region. They shop in Athens, attend fashion shows in Milan,
dine at the finest restaurants in Paris. They care about all that _
a lot more than they care about Kosovo. The point of a ``soft
assets'' campaign would be to take all that away.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its NATO allies should publish on the
Internet a list of the names of the 3,000 to 5,000 people (and
their families) who comprise the Milosevic elite. Once published,
anyone who is on the list or related to someone on the list would
be denied entry into every NATO country.
</P>
<P>
   All existing visas would be canceled. All students would be sent
home. All businessmen would be sent packing. All diplomats would be
told to get out. Let the Serbian elites educate their children in
Moscow. Let them shop in Belgrade. Kick them out and never let them
back through customs again until Kosovo is restored.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its NATO allies should also freeze and
seize all financial assets of the Milosevic elite. Serbian elites
are legendarily corrupt. Over the years, they have stolen hundreds
of millions of dollars from their country. Many of these assets are
tucked away in Swiss banks and off-shore accounts. They use these
money havens to protect themselves in the event that their
countrymen someday take exception to their malfeasance.
</P>
<P>
   The Genocide Convention, signed after World War II by most
countries, including the United States and Yugoslavia, establishes
genocide as an international crime and makes possible criminal and
civil charges against specific individuals. The United States and
its NATO allies should freeze and seize all financial assets of the
Milosevic elite as part of a concerted legal effort to prosecute
specific individuals on charges of genocide.
</P>
<P>
   A ``soft assets'' campaign could be very effective. It might
make the Milosevic elite realize that they will never be Europeans
so long as they occupy Kosovo. It could steal back the money they
stole. And it could serve as a kind of test case for future ``soft
asset'' campaigns, which may become necessary if, for example,
nationalist forces in Russia prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Waging a ``soft asset'' campaign against Yugoslavia would set
useful legal precedents for the future. And it just might split the
Milosevic elite into warring factions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
