<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CHILDREN SEE THAT PARENTS AREN'T PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As parents, we know we aren't perfect. Our children, however,
think we are, at least when they are young. Depending on how and
when we fall off our pedestal, their reaction can range from mild
disappointment to intense anger: From their perspective, we have
let them down, and that is no small thing.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Brotter, father of three boys, found out the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   One evening last January, as he was driving the family to his
brother's birthday dinner, their car was hit nearly head-on. Both
air bags inflated, emitting an acrid smoke that caused Brotter and
his wife, Deborah Jurkowitz, to think the car was on fire. (For the
record, Jurkowitz is my cousin.) Amid lights and sirens, police and
two ambulances arrived. No one in their family was hurt, but the
occupants of the other car were taken away on stretchers and their
car was towed. Later, Jurkowitz went to the emergency room for
minor bruises.
</P>
<P>
   For Jesse, 5, Cody, 7, and Jake, 12, this was indeed a scary
scene.
</P>
<P>
   That night and the next day, they talked as a family about how
frightened they had been. Cody, however, began acting out toward
his father. ``If I tried to help or comfort him, he pushed me
away,'' says Brotter. ``If I talked to him, he put his hands over
his ears.'' Day 2 was even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Brotter is a psychotherapist who recognized not only
that Cody needed to get his anger out but also that he needed
Brotter's permission to be angry with him. ``As the driver, I had
let him down, I had put the family in danger,'' says Brotter. ``I
told him I wouldn't be surprised if he was angry at me because,
even though I did a good job of preventing a worse accident, I
wasn't able to keep it from happening altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody responded with fury: ``I am mad at you!''
</P>
<P>
   Being able to confront his father worked like a charm for Cody;
anger spent, his behavior soon returned to normal. Brotter,
however, felt worse. ``It was one thing to know it intellectually,
but to hear my son tell me I had let him down in such a big way
made me feel awful,'' he says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
An adaptive process &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All parents disappoint their children sooner or later. Happily,
most of us don't come off the pedestal with such a loud thunk.
</P>
<P>
   Young children think parents are omnipotent, giving us powers
that are beyond human capability. ``They can be angry with you that
you didn't keep a pet from dying or a best friend from moving
away,'' says psychologist Susan Linn of the Judge Baker Children's
Center in Boston. This is an adaptive process, she says; when they
are young and powerless, the world would feel too overwhelming if
they didn't think Mom and Dad could provide total safety and
security.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at about age 7 and continuing for several years,
however, children enter a developmental stage where they gradually
come to understand that parents have strengths and weaknesses like
everybody else and that there is a certain amount of randomness in
the world beyond even our control.
</P>
<P>
   In the normal course of events, this doesn't frighten them as
much as we think because they are also developing a greater sense
of self-control, says psychologist and researcher Judith Newman of
Pennsylvania State University. ``As they become more competent,
they have less need for us to be all-powerful and all-protective,''
she says. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Growing awareness &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Typically, this growing awareness comes from life's daily
disappointments: You forget to send him to school with lunch; you
get caught in traffic and miss the first half of her soccer game.
When it is provoked by something traumatic, however, like a car
accident, it can be more dramatic: ``If you can't protect me from
this, what can you protect me from?''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ordinary disappointments, even though a child
seems angry about the event itself, that's only half the story,
says family psychologist Linda Budd of St. Paul. ``He's really
angry that you messed up,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Parents aren't supposed to do that.
</P>
<P>
   If the mess-up is small, and assuming you don't make matters
worse by ignoring or denying it, the incongruity is absorbed
without much difficulty. But if you disappoint him consistently _
you miss game after game _ or in big way, it can be shattering.
``It's as if she's looking at you for the first time: `Omigod, this
person is not who I thought he was!' '' says Budd.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, a parent is off the pedestal in a very specific
way: only as a driver, for instance, or only as a driver on the
street where the accident happened. Budd tells of a father who
missed his 8-year-old's birthday party because bad weather
prevented him from returning from a business trip. Even though he
had been at her party every other year, for the next three years,
as her birthday neared, she would tell him, ``I guess you won't be
here for my party this year, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Budd says the response was self-defensive. ``She's protecting
herself so if there is another disappointment, it won't be so
bad,'' she says. Had the parent taken it personally _ asking
angrily, ``Why do you keep bringing up the one party I missed?!
I've been at every other party all your life!'' _ he would have
denied her her reality. A steady dose of that, says family
psychologist Peter Goldenthal of Children's Hospital of
Philadelphia, and a child learns not to share feelings because she
doesn't want to incur your anger. (She'll also stop telling you if
it makes you so sad you're tearful.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Facing up to the letdown &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you know you've let your child down, Goldenthal and others
urge parents to:
</P>
<P>
   --Validate the disappointment: ``I know it was hard for you not
to have me at your birthday party.''
</P>
<P>
   --Acknowledge that you blew it: ``I thought I did a good job of
planning, but it turned out I didn't. I'm really sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   --Express your own disappointment: ``I hated missing your party;
it made me very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   --Promise to try harder next time: ``From now on, I'm planning
my trips more carefully so this won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing what to say is sometimes not as much of a problem as
knowing that you need to say anything at all. With children who are
not expressive or in touch with their feelings, we may not even
know we have disappointed them. Goldenthal's advice is siple: ``If
you even think she thinks you've let her down, ask her if that's
so,'' no matter how young or old she is.
</P>
<P>
   This is easier to do if you start when your children are young
to create an atmosphere where feelings get talked about, including
angry feelings about you. Otherwise, he says, over time, feelings
of disappointment bottle up and lead to loss of trust, withdrawal,
or antisocial behavior. ``I see parents who feel badly and don't
say so because they think talking about it makes a child feel
worse. Not true,'' he says. ``Resentment builds quickly, especially
in teens.''
</P>
<P>
   The older the child, the more likely he'll tell you, ``It's not
a big deal.'' If he typically handles disappointment well, perhaps
you can take him at his word. But if his history is that he'll wake
up tomorrow with a stomachache, push it further: `` `I think I let
you down. How you feel is important to me, so I reserve the right
to ask you again later.' '' Even if you never get a response,
you've modeled self-awareness and introspection.
</P>
<P>
   After Brotter had his conversation with Cody, he repeated it to
his other sons to give them the opportunity to confront him with
their anger, too. Neither did. Jesse continued to talk about the
noise, the lights, and the air bags; at 5, he's in a stage of
concrete thinking, where a child can focus on only one thing at a
time. But psychologist Linn says anger could surface in a year or
two when he's at a different stage of development.
</P>
<P>
   Jake didn't express any anger either, perhaps because he's
already learned that sometimes things happen that are beyond our
control or because he's at a stage where it will take more effort
to get him to express his feelings. With a child this age,
Goldenthal recommends coming back to the subject in a few months.
``It's never too late to get feelings out or make amends,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Then he grows quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he says, ``I disappointed my daughter a few months
back when I couldn't be a guest reader in her class. I've had in my
mind that I would ask the teacher if I can read in the spring
instead but I've never told my daughter that that's my plan. I
could use a little of my own advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Brotter, meanwhile, is continually going back to the subject.
All three boys had some trepidation driving with him after the
accident, but Cody was the most anxious, often sitting in the back
seat with eyes wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could promise it will never happen again, but I know
that would be a mistake,'' Brotter says wisely. Instead, he
reassures them of the precautions he's taking. ``Does everyone have
a seat belt on?'' he'll ask. Then he might add, ``Just in case
you're wondering, I'm being extra careful as a driver.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Let a child know it's OK to express his anger with you but not
in a disrespectful way.
</P>
<P>
   --If you let your child down and he continues to hold it against
you long after it happened, seek professional advice.
</P>
<P>
   --Apologies are important, but even young children see through
them if they aren't genuine and you don't try to do better.
</P>
<P>
   --Every time we kiss a hurt to make it better, we contribute to
the belief that we have extra-human powers. Don't stop doing it,
though; children ascribe powers to us no matter what we do, and
this particular one can be loving and even helpful.
</P>
<P>
   --When a disappointment is beyond control _ a car accident, a
theft _ acknowledge that it's upsetting but also talk about the
ways in which you keep her safe: ``I always make sure everyone
wears a seat belt, I always obey traffic signals, and I drive very
carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's first book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is now
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments and can
be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
