<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO STRIP OR NOT TO STRIP, TO STAIN OR NOT TO STAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With spring finally in full bloom, it's nice to get out in the
yard and garden, cleaning up, planting pansies and impatiens in the
window boxes, and planning all kinds of other good things. It is
particularly pleasant when the sun is warming your winter-weary
bones.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something else that you can enjoy in the warm
weather: refinishing or cleaning up that old chest, an old wardrobe
gathering mildew in the basement, or any wood furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this work can be done outdoors, which will help protect
you from all those toxic finishes and strippers that you'll be
using.
</P>
<P>
   The only things that should not be done outdoors is painting and
varnishing. Even a mild breeze can blow dust and other debris on a
paint or varnish job.
</P>
<P>
   Not so incidentally, when working with finishes and strippers,
oils and varnishes, wear rubber gloves and safetly glasses or
goggles. When sanding or spraying, wear a face mask and/or a
respirator. A simple, paper respirator is good.
</P>
<P>
   Minwax, manufacturer of stains, wood fillers, varnishes,
finishing oils, refinishers, and wood conditioners, has published a
dandy little booklet called ``Tips on Wood Finishing.'' It is
available at paint stores and building supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   Always practical, Minwax suggests the refinisher wear old
clothes, not only because they are expendable, but also because
they are lint free.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now let's get to work.
</P>
<P>
   But wait! If you have an antique piece, or think it's an
antique, do not strip or refinish it, even if the piece looks
pretty tired. Stripping and refinishing can cut the value of an
antique by half and more.
</P>
<P>
   If in doubt, take it to an auctioneer for appraisal. Local
auctioneers are quite helpful in identifying an antique or
determining whether it really is an antique.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you can do with an antique is clean it. Wipe it with a
cloth dipped in mineral spirits (paint thinner), and rub small
areas, then wipe with a dry cloth.
</P>
<P>
   You can do the same with non-antiques. Cleaning may surprise
you, removing all the dirt and old wax.
</P>
<P>
   And to make sure it is clean, Minwax offers this tip it calls
the white glove inspection. Go over the entire piece with a fresh
cloth and mineral spirits (paint thinner). If the piece is really
clean, the cloth will stay clean.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes pieces never come clean; you can wipe with mineral
spirits until the cows come home, and you still get brown stains on
the cloth. Hmm. That's because the mineral spirits are taking some
of stain off. The answer: refinish.
</P>
<P>
   Paint thinner may dull the finish, but often it can be restored
by buffing with a dry cloth. The finish is just awaiting a little
polishing, but not polish. Avoid polish.
</P>
<P>
   If there are a few bare spots in your piece, touch them up with
a penetrating oil stain to match. It will be dull but the same
color. You can also disguise scratches with an almond stick or
other scratch filler. They come in various colors.
</P>
<P>
   Minwax calls its oil stain ``wood finish.'' By any name, though,
Minwax stains are good, and in most cases clear, providing the
color without hiding the wood, as some pigmented stains do.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing you can do with an old piece without stripping
it: paint it. It's a good idea if the piece has been painted in
psychedelic colors _ you know: purple, orange, that awful green _
or the paint is chipping badly. Or, if the wood is not particularly
attractive, even stained and varnished. Some pieces look better
painted.
</P>
<P>
   Painting is easy, compared with stripping and refinishing, but
there are rules to follow: 1. Sand the old paint thoroughly to
roughen the finish and reduce gloss. 2. Wash with paint thinner or
a strong solution of detergent and water. 3. Apply one coat of a
latex enamel undercoater, also called primer sealer. If you skip
this rule, you'll regret it. 4. Apply two coats of finish paint:
high-gloss, oil-baed indoor-outdoor enamel; semigloss or satin
latex enamel; or eggshell (low sheen) latex wall paint.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth rule: use thin coats, not thinned-down paint but thin
layers.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now let's really go to work. Stripping gets the wood ready
for stain and varnish or just varnish. There are several ways to
strip: sanding, paint remover, and a hot-air gun.
</P>
<P>
   Remove all hardware, hinges and other metal pieces that could be
damaged by the stripping process.
</P>
<P>
   Sand with a small power sander, being careful to keep the
surface even, with no ripples or high or low spots.
</P>
<P>
   Sanding will remove both varnish and stain, which is good, but
you can't sand the little nooks and crannies and fancy trim. You
have to use chemical paint remover for those areas. Apply the
remover, let it soak into the niches and nooks, then scrub out the
old finish with an old toothbrush. Get the stubborn spots with an
awl, ice pick, or other dull-pointed tool.
</P>
<P>
   But how can you sand the grooved turnings in chair and table
legs? Try this: Spin steel wool on a stout cord and pull the string
back and forth in each groove. In fact, you can buy sanding cords
in building supply and paint stores.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical paint stripper is the second way to remove old
finishes, but they may not remove a stain. Sanding is the only way
to get the stain out.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest strippers contain methylene chloride, a toxic
chemical, but they work the fastest. Rubber gloves and a face mask
are the things to wear when working with this material. If working
iondoors, use lots of ventilation.
</P>
<P>
   Some strippers do not contain methylene chloride; one is a
citrus-based remover called Citristrip.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical strippers will remove varnish very quickly; it takes
longer and more work to strip paint. These jobs are sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   Let the stripper stay on the finish for at least 15 minutes to
soften the finish; if the finish does not soften, apply another
coat of stripper over the first.
</P>
<P>
   Use a wide putty knife to scrape off the softened finish. If any
remains, repeat with the stripper and scrub with steel wool, or
sand off the final bit.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid using steel wool on surfaces you plan to use water-based
finishe on; shards of steel get caught in the wood, and the
water-based materials will create all kinds of little rust marks on
your work.
</P>
<P>
   A hot-air gun is an excellent way to remove paint and varnish;
it heats the material enough to soften the finish, which is then
scraped away with a putty knife. And this project is clean; when
the scrapings are removed, they dry out as they cool off, and they
are easily swept up for disposal.
</P>
<P>
   A hot-air gun is another reason to work outdoors. A hot-air gun
(it shoots air 700 to 1,000 degrees) should never be used indoors.
Wood ignites at about 500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the finish is off, to stain or not to stain is a
question you will have to answer yourself. It's a matter of taste,
and penetrating oil stains come in many colors.
</P>
<P>
   Hardwoods take stains very well, and evenly. Softwoods,
especially pine, take stains unevenly, leaving strong and weak
colors. To avoid this unevenness, apply a sanding sealer, which
will seal the wood enough so stain will go on evenly. Minwax calls
its sealer Wood Conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   Apply stain with a paintbrush, foam brush, or the down-and-dirty
way, with a cloth dipped in the stain. For a light stain, wipe it
off with a dry cloth immediately after applying. For darker tones,
let the stain sit a while before wiping dry, or apply a second
coat.
</P>
<P>
   For the finale, finish with a polyurethane varnish. How good
your finish will be depends on your skill and the brush. Your skill
can be honed by practice; the quality of the brush depends on its
price. So don't stint on the brushes.
</P>
<P>
   For old pieces, especially those previously varnished, use an
oil-based polyurethane varnish; it is apt to be more compatible
with different finishes than water-based polyurethane varnish. You
can use high gloss, but that may not be to your taste, and some
furniture is not meant to have a high gloss. Or, choose satin or
semigloss. Two coats are usually all you need, although sometimes
three are better.
</P>
<P>
   Another good tip that Minwax gives is to follow instructions on
the container, no matter what you use. This is especially important
when applying the final finish.
</P>
<P>
   For many pieces, you can use water-based polyurethane varnish,
which has these advantages: It is fast drying and brushes can be
cleaned up with water.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to be more careful with water-based polyurethane
varnish because it may not be compatible with old finishes, and
also with oil-based polyurethanes.
</P>
<P>
   As with any application, thin coats can make all the difference
in the final result.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that is one thing you have to be careful about with the
water-based varnish. It looks milky in the can, and sometimes goes
on milky, but the manufacturers assure us that this milkiness will
go away when the varnish begins to dry.
</P>
<P>
   But not always, particularly if you are careless in how thin you
make the coats.
</P>
<P>
   So, thin coats count double with water-based varnish.
</P>
<P>
   OK, you're all set. You can even do the work on Easter Sunday,
because there's an old Latin saying (I forget the Latin): ``To Work
is to Pray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
