<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENOPAUSE MADE MORE MEMORABLE  
 LUNG CANCER FIGHT FACES NEW HURDLE  
 BIRTH DEFECT STUDY SHOWS LATER RISKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Menopause made more memorable
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Menopause may be inevitable, but the memory loss that often
accompanies it may not be.
</P>
<P>
   Taking estrogen stimulates activity in areas of the brain known
to control memory, according to a study published this week. And
researchers are hopeful that the hormone can help reverse the
difficulty many post-menopausal women have remembering names and
performing other simple tasks requiring short-term recall.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have long suspected such a link, based on their work
on how children learn to read and on how estrogen affects the
brain. The new study at Yale University confirmed those links by
using magnetic resonance image tests to actually measure the
brain's response on 46 postmenopausal women while they were
performing simple memory tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The results were encouraging: doses of estrogen typically used
in hormone replacement therapies produced responses in areas of the
brain that control memory, suggesting that it's possible to alter
those memory receptors in ways that would restore the women's
impaired recall. But the tests didn't produce actual improvements
in memory, which researchers say may be because they weren't done
for long enough and the memory tasks tested were too simple.
</P>
<P>
   So what should women considering estrogen therapy do while more
tests are being done?
</P>
<P>
   ``Specific decisions are highly personal and have to be made
between a woman and her doctor,'' advised Dr. Sally E. Shaywitz,
professor of pediatrics at Yale and lead author of the study in
this week's Journal of the American Medical Association. ``But this
evidence now enters into the equation and becomes an important
factor. It should encourage doctors who care for these women to ask
about memory loss.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lung cancer fight faces new hurdle
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have known for half a century just how resilient
cancer cells were at evading our attempts to annihilate them. Now
there's more disturbing proof.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have been trying lung transplants to treat some patients
with bronchioloalveolar carcinomas, a rare but increasing type of
lung cancer where the tumor spreads quickly within the lungs but is
barely detectable outside them. That contained damage led
researchers to believe that new lungs could mean new lives for
patients, of whom there are more than 5,000 a year in America, and
it has meant a considerably longer life for many.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, there's evidence that the cancer resurfaces in the
transplanted lungs. That happened in four of seven transplant
patients studied at the University of Alabama at Birmingham and
reported on in the current New England Journal of Medicine.
Researchers believe that cancer cells from the original tumorous
lungs may have spread beyond the lung, remained dormant, then
reinfected the new lungs but not any other organ.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that these cancer cells have some sort of address
on them that sends them back to the lungs,'' explained Dr. Robert
I. Garver Jr., lead author of the study and associate professor of
medicine at the University of Alabama. While he was disappointed
that the tumors recurred, Garver added that ``we've shown that lung
transplants can add a lot of high-quality life time to these
patients who would have died within several months using any
conventional therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Birth defect study shows later risks
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The damage done by birth defects can persist for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound obvious, but until now doctors have focused most
of their attention on risks just after birth and during infancy.
Now Norwegian researchers have studied 24 different kinds of birth
defects, ranging from a cleft lip to heart deformities, in the
8,192 females born with birth defects there between 1967 and 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent survived to 15 years of age, compared to 98
percent of a control group without defects. But subjects with
defects were a third less likely to give birth by the age of 30,
and their children had a substantially greater chance of having the
same defect as their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   The lower birth rate among women with birth defects is caused by
social factors as well as biological ones, according to researchers
at the University of Bergen in Norway, who published their findings
in the current New England Journal.
</P>
</TEXT>
