<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0574 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VOYSEY-ART-BOS &LR;      04-08 1901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VOYSEY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIRKY DESIGNS OF C.F.A. VOYSEY STILL INSPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH, Mass. _ If the English architect C.F.A. Voysey thought
a client's wishes might compromise his design, he would walk away
from the project. As a result, word spread that he was
``difficult,'' and Voysey houses are few and far between. They do
exist, in tantalizing form, in drawingsand plans; and one of these
days, David E. Berman of Plymouth, who's one of the chief Voysey
votaries, will build himself a Voysey.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Berman is in the satisfying business of tending
the flame of one of the more intriguing figures in the English Arts
&AMP; Crafts movement. He does this in several ways. He helps the lucky
few who actually own a Voysey to restore their houses and furnish
them. He also has a hand in the reproduction of Voysey's designs
for wallpaper, textiles, and furniture. And if Voysey didn't think
to design lighting fixtures or TV armoires, Berman adapts Voysey to
the task at hand. Berman even has Voysey coming out of the oven. An
accomplished baker who's a notorious punster, Berman calls the B &AMP;
B he runs Sconehenge, and for tea he serves up shortbreads in the
shape of Voysey's signature heart.
</P>
<P>
   Who was Charles Francis Annersley Voysey (1857-1941), and why is
he a cult figure? Active toward the end of the Arts &AMP; Crafts
movement, he was a younger contemporary of William Morris. By
training and vocation an architect, Voysey was also gifted at
designing ``flat patterns,'' used for such surfaces as wallpapers,
textiles, and carpeting. When he needed money, he sold his textile
patterns, many to Liberty of London, which was then the leading
emporium for Arts &AMP; Crafts decor (and still does a roaring trade in
Liberty prints).
</P>
<P>
   As for Voysey houses, the nearest most of us have come to one is
via the Hercule Poirot episode on ``Mystery'' in which a Voysey is
used for a swell boat club on Windemere in England's Lake District.
Once seen in picture books, however, Voyseys seem the archetypal
homey house. They are long and low slung, a horizontality also used
by Frank Lloyd Wright in his ``Prairie House'' period. Lucky owners
must feel embraced and safe, yet elevated by the sureness of
Voysey's design.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Morris was the intellectual capital and emotional motor of
Arts &AMP; Crafts, then Voysey is a ramble in the countryside with
Peter Pan. Morris and his immediate circle had fought the good
fight against mass-produced decor and won. Their best work was
lofty but livable, Victorians pitching their comfortable tents in
the Gothic Middle Ages and producing things of serene beauty. This
would get dumbed down, till ``artsy craftsy'' said it all and
Morris became the hand-me-down stuff the Bright Young Things put
out with the trash. In fact, Voysey himself was declared dead
before he actually died: A retrospective of his work in 1931 was
ill-attended. The last public acclaim was the eulogy delivered on
the BBC by actor Robert Donat (who had married Voysey's niece,
Emily).
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the 1980s, the English Arts &AMP; Crafts style came back
into vogue, and with it the rediscovery of the American Aesthetic
movement. Revivals being draconic and scholarly, the artsy-craftsy
was soon shunted to flea markets. Morris got another 15 years of
fame. And when it got too crowded on the Morris bus, people like
David Berman _ and Judith Tankard of Newton is another _ moved on
to Voysey. Tankard, now a garden historian, wrote her master's
thesis on Voysey's flat patterns.
</P>
<P>
   To understand Voysey, Berman and others say it helps to know
about a defining event in his childhood. His clergyman father was
removed from the Church of England ``for preaching a God that was
too benevolent for those times,'' as Berman puts it. This was a
message much liked by the upwardly mobile middle class, and the
Rev. Voysey found people to set him up as a theist minister. But
the elder Voysey's ouster from the Establishment, necessitating the
family's relocation, traumatized his son. As an adult, Voysey would
retreat to the surer worlds of childhood and the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good part of childhood never left him,'' Berman says.
Voysey would marry but live apart from wife and children. For much
of his life, home was two rooms at various London addresses. His
last office was hit by a Nazi bomb and disappeared in the London
Blitz.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the rather fierce glare of the birds that figure in
so many Voysey designs, you might think all his life had gone
ticketyboo. But that glare is lifelike. And so is the food chain
that Voysey depicts in a design Berman will develop as a
needlepoint kit. Called ``Let Us Prey,'' it shows a cat stalking a
bird eying a worm, which will eat the sheltering flower.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One snowy morning, Berman opened Sconehenge's front door and a
visitor stepped into the green and pleasant world that is his
showcase for Voysey designs. Not every room is papered in Voysey.
Not every Voysey rug is on the floor: An all-over floral, rendered
by Berman in needlepoint, makes a stunning coverlet for one of the
B &AMP; B beds. The side porch boasts two of Voysey's invalid chairs.
These have high wooden sides ending in tester tops, and not just
the infirm will want to curl up on their generously cushioned
seats. But that wooden hand (from the statue of a saint) camping
out on the pump-organ keyboard surely isn't Voysey.
</P>
<P>
   As craftsmen, Berman and Voysey are somewhat alike in their
dress. Berman wears an artisan's tunic and turtleneck; Voysey hated
anything that harbored dust, so his jackets had no lapels, his
trousers no cuffs. He loved color: His starched collars were the
bright blue of old butcher's striped aprons. But there are
differences: Berman moves easily in cyberspace. Voysey was
buffaloed by the movies. He'd gone to see one of Donat's films and
left after 20 agonizing minutes. ``That dreadful noise!'' he said
of the soundtrack. ``And why did they keep on slipping in a huge
picture, a huge portrait of you?'' Donat explained this was a
close-up. ``But why?'' Voysey persisted. ``It isn't necessary, damn
it all; we're not as stupid as all that. We can see who it is and
what he's doing, without having it stretched far and wide across a
great big space.''
</P>
<P>
   At nearly 6 feet, Berman is taller than Voysey, who stood at a
little over 5 feet. Height says much about Voysey. He did not
believe in tall ceilings. Apart from the two-story halls of some
houses, ceilings were dropped to 8 feet, even to 7 1/2 when Voysey
could persuade clients. But Voysey's sense of proportion was such,
says Berman, that his houses have the feel of amplitude. Wide doors
gave the rooms a welcoming feel. Architects who admired Voysey
ranged from Sir Edwin Lutyens, that master builder of English
country houses, to Robert Venturi, the postmodernist.
</P>
<P>
   Voysey houses look bigger than they are. Berman remembers one he
could see clear across a valley. The living space was contained in
a shoebox, a two-story rectangle, and Berman sees Voysey's
inspiration in the long, low houses of 17th-century England.
``Which he slightly upgraded.'' Covering the shoebox was a high
pitched roof; some were so high and steep that Voyseys seem more
roof than house. Not exactly quaint but unsettling: houses for
gnomes, you might say. The exterior walls were a white, countrified
rough-cast stucco. The windows, grouped horizontally, were framed
in stone. A fine red line marked the water coursing. The house sat
on a dark terrace, actually a tarred plinth that kept the damp out.
The big, mouth-like front doors were set into the house so you
could stand out of the rain. Right inside the front door, Voysey
put a loo so the traveler could freshen up. This was the era of
dusty roads and tire punctures. But when the green slate roof swept
down almost to the green lawn, there was drama of line and mass as
well as interplay of color.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, and yet. Voysey's houses were somehow toy-like, writes
the architectural critic David Gebhard. They ``seem to be
dollhouses which have been taken from the children's nursery,
magically enlarged, and then placed in the pastoral countryside.''
This storybook aspect of Voysey extends to his flat patterns, and
it has caused some people to confuse subject matter with scale.
Voysey really did mean his designs to bulk large. His first drafts
were most often his final drafts, and his ease in composition
Berman likens to ``the way we think of the young Mozart and the
music just coming off the ends of his fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   So in restoring Voysey, Berman must also restore his scale. He
works from documentary prints, many in London's Victoria &AMP; Albert
Museum, and he treasures the friendship and help of the last living
link to the Voysey architectural practice, John Brandon-Jones of
Hampstead, who worked for Voysey's son. ``He's enormously kind in
loaning me things and does copy work for me, and when I leave his
house to go back to America, he always says, `Don't be too long
coming back.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Voysey is now a cottage industry. Wallpaper reproductions are
handled by Carol Mead of Pomfret, Conn. One is the 1890s pattern
called Isis. Computer wizardry returned it to the original scale.
If silk-screened in flat solid colors, this pattern would seem
harsh and daunting; to reproduce the gentler textures of Voysey's
watercolor draft will require as many as 13 screens. As a companion
to Isis, Berman offers a paper border of little shamrocks to make a
4-inch frieze close to the ceiling. Isis is a riot of birds and
poppies and thistles and Tudor roses. ``When you add the
shamrocks,'' says Berman, ``you've got the whole British Isles.''
</P>
<P>
   Voysey carpeting, with its sometimes dizzying patterns, is
available through John Burroughs, Historical Design Merchant, of
Rockland. Burroughs's business manager, Dan Cooper, is Berman's
partner in Trustworth Historical Design. Through his Trustworth
Studio, Berman produces lighting, furniture, and accessories
``after Voysey,'' which he makes himself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where did Voysey get his ideas? He may look more modern than
Morris; he was a more practical man than Morris. Not for Voysey the
labor-intensive cabinetry of Arts &AMP; Crafts furniture. Even if
Morris had lived into the Automobile Age, you wouldn't expect him
to design a gas station. Voysey's, alas, with its fanciful
iconography, awaits its oil tycoon. Still, Voysey would not have
approved of our copying machines. It was all right to study other
people's work for ideas, but ``sketching was stealing.'' He could
not help knowing Art Nouveau. How else to explain certain Voysey
patterns so dense they rival Art Nouveau at its most headachy?
(Interestingly, he did not use patterned papers in the houses he
designed but preferred a plain silk-threaded paper in green or
purple. With this, turkey-red curtains.) But, in fact, Voysey
thought Art Nouveau too sinuous and sensuous. ``It offended the
puritan in him,'' Berman says.
</P>
<P>
   What looks like Art Nouveau may be just Voysey's wish to stay
lost in the forest. The Voysey style, says Berman, is very natural,
very English. ``He thought of himself as a Victorian, not a
pioneer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1358EDT &QL; 
