<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0575 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-08 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEATH BUSINESS IS BOOMER-ING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; once speculated here, apropos of something or other, that
when my time draws nigh I'm sure Martha Stewart will be standing by
with a lavishly illustrated book of elaborate do-it-yourself
funeral arrangements. I was joking. Well, half-joking. As we've
seen, Martha is capable of anything, emphasis on ``capable.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately I've been looking at death as a marketing opportunity,
and I'm here to report that a Martha funeral tome is a modest
notion compared with some new developments on the funeral front.
</P>
<P>
   Death be not dull. The baby boomers have discovered death and,
as usual, they want to do it their way. A cartoon I saw the other
day captured the situation. Man in bed, clearly in extremis. Woman
hovering over him, saying, ``If it's any comfort, Vanity Fair says
that death is `in.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Death is always ``in,'' alas. So is the impulse to memorialize
self and loved ones; it's as ancient as man. But there are new
twists, among them the Art Casket. A story in the Stamford Advocate
reports that its creators, a company called WhiteLight, will
``personalize'' a coffin to convey ``a life statement on behalf of
the deceased.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has several designs, among them ``Fairway to
Heaven'' for golfers, a casket adorned with an image of a par-3
hole on a verdant course. Other themes are nature, religion, AIDS
awareness, and the Alamo. The president of the company says he sees
a future for caskets with sports logos, the NBA, the NFL, Major
League Baseball, and colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reports that high-tech innovations
promise ``to transform cemeteries from places bound by granite into
playgrounds for the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Digital memorials are available that allow visitors to call up
an image of the departed and listen to a recorded message from
beyond the grave. In the works are holograms that will project 3-D
images of the deceased and tombstone computers that can be
programmed to simulate the departed's personality, allowing vistors
to have a virtual-reality conversation with the dead. Special
effects are everything these days.
</P>
<P>
   What would Jessica Mitford have made of all this? In the early
1960s Mitford, who died in 1996, wrote ``The American Way of
Death,'' a brilliant and savagely funny expose of the excesses of
the American funeral industry. An updated edition of her book was
published recently because much of what she criticized hasn't
changed. Indeed, things have gotten worse, with big corporate
funeral homes gobbling up family operations, and pushing up prices.
</P>
<P>
   Death is the final major consumer opportunity, and we do love to
consume. Many people are pre-planning their own funerals. In his
wonderful collection of essays, ``The Undertaking: Life Studies
From the Dismal Trade,'' undertaker/poet Thomas Lynch writes that
the dead don't care about their own funeral arrangements. But they
care while they're alive, hence the growth in ``pre-need''
planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a plot?'' a friend asks.
</P>
<P>
   Plot? When I hear the word ``plot,'' I think of a novel or a
movie. I tell her I've never been good at plotting.
</P>
<P>
   ``A burial plot,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She's shopping for one, even though, given her age, life
expectancy and a little luck, she won't need a plot for another 30
years or so. When she finds the plot of her dreams, she may want to
engage the services of a cemetery beautification and maintainence
service to keep it looking nice. Not long ago I received an
invitation to a seminar sponsored by one of these services. The
subject was, ``Death is Not the End of the Road.'' Not for this
company, apparently, which will tend your plot in perpetuity, for a
price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
