<HEADER>
A0577 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-08 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUPID FLIES INTO CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend Beth is an incredible woman.
</P>
<P>
   Here, I'll let her tell you in her own words.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to meet at a party, I'm the vivacious, tall,
elegant woman very engaged in conversation, listening intently. You
find out that I am a consultant to financial services companies all
over the country. You watch my wild silver-blond hair because it is
so unruly, longer than most, and the texture of silk. You are
seeing the public self.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to stumble on my Cape Cod summer garden in the
woods, you would notice a well-muscled woman in cutoff shorts,
T-shirt, wild hair captured in a ponytail under a baseball cap,
dirt smearing my arms, hands, and cheeks, as I dig in the black,
crumbly earth. You think I am attending my garden. I am really
attending my soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to see me in the gym, you would find a determined
athlete. If you were to enter my mind, you would find a discerning,
critical thinker. If you were to ask what I want in a man I would
say: Make him emotionally available, entrepreneurially flexible, a
loving father with a good relationship with his kids, someone who
finds it important to give back to society in thanks for what he
has achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound fantastic? That's because she is.
</P>
<P>
   Beth has been happily single for 11 years. Yet every once in a
while she has the urge to ``go back out there,'' as she puts it;
but where can a 55-year-old woman find male companionship these
days? She's far too professional to flirt during business hours.
Yet, in her very busy life, she doesn't meet many available men.
Given that the last place she'd seek a soulmate is at a bar, where
in the world can she go?
</P>
<P>
   How about to an Internet dating service?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the initial investment is low. The service Beth
chose, www.match.com, has a free seven-day trial period before
charges of $12.95 a month kick in. For another, an on-line dating
service also provides all the space you need to present yourself in
depth. You can write to dozens of applicants on line before you
ever have to face one in person. In addition, the answers you give
to questions about ethnicity, religion, age, body type and height,
smoking, drinking, and children are organized in browse fields so
that someone looking for a particular combination can quickly
locate participants who match his or her requirements.
</P>
<P>
   That is, of course, if people are honest.
</P>
<P>
   When Beth listed her true age, she received only one reply. When
she deducted 10 years, however, she drew 15 responses in 24 hours,
all from men between 50 and 65. To her credit, the first thing she
did when she responded was confess how old she was. To her
surprise, only a few correspondents withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   Beth, who goes by the handle of Paradise Hill, has corresponded
with several men in the past month, ultimately meeting two of them
in very public places. One drank too much for her taste. The other
came across as condescending. Another, however _ a divorced,
successfully self-employed business writer who lives in Connecticut
and works for a range of corporate clients _ seemed a perfect
match. His first response ran to three single-spaced pages and
included the following: ``I certainly have room for a woman in my
life, with an emphasis on the sensual and an emphasis on the
heartfelt. One thing I've come to terms with in the past few years
is the power of openness and honesty in a relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder Beth looked forward to reading her e-mail with
renewed enthusiasm; but before they could meet, this man informed
Beth he'd decided to pursue a relationship with a woman closer to
home.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection barely hurt. ``It isn't as if there isn't an
ever-renewing audience for my profile,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Beth understands the risks of meeting people on line. In the
anonymity of cyberspace, the married easily get divorced and
criminals can claim to be college professors. She's also aware,
however, that this is a chance to meet men she'd never encounter
any other way. Taking a small risk seems vastly superior to giving
up hope of ever finding a life partner.
</P>
<P>
   As the millennium approaches, there are more and more culturally
accepted ways of finding a mate. Let's hope that enchantment via
e-mail turns out to be at least as reliable as love at first sight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
