<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ROUGH-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      04-08 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROUGH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUGHER? NOT REALLY . . . BUT TOUGHER? YOU BET 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN GOBE STAFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ The slick can do so much with words. Not talking
politics, either, but golf, because the slick have taken the word
``rough'' and smoothed its meaning. So much so here at Augusta
National Golf Club, that the rough _ though smooth _ is still
called ``rough'' by the smooth-talkers. And tradition is said to
tremble.
</P>
<P>
   The word has been out for months: Augusta National was changing.
Bobby Jones, wherever he is, was said to be quivering at the mere
thought. Clifford Roberts, too. And introducing ``rough'' to this
Taj Majal, this Vatican, this Mecca, this absolute shrine of golf,
was the most radical of changes.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the White House were painted pink, the ceiling of
the Sistine Chapel festooned with McDonald's ads, the Mona Lisa
redone in velvet, Fenway Park sold out to a giant Coke bottle
hanging over The Wall, the change was that traumatic.
</P>
<P>
   Except the ``rough'' is not rough. The new, insidious,
invidious, and despicable ``rough'' at Augusta National is all of 1
3/8 inches high, compared with the 4 inches of rough usually found
at PGA Tour events and the rough of 5 inches at the US Open, where
rough is really rough. The slick cannot smooth out that truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how this is going to affect the play very much,''
said the straight-talking Greg Norman. ``The guys still have have
plenty of fairway to aim at out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Fred Couple put it, ``It's not like real rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more, the grounds at Augusta National are so pristine that
even those 1 3/8 inches of rough are in such perfect condition that
balls ending up in it will present lies as good as or better than
average golfers find on 99 percent of the fairways they play on.
The fairways have been made a bit narrower with the addition of the
rough, but not dramatically so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been thinking about the second cut (second cut is the
Masters' euphemistic term for rough) for a good little while,'' new
Masters tournament chairman Hootie Johnson said Wednesday. ``As you
know, we've had a little fuzz there around the edges. But (the move
to rough) has been made primarily to put a greater premium on
accuracy off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   As England's Lee Westwood put it, ``I think the rough is fair,''
which means it is really a non-factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a flyer or two coming out of that rough,'' said
Norman, ``but that's about it. If the rough was thick, where you
really had to muscle it out, then it'd be a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the rough may actually help golfers on these wide-open
fairways, because one of the few dangers off the tee was to push
drives on holes such as the second, fifth, 10th, and 11th where
trees line the right side.
</P>
<P>
   Shots too far right often would roll through the fairways and
into the trees. Now, the second cut could help stop balls from
reaching the trees. ``If you fly your ball into the rough it's not
going to go as far,'' said Couples.
</P>
<P>
   An example of that came during defending champion Mark O'Meara's
practice round Tuesday when he pushed his tee shot on the 10th. The
rough stopped his ball, giving him a clear shot to the green. ``I
think,'' said Jack Nicklaus, ``the rough will keep more balls out
of the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is no rough around the greens.
</P>
<P>
   As Nicklaus so aptly put it, ``I don't think the rough is much
of an issue.'' All golfers know rough. The new grass at Augusta
National, whether it be known as rough or second cut is not really
rough. Except to the smooth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Union Gen. William Tecumseh Sherman undertook his famous
(``infamous'' down here) March to the Sea from Atlanta to Savannah,
and then north into South and North Carolina, Sherman chose to
bypass Augusta. That reference to 135 years ago is apt because,
inside the gates of Augusta National, it seems that so much has
remained untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Augusta National this year chose to make four changes,
changes that are much more significant than the addition of the
pseudo-rough. The changes have been praised by some, criticized by
others, and shuddered at by a few. Traditionalists, those few.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are these: The tee on the second hole (par 5, 575
yards) has been moved back into the pine trees by some 25 yards;
the green on the 11th hole (par 4, 455 yards) has been raised and
altered, and a bunker has been added to the rear of the hole; 20
pine trees have been planted on the right side of the 15th hole
(par 5, 500 yards) and several large mounds on the right side have
been removed; those same trees also affect the tee shot on the 17th
hole (par 4, 425 yards) and the tee on 17th also has been moved
back some 30 yards or so.
</P>
<P>
   None of these changes are pseudo or subtle. All dramatically
change the look of the holes and, even more significantly, change
the shotmaking on all of them. While Augusta National has made many
changes to the course over the years (upwards of 75, according to
Johnson, many subtle, a few major) never have so many significant
changes been made in one and the same year.
</P>
<P>
   In one breath, Johnson said what had to be said. ``This is the
Masters tournament and it is a national treasure. It's something
precious and something to be preserved.'' Yet, in the next breath,
the chairman detailed the opposite: ``Yes, yes they are'' the most
significant changes ever made to the course. ``And not just in
recent memory,'' continued Johnson, ``but ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The premise for the changes is Tiger Woods. When Woods shot his
18-under par score of 270 two years ago, breaking all Masters
records, Jack Stephens, the former tournament chairman, and now
Johnson decided to make changes. ``The final decision about whether
to do it, I guess, would be either Mr. Stephens or myself,'' said
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were made, Johnson went on, not necessarily to
``Tiger-proof'' or ``Duval-proof'' the course, ``but that what we
hope to do is to keep up with the world and the game of golf today.
And the guys are hitting it longer and they're in better condition
and the equipment is better. We're attempting to strengthen the
golf course and stay in tune with the times.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, upon examination of Masters scores over the years, the
premise for the changes might be open to question. The winning
Masters scores have been very similar except for a
dramatically-improved score once every 15 years or so, followed by
a long period of similar scores; a bolt of lightning, it seems,
once a generation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
