<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0597 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ROUGH-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     04-08 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROUGH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 AUGUSTA, Ga.: ... once a generation.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first five years, winners scored in the 280s until Ralph
Guldahl shocked all with his 279 score in 1939. Guldahl's record
stood until Ben Hogan shattered it by 5 strokes with his 274 in
1953. Then, for the next 12 years, no Masters' winner came close to
Hogan's mark until Jack Nicklaus smashed it with his 271 in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Raymond Floyd, who tied Nicklaus's mark in 1976, no
golfer came within range of the record for the next 22 years, Ben
Crenshaw coming closest with 274 in 1995. Finally, 33 years after
Nicklaus set his mark, Woods broke it in 1998 _ by all of one
stroke. O'Meara, last year's winner, reverted back to a very
typical winning score of 279.
</P>
<P>
   False premise or no, though, the changes have been made in an
attempt to send Masters scores back up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, no matter what's been done, I think the guy who
hits it long and straight still has the advantage around here,''
said Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, all in all, now it's a visually different golf
course. (The changes on) 17 I'm not a fan of. It just makes it more
difficult to hit the fairway, especially when the (new) trees get
up (and grow) in 10 or 15 years time. Secondly, the design (of the
green) is not for a 7-iron or a 6-iron or a 5-iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``The green on 17 is so small, it's got a lot of movement to it,
it's very crowned, and it's just not a 6-iron-shot green. Most of
the time, the prevailing wind is hitting you there when it's warm
and from the south, and the green's going to dry out and be firmer,
and there's going to be places where you're just not going to be
able to hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Translation: The changes on 17 are challenging, especially
because of the lengthier shot to the green, and most likely will
change a routine par-4 hole into a thinking-golfer's riddle,
especially on Sunday afternoon with a major championship on the
line.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The 15th hole is a little bit different, because the tee's
been moved a little bit to the right,'' said Norman. ``There'll be
a little different angle off the tee but, all in all, all you're
going to do on 15 is hit it hard and hit it straight and you're
going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   (Translation: The planting of 20 trees along the right removes a
huge advantage for medium-range hitters who could bounce tee shots
off the high mounds and get an extra 50 yards or so of ricochet
toward the green. Longer hitters such as Woods usually flew their
shots over the mounds. As Norman sees it, though, the 15th hole now
seems fairer because all drives must be straight and true.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've got to understand about the second hole,'' Norman
said of moving the tee back on that hole, ``is that it still favors
long hitters. The long hitters are still going to get it down there
near the front bunker (near the green). I mean, that's where we're
all trying to hit our (second) shots anyway. We're all still going
to end up in the same place. And the real long hitters _ the Dalys,
the Woods, maybe the Ernie Elses _ will still be down there 340
(off the tee), but they'll be off the downslope. Instead of hitting
a 7-iron, they'll probably be hitting a 5-iron.''
</P>
<P>
   (Translation: Woods, Daly, and a few others still will be able
to drive over the fairway bunker, now some 300 yards away. Many
others will hit only a 3-wood off the tee, hoping to lay up short
of the bunker. The end result is the shorter hitters might be more
severely penalized than the longer hitters.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The 11th green is a great improvement. I think that, by far,
is the best improvement. It's really improved the playability of
the hole. It looks better on your second shot. I'd give that one a
100 percent markup.''
</P>
<P>
   (Translation: If this change had been made 13 years ago, Norman
might have a Masters championship and would not have writhed in his
sleep for a decade or more. Larry Mize was able to chip in from
wide right of the 11th green (the second playoff hole) and seize
the title from Norman. Such a chip shot would be impossible now
that the green is raised instead of sunken and a bunker now lies
between the green and where Mize made his famous chip. Norman,
quite naturally, loves these changes.)
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, Norman is dismayed by the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to see this, because I like to step on the tee
and say, `Well, Gene Sarazen did this or Byron Neson did this' and
feel the same piece of nostalgia and history under your feet as
what those guys played on. When you change the course, you change
all that. I hate to see golf courses changed because of low
scores.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Woods, the object of many of the changes, said they ``are good.
All the changes, I think, are beneficial to all the long hitters.
There's no doubt about it. They've made the par 5's longer, which
means that 2 and 15 are going to be more difficult to hit in two,
which helps out the long hitters.'' O'Meara was distressed by the
lengthening of the 17th hole, particularly because Ike's Tree _ the
infamous tree along the left edge of the fairway that President
Eisenhower wanted hacked down because so many of his drives found
it _ now will be even more on his mind when he stands on the tee.
``(The tree) bothered me before, and unless the conditions are
right, I probably can't hit it over the Eisenhower Tree (now 195
yards from the tee). I'll probably have to work around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples said the changes may add a stroke or so to each player's
round, and Nicklaus agreed. The irony, though, is what O'Omeara and
others said. The changes make the course longer ``and when you make
the course longer, it kind of favors (Woods).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, and almost always, the Masters champion is decided
by the greens of Augusta National, those infernal, undulating,
hidden-break greens that never can be appreciated on television. It
is the best putter the week of the Masters who usually wins the
Green Jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Strange that it is the men closest to the traditions of the
Masters who have forgotten that it is the strongest-willed and not
the strongest-armed who most often win at Augusta National. All
their tampering just may be for nought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
