<HEADER>
A0599 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     04-08 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANNIVERSARY MORE PRECIOUS THAN GOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My in-laws are having their 65th wedding anniversary, and I
can't find any information about gift traditions to mark the
occasion. What's associated with anniversaries beyond the 60th?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.B., Hurst, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Most lists don't go beyond the diamond anniversary, which
marks 60 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Some lists also call anniversaries of 65, 70 and 75 years
diamond anniversaries.
</P>
<P>
   The World Almanac gives wedding anniversaries these names:
</P>
<P>
   One through 15: paper, cotton, leather, linen, wood, iron, wool,
bronze, pottery, tin, steel, silk, lace, ivory and crystal.
</P>
<P>
   After that, anniversaries are named every fifth year: china
(20), silver (25), pearl (30), coral (35), ruby (40), sapphire
(45), gold (50) and emerald (55).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where did House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt go to
school? I attended school with a Richard and Robert Gephardt in
Erie, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   _ E.K., Azle, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Richard Gephardt attended school in St. Louis and has a
brother named Don, said Laura Nichols of Gephardt's communications
office.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of House Democrats was born in the same St. Louis
district he represents. His official biography describes him as a
``fiercely loyal'' St. Louis Cardinals fan.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt graduated from Northwestern University, where he became
student body president, and the University of Michigan Law School.
</P>
<P>
   You can write to him at the Office of the Minority Leader, Room
H204, The Capitol, Washington, D.C. 20515.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My dad swears by cough drops called Fisherman's Friend. I've
always wondered: Where does the name come from?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.J., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Fisherman's Friend lozenges, developed in a fishing village
in 1865, were marketed as ``on-the-spot relief'' for fishermen,
said Mike Bartz of Mentholatum, the product's U.S. distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Descendants of the pharmacist who created the product still
manufacture it in Fleetwood, England.
</P>
<P>
   Fisherman's Friend is available at Wal-Mart, Walgreens and
Albertsons. For more information, write to Mentholatum at 707
Sterling Drive, Orchard Park, N.Y. 14127, or send an e-mail to
bartz &LR; mentholatum.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
