<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS CLINTON SMARTER THAN YOU THINK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once more into the brier patch.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton keeps saying that he doesn't want to go there,
but some of the pundits, committed Clinton-bashers, potential
congressional and presidential candidates, retired military
kibitzers and American public opinion are coalescing into a force
to throw him in it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton keeps saying like a stuck compact disc that he and the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization allies have no plans to insert
ground troops into the Kosovo unpleasantness. And he is now drawing
volleys of criticism from across the political spectrum for his
lack of an endgame strategy, his military inexperience and his
foreign policy ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   Unidentified sources are now being referenced as having told the
president that airstrikes alone would not be sufficient to convince
Yugoslav strongman Slobodan Milosevic to abandon his genocidal
course in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, some assert that Clinton should never have
committed this nation to a course of military action that he knew
in advance would not get the job done. By continuing to demur on
the deployment of ground troops, Clinton reinforces their view of
him as a draft dodger who is incapable of providing the nation with
the kind of leadership it needs in wartime.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it passing strange what a couple of weeks, televised
images of thousands of destitute, dispossessed Kosovars and a trio
of kidnapped American soldiers can do?
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only the day before yesterday that many of those
same wise ones who are now lambasting the president for not having
the guts and the vision to do what it takes to prevail in the
Kosovo conflict were singing a different tune. They were speaking
of the difficulties of fighting a ground war in the Balkans and
citing the Germans' World War II experience there as a classic case
in point.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the notion of sending ground troops into the
Kosovo fray was unthinkable for most of those wise heads and the
overwhelming majority of the American people. If the president had
intimated that the air campaign against Milosevic's forces might
lead to the use of U.S. ground forces, he never would have been
able to get the air campaign off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion would have been overwhelmingly opposed to the
airstrikes if the American people had become convinced that they
could lead to down-to-earth bloodletting. And, as Clinton's critics
are quick to point out, the president pays attention to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there were those who contended that Clinton was being
devious, that he did understand from the outset where the course
that NATO was setting might lead. They may have assessed the
situation then better than they realized.
</P>
<P>
   But that assessment doesn't fit into the current strategy of
Clinton's staunchest opponents, especially those posturing for
political races next year. Their strategy is to portray Clinton as
leadership-challenged, as one who would blunder into a military
conflict with no plan for either winning it or cutting U.S. losses
and pulling out.
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question: What constitutes effective national
leadership today?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been criticized as someone who allows public opinion
polls to dictate his policy. And some see that as a failure of
leadership. But is it really? Is it not possible that a really
clever leader can manipulate things so that the polls point in the
direction he wants to go?
</P>
<P>
   One stratagem for making that happen is the old ``please don't
throw me in the brier patch'' ploy, a tactic employed by Br'er
Rabbit in the well-known fable to get Br'er Bear and Br'er Fox to
chunk him to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Picture this: While Clinton insists vehemently that NATO has no
intention of sending in ground troops, a Washington Post poll shows
that 55 percent of Americans now favor using ground forces against
the Serbs. A poll conducted by New York pollster John Zogby shows a
60 percent level of support.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some potential candidates for the Republican
presidential nomination are now speaking of the need to send in
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   What's a president to do in the face of all that body of
political and military wisdom and that groundswell of public
opinion?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, therefore, can't lose now politically. Milosevic
already is showing signs of willingness to yield because of the
intensity of the air war and the damage being done to his already
economically depressed country. If he does, Clinton comes out ahead
politically as a result of having resisted the calls for ground
troops.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic perseveres in his folly ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, Clinton has no choice. The American people have spoken.
They are now telling him what kind of endgame they want played.
</P>
<P>
   Is that slick or what?
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
