<HEADLINE>
GET ORGANIZED WITH A PIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Journalists tend to be disorganized, and I'm the worst of a bad
lot. I'd never remember an appointment if it weren't for a Personal
Information Manager program that slaps me out of a gearhead daze.
My PIM of the moment is Microsoft's Outlook. It suffers from the
usual Microsoft failings -- it eats up too much memory and runs too
slowly. But it combines a calendar, address book and e-mail which
work almost seamlessly together.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of Outlook is the chief reason I still haven't
been able to switch entirely to Linux, my favorite alternative
operating system. Try though I might, I haven't found any
Linux-based alternatives that measure up.
</P>
<P>
   However, one can rely on a Web browser and a growing number of
Internet PIMs -- Web sites that provide registered users with free
calendars and address books.
</P>
<P>
   There's a PIM site boom these days. Firms like Anyday.com and
PlanetAll are clamoring for new users. Another entrant, When.com,
was purchased by America Online Inc. last week, and is already the
Web-based calendar for AOL's Netcenter Web portal. Other top
portals like Lycos and Yahoo are also wooing visitors with online
calendars. The services are all free; the goal is to keep you
coming back to the site, where they can fling ads at your eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   As with most other free Internet services, all these sites will
eventually offer identical features, so that it won't matter which
one you use. But right now, it makes quite a difference. Some, like
Cambridge-based Anyday.com, are still in test mode and aren't ready
for serious use. And there are sizable differences among the
well-established on-line PIMs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, When.com makes a good lightweight calendar for
casual Web users. After you get a free password, you can record
appointments months or years ahead. There's also a handy little
feature called Event Tracker that keeps watch on a variety of
upcoming events you might want to track. Say you're a fan of the TV
series Law and Order. Event Tracker will remind you to tune in, and
provide a summary of that night's episode. It also tracks concerts,
the latest movies, corporate earnings reports -- quite a lot of
useful stuff.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, When.com doesn't include an address book. Worse
yet, it doesn't offer one of the most important features for an
on-line PIM -- synchronization.
</P>
<P>
   After all, many users of on-line PIMs already have similar
software on their computers. Copying your calendar to the Web lets
you get access to it from any Internet-linked computer on earth.
But you need a way to dump data from your PC or Palm Pilot into the
Web-based PIM.
</P>
<P>
   That's where synchronization comes in. Some of these sites let
you download a program that will copy data from your computer and
send it over the 'Net to your on-line calendar or address book.
</P>
<P>
   PlanetAll has been offering this for some time. Their software
can synch up with Palm Pilots, or with PCs running Microsoft
Outlook. And when your Outlook address book changes, the software
reminds you to send those changes along to PlanetAll as well. Too
bad the PlanetAll software only covers the address book. It won't
let you automatically transmit appointment data to the service's
on-line calendar.
</P>
<P>
   That's a major blunder, one which Yahoo has avoided. Their
synchronization software lets you transfer both address book and
calendar data. The first transfer can take a long time if you've
got lots of data. But from then on, the software only transmits
updated files, so the job only lasts a minute or so.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I've got my PIM data stashed on a Web site, it doesn't
matter whether I'm running Windows or Linux or any other obscure
operating system. All I need is an Internet connection and a Web
browser. It also helps to be the trusting sort -- after all, you're
putting a lot of personal information onto somebody else's
computer. Firms like Yahoo and PlanetAll pledge to respect the
privacy of the data you store in their PIMs, and soft-headed fool
that I am, I believe them.
</P>
<P>
   These on-line services aren't a completely adequate substitute
for PIM software on your own machine, especially if you've got a
slow modem connection to the Internet. Then again, considering how
slow Microsoft Outlook runs, it's nearly a draw.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
