<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICETROUBLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRICE IS NOT RIGHT: OIL PRODUCERS SAY INDUSTRY NOT YET OUT OF
TROUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The bluebonnets are in bloom, baseball
season is back, and energy prices have moved up about 40 percent
since midwinter.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas oil producers, who saw daily posted prices drop below
$8 per barrel during a grim winter, are still seeing the glass as
half-empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be seeing some light at the end of the tunnel,'' said
John Pinkerton, chief executive of Range Resources of Fort Worth.
``But we're still in the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   What bothers Texas drillers are daily reports in their
newspapers and on television that tell of $17-per-barrel futures
prices, a level tantalizingly close to the $18 price that oil
producers say they need to justify bigger exploration and drilling
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, Texas oil producers aren't getting the $17 that
traders are paying on the New York Mercantile Exchange for futures
contracts. They are getting the ``posted,'' or wellhead cash price,
which is around $14. The posted price is cash that refiners and
transporters pay producers for oil right out of the ground.
</P>
<P>
   That's better than the $8-$9 per barrel they were getting in
December and January, but doesn't justify a flurry of orders for
drilling rigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to shut down the doors of the industry at $14,
but clearly there isn't enough spread to justify expansion,'' said
Pinkerton, whose company is among many that reduced their work
forces this year because of declining prices and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Energy price analysts say they believe that the posted prices
will rise gradually this year, to about $16 per barrel by summer
and maybe to as high as $20 per barrel by later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Goldstein, analyst with the Petroleum Industry Research
Foundation in New York, noted that while the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries has had difficulties in enforcing
production quotas, it has reduced the flow of oil. That in turn has
pushed prices higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC took 2 million barrels (out of 27 million barrels of
production daily) out of production, and now is working on another
2 million barrels,'' Goldstein said. ``They wanted to cut more, but
the point is that they have reduced output and the market will feel
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Combine that with a decline in U.S. production and flat demand,
particularly in Europe and in Asia, and the scenario is set for oil
to return to near $20 by the year's end, Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for producers, Goldstein said, OPEC members have
spare drilling capacity, and as prices rise, they will inevitably
drill more to earn cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see $24 per barrel oil. In fact, by the end of this
year, prices may be declining again, although they won't go down to
$12 like before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Any breather for producers would be welcome. Bill Stevens of the
West Central Oil &AMP; Gas Association in Abilene said that the recent
run-up in prices has ``generated some activity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a little cash to do some workover and maintenance
on wells,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said ``the rule of thumb is that we need crude prices _
posted, that is _ at $15 before people will feel comfortable
putting money into drilling and exploration.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the energy industry in Texas continues to contract.
The Texas Workforce Commission reports that in February, the last
month for which figures have been compiled, 150,100 Texans worked
directly for the oil and gas industry. That was down from a high of
162,400 in December 1997, just as oil prices were tipping from
their average of $20-$22 per barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' rig count has been cut almost in half from a high of
1,000 in September, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The job losses are felt in cities and in the fields. Halliburton
Energy Services said last month that it will close its Fort Worth
plant that made wireline equipment. That will cost the city about
400 jobs, although some of the workers will be offered positions in
Houston and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Halliburton announcement was the latest cutback, after the
news that Union Pacific Resources Group would reduce its downtown
Fort Worth work force by at least 140.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said the job loss figures are understated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the people who used to work in the oilfields as
contractors have found other work, in construction or cattle
tending or the like,'' he said. ``Because they don't file for
unemployment compensation, they aren't counted as jobless. But they
are lost to the industry and we worry that we won't get them
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said that among producers, the survivors of the late
1980s energy bust emerged as better capitalized, leaner and better
operators. For that reason, most are likely to ride out the current
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't seeing a lot of bankrutpcies and liquidations now,
and that's kind of surprising,'' Stevens said. ``Most are able to
hunker down and wait for better times.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton, who has built a New York Stock Exchange company
during the past 10 years, said that the recent price slump has been
``incredibly debilitating'' to the industry.
</P>
<P>
   He said the much-heralded jump in stock prices, which followed
the most recent OPEC announcement in late March, won't put any more
money in producers' cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen some improvement in our stocks, although most are
still trading at or near the 52-week low,'' Pinkerton said. ``But
you aren't seeing new issues of stock or IPOs, so you can't count
this little blip as any increase in companies' liquidity.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
