u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WOODS-BOS &LR;      04-08 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS CONFIDENT HE IS STILL THE TIGER TO BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ David Duval and Tiger Woods. Tiger Woods or David
Duval. The golfers themselves are not much more daring _ or
insightful _ than sportswriters when predicting the winner of the
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger Woods can do anything,'' is how Fred Couples put it.
``David Duval can do anything. It's just that they're totally
different. They play differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval ``hits it the same every single time,'' said Couples.
``Tiger plays with a boat load of emotion; and when he's going
strong, he's pumping his fists, he's hitting it even farther.''
</P>
<P>
   No question, said Jack Nicklaus, Woods and Duval ``have been way
above everybody else in the last few months, in the last year or
so. And I think it would be great if one of them won this week and
one of them won the US because that would fuel the rivalry,'' the
same type that Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer had 35 years ago, the
rivalry that so energized golf, the rivalry that golf itself has
been searching for.
</P>
<P>
   But look closely. Tiger Woods leaves the 18th green after
finishing his practice round and, altering his routine, does not
head to the practice tee. Instead, he heads to the putting green
where he taps and taps and taps one ball after another. And does
not bend over that often.
</P>
<P>
   That ``boat load of emotion'' that Fred Couples mentioned seems
far away from Woods, so in control here. If he taps his putter and
then bends over to pull his ball from the cup after only one tap,
doing it time and again, maybe the fists will pump and the emotion
will sky. And the electricity, too. Just like two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good motivation, the fact that David's playing
extremely well,'' Woods says in one sentence. And then follows with
another sentence, dampening any hint of a rivalry. ``You can't get
caught up in all that and have that as your only motivating factor.
You have to try and get better and I have been.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Just as there is little doubt that Woods is becoming more and
more inscrutable in the public eye. ``Just now, unfortunately, I
haven't been able to get as many wins as David,'' Woods says, too
matter-of-factly. ``I haven't been able to make shots at the right
time, and guys are outplaying me down the stretch. It's just part
of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, too matter-of-factly. Understandable, of course,
since Woods was called upon to carry golf on his shoulders after
his record-breaking win here two years ago, and he needed a shell
around his soul with so much, too much, attention. Still. ``Guys
are outplaying me down the stretch . . .'' Words that would never
be heard from the lips of Palmer or Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   It's a relief, Woods says, that it is Duval and not he who is
getting all the attention. ``I can tell you one thing,'' Wood says.
``It's a lot easier to come to tournaments and not have to do a
mandatory press conference every day. Now, David's doing that, and
he can have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, for others, it might be a relief not to see so many
Tiger Woods commercials every day, either. ``Yeah,'' Woods says,
``the hype kind of got up a little bit. It's a little different
now. Now, David's got to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   So Woods is pleasant, pleasantly testy. When asked how he feels
that it is Duval, and not Woods, who is being inspected so closely
these days days, Woods's rejoinder is, ``Trust me, I still am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
