<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORTER PUTS REVOLUTION MIDFIELD ON GOOD FOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Revolution are regrouping for their MLS home
opener against D.C. United Saturday. Edwin Gorter will return from
suspension and Giovanni Savarese is on the verge of recovering from
a deeply bruised ankle and shin.
</P>
<P>
   Gorter played the entire 75 minutes of Wednesday's scrimmage
against the Boston Bulldogs at Babson College in Wellesley and is
expected to make his first regular-season appearance for the
Revolution since Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The teams played to a 0-0 tie, but at least the Revolution
survived intact _ last week, Savarese was injured in a scrimmage
against the New Hampshire Phantoms.
</P>
<P>
   Gorter directed the attack from midfield, along with Jair, and
helped control the tempo against the Bulldogs, who provided a
strong test.
</P>
<P>
   Last season was unfulfilling for Gorter, who was recruited to
the Revolution by Thomas Rongen as the answer to D.C. United's
Marco Etcheverry and Miami's Carlos Valderrama. Gorter displayed an
excellent touch, but the Revolution's lack of cohesiveness limited
Gorter's effectiveness in midfield, and midway through the season
he was moved into central defense in a desperate attempt to settle
the team. The Revolution continued to lose, and dissension became
apparent, climaxing in a postseason brawl involving Gorter and
David Nakhid, for which Gorter was fined $25,000 and suspended for
the first two games of this season.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Walter Zenga had replaced Rongen, who was on the way to
D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas is one of my best friends,'' Gorter said. ``We are
professional soccer players, but after the game I will have dinner
with him. But the only thing that counts Saturday is the three
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, D.C. is the best team in the league. We always play
well against D.C. But they are so strong, a very smart team with a
lot of quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have held the lead for 134 of 180 official
minutes in taking a shootout loss to Miami and a win at Kansas
City, indicating a sharp turnaround in the team's fortunes. But the
advantages have been earned by a composed and experienced defense,
keyed by Zenga's goalkeeping, and opportunistic strikes by Joe-Max
Moore and Savarese. They have failed to display inspirational
midfield combinations, so the understanding shown by Gorter and
Jair was encouraging Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gorter had the Revolution's best scoring chance, from the edge
of the goal area midway through the first half, but failed to round
goalkeeper Anthony Latronica. Jair and Paulo Dos Santos also barely
missed with shots, Dos Santos sending an impressive 25-yard drive
just high. And the Bulldogs' Unisa Conteh hit the post in the 12th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United will provide a stiff test for Gorter's defensive
abilities and fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided all together to play this way, where our forwards
are the first defenders and the No. 10 is the second defender,''
Gorter said. ``We are more defensive than offensive now. But when
you are building a house, you start with the basement. Later, you
add the roof. It is going to take a couple of months, but we are
getting better with every game and the season is long. We have
three points, and almost had six points, in two games. And points
are what counts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 20,000 is expected for the opener. ``We are starting
a week earlier than last year,'' general manager Brian O'Donovan
said. ``And people want to see what kind of team we have.'' About
6,000 season tickets have been purchased, about 300 fewer than last
year . . . Giuseppe Galderisi, who played for the Revolution and
Tampa Bay in 1996 and '97, attended practice in an advisory
capacity. ``I am here to see if I can help the team,'' Galderisi
said. ``I want to be a coach, and this could be a chance to get
some experience, and to help this team and the league.'' Galderisi,
who won Italian Serie A titles with Juventus and Verona, is
scheduled to enroll in coaching license courses at Coverciano, the
Italian Federation training center, in June but could postpone his
participation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
