</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ WASHINGTON _ A former president of Cyprus has
arrived in Belgrade, where he's trying to secure the release of
three American soldiers. Meanwhile, NATO assesses damage from
another night of attacks amid growing concerns that Albanians are
being used as human shields in Kosovo. NATO also says it's not
responsible for the widespread damage in Pristina, the provincial
capital of Kosovo. According to NATO officials, the damage was
probably carried out by the Serbs. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
