<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL A WINNER, BUT HE'D RATHER BE SNOWBOARDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ David Duval says he is sometimes at his most
relaxed when he is snowboarding down the mountainside in Sun
Valley, Idaho, or fishing near his home outside Jacksonville, Fla.
He is quiet, introspective and hides behind a pair of Oakley
sunglasses on the golf course. He is now also the game's best
player, in the middle of an astonishing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Should he win this 63d Masters and don the green jacket that got
away from him a year ago, he will have five victories in nine
starts this year and 12 wins in his last 34 starts. After earning a
reputation as a perennial bridesmaid, he burst to the front with
three straight victories to end the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   The only players in the past 49 years to enter the Masters with
four Tour victories were Arnold Palmer (1960) and Johnny Miller
(1974), and a Masters victory would give Duval three straight
following his triumphs at The Players Championship the BellSouth
Classic. Duval, who is 27, has earnings of $2,598,33, a PGA season
record with The Tour barely into April.
</P>
<P>
   Duval said winning The Players Championship near his home in
Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla., was even more special in that his father,
Bob, was enjoying his first Senior Tour victory on the west coast
of the state the same day. Winning the BellSouth in Atlanta was
special to him because he played his college golf at Georgia Tech
and led the tournament after three rounds when he was 20. The
Masters? The taste of victory would be even sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to have it wrapped up a year ago, leading by three
with three holes to go. Then his bogey on the par-3 16th opened the
door for Mark O'Meara, who registered birdies on three of the final
four holes, rolling in a 20-foot putt on the 18th to win.
</P>
<P>
   Duval seems to maintain a calm, relaxed demeanor in contrast to
the fiery presence of Tiger Woods. After his victory at The Players
Championship, Duval became the world's No. 1, displacing Woods.
``To be successful out here you have to find the demeanor and
personality under which you perform your best,'' says Duval.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me that's not worrying about stuff. Other players might
get fired up by getting upset. That doesn't do me right. It doesn't
serve me well at all, so I don't worry about it. I can't do
something over. I can't rehit a shot. I can only move forward. So
that's what I try to do. Certainly stuff bothers me away from the
golf course. I try not to let outside influences dictate whether
I'm happy or not. I guess that's what it boils down to.''
</P>
<P>
   They are arguably the world's two best players, and there is a
mutual respect. When Woods burst on the scene after capturing his
third US Amateur title in September 1976 and tore up the field and
the course to win the Masters, it forced the other players to try
to elevate their games. Duval was one of them, turning to weight
training and talking with sports psychologist Bob Rotella.
</P>
<P>
   Duval doesn't see himself in the same category as Woods, or a
Michael Jordan, or a Jeff Gordon. ``I've always thought I've had a
pretty good responsibility anyway,'' said Duval. ``I might be in
the process of becoming a golf star or whatever you want to call
it, but I'm not like Tiger in the sense that Tiger's a star. I
don't think because I've surpassed him as No. 1 I've been given any
more responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The tables are reversed, and Woods seemed poised to respond.
They're also friends. ``I don't know if I can say he's good for me
from that standpoint,'' says Woods. ``I think he's good from the
standpoint that he's playing so well and that's what we all want to
do. So as players we want to get to where he's at right now. I knew
it was a matter of time the points would add up and David was going
to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating from the standpoint I was playing well
but not getting the victories. If you look at my finishes, I was
always in the top five. I just wasn't able to get a victory before
San Diego. Even then, I had to play great golf on the weekend for a
victory. It just hasn't been one of those stretches where guys are
making mistakes or I'm making shots at the right time to make guys
make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The ascent to No. 1 has placed new demands on Duval, requiring
more time away from the course and taking him away from live-in
girlfriend Julie McArthur whom he met at Georgia Tech. Now he's the
favorite, a responsibility he realizes he has properly inherited as
he seeks his first major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me,'' said Duval. ``I embrace it. I believe
it's my responsibility now; it's part of playing tournament golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to choose, would I seek it out? No. I think everybody
knows I wouldn't seek out attention. I firmly believe it's my duty
to be here and do the best I can. I've always thought I have a
pretty big responsibility anyway. I won't have to rely on
adrenaline here. If you can't get worked up and ready to play here,
you need to go and do something else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
