<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALREADY HE'S A FALLEN ANGEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Eighty million dollars . . . and he was hurt
before he took his first swing in his new uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty million dollars . . . and he was in a hospital before the
end of his first game with his new team.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty million dollars . . . and he was on crutches in the
locker room after the first game.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn toiled for 10 seasons in the Boston Red Sox
organization. He knows all about curses. He knows the feeling of
helplessness when it seems larger forces are calling the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Now he plays for the Anaheim Angels, another franchise that
seems to have angered the diamond gods.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning of his first game with Anaheim Tuesday
night, Vaughn fell into the Cleveland Indians dugout while chasing
a pop fly. He hung around for five innings and went 0 for 2, but
left for the hospital at the start of the sixth (x-rays were
negative) and was out of the lineup for Wednesday night's game with
a sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``No curses,'' said Vaughn. ``I've been through that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Players who have worked for the Red Sox, Cubs, and
Indians have a working knowledge of Why Bad Things Happen To Good
Teams. But it would appear that there's also a black cloud over the
Angel halo.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels never have been in a World Series. Their closest
brush came in 1986, when they led the Red Sox, 3-1, in the American
League Championship Series and held a 5-2 lead in the ninth inning
of Game 5. But Gene Mauch maneuvered himself out of the playoffs
and reliever Donnie Moore surrendered a crushing home run to Dave
Henderson. Moore killed himself three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was not the first Angel to die tragically. Outfielder
Lyman Bostock was shot to death in Gary, Ind., in 1978, one year
after signing a big free agent contract with California.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Sox and Cubs, the Angels are known for late-season
folds. They lost a one-game playoff to the Mariners in 1995 and
last year collapsed in the final week and handed the American
League West to the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries decimated the Angels in September 1998, and it hasn't
gotten any better this year. Anaheim opened the 1999 season with
eight players on the disabled list. Then Vaughn was on crutches
after the 6-5 victory over the Indians in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   The foul pop that did in Vaughn was hit by Cleveland shortstop
Omar Vizquel. Clearly unfamiliar with his new home field, Vaughn
bolted for the first-base boxes and quickly ran out of room. He was
lucky that he came down on the dugout floor, rather than on one of
the steps. Not one Cleveland player made any effort to catch him or
break his fall (Vaughn did not make the catch).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not our players' job,'' said Cleveland general manager
John Hart.
</P>
<P>
   True. But it would have been the sporting thing to do. Vaughn
easily could have broken one or both ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the lack of help he got from the Tribe, Mo said,
``People talk about, `The guys do this or that.' My job, first of
all, is to take care of myself, and I didn't. So I don't blame
anybody in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he have grabbed a Cleveland fielder if the situation were
reversed?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let anybody fall,'' he said. ``But I don't
blame anybody in their dugout. I've got a lot of friends on that
team and know that team pretty well. It was just one of those
things that happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a high sky, so I wasn't really able to look back and
look where I was. My main thing is nothing was broken, so
everything's all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn stayed in the game and received a standing ovation when
he came to the plate in the bottom of the first. When he hit a
routine fly to left, he collapsed in the batter's box, further
aggravating the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my back leg and my drive leg,'' he said. ``You know
you're not 100 percent, but I'm going to play until something's
broken. As long as I can. That's just the way I am. I tried to go
out there as long as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   He was late getting on the field in the top of the second
because he was having his ankles taped. He flied weakly to left in
the third and lasted two more innings before going to the hospital
for X-rays. Team doctor Lewis Yokum said Vaughn had a high sprain
of the left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me, but I was going to go as long as I could go
and do what I could,'' said Mo. ``I knew I was hurt, but I'm one of
those dumb guys who tries to keep playing at all times. I had them
both taped to try to get some balance, but it just started getting
really tight. I didn't want to be a defensive liability in a close
game like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was back in the clubhouse, icing the ankle, when the
Angels rallied for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very exciting,'' he said after putting down his
crutches. ``We've got a ball club that plays together and plays
hard, and the guys came in and picked me up. These guys all did the
job, so that was one to work off right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to heal pretty fast, so I'm not looking to be out too
long. You ain't gotta be 100 percent to play this game. I've had
sprained ankles before. I'll get some treatment and we'll see what
happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen. We've got 160 more games to play. I'm pretty
durable, but that's the way things go sometimes. I guarantee you it
won't be too long. Believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1411EDT &QL; 
