u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      04-08 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROANING CHIMNEY CAN BE EXPLAINED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a problem that no one seems to be able to solve, so
I'll see what the Handyman has to say. My 100-year-old farmhouse in
Hampton, N.H., has three chimneys with bluestone caps and hardware
cloth (steel mesh) over all three to keep out critters. But every
day, groans come from somewhere in one of the chimneys. They are
low, long, and weird, starting in late morning and going to 10 or
11 p.m. There are no trees nearby, and the hardware cloth keeps out
animals. So what is happening?
</P>
<P>
   NANCY BENSON, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Those groans sound like my refrigerator, which sometimes
makes similar noises, maybe when the fan goes on. I have gotten
used to them, but when they started, it was, indeed, weird.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've excluded the possibility of a poltergeist (they are
reputed to make a terrible racket!), you're left with wind and
downdrafts as the probable cause. What I think is happening is that
there is always a downdraft in one or more chimneys: a wafting of
air downward, caused by lower air pressure in the house than
outdoors. Wind, however small, may be forcing more air down the
chimney, but the downdraft continues even without wind.
</P>
<P>
   Being 100 years old, the chimneys are unlikely to have liners in
them, or maybe a piece of liner has broken off, or a brick has
become dislodged, wedging in the flue (the chimney opening) at an
angle, forming a whistle. When the downdraft hits this whistle, it
sounds. It's like blowing across a Coke bottle to get a toot, or
across the mouth of a jug to get the groan. Or, the downdraft is
vibrating a piece of liner tile or brick shard. But I don't know
why it occurs only between the hours you mention.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, the wind may be blowing across the soil pipe (the
sewer gas vent on the roof), making a jug-like groan. Cover that
pipe (temporarily) to see if the sound stops. If it does, you can
put an inverted U-shape extension on the soil pipe, which should
stop the noise by changing the position of the pipe opening. Don't
keep the pipe covered; it will affect the plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   One other thing: A breeze may be sounding when it blows through
that hardware cloth, which is 1/2-inch or 1/4-inch steel mesh. We
have all heard an ordinary insect screen whistling in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   To find out if all this is so, try this: Cover that hardware
cloth with a piece of polyethylene, sealing all joints with duct
tape (Don't do this with a fire or a heater going). Try this on one
chimney at a time, then all three.
</P>
<P>
   If the groans stop, it's the hardware cloth. If they don't, then
seal the bottoms of the chimneys, too, in the basement and in any
fireplaces. Just cover the firebox openings with plastic, sealing
them with duct tape. What you are trying to do here is stop the
downdrafts. If the groans stop when the downdrafts are stopped, you
know what you have to do. And, have a chimney sweep check the
chimneys for any blockages or partial blockages, and remove them.
</P>
<P>
   A final cause may not be the chimneys at all. This has happened
before. Sometimes a tree in a wind will bump up against the
telephone or electric wires coming into the house. The tree
branches are caressing the wires, like Heifetz on a violin, and the
whole house is the violin, the sounding board. The same thing could
happen with tree branches caressing the side of the house. I know
you said there are no trees nearby, but it is still worth a careful
check around the house, for anything that might be rubbing against
anything. Sometimes a loose wire will fly in the breeze. Check for
it. Check to see where the various wires to your house end up in
the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   If you do find anything, the Handyman would appreciate a call or
a letter, so he can add it to his vast files.
</P>
<P>
   These ideas might be a little harebrained, but the phenomenon
has happened before, with amazing cures, and all of them are in the
Handyman's files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My roommate insists on keeping the bathroom window open about
12 inches, as well as the door. She says that since we have central
air conditioning, opening the window is necessary for fresh air to
get in. I believe that with the advanced state of this technology
there is built into the system a provision to bring and circulate
fresh air. We are either cooling the outdoors or heating the
indoors _ very expensive, and hard on an air conditioner. What say
you?
</P>
<P>
   ANGELA HESS, Lake Wales, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. Whether your system has a fresh-air provision depends on its
age. We called Richard Kessler, an HVAC (heating, ventilation, and
air conditioning) consultant in Westfield, who said that the
fresh-air provision was developed five to seven years ago when air
quality became an issue. So if your system is seven to 10 years
old, chances are there is no fresh-air provision in it. Some
systems have an extra duct to allow fresh air to come in; others
have a damper that can be adjusted to control the amount of
incoming fresh air. A contractor can install such a duct for you in
a few hours, Kessler said.
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it. If your system has the fresh-air
provision, you don't have to open the window. If it doesn't, then
opening the window will help until you can put in the required
duct. But 12 inches? That's a bit much. An inch, even half inch, is
enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
