<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, April 9.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO says it will bomb Yugoslav TV and
radio to knock them off the air. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels) _ A military-diplomatic analysis: The
Serb herding of ethnic-Albanian refugees back into Kosovo changes
the equation for NATO, posing new targeting problems. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POWS (Dateline to kum) _ Developments on the three
captive U.S. soldiers and Cypriot efforts to win their release.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT (Washington) _ A look at Madeleine Albright, her
State Department and how they are weathering the crisis. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Dateline to kum, Albania) _ Developments at the
Albanian border. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ Developments in Macedonia. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIEF (Washington) _ With NATO and the U.N. now partners
in refugee work _ and half of the daily briefings in Brussels,
Washington and London taken up with refugee matters, questions are
being raised about the neutrality of the humanitarian organizations
and the role of the refugees in the military planning. By Elizabeth
Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VIETNAM (Hanoi) _ The Vietnamese, veterans of a U.S.
bombing campaign, excoriate the NATO attacks on Yugoslavia. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
