Healthcare falls 8 percent after the hospital operator issues its
own earnings warnings. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   With this related story:
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-TECH-COST (Undated) _ Improvements in technology, the
pride of America's health system, add inexorably to medical costs,
which are accelerating again after several years of slow or zero
growth. Many economists say that technology, including both new
techniques and medical hardware, accounts for half the overall
growth in costs. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-ECON (Frankfurt) _ The Bank of England lowers its base
lending rate to 5.25 percent from 5.5 percent. The European Central
Bank is meeting and also may reduce interest rates. The euro rises;
even though rate cuts often weaken a currency, the prospect that
lower rates in the 11 nations will spur economic growth is giving
support to the euro. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BIBLIOWICZ-NATIONAL (New York) _ Jessica M. Bibliowicz, who last
year surprised the financial community by stepping down as head of
Smith Barney's mutual fund business and joining John A. Levin, an
investment-advisory firm, moves again, becoming president and chief
executive of National Financial Partners, a new company.
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI-LVMH (Frankfurt, Germany) _ LVMH sweetens its offer for
Gucci to $85 a share from $81, but Gucci rejects the new proposal
and says it wants to hold talks with LVMH. Gucci says it finds
unacceptable a demand by LVMH that Gucci sell new shares to LVMH if
needed to secure a controlling stake. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 37
points, or 0.4 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 8 points, or
0.3 percent. Elsewhere, prices increased 1.8 percent in Tokyo and 1
percent in Hong Kong. They rose 0.8 percent in Frankfurt but fell
0.4 percent in London. Prices were up 1.6 percent in Brazil and
flat in Mexico. On the American debt market, the long bond was up
8/32 point. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments; plus the weekly
money-supply report. By Robert Hurtado.
