<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALM-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME WOMEN SEE SUGGESTIVE TECH ADS AS TURN-OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The maker of the Palm Pilot personal electronic
organizer is being criticized for using the female form to market
the device.
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign, labeled ``Simply Palm,'' features a nude woman
demurely caressing a sleek new Palm V, the latest version of the
best-selling hand-held personal electronic organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm ad campaign is the second recent dust-up over Silicon
Valley's use of the female form to sell products. Last year, a
marketing pitch featuring Katrina Garnett, an executive of
Burlingame-based Crossworlds Software Inc., was criticized because
she appeared in numerous magazine ads clad in a low-cut, black
dress, pushing her role as a dynamic component of the software
company. The company continued to run the ads despite the
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Palm has taken center stage, there could be
another storm in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Network Associates, a Santa Clara-based network security
company, has erected a billboard in Redwood City that shows a
voluptuous blonde asking: ``While you're watching me, who's
watching your network?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that's what I call offensive,'' said Donna Hoffman, a
professor who teaches electronic commerce at Vanderbilt University
in Nashville, Tenn. ``It really hearkens back to a time when women
were simply adornments in the office.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of other women contacted for comment on the Palm ad
campaign criticized Network Associate's billboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't the intention of the ad,'' said Jennifer Keavney,
director of public relations for Network Associates. ``The woman is
a hacker, she's in a position of power. She's calling the shots.
That was really the intent of the billboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Some women in the computer industry have publicly castigated
3Com Corp., the Santa Clara manufacturer of the Palm V, saying the
ads are demeaning to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a slap in the face,'' said Aliza Sherman, president
of New York City-based Cybergrrl Inc., which publishes the
Cybergrrl.com Web site, a clearinghouse for contemporary women's
issues and Internet culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so beyond anger,'' Sherman said. ``I'm completely
insulted. It shows that when it comes to technology, women are
simply adornments.''
</P>
<P>
   One women said she did not understand what message the ad tries
to convey.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lusty, a director at San Jose-based TSI Communications
Inc., a Silicon Valley public relations firm, said she drove by a
Simply Palm billboard every day. ``And I have no idea what's going
on with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get the fetal position of the woman,'' she said, ``and
the image together with the device is confusing. It just doesn't
correlate for me.''
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley pundit, Upside.com's Tish Williams, chided 3Com
for ads that appeal to the sexual fantasies of men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I confess, I laughed,'' she wrote in her daily Web column.
``To be more specific, I did a double take, made sure I wasn't
missing any fine print, and then I laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet reaction to 3Com's campaign was typically quick and
pointed. A Web site called Simply Porn satirized 3Com's campaign by
doctoring the ads and putting the device on the laps of naked
pornography starlets. A 3Com lawyer's warning prompted the site's
author to take it off the Web, though other Web sites had already
copied and posted the parody.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman, while criticizing the Network Associates ad, said the
message she got from the Palm campaign was one of ``design and
simplicity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of an art form than anything else,'' she added. ``I
find the ads very elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what 3Com intended, according to the woman who approved
the marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this as a celebration of design,'' said Liz
Brooking, the director of marketing communication at 3Com. ``We
wanted to have simple and arresting images that were aesthetic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
