<SLUG> BC-GREMLIN-CAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHTY CAT RELEASED FROM HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC DRUDIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gremlin, the 2-year-old cat who leapt into the
nation's imagination when he jumped from the fifth floor of a
burning building in February, scaled smaller heights at a ceremony
marking his release from the animal hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by news crews and photographers, the black-haired cat
perched on owner Wiley Clark's shoulder Wednesday and ... jumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't go jumping anymore,'' Clark said as Gremlin dodged
between the legs of veterinarians and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he's just not used to this many people,'' he said.
``But he has to be careful _ he has already used up at least one of
his lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Gremlin broke his jaw and suffered internal injuries when he
jumped from the Hartland Hotel during a fire Feb. 12. A videotape
of the cat's jump was broadcast on all-news stations, and donations
from around the country soon followed Gremlin to Pets Unlimited,
the San Francisco animal hospital that operated on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``One lady even wanted to give (us) her credit-card number and
said to charge whatever it cost to help Gremlin,'' said Peter
Pattengill, Pets Unlimited's director of development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so very appreciative and grateful for everything,'' Clark
said. ``I didn't think he'd even make it, and so many people have
helped him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gremlin's medical bills were about $5,000. Donations more than
covered the expenses, and the extra money went to the hospital's
general fund to help other animals, said Robert Marshall-Walker,
president of Pets Unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   Gremlin required surgery and nearly two months of care. He was
fed through a tube in his stomach for nearly a month, and his
dislocated jaw had to be wired and covered with a ``composite
bonding'' to keep it stable, said hospital medical director Tom
Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that when the fire broke out at his home in the
Hartland Hotel, he tried to grab Gremlin _ but the cat hid under
the bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the wall of smoke and flames, I knew I had to make
a choice,'' Clark said. He later saw the cat _ ``a black streak in
the air'' _ jump from a ledge, but couldn't find him until the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like he's in real good shape,'' Clark said. ``When I
first saw him (after the jump), I lost it. I didn't think he was
going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gremlin left the hospital with no lingering injuries _ just a
few missing teeth, Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   Pets Unlimited, founded in 1947, also runs an animal shelter and
adoption center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
