<HEADLINE>
NICKNAME OR NO NICKNAME FOR HOUSTON'S NEW STADIUM? THE FANS WILL
DECIDE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Now that Enron Corp. is paying more than $100 million
for the naming rights to the baseball park under construction
downtown, will people call it Enron Field?
</P>
<P>
   Or will they call it ``The Ron?'' How about ``Union Station?''
Maybe just ``The New Ballpark.'' Or ``The Downtown Ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   How about the ``Pop-Top,'' for the stadium's retractable roof?
</P>
<P>
   In the world of sports facility naming, monikers sometimes
stick.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Field in Atlanta is just that. Coors Field in Denver
doesn't need a nickname. Does Wrigley Field in Chicago need another
name?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they don't.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank One Ballpark in Phoenix is called ``The Bob.'' Jacobs
Field in Cleveland is ``The Jake.'' Qualcom Stadium in San Diego is
``The Murph.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, they get a little confusing.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Rockets play in The Summ ... uh, no ... uh, Compaq
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Brenner, editor of the Chicago-based Team Marketing Report,
predicts that Houston fans will join their counterparts who call
their stadiums by the corporate name. Fans are getting used to such
names, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1990, only four sports facilities, none in baseball, had
corporate names, Brenner said. This year, he said, 68 facilities in
the four major sports _ baseball, basketball, football and hockey _
have corporate names, including half of the 30 Major League
Baseball teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The further we move into the era of naming rights, the more
likely those names are to stick,'' Brenner said. ``The last good
example of significant resistance was when Candlestick Park was
renamed 3COM Park. But now it's an accepted part of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Enron Chairman Ken Lay hopes so.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference outside the ballpark Wednesday, as a
single-engine plane flew above towing a sign reading ``Enron Field:
Home of the Astros,'' Lay and Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr.
unveiled the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Enron will pay more than $100 million over 30 years for the name
to be placed atop the stadium. It will get a 30-year contract worth
about $200 million to manage energy services and certain parts of
the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Astros spokesman Rob Matwick said the team has already changed
the name on its Internet location and is rewriting other
publications to match.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want everyone to call it Enron Field,'' Matwick said.
</P>
<P>
   But will they?
</P>
<P>
   Houston lawyer Stan Perry, a season ticket holder at the
Astrodome, said he probably will call the field ``Union Station.''
He associates it with the physical location rather than a company's
marketing ploy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of the Sugar Bowl, I don't think of Nokia,''
Perry said, referring to the football game played each year in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Garth Jowett, a University of Houston communications professor,
said the ballpark may attract a nickname at first, but as the media
continue to pound ``Enron Field'' into the public's consciousness,
that name will eventually surface.
</P>
<P>
   But if people do call it by a different name, that would not be
unusual in Houston's baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Astrodome's formal name is the Harris County
Domed Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
