<HEADER>
A0639 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISC-REVIEWS-LADN     04-08 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISC-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VARIOUS/``THE LAST SOUL COMPANY'' (Malaco)
</P>
<P>
   Soul music didn't disappear with the popularity of hip-hop, it
just packed up and moved to Jackson, Miss., where the mighty Malaco
label is based. This delightful six-disc box proves the patient is
still robust. Included among these 112 examples of gritty Southern
r&AMP;b magic are obvious '70s gems like King Floyd's ``Groove Me'' and
Jean Knight's ``Mr. Big Stuff'' (both cut with New Orleans horn
arranger Wardell Quezerque), Dorothy Moore's elegant ``Misty
Blue,'' and raw, earthy sides from Little Milton, Bobby ``Blue''
Bland, Johnny Taylor, Denise LaSalle and the great Bobby Rush.
Makes a nice companion to the award-winning first Stax box. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BLUR/``13'' (Virgin)
</P>
<P>
   For the 20 percent of the population that still requires what
used to be known as alt-rock comes the painfully lo-fi new effort
from Brit art-school refugees Blur. Don't look for anything
resembling the band's upbeat radio hit, ``Song 2'' (the
``whoo-HOO'' song), though, because this is one dense, often atonal
but eventually rewarding journey. Produced by William Orbit
(Madonna's ``Ray of Light''), the album opens with the hymnlike
``Tender,'' helped along by a church choir. The grating ``Bugman''
is one of the few rockers here, while the lyrics to many of these
moody tracks seem to be about the breakup of Blur singer Damon
Albarn and longtime girlfriend Justine Frischmann of the
missing-in-action Elastica. 2 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
VARIOUS/``HOTS RODS &AMP; CUSTOM CLASSICS: CRUISIN' SONGS &AMP; HIGHWAY
HITS'' (Rhino)
</P>
<P>
   Rev up those engines. With typical elan, Rhino turns its sharp
repackaging eye toward hot-rod culture in this fine-tuned four-disc
anthology featuring a showroom's worth of songs _ including many
out-of-print items _ about America's love affair with the auto.
Car-related commercial sound bites and sound effects are sprinkled
throughout, including a rare James Dean public service announcement
encouraging listeners to drive carefully.
</P>
<P>
   The 87-track collection, which comes complete with decals, key
chain and a pair of fuzzy dice that look good hanging from your
dashboard or on top of your computer, travels from Duane Eddy
(``Forty Miles of Bad Road'') and the Beach Boys (``Little Deuce
Coupe'') through Rod Stewart (``Gasoline Alley''), the Flying
Burrito Bros. (``Wheels'') and Junior Brown (``Highway Patrol'').
Best of all, though, are the many obscurities, such as ``Motorhead
Baby'' from Johnny ``Guitar'' Watson and ``Hot Rod Lincoln'' by
Johnny Bond. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TOM RUSSELL/``THE MAN FROM GOD KNOWS WHERE'' (Hightone)
</P>
<P>
   Known primarily for making authentic-sounding western music on
such albums as ``Cowboy Real,'' Russell here takes on the ambitious
task of telling his family history in song. Employing a multivoice
approach _ Russell as well as guest vocalists Iris DeMent, Dolores
Keane, Sondre Bratland and Kari Bremnes all sing for several,
sometimes recurring characters _ he charts his forebears' progress,
from the immigrant pioneers who settled the Iowa prairie (``Patrick
Russell'') to his own high-livin' father, who raised Tom and horses
in Topanga Canyon (``Throwin' Horseshoes at the Moon'').
</P>
<P>
   The album's great musical coup is the way it charts the
development of our traditional music from its European antecedents,
best represented by the haunting mix of Uilleann pipes and
Hardangar fiddles _ the instruments of Russell's Irish and
Norwegian ancestors _ with American folk idioms. Its poetic triumph
is an achingly personal mosaic of (mostly) unfulfilled pilgrims'
yearnings, how it captures the restless national need for both a
sense of belonging and a promising horizon. Far from downbeat,
though, ``God Knows Where'' also incorporates hard-bitten optimism
and even wry satire, as in Keane's lilting, adorably gossipy
lament, ``When Irish Girls Grow Up.'' 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Strauss &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
VARIOUS/``THE DISCO BOX'' (Rhino)
</P>
<P>
   This four-CD retrospective on the golden age of polyester packs
enough bootie-shaking bass lines, propulsive horns and cheerfully
insinuating and/or inane lyrics to keep you and your
medallion-wearing friends wiggling your groove thangs from dusk
till dawn. Especially welcome are such early-'70s disco forerunners
as the Jackson 5's Motown-meets-Munich synth-funk hit, ``Dancing
Machine,'' and ``Get Dancin','' a braggadocious, quasi-rapping
party tune from the unfortunately named Disco-Tex &AMP; his
Sex-O-Lettes. But what's this? A disco boxed set that's completely
missing the Brothers Gibb (that's Bee Gees, to those under 30), and
with only minimal contributions from Donna Summer and none _
repeat, none _ from Rick James, Prince or George
Clinton/Parliament/Funkadelic? Blasphemy! The producers' narrow
focus is especially damning on the weak Disc Four, which misses a
chance to illustrate the bridge between American disco-funk and the
pioneering New Wave and techno-disco of, say, Kraftwerk and the
Human League. Still, this is a useful compendium for a
much-maligned genre. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Reed Johnson &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
OSCAR PETERSON/``A NIGHT IN MUNICH'' (Telarc)
</P>
<P>
   Those who were lucky enough to have seen pianist Peterson and
his outstanding quartet last summer at the Hollywood Bowl should
pick this disc up, as it contains several of the songs he played
that evening. (A rip-roaring ``Satin Doll,'' one of the night's
many highlights, is among the compositions included here.) If you
weren't there, now's your chance to see what you missed. The
73-year-old Peterson debuts a couple of lovely ballads _ ``Evening
Song'' and ``When Summer Comes'' _ proving that his way with a
melody has not diminished over time. Nor has his keyboard skill,
despite a stroke several years ago that forced him to alter his
style. (For proof, check out the barnstorming opener, ``Backyard
Blues.'') Peterson remains a towering figure in jazz. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MCCOY TYNER/``MCCOY TYNER AND THE LATIN ALL-STARS'' (Telarc)
</P>
<P>
   After going symphonic with the music of Burt Bacharach with his
last album, pianist Tyner goes off on another unexpected path here
with an album of Afro-Cuban music. Tyner has been down this road
before, though (just not that often), and knows his way around a
groove as well as anybody. The album features familiar
compositions, such as Kenny Dorham's ``Blue Bossa'' and Ahmad
Jamal's ``Poinciana,'' delivered with an elegant authority by pros
like trombonist Steve Turre and flutist Dave Valentin. There's
nothing groundbreaking here, just many fine musical moments. 3
stars
</P>
<P>
   _ G &UR; l &LR; enn Whipp &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
