<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL TEAM ACCUSED OF SEXUAL ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A veteran high school baseball coach has been
dismissed and the team's season abruptly canceled amid allegations
that several teen-age team members sexually assault other students
in a hazing ritual.
</P>
<P>
   The reported incident involved 10 students from Raoul Wallenberg
Traditional Alternative High School who were playing at a
tournament in to San Diego. What began as a poolside hazing was
said to have devolved into sexual assault by four students on six
others. The students were at the tournament from March 30 through
April 2.
</P>
<P>
   Three students were arrested, and a fourth player from the high
school will be arrested, the police said. School district officials
said they recommended the students be expelled if the investigation
of the incident confirmed the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of Wallenberg's baseball season was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Although none of the students allegedly involved, all boys 16 or
17, was identified, sketchy details of the alleged sexual battery
on younger teammates emerged Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Police sources said ``foreign objects,'' possibly coat hangers
found in the hotel, had been used by the older boys to sexually
assault the other students.
</P>
<P>
   Wallenberg's coach, Bob Babick, who founded the school's
baseball program in 1990, said he had learned of the allegations
only Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm beyond disappointed ... I'm totally devastated by this,''
said Babick, 51, a coach in San Francisco schools for 16 years.
``This has always been my labor of love. It's where my heart is.''
</P>
<P>
   School district spokeswoman Sandina Robbins said Babick had been
``released'' pending the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's no season, there's no coach,'' Robbins said. ``It's
unfortunate that the season is ended, and the coach was released.
But we have to send a strong message of zero tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's high school athletics program involves about
4,700 students who participate in 16 sports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
