<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTING-HAZARDS-2TAKES     04-08 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTING-HAZARDS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAK A LEG: STAGE PERFORMERS FACE HIGH RISK OF INJURY 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Watch out for that rake!
</P>
<P>
   That's the advice Houston doctors Randolph and Richard Evans
have for theater performers after conducting two studies on their
injuries in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The warning does not refer to farm tools in revivals of
``Oklahoma!`` but to the raked or sloping stage floor used in many
shows to give audiences a better view of the action. Though they
may be an aesthetic boon, the Evans' two studies found that they
caused a threefold increase in the likelihood of performer injury.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was a raked stage that inspired the studies.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Evans, a neurologist with the Texas Medical Center, was
taking a backstage tour after attending ``Miss Saigon`` at the
Broadway Theater in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like standing on a ski slope!'' Evans said of the stage
floor. ``I asked cast members, especially dancers, if it was
difficult performing on it. They said that it was and that some had
made complaints to management, but had gotten little response.''
</P>
<P>
   A longtime theater buff with friends in the business, Evans
decided to do a study on the frequency of actor injuries, the
contributing factors and possible ways of making the stage a safer
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I contacted Actors Equity (the profession's union), and they
were very interested in the idea. Especially when they learned I
wanted to do the survey free of charge. In other cases, they've
hired companies to do studies of particular occupational hazards
and had to pay a good deal for them. As I'm in private practice,
the cost to me was mostly my time.''
</P>
<P>
   The project soon involved Evans' father Richard, distinguished
professor and director of social psychology and behavioral medicine
at the University of Houston and another longtime theater buff (and
friend of the late Alley Theater founder Nina Vance).
</P>
<P>
   ``My father and his graduate students were very helpful in
designing the survey and analyzing the results. I came up with the
concept, wrote up the findings and was the contact with the unions,
arranging things.''
</P>
<P>
   The first study was conducted in 1993 among cast members of 10
Broadway productions and 13 national tours, with results published
in the American Journal of Public Health in 1996. Involved were 168
dancers and 151 actors in the 23 productions.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 55 percent sustained injuries at some
point. Most common were strains and sprains of the lower
extremities. About 37 percent of dancers and 28 percent of actors
incurred an injury serious enough to make them miss at least one
performance, and 13 individuals required surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The raked stage was found to be the highest risk factor. ``Miss
Saigon,'' which had the steepest rake _ 10 degrees _ had the
highest number of injuries, followed by ``Cats.`` Among the road
tours, ``Cats'' registered the most injuries, followed by ``The
Will Rogers Follies,'' which didn't have a raked stage but featured
an elaborate staircase on which many of the numbers were performed.
</P>
<P>
   Other risk factors were: fog and smoke effects, which hindered
visibility and caused upper respiratory irritation; heavy wigs,
masks and costumes; uneven floors; and trap doors. Women were
injured more often than men, presumably because they often had to
perform the same maneuvers wearing heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would seem like common sense that certain things increase
risk,'' said Kenneth Greenwood, senior representative of Actors
Equity. ``But we can't make significant progress at the bargaining
table unless we have studies showing the harm caused. So Randy's
study has been very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actors Equity was thrilled because the study supported their
position,'' said Randolph Evans. ``They got some changes in the
production contract, which now recommends a maximum rake of 7.5
degrees, (and specifies) that shows with raked stages have a
physical therapist on staff to help the actors work more safely.
They also recommend more judicious use of fog and smoke, and that
machines producing it be placed farther from the singers to cause
less damage to vocal cords.''
</P>
<P>
   When Randolph Evans suggested in 1996 that the study be
replicated in London's West End, British Equity greeted his plan as
a welcome coincidence. Only the week before, the union had
circulated a memo about performance injuries. In London, the study
looked at 269 actors and dancers in 12 dramas and eight musicals.
</P>
<P>
   The results, published last fall in Occupational and
Environmental Medicine, were similar to the New York findings,
pointing to raked stages and fog machines as leading dangers. Close
to half the players (46 percent) suffered work-related injuries at
some point in their runs. ``Starlight Express,'' Andrew Lloyd
Webber's musical roller derby, was found to be the most hazardous
show (surprise!).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In both studies, sprains and strains of lower extremities proved
the most common injuries, though back and neck injuries were fairly
common.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed at the attention the studies received,'' said
Randolph Evans. ``I was interviewed by USA Today and the BBC, among
others. Best of all, our little studies had an impact on production
contracts, both on Broadway and the West End.''
</P>
<P>
   Though not included in the Evans' studies, Houston's resident
theaters have seen their share of mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   In the Alley's 1997 production of ``Mere Mortals,'' Annalee
Jefferies was leaving the stage after curtain call and (she
confesses) ``horsing around'' a bit with fellow actor Paul Hope.
She took a tumble, and the resultant ankle injury caused her to
miss a performance and play the show's final week in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, veteran Houston actress Marjorie Carroll took
a wrong turn exiting the stage during a rehearsal for ``Hedda
Gabler'' and fell. Her resultant ankle injury caused her to
withdraw from the show. Bettye Fitzpatrick replaced her opening
night, and Carroll's understudy, Sharon Bennett, played the rest of
the run.
</P>
<P>
   An accident with far greater potential for harm befell Richard
White, leading man of Theater Under The Stars' ``Zorro'' in 1998.
During a rehearsal, the horse he was riding slipped and fell on
White's leg. (Theater buffs know that a similar accident crippled
composer Cole Porter.) Though the accident exacerbated an earlier
knee injury, White nonetheless got back on the horse with no
further mishaps during the run. After the engagement, however, he
had surgery on the knee. ``There was no permanent damage,
happily,'' said TUTS spokesman Susie Works.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most extreme result of actor injury in recent years
befell ``Busker Alley,'' the Broadway-bound musical that played
here as part of a tryout tour in 1995. The show put star Tommy Tune
and the male chorus through their paces in athletic dance numbers
that often involved swinging on a phalanx of onstage lampposts.
Though there were no disasters during the Houston engagement, star
Tommy Tune ``landed wrong'' during a number on the tour's final
stop in Tampa, breaking his foot. As the show was frankly a vehicle
for Tune, who couldn't have danced for many months, it folded
without reaching Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it odd that millions of people are riveted to every
detail about a sports figure's injuries,'' said Randolph Evans,
``but no one pays much attention to actors' injuries. The theater
is thought of as such a glamorous profession. Yet it's very hard
work, usually for far less pay than the audience realizes, and
often under less than ideal conditions. The Broadway and London
theaters are wonderful and historic _ but they often have backstage
areas far less spacious and comfortable than those of university
and community theaters. Besides the onstage risks, the performers
are racing on and off through crowded dressing rooms and sometimes
up and down steep, narrow stairways.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans admits that, in the cosmic scheme, actors' injuries may
not seem an important issue, as they affect so few people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet it's important to the actors who make this their life's
work, and to all who attend these shows and enjoy their work. It's
a quality-of-workplace issue. If you love the performing arts, you
are concerned about these artists, especially since most of them
rarely get the recognition they deserve. And what we learn looking
at their safety concerns can be applied to those in amateur and
student productions, which opens it up to a lot more people.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
