<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0750 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY09-COX     04-08 1673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ceramics showcase flourishes amid rolling pastures
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEAGROVE, N.C. _ In this tiny Piedmont town where just about
everyone is a potter, and nearly every gravel driveway winds back
to a pottery shop, customers make an art of searching for the
perfect pot.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, Darlene Samuelson, who was in the hunt last
week when she popped into Turn and Burn Pottery, one of more than
100 _ yep, two zeroes _ ceramics shops within 15 miles of here. The
46-year-old Cincinnati nurse was staying overnight on her second
visit to Seagrove, 45 minutes south of Greensboro, breaking up a
long drive to a beach vacation. Her mission: finding a primitive
piece for herself and a contemporary one as a present for friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice off-the-beaten-path way to spend the day,'' she
said, before turning to shop proprietor David Garner and adding,
``I guess you don't particularly like hearing Seagrove called `off
the beaten path.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, for Garner, 47, who happens also to be mayor of this
town of 250, that kind of smarts.
</P>
<P>
   Seagrove has long been a bit of a secret among ceramics lovers,
decorators visiting the nearby High Point furniture showrooms and
spouses of golfers playing at neighboring Pinehurst.
</P>
<P>
   Then, nearly two years ago, a stretch of new interstate opened,
bypassing Seagrove and removing most of the 29,000 cars that used
to tool through the heart of town on U.S. 220 _ many on the way to
Myrtle Beach, S.C. At first I-73/74's exit signs didn't even
mention the name Seagrove, quite a slight for a place where
pottery-making goes back so many generations that some shops
include family ``museums.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there are more interstate signs than billboards for Mickey
D's and, while traffic isn't what it was, there are encouraging
signs of renewal. The $1.2 million North Carolina Pottery Museum,
which opened late last year, not only gives the area a new
attraction but also serves as a needed information center for
tourists not quite sure where to start. And there's also the Duck
Smith House, a new B&AMP;B, the town's first, to keep them overnight.
</P>
<P>
   And, just as the oaks leaf out and dogwoods blossom, there's
also the promise of customers returning after winter's doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   To help launch the season, 60 of the potteries are participating
in the 6th annual Spring Kiln Opening on April 17-18. Many of the
potters will unload their freshly fired wares from their kilns (the
ovens in which the glazed clay forms are baked into pots at
temperatures higher than 2,000 degrees) in front of customers who
line up to get first pick. The crowd is typically so big at the
pottery of Ben Owen III, a seventh-generation potter, they have to
give out numbers to maintain order.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the potters are much more casual about it, doing the
unloading and finishing work ahead of time and simply displaying
the new wares for sale. But many literally put on a show _
demonstrating how to ``throw'' pots or firing some. At Turn and
Burn, for instance, Garner plans to have two raku kilns stoked,
yanking pots out of the infernos every 20 minutes or so with long
fireplace tongs then smothering them in sawdust to get a crackled
decorative effect on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, Phil Morgan, who creates porcelain pieces with a
gorgeous crystalline glaze, will be holding his breath as he opens
his kiln. With any firing, there's an element of chance _ a
mistake, or even a sudden climactic change, can ruin a load that's
taken a month or more to produce. Morgan's glaze, in which colorful
crystals burst onto the pots' glowing surfaces by alterations of
temperature during firing, is harder to control than most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's Christmas when I open the kiln, and sometimes
it's Halloween,'' says Morgan, 50. ``But it's exciting to know that
here's this big kiln cooling down, and (the customer is seeing
what's inside when the potter sees it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you can't make it to the spring event _ or to the 18th
annual fall festival, held at a central location rather than the
individual potteries, on Nov. 21 _ Seagrove is a fun, down-to-earth
destination almost any time.
</P>
<P>
   While there are bigger employers here, including a furniture
manufacturer and a canning plant, Seagrove seems to boast more
potteries than Luck's has pinto beans. Most of them are off N.C.
705 as it winds east out of Seagrove through the barely-there
communities of Whynot, Westmoore and Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   It's a beautiful drive past rolling Piedmont pastures where
cattle are already working overtime to keep the grass trimmed and
tidy. Colorful, hand-painted road signs for the potteries dot the
roadside, pointing you down side streets where shops are
interspersed with farmhouses.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the pleasure of the hunt is seeing what's around the
next bend _ every time you think you've found the last shop and
start to turn around, there's another one. Just don't act like a
city slicker and get all startled when one of the neighbors looks
up from his mailbox run or garden dig and actually waves as you
cruise by. (Tip: It's polite to wave back.)
</P>
<P>
   Just as there's no typical style of Seagrove pot _ it's the
variety that helps keep more than 100 potteries in business _ the
shops themselves run the gamut. Westmoore Pottery is housed in a
chalet-style cottage with a cedar shake roof, somehow fitting for
the Moravian and English reproduction wares that are its
speciality. Other shops are a living lesson in rural recycling:
Phil Morgan Pottery used to be a roller rink, a bootleg bar and a
Holiness church. Luck's Ware is half of a former chicken coop.
Michael Mahan's From the Ground Up pottery _ so named for the
burnished pots that he fires in an earthen pit _ is in converted
outbuildings.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the places conduct business in a style so low key they
barely seem to be in business. One customer last week spent 15
minutes wandering though historic Jugtown Pottery and its adjoining
museum without anyone appearing to say as much as howdy.
</P>
<P>
   At the nearby M.L. Owens Pottery Shop, the sign out front
promises, ``M.L. Owens is here.'' But on two visits, the front door
was wide open, the birdhouses and ashtrays and such were sitting
out and the lights were on, but ol' M.L. wasn't home. Finally, the
visitor noticed the note scrawled on scratch paper on the desk:
``Wait on yourself if no one's here. Please add 6 percent tax and
leave money in basket. Thanks, M.L.O.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, you'll have to come back if you want to talk to the
80-something dean of local potters about the history of Seagrove,
which, like a pottery wheel, has gone in a circle.
</P>
<P>
   The industry was born to produce food storage wares for the
Moravian farmers who settled in the Piedmont in the 1750s. There
were more than 250 potteries here around the turn of the century,
but the advent of factory-produced containers and other factors
reduced them to a handful after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Working at Jugtown Pottery from 1923-1959 and then in his own
shop until 1972, Benjamin Wade Owen Sr. was instrumental in a sea
change in Seagrove, from strictly utilitarian pieces to the more
artistic works that collectors covet today. His Asian-inspired pots
_ with their serene lines and vividly hued glazes _ are handsomely
displayed alongside his grandson's in the new museum that adjoins
Ben Owen III's gallery, as slick as any in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   After traveling to Japan several years ago for a workshop, Ben
III has delved deeper into Asian design, incorporating glazes such
as Chinese red, oribe (a sea-foam green) and shino (sand).
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the museum last week, Owen, 30, marveled over how
Seagrove has rebounded to reign as the country's biggest pottery
center. ``We're all influenced by many different backgrounds,'' he
said. ``That's what people notice when they come into this
community. When they go into different potteries, they see
different, not better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every piece produced in Seagrove is one of a kind because
everyone's hand has a different touch on clay.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: It's a six-hour drive to Seagrove: From Atlanta
take I-85 north to Charlotte and N.C. 49 to Asheboro and U.S. 73/74
South. Or by plane, it's $98 round trip on AirTran or Delta to
Greensboro, with a 14-day advance purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spring Kiln Opening details: 9 a.m.-5 p.m. April 17 and noon-5
p.m. April 18. Free. Maps available at any of the 60 participating
potteries or at the North Carolina Pottery Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About the North Carolina Pottery Center: The long, low-slung
building, which evokes a train station on the outside, features a
200-piece collection detailing the traditions and innovations of
perhaps the country's most active pottery-making state. Just inside
the entrance there are maps and a display of contemporary Seagrove
potters to help visitors decide which shops to hit first. 10 a.m.-4
p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays. 250 East Ave. 336-873-8430.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging: The four-bedroom, two-story Duck Smith House, an
immaculately restored 1914 farmhouse, features a wrap-around porch,
heart-pine woodwork, antiques and historic quilts and coverlets
among the craftsy decorations. $75-$95, full breakfast included.
465 N. Broad St. 336-873-7099. There are three chain hotels 11
miles away in Asheboro, including Days Inn (336-629-2101), which
offers a discounted rate for Seagrove pottery shoppers of $45-$48
through June 30.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining: Only one full-service eatery: the Westmoore Family
Restaurant (specializing in fried seafood, but also offering
barbecue and lighter options), 2172 N.C. 705, 910-464-5222. A nice
place for a break is the coffeeshop in the Earth Spirit Pottery,
326 Adams Road, 336-879-6200.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Phil Morgan Pottery, 336-873-7304; Ben Owen
Pottery, 910-464-2261; Fork Creek Mill Pottery, 336-873-7258.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Pousner is the Travel editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
