<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans _ The French Quarter Festival Friday through
Sunday includes free musical entertainment and cuisine.
504-522-5730 or www.fqfestivals.org. Also, the 20th Annual Spring
Garden Show is Saturday and Sunday at the Botanical Garden at City
Park. 504-482-1107.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Memphis _ ``A Celebration of Southern Chefs'' returns to the
Peabody Hotel for the second year, Friday through Sunday. The event
brings together 14 of the South's most acclaimed chefs for a
weekend of activities including seminars and tastings, cookbook
signings and special meals featuring regional food and wine.
901-529-4000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eufaula, Ala. _ The 34th annual Eufaula Pilgrimage and Antique
Show is Friday through Sunday. In addition to tours of historic
homes and churches, there will be a candlelight tasting, ``Tales
From the Tomb'' (storytelling at Fairview Cemetery), a needlework
display, outdoor art show and concerts. 1-888-383-2852.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Theodore, Ala. _ More than 250,000 azaleas are on display
through April 15 at Bellingrath Gardens' Spring Spectacular. Guests
can view the dazzling flora from the azalea pathway and from river
cruises. 334-973-2217.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Durham _ The DoubleTake Documentary Film Festival, Thursday
through Sunday, a program of the Center for Documentary Studies at
Duke University, features curated programs including ``Documentary
as Witness: The Great Films of the 20th Century'' and ``A World
Without Limits,'' a series of films shown in collaboration with
Special Olympics focusing on the issues and achievements of the
disabled. 919-660-3699; 1-800-334-1085 (for travel information).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C. _ The 52nd Annual Festival of Houses and
Gardens, through April 17 offers visitors a glimpse of elegant
homes and gardens in Charleston's historic district. Festival-goers
also can partake in three Lowcountry plantation oyster roasts.
1-843-722-3405.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Natchez, Miss. _ The Natchez Spring Pilgrimage, a tour of 31
pre-Civil War mansions, continues through April 10. Daily tours
include the Confederate Pageant, which features performers in
period costumes. 1-800-647-6742.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbus, Miss. _ The 1999 Spring Pilgrimage, through Sunday,
features 12 houses including the Williams-Gass Home, built in the
early 1840s by two ``free men of color,'' along with the typical
antebellum homes of the Southern white aristocracy. 1-800-327-2686
or www.historic-columbus.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Baxley, Ga. _ The Turpentine City celebrates trees and tree
products April 15-18 with the Paul Bunyan Lumberjack Show,
motorcycle show, street dance, carnival, arts and crafts,
entertainment, air events and more. 912-367-7731 or www
</P>
<P>
   .applingdacoc.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Birmingham _ The Birmingham International Festival presents
the Moroccan Street Festival Friday through April 18 in Linn Park
downtown, featuring Moroccan artists, musician, dancers and food.
Also, a simulated archaeological dig for children. 205-252-7652.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Knoxville _ The Dogwood Arts Festival Friday through April 25
includes visual arts, dance, music and 60 miles of dogwood trails.
423-637-4561 or www.knoxvilletennessee
</P>
<P>
   .com/DogwoodArtsFestival/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville _ Biltmore Estate presents its annual Festival of
Flowers, through May 2, ushering in spring with more than 10 acres
of formal gardens in bloom. 1-800-543-2961.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Fla. _ The annual ``Epic Celebration of
Spring'' April 15-18 includes the Flower, Garden and Art Show, An
Evening with Chef Ned Pollack, A Taste of St. Augustine and the
Historic Inns Home and Garden Tour. 904-829-3295.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher
</P>
