great acting. 
 
 
WESTON-RETROSPECTIVE (Los Angeles) _ Edward Weston exhibits at the
Los Angeles County Museum of Art bring the Modernist photographer
into perspective. By Reed Johnson. 
 
 
DISC-REVIEWS _ Music reviews. By Daily News Staff.
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0753 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-JANISJOPLIN11-CO     04-08 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-JANISJOPLIN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Behind rocker Janis Joplin's flamboyant persona, biographer
finds an empty life
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 11.
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 30 years after she became the hottest female entertainer
in rock 'n' roll, Janis Joplin is perhaps better known for her
sordid death than for her groundbreaking body of work.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to forget how shocking her arrival on the music scene
was in 1967. Long before the ditch-your-makeup emergence of the
women's movement, Joplin was shaking her wildly unkempt hair,
wearing feathers and bangle bracelets, pushing her bare chest into
our faces like the ultimate flip-off. Her voice was a howl _ part
soul diva, part banshee _ that stunned audiences. She caught
America's attention like a train wreck and shot to the top of the
music charts as the ultimate rock chick.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, history has chosen to remember her more as the ultimate
rock corpse, a 27-year-old alcoholic-addict who lay dead on the
floor of Los Angeles' seedy Landmark Hotel for 18 hours before any
of her doped-up friends figured out she was missing. Joplin's fatal
heroin overdose in 1970 put her squarely in the triumvirate of
death by overindulgence, joining Jimi Hendrix and Jim Morrison as
icons of the dark side of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Biographer Alice Echols _ a scholar of radical feminism, not a
rock journalist _ renovates the myth by shifting the focus from
Joplin's infamous death to the events and social attitudes that
shaped her life. No doubt it's the author's background that makes
the approach here more one of female character study than gossip.
</P>
<P>
   The book has, of course, its salacious moments. It would be
impossible to write honestly about Joplin's life without exploring
fringy details such as her insatiable sexual appetite (for both men
and women), unbridled drug use and ever-present bottle of Southern
Comfort. Echols shows how the singer's outrageous persona was
created largely to cover up bottomless insecurities about her
looks, her voice and her countercultural lifestyle. (At one point
Joplin even became engaged, left San Francisco, went home, put her
hair in a bun and worked on her trousseau.) Echols writes that one
potential boyfriend was put off by Joplin's overwhelming
``sexual/personal neediness, saying, `Whoa, it's too big for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   The foundations of the Joplin legend begin in Port Arthur,
Texas, the bleak industrial town where she grew up in a
conservative, middle-class family that expected her to go to the
community college, get a teaching certificate and get married. A
pampered and popular child, she ``lost her looks'' at age 14,
Echols writes: She gained weight and developed a severe case of
acne, two things you did not want to happen in the beauty-pageant
'60s of the South.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to her declining social status and the taunts of
schoolmates, Joplin developed the rude and bawdy character she
would later make famous, wearing oversize men's shirts over
leotards to high school, swearing like a barfly and swilling
alcohol in Cajun dives across the state line in Louisiana. Along
the way, she began singing along with the jukebox and experimenting
with her voice, whose natural sound was said to be sweet and folkie
like Joan Baez. Influenced heavily by the Jack Kerouac-inspired
beats of the era, Joplin developed a passion for blues and began
adding rawness to her sound to emulate Bessie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   After a short, wild stint at the University of Texas in Austin
in 1965, Joplin became one of the first immigrants to the
burgeoning hippie haven of San Francisco. Echols' description of
this now-revered peace-and-love scene is unsettling as she pulls
back the tie-dyed facade to reveal the sexist and reckless
underbelly of this piece of American folklore. Placing Joplin
squarely in this world, Echols writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of undoing the deeply rooted sexual double standard,
free love only masked it in countercultural pieties. Nor did hippie
households pioneer an alternative to the traditional division of
labor. Although many hippie guys managed to avoid nine to five
jobs, few hippie females avoided housework.''
</P>
<P>
   Joplin was deified as an entertainer, yet vilified for bucking
convention. As Echols puts it: ``Janis's fame had revealed the
limits of the San Francisco free thing, but her real sin was in
being a ballsy broad, a chick with acne who took up too much space
in the boys' club of late-sixties rock and roll.''
</P>
<P>
   But to say that sexism is what killed Janis Joplin would be a
cliche. Other women, such as Grace Slick, survived those years
(admittedly, with scars). And female rockers in the 1970s and '80s,
from Chrissie Hynde to Madonna, faced many of the same obstacles
without self-destructing.
</P>
<P>
   Echols leads one to believe that Joplin may have been a victim
of her own insecurities and rebellious perspective, a
hope-I-die-before-I-get-old attitude that sees excess as romantic.
But as jazz vocalist Nina Simone once said, ``The saddest part of
performing was that it didn't mean anything once you were
offstage.'' Utterly empty in her personal life, Joplin appeared to
embrace the role of tortured artist, subscribing to the notion that
creativity and glamour are only enhanced by personal destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's a fine line between walking on the edge
and falling off.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BIOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   Scars of Sweet Paradise: The Life and Times of Janis Joplin. By
Alice Echols. Metropolitan Books. $26. 408 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Revives the myth of the ultimate rock 'n' roll
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino covers pop music and radio for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
