<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0754 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SKUBE11-COX     04-08 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Common sense not so common in the academy
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 11.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Several years ago, a prominent academic at Duke
University took offense at something I had written about the
English department and offered a suggestion that revealed how deep
in the sand her head was buried. Newspapers, she said, train
reporters to cover fields such as medicine and science as well as
law, business and economics.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, she said, newspapers needed specialists to
cover the English department. I let pass the implication that there
was anything to cover in the first place. Instead, I asked why it
was necessary to learn a pseudo-technical jargon to understand what
should be common to all educated people: the English language.
Whatever she said in reply, it was her remoteness from ordinary
life that struck me.
</P>
<P>
   She was the president-elect of the Modern Language Association
at the time, but, for all she understood of the world, she might as
well have just checked in from Pluto. She was representative of the
postmodern intellectual in the academy, a figure of public ridicule
who doesn't know why.
</P>
<P>
   Such a figure is Judith Butler, a philosophy professor at the
University of California at Berkeley and winner recently of the
1998 Worst, Most Awful Writer Award. That's not exactly what the
humanities journal Philosophy and Literature calls it, but it's
close. The journal's editors created the award to recognize the
``ugliest, most stylistically awful passage found in a scholarly
book or article published in the last few years.'' Mine is more
succinct, theirs more precise. Take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   A philosopher responds to her critics
</P>
<P>
   What matters is that Butler won hands down, and her prose has
been in demand ever since. To say the least, it is not the kind of
demand a writer enjoys. Last month, I quoted Butler's winning
sentence, and some readers thought it was a hoax on her part,
others a typographical catastrophe. From English departments in
Georgia came two unsigned letters berating me for aggressive
``anti-intellectualism.''
</P>
<P>
   Indignant, or maybe just tired of being beaten up, Butler
herself is fighting back. Recently, she took to the op-ed page of
The New York Times to explain why intelligent people should not
expect to have the faintest idea what she's trying to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt,'' she conceded, ``scholars in the humanities should
be able to clarify how their work informs and illuminates everyday
life. Equally, however, such scholars are obliged to question
common sense, interrogate its tacit presumptions and provoke new
ways of looking at a familiar world. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``If common sense sometimes preserves the status quo, and that
status quo sometimes treats unjust social hierarchies as natural,
it makes good sense on such occasions to find ways of challenging
common sense. Language that takes up this challenge can help point
the way to a more socially just world.''
</P>
<P>
   What do you think? No one, on the basis of the above, would call
Butler a stylist, but you have to say she can write clearly and
forcefully when she wants to. She's not the nincompoop her award
would suggest _ but no deep thinker either. Just another leftover
leftist still living in the '60s, still citing Theodor Adorno and
Herbert Marcuse. (Marcuse! Somewhere I have my pink and black
paperback copy of ``Reason and Revolution,'' solemnly annotated so
many years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Being difficult for difficulty's sake
</P>
<P>
   What Butler wrote in the Times was not so much an apologia pro
vita sua as a defense of ``difficulty.'' The word is fashionable
among academics afraid that their profession is anything but. Is,
in fact, a bit Mickey Mouse (as we used to call courses that were
easy A's). Insecurity creates the pose it needs.
</P>
<P>
   But letter writer after letter writer in the Times saw through
it. And none was fooled by Butler's invocation of a sentence from
Adorno, a German emigre who was instrumental in founding the
voguish ``critical theory'' school in the academy: ``Man is the
ideology of dehumanization.'' For Butler, it is the kind of
sentence that is not immediately transparent, yet is jampacked with
profound meaning. Thus, she supposes, a reader pauses over it,
puzzling out its secrets.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, as one letter writer neatly put it, it's
nothing more than ``the verbal equivalent of a secret handshake,''
an insider's signal that he knows the lingo. No one begrudges
physics its difficulty, because it strives to simplify what is
complex. Postmodern criticism does the opposite. It obfuscates for
the sake of obfuscation, and in doing so mistakes artificial
``difficulty'' for ideas. This is impossible to do without the
protective cover of tenure, but that's what universities are for.
In their security, some critics have dispensed with the mask
entirely. Jonathan Culler, a mediocrity but druid in some circles,
calls the ``ideology of lucidity'' one more form of oppression.
</P>
<P>
   When you put it that way, you can't be accused of burying your
head in the sand. You can only be accused of not caring. If the one
prompts pity, the other elicits contempt. And richly deserved it
is.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
