<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0755 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-BAKERIES09-COX     04-08 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-BAKERIES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From birthday parties to doggie delis, new treateries cheerfully
catering to canines
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a warm afternoon, and Rick Sisson's customers,
fresh from a walk in the park, are stopping by for their just
desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Sisson pulls a tray of chunky pretzels out of the oven and
arranges them _ just so _ on a tray, which he slips into a display
case. The case is filled with other temptations as well _ clusters
of truffles there, miniature carob-chip cookies here, peanut
brittle and darling little tarts with a piped filling.
</P>
<P>
   A shopper wants a treat personalized, so Sisson writes ``Holly''
in carob icing.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, he'll wipe down the display case, removing
smears left by wet noses. And someone will give the floor a coat of
disinfectant, to discourage the next day's bakery clientele from
peeing on it.
</P>
<P>
   Even at a store where canines are treated a lot like people, a
few things still separate the paying customers from the four-legged
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Three Dog Bakery is one of a growing number of treateries in
Atlanta and elsewhere that caters solely to dogs. Another, Barking
Hound Village, opened Wednesday. In less specialized settings as
well _ Einstein Brothers with its bagel-shaped dog biscuits and pet
stores with various upscale nibbles _ gourmet dog food is becoming
a noticeable niche market.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo.-based Three Dog has 18 outlets selling items
such as Dottie's Donuts, two for $1.75, and 7-inch carob-chip cakes
for $16. Ten more stores are scheduled to open in the next two
months, and the chain is putting together dog related programming
to start this fall on cable's Animal Planet. Some of Three Dogs'
dry treats are sold through PetSmart and Neiman Marcus, too.
</P>
<P>
   Three-year-old Bone Appetit Bakery, based in Omaha, Neb., has 22
franchises, with three more opening soon. In Seattle, there's the
Bow Wow Meow Treatoria, with baked goods and a deli serving fresh
food for dogs and cats. In Dallas, the Big Bark Bakery holds
birthday parties complete with apple-cinnamon, banana-nut or
honey-almond cakes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Atlanta area, David Reid of Powder Springs, a chef who
trained at the Culinary Institute of America, prepares peanut
butter and carob pinwheels, biscotti and bones for stores such as
Highland Pet Supply in Atlanta and Pet Land in Duluth (Ga.). This
summer, Highland Pet plans to add refrigerated takeout meals.
</P>
<P>
   Gourmet pet chow purveyors tout their products as low-fat health
foods without salt, sugar and chocolate. Some items are advertised
as free of preservatives and antibiotics; others say they are
organic or made of meat suitable for human consumption. Wheat, oats
or rice are the base for many baked treats.
</P>
<P>
   Giving dogs an occasional treat is fine, as long as snacks don't
make up more than 10 percent of their diet and they're not
overweight, says Sherry Sanderson, a clinical nutritionist at the
University of Georgia's veterinary school.
</P>
<P>
   But dogs don't care whether they snack on an old-fashioned pig's
ear treat or a bakery-prepared carob cake, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners do seem to care, however. Driving the boom in
gourmet chow are pet owners who want the same things for Fido as
they do for themselves or their children. Consider what Barking
Hound plans to open by summer: a doggie deli, a gym with a
treadmill and a day care center with Internet cameras, so owners
can keep an eye on their pooch from work. It will also have a cafe
where people can dine next to their dogs _ albeit separated by a
window.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Barking Hound threw the first of 14 birthday parties
already scheduled for its back room, a $150 affair with balloons, a
gift basket for the birthday dog, a layer cake for humans and, for
the canines, slices of a pineapple, oatmeal, apple and whole wheat
layer cake artfully arranged on white paper doilies in shiny bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting the same thing for your pet as yourself only goes so
far, however.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Heath, co-owner of the Atlanta Three Dog franchise, says
he's snacked on Dottie's Spots, a peanut butter cookie with carob
chips, and Pawlines, a rice flour and vanilla chip concoction. Some
of the treats are bland because they contain no sugar or chocolate,
he says, but the Pawlines are tasty even for humans. Want to try
one? Uh, no.
</P>
<P>
   Over in the corner of the bakery, Roger Massell of Asheville,
N.C., is looking around with his mother and son. They've seen a
triple-tiered cake in the window and have come inside for a snack
for themselves. No luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this is for dogs?'' he asks. ``Golly, this is
unbelievable. They sure don't have this in Asheville, do they,
son?''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the Massells are on the way out, with a bag of
goodies for their two bichon frises.
</P>
<P>
   Joey and Andrea Hirsch, holding their pug Scooby, eye the
display case with the ardor of new pet owners. They buy a
personalized bone for Holly, the pug next door, and treats for
Scooby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always buy him stuff,'' says Joey Hirsch. ``We're supposed
to be on a budget, but just look at his face.''
</P>
<P>
   They also figure that if the 4-month-old puppy has treats to
nibble on, he won't chew the furniture or their sneakers, which
have a few shredded spots already.
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, Teddy snuffles around barrels with biscuits
piled up at just the right height for a hungry Weimaraner. A
moment's inattention by Lou Flauraud of Smyrna, the guy holding the
business end of the leash, and Teddy snags a cheese-and-herb treat.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dog's life.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
