<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-SPRING11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Before you can say `designer label,' copycats have translated
high-fashion trends into affordable looks
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 11.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fashion moves quickly these days. And the track from
runway to reproduction is faster than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet and television have enabled copycat designers to
duplicate styles in record time, in order to sell them, of course,
at a fraction of the price. Instead of months, production time for
copying a style and shipping it to retail stores has been cut to as
little as four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a world that moves fast,'' says Freda Greenbaum,
fashion director at A Nose for Clothes, a specialty shop for women
that has stores in Sandy Springs (Ga.) and Alpharetta (Ga.). ``It's
not just coming from Europe. Middle America is able to see high
fashion almost at the same time designers are presenting the same
style. There's an entire entity of fashion designers who look to
the runway for design inspiration. They are able to create these
looks at popular prices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Popular'' doesn't necessarily mean cheap. But these
reproductions are often much more within reach than the cost of a
designer label.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a designer jacket modeled on the runway for the
spring 1999 collection could cost around $1,500, estimates Kaye
Davis, fashion director for the Atlanta Market Center. A similar
jacket, made by a lesser known designer, could run around $500.
</P>
<P>
   The pink Ralph Lauren gown that Gwyneth Paltrow wore to the
Oscars last month costs about $4,000, says Kevin Knaus, president
of Inside Fashion, a local company that studies the industry. But
Victor Costa has already started production on a similar version
that will retail for around $400, just in time for prom season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is an issue in most American homes,'' said Scott
Krugman, spokesman for the National Retail Federation in
Washington. ``You're finding more of a mix between the actual
designer brands and things that might have the designer look,'' he
said, referring to consumer spending habits.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving the look
</P>
<P>
   The key to replicating runway styles is knowing what to look
for. Names still count. But instead of searching for a Calvin
Klein, Jil Sander or other top designers, focus on copycat labels
such as Victor Costa or ABS by Allen B. Schwartz. Private label
store brands, such as Gap, Ann Taylor and Banana Republic, also
resemble designer looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a woman has the time, go to a designer store to see what's
out there,'' advises Greenbaum. ``If you recognize that when you
walk into another store and you like the fabric, it fits you and
it's at a price that's affordable, feel secure that you're into
something great. But you have to do your homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion magazines (InStyle is mandatory reading for Greenbaum's
sales staff), televised runway shows and the Internet provide some
good places to ``study.'' To get started online, check out these
sites:  &QR;  www.7thonsixth.com/html/table.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.papermag.com/stylin/nyfall99/index.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.fashion.at/collections/index.htm _ Spring/summer 99
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.yslonline.com/va/collections/YSLhcep99
</P>
<P>
   /index.html _ YSL Spring-summer 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.worldmedia.fr/fashion/catwalk/PAP00ha
</P>
<P>
   /villes/NWYframe.html _ Spring/summer 99
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.firstview.com/home.html _ You must pay a fee to view much
of this site, but it offers a wide range of designer looks and
trends.
</P>
<P>
   Anything lost in translation?
</P>
<P>
   You will save money by not paying premium designer prices, but
you should also be prepared to sacrifice a little on the style.
</P>
<P>
   Designer garments tend to have more detail, such as stitching,
lining and buttons. The fabric also tends to be more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll never get them to look the same stitch for stitch, but
there are so many fabrics out there that are much less expensive
that look just as good,'' Knaus said.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
