<SLUG> BC-COOKIE-ALTMAN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First, he sets the stage; then Altman `insists' on good acting
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune'' is about a whole lot of not much. And
that's the way Robert Altman intended it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sign in the picture that tells you about that,'' the
legendary director of ``Nashville,'' ``MASH'' and ``The Player''
says by telephone from Los Angeles. He's referring to a historic
plaque glimpsed in ``Fortune,'' engraved with the inscription, ``In
1876 absolutely nothing happened on this spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Altman's new Southern slice-of-life comedy has plenty
of things going on, from a suicide cover-up to a gloriously awful
church production of ``Salome.'' But the movie is basically an
excuse to let actors Glenn Close, Charles S. Dutton, Julianne
Moore, Patricia Neal, Chris O'Connell and Liv Tyler turn in
performances packed with sharp detail and little grace notes. It's
the sort of work most movies these days don't slow down to
showcase.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he does to get such good performances, Altman says
simply, ``I make 'em do it. I insist. I insist that they do what
they became actors to do in the first place, which is to create.
I've made many, many good friends who are actors, and I love
actors. But I don't understand what they do. Even now, 'tis a
mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   When shooting ``Fortune,'' everyone stayed in Holly Springs,
Miss., where accommodations are far from West Coast swank. No
restaurants, just one cafe, open only in the afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cooked in our own homes,'' Altman says. (The cast and crew
rented about 18 private homes for the shoot.) ``Glenn used to ride
her bike to work, and people waved at her, and came by at night to
watch us shoot. They brought their kids and dogs, and caught
fireflies and put them in bottles.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 74, Altman has sculpted a career by choosing scripts based
on character and often a sense of place. He's charted his native
Kansas City (``Kansas City''), ``Nashville,'' the Los Angeles of
``Short Cuts,'' the rainy Savannah of ``The Gingerbread Man'' and
the opium-dream idea of the old West (``McCabe and Mrs. Miller'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Agents want to keep their clients in L.A. where they can keep
an eye on them,'' Altman quips. ``Otherwise they might go off and
do something good that doesn't make a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his 30-odd feature films, the director claims he doesn't have
a favorite: ``They're like your children. You tend to love your
least successful children the most.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses a moment and makes his point by adding, ``I love
`Popeye.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0759 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-COOKIE09-COX     04-08 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-COOKIE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mellower Altman heads south with leisurely, masterly `Fortune'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having proved with last year's ``The Gingerbread Man'' that he
can make a well-crafted mainstream movie as well as the next
director, it's nice to see Robert Altman return to his old
eccentric self with ``Cookie's Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   A kind of Southern Gothic shaggy-dog tale, the film takes place
in tiny Holly Springs, Miss., where about the biggest show in town
is the church's annual Easter play, directed by self-appointed
artiste Camille (Glenn Close) and starring her sister Cora
(Julianne Moore), who's as sweetly dim as Camille is imperiously
domineering. Probably the town's second-biggest show _ by default
more than anything else _ is the return of Cora's prodigal
daughter, Emma (Liv Tyler). A rebel in black overalls and cut-off
T-shirt, Emma has always flouted authority. She even has the 234
outstanding parking tickets to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Things pick up in Holly Springs, however, when the focus moves
to Camille and Cora's Aunt Cookie (Patricia Neal). A genteel,
pipe-smoking eccentric who shares her frayed-around-the-edges
antebellum home with Willis (Charles S. Dutton), her
African-American caretaker, Cookie decides that she misses her late
husband, Buck, so much that she'd like to join him.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, what could have been a nice, quiet suicide is
turned topsy-turvy when family members try to make it look like a
homicide. Things spin mischievously out of control from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune'' goes down smooth and easy. The laid-back,
affectionate tone is set early on by Dave Stewart's bluesy score
and by Altman's leisurely, let's-just-look-around approach to Anne
Rapp's script. Once the ostensible plot kicks in, you can sense
that Altman (``MASH,'' ``Nashville,'' ``The Player'') is still more
interested in poking around among his various characters than in
getting on with the investigation of the supposed murder.
</P>
<P>
   The film is full of flavorful touches. For example, the way the
church production of ``Salome'' is billed as ``By Oscar Wilde and
Camille Dixon.'' And the way Willis is characterized as ``a
responsible man who never drinks before Tom Brokaw.''
</P>
<P>
   The performances demonstrate a master's touch as well. Tyler has
never seemed so lively and appealing. The long-absent Neal, who has
co-starred with everyone from Gary Cooper to Paul Newman, turns
gentle dementia into a kind of grace note. Moore is demurely dotty
without ever descending into a cliche. And Dutton is like a bear
hug made flesh as the wondrously generous Willis, whose true place
in the scheme of things is revealed in a tumult of blood-relation
revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune'' gives us Altman the maverick in a mellower
mood, with disdain for few and compassion for all. Well, almost
all: Close gets stuck with a madwoman bit that's uncomfortably
close to ``Sunset Boulevard'' territory. Otherwise, ``Cookie's
Fortune'' is indeed a small treasure, one that celebrates the
phenomenon of human foibles as well as that of simple human
decency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Glenn Close, Charles S. Dutton, Liv Tyler and Julianne
Moore. Directed by Robert Altman. Rated PG-13 for sexually
suggestive scenes. 2 hours. At Phipps.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: You'll like the way this ``Cookie'' crumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
