<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0760 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-KISSED09-COX     04-08 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-KISSED09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's something about Drew: Actress lifts sophomoric tale
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a whole lot of unbelievable stuff going on in ``Never
Been Kissed,'' not the least of which is expecting audiences to buy
Drew Barrymore as somebody who's never really locked lips.
</P>
<P>
   Even E.T. smooched with her when she made her first movie.
</P>
<P>
   In this story, Barrymore, the film's executive producer, plays
Josie Geller, a twentysomething newspaperwoman, and former high
school dweeb (they called her ``Josie Grossie''), who goes back to
teenville as an undercover reporter, relives her high-school hell
and bumbles her way to popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about her career is implausible. (Where on the planet
is there a front-line newspaper copy editor who has an assistant
and an office?) Plus, at school, she and her twentysomething
English instructor, Sam, have so many eyes-locked dangerous
liaisons that you'd think somebody would wise up about their
student-teacher close encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the script's lame jokes and loopy situations, the movie
does have a solid fix on the shallowness of high school popularity.
At school, ``rufus'' becomes the coolest of words to say only
because one of the most popular kids deems it worthy. (``Spread the
word,'' he exclaims, rufus is cool).
</P>
<P>
   Barrymore does make a go of all this. Ultimately she has about
five roles going on: Josie as gross-out high schooler all wired up
in braces from earlier days; Josie as reserved, permanently pressed
modern-day copy editor; Josie as girlish, insecure, cool-kid
wannabe returning to school; Josie as potential prom queen; and
Josie as the end-of-reel, wiser woman waiting and wishing and
hoping the new love of her life will at last bestow the smooch
she's always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   While not always believable, Barrymore is at least charming. And
she gets plenty of solid support from David Arquette (``Scream's''
jim-dandy Deputy Dewey). He plays her brother Rob, a grown-up
slacker stuck in a dead-end job requiring that he dress like a
dime-store Tahitian.
</P>
<P>
   Rob also sneaks back into school, and that's a blessing. He has
all the good lines _ all two of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never
</P>
<P>
   Been Kissed''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Drew Barrymore and David Arquette. Directed by Raja
Gosnell. Rated PG-13 for language, drug use and sexual references.
1 hour, 47 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Class dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
