<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Thursday, April 8, 1999    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about Houston
Chronicle sports stories, please call 713-220-7896.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: KOSOVO-NATO; KOSOVO-CAPTIVES; ZHU; BUSH-KOSOVO;
ROCKET-RIDES; SALES-TAX; SHELL-BRUTUS; GLF-MASTERS; BKN-ROCKETS;
and BBN-ASTROS.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Defense Secretary William Cohen tells
U.S. fliers, ``We will prevail.'' But U.S. military officials also
begin to express concern that the Serb crackdown on refugees will
make it harder to hit military targets, leaving no ``clear lines''
between civilians and soldiers. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CAPTIVES (Washington) _ Cyprus' ambassador to Washington
says the speaker of the Cypriot Parliament is not intending to
negotiate the release of three American servicemen being held by
Yugoslav forces, but to take custody of them _ with no conditions
attached. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   ZHU (Washington) _ President Clinton welcomes Chinese Premier
Zhu Rongji, calling for the two leaders ``to speak with candor and
listen with an open mind.'' Still, agreement on tough trade issues
is unlikely. By JENNIFER DAY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-KOSOVO (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush has gone
from saying he would leave military decisions to the current
commander-in-chief to, essentially, let's go in to win. This comes
after a Tuesday meeting with his foreign policy advisers, all
veterans of the Reagan-Bush years. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKET-RIDES (Houston) _ Two men who planned to offer 15-minute
suborbital rocket rides launched off Galveston Island, Texas, have
had to abandon the project and refund the $200,000 they collected
from each eager passenger because of financing problems. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   SALES-TAX (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas Senate gives Texans a $250
million sales tax break, exempting over-the-counter medications for
children and diapers from taxes and granting a 14-day ``holiday''
from taxes on clothing in August. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
