<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOUNTAIN-BOOK-REVIEW-     04-08 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUNTAIN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRACTING DETOURS IN THE HUNT FOR A FINAL EXIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though David Guterson's new novel ``East of the Mountains'' is
set in an area of Washington state not far from the backdrop of his
1994 best seller ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' the two books could
not be more different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cedars'' conjured up in vivid detail a small Puget Sound
community ractured by racial prejudice and historical hurts. It was
a rich, suspenseful novel that turned the murder trial of a
Japanese-American fisherman into both a courtroom drama and a
beautifully nuanced examination of public and private memory and
the wages of resentment and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``East of the Mountains,'' in contrast, is a much smaller, more
claustrophobic book. Instead of a community of neighbors and
acquaintances linked by grievances and affection, it gives us one
man: a loner, cut off from family and friends and isolated by his
skeptical intelligence. Instead of the vast vistas of history that
haunt the individuals in ``Cedars,'' it portrays one man's tortured
efforts to come to terms with illness and mortality.
</P>
<P>
   In structure and concept ``Mountains'' is a sort of dry, prose
version of Ingmar Bergman's ``Wild Strawberries'' minus the
haunting, surreal imagery and minus the masterly cinematic
manipulation of time and mood. As in ``Wild Strawberries'' we are
introduced to a crotchety old man reliving his past during a long
journey. As in ``Wild Strawberries'' we are supposed to piece
together a portrait of this man through his dreams, memories and
encounters with assorted strangers.
</P>
<P>
   The old man in this case is Ben Givens, a retired heart surgeon
and recent widower who has colon cancer. Ben, we learn in the
opening pages, has decided to commit suicide: he does not want to
suffer the pain and debilitation he knows will accompany his
cancer, and he has decided to go off on a long hunting trip and
shoot himself. Only his doctor, Ben thinks, will suspect the truth,
and he will spare Ben's family from such suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   As depicted by Guterson, Ben's momentous decision never feels
particularly convincing. We never understand why his daughter and
grandchildren are not incentives to go on living, nor do we
understand why Ben does not elect the option of ``palliative
surgery'' that might ease his pain. Instead, we are supposed to
believe that Ben, a renowned physician, believes it is ``better to
avoid pain than engage it,'' ``better to end his life swiftly,
cleanly, and to accept that there would be no thwarting the
onslaught of this disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben loads up his car with his hunting gear and his two hunting
dogs and sets off on the long drive east from Seattle to the
Columbia Basin, the apple-growing region where he grew up. His
carefully laid plans soon go awry, however, when his car skids off
the road in a rainstorm and crashes into a tree. Ben, slightly
injured, is rescued by a young couple who remind him of his
youthful love for his late wife, Rachel.
</P>
<P>
   Ben's efforts to get his suicide mission back on track soon lead
to a further series of picaresque adventures. He meets a drifter
who gives him some marijuana cigarettes. He hikes across some
desert country and goes on one last hunt. He has an unpleasant
run-in with a coyote hunter, whose wolfhounds kill one of his dogs
and maim the other. He hikes on through the desert to get his
injured dog to a veterinarian. He hops a bus and meets an illegal
Mexican alien in need of medical attention. He spends a night in an
apple pickers' camp, where he helps deliver a baby.
</P>
<P>
   There is something hokey and schematic about these encounters:
Ben's exchanges with the strangers he meets have a cliched quality.
The young lovers who help him after the car accident say things
like ``We're soul mates,'' ``We're forever.'' The vet who saves his
dog notes that one is ``better old than dead'' and a girl who helps
Ben help the ailing illegal alien pronounces him ``Un angel de
Dios.'' Unlike the carefully observed characters in ``Cedars,''
these people feel like cardboardy mouthpieces for Guterson, each a
cipher whose role is simply to telegraph messages to Ben that he
should rethink his suicide plans.
</P>
<P>
   The flashbacks triggered by these encounters are somewhat more
persuasive. Although Ben's memories of hunting with his father
sometimes feel like ersatz Hemingway, Guterson does an admirable
job of evoking the harsh, physical world of Ben's youth, the
arduous and gratifying work of farming and the unforgiving beauty
of the Columbia Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Ben's memories of fighting in World War II, reminiscent of
similar passages in ``Cedars,'' are by far the most powerful
portions of this novel. The rigors of military training, the shock
and horror of being under fire, the spectacle of seeing his best
friend being brought back from the dead by an army surgeon: such
scenes are visceral, uncompromising and harrowing, and they remind
us what this talented writer can do when he isn't coasting along on
automatic pilot.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `EAST OF THE MOUNTAINS'
</P>
<P>
   By David Guterson
</P>
<P>
   279 pages. Harcourt Brace. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
