<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOD-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLOOD, GUTS, ... OCTANE': DON'T BUY A USED CAR FROM EITHER OF
THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Carnahan's maniacally frenzied little film, ``Blood, Guts,
Bullets and Octane'' is set in the desert wasteland around Needles,
Calif., where Sid ( Carnahan) and his partner Bob (Dan Leis), two
motor-mouthed used-car salesmen, are desperately trying to keep
their failing business afloat. Just when they are about to throw in
the towel, their sleazy broker hands them an opportunity to make
$250,000 simply by letting a 1963 Pontiac LeMans sit in their lot
for 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   There's a deadly catch, of course. The car, which has been on a
long intercontinental journey, will be under constant surveillance
by gunslingers who have left a trail of carnage behind them, and
the vehicle is wired to explode should anyone attempt to open the
trunk. No sooner has a deal been struck than Sid hatches the notion
of stealing the Pontiac and holding it for $500,000 ransom.
Meanwhile, the FBI is hard on the trail of the car and its owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood, Guts, Bullets and Octane'' runs on the movie equivalent
of fake adrenaline. The story is continually interrupted and kicked
into high gear by the flash of sardonic chapter titles and the kind
of sonic blasts that punctuate items on tabloid news shows. Between
chapter titles, the characters yammer at each other in dialogue
that feels semi-improvised, and people get shot. Although the pair
succeed in taking the hot car to a repair shop, where blood is
discovered leaking from the bottom of the trunk, they don't get
much farther than that. The grainy, jittery cinematography and flat
deadpan performances give this preposterous scenario a patina of
realism.
</P>
<P>
   The movie aspires to be a David Mamet-like slice of lowlife in
the American wasteland with added Quentin Tarantino-like
muscle-flexing and dripping gore. Desperate, lying used car
salesmen out for a big score; deadly macho games of gun-waving;
suitcases stuffed with drugs and cash; absent women: do I hear a
metaphor? It's all grindingly familiar and has been done by others
with far more style and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It includes profanity and scenes of violence.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BLOOD, GUTS, BULLETS AND OCTANE'
</P>
<P>
   Written, edited and directed by Joe Carnahan; director of
photography, John A. Jimenez; music by Mark Priolo and Martin
Birke; produced by Leon Corcos, Patrick M. Lynn, Dan Leis and
Carnahan; released by Lions Gate Films. Running time: 87 minutes.
This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   With: Joe Carnahan (Sid French), Dan Leis (Bob Melba), Ken
Rudulph (F.B.I. Agent Jared), Dan Harlan (Danny Woo), Hugh McChord
( Reich), Kurt Johnson (Hillbilly Sniper), Mark S. Allen (F.B.I.
Agent Franks) and Kellee Benedict (F.B.I. Agent Littel). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
