<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0775 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TA     04-08 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID HARE: A PLAYWRIGHT REPORTS IN PERSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You might not fully appreciate it when it happens,
but the most memorable and gutsy moment of this theatrical season
to date is when David Hare, a slim, trim, unassuming figure in his
50s, wearing gray slacks and an open-neck shirt, steps onto the
stage of the Booth Theater to begin his performance playing David
Hare in his own ``Via Dolorosa.''
</P>
<P>
   David Hare, the British playwright? Yes, and not only that, but
a playwright making his debut as a professional actor.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about the man American audiences have long
identified with such polemical works as ``Plenty,'' ``Racing
Demon'' and ``Skylight.'' He is a writer of such an imposing,
rather chilly reputation for dismembering British society and its
institutions that when his bitter sex comedy, ``The Blue Room,''
opened on Broadway earlier this season, many critics regarded it as
an aberration. This is the same fellow exactly, though you have
never really seen him until now, nor have you heard his voice with
such clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing Hare has done before prepares you for ``Via Dolorosa''
and its discoveries, including the demonstrated fact that he can be
such seriously invigorating company. But, then, there are no exact
precedents for what he is doing here.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Via Dolorosa,'' the playwright comes out from behind the
characters through whom he has been talking all these years to
confront audiences as himself. For the moment, he has abandoned
what he calls ``the conventions of the theater of fiction,'' at
least to the extent that such conventions can be abandoned in any
structured theatrical presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Via Dolorosa'' is no ordinary 90-minute one-man show, a
stand-up performance of prepared ad-libs and well-rehearsed riffs
designed to persuade audiences that, after all, life's horrors and
funninesses are no different from those in any sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, ``Via Dolorosa'' is the playwright's carefully
considered report on his reactions following several trips to
Israel and the West Bank to gather material for a play. Apparently,
this sort of journalistic research has often been a part of his
mode of operation, whether taking aim at the Church of England
(``Racing Demon'') or British law (``Murmuring Judges''). It has
also sometimes given his plays a schematic tone that can subtly
sabotage their dramatic effect as well as the questions he wants
the plays to raise.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Via Dolorosa,'' however, he came to feel that
the subject was beyond any treatment as theater of fiction, the
reality being too blunt, the stakes too large and the likely
outcome too grim. Throughout ``Via Dolorosa'' there are frequent
asides in which the adequacy of fiction is questioned, and this
from one of the London theater's most successful practitioners of
the art.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he goes through Yad Vashem, the Holocaust museum
in Jerusalem, where he is moved by its ``simplicity,'' its ``bleak
photographic record'' and especially by the text of a speech in
which Himmler ``congratulates his men on the discipline they have
shown in exerting what he calls their `moral right' to exterminate
the Jews.'' Hare finds that the only false notes are struck by the
museum's sculptures and paintings, which he describes as
``superfluous'' and ``inadequate.'' ``What is a painting, a
painting of a starving man? What is a painting of a corpse? It's
the facts we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Having decided that this material could only be handled as
reportage, Hare has written a piece that, in a modest, moving way,
illuminates not only the Israeli-Arab conflict but also some of the
other confrontations that keep the world on bloody edge. It is not
necessarily the facts that are persuasive, though he does seem to
have done his homework, but the skeptical if always humane point of
view Hare brings to a complex situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Via Dolorosa'' is, of course, fiction in that Hare has shaped
his material for theatrical effect. We are not seeing what he saw
at the moment he saw it. Instead, it is a very particular
recollection, written by a gifted playwright attempting to give
theatrical fiction a new dimension of reality, one unencumbered by
the usual make-believe.
</P>
<P>
   He, himself, stands at the center, the reporter and narrator.
Here is the playwright undisguised, a man of Christian background,
from a land where passions are mingy, voyaging through a part of
the world where passions are the stuff of life. Or, as one Israeli
friend tells him, in any single day the Israeli experiences events
and emotions ``that would keep a Swede going for a year.'' Hare is
the outsider idealized, sometimes ignorant and naive, but always
curious and reactive. More important, he functions as if he were
our conscience, which at any single moment is both safely aloof and
profoundly implicated.
</P>
<P>
   The result is this fascinating production by the Royal Court
Theater of London, being presented in New York by Lincoln Center
Theater. As directed by Stephen Daldry, ``Via Dolorosa'' has such
an astonishing abundance of stories, characters and ideas that,
when you leave the theater, you feel as if you had lived through
some kind of crazy, continuing epic.
</P>
<P>
   At one point and another, ``Via Dolorosa'' has something to
offend just about everybody. Hare is dismayed by the religious Jew
who, since the Six-Day War in 1967, has come to see the Bible ``not
as a historical story but as an operations manual''; by the
corruption within the Arafat leadership; by the constant harping on
the holiness of places by both sides. At the same time, he is
amused by the sight of busloads of ``American evangelicals'' in
Jerusalem, ``searching vainly in an old Arab city for any remaining
evidence of Our Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is there not more?'' they ask. To which he responds:
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I share their bewilderment. After all,
Christianity's a well-known religion and I'd say influential in its
day. You'd think it was still worth a pilgrimage, but in this town
we come a sporting third.''
</P>
<P>
   He notes that the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, which contains
the stone where Christ is said to have been crucified, is ``shared
unhappily,'' with 70 percent going to the Greek Orthodox and the
rest ``doled out higgledy-piggledy between the Armenian Christians,
the Coptic Christians, the Latins, the Syrians and the
Ethiopians.''
</P>
<P>
   His comment: ``A people divided by a common religion. Sects and
the single Church.''
</P>
<P>
   The playwright's dominant theme: ``Stones or ideas? Stones or
ideas?'' After all, he adds, ``Does the literal truth matter?''
That is, when someone kisses the stone in the Church of the Holy
Sepulcher, isn't he kissing an idea?
</P>
<P>
   As an actor, Hare is an excellent student. He plays the
character with enthusiasm, though not with the kind of professional
smoothness that might separate him from his own material. He is a
non-pro, and that is in his favor. Though there is a gentle
awkwardness about the performance, it appears to italicize the
dramatic effectiveness of the array of characters he recalls with
such vivid exactitude.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: Eran Baniel, the Israeli theater director who made
his name with a startling and somewhat abbreviated co-production of
``Romeo and Juliet,'' in which the Capulets were played by
Palestinians and the Montagues by Jews; Danny and Sarah Weiss, who
are making their contribution by living in a ``disputed''
territory, an Israeli community in Hebron, where 521 Jewish
militants live in middle-class comfort, protected by 4,000 Israeli
troops; Benni Begin, son of the former prime minister, who has
become the articulate, intellectually commanding spokesman for the
settlers.
</P>
<P>
   There is also Haider Abdel Shafi, the popular 70-year-old Gaza
politician who resigned from the Palestinian legislative body to
protest the corruption within the Arafat regime. To Hare's
consternation, Shafi agrees to see him under the impression that he
is David Hirst, a correspondent for The Guardian. Comments Hare:
``A man who knows nothing is now about to interview a man who
thinks he is someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The stage is crowded with figures large and small, passionate
and disaffected, gloomy and scarily self-assured. Like a seasoned
journalist, Hare knows not only how to listen, but also how to
persuade his subjects to express themselves far more freely than
they might otherwise. His language is clean, spare, sometimes blunt
and, on occasion, unaffectedly poetic. He does not presume to offer
solutions; Hare is a playwright, not a politician. His not immodest
concerns: thought, mind, the fate of what has loosely been called
the civilized world.
</P>
<P>
   Daldry and his associates, including Ian MacNeil, who designed
the spectacular set for the Daldry revival of ``An Inspector
Calls'' seen here in 1994, make sure that the physical production
of ``Via Dolorosa'' never gets in the way of the material or its
narrator. There is one extremely theatrical moment, a scenic
effect, that appears near the end as a kind of vision of peace. It
lasts no longer than a slow blink of the eye, and it is all that is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Via Dolorosa'' is an experience of most uncommon
theatricality.
</P>
<P>
   `Closer'
</P>
<P>
   The production of Patrick Marber's ``Closer,'' directed by the
playwright and now at the Music Box, would seem to be a faithful
approximation of his initial London staging of the work in 1997. A
hit at the Royal National Theater, ``Closer'' later successfully
transferred to the West End.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``would seem'' because though I went to see it at the
Lyttelton Theater in the National, I endured only one act before
making an exit. Because I wasn't able to give it a fair test, I
made no attempt to write about it at the time. I had seen it on my
first evening in London after having been swept away by a matinee
performance of ``The Invention of Love,'' Tom Stoppard's splendidly
witty meditation on the sad life of A.E. Housman.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't only jet lag that forced me out of the theater. It was
a creeping suspicion that Marber's brittle, brutal comedy about the
emptiness of love and sex in our numb times was saying nothing that
hasn't been explored to greater effect by other people. That
suspicion has now been certified (to my own satisfaction anyway) by
a visit to the Music Box, where the four members of its dream cast
are playing ``Closer'' with such intensity and conviction you can
believe that they believe in it.
</P>
<P>
   The play is an exhaustingly hip, pore-tight close-up of the
tangled romantic lives of four gabby, singularly dim people: Anna
(Natasha Richardson), a successful London photographer bewitched by
the surfaces of things; Larry (Ciaran Hinds), a dermatologist; Dan
(Rupert Graves), an unsuccessful novelist who writes obituaries for
a living, and Alice (Anna Friel), a waif who works as a stripper
and talks tough but, inside, is mint jelly longing for a lamb chop.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of 2 acts and 12 scenes that span 4 years, Anna
and Alice, who are the passive-aggressive victims, each fall into,
out of and back into terrible relationships with both Dan and
Larry. Each of the men is a sex-obsessed beast who whines a lot
while nattering on about love.
</P>
<P>
   As he demonstrated in his first dark but far less trendy play, a
melodrama titled ``Dealer's Choice,'' Marber can write funny,
perceptive, character-defining dialogue. In ``Closer'' you get the
feeling that almost any line might sound equally valid issuing from
at least one of the other characters. There is also some mildly
amusing throw-away dialogue and a cyberspace seduction scene that,
in the manner of patches that turn up throughout the rest of the
play, holds the attention while it is going on, without being
believable for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   If aggressively dirty talk doesn't reduce you to helpless
rapture, the principal reason to see ``Closer'' is to watch two
expert performers do the impossible. The enchanting Ms. Richardson
gives urgency and cohesion to a character that has the substance of
a smoke ring. As the lost Alice, Ms. Friel recalls those completely
improbable but seductive young women drifters once so popular in
French films when played by Miou-Miou and her spinoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the graphic descriptions of offstage sex and whether
or not it was good, and in spite of the dreary consequences,
``Closer'' is far too sentimental to be effective even as a
cautionary fable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
