<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0783 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GREAT-COMPOSERS-2T     04-08 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GREAT-COMPOSERS-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSICAL MUSIC'S HEAVY HITTERS IN ABBREVIATED AT-BATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 Ed Ward, the author of the first volume of ``Rock of Ages,''
Rolling Stone's rock history, is a freelance writer in Berlin.  
 (bl)  
 By JOSEPH HOROWITZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 40 years ago, Leonard Bernstein presented a nationally
televised New York Philharmonic Young People's Concert titled ``Who
Is Gustav Mahler?'' Addressing an audience of children, Bernstein
offered an analysis of Mahler's ``double personality,'' a product
of ``inner battles'' between composing and conducting, emotional
innocence and torment, Western music and exotic Eastern influences.
</P>
<P>
   This month, PBS will telecast ``Great Composers,'' six programs
beginning on Wednesday, April 14, and including, on Wednesday,
April 21, ``Gustav Mahler.'' Juxtaposed with Bernstein's concert,
this hourlong introduction to the composer documents a sea change
in the ways symphonic music is explained, observed and absorbed on
the home screen.
</P>
<P>
   In place of Bernstein's Carnegie Hall, we are regaled with
footage of the cities and mountains, houses and ``composing huts''
that Mahler knew and used, and with enacted re-creations of
incidents from his life. In place of a single commentator and a
sustained point of view, there are no fewer then 16 talking heads:
sources of innumerable sound bites of less than a minute each. In
place of Bernstein and his musicians, we observe in performance a
piano quartet, a couple of singers and the BBC Symphony Orchestra,
from which emanate tiny  &UR; music &LR;  bites, rarely exceeding 30 seconds
unless a sound bite is overlaid.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein, who never talks while music is being played,
introduces his young people to the ``Abschied'' (``Farewell'') from
Mahler's ``Song of the Earth'' with a four-minute exegesis
culminating in a personal interpretation: that the movement is,
among other things, Mahler's necessary but intensely nostalgic
farewell to German Romanticism. He then conducts the final five
minutes of this painful leave-taking.
</P>
<P>
   In the new ``Mahler,'' we hear 45 seconds of the ``Abschied''
before a 25-second sound bite by filmmaker Ken Russell takes over.
The next 25 seconds of music are embellished by a danced
interpretation and images of trees and flowers. While these
enhancements may be less banal than the rainy windowpane inflicted
on ``Kindertotenlieder,'' they effectively fracture music that even
a child _ especially a child, according to Bernstein _ would
recognize as hypnotically poised and inviolable.
</P>
<P>
   Then come two more sound bites, totaling 45 seconds, another 10
seconds of music, and we are done with ``The Song of the Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the ``Mahler'' talking heads _ in particular,
Russell, musicologist Donald Mitchell and biographer Henry-Louis de
La Grange _ are promising, but these contributions are drowned in a
sea of cliches. The music bites, without exception, are shrewdly
chosen. We hear, for instance, the amazing opening measures of the
Sixth Symphony's finale. No words can convey the metaphysical chill
of this passage, with its combination of soaring flight and
fatalistic descent. The prosaic tag here imposed drones, ``The last
movement of the Sixth Symphony includes some of the most
emotionally charged and frightening music Mahler would ever
write.''
</P>
<P>
   All six composers in the series are subject to the same
formulaic restrictions, a strategy to ward off boredom and placate
short attention spans. Sadly, it is all business as usual. Nervous
cameras compete for novelty of perspective. There are close-ups of
fingers, fingernails and fingerboards, of vibrating hands and
strings. One memorable shot, from the floor, shows a bloated elbow
connecting, at a great height, with a tiny fiddle.
</P>
<P>
   The sound bites are numbing in their superficial variety. The
intention, no doubt, is to instill a condition of feverish
passivity, so we won't switch to ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the series' first two installments, broadcast back to back
Wednesday, ``Beethoven'' is curiously disorganized: particles of
speech and music scattered like so many scraps of paper. Too often
the talking heads are celebrities with nothing much to say. The
quest to define Beethoven's genius leads nowhere. We learn that the
late string quartets are ``the greatest music Beethoven ever
wrote,'' that the ``Eroica'' Symphony was the first piece to
convince everyone that ``this really is Beethoven's voice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mozart,'' also broadcast this week, is better. More than the
other programs, it manages to concentrate, as Bernstein used to, on
a piece of music. Seven minutes are spent with the Piano Concerto
in A (K. 488), and with two terrific commentators. One is pianist
and musicologist Robert Levin, whose excited delivery is messianic,
even over the top. The other is conductor Colin Davis, soft-voiced
and melancholically intense. They disagree about the proper
performance of the coda to the concerto's slow movement. Citing a
manuscript in the hand of Mozart's pupil Barbara Ployer, Levin
insists that it should be lavishly ornamented. Davis reads Mozart's
score, barren of embellishment, as a self-sufficient text. ``You're
missing the moment of extraordinary depth and desolation,'' he
woundedly intones, ``by dressing him up in dolly's clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   To clinch this argument _ what could be more obvious? _ one
would have to hear the entire coda, only a minute long, in both
versions. The ground rules will not sanction this.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Mozart'' transcends cant and caricature. It
respectfully samples recent scholarship. It handsomely summarizes
the composer's life.
</P>
<P>
   If these shows suggest that the heroic Beethoven connects less
with our time than the elusive Mozart, ``Wagner,'' on April 21,
brings bad news: that an appreciation of this composer is today
muddled by issues of politics and morality, simplistically
understood. Extremist rant _ that Wagner's operas are infested with
encoded representations of the Jew _ is allowed to stand
unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers to Wagner could not possibly glean from such a
presentation the psychological complexity of ``Tristan und
Isolde,'' or the emotional wisdom of ``Die Meistersinger'' (here
characterized, in a single phrase, as ``a nationalistic tribute to
German art''). Even Wagner's anti-Semitism, the program's idee
fixe, remains a cartoon. His ambivalences are denied. His complex
practical and psychological dependency on the Jew, a rewarding
topic, goes unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   It hardly surprises that the program also manages to misread one
of Wagner's most famous and unnervingly explicit musical
descriptions. The unresolved climax of the ``Tristan'' Prelude, a
portrait of solitary, unslaked sexual thirst (``desire without
attainment,'' Wagner called it), is reduced, by a pair of dancers,
to an anodyne vignette of lovers kissing.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tchaikovsky and Puccini _ the final pair of composers, on
April 28 _ are effectively presented. (A seventh film in the
series, ``Johann Sebastian Bach,'' will not be shown on PBS but is
to be released with the others in May for home video by NVC Arts.)
</P>
<P>
   Conductors Yuri Temirkanov and Valery Gergiev are powerfully
articulate Tchaikovsky advocates, insisting on a dignified
rendering of the composer's music and personality. The Moscow and
St. Petersburg locations are telling. Even in snatches, the
performances of the St. Petersburg Philharmonic are distinguished.
Tchaikovsky's homosexuality is thoughtfully discussed; the pain it
caused him, it is plausibly suggested, inflected his creative
personality. Current scholarly dissension over Tchaikovsky's death
_ was it suicide? _ is entertainingly sampled.
</P>
<P>
   The least challenging of the six composers, Puccini furnishes a
diverting finale, in which the soap opera of his personal life _
his arrogance, miserliness and promiscuity _ is colorfully
described by surviving neighbors and hunting buddies. Three
commentators _ singers Julia Migenes and Jose Cura, conductor
Richard Buckley _ prove sincere and unaffected adherents. The
contradiction between this composer's high popularity and his low
esteem among certain scholars and connoisseurs is, if not explored,
at least acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes of Maria Callas singing ``Vissi d'arte'' (in black
and white, with a single stationary camera) would completely
upstage _ or wonderfully enhance _ this show, but never mind.
</P>
<P>
   What finally disappoints about ``Great Composers'' is not the
restriction on intellectual and musical content but something more
basic. For some time now, the canon of Western classical music has
not defined what is musically best and most prestigious. Already,
the concept of an elite caste of dead European great composers,
sources of timeless and eternal high art, caricatures itself.
</P>
<P>
   A co-production of WNET in New York and the BBC and NVC Arts in
London, ``Great Composers'' benefits from the participation of
leading American and British musicologists (on the whole, better
talkers than the musicians), who supply up-to-date findings and
perspectives. To be genuinely up to date, however, the series would
have to include a non-European composer, or a composer at least
partly invested in popular music, or both.
</P>
<P>
   A segment on George Gershwin would have been timely, provocative
and fun. The late-20th-century collapse of separate ``classical''
and ``popular'' musical spheres _ of which Gershwin was an early
embodiment _ could have been explored. The absorption of Old World
music by New World composers, performers and institutions _ a
fascinating and important theme, especially (one would think) for
Americans _ could have been addressed.
</P>
<P>
   These are chronic oversights that Bernstein, nearly half a
century ago, consistently avoided. His musical illustrations were
as likely to sample Copland and Harris, or Presley and the Beatles,
as Mozart and Beethoven. His passionate enthusiasms included
American musical theater and jazz.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Bernstein was part of a more courageous broadcasting
era, a beneficiary of such distinguished CBS showcases as
``Omnibus'' and ``Ford Presents.'' The rival NBC created its own
opera company, presenting opera in English and emphasizing
contemporary and American repertory. And NBC 10 times televised
concerts by the NBC Symphony under Arturo Toscanini, alongside
which most symphonic ``Great Performances'' via PBS are yesterday's
banquet barely warmed over.
</P>
<P>
   One appreciates that PBS lacks the financial resources that
NBC's David Sarnoff and CBS's William Paley commanded before
commercial television was, in effect, relieved of responsibility
for cultural programming through the advent of public television.
One understands the need to satisfy a gamut of affiliated public
stations, and to compete with popular commercial fare.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, too, it must be said that ``Great Composers'' will
do some good. I know, because I tested three segments on my
11-year-old son. He was galvanized by the exchange between Don
Giovanni and the statue of the Commendatore, powerfully staged
(though intermittently interrupted) in ``Mozart''; he announced his
desire to see ``Don Giovanni'' as soon as possible. ``Tchaikovsky''
was found equally gripping. ``Beethoven'' was pronounced
``overemphasized,'' which, it turned out, meant full of hot air.
</P>
<P>
   At best, ``Great Composers'' is a kind of holding action,
innocuous in the short run but ultimately self-defeating. Surely it
is not too late to hope for something better from public
television: something more timely, more challenging, more
inspirational. Or is it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
