<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0787 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATIN-PLAYBOYS-MUSIC-     04-08 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-PLAYBOYS-MUSIC-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN ROOTS LEAVE ROOM FOR ALL-AMERICAN AMBITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (bl)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take it with a grain of salt, and maybe a squeeze of lime, when
the Latin Playboys declare ``It's not about hip, you won't get it,
it's a Latin trip'' in the middle of their second album, ``Dose''
(Atlantic, CD, 834173).
</P>
<P>
   They're not making a policy statement. Whether or not the Latin
Playboys aspire to hipness, any kind of Latin separatism is the
furthest thing from their musical intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin Playboys assimilate whatever they like, from
slide-guitar blues riffs to Indonesian gamelan gongs; it's a Latin
trip simply because they're not going to let go of roots, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin Playboys are one spinoff from Los Lobos, whose most
recent album, ``Colossal Head,'' was released in 1996. The Playboys
include David Hidalgo and Louie Perez, songwriters from Los Lobos,
along with Mitchell Froom and Tchad Blake, who have produced and
engineered Los Lobos' albums since ``Kiko'' in 1992. (The Playboys'
tour brings them to Tramps in New York City on Thursday.)
Meanwhile, Cesar Rosas, who shares Los Lobos' lead vocals and
songwriting, has made a solo album, ``Soul Disguise'' (Rykodisc,
CD, 10459). And Hidalgo and a blues singer, Mike Halby,
collaborated on an album, ``Houndog'' (Columbia Legacy, CD, 65861).
</P>
<P>
   Los Lobos became a flagship for Mexican-American rock in the
1980s. They had a No. 1 single in 1987 with a remake of Ritchie
Valens' hit ``La Bamba'' and followed it with ``La Pistola y el
Corazon,'' an album of Mexican and border songs. Last year, Los
Lobos' two guitarists, Hidalgo and Rosas, were part of Los Super
Seven, an all-star revival of Tex-Mex norteno music.
</P>
<P>
   But Los Lobos decided to be not a Mexican-American ethnic symbol
but an all-American band, tuned in to the whole world and ready to
slip in African or Asian licks alongside a blues shuffle or a
Tex-Mex waltz. In the '90s, Los Lobos began to make music that
sounded more subterranean, conjuring smoky clubs and cluttered
garages, staticky broadcasts and scratchy disks.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Kiko,'' ``Colossal Head'' and the first Latin Playboys
album, from 1994, guitars are distorted; peculiar keyboard sounds
tootle and hum; drumbeats thump on unexpected offbeats. The
traditionalists had suddenly become sonic guerrillas, knocking
ideas together like the younger generation of Rock en Espanol
bands. The music pursued its own impulses, not a format.
</P>
<P>
   The new albums take disparate routes toward their all-American
ambitions. Rosas chooses eclecticism, proving himself in one style
after another. ``Houndog'' concocts a stark, neoprimitive version
of the blues. And The Latin Playboys throw all the music they love
into a studio cauldron, then see what happens when it's heated,
melted and stirred.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Soul Disguise,'' Rosas strips away Los Lobos' tangents and
works his way through musical geography from accordion-driven
norteno to New Orleans funk to Chicago blues to Los Angeles
folk-rock. It's a tour of rock before hip-hop, with most songs
telling an old story: he's got woman trouble, and she's to blame.
Rosas sings with an amiable growl, then follows through with
coiled, teasing, pointed lead guitar solos. He's a master of his
chosen styles, and he makes his studio band steam through every
groove. But few of the songs are more than genre pieces, presenting
Rosas as an overqualified leader of a bar band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houndog'' is Hidalgo's inward-looking version of a genre
workout: not Rosas' public blues, but a private meditation on
``lonely dying love.'' Hidalgo produced, performed and wrote songs
with Halby, whose sleepy voice moves so languidly that it sometimes
sounds like the tapes have been slowed down. Singing like
Mississippi John Hurt meeting John Lee Hooker in a thick fog, Halby
gets minimal backup: a muffled beat, a guitar or two and Hidalgo's
rough-hewn fiddle. The music is quietly bereft, as if resigned to
misery. Yet while individual songs like ``All Fired Up, All Shook
Down'' hit home, the album as a whole grows logy.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin Playboys sound like they're having more fun in
musicianly ways: savoring odd beats and unlikely textures, fooling
around with riffs and tape loops, sometimes fighting against their
own facility to force new ideas. They process their deep knowledge
of blues, rock and Mexican music through samplers and noise gizmos,
pulverizing any notion of purism.
</P>
<P>
   Like the first Latin Playboys album, ``Dose'' is short _ under
40 minutes _ and wayward. A blues instrumental called ``Tormenta
Blvd.,'' only plays on the right channel; the album's most tuneful
song, the disillusioned come-on of ``Lemon `N Ice,'' ticks along
for a minute and a half before the vocal arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Anything can turn up in the Latin Playboys' songs: a steel-drum
hook and a low-riding piano riff in ``Latin Trip,'' Javanese
gamelan and tape-reversed percussion in ``Dose,'' a guitar line in
``Mustard'' that could be from southern Africa or Bali, Indian
film-music violins answering phased, fuzzed guitar in ``Fiesta
Exotica.'' Hidalgo makes his guitars poke and twang; Froom laces
the songs with outre, obsolete analog keyboards, and the whole
group searches for the raunchiest tones and lumpiest rhythms it can
sample.
</P>
<P>
   But the Latin Playboys aren't trying to flee their background,
only to gain perspective. The lyrics, mostly by Perez, are filled
with barrio memories _ looking at characters like a natty tough guy
in ``Latin Trip'' or a faded glamour girl in ``Cuca's Blues,''
taking the family pickup truck to the movies in ``Ironsides'' or
wondering about a kid who ``grows up brown'' in ``Dose.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Playboys get to folky Mexican styles in the album's
final songs, the sound is thoroughly untraditional. A distorted
bajo sexto bass line holds the foreground in ``Paletero''; the buzz
and snap of the strings of the requinto punctuates ``Paula y
Fred,'' a cheerful son jarocho, sung in Spanglish, in which
unrequited love leads to murder.
</P>
<P>
   It's still a Latin thing, but one that can no longer stay
insular. Now it's part of a larger, more chaotic world, where
strange connections have turned into family ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
