u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLINGTON-GRIEG-NYT &LR;      04-08 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLINGTON-GRIEG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ REVIEW: A MIX AND MATCH OF TREASURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If jazz has been about one thing over the last 100
years, it has been about transformation. Jazz musicians changed the
sound of European instruments to reflect the needs of the new
environment. They transformed staid melodies and songs, making them
hop with the heat of improvisation. And jazz's endless revision of
standard pop harmony created a new way of thinking about chords,
one based on the idea of replacing the old and simple with the new
and complex.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed almost inevitable when Duke Ellington and his
longtime collaborator Billy Strayhorn took on Edvard Grieg's ``Peer
Gynt'' Suite and transformed its lush melancholia into something
less somber and more American. Using the raw materials of the
original work's melody and a bit of its harmony and shape, the two
produced an individual suite in 1960 that is the original's equal
in profundity.
</P>
<P>
   At Avery Fisher Hall on Wednesday, the New York Philharmonic and
the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra collaborated on the composition,
alternating pieces of Grieg's original with their Ellington and
Strayhorn counterparts, and produced an extraordinary event from
something that might have been pedantic. Pedantic because comparing
the two versions is something one does alone with a CD player or
lecturing from a podium. But the two works are so different and so
rich in varying ways and both orchestras are so accomplished in
their interpretations that the music stood firmly on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison enriched the experience, enabling listeners to
follow the scraps of repeated melodies, the octave jumps sung by
the soprano Kelley Nassief with the philharmonic mirrored in the
clarinet solos of Victor Goines during the Lincoln Center Jazz
Orchestra's turn.
</P>
<P>
   One could follow the Ellington and Strayhorn reharmonization,
the abruptness the two put in the changing harmonic scenery. Where
Grieg kept his emotional colors cool and gorgeous, using big blocks
of harmony in the strings with little polyphony, Ellington and
Strayhorn used counterpoint, clashing lines of melody and polyphony
to expand the emotional range of the work. One could hear the
different ways of producing a foundation for music: in one section,
Ellington and Strayhorn used a rhythmic pattern that both reflected
and informed the melodic development of the music.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra moved from static
rhythms to all the various swing rhythms Ellington and Strayhorn
brought to the piece, the music opened up as if its palette had
suddenly tripled the available colors. Ellington and Strayhorn were
masters at scoring and arranging, and their control of rhythmic
change was unparalleled.
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the concert featured Ellington works scored
by Wynton Marsalis for the combined forces of the philharmonic and
the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra. They included ``Bula,'' from the
``Afro Bossa Suite''; ``Blues in Blueprint,'' ``Happy-Go-Lucky
Local'' and ``A Tone Parallel to Harlem''; Kurt Masur directed the
united orchestras with energy, and if the pieces didn't have the
heft of ``Peer Gynt,'' little does.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a sense that the collaboration had historical
weight. Masur, the music director of the philharmonic, and
Marsalis, the music director of Jazz at Lincoln Center, have been
talking about a collaboration for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Peer Gynt'' was their debut joint effort, and they plan
to do more. These five concerts at Avery Fisher Hall _ with
performances Friday, Saturday and next Tuesday _ are sold out.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of the collaboration has ramifications for the jazz
world because it exposes the music of Duke Ellington to a broader
audience. Over the next month, the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra
will perform the program with the orchestras of Chicago, Boston,
London, Amsterdam and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The size and success of the collaboration is a tribute to the
imaginative use of institutional power.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps it's testimony to the continuing ability of jazz to
transform a variety of forms _ in this case, the classical music
structure _ to fit its needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
