</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METROLAND-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`METROLAND': DELUSIONS OF A FAILED BOHEMIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Based on an obviously early novel by Julian Barnes,
``Metroland'' assails its hero's bourgeois family life in a London
suburb. From the film's standpoint, Chris Lloyd (Christian Bale)
has sold out and abandoned his dreams. He is aggressively reminded
of that by the arrival of his best friend (Lee Ross), who spells
his name Toni, writes poetry, boasts about sexual conquests and
roams the world. One of Toni's postcards: ``Africa's where it's
happening. Vibrant culture. Great people. Thinking of hanging out
here for a while. Eat the rich. Love, Toni.''
</P>
<P>
   The story is set in the 1960s and 1970s, which makes its social
observations a lot more dated than, say, Edith Wharton's. It flips
from when the men are in their early 30's (1977) to their
Beatlemania-era boyhood (when they dropped Jean-Paul Sartre's name
and sneered at the bank managers in their neighborhood) to 1968.
That was the year when Chris, in the film's own most bourgeois
notion, fancied himself a bohemian by ``going to Paris to be an
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   His life was a whirl of Gauloises, Rimbaud, Lawrence Durrell
novels and Francoise Dorleac records as he experienced first love
with a smiling French hedonist named Annick (Elsa Zylberstein), who
obligingly posed for his arty boudoir photographs. ``Annick, do you
want to see a film on Friday?'' he remembers saying, during one of
his nostalgic daydreams. ``There's a new Bresson.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Chris' sexual freedom is curtailed by marriage and
responsibility. (For a better film on this subject, see ``A Walk on
the Moon.'') While with his English wife Marion, who is played by
Emily Watson with welcome acuity, he daydreams about his wilder
times. In one of the film's wittier strokes, he also imagines
Marion saying: ``I want you to have affairs. It'll be good for our
marriage. And of course I'll still cook your dinner and do your
washing and ironing.''
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is a little goading from Toni and Chris begins
wondering why he settled down so early. During a flashback to their
courtship, Marion spells it out for him with the film's best line,
``You're not original enough not to.'' Later on, in a very forced
ending, it is Marion who has to explain away Toni's troublemaking
in the silliest possible terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Metroland,'' directed by Philip Saville and adapted by Adrian
Hodge, does seem plausible as a cri de coeur from a trapped young
husband and father. But its affectations are more galling than
Gallic most of the time. Though Ms. Zylberstein is a Frenchwoman,
she plays such a stereotype that she seems to be impersonating one.
</P>
<P>
   Its strongest assets, aside from a performance by Ms. Watson
that pierces through the nonsense, are Mark Knopfler's fine,
expressive score and the attractiveness of its star. Bale is a
babe, as the film's characters make a point of mentioning. (Annick
calls Chris ``a beautiful English boyfriend.'') The story often has
him leaping into bed quite often, in search of bohemian thrills.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `METROLAND'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Philip Saville; written by Adrian Hodge, based on
the novel by Julian Barnes; director of photography, Jean-Francois
Robin; edited by Greg Miller; music by Mark Knopfler; production
designer, Don Taylor; produced by Andrew Bendel; released by Lions
Gate Films. Running time: 99 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Christian Bale (Chris), Emily Watson (Marion), Lee Ross
(Toni), Elsa Zylberstein (Annick) and Rufus (Henri).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0806 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRANSGENDER-PROTEST-H     04-08 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSGENDER-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP ACCUSES SAN FRANCISCO POLICE OF ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A coalition representing people who have had sex
changes is accusing the police and sheriff's deputies of abuse and
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The newly formed coalition, TransAction, made its case outside
the Hall of Justice on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing transgendered persons who are the victims of
police brutality and the numbers are on the rise,'' said Shawna
Virago, one of those who spoke at the gathering. Some of the
speakers said they were former prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   The police and sheriff's office deny the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Veronika Cauley, a member of San Francisco's Veterans Affairs
Commission, said she had been verbally harassed by the police or
mistakenly stopped for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a prostitute in a past life,'' Cauley said. ``But that
doesn't excuse what has been done to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Officer Sherman Ackerson said the San Francisco Police
Department does not single out ``any group for any reason. We do
not target transgender people for any reason. We are treating them
like any other person in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers at the Hall of Justice complained about
practices in the San Francisco Jail, saying they have been strip
searched to determine their gender. They also complained of being
subjected to verbal abuse and harassment behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was in part to show support for Victoria Schneider, a
transsexual who has a lawsuit pending that alleges she was
subjected to an illegal strip search by officers following a 1996
misdemeanor arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the police strip search women, it's as though we've been
raped. It strips us of our dignity and our self-esteem,'' Schneider
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The city has denied wrongdoing and is fighting Schneider's
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Michael Hennessey said Wednesday that it is against his
department's policy to strip-search in order to determine gender.
He said that deputies will perform strip searches only if a
suspect's recent criminal history indicates use of drugs, weapons
or violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That applies to all arrestees in that category whether they
are transgender or not,'' the sheriff said. ``This is in order to
keep drugs and weapons out of the jail system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sheriff's Department is in charge of jails.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessey also said his department does not tolerate deputies
harassing inmates. He said the jail system has made special efforts
to accommodate people who have had sex changes and keep ``any
inmate who is believed to be vulnerable'' away from the general
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assess every single person for possible harm,'' Hennessey
said. ``We take that very seriously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
