<HEADLINE>
`NEVER BEEN KISSED': GRADUATION IS THE BEST REVENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does it say about ``Never Been Kissed,'' the latest and
dumbest in the deluge of high school comedies from Hollywood, that
the most despised nerd in the senior class, a girl who is
humiliated at the prom by having dog food poured down the back of
her dress, is better looking than the actual prom queen or any of
her attendants? That nerd, Aldys (Leelee Sobieski), who leads a
high school math team, is not much of a role. But Ms. Sobieski
lends the character about the only dignity to be found in this
bogus, bottom-of-the-barrel Cinderella story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never Been Kissed'' deals with the fantasy shared at one time
or another by most graduates of that savage institution known as
the American high school of reliving those traumatic years with an
adult's knowledge of the world. It is a potentially rich subject
that was treated a bit more seriously 13 years ago in ``Peggy Sue
Got Married.'' In that comforting but ultimately silly movie, an
older and wiser Kathleen Turner goes back in time and despite
having the chance to do things differently ends up making the same
major life decisions she did before.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Drew Barrymore, playing Josie Geller, a 25-year-old
reporter for a Chicago newspaper, poses as a high school student to
get the inside scoop on what it's like to be a millennial
teen-ager. Flashbacks reveal that in high school Josie was a
stringy-haired, hunched-over geek with braces on her teeth who was
unmercifully persecuted by the pretty people in her class. This
time around, of course, Josie rules. But by the end of her
assignment, she also learns that being the most popular girl in her
class and its prom queen are not all they're cracked up to be. And
when her true identity is revealed, she even gets to lecture her
stunned classmates about their cliquish narrow-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrymore, who is the executive producer of ``Never Been
Kissed,'' has shown enough cuddlesome spunk in the past to
illuminate otherwise mediocre movies, like ``Ever After,'' with a
flash of charm. But ``Never Been Kissed'' is so hopelessly
cartoonish and wrongheaded in its details that there's not even a
semblance of reality for her to grab on to.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the movie's view of journalism. Rigfort
(Garry Marshall), the editor of the paper for which she works, is a
railing buffoon who loudly threatens to dismiss people every five
minutes. Once Josie, outfitted with a tiny video camera, has gone
back to high school her newsroom colleagues appear to spend all
day, every day, huddled around a television set absorbed by her
adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Josie's initial foray into high school life is a disaster. It
isn't until her brother Rob (David Arquette), who was a popular
jock in his day at the same school, re-enrolls, becomes instantly
popular and tells everyone how cool Josie is (she poses not as his
sister but as a former date) that she is taken up by the in-group.
Presiding over that inner clique is a triumvirate of vicious
shallow little witches who are carbon copies of the vixens in the
recent and equally awful ``Jawbreaker.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that Arquette is not only charmless but also
entirely unconvincing as both a high schooler (he appears to be on
the far side of 30) and a jock. Nor does it help that the
screenplay, by Abby Kohn and Marc Silverstein, is virtually
joke-free, unless dog food poured down the back of a party dress
qualifies as humor.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, directed by Raja Gosnell, gives Ms. Barrymore a
Prince Charming in Sam (Michael Vartan), a handsome English teacher
who is drawn to Josie's mature-for-her-years literary imagination.
But the movie is so nervous about the possibility of promoting
student-teacher sexual relations that it makes sure we know that
Josie, at 25, has never even been kissed. But not to worry, Josie
eventually becomes the lucky recipient of one very long,
passionless smooch that is applauded by an entire stadium of
onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Never Been Kissed'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It has some off-color humor.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   NEVER BEEN KISSED
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Raja Gosnell; written by Abby Kohn and Marc
Silverstein; director of photography, Alex Nepomniaschy; edited by
Debra Chiate and Marcelo Sansevieri; music by David Newman;
production designer, Steven Jordan; produced by Sandy Isaac and
Nancy Juvonen; released by 20th Century Fox. Running time: 97
minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Drew Barrymore (Josie Geller), David Arquette (Rob
Geller), Michael Vartan (Sam Coulson), Molly Shannon (Anita), John
C. Reilly (Gus), Leelee Sobieski (Aldys), Jeremy Jordan (Guy
Perkins), Jessica Alba (Kirsten) and Marley Shelton (Kristin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
