<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANA? PHILADELPHIA, OF COURSE  
 SWEDISH STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.Y., Sweden)  (js) 
 BY WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As American antiques go, it is hard to think of anything more
famous than the Liberty Bell. So it's not surprising that the
annual antiques show in Philadelphia, home of the bell and cradle
of liberty, has exceptional examples of Americana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best show of its type, in terms of fairs that focus
on Americana,'' said Leigh Keno, a Manhattan dealer who
participates in only two shows a year, New York City's Winter
Antiques Show and the Philadelphia Antiques Show, which opens
Friday night and runs through April 14. ``For the collector of
Americana and the decorative arts appropriate to it, like Chinese
porcelain and Oriental rugs, there's no better show.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lindsey, curator of American decorative art at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art, said of the show: ``Dealers bring their
best American things to it. In terms of prices and quality, a lot
of records have been set at the show, but because Philadelphia is
so quiet you never hear about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six dealers are participating this year, including a few
who are new to the show: John Alexander of Philadelphia; Stephen
and Carol Huber of Old Saybrook, Conn.; William Reese of New Haven
and Marcy Burns of Wyncote, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   At the show, at the 103rd Engineers Armory, at 33rd and Market
streets, many dealers specialize in early American furniture,
porcelain and silver. A few focus on Philadelphia antiques.
``Philadelphians appreciate their home-grown antiques, and,
happily, everyone else seems to as well,'' Lindsey said.
</P>
<P>
   He has organized an exhibition of 500 examples of Pennsylvania
baroque furniture and decorative arts made between 1681 and 1758
that opens at the museum on Oct. 7. He said that 25 objects at the
museum show would be on loan from local collectors who had bought
them in the last few years at the antiques show.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia antiques do not come cheap. On Jan. 16, Christie's
sold a magnificent Philadelphia rococo tilt-top tea table (circa
1765) from the Britton Collection to the Chipstone Foundation for
$1,542,500. And at the antiques show, Keno is selling a pair of
Philadelphia side chairs in the rococo style, circa 1770, with
leafy carved knees, for $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between 1755 and 1785, Philadelphia was the center for the
rococo style in the colonies,'' Keno said. ``It produced the most
opulent designs, full-blown rococo pieces with naturalistic,
asymmetrical foliate carving.''
</P>
<P>
   The show also features a loan exhibition of 38 idiosyncratic
chairs, many made in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose antiques that were quirky,'' said Fyte Ludington
Drayton, co-chairwoman of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Drayton was a founding member of the Fairmount Park House
Guides, Philadelphia Museum volunteers trained in the American
decorative arts. The guides will give a group tour of the antiques
show every morning at 10 before it opens. It costs $20. Mrs.
Drayton said she was not a collector: ``I'm an inheritor.''
</P>
<P>
   One item in the loan exhibition is a 19th-century wrought-iron
``cemetery chair'' with the name ``K. Getman'' on the crest rail.
(It can be assumed the chair was given in his memory.) ``It was
designed for a rural cemetery like Philadelphia's Laurel Hill,''
Mrs. Drayton said. ``One could sit there and think about the
deceased.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Johnson, her co-chairwoman, has been in charge of loan
exhibitions at the show since 1976. She singled out a reclining
``gout chair'' made in China of rosewood, bamboo and cane for the
American market. ``It supposedly belonged to Commodore Barry, the
father of the American Navy,'' Mrs. Johnson said. ``But he died in
1803. It was probably bought by his nephew, who was involved in the
China trade in the 1850s.'' The chair has a footrest. ``Gout is
very painful; this must have helped the afflicted person when his
ankles swelled,'' Mrs. Johnson added.
</P>
<P>
   Swedish Style
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saturday afternoon, Christie's will be the host of a
forum on Swedish design at its salesroom at 502 Park Ave. at 59th
Street. The session will be opened by Princess Christina of Sweden,
chairwoman for 10 years of a society that is trying to establish an
independent museum for design and the decorative arts in Stockholm.
``This is nothing new,'' the princess said. ``The museum has been
under discussion for 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The princess' group has a private gallery for seminars and
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a lobbying group,'' she said. ``We are trying to create
a wide interest in the museum idea among fashion people, industrial
designers, artists and craftsmen. Eventually, it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's symposium, organized by the American Craft Museum,
the Swedish Information Service, the Bard Graduate Center for
Studies in the Decorative Arts, and Christie's itself, will trace
Swedish design from 1900 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1897 Stockholm had an exhibition of Swedish art and
industry that attracted 1.2 million people,'' said Dr. Elisabet
Hidemark, a Stockholm museum curator who will discuss the roots of
Swedish design. ``There were only five million people in all of
Sweden. Swedish artists and architects took Art Nouveau and created
something new that was distinctly Swedish. You see it in the cut
and engraved glass and the colorful ceramics until about 1908.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerstin Wickman, a lecturer at the Konstfack Institute in
Stockholm, traced modern Swedish design to 1917, ``when artists
began to work together with the craftspeople in the factories in
the small villages of Orrefors, Kosta and Boda.'' Things changed
drastically in 1932, she said, when the Social Democrats passed new
laws to promote affordable housing, health, convenience and
hygiene. ``Rents were low and the government gave newly marrieds
loans to buy proper furniture,'' she said. ``The designers came
together to promote pragmatic, practical designs. No designers
became `stars' because they felt designers should not become
famous.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation changed again after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now a whole generation in Sweden wanted to be modern and live
in a new way,' Ms. Wickman said. ``Tradition was not worth much
anymore. That stimulated the designers. Blond wood came in. It's
elegant, well-done, quality, and it gives an idea about the good
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Cilla Robach, curator of 20th-century applied art and design at
the Nationalmuseum in Stockholm, will discuss Swedish design after
1970. She said designers today were trying to create objects that
are both beautiful and practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swedes have a feeling for natural materials and lightness of
form,'' she said. `The language of the forms is quite austere. The
beauty comes in the proportions. The furniture looks simple, but
there is a lot of work involved in it. We are famous for this
austere design. If you are interested in comfort, choose another
style.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets cost $50 at the door. Information: (212) 583-2586.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
