<HEADLINE>
`TWIN FALLS IDAHO': IT'S NOT THE USUAL MENAGE A TROIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ However many films you may have seen, you probably
haven't seen anything like ``Twin Falls Idaho'' on screen. One of
the most eerily effective films at the New Directors/New Films
festival this year, it takes the real-life closeness of the
identical twins Michael and Mark Polish into the realm of haunting
fantasy. These arrestingly gaunt, watchful-looking brothers star in
the film as conjoined twins, Blake (Mark) and Francis (Michael)
Falls, whose delicately balanced interdependence provides a rare
brand of tension.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which the Polish brothers wrote and Michael directed,
begins as the twins encounter a wild, gorgeous young woman named
Penny (Michele Hicks, a former model) in an interestingly desolate
hotel. It's a setting that the cinematographer, M. David Mullen,
photographs with bleak and painterly precision. And it is here that
the brothers' differences begin to emerge, with Francis as the
stronger figure, and the one most powerfully drawn to Penny.
Imagine how a Siamese twin might conduct a courtship, and imagine
this rendered with intense acuity and no gimmicks. Then you have
some idea of how tricky ``Twin Falls Idaho'' eventually becomes.
</P>
<P>
   Because Blake is the weaker and more dependent of the two, and
because the situation's menage a trois possibilities are
unavoidable, the film explores aspects of symbiotic relationships
that nonconjoined viewers will easily understand. It also has
strong, offbeat atmosphere and a richly perverse sense of mischief
where the twins are concerned. A pivotal part of the film unfolds
on Halloween, when the Falls boys impress strangers with their
marvelous costume (a two-armed, three-legged suit) and attend a
party where they seem like the most normal people in the room.
Though the twins have done time as a circus attraction, the film
itself never treats them like freaks.
</P>
<P>
   With an especially affecting performance by Michael Polish as
the story's dominant figure, and with Ms. Hicks a striking
kohl-eyed presence even when she struggles with the story's more
demanding scenes, ``Twin Falls Idaho'' has style, gravity and
originality to spare. It's a film that dwells as hauntingly on
loneliness as it does on never actually being able to be alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twin Falls Idaho'' will be shown Friday and Saturday as part
of the New Directors/New Films series at the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TWIN FALLS IDAHO'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Polish; written by him and Mark Polish;
director of photography, M. David Mullen; edited by Leo Trombetta;
music by Stuart Matthewman; production designer, Warren Allen
Young; produced by Marshall Persinger, Rena Ronson and Steven
Wolfe; released by Sony Pictures Classics. Shown as part of the
28th New Directors/New Films series of the Film Society of Lincoln
Center and the Department of Film of the Museum of Modern Art.
Running time: 110 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Mark Polish (Blake Falls), Michael Polish (Francis Falls),
Michele Hicks (Penny), Jon Gries (Jay), Patrick Bauchau (Miles),
Garrett Morris (Jesus), William Katt (Surgeon) and Lesley Ann
Warren (Francine).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
