<HEADER>
A0832 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-KISSED-SPI &LR;      04-08 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KISSED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEVER BEEN KISSED' PREDICTABLE, RARELY FUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drew Barrymore's first foray as executive producer in ``Never
Been Kissed'' certainly gives her a lot of close-ups.
</P>
<P>
   In this predictable Cinderella story of a nerdy Chicago
Sun-Times copy editor who gets her big chance by going back to high
school to write an undercover expose on student/teacher relations,
Barrymore stacks the deck.
</P>
<P>
   Her character is so intent upon repairing her own traumatic
teenage experience that she can barely do her job. By focusing on
becoming popular, she ignores deadlines, and finds true love.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to give Barrymore credit for portraying herself as
the ungainliest of geeks, but as a newspaperwoman she's about as
believeable as Julia Roberts' hooker in ``Pretty Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Never Been Kissed,'' Barrymore plays Josie Geller, a nerdy,
virginal 25-year-old copy editor on one of Chicago's two big daily
papers. She might have her own office, which is a feat in itself,
but Josie hasn't even been ``properly kissed,'' she tells her
libidinous best friend, Anita (Molly Shannon).
</P>
<P>
   Her dream is to be a reporter, but she can't get her editor, the
seasoned Gus (John C. Reilly), to give her a chance. Then the
paper's owner (played by Garry Marshall) assigns her to an
undercover expose: She has to find a story somewhere in the
hallowed halls of high school.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her joy, Josie has a problem. She was a total zero with
braces in school, humiliated on prom night and called ``Josie
Grossie'' by the other kids. Her brother, Rob (David Arquette) was
the popular kid, though his life is now on the skids. This could be
her big chance to redeem herself from her nightmares and bad
memories. But will history repeat itself or will Josie finally get
a date with the most popular guy in school?
</P>
<P>
   It's not too tough to see what's coming in this only
occasionally amusing romantic comedy. Barrymore goes out on a limb
to act the geek and, indeed, those are the films best (and meanest)
moments.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no real conflict or friction at the story's core and
there are so many incidental bits that the lessons Josie learns
feel hackneyed and tacked on. We know what will happen within the
first half hour. Barrymore is whinily bland, as is Michael Vartan,
in a thankless role as the school's handsome, popular English
teacher, who takes an interest in Josie.
</P>
<P>
   It's a small role by LeeLee Sobieski, who gave an impassioned
performance in last year's ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries,''
that stands out. She's Josie's new best school friend, an offbeat
chemistry and calculus whiz named Aldys. When Josie finally
achieves status and becomes everything she never was the first time
around, the pain of rejection is evidently clear on Sobieski's
face. She scoops Barrymore in every scene of this painfully tepid
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Never Been Kissed. Directed by Raja Gosnell. Written by Abby
Kohn, Marc Silverstein. Cast: Drew Barrymore, David Arquette, Molly
Shannon, LeeLee Sobieski. 20th Century Fox. 100 minutes. Rated
PG-13 for language, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
