</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTARCTIC-ODYSSEY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTARCTICA: AS GORGEOUS AND DEADLY TODAY AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Standing astern of Shackleton's whaleboat while watching
computer-generated waves play across movie screens off her bows, I
could almost feel the sting of freezing brine thrown up by the
mountainous Cape Horn rollers.
</P>
<P>
   The vantage point, of course, was on dry land in New York inside
the American Museum of Natural History, and the 22{-foot boat, the
James Caird, now nearly a century old, was part of the exhibition
opening Saturday, April 10, called ``The Endurance: Shackleton's
Legendary Antarctic Expedition.'' But so convincing are those big
video waves that a person could get seasick watching.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a memorial to Sir Ernest Shackleton and the stamina
of his 27 shipmates during their hellish 22-month voyage over water
and ice at the bottom of the world. But it is as much about
Antarctica itself as it is about Shackleton's heroes, and to anyone
who has spent time on the White Continent, it must touch a resonant
chord.
</P>
<P>
   Antarctica is as beautiful as it was in Shackleton's day, and it
is still deadly dangerous; some things don't change. It has been 83
years since Shackleton's Endurance saga ended, but the seafaring
memorabilia and the photographs that make up this beautiful
exhibition seem almost modern in some ways.
</P>
<P>
   During my five sojourns in Antarctica since 1974, all under the
auspices of the National Science Foundation, I have come to
understand (in a small way) the peculiar magnetism of the place.
People have always journeyed to Antarctica to profit, to glimpse
its incredible beauty and to probe its scientific secrets. But they
also go partly to taste the continent's inherent danger and the
thrill of risk taking, however large or small the risk may be.
</P>
<P>
   Something deep down in most people yearns for adventure, and
Antarctica is an icon for adventure.
</P>
<P>
   There have been enormous technological changes since the glory
years and derring-do of Roald Amundsen, Robert F. Scott, Douglas
Mawson, Adm. Richard Byrd and a legion of other polar explorers.
Gone are the dog sledges and skis on which explorers formerly
traveled, now replaced by snowmobiles, motorized sledge trains,
C-130 cargo planes, helicopters and Zodiac boats.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation over the continent's trackless wastes no longer
depends on compass and sextant; today the global positioning
satellite system informs travelers exactly where they are at all
times. Satellites have also provided such efficient voice
communication that the sense of isolation people often felt as
recently as 20 years ago has mostly vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Antarcticans are no longer compelled to nourish themselves with
``hoosh'' _ the disgusting stew of seal or penguin meat mixed with
lard, flour, cocoa, sugar, salt and water that fed many generations
of polar travelers. There are modern galleys with fine chefs at all
the big stations now, and even in the field, most travelers eat
fairly well.
</P>
<P>
   The sights are stunning: towering blue, white and green icebergs
and giant penguin rookeries near Palmer Station on the Antarctic
Peninsula; vistas of the snow-covered Transantarctic Mountains
across the sound at McMurdo; dancing solar halos around the sun at
the South Pole. Even winter, when most of the continent is shrouded
in continuous darkness for four months, has its beauties,
especially the shimmering aurora australis.
</P>
<P>
   The subfreezing cold that perpetually grips most of the
continent takes snapshots of life that never fade. The Ross Island
huts used by Scott, Shackleton and other explorers from 1902 to
1914 look much as they did when they were occupied by expeditions.
They are still littered with discarded trash and the carcasses of
seals and penguins slaughtered for meat, as well as the 89-year-old
body of a husky dog that looks as if it just died. Ancient copies
of The London Illustrated News and other early-20th-century reading
matter in some of the old huts evoke the ghosts of storybook
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   These days, tourists aboard cruise ships go to Antarctica to
savor its special flavor, and a veneer of security seemingly
protects visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But even tourism carries risks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the worst aviation accidents in history occurred on Nov.
28, 1979, when an Air New Zealand passenger plane on a sightseeing
flight was swept by a powerful downdraft onto the slopes of Mount
Erebus, a volcano on Ross Island. All 257 people aboard were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year alone, the National Science Foundation
estimates, 10 people have been killed in Antarctica, several of
them in the crash of a Russian helicopter making a scientific
flight.
</P>
<P>
   People still mistake snow bridges for solid ice and fall to
their deaths in concealed crevasses.
</P>
<P>
   Antarctica is the coldest place on earth; a temperature of minus
129 degrees Fahrenheit was recorded in 1983 at Russia's Vostok
Station on the South Polar Plateau. Clad in parka, wind pants,
thermal boots, bear-paw gloves and so forth, a traveler finds such
temperatures bearable, but vigilance is always needed. Many a time
a companion has warned me that my nose had turned white: a signal
of frostbite.
</P>
<P>
   This was nothing compared with the suffering undergone by one of
my polar friends, Liv Arnesen. A 40-year-old Oslo schoolteacher,
she set out in 1994 to become the first woman to ski unaccompanied
from the edge of the Antarctic continent to the South Pole. I
happened to be at the pole when she arrived on Christmas Eve 1994:
still dogged, her face torn by the elements and her endurance
practically exhausted. To clear ice crystals from her goggles, she
had frequently removed her gloves to scratch the rime away during
her 50-day, 720-mile trek, and her fingers were so frostbitten that
the South Pole Station surgeon had to amputate part of her
gangrenous thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later Ms. Arnesen was helping with the cooking in the
station galley, and ``yarning'' cheerfully with her new American
friends.
</P>
<P>
   She survived, but two of my other friends were less fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Palmer Station is a small American scientific post on an island
just off the Antarctic Peninsula. Most of its heavy supplies are
brought by a small icebreaker from Punta Arenas, a port on the
Chilean coast of Tierra del Fuego.
</P>
<P>
   These trips are usually arduous. The stretch of water between
Punta Arenas and the Antarctic Peninsula, known as the Drake
Passage, has been famous since the 17th century for its mountainous
waves, hurricane-force winds and savagely unpredictable weather.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 I spent some time cruising the Drake Passage aboard the
Erebus, a French ship chartered by the National Science Foundation
to carry freight and scientists between Punta Arenas and Palmer
Station. I got to know the vessel's first mate, a 38-year-old
American mariner and adventurer named Mark Eichenberger.
</P>
<P>
   Mark had sailed under all conditions and had achieved modest
fame in 1988 when he and three companions paddled a modified
aluminum canoe 600 miles across the Drake Passage from Punta Arenas
to Antarctica: an incredible achievement.
</P>
<P>
   But during Christmas week 1991, the sea had its revenge. I had
left the Erebus at its dock at Punta Arenas when a sudden storm
swept ashore from the Drake Passage. The only officer aboard, Mark
ran out on deck to tighten the hawsers and secure the ship against
the onslaught, but a huge wave crashed over him, and he was swept
out to sea. His body was never found.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 I lost another friend, Bruno Zehnder, to Antarctica's
treachery. Bruno was a Swiss photographer famous for his eagerness
to take on any danger for the sake of a good picture. His style and
artistic touches reminded me of Frank Hurley, the photographer
whose images of the Endurance expedition grace the new museum
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   In his last years Bruno made his living mostly by photographing
Antarctic penguins, especially the big (and very photogenic)
emperor penguins that breed in the darkness of midwinter. In July
1997 (midwinter in Antarctica) Bruno had arranged to spend several
months at Russia's Mirnyy Station on the Antarctic coast along the
Indian Ocean. On July 7 he was out as usual looking for subjects
close to the Mirnyy huts when a violent storm struck. So much snow
was blowing, the Russians later said, that visibility beyond about
one yard was nil.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno did not return, and when the storm finally abated, the
Russians started searching. They found his frozen body less than
100 yards from the station.
</P>
<P>
   In the Swiss village of Bad Ragaz, where Bruno grew up, his
friends and family are building a small memorial, a circle of stone
penguins with their beaks bowed in sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Like Shackleton's whaleboat in its temporary berth at the Museum
of Natural History, the stone penguins memorialize all those who
gave their lives to a beautiful but unmerciful continent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0844 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-COOKIE'S-FORTUNE     04-08 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-COOKIE'S-FORTUNE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COOKIE'S FORTUNE' A MOST LIKABLE ALTMAN FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Altman once said that his basic philosophy of filmmaking
was to gather the best possible ensemble of actors, take them to
some interesting location, allow them to play with their roles and
improvise some of their dialogue, and then hope something magical
happens.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it does _ witness such classics as ``MASH,'' ``McCabe
and Mrs. Miller'' and ``The Player.'' Sometimes, perhaps more
often, it doesn't _ witness such travesties as ``Popeye,''
``Buffalo Bill and the Indians'' and ``Quintet.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, ``Cookie's Fortune'' _ Altman's 33rd feature film in 42
years of trying _ is one of his most magical brews. Indeed, it
would be hard to think of a more completely likable Altman film or
one in which the chemistry of his cast seemed more perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the (real) small-town of Holly Springs, Miss., it's a
rambling, amiable story about what happens when a pipe-smoking
Southern dowager named Cookie (Patricia O'Neal) commits suicide in
order to join her beloved late husband.
</P>
<P>
   Stumbling upon the body, Cookie's scheming, slightly crazed
niece, Camille (Glenn Close), eats the suicide note and concocts a
string of ``evidence'' to make the death look like murder _ because
``suicides don't happen'' in their family.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately (and unintentionally), this concocted evidence
gradually points to Cookie's handyman, Willis (Charles S. Dutton),
an easy-going, middle-aged black man who has been sharing the house
with her in a kind of ``Driving Miss Daisy'' relationship.
</P>
<P>
   This is the set-up of the movie, and at this point we might
naturally expect the proceedings to turn into one more
heavy-handed, self-righteous indictment of racism in the small-town
South _ especially since Willis is so downright lovable and such an
obvious potential martyr.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Cookie's Fortune'' goes against all expectations to be a
lazy, irresistibly good-natured little comedy in which race is
ultimately not much of an issue, and just about everyone in this
small town _ excluding Close's character _ is a fairly decent human
being. It's Mayberry, not Mississippi Burning.
</P>
<P>
   As usual in an Altman movie, a wide assortment of characters
wander in and out of the storyline: Ned Beatty as a sheriff who'd
rather be fishing; Donald Moffat as the town's affable only lawyer;
Courtney B. Vance as a frustrated state prosecutor; Julianne Moore
as Camille's addled sister and co-conspirator.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as in only the best Altman, every character seems to click
into place. As Cookie's free-spirited grand-niece, Liv Tyler has
never been more movie-star radiant. As Cookie, veteran movie-great
O'Neal gives a blissfully broad and fearless performance. Even
Chris O'Donnell _ the town's Barney Fife of a deputy _ is a welcome
part of this inspired ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   The film comes together to be less the wild farce and scathing
satire that its publicity promises than a mellow comedy of
character that communicates a gentle acceptance of human nature in
general and family eccentricity in particular _ a film that likes
its characters so much that it's impossible not to feel the same
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, ``Cookie's Fortune'' has the same kind of uncanny
authenticity that Altman was able to give 1902 Puget Sound in
``McCabe and Mrs. Miller,'' '90s Hollywood in ``The Player'' and
'70s Nashville in ``Nashville.'' Few directors convey a sense of
time and place so convincingly, and this most convincing vision of
the post-civil rights Mississippi is a place that's definitely
worth a two-hour visit.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie's Fortune. Directed by Robert Altman. Screenplay by Anne
Rapp. Cast: Glenn Close, Julianne Moore, Liv Tyler, Patricia
O'Neal, Charles S. Dutton, Chris O'Donnell, Ned Beatty. October
Films. 118 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
