<SLUG> BC-FILM-GO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GO' A JOYRIDE THAT RARELY DOWNSHIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Swingers pushed first-time director Doug Liman into the
limelight. ``Go'' will keep him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swingers'' was an acquired taste, and people either loved or
hated it (I was in the second group), but ``Go'' displays Liman's
storytelling as well as moviemaking abilities.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he borrows from the ``Pulp Fiction'' school of structure,
dividing his tale of six young people from Los Angeles who share
one night of crime and chaos, into three intertwining chapters. But
he also constructs _ from a script by John August _ a scary, darkly
funny and suspenseful film that surprises and engages at every turn
and became an audience favorite at this year's Sundance Film
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go'' features a terrific up-and-coming cast. Canadian Sarah
Polley, who was so good in ``The Sweet Hereafter,'' Scott Wolf from
TV's ``Party Of Five,'' Jay Mohr, Katie Holmes from ``Dawson's
Creek,'' William Fichtner, Desmond Askew, Taye Diggs and Timothy
Olyphant are among the ensemble who wreak havoc through L.A. and
Liman's favorite haunt, Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Ronna (Polley) is a supermarket clerk who is on the verge of
being evicted from her apartment. Her co-worker, Simon (Askew),
offers her some money up front if she'll take his shift so he can
go to Vegas with his buddies. Claire (Holmes) is the bystander who
becomes embroiled in Ronna's scheme to score some extra bucks.
</P>
<P>
   When two TV stars, Zack (Mohr) and Adam (Wolf), show up at the
store looking for Simon, who has been their drug dealer in the
past, Ronna decides she can turn the deal instead, especially since
Simon is out of town. She cajoles Simon's supplier, Todd Gaines
(Olyphant), into giving her the stash. But everything goes awry
when Ronna smells a rat and Todd finds he's been stung.
</P>
<P>
   Over in Vegas, Simon discovers that idle hands are truly the
devil's playthings. After he runs out of money at the casino, he
takes up with a couple of young women while best pal Marcus (Diggs)
is still at the tables. Simon's over-enthusiasm lands all the
friends in trouble and soon they've stolen a car, shot a strip club
bouncer, and are being pursued at high speed through the Vegas
streets.
</P>
<P>
   These disparate pieces manage to fall into place and create a
throroughly enjoyable, fast-paced movie that reminds us what it's
like to live on the edge and to react with the impulsive energy of
youth.
</P>
<P>
   While the best thing about ``Swingers'' was Liman's use of the
camera, he's equally up to the task here. He gives us a Los Angeles
that is as eerie and unworldly as it is familiar and his ability to
use cinematography as a storytelling tool has refined and
developed.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, most of the credit must go the vibrancy of
August's script and a cast whose lively performances even manage to
make unlikeable characters accessible. ``Go'' is a joyride that
rarely downshifts; it's unpredictability is its strongest asset.
</P>
<P>
   Go. Directed by Doug Liman. Written by John August. Cast: Taye
Diggs, Katie Holmes, Breckin Meyer, Sarah Polley, Scott Wolf.
Columbia Pictures. 100 minutes. Rated R for language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
