<HEADLINE>
QUICK TREKS TO WILD ADVENTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   Editors: New York Times correspondents report on places to watch
and listen for wildlife.  
 
 c. 1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   India: A secure (and noisy) place for birds
</P>
<P>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER
</P>
<P>
   We awoke in the bird sanctuary of Bharatpur to the shrieks of
peacocks, the mimicry of magpie robins and the assorted cries,
tweets, cheeps and caws of one of the most astonishing
concentrations of avian life on the planet. My husband, Barry, and
my son, Max, 8, complained that the racket had disturbed their
slumber.
</P>
<P>
   The birds here in the Keoladeo National Park, near Agra, home to
the Taj Mahal, are not a shy bunch. Sparrows fly boldly into the
restaurant of the Forest Lodge to perch on chairs. Big-bodied Sarus
cranes take stately flight from the marshlands, soaring over the
narrow main road and buzzing bare-legged tourists who stand gawking
through binoculars. Purple herons, Indian rollers and rose-ringed
parakeets fish and catch insects and even kiss right in plain view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The birds feel very secure in this place,'' said Shruti
Sharma, deputy chief wildlife warden for the Indian Forest Service
and the director of the park.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always like this. The sanctuary, one of the most
popular tourist attractions in India, was the creation of the
Maharajah of the princely state of Bharatpur, who wanted a place to
shoot wildfowl. He deepened and extended a marshland at the
confluence of the Gambhir and Banganga Rivers, constructed
embankments to contain the monsoon downpours and diverted water
from a nearby irrigation canal into the reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The birds flocked to his marshy trap in the vast Gangetic plain
from Siberia, China and Central Asia. ``The coots followed the same
route as Ghengis Khan,'' Mrs. Sharma said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1902, the Maharajah's creation became a playground for
aristocratic colonialists and Indian royalty. A wall of shame still
stands in the middle of the park, engraved with the number of birds
bagged on notable outings. On Nov. 12, 1938, the shooting party of
Lord Linlithgow, the British Viceroy of India, killed 4,273 birds
in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, nine years after India gained its independence from
Britain, the reserve became a bird sanctuary, then, in 1981, a
national park covering just over 11 square miles. It is a four-hour
drive from Delhi on the so-called golden triangle for tourists,
with Delhi at its northern point, Jaipur to the southwest and Agra
to the southeast. Perhaps the best time to visit the park is from
November to February, when the great migrations of birds from
northern climes sail into the park. They are enticed not only by
the marshland habitats but also by grasslands and woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   By early March this year, many of the migratory birds had
already left, but the splendor of the remaining creatures was still
remarkable _ predatory eagles and knobby-kneed storks and green
bee-eaters. White-breasted kingfishers, with their plumage of
iridescent cobalt blue, swooped from acacia trees. Snake birds, so
called because of their long necks, sat with their black,
silver-streaked wings spread to dry in the sun. ``In no other park
can you see so many birds in such a short time in such a small
space,'' Mrs. Sharma said.
</P>
<P>
   The park managers have tried to maintain the park's pristine
condition by keeping out cars and jeeps. But the park is not immune
to ecological pressures. Farms come right up against the stone wall
that surrounds the park. Sometimes, farmers knock down the walls so
their cattle can get in to graze illegally. The pesticides and
fertilizers they use on their crops wind up in the water that comes
into the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, the pesticides will affect the fertility of
the birds,'' Mrs. Sharma said. ``Eggshell thinning takes place.
Even before eggs hatch, they crack.'' The park workers also battle
exotic plants that infest the park, choking out indigenous plant
life.
</P>
<P>
   But the sanctuary is still a magical world unto itself. On a
recent morning, a spotted owl of softest doe brown perched in a
tree with his eyes closed. ``He looks just like Mr. Brown in
`Squirrel Nutkin,''' Max said _ and it did.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to Keoladeo National Park, (91-5644) 22777, fax
(91-5644) 22555, costs $2.35. Tourists can explore on foot, or rent
a boat for about 50 cents a person an hour, or a bicycle for 50
cents a day. Or for 70 cents an hour, they can hire one of 108
bicycle rickshaw drivers who have taken an intensive bird-watching
course.
</P>
<P>
   The nearby Bharatpur Forest Lodge, (91-5644) 22760, fax
(91-5644) 22864, has 17 clean and pleasant rooms on beautifully
kept grounds. Doubles cost about $60 a night. _CELIA W. DUGGER is
co-chief of the New Delhi bureau of The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State: Sitting and waiting for killer whales
</P>
<P>
   By TIMOTHY EGAN We settled not long ago into a perch in the
rocks that rise above the far western edge of the continent, ready
for marine theater below. It can try the patience of an urban
American to watch and wait for something that may not even come.
But at Lime Kiln Point State Park, a half-day's trip from Seattle
on the western shore of Washington's San Juan Island, that is what
you do.
</P>
<P>
   Killer whales are the show. Not the orcas of Sea World or Free
Willy, but the wild natives that live year-round in the salt water
north of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Lime Kiln Point, established in 1984 as perhaps the only park in
the country dedicated exclusively to whale watching, is a front-row
seat. On average, dozens of whales, from three resident pods, will
swim by once or twice a day. Some days, though, they never show.
</P>
<P>
   For us, the curtain rose in late afternoon, about an hour into
our vigil. ``I see a fin!'' my 8-year-old son shouted, as a dorsal
fin pierced the water. Then came a burst of exhaled water, and a
crowd of whales.
</P>
<P>
   Soon they were breaching, spy hopping and doing all the other
frolicking that are trademarks of Puget Sound orcas. They swam
within 50 yards of shore, in the swift current of Haro Strait. In
an hour, more than 50 passed by.
</P>
<P>
   As an eco-tourism experience, watching whales in the San Juans
is definitely not a solitary pursuit. Last year, 185,000 people
visited the park _ by land alone. As we watched with about 15 other
visitors, some people applauded, but most just oohed and aahed, as
if at a fireworks spectacle. It was a wondrous event, and not all
that unusual. ``We estimate that about 25 percent of the people who
come to the park will see whales,'' said Chris Guidotti, a park
ranger.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Black and white killer whales, hopelessly misnamed, chase sea
otters, salmon and myriad varieties of fish, but they do not seem
to mind humans. If anything, they seem to show off for them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they are predators at the top of their food chain.
Federal law prohibits people from getting closer than 100 yards to
the whales. But kayakers, tour boats and other vessels get around
the law by simply positioning themselves in the usual path of the
orcas, then wait to be surrounded. Last year, a woman even paddled
out in the cold water on an air mattress. She may have seen too
many friendly whale movies: the crash of two whales around her gave
her enough of a scare to send her back to shore, Mr. Guidotti said.
</P>
<P>
   Just over 100 whales live year-round in several pods around the
San Juans. The orcas are the source of a booming business for tour
boats, kayak rentals and bed-and-breakfasts in nearby Friday
Harbor. But biologists wonder if there will soon come a time when
too many oglers start to change the behavior of the whales.
</P>
<P>
   The park, basically a parking lot and about a milelong trail
along the bluff, is limiting land visitors this season to 53
carloads _ what can be accommodated in the parking lot. But a visit
during the week, or in the off season (other than summer), can
still bring the kind of personal encounter that makes people fall
in love with killer whales.
</P>
<P>
   Lime Kiln Point State Park is three to four hours from Seattle,
including car and ferry rides. There's no admission charge.
Information: (800) 233-0321.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington State ferry from Anacortes, about 90 miles north
of Seattle, makes five to seven round trips a day to Friday Harbor,
on the opposite side of the island from the park. Round-trip fares
are $17.25 for a car and its driver and $5.10 a passenger.
Information: (206) 464-6400, www.wsdot.wa.gov/ferries.
</P>
<P>
   Bicycles can be rented in Friday Harbor to ride to the park, and
there will be a shuttle bus from the dock to the park starting this
week, for $7 round trip; (360) 378-8887. A ride on one of the tour
boats from Friday Harbor or Roche Harbor Resort costs about $40 to
$50. _TIMOTHY EGAN is a national correspondent for The Times, based
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Getting face to face with a great white
</P>
<P>
   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr
</P>
<P>
   I saw the great white, and she saw me, and I'm sure she was a
lot less impressed than I was. Had she been able to peer into the
boat, she would have seen nine off-green humans lying on their
backs with their eyes shut, trying to control the waves of nausea
rolling over them as they waited for two hours, anchored off
Gansbaai, South Africa, in a swelling sea under a hot sun, for a
shark to appear. Our captain, Gerrit Boshoff, and our dive master,
Schalk De Klerk, remained irritatingly perky, lolling on the
outboard motors only 18 inches above the water, telling jokes and
occasionally asking solicitously, ``How you doing, sir?''
</P>
<P>
   Our situation wasn't helped by the first spot we had stopped:
Dyer Island, home to more than 20,000 Cape fur seals, which is why
great whites are always nearby. Seals en masse under the African
sun smell like nothing else on earth.
</P>
<P>
   We were now far enough away to make the reeking hordes only an
aromatic landscape. Then Schalk dropped overboard 50 pounds of
slimy fish liver, two shark's heads, and a last macabre bit of
bait: a floating cutout of a baby seal.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, the cry rose: ``Shark! Shark! Who's first in
the cage?'' We staggered to our feet; the bravest jumping to the
port side to gape at the smallish six-footer. I lurched starboard,
and was trying to be discreet about my problems when she _ when the
shark turned sideways, there were no claspers of a male to be seen
_ circled the boat and regarded me with a baleful eye.
</P>
<P>
   Six of us were divers and due to take turns slipping into the
two-person steel cage tied alongside to watch her from underwater.
As it turned out, only the first pair got a turn, and, with
visibility at four feet, they barely saw her. Far from being the
ravenous monster of ``Jaws,'' she was cautious, circling the baits
repeatedly before mouthing one gently _ although a big shark's
three-ton bite pressure makes ``gently'' a relative term.
</P>
<P>
   After a dozen passes, she left. After two more stomach-bending
hours, we gave up. Luckier visitors, on calm, cool days in July and
August, have seen up to 30, shark captains claim. There is even one
skipper who grabs the sharks' noses, getting them to open their
jaws for photographers. (His name won't be revealed here, but
someday it'll be Lefty.)
</P>
<P>
   There is some controversy over great white viewing, which has
gone on for 17 years but increased three years ago. Shark attacks
on the South African coast surged last year to at least nine _ one
fatal _ compared with an average of four. The operators contend _
and shark biologists generally agree _ that it was a coincidence.
No attacks took place in Gansbaai or Mosselbaai, where the tour
boats go, and the bait they use is what fishermen cleaning their
catches always tossed overboard. Nothing the boats do encourages
sharks to think of humans as food. Annoying, perhaps, but not worth
snapping at.
</P>
<P>
   A day on the water looking for sharks costs $90 to $160,
including the use of scuba equipment, breakfast and lunch.
Operators are supposed to be licensed by the South African
Department of Sea Fisheries, but enforcement is erratic. Our boat,
operated by White Shark Ecoventures, for example, had no life
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Gansbaai, the most popular spot, is a fishing village about two
hours from Cape Town by car. Tour operators will usually pick you
up early in the morning at any Cape Town hotel for $15 to $25.
Alternatively, they can arrange accommodations _ for as little as
$25 a night in some cases _ at guest houses or private homes in
Gansbaai. The boats don't go out in bad weather or if they don't
have enough passengers to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some boat operators: White Shark Ecoventures, (27-21)
419-8204; African Shark Ecoventures, (27-21) 788-4492; White Shark
Adventures, (27-28) 344-1380 or (27-28) 344-2519; White Shark
Expeditions, (27-83) 725-3186 or (27-21) 686-7041. _DONALD G.
McNEIL Jr. reports on southern Africa for The Times.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
