A0848 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALE-BREASTCANCER-TEX     04-08 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALE-BREASTCANCER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR KNOWS IT CAN HAPPEN TO MEN; IT HAPPENED TO HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Dr. Alan Johns stepped out of the shower one
evening about a year ago and was putting on his tux shirt for a big
formal auction at his daughter's school when he glanced down at his
chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``My blood ran cold,'' he recalls. ``My nipple was inverted. I
reached up, and I could feel a tiny little bump under it. I felt
real cold, and I started sweating. I kept thinking, if I were a
woman, I would really be alarmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth obstetrician/gynecologist has pointed out similar
suspicious lumps to hundreds of his patients over the past 20
years. He estimates that as many as 50 of them turned out to be
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he did nothing about the lump in his right breast until
the first week of June last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine was a typical case. I didn't tell anybody for three
months. I spent sleepless nights poking at it and telling myself it
was no bigger than the night before. I even tried to use my
ultrasound equipment on myself here in the office. That was pretty
dumb. I kept thinking, `I need to get it looked at, but it couldn't
be breast cancer. Men don't get breast cancer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Johns, who specializes in laparoscopic surgery for endometriosis
and other pelvic diseases, does most of his surgery on Mondays at
Harris Methodist Fort Worth. He decided he would get a radiologist
to check out the lump the first Monday afternoon he finished early,
but he never seemed to finish early.
</P>
<P>
   Two things finally prompted him to consult a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night, I sat down with a glass of wine and turned on the
TV without checking any schedule, and the topic of the news show _
`20/20,' I think it was _ just happened to be male breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had already looked up everything I could find on the subject
on the Internet, but that show took me by surprise _ like somebody
was trying to tell me something,'' Johns recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The following Sunday, he was out on the family boat at Possum
Kingdom Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have on a shirt, and suddenly my younger daughter
pointed at my chest, and said, `Eww, that's ugly. What is it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Johns shrugged off the question, but the next day when he
finished surgery, he walked over to the Doris Kupferle Breast
Center at Harris and asked a friend to take a look. When a sonogram
showed that the lump was solid, Johns asked the radiologist to take
a biopsy. He hand-delivered the tissue that same day to another
friend, a pathologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking into the microscope at the same time he was when
he diagnosed a ductal cell carcinoma,'' Johns says. ``I was totally
drained. I was hit hard by what I had known all along: It was
breast cancer. I was real scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Johns has had surgery and chemotherapy. He continues
to have follow-up mammograms and to take tamoxifen, a cancer drug
recently approved for the prevention of breast cancer in high-risk
patients, including those who have a history of breast cancer.
Tamoxifen halves the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chemo was a shock,'' Johns says. ``I had it in my mind
that once the cancer was cut out, that was the end of it, but after
surgery my doctor went over all the parameters of the tumor and
said my five-year survival rate was 85 percent _ and I had been
thinking 100. With chemo it would go to 92 percent, and with chemo
and tamoxifen, better than 95 percent. I opted for the best odds I
could get.''
</P>
<P>
   The chemotherapy ``made me terribly sick, and every time I
started to feel human again, it was time to hit me with it again.
My hair all fell out. I was balder than a bowling ball. I've had
hair, and I've been bald. I'll take hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Johns says, the hair loss is much easier for a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends would see me who didn't know I had cancer and ask
things like, `Did you lose a bet or something?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm taking tamoxifen for at least five years, maybe
forever, and I'm having hot flashes from it. That may be poetic
justice. I have a lot of patients with hot flashes,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And, Johns admits, the mammograms are a little more traumatic
for him (''There's not much tissue there for them to squeeze'')
than he has, in the past, led his women patients to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society says 1,300 new cases of breast
cancer will be diagnosed in men in 1999. An estimated 400 men will
die of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Johns says the day after he was told the diagnosis, he gave his
sister the news, and she reminded him that an uncle _ their
father's brother _ died of breast cancer about 10 years ago,
although no one talked about what kind of cancer he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had totally forgotten that's what he had. For three months,
I was trying to convince myself that I couldn't possibly have
breast cancer, and here I had a family history,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Johns recently joined the board of the Fort Worth chapter of the
Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer Foundation and will be running as a
breast cancer survivor in the five-kilometer division of this
year's Race for the Cure, along with his support team: wife, Jenny,
and two daughters, Julie and Jessica.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls that 22 years ago when he was a resident at John
Peter Smith Hospital, he would see women whose breast cancer was so
advanced, their tumors had broken through the skin before they were
finally diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't afford mammograms, and there were no free ones
to be had then,'' he recalls. ``That has changed. There shouldn't
be anyone in this community who can't get a mammogram today.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
