<HEADLINE>
UNTIL THE EROTIC ENCOUNTER WITH THE RAT, IT WAS COOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Francois Ozon's exquisitely unsettling ``See the Sea'' was one
of the high points at last year's New Directors/New Films series.
Now Ozon returns with a black comedy that means to be no less
disturbing than his expert thriller. But ``Sitcom,'' which is
sardonically filmed with the snappy look of a television comedy,
has a sour streak that eventually poisons its humor. Ozon pushed
the limits of shock value much more effectively with the carefully
measured violence of ``See the Sea'' than he does with this frontal
assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitcom'' begins promisingly enough with the sounds of gunfire
and screaming at a picture-perfect suburban house. The father of
the family (Francois Marthouret) evidently has not been pleased by
the surprise birthday party that greeted him. Then the film flashes
back to presumably happier times, when the mother (Evelyne Dandry)
fussed demurely about the housekeeping and the son Nicholas (Adrien
De Van) and daughter Sophie (Marina De Van, the same sullen actress
who set off chills in ``See the Sea'') looked like model children.
Needless to say, they're not.
</P>
<P>
   Two new members of the household, a pet rat and an insinuating
maid named Maria (Lucia Sanchez), touch off some amusing first
rounds of trouble. One night Maria arrives for dinner in
unexpectedly formal dress and accompanied by Abdu (Jules-Emmanuel
Eyoum Deido), her unexpectedly black husband. (The family is white
but the mother feigns interest in African history.)
</P>
<P>
   This is the same night on which Nicholas abruptly announces that
he is gay and stomps off to his room. Abdu offers to have a helpful
talk with Nicholas, but it soon becomes clear that Abdu's idea of
help isn't what the parents have in mind. Soon Nicholas' room is
home to a parade of strangers doing who-knows-what. The mother
greets these guests politely, if bewilderedly, at the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sophie has an erotic encounter with the rat, leaps out a
window, cripples herself and becomes a bad-tempered paraplegic
dominatrix. It is at about this point that the film's light touch
falls into jeopardy. As the rest of ``Sitcom'' dwells on broken
incest taboos, the popularity of zucchini among Nicholas' guests
and assorted other supposed outrages, we get the point and then
some. In the end, ``Sitcom'' isn't any more barbed about
middle-class complacency than many situation comedies, however
inadvertently, are themselves.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SITCOM'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Francois Ozon; in French, with English
subtitles; director of photography, Yorick le Saux; edited by
Dominique Petrot; music by Eric Neveux; produced by Olivier Delbosc
and Marc Missonnier; released by Leisure Time Features. Running
time: 80 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Evelyne Dandry (The Mother), Francois Marthouret (The
Father), Marina De Van (The Daughter), Adrien De Van (The Son),
Stephane Rideau (The Boyfriend), Lucia Sanchez (The Maid),
Jules-Emmanuel Eyoum Deido (The Maid's Boyfriend).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
