<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-FASHIONS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHIONS FOR THE FUTURE &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   As the fall 1999/winter 2000 women's ready-to-wear collections
drew to a close in Paris, two thoughts were uppermost in the minds
of those who had followed the fashion trail from New York through
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   First was that U.S. designers had undoubtedly best captured the
mood of today's women and that the cohesiveness of the Americans'
showings of luxurious casual wear was exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   The second thought, of a more puzzling nature, was what about
the millennium? Where was the barrage of futuristic dressing that
had been anticipated?
</P>
<P>
   Fashion designer Rudi Gernreich, the man who gave the world
topless swimsuits for women, once proclaimed that the Space Age
ended when man landed on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was correct, for there were scant signs of Space Age
dressing on the runways, really only Helmut Lang's casualized
spacesuits in soft, comfy fabrics with flattering padded collars,
all shown in New York.
</P>
<P>
   What Paris proved, however, is that futuristic fashions do
exist, and in the French fashion capital, Alexander McQueen was the
designer most attuned to 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In a show with music that was a homage to Stanley Kubrick's
``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' the runway and stage were paved and
backed with mirror-finished materials. The fashions were even
better.
</P>
<P>
   McQueen is a mean tailor, shaping shoulders and waists to his
will, and for once he's got the shoulders right, setting their
softness or sharpness off with pyramidal wigs of a type worn by
ancient Egyptian royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Suits had wide, white bindings, perhaps a little too much of a
takeoff on Andre Courreges' old designs, but McQueen's dresses and
catsuits with reflective prints _ a cross between hieroglyphics and
computer circuit boards _ were dazzling, a tour de force of design.
</P>
<P>
   More important, these were clothes not beyond the realm of what
real women might wear.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps McQueen's hooded jackets festooned with lighted
circuit-board patterns weren't exactly wearable, but at least
McQueen is not asleep at the wheel. He, for one, realizes that if
the first Space Age is dead, the second, this time guided by
computer, is alive and on target.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, for the first time, clothing beyond contemporary
casual _ sleeveless tops, severe skirts and stretch khaki pants _
begins to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   One of the labels leading the way is, in reality, playing an
encore. Paco Rabanne, the man who made a name for himself decades
ago with dresses and tunics of linked-together metal discs, is at
the head of the house's new design team.
</P>
<P>
   This time around it bridges the gap between casual and
futuristic. Tunics have triangles of vinyl bradded onto wool. A
jumpsuit is made of gold metal mesh, while gold is also used as
belts or accents on other clothing. And instead of a total
made-in-metal show, the Rabanne fashions are wisely into leather
and hides, with circles cut out of the materials, then metal-linked
back into place.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Issey Miyake's designs of permanently wrinkled and
pleated fabrics qualify as millennium-minded. Not only do they go
anywhere, arriving in the same shape in which they departed, but
they also can often be cut to desired lengths and shapes by the
clients.
</P>
<P>
   And Miyake's designs are colorful. For a while, fashion
observers were fearful that this century would end with women in a
dourful shrouds accessorized with Earth shoes and messenger bags.
But now it appears colorful. Miyake's creations almost took second
place to their vibrant colors.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Lacroix, never a shy violet in the color department,
stuck to his palette of hot pinks, purples, red, orange and lime,
even adding neon brights. And as if color were not enough, he sewed
on huge paillettes and crystals as large as thumbnails, and then
pasted on flat bows wherever the mood struck.
</P>
<P>
   Color and shine together was a recurring theme, whether the
colorful fabrics were satin or charmeuse or they were encrusted
with sequins or crystals. For Loewe, Narciso Rodriguez meticulously
covered shell tops and dresses with garnets, peridots and rose
quartz, then teamed a garnet shell with a bright red, patent
leather skirt.
</P>
<P>
   At Cerruti, the line's new Greek designer, Peter Speliopoulos,
sent out futuristic patchworks that were shiny squares and other
shapes sewn onto dresses and skirts in geometric or haphazard
patterns.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature vs. NASA'' is how Speliopoulos described his designs,
although most had more in common with the patterns of modern art.
</P>
<P>
   Costume National sent black down its runway, but black with the
difference of shine. Caught in the headlights, these threads,
finishes and decorations would glow like fish scales.
</P>
<P>
   Silver and aluminum finishes on fabrics and accessories were
another way designers subtly moved fashion forward. Karl
Lagerfeld's designs for Chanel were the best of these, with silver
leather skirts, dresses and pants, softened with recognizable
Chanel woolen jackets, then toughened with huge link belts.
</P>
<P>
   Even the U.S. designers now working for big Paris labels found a
way to fold their comfort clothes _ aka American sportswear _ into
the trend to shine. Michael Kors topped a black sweater and camel
pants with deep red shiny coat with fur hood for Celine. Marc
Jacobs put together all that bright plasticized luggage for Louis
Vuitton.
</P>
<P>
   Although not the pervasive theme it was in New York, sportswear
was indeed a major trend in Paris. Even John Galliano tipped his
hat to sweaters and knits _ and it was a big howdy.
</P>
<P>
   For Christian Dior, there were way-oversize Aran Isle, or
fisherman knit, sweaters. Colors ranged from red, lime, yellow and
robin's egg blue to ivory and black and white, the latter mostly
with African-inspired patterns.
</P>
<P>
   For his signature collection, Galliano showed more oversize
black and white coats and capes, but he chose more form-fitting
knits, too. His saucy suits in fuchsias and caution yellow were
showed to best advantage played against his theme of a construction
zone.
</P>
<P>
   The prolific use of fur, leather, suede and cowhide, all highly
resilient materials, continued in the Paris shows, with next fall
and winter shaping up to be a season when animals should run for
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Fur was used, as in Milan and New York, as a fabric, with fur
shells, fur skirts, fur dresses, coats and handbags. Fur trims
remain popular, but usually worked in new ways, not just the same
old fur collar. Think fur hoods, fur muffs, tiny fur edging or wide
bands of fur at hemlines.
</P>
<P>
   Hippie looks from the '70s returned to Paris runways, with
Emanuel Ungaro showing the master's touch. Ruffles, prints, peasant
blouses and long skirts were not hippie garments per se, but worn
together and accessorized with artsy-craftsy feather necklaces and
high boots, they longed for guitar music and free love.
</P>
<P>
   Even Valentino, a designer whose swirling and diaphanous evening
creations are usually sought after by charity ball chairwomen,
loosened up for fall. Metallic lace and charmeuse tap pants with
the Valentino label are meant to be worn with a loose cashmere
sweater and tights. Or a crystal-pleated satin skirt might be
topped with a tie-on scarf at the bodice.
</P>
<P>
   This is sportswear but certainly of a different ilk, a new
height of luxuriousness more than seen on other runways.
</P>
<P>
   This was a season of change in Paris, with Israeli-born designer
Alber Elbaz moving to take over Yves Saint Laurent's Rive Gauche
line and Dutchman Ronald van der Kemp filling Elbaz' shoes at Guy
Laroche. Neither designer turned in a stellar performance, although
both showed promise.
</P>
<P>
   Elbaz took too many cues from YSL's former designs. The best of
what he showed, however, were Asian-inspired ensembles on which
thin cord belts defined the waists.
</P>
<P>
   While there are no photos of Jean-Paul Gaultier's collection _
photographers boycotted the show due to dangerous working
conditions _ he was one designer who had the right idea on how to
work today's sportswear into a millennium theme.
</P>
<P>
   Starting an onstage clock at the year 0, he sent out African,
Asian and Caucasian couples, then mixed things up with multiracial,
multiethnic and same-sex couples. The years _ and fashions _ crept
towards 2000, ending with a gray-haired couple in quilted silver.
</P>
<P>
   Gaultier's biggest theme was a duvet coat for two, more like
wearing your bedspread than an overcoat. Talk about comfort
clothes! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
