<HEADLINE>
A DOWNSIZED NEO-PIMPERNEL  
 AND THEN THERE WAS DARKNESS  
 INSPIRATION IN MEMORIES  
 ETC. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sudden downsizing of an oft-reworked show, 20
cast members of ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' were told this week that
their services would no longer be needed in yet another version of
the show, which is to tour this summer and open at the Neil Simon
Theater in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The musical, which underwent a major overhaul last fall, is to
close its run at the Minskoff Theater on May 30, rehearse a
slimmed-down version, tour and reopen in September. The Minskoff is
booked for the musical ``Saturday Night Fever,'' which is to open
in October.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, actors were told that the new version will have a
cast of 29 as against the current 41. In addition, eight other
roles will be recast.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hawkins, executive producer, said the reason for slimming
down the production was that the Neil Simon, which seats 1,366, is
significantly smaller than the Minskoff, with 1,621.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the theater is smaller, the production will be
rescaled in order to make it the right show for that space,''
Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Eisenberg, executive director of Actors' Equity, said the
move had been approved two weeks ago by the union's production
committee. But it angered cast members, who said Equity had not
informed them that the changes were coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``This came totally out of the blue,'' said one member, who
spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``Equity didn't talk to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cast members were also upset that the union had made an
exception to a long-standing contractual rule. Under the standard
Equity production contract, producers cannot reduce the size of a
cast without first closing a production for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, Eisenberg said the union would allow
``Pimpernel'' to close on May 30 and begin rehearsals for the
slimmed-down version in early June without compensation for the 20
actors who have been released. The exception was made in this case,
Eisenberg said, because ``Pimpernel'' officials offered a higher
rate of pay for the touring company and because the show's
producers were also considering closing in mid-April, rather than
May 30, to avoid a conflict with the six-week rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt it was better to provide six weeks of employment to
the current actors under the production contract to the end of
May,'' he said, ``and then send the tour out under the production
contract rather than under a stock agreement,'' which pays less.
</P>
<P>
   The change is just the latest for the musical. Last fall, after
Cablevision purchased the show from its original producers,
``Pimpernel'' was rewritten and rerehearsed. Two of the three leads
were changed. The new version of the musical opened on Nov. 4;
critics generally approved. Sales have also improved, though the
show is still millions from recouping the original investment.
</P>
<P>
   For the actors whose jobs were eliminated, the move smacked of
corporate thinking. ``We're dealing with people whose absolute
bottom line is profit,'' one cast member said. ``These aren't
people who love theater. These are corporate people.''
</P>
<P>
   Heaven Didn't Help
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, there was light. In the end, there just
weren't enough people to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, producers of ``The Most Fabulous Story Ever
Told'' told their cast that the show would be posting a closing
date of May 2. The Bible-based comedy, by Paul Rudnick, received
good reviews in December when it opened at the nonprofit New York
Theater Workshop; it subsequently moved to a commercial run at the
Minetta Lane Theater.
</P>
<P>
   But ticket sales in the last month have slumped. Recent weeks
have seen losses of $10,000 to $15,000, said Tom Viertel, one of
the show's producers. ``I just don't think we've found the audience
for it,'' he said. ``We've done a ton of promotional stuff and some
other forms of advertising, but we've really hit a wall.'' He said
costs from extensive recasting had also taken their toll. One
possible candidate for the theater's next tenant is ``Betty's
Summer Vacation,'' Christopher Durang's searing satire on modern
media, which closes its run at Playwright's Horizon on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   A Complete Circle
</P>
<P>
   In a strange way, Jim Norton's role in ``The Weir'' has been a
sort of homecoming. The 60-year-old actor, who plays the feisty old
rustic, Jack, left his native Ireland in 1969 to pursue acting in
London.
</P>
<P>
   There, Norton found success in a wide variety of plays,
including several productions at the Royal Court and on the West
End. But he avoided certain roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was determined not to be seen as an `Irish' actor,''
he said, in an accent that sounds more English than Gaelic. ``I
kind of deliberately chose not to play Irish parts.''
</P>
<P>
   His stay in London lasted 20 years. In the late 1980s, suffering
from what he said was a midlife crisis, Norton moved to Los Angeles
and made a healthy living on roles in television and film. Then,
about three years ago, he took roles in two plays in Dublin, where
he had been born and bred but had not lived full-time in almost 30
years. While there, Norton was cast in ``The Weir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the part and took a walk,'' he said. ``When I got back,
I called my agent and said, `If I don't do the part, I'll die.'''
</P>
<P>
   Norton said he had found inspiration for the role in memories of
his Irish uncles and friends. In fact, a photograph hanging on the
wall of the set is of his grandparents and his uncle. ``Whenever I
get nervous, I look over at that picture,'' Norton said. ``Compared
to those people, I have it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect some butterflies on Monday at about 3 p.m. That's when
this season's Pulitzer Prize for drama will be announced. Both
``Wit,'' playing Off Broadway, and ``Side Man,'' on Broadway, have
been mentioned as possible contenders. Of the two, ``Side Man'' is
more in need of any potential boost in revenue. Box office sales
dropped to $84,684 last week, the lowest of any Broadway show.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Public Theater will offer a free public reading of new
plays by Tony Kushner, Suzan Lori-Parks and David Greenspan as part
of its ``New Work Now'' festival beginning on April 19.
Information: (212) 260-2400.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
