<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0865 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     04-08 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY'S EMPLOYEES REFLECT CONCERNS, PHILOSOPHIES OF PERSON
LEADING THEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Great service comes in many forms.
</P>
<P>
   It may be the way a customer's purchases were replaced free
after she left her bag in the parking lot and drove away, later
returning to find the bag gone.
</P>
<P>
   Or in the way an airline uses china plates and cloth napkins,
offers free wine or champagne and bakes cookies right on board the
plane _ and not just for first class.
</P>
<P>
   Or the way an office furniture sales representative sits down
with a customer, discusses her needs, fits her budget, lets her
choose colors and fabrics, immediately sends the order to the
factory via computer and has 200 furniture systems ready within two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Great service is not random or unusual, says Leonard L. Berry,
Texas A&AMP;M University marketing professor and chairman of retailing
studies. Great service is part of the soul of a company, from its
top officers to its dishwashers. It's consistent and impresses
customers every day.
</P>
<P>
   After studying 14 successful service companies, Berry discovered
that the basic elements, or drivers, of great service can be found
in virtually any industry. The companies he reviewed were as
diverse as a mattress distributor, a minor-league baseball club and
an airline. But their common elements can be imitated by any
company.
</P>
<P>
   That common ground is the basis of Berry's latest book,
``Discovering the Soul of Service: The Nine Drivers of Sustainable
Business Success'' (Free Press, 269 pages, $26.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Services are performances,'' he writes, ``and the challenge of
sustaining the performers' energy, commitment, skills, and
knowledge day after day, week after week, month after month, year
after year _ especially as the organization grows and becomes more
complex _ is daunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry identifies nine drivers of sustainable success in service
business from his extensive research into such companies as Charles
Schwab, Midwest Express Airlines and The Container Store. Eight
drivers connect to a central driver of excellence, which he calls
``values-driven leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Values-driven leaders infuse their values into the fabric of
the organization,'' Berry writes. ``They lead not with commands,
not with a thick rule book, but with a set of core values _ what
the firm represents and aspires to be. The more these values tap
into employees' own core values, the more they guide individual
decision-making and inspire personal achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Other drivers Berry identified include terms often not heard in
the typical business lexicon. Ideas such as generosity, trust-based
relationships and investment in employee success are as important
as the more businesslike ideas of strategic focus, brand
cultivation and excellence, Berry theorizes.
</P>
<P>
   Treating employees in a humane way at all levels is vital to the
success of the service business, Berry says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In services performed directly for customers, such as in
retailing, education, health care, and transportation, the service
is inseparable from the people performing it,'' he writes. ``An
inept salesperson is an inept store; a nurse's personality may send
patients in search of a new doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mutual respect, honesty'' and ``integrity'' are some of the
words Berry uses to describe the relationship between the company
leaders he studied and their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Such values will be seen repeatedly in the split-second
decisions that employees make every day.
</P>
<P>
   These companies ``use the power of values-driven leadership to
sustain their success,'' Berry writes. ``The leaders of these
companies recognize that every employee makes countless decisions
each day that directly or indirectly affect customers and
strengthen or weaken the company's reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry makes a strong case for this theory, which is well
supported with other schools of thought from the likes of Peter
Drucker and Noel Tichy. Berry has done his homework and research
well, and his book provides a clear picture of how to run a
successful service company.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance Lessons: Six Steps to Great Partnerships in Business
Life''
</P>
<P>
   By Chip R. Bell and Heather Shea
</P>
<P>
   Berrett Koehler, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   With blessings and a foreword by business guru Tom Peters,
Dallas consultants Chip Bell and Heather Shea discuss the complex
and in-depth world of partnerships. Using dance as a metaphor, the
authors have created six ``steps'' identified during their
interviews with successful partners. The steps range from picking a
partner to getting out before things really get bad.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Profit Patterns: 30 Ways to Anticipate and Profit From
Strategic Forces Reshaping Your Business''
</P>
<P>
   By Adrian Slywotzky, David Morrison, Ted Moser, Kevin Mundt and
James Quella
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $24.50
</P>
<P>
   The authors, all consultants with Mercer Management, have
written a 432-page book about strategy. Their premise is that
everything successful has a pattern, and that the ability to see
those patterns and react to them is something they call ``Strategic
Anticipation.'' The authors outline 30 patterns that are changing
the landscape of every industry. They also show readers how best to
capitalize on those patterns.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Be Heard Now! Tap Into Your Inner Speaker and Communicate with
Ease''
</P>
<P>
   By Lee Clickstein
</P>
<P>
   Broadway Books, $20
</P>
<P>
   Think about the best speakers you've heard lately. Did they
perform as if in a play, or did they talk to you as if you were
sitting next to them at a table? Speaking consultant Lee Clickstein
is betting the latter. His book evolves around the idea of relating
one-on-one to your audience, which coincidentally takes the fear
out of speaking as well. Although this work is geared toward the
public speaker, even shy people can benefit from Clickstein's
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
