<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0871 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OFFICEPOLITICS-BOOK-T     04-08 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICEPOLITICS-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO SWIM WITH THE OFFICE SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As someone who has always been a chronic sufferer of
foot-in-mouth disease, I can't say how much I wish Ronna
Lichtenberg's new book had come across my desk sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work Would Be Great If It Weren't for All the People''
($12.95, Hyperion) is subtitled ``Making Office Politics Work for
You.'' And while Lichtenberg comes from the kind of cubicled
corporate world that Dilbert calls home _ she's a former senior
vice president at Prudential Securities and now runs a marketing
and strategy consulting firm _ she manages to cram in information
relevant to almost any office environment.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a selection of some of the more valuable tidbits you
should remember before wading into the shark pool:
</P>
<P>
   _In a new job, beware the first person who wants to be your
friend. The odds are there's a good reason for this, and that it's
generally not good for you.
</P>
<P>
   _Friends are what you have outside the office.
</P>
<P>
   _Snitching is like planning the perfect murder: It's hard to
pull off.
</P>
<P>
   _Even if you're doing everything else right, if you're doing
time wrong (i.e., slacking off), you're toast.
</P>
<P>
   _Always treat people above you as though they were your main
clients.
</P>
<P>
   _If you don't have anything nice to say, don't write it down in
a memo.
</P>
<P>
   _Control your lying, and lie sensibly. It's better to lie about
your feelings than about reality.
</P>
<P>
   _Everyone speaks from his or her own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   _Do as much as you can for the right people before being asked.
</P>
<P>
   _Just because Spouse pops up the hood does not mean that Spouse
can fix the engine (i.e., don't always take your spouse's advice on
your work problems).
</P>
<P>
   _If your boss isn't talking to you about your future, then you
probably don't have one.
</P>
<P>
   _Even when you're sure someone hates you, the odds are good
you're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   _If you always eat with people junior to you, it communicates a
message, as does eating only with people senior to you.
</P>
<P>
   _Most people are defeated not by other people but by their
reactions to other people.
</P>
<P>
   Paranoid yet? Good. Now I've gotta go pick up my boss's
dry-cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
