<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BERKELEY SQUARE': ANOTHER JOURNEY UP AND DOWNSTAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a world so bizarre that nannies are hired without even
meeting the children, much less getting their approval, a place so
exotic that a lady can cover her infidelity by pretending she is
going to the theater to see Sarah Bernhardt.
</P>
<P>
   This world of pure escapism is delivered in the delightful,
frothy Edwardian soap opera ``Berkeley Square,'' a breezily
successful ``Upstairs, Downstairs'' clone. The first two hours of
the BBC series will be shown this Saturday on Channel 13, with
hourlong episodes running for the next eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With its spunky characters drawn from the realms of lords and
ladies, housemaids and footmen, the series taps into the essential
quality that made ``Upstairs Downstairs'' so appealing; this is a
world of surface order and underlying chaos, which we can envy and
feel superior to at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening episode, set in London in 1902, three young women
are hired to work in Berkeley Square households. Each story is set
up separately, with an efficient though slightly clumsy structure.
Matty Wickham, a levelheaded, experienced nanny, arrives to care
for the St. John children, whose pretty blond mother goes riding in
the park with men not her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the country, Hannah Randall has been dismissed as
a maid to Lady Harmonsworth and banished from the estate because
she bore a child by Lady Harmonsworths' son. (She loves him, of
course; she is a heroine, not a trollop.) Alone in London with her
infant, Hannah is befriended by Mrs. Bronowski, a sympathetic and
eminently commonsensical Polish immigrant who cares for the baby
while Hannah goes to work as a nursemaid for poor, neglected little
Albert Hutchinson. ``Be the very best of boys for Mama,'' Mrs.
Hutchinson will tell the child in a future episode, giving him a
peck on the forehead as she and her husband blithely take off for a
year's posting in India.
</P>
<P>
   And Lydia Weston is a spirited, good-hearted farm girl taken
into the household of the Lamson-Scribeners, whose very name
suggests the overload of breeding and social arcana that will
eventually topple. Hired to help the aging Nanny Collins, who has
been with the family for 50 years, Lydia is so green that she
mistakes the butler for the master of the household, Lord George.
Fortunately, she is employed by one of the series' most winning
characters, the American-born Lady Connie, who brings an air of
egalitarianism to Berkeley Square with her belief that the lower
classes deserve opportunities, too. Lady Connie's philosophy is: If
you don't teach them, how are they to know? Turning up next week is
Hugh Scammon, Lord George's grown son from his first marriage, who
does not disappoint: He is a handsome rogue.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Saturday's second episode, the three nannies have
met in the park and become friends, the series' structure has
become smooth and its intrigues have taken off. Will the St. Johns'
vinegar-faced housekeeper, Mrs. McClusky, succeed in bringing her
disreputable son into the household as a footman? Will the
Hutchinsons discover that Hannah has forged her letter of reference
from Lady Harmonsworth? More troubling still: how do the women
balance those architecturally challenging hats?
</P>
<P>
   In large and small roles, the cast is vibrant, with many faces
(if not names) familiar from years' worth of Masterpiece Theaters.
Rosemary Leach exudes comfort as Nanny Collins, and Judy Parfitt
(who enters next week) is elegantly vicious as Hannah's nemesis,
Lady Harmonsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Reassuring though it is to vanish into this world of surface
calm, a strong undercurrent works subtly to affirm contemporary
assumptions about family. These Edwardian aristocrats are
emotionally icy, a breeding ground of family dysfunction; they are
not to be envied despite their wealth. Only those born outside the
English upper classes escape such coldbloodedness. Hannah is
devoted to her son. And Lady Connie, that bold American, actually
breast feeds her own child.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Connie gets to have the best of both worlds, and ``Berkeley
Square'' puts the American viewer in much the same soothing if
slightly condescending position. We can enjoy this indulgent
fantasy while congratulating ourselves on how far we've come. It's
a nonguilty pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BERKELEY SQUARE'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Saturday at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Written by Deborah Cook, Amanda Coe, Simon Ashdown and Lilie
Ferrari; producer, Alison Davis; Leslie Manning, Richard Signy,
Martin Hutchings and Richard Holthouse, directors. A 1998 BBC
production acquired by American Public Television for syndication
to PBS television stations nationwide. A local presentation of
Thirteen/WNET, New York.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Victoria Smurfit (Hannah Randall), Tabitha Wady (Lydia
Weston), Clara Wilkie (Matty Wickham), Rosemary Leach (Nanny
Collins), Ruth Sheen (Mrs. Simmons), Jason O'Mara (Ned Jones),
Etela Pardo (Mrs. Bronowski), Kate Williams (Mrs. McClusky),
Hermione Norris (Victoria St. John), Sean Murray (Arnold St. John),
William Scott-Masson (Captain Mason) and Rupert Frazer (George
Lamson-Scribener).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
