<HEADER>
A0941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-08 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GO': PULP FRICTION, WITH DRUGS, ENERGY AND ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Borrowing truckloads of inspiration from ``Pulp Fiction,'' Doug
Liman's ``Go'' has three interrelated sections. It begins and ends
at the same time and place, turns a banal spot into its central
setting (supermarket instead of coffee shop), flirts with drugs and
violence and lets its characters riff amusingly on assorted trivia,
in the manner of ``le Big Mac.'' But derivative as it is, ``Go''
has a powerful personality of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Before the opening Columbia Pictures icon has even finished
brandishing her torch, the film erupts into a hyperkinetic rave
scene and it keeps on flashing that kind of energy throughout. If
Liman breaks no ground here, he does not simply appropriate the
familiar. More often than not, he takes it by storm.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Go'' has no character as ingratiating as the one played
by Jon Favreau in the director's ``Swingers,'' its ensemble cast is
young, quick-witted and loaded with attitude. Just the way Ronna,
the cashier played with improbable grace by Sarah Polley, sullenly
asks, ``Paper or plastic?'' on the supermarket checkout line is
enough to signal a film in which nobody is dull. Sure enough, even
when the screenplay by John August embroils Ronna in a botched drug
deal, she remains a sufficiently sharp-eyed Alice to make her trip
through a grunge Wonderland worth following. And Liman, who shot
the film as well as directed it, gives all the characters' exploits
their distinctive visceral kick.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those exploits are tired. (This is yet another movie in
which a group of guys sprint off to Las Vegas and get into a mess
involving strippers and gunplay, culminating in a chase dramatized
by the town's neon lights.) And some turn nasty, but ``Go'' mostly
sustains a nicely sardonic sense of adventure. It all begins when
Ronna is asked by an English co-worker, Simon (Desmond Askew,
making a memorably funny American debut) to take his place in a
drug buy while he goes out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ronna, who badly needs rent money, decides to deal some
Ecstasy on her own. Her ingenuously pretty friend Claire (Katie
Holmes of ``Dawson'Creek''), decries this as ``an evolutionary
leap,'' adding, ``You're moving up the drug food chain without
permission!'' The next thing she knows, Claire is being parked as
collateral in the lair of a colorfully menacing dealer named Todd
(played with offbeat flair by Timothy Olyphant while Ronna gets
into additional trouble of her own.
</P>
<P>
   In a film whose characters often size up one another with
all-too-justifiable suspicion, Ronna escapes a much too eager trio
of customers (Scott Wolf, Jay Mohr and William Fichtner, the film's
most enjoyable weirdo) before getting revenge of sorts by dealing
baby aspirin at a rave. ``Go'' leaves her there and spirals back to
the supermarket, where it picks up the thread of Simon's story: the
Vegas spree, in which the smoothly appealing Taye Diggs plays a
major role. Then it's another trip to the store to follow a third
subplot, the one that introduced Ronna to her rogue customers in
the first place. Along the way, ``Go'' is a jaundiced comedy of
manners that toys with who may or may not be gay, and has a white
character tell a black one that ``color's just a state of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Artfully executed, druggy flights of fancy include a
hallucinatory macarena in a supermarket, a mind-reading black cat
and a smart visual approximation of how it feels to be on the verge
of throwing up. Here and elsewhere, Liman manipulates speed, light,
editing and point of view vigorously and keeps the radio humming.
He creates a film that lives up to the momentum of its title and
doesn't really need much more.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Go'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It includes profanity, topless dancers and
frequent references to drug use.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   GO Directed by Doug Liman; written by John August; director of
photography, Liman; edited by Stephen Mirrione; music by BT;
production designer, Tom Wilkins; produced by Paul Rosenberg,
Mickey Liddell and Matt Freeman; released by Columbia Pictures.
Running time: 100 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Desmond Askew (Simon Baines), Taye Diggs (Marcus), William
Fichtner (Burke), J.E. Freeman (Victor Sr.), Katie Holmes (Claire
Montgomery), Jane Krakowski (Irene), Breckin Meyer (Tiny), Jay Mohr
(Zack), Timothy Olyphant (Todd Gaines), Sarah Polley (Ronna Martin)
and Scott Wolf (Adam).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
