<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-INTERNET-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET BECOMES A PROPAGANDA TOOL IN KOSOVO CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11)   (EDs: With KOSOVO-INTERNET-SITES)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just as television brought the startling realities
of warfare into living rooms during the Vietnam conflict, the
Internet is providing an intimate view of the struggle over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Through chat rooms, electronic mail and Web sites brimming with
colorful photos and propaganda, people with Internet access can
eavesdrop on or offer an opinion about a struggle in a distant
corner of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The availability of information is like nothing the world has
ever seen,'' James Wesley, a specialist on information and war at
Georgetown University in Washington, said in referring to the
Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In the eight years since the Gulf War with Iraq, when the
Internet was a fledgling public medium, home computer use has
skyrocketed along with access to cyberspace. Today an estimated 150
million people, 60 million in the United States, have access to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A few strokes on the keyboard can link Belgrade to Boston in the
time it takes to make a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the propaganda war that intensified with the
outbreak of NATO air raids on Yugoslavia quickly moved to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Groups such as the Kosovo Liberation Army, the rebels fighting
the Serb-dominated government of Yugoslavia, and the Serb
government, which has ruthlessly targeted the ethnic Albanian
population of Kosovo, have home pages on the Internet. Each posts
its views on the war.
</P>
<P>
   At the official Yugoslav Foreign Ministry Web site, the blue,
white and red flag of Yugoslavia ripples above colorful pictures
and icons. A quick click on the highlighted ``NATO Aggression''
icon brings up a list of government press releases on the conflict,
maps and pictures showing the damage done by the NATO bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a barbaric attack of NATO air force planes against the town
of Vranje on Monday, two people were killed, 23 injured,'' reads an
April 7 Yugoslav press release on the bombing of a village about 30
miles from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The site also provides telephone numbers and e-mail addresses of
Yugoslav press officials.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, the official site for the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization allows computer users to choose from an array
of options, including press releases, texts of speeches,
photographs and videos of NATO air attacks against Serb positions.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want immediate updates on the action, NATO also
can send press releases via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In a counterattack against NATO, hackers in Belgrade disabled
the NATO Web site for several hours on March 28, bombarding the
site with e-mail and computer queries that made accessing the site
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the 28th of March, the service from our Internet home
page has been erratic, to say the least,'' NATO spokesman Jamie P.
Shea said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet provides more than information from government
Web sites. Because of the availability of e-mail, large numbers of
people from all sides of the conflict can and do communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That a regular person in Seattle can write on a daily basis
with someone in Belgrade is unlike anything in the history of
warfare,'' Wesley said.
</P>
<P>
   At eGroups, a global e-mail clearinghouse, messages from both
Serbs and Albanians are posted for computer users around the world
to read and answer.
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail posted on April 7 from Emilija Nackov, who identified
herself as a doctor living in Belgrade, states: ``NATO bombs are
killing innocent people all over Yugoslavia. When will they stop?
Do they want to kill us all?''
</P>
<P>
   Another e-mail from the Kosovo capital of Pristina, posted on
March 28 by a person under the signature V., states: ``The army
ordered hundreds of Albanian families in my neighborhood to leave
their houses yesterday so the army can use them to hide from
attacks. Any store owned by an Albanian was destroyed. I don't know
where the families are, but they are not here anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
