<P>
   OIL-PRICE TROUBLES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The bluebonnets are in bloom, baseball
season is back, and energy prices have moved up about 40 percent
since midwinter. But Texas oil producers, who saw daily posted
prices drop below $8 per barrel during a grim winter, are still
seeing the glass as half-empty. ``We may be seeing some light at
the end of the tunnel,'' said John Pinkerton, chief executive of
Range Resources of Fort Worth. ``But we're still in the tunnel.''
By DAN PILLER. Story has moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Great service is not random or unusual, says Leonard
L. Berry, Texas A&AMP;M University marketing professor and chairman of
retailing studies. Great service, rather, is part of the very soul
of a company, from its top officers to its dishwashers. It's
consistent and impresses customers every day. By TERESA MCUSIC.
Story has moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
