<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOORE-515&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL MOORE BACK TO ROUSE RABBLE ON BRAVO 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Break out the Old Milwaukee and pretzels. Michael Moore is back
on TV, pestering everyone he doesn't like.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't like Republicans. He doesn't like the rich and
powerful. And he doesn't like bigots.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in his rabble-rousing heart, though, Moore surely
loves them all. They made him famous for ``Roger &AMP; Me'' and for
``TV Nation.'' They may even have made him rich and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after ``TV Nation'' petered out at NBC and Fox, Moore
has revived his TV fortunes on the Bravo cable network, and in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Awful Truth,'' his new series, premieres Sunday on Bravo.
Though its look is entirely American, the half-hour show is
co-produced by the BBC, which also airs it. Anyone familiar with
Moore, or his work, knows that he can be mean-spirited, demagogic
and juvenile in his ambush attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who likes his stuff also knows that most of his
targets could stand to lose a little stuffing from their shirts.
They know too that Moore's best material is screamingly funny. And
they're probably tickled to see a TV show with a point of view,
along with sharp teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Awful Truth'' begins with easy targets on Sunday, as Moore
takes on Washington, Ken Starr and Bill Clinton's Republican
tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by a troupe of actors in Puritan garb, Moore leads a
Salem-style witch hunt on the streets of Washington and halls of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tinge of rueful satisfaction _ I speak for myself, of
course _ in seeing him clap a microphone in front of Representative
Asa Hutchinson, one of the Republican impeachment managers, and ask
him, ``Have you sinned? Are you a fornicator, congressman?''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's second segment is more macabre. Moore goes to bat for
Christopher Donahue, a 34-year-old diabetic whose health
maintenance organization has refused to pay for a pancreas
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Without the transplant, Donahue will die. So Moore and Donahue
go to the HMO's headquarters in Louisville, Ky., for a run-in with
a PR guy who tries to coax them out of the building. Eventually,
``The Awful Truth'' stages a mock funeral on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   I am duty bound to report that the next week, Moore outfits a
hot pink Winnebago with gays and lesbians for a ``Sodomobile''
excursion to states with anti-sodomy laws.
</P>
<P>
   When the ``Sodomobile'' pulls within range of the Rev. Fred
Phelps, in Kansas, grand fun ensues. Phelps is the hate-monger who
came to San Francisco five years ago to picket the funeral of gay
journalist Randy Shilts, who died of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   You get the idea. If you ever laughed at the old notion of
tossing snowballs at the top hats of rich men, ``The Awful Truth''
is for you. If you thought the snowball tossers should be rounded
up and sent to the slammer, you might want to browse some other
channel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ Also Sunday, the Fox animated comedy ``Family Guy'' makes its
premiere, following its ``sneak preview'' after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's episode is as briskly paced and even funnier than the
January pilot, a sign that ``Family Guy'' is here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   The main story line involves Dad, Peter Griffin (the voice of
series creator Seth MacFarlane), who crashes his car into a
satellite dish and deprives an entire city of television.
</P>
<P>
   But over on the side, there's always baby Stewie. Stewie (also
MacFarlane's voice) is the dangerously precocious toddler, who
appears to have gotten over his desire to kill his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Now the enemy is broccoli, and Fox invites you to see Stewie
fuming at an inert broccoli crown and hissing, ``Stop mocking me!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
