<P>
   BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS-KERR _ SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ He had spent the entire
game on the bench, and now Steve Kerr was summoned by his coach to
produce some magic during the final seconds, maybe pull a
three-point shot out of his warmup jacket sleave. The San Antonio
Spurs needed one late in a recent game against Toronto. Kerr never
did get the chance to shoot. But Kerr believes that had the flow of
the game enabled him to pop open for a split second with the ball
in his hands, he could have nailed the shot, even having come into
the game cold. ``That's going to be my role on this team _ to go in
there every once in a while and hit one shot,'' Kerr said. Those
are encouraging words for San Antonio coach and general manager
Gregg Popovich, who signed the 6-foot-3-inch, 180-pound Kerr in
January with hopes that he could make the critical jump shots that
other Spurs missed last season. Jaren Jackson, signed by the Spurs
for his defense last season, missed important perimeter shots at
the end of playoff losses to Phoenix and Utah. (Rosner, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
