<HEADER>
A0970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WATER-OZONE-NYTR &LR;      04-08 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-OZONE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 FISH COMPANY TO TRY OZONE AS BACTERIA-KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRIAN FEAGANS   
 Wilmington (N.C.) Morning Star   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Sure, ozone can shield Earth from the sun's
harmful rays.
</P>
<P>
   But can it protect a tuna fillet?
</P>
<P>
   That's what scientists starting a study later this month at a
Wilmington seafood company want to know.
</P>
<P>
   With a $31,300 grant from N.C. Sea Grant, researchers from N.C.
State University and the National Food Processors Association are
going to investigate whether ozone would make a good sterilizing
agent for fish shipped on ice to grocery stores and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The team will set up a portable ozone generator that will pump
ozone into water at Hanover Packing Inc. During the experiment,
fish fillets will be rinsed with the treated water before they are
inserted into air-tight packages.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at N.C. State's Seafood Laboratory in Morehead City
will then test the fish for taste, color and how long it takes to
spoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flattering that they're going to use our facility,'' said
Hanover Packing owner Peter Mairs. ``If they endorse this
procedure, perhaps more processors like myself will really get some
real benefits from the process.''
</P>
<P>
   A layer of naturally occurring ozone in Earth's atmosphere
deflects much of the sun's ultraviolet rays. Ozone is also created
as a byproduct of internal combustion engines and contributes to
the smog that chokes residents of urban centers like Mexico City
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Synthetically produced ozone has also shown potential for
cutting bacteria on raw fillets and extending the shelf life of
seafood, said Barry Nash, a seafood technology and marketing
specialist with N.C. Sea Grant.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Grant-funded study, which will be completed by March
2000, should document how real those effects are and whether the
ozone treatment detracts from the food's taste, odor or color, Nash
said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have chosen to test tuna, which is representative of
red fish, and bluefish, which should indicate how most oily fish
will react to ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Synthetic ozone's bacteria-killing properties have led some
countries in Europe to use it for cleaning drinking water. And
experiments on raw poultry have shown it can extend the shelf life
of chicken by up to two days, Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   Recognized as a safe sterilizing agent by the U.S. Food &AMP; Drug
Administration in 1997, ozone isn't without its possible drawbacks,
however.
</P>
<P>
   While decreasing the number of some spoiling agents, ozone could
allow other disease-causing bacteria to flourish, Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do what we can in this state to improve the safety
factor for seafood in the long term,'' he said. ``We're looking at
all angles.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mairs, it's all about having a product that will stay
fresher longer. Hanover Packing's business depends on keeping that
fresh-off-the-boat taste for customers in the Carolinas and
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Mairs has tried nitrogen treatments, but found that the added
day of shelf life wasn't worth the resulting ``balloon-like''
packages that allowed the fish to slosh around and eat up space
during shipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this will work better,'' he said. ``Everybody's looking
for extended shelf life.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Wilmington, N.C., Morning Star is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1755EDT &QL; 
