<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     04-08 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCAS MAKES DEMANDS  
 COMING SOON FROM OMAHA  
 BORN TO PERFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Md.)  (mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ They're counting the days here.
</P>
<P>
   No film will arrive in movie theaters this summer with the same
dizzying expectations as George Lucas' ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The
Phantom Menace,'' which is to be released by 20th Century Fox on
May 19. The 130-minute, $115 million epic is the first of three
planned ``prequels'' to ``Star Wars,'' and will center on young
Anakin Skywalker's rise to Jedi Knight and his surrender to the
dark side.
</P>
<P>
   The normally reclusive Lucas has gone on a publicity blitz for
the movie. And who can blame him? It will probably open to a record
weekend box office _ estimates run over $100 million for the first
five days _ but there is still uncertainty that it could eventually
surpass the $1.8 billion in worldwide ticket sales taken in by
``Titanic.'' Lucas could earn more than $400 million. He already
owns all merchandising rights for ``Star Wars,'' which has
delivered about $4.5 billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 54-year-old filmmaker and the studio, hoping to
guarantee the widest possible audience, have made some unusual
demands of theater owners. Daily Variety reported that they would
have to pay a penalty, or even have their prints confiscated, if
the strict requirements were not met. Theater exhibitors, eager to
show the film, are not expected to balk, but they are not expected
to like the demands either.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions include these: The film must run in the largest
auditorium in a complex and cannot move to a smaller one without
Fox's permission; minimum runs of the film are eight to 12 weeks;
if an exhibitor commits to playing the film on two or three screens
in a multiplex, the film must stay on those screens for a minimal
run; theaters are not to honor any passes for the first eight
weeks; paid onscreen advertising is prohibited in the first two
weeks; no more than eight minutes of trailers are to run before the
film; theaters can begin showing the film at 12:01 a.m. on May 19,
and advance tickets may not be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Fox declined to comment on the conditions. But an executive
close to the film said the measures were suggestions, not demands.
If there were problems, the executive said, they would be worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   For example, some distributors objected to the ban on advance
ticket sales. The studio and Lucas said that this was sought to
prevent scalping, but that if theater owners had contracts with
companies selling advance tickets, arrangements would be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to work with them, not against them,'' the executive
said.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, Lucas has controlled production and the film's
release. He financed the movie, as he did ``The Empire Strikes
Back'' and ``The Return of the Jedi.'' And he avoided casting the
most expensive Hollywood superstars. Instead, he hired Liam Neeson
as the Jedi master, Qui-Gon Jinn; Ewan McGregor as the young
Obi-Wan Kenobi; Natalie Portman as Queen Amidala and Jake Lloyd as
young Anakin. Except for showing the film to some friends,
including Steven Spielberg and Francis Ford Coppola, the movie is
off-limits to the press and Hollywood executives until just before
its release.
</P>
<P>
   Even top Fox executives haven't seen the film, and probably
won't until just before its release. Asked when studio executives
would see it, one executive laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown Boy
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen has New York. John Waters has Baltimore. And
Alexander Payne has ... Omaha!
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much is shot there at all, and most filmmakers seem to
have grown up in New York or L.A.,'' said Payne, the
director-screenwriter of the new film ``Election,'' which is set in
Omaha, Neb., his hometown, and will open on April 23. His previous
movie, ``Citizen Ruth,'' an acclaimed offbeat comedy that dealt
with abortion, was also set in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omaha is a place I understand,'' said Payne, who now lives in
Los Angeles. ``I walk around and feel these early connections, and
you don't see the Midwest represented accurately in films. Often
the people who make films there don't understand it and you can see
the difference; either it's kind of the noble savage, all those
hard-working, salt-of-the-earth people, or it's, `Look at all this
dysfunction.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Election'' is a comedy-drama about the most popular teacher in
an Omaha high school, played by Matthew Broderick, who puts his
career and reputation on the line for a student election. He is
pitted against an alarmingly ambitious go-getter student, played by
Reese Witherspoon, who views the election as the first step in a
career that winds up _ where else? _ in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, who wrote the script with his writing partner, Jim
Taylor, spent years struggling to make films after graduating from
Stanford University and earning a master's degree in filmmaking at
UCLA. His thesis film, ``The Passion of Martin,'' about an
obsessive love, was screened at more than 20 festivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Election'' is based on a novel of the same name but set in New
Jersey, by Tom Perrotta.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was sent the novel, I didn't read it for a while; I'm
not so interested in high school,'' Payne said. ``But when I read
it, I thought it was funny and sad, kind of like life. There was
this sense of melancholy to it. I knew it would be an easy
transplant to Omaha.''
</P>
<P>
   As Payne began filming, he said, he increasingly identified with
the character played by Broderick, a man muddling through life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's about my age,'' said Payne, who is 38. ``I have friends
who teach in high school. I have friends in other jobs. And there's
a certain sense now of what you've accomplished at this point in
your life and what you haven't accomplished and the frustrations
you feel. This film could have been made 20 years ago, or it could
be made 20 years from now. The themes are kind of timeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he was nervous about the opening of the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but think there are people like me who are hungry
for intelligent films,'' he said. ``I'm not saying I make great
films, but I do know I want to do things that are different from
anything I've ever seen before. And I don't think you've seen
`Election' before.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
