<HEADER>
A0976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE     04-08 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: `Election' before.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeling Blessed
</P>
<P>
   No actor has had quite the life _ and career _ of Charles
Dutton.
</P>
<P>
   A sought-after character actor with a booming voice and
often-gentle presence, the 48-year-old Dutton has worked nonstop in
recent years. He is in two films that are to be released later in
the year. One is ``Detox,'' with Sylvester Stallone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a murder-mystery thriller,'' Dutton said. ``I play Sly's
partner; we're FBI agents.''
</P>
<P>
   The second film is ``Random Hearts,'' in which he plays Harrison
Ford's police partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm everyone's partner,'' Dutton said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Dutton is appearing as Willis in ``Cookie's
Fortune,'' the whimsical comedy-drama directed by Robert Altman.
Altman and the screenwriter Anne Rapp wrote the script with Dutton
in mind for the role of Willis, who is accused of a murder that no
one in town believes he committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was attractive to me was that although this was set in
the South, in the state of Mississippi and all that entails, it was
about a black man totally devoid of anger and rage and
bitterness,'' Dutton said. ``It's one of the first times in film
I've gotten to play a complete human being, with a range of
emotions and nuances, and not just somebody's partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutton has also had a notable Broadway career in the August
Wilson dramas ``Ma Rainey's Black Bottom'' and ``The Piano
Lesson,'' and he has starred in a television series, ``Roc.''
</P>
<P>
   As a black actor, Dutton said, he is no longer bothered by the
notion that his race worked against him in finding jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I felt that five years ago, even two years ago,'' he
said. ``But I don't dwell on it anymore. There's a scarcity of work
in this business for everyone, white actors as well as black. The
few of us who actually work and make a good living at it should
consider ourselves extremely lucky and blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutton never considered himself lucky. He grew up in a Baltimore
housing project, and his childhood was bleak. At 17, he stabbed and
killed someone he said had attacked him and went to prison. He
spent seven and a half years in the Maryland Correctional
Institution for homicide and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, Dutton began reading plays and helped form a drama
group. He also entered a high school equivalency and junior college
program.
</P>
<P>
   After an early release, he studied theater at Towson State
University in Maryland. One of his teachers there suggested he
apply for a scholarship after graduation in 1978 to the Yale School
of Drama. He was accepted, and soon began his successful career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I discovered theater in prison,'' Sutton said, ``I said
to myself, `OK, this is it _ I will pursue this with whatever
talent I've been blessed with.' When I began acting and directing a
ragtag bunch of inmates who'd never done a play, I knew, I just
knew, this was what I was born to do on this planet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
