<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VIDEO-1030(2TAKE     04-08 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-1030(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC SLAUGHTER IN BOSNIAN WAR  
 A SOLDIER'S DAUGHTER NEVER CRIES  
 DETROIT 9000   
 APT PUPIL  
 ONE TOUGH COP 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ETHNIC SLAUGHTER IN BOSNIAN WAR: The father addresses his
daughter, a young woman named Vera, who is holding her newborn.
``You should have killed yourself,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried, but they stopped me,'' she replies.
</P>
<P>
   He hands her a gun. ``No one is stopping you now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't, Papa,'' she answers. ``I have a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I am going to kill you both,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Now and then catching up with movies on video provides an
unusually reflective experience. That is certainly the case with
``Savior,'' about the 1995 conflict in Bosnia. Stark and riveting,
Peter Antonijevic's film, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York
Times, ``conveys the nihilistic essence of war with the force of a
kick in the gut.''
</P>
<P>
   To dramatize the senselessness of ethnic hatred, Antonijevic,
who is Serbian, keeps the identity of Serbians, Croatians and
Muslims deliberately vague. In the film they are virtually
interchangeable, with each group slaughtering the others so
routinely it hardly seems to matter who is who.
</P>
<P>
   Vera (Natasa Ninkovic) and her father (Miki Krftovic) are
Serbian. Captured by Muslims, she was raped and impregnated. To the
Serbians that deserves the death penalty. A Serbian soldier calls
her a Muslim whore, stomps her and stands ready to shoot the baby
as it is born. An American mercenary (Dennis Quaid) fighting for
the Serbians has had enough and shoots the soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Later the people in Vera's village, her father among them, are
led off, presumably to their execution, by Muslim soldiers. Near
the end of the film prisoners are clubbed to death by a giant who
walks among them wielding a huge mallet as routinely as if he were
in a sheep pen. Traumatized, they submit to their fate. They are
Muslims and he is Croatian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Savior,'' to be released on Tuesday by Columbia Tri-Star,
often is not easy to watch. Used sparingly and circumspectly, the
violence imparts horror. ``The audience crosses from feature to
documentary,'' Antonijevic said in an interview. Just the sight of
soldiers in fatigues is enough. ``You know what direction it's
going to take.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's major concession to movie convention is the situation
around Guy, the American mercenary superbly portrayed by Quaid.
Antonijevic wanted to speak through an American so he planted one
in the middle of the hostilities, not as an observer but as a
combatant.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after one of many real-life mercenaries fighting then
and now in the former Yugoslavia, Guy arrives by way of the French
Foreign Legion. At the outset of the film his wife and son are
killed by a bomb blast in a French cafe. Suspecting Muslims, Guy
walks into a mosque and shoots a few. Ever since he has been on the
run as a soldier of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   If that seems a little formulaic, given the fine, dark
originality of the rest of the film, it at least gets him into
position physically and spiritually. A bitter, empty blank of a
man, Guy steadies his weapon and picks off a Muslim child as if he
were a can on a fence.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he rediscovers his humanity. That also may be
standard film procedure, but it is important to Antonijevic. Now
40, he was reared in Yugoslavia when it was whole. ``We were taught
that differences between people didn't matter,'' he said. ``Back
then it seemed to be quite a successful experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   A SOLDIER'S DAUGHTER NEVER CRIES: Based on an autobiographical
novel by Kaylie Jones, daughter of the novelist James Jones, James
Ivory's film chronicles the life of the daughter of a famous writer
as she comes of age in Paris and the United States. A war veteran,
Bill Willis (Kris Kristofferson) reminds young Channe Willis
(Leelee Sobieski) about soldiers' daughters but allows that
writers' daughters cry all the time. Written by Ivory and Ruth
Prawer Jhabvala, the story sprawls at a loosely anecdotal pace,
but, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, conveys ``with
abundant sensitivity the experience of growing up in the shadow of
literary celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $98.99. 127 minutes. Closed captioned. English
and French with English subtitles. Release date: April 13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT 9000: Resurrected by Quentin Tarantino 25 years after it
was made, Arthur Marks' film says much about current racial
attitudes. Two detectives, one white and one black, investigate a
theft, but the true heart of the matter lies in the dynamic between
Lt. Danny Bassett (Alex Rocco), white, blunt and trained on the
street, and Sgt. Jesse Williams (Hari Rhodes), black, educated and
a good guy. ``That he and Bassett never resolve their relationship,
like the latter-day team of Danny Glover and Mel Gibson in the
`Lethal Weapon' series, is telling'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   1973. Miramax. $104.16. 106 minutes. R. Release date: April 13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   APT PUPIL: A cool (chilly, not hip) teen-age schoolboy named
Todd Bowden (Brad Renfro) discovers that his hometown has its very
own Nazi war criminal living incognito in its midst. After some
surveillance that would put the CIA to shame, Todd confronts Kurt
Dussander (Ian McKellen) with his true identity and then reveals
his own: a strange and sadistic brat with a taste for the macabre.
Fascinated with all things Nazi, Bowden forces the old man to
relate his past. But then the tables turn in a film adapted by
Bryan Singer from Stephen King's novella with ``dazzling
craftsmanship and clinical precision'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 111 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: April 13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ONE TOUGH COP: Although strongly acted and pungently written,
Bruno Barreto's film demonstrates how much television police drama
surpasses the big-screen variety. When a nun is raped and tortured,
the detective Bo Dietl (Stephen Baldwin) investigates against
orders, getting himself tangled with federal agents and in trouble
because of his old low-life associations. Caught up with choices
facing people in extreme circumstances, the narrative is freighted
with ``more story than it can comfortably handle, and as it goes
along it grows progressively less believable'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 90 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: April 13.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE FARM: LIFE INSIDE ANGOLA PRISON: ``You can learn to help
other people,'' says Bones, an old inmate who lies dying of lung
cancer in the hospital at the Louisiana State Penitentiary at
Angola. A former slave plantation and arguably the toughest prison
in the United States, Angola does encourage cooperation among those
who are sent there, most of them for the rest of their lives. An
Academy Award nominee for best documentary, Jonathan Stack, Liz
Garbus and Wilbert Rideau's film reviews six cases of men who go on
nurturing their slim hopes of release. That would include Rideau,
an inmate for 38 years. 1998. A&AMP;E. $24.95. 100 minutes. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   THE MOTHER AND THE WHORE: A professional narcissist (Jean-Pierre
Leaud) brings home a sex-obsessed nurse (Francoise Lebrun) to join
him and his mistress (Bernadette Lafont). Alternately revered and
mocked, Jean Eustache's film, which is sometimes mentioned in the
same breath with ``Last Tango in Paris,'' purports to dig into all
aspects of the relations between men and women. These three do talk
a lot. 1973. New Yorker. $94.98. 215 minutes. French with English
subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   THE WORKER AND THE HAIRDRESSER IN A WHIRLWIND OF SEX AND
POLITICS: The title about sums up Lina Wertmuller's raucous comedy
about a right-wing zealot (Veronica Pivetti) who gets involved with
a leftist labor organizer (Tullio Solenghi). 1996. Hen's Tooth.
$79.95. 104 minutes. Italian with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
