<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-SADLER-NYTR- &LR;      04-08 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-SADLER-NYTR- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLIOTT SADLER STARTING TO TUNE UP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger (Lakeland, Fla.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 23, Elliott Sadler has been plucked out of the Busch ranks to
drive one of the most-storied cars in Winston Cup, the No. 21 Ford
prepared by Wood Brothers Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am excited, but more nervous than anything about the
upcoming season,'' Sadler said back then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wood Brothers are taking a big chance on me and I hope I
can turn things around for them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Once the racing began, though, Sadler seemed to forget the last
part of that, the part about turning things around.
</P>
<P>
   Because the simple truth is the Wood Brothers' Ford running now
is not the car Cale Yarborough and David Pearson drove when they
were dominating the superspeedways.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the late '60s and through the '70s, the Wood Brothers
didn't run the entire circuit, preferring to concentrate on the big
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   But when they showed up, especially with Pearson, they were
usually awesome. In 1973, Pearson entered 18 races and won 11. In
1976, he ran 22 and won 10.
</P>
<P>
   But much of this happened before Sadler was even born. In recent
years, the Wood Brothers' Ford has been just another car.
</P>
<P>
   It has only won twice in the '90s, the last time in March 1993
at Atlanta with Morgan Shepherd driving.
</P>
<P>
   In Sadler's mind, though, he was striving to reach a standard
set by Pearson, a level of excellence which has escaped the Wood
Brothers since Pearson got out of the car in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler had to use a provisional to get in his first race, the
Daytona 500. In the first five races this year, he could finish no
better than 31st, at the March 15 Cracker Barrel 500 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very down,'' Sadler said. ``I felt as bad as you could
feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like we had a good enough team to run in the top 20,''
Sadler said. ``And I felt like I was not doing my part on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sadler felt pressure, it was not because of his sponsor,
Citgo, which has been backing Wood Brothers for 15 years despite
their lack of success.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly wasn't from the second generation of Woods now
running the team _ Eddie and Len _ who understand how difficult it
is to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   They are the sons of Glen Wood, who started Wood Brothers Racing
in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler was putting the pressure on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fear in life is being a failure as a race car
driver,'' Sadler said. ``The first couple races, we didn't do too
great. I got in situations I probably shouldn't have been in and
got in wrecks. I'd look in a mirror and wonder if I was gonna make
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Woods have been great about it and Mike Beam has been
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Beam left Bill Elliott to become Wood Brothers' crew chief this
year. After seeing how much Elliott, once the dominant driver on
the circuit, has struggled recently, he understood what Sadler was
up against.
</P>
<P>
   ``His expectations are so high,'' Bean said. ``I kept telling
him, `Don't focus on the negative. Focus on the positive. Just do
your part and don't worry about anything else.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't easy for Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worried about my job being in jeopardy,'' he said. ``I was
pretty hard on myself. When I don't do something, I get down. I
worried I wasn't doing the job they brought me in to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd try to just go race, but it was hard to put out of my
mind,'' Sadler said. ``I'd see all those pictures of that car in
victory lane, and that puts a lot of pressure on you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was my job to get them back in that situation, even
though I know it's probably not going to happen this year,'' Sadler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the Food City 500 in Bristol, Tenn., this week,
though, Sadler is breathing a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   In the last race _ the Primestar 500 at the Texas Motor Speeday
_ Sadler finished 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like a win for us,'' Sadler said. ``It took a load off
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, it took a load off the driver, who knows he's got a long
way to go, but finally may be feeling like he has a chance to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
