<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-PROSPECTS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR DRIVERS TO WATCH IN THE COMING YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The (Lakeland, Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is racing's new role model, on and off the track, and he is
making millions both places.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, 27, has replaced Dale Earnhardt, 47, as racing's
poster boy. Earnhardt is a throwback to what racing was. Gordon is
the image of racing's future.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new generation of drivers, all roughly Gordon's age or
younger, is coming along to challenge him. One, in fact, is
Earnhardt's son, Dale Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   So which ones are most likely to succeed? The top four might
look something like this:
</P>
<P>
   NO. 1: TONY STEWART, 27
</P>
<P>
   Experienced driver who has done it the right way, moving from
open wheel to Busch ranks last year. He has the talent to compete
with Gordon and, driving for Joe Gibbs as Bobby Labonte's teammate,
will have good equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest asset: Perhaps more than any of the challengers, Stewart
understands how difficult it is to get to the top and stay there.
He is extremely focused and that, combined with his talent, will
make him successful.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 2: MATT KENSETH, 27
</P>
<P>
   Battled Earnhardt Jr. for the Busch championship last year and
finished second, but many think he is more advanced and maybe more
talented. Signed by Jack Roush, who owns Fords driven by Mark
Martin and Jeff Burton, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest asset: Has made slow, steady climb through stock car
ranks and has not moved up until circumstances were right.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 3: KENNY IRWIN, 29
</P>
<P>
   In second season driving for Robert Yates. Dale Jarrett's
teammate, Irwin has a ton of talent, but was inconsistent his
rookie year. That might have been because everything has come
pretty easily for him on the way up. Another open wheel star who
chose Winston Cup, he will move up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest asset: Natural ability. There is no doubt Irwin can
drive a race car, a fact Robert Yates noted when he made Irwin, a
relative unknown with virtually no stock car driving experience,
his choice to replace Ernie Irvin in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   NO. 4: DALE EARNHARDT JR., 24
</P>
<P>
   Exploded on the Busch circuit in 1998, winning seven races and
the championship in his first full season. So highly sought after
by Winston Cup teams that his dad drew up a legal contract with him
after operating on pretty much of a handshake deal. Already has
big-league sponsor, Budweiser, for Winston Cup debut in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest asset: Has one of the sport's greatest drivers, his dad,
for a teacher and what's more important, he listens to him. Will
have grade A equipment.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
