<SLUG> BC-FILM-GIANTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMONG GIANTS' IS POIGNANT ROMANCE FROM WRITER OF `FULL MONTY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Among Giants'' is an affecting and unlikely romance that owes
a huge debt to its lead actors.
</P>
<P>
   Though the gravelly voiced _ and faced _ Pete Postlethwaite
(``In The Name Of the Father'') is hardly be anybody's idea of a
romantic leading man, it's his very cragginess that gives his
performance weight as well as pathos.
</P>
<P>
   Add the unorthodox gutsiness and sexiness of Australian actress
Rachel Griffiths, who was recently nominated for an Oscar for
``Hilary and Jackie,'' and ``Among Giants'' radiates tremendous
appeal, if on a small, intimate scale.
</P>
<P>
   The film was written by Simon Beaufoy, the previously gave us
``The Full Monty.''
</P>
<P>
   Here he follows another motley group of Englishmen _ five
reprobate characters who are hired by Ray (Postlethwaite) to paint
high-wire electrical towers on an isolated 15-mile stretch of
English moors. Ray's best mate is handsome and brash young Steve
(James Thornton), a daredevil who enjoys rock climbing on the
Sheffield cliffs in his time off.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic between this bunch of misfits radically changes when
Gerry (Griffiths), a hiker trekking through England on a
``spiritual quest,'' asks Ray for a job. A triangle forms between
Ray, Gerry and Steve and, when Ray and Gerry embark on a love
affair, their actions lead to surprising consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is prepared for commitment _ Ray has just been divorced
and Gerry is a free spirit who shuns being tied down and indeed,
often unwittingly wreaks havoc on the lives of those around her.
But soon Ray, confused by the intensity of his attraction, asks
Gerry to marry him _ an act that forces each to evaluate and
confront demons and desires.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Postlethwaite and Griffiths, who even daringly display
themselves naked in one scene, the real star of ``Among Giants'' is
the tone and sense of restlessness evoked by Beaufoy, director Sam
Miller and cinematographer Witold Stok.
</P>
<P>
   It's the closest thing to capturing the mystique of a dying way
of life _ the ``western'' loner anti-hero _ that the movies have
given us for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   Directors and actors have been so intent upon turning that
mystique into a caricature of itself that most films fail to convey
the true loneliness and pain in the lifestyle. ``Among Giants''
allows us to feel the rootlessness and the high price of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   And until the final scenes in the film, which are jarringly out
of place in such a yearning work, it lives up to Ray's explanation
as to why he's taken on such a reckless existence. ``I'm king up
here, lass,'' he says to Gerry, and for awhile, we actually believe
him.
</P>
<P>
   Among Giants. Directed by Sam Miller. Written by Simon Beaufoy.
Cast: Pete Postlethwaite, Rachel Griffiths, James Thornton. Fox
Searchlight Pictures. 94 minutes. Rated R for nudity, sexual
content, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
