<HEADER>
A0987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-SAFETY-MALES-NYT     04-08 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SAFETY-MALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BICYCLISTS AND PEDESTRIANS SHOULD AVOID MALE DRIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Safety experts have known that although male and
female drivers have roughly equal numbers of car crashes per mile
driven, men are 70 percent more likely to be driving in a crash
when someone is killed. But that statistic lumps the fatalities
together, whether the victim is the driver, a passenger, a person
in another vehicle or someone on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Now a study in New York City has produced new data on the sex of
the drivers involved when a pedestrian or a cyclist is killed. The
data suggest that pedestrians might do well to get off the street
when a male driver is coming.
</P>
<P>
   Male drivers are involved in crashes that kill pedestrians three
times more often than female drivers, per mile driven, according to
the study. In crashes that kill bicyclists, men are involved
roughly 10 times more often as women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising,'' said Julie Rochman, a spokeswoman for
the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety. ``Males are
over-represented in fatal crashes _ period.''
</P>
<P>
   The definitive national count is published by the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration, part of the Transportation
Department, which integrates data on crashes with information on
how many people of each sex are licensed to drive, and how far, on
average, they do drive. Its most recent report, released in
January, covers 1996; it showed that per 100 million miles driven,
male drivers were involved in 562 crashes and female drivers in
611.
</P>
<P>
   But for crashes in which someone died, men were involved in 3.11
per 100 million miles, and women in a little more than half that
many, 1.81.
</P>
<P>
   That research carves out only one subset of the universe of
fatal crashes: accidents in which the driver died. It found that
1.4 men died per 100 million miles driven, compared with 0.8 women.
</P>
<P>
   But the gender disparity in crashes that kill pedestrians is
more striking. Charles Komanoff, a transportation consultant and
advocate for bicyclists and pedestrians, recently published a study
of all the crashes in 1994-97 in New York City that killed a
pedestrian or a bicyclist. (New York is one of the few places in
the country where most of the people who die in traffic crashes are
outside vehicles, but such deaths are a significant problem
nationwide, running about 15 percent of total motor vehicle
deaths.)
</P>
<P>
   Komanoff found 1,020 deaths of pedestrians and cyclists on city
streets, but the driver's identity could be established in only 820
of those. In that group, 747, or 91 percent, were men; 73, or 9
percent, were women.
</P>
<P>
   The study is available on the Internet at
http://www.rightofway.org. The Transportation Department study is
available at http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/people/ncsa/ &QL; 
agesex.html.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soccer moms notwithstanding, men do more than half of all
driving. Nationally, they account for about 63 percent of miles
driven, according to Federal statistics. Komanoff's group, called
Right of Way, calculated that because nearly all taxi and bus
drivers in New York City are male, and because those two categories
account for a high proportion of the total miles driven, men do
about 75 percent of all the driving in New York City. (He limited
his analysis to city streets, excluding highways.)
</P>
<P>
   But even when that extra driving is factored in, men are heavily
over-represented in accidents that kill pedestrians, and especially
bicyclists.
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``The easy answer would be aggressiveness, risk-taking,''
said Tad Lee, a spokesman for the National Association of
Governors' Highway Safety Representatives. Aggressive driving is a
harder problem to solve than behavioral problems like drunken
driving or failing to buckle up, he said. For those problems, he
said, ``first you raise awareness, then people become aware of the
dangers of what they're doing, and then, because of pressure by
society, they become ashamed for going against society and doing
things wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we haven't gotten to that point yet with aggressive
driving and risk taking,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lee acknowledged that he had no evidence. ``That's the easiest
explanation,'' he said. ``I don't know if it's actually true.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. Arizona takes aggressive driving very
seriously, and last year enacted the nation's first law that
defines aggressive driving and sets penalties. The offense is
defined as speeding plus two of the following: passing on the
right, failing to observe a traffic light or stop sign, tailgating
and failing to signal. But Alberto Gutier, director of the
Governor's Office of Highway Safety in Phoenix and an author of the
law, said, ``I have not heard the comment from any officer that
`we've got fatalities or major injuries because an aggressive
driver hit a pedestrian.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Komanoff's study got a quick response from
the Dutch Pedestrian Association, which analyzed the 114 pedestrian
deaths in the Netherlands in 1995. Willem Vermuelen, a psychologist
with the group in The Hague, said that 88 percent were killed by
male drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Vermuelen said that men behave more dangerously than women, ``or
are more clumsy.'' That is demonstrated both by drivers and
pedestrian victims; ``more than 1.5 times as many men are killed as
pedestrian or cyclist,'' he said, although women actually cycle and
walk more. Men take risks and break rules more often, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said female drivers ``better identify with the role of the
unprotected participants'' _ that is, pedestrians. ``The men tend
to behave in a more hierarchical way, in which the car-driver is
superior to cyclist or pedestrian.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rochman, of the Insurance Institute, said that the locus of
pedestrian deaths is at intersections, where drivers fail to give
the right of way. That, she said, is an established characteristic
of male drivers. ``People are trying to catch a stale yellow light
or go through a red light, and red-light runners tend to be male,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance rates reflect this trend for young male drivers, who
pay far more because insurers find they are involved in more
claims. Gender generally plays a smaller role in rates as drivers
get older.
</P>
<P>
   Komanoff said that men and women had roughly equal numbers of
crashes ``because the vast majority of accidents are
fender-benders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's just not that much skill difference between men
and women drivers, but men are more inclined to take risks and act
aggressively behind the wheel,'' he said. ``It's the risk-taking
and aggressiveness that translate into fatalities.''
</P>
<P>
   If everyone driving a vehicle in New York City drove like a
woman, Komanoff calculated, the annual death toll among pedestrians
would drop to about 100, from 250 now. The number of bicyclists
killed would fall to 2 or 3, from 18 a year now.
</P>
<P>
   Komanoff has his own theory about bicyclists. ``Bicyclist
fatalities are not just a product of cyclists' recklessness or
carelessness, but a male driver resentment _ if not rage,'' he
said. ``Men want the bicyclists to get out of their way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
