<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 11 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will send the following Money
and Business articles for release Sunday, April 4, 1999:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE SECTION FRONT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FCC-KENNARD-PROFILE _ FCC Chairman William Kennard is
Washington's key official on issues of importance to the nation's
fastest growing industries. He has found himself politically hemmed
in from the start; relies to a surprising degree on Washington's
black power structure for support, and focuses much of his effort
on issues like minority ownership of TV stations and getting more
advertising for minority broadcasters. By Steven Labaton. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-TROUBLESHOOTERS _ There's so much merging going on that
the busiest companies have full-time teams that do nothing but
integrate acquisitions and concentrate on preventing and/or solving
problems arising from combining two corporate cultures. By Claudia
H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (New York) _ A weekly feature looking at
developments of the market worldwide. By Gretchen Morgenson. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-INSURANCE (Undated) _ Some major insurance companies
have got a deal for you. Well, maybe. First, you pick one of their
funds _ from high-risk to mild-mannered, your choice. Then, for a
nominal fee, these companies will guarantee that the money you put
up, plus an annual gain of 4 percent or 5 percent, will always be
there, no matter how far the market plunges. Sounds good, but
there's a catch: You have to die in order to collect on the
guarantee. What the companies are selling is life insurance tied to
your mutual funds. By Joseph B. Treaster. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONE-SABOTAGE _ Many people are irritated by intrusive
cell-phone use in restaurants, theaters and public transportation.
But not everyone likes one company's proposed solution: A box that
jams all mobile phones within in a 100-foot radius. By David
Wallis.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-SCOTCHES _ The quest for ever more arcane experiences in
single-malt drinking has driven Scotch whisky producers and
distributors to hunt for ever more arcane whiskies to meet the
demand. The growing popularity of single malts, whose prices range
from well-above-average to astronomical, may be a reflection of
U.S. prosperity. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   PRINTER-PAPER _ The consumer market for printer and copier
paper, once a quiet backwater of the paper products industry,
explodes with advertising and branding campaigns as more and more
printing moves out of professional shops and into home work
stations. By Claudia Deutsch. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   NETMUSIC-ROBINSON-PROFILE _ MP3.com, a 16-month-old San
Diego-based firm that distributes music over the Internet with
digital compression technology, is headed by Michael Robinson, who
has been hailed by rock musicians as a fellow revolutionary, even
though he really isn't. By Alec Foege. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   MILK-DEREG _ After years of being told that its complex
milk-price-control system hurts consumers, the government finally
offers a plan to dismantle it _ in a way that is likely to hurt
consumers, not help them.
</P>
<P>
