</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-COOKIE'S-FORTUNE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COOKIE'S FORTUNE' A MOST LIKABLE ALTMAN FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Altman once said that his basic philosophy of filmmaking
was to gather the best possible ensemble of actors, take them to
some interesting location, allow them to play with their roles and
improvise some of their dialogue, and then hope something magical
happens.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it does _ witness such classics as ``MASH,'' ``McCabe
and Mrs. Miller'' and ``The Player.'' Sometimes, perhaps more
often, it doesn't _ witness such travesties as ``Popeye,''
``Buffalo Bill and the Indians'' and ``Quintet.''
</P>
<P>
   Happily, ``Cookie's Fortune'' _ Altman's 33rd feature film in 42
years of trying _ is one of his most magical brews. Indeed, it
would be hard to think of a more completely likable Altman film or
one in which the chemistry of his cast seemed more perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the (real) small-town of Holly Springs, Miss., it's a
rambling, amiable story about what happens when a pipe-smoking
Southern dowager named Cookie (Patricia O'Neal) commits suicide in
order to join her beloved late husband.
</P>
<P>
   Stumbling upon the body, Cookie's scheming, slightly crazed
niece, Camille (Glenn Close), eats the suicide note and concocts a
string of ``evidence'' to make the death look like murder _ because
``suicides don't happen'' in their family.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately (and unintentionally), this concocted evidence
gradually points to Cookie's handyman, Willis (Charles S. Dutton),
an easy-going, middle-aged black man who has been sharing the house
with her in a kind of ``Driving Miss Daisy'' relationship.
</P>
<P>
   This is the set-up of the movie, and at this point we might
naturally expect the proceedings to turn into one more
heavy-handed, self-righteous indictment of racism in the small-town
South _ especially since Willis is so downright lovable and such an
obvious potential martyr.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Cookie's Fortune'' goes against all expectations to be a
lazy, irresistibly good-natured little comedy in which race is
ultimately not much of an issue, and just about everyone in this
small town _ excluding Close's character _ is a fairly decent human
being. It's Mayberry, not Mississippi Burning.
</P>
<P>
   As usual in an Altman movie, a wide assortment of characters
wander in and out of the storyline: Ned Beatty as a sheriff who'd
rather be fishing; Donald Moffat as the town's affable only lawyer;
Courtney B. Vance as a frustrated state prosecutor; Julianne Moore
as Camille's addled sister and co-conspirator.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as in only the best Altman, every character seems to click
into place. As Cookie's free-spirited grand-niece, Liv Tyler has
never been more movie-star radiant. As Cookie, veteran movie-great
O'Neal gives a blissfully broad and fearless performance. Even
Chris O'Donnell _ the town's Barney Fife of a deputy _ is a welcome
part of this inspired ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   The film comes together to be less the wild farce and scathing
satire that its publicity promises than a mellow comedy of
character that communicates a gentle acceptance of human nature in
general and family eccentricity in particular _ a film that likes
its characters so much that it's impossible not to feel the same
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, ``Cookie's Fortune'' has the same kind of uncanny
authenticity that Altman was able to give 1902 Puget Sound in
``McCabe and Mrs. Miller,'' '90s Hollywood in ``The Player'' and
'70s Nashville in ``Nashville.'' Few directors convey a sense of
time and place so convincingly, and this most convincing vision of
the post-civil rights Mississippi is a place that's definitely
worth a two-hour visit.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie's Fortune. Directed by Robert Altman. Screenplay by Anne
Rapp. Cast: Glenn Close, Julianne Moore, Liv Tyler, Patricia
O'Neal, Charles S. Dutton, Chris O'Donnell, Ned Beatty. October
Films. 118 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
