<HEADER>
A0991 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FLESH-SPI &LR;      04-08 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FLESH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SCHOOL OF FLESH' A HAUNTING CHARACTER STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   French critics are forever crying that Hollywood values are
destroying their beloved national cinema but, in at least one
respect, U.S. movies seem to have little or no impact: Gallic films
are still packed with great roles for women.
</P>
<P>
   While you can count the number of solid star vehicles for
actresses in Hollywood films each year on one hand, almost every
French film has a great woman's role. Why is this? Clearly, they
like women more than we do. They think they're fascinating
creatures.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the chief pleasure of seeing Benoit Jacquot's
``The School of Flesh'' is the close-up spectacle of Isabelle
Huppert in almost every second of its 100 minutes. It's not that
she eats the scenery, either. She actually underplays the role in a
performance of immense subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   Based on one of the many novels of twisted passion by Japan's
Yukio Mishima, it's the story of Dominique (Huppert), a rather
cold-blooded, fortyish career woman who goes to a club one night
and falls in quiet, smoldering lust with Quentin (Vincent
Martinez), a young, part-Arab bartender.
</P>
<P>
   It's soon apparent the young man is bad news _ a cruel, abusive,
game-playing user and part-time male prostitute to boot. But she
doesn't care: she likes the unromantic, even mechanical approach he
brings to the sex act; she enjoys her humiliation at his feet; and
begs to become his ``sugar daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   The script follows the stumbling stages of their off-and-on
affair, which comes to a crisis after an abortive holiday in North
Africa when he meets and finds himself attracted to the nubile
young daughter (Roxanne Mesquida) of Dominique's best friend
(Marthe Keller).
</P>
<P>
   It's a familiar story, and, frankly, the script doesn't do
anything remarkably new with it. As insouciantly played by Martinez
(younger brother of French star Olivier Martinez), Quentin is
simply never interesting enough for us to care much one way or
another who gets him.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the movie is mesmerizing _ in the same way that almost
any '40s Hollywood vehicle of Bette Davis or Joan Crawford is
mesmerizing. Jacquot's camera stays firmly riveted to Huppert's
face as it conveys her character's every thought and emotion.
Inadequate as the film may be in other respects, it's a haunting
character study and a terrific star vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The School of Flesh. Directed by Benoit Jacquot. Written by
Jacques Fieschi, from a novel by Yukio Mishima. Cast: Isabelle
Huppert, Vincent Martinez, Marthe Keller, Vincent Lindon.
Stratosphere Entertainment. 101 minutes. In French with English
subtitles. Rated R for sex scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
