r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKCHURCHES09-COX     04-08 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKCHURCHES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Think tank aims to boost black churches
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The formation of a center that may revolutionize the
way black churches do business in the next century was announced
Thursday by the Atlanta-based Interdenominational Theological
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The think tank, called the ``ITC/FaithFactor,'' is being created
with the belief that the effective black pastor of the next century
must be interested not only in private virtue but in public policy
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to prepare effective congregation leaders, but we also
want those leaders to be sophisticated,'' said ITC President Robert
Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   The ITC, a predominately black group of six seminaries, is
located near downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The think tank, funded by such groups as the Ford Foundation and
the Lilly Endowment, will include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A technology program, already pledged to donate 30,000
computers to black churches, that will teach participants how to do
everything from set up computer learning labs to create their own
World Wide Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An outreach program that will teach church officials how to
provide technical skills to people in need of training and
employment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An educational program that will teach churches how to
establish after-school programming and Christian academies.
</P>
<P>
   The think tank will also serve as a national clearinghouse for
the nation's estimated 70,000 black churches, according to Cicero
Wilson, the executive director of the program and head of its staff
of eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must create a communication system that will allow us to
share our best practices,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ITC officials hope the new center will usher in a day when the
black preacher will become a ``public theologian,'' someone who can
quote the lastest study or survey as well as Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must prepare someone not just to preach, but we must also
show them how to manage,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
