A1004 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKNOTES09-COX     04-08 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Pilot's Wife' latest to score on Oprah book club
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Big Game jackpot is enticing to ordinary folks, but authors
have their own lottery. It's called the Oprah Winfrey Book Club,
and the latest winner is Massachusetts writer Anita Shreve. ``The
Pilot's Wife'' (Harvest Books, $13.95, paperback), Shreve's novel
about a widow's discovery of her dead husband's secret life, has
been chosen as Winfrey's April selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful,'' Shreve says from her home in Longmeadow,
Mass. ``Life was already great. Now it's better.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Pilot's Wife,'' the protagonist attempts to clear her
husband's name after he is blamed for a fatal air crash. Her
discoveries force her to realize she really didn't know her husband
of 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Shreve has just finished a new book, ``Fortune's Rocks,'' that _
coincidentally _ takes place in the same house as ``The Pilot's
Wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's set about a hundred years earlier,'' Shreve says. ``It's
about a 15-year-old girl who falls in love with a 42-year-old
married doctor. It's like a 19th-century novel with a huge cast of
characters. It's written in 19th-century language, which is
familiar to me because I wrote `The Weight of Water' in that
style.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, three of Shreve's earlier books _ ``Strange Fits of
Passion,'' ``Eden Close'' and ``Where or When'' _ have been
optioned for films.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING THE LIST: Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' was a big book
(in size and sales) last year, but it wasn't the biggest. Wolfe,
whose Atlanta-centered novel sold 1.26 million copies, finished
fourth on the Publishers Weekly 1998 list, behind John Grisham's
``The Street Lawyer,'' Tom Clancy's ``Rainbow Six'' and Stephen
King's ``Bag of Bones.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE PULP: Jacqueline Susann and Grace Metalious are dead, but
fans can still get a dose of their trademark glitz this summer.
Northeastern University Press is reissuing a paperback edition of
``Peyton Place'' 43 years after Metalious' scandalous (at the time)
classic was published. In her introduction, Maine professor Ardis
Cameron writes, ``Metalious tweaked the mythologies of tourist New
England, turning the familiar postcard portrait into a voluptuous
pinup poster.'' Meanwhile, resurrecting Susann's 1966 novel
``Valley of the Dolls'' wasn't good enough for one publisher.
Publishers Weekly reports that Crown has hired a pseudonymous
author, Rae Lawrence, to use some of Susann's notes _ made for her
next book project _ to write a novel in Susann's style. Titled
``Jacqueline Susann's Shadow of the Dolls,'' the novel will be
published next year after the remake of the film ``Valley of the
Dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   DOWNSIZING: Any independent bookseller will tell you the market
is shrinking, but apparently books are, too. Publishers from
Abbeville Press to Running Press are turning to minibooks to
generate more income. Publishing Trends reports that the tiny books
_ available in Crate &AMP; Barrel stores as well as traditional outlets
_ have produced net sales of $20 million in the past five years.
Some of the best selling titles have been Abbeville Press'
miniature museum books, Running Press' ``Star Wars'' books, and Ten
Speed Press' minicookbooks, ``Totally Garlic'' or ``Totally Crab.''
``What you're getting is not just the gimmick of the little format,
but really delicious, usable recipes,'' says Veronica Randall,
editor of Ten Speed Press. Even Christian booksellers are getting
into the act, with ``God's Little Instruction Book'' and ``One
Minute Pocket Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   IN THE NEWS: Georgia writer Deborah Smith, who moved from
romance novels to mainstream fiction with ``A Place to Call Home,''
has signed a $1.25 million two-book deal with Little, Brown. The
first, ``The Iron Bear,'' will be published next summer.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
