<HEADER>
A1006 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUDORA-WELTY11-1STTAK     04-08 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUDORA-WELTY11-1STTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home is where the heart is for beloved writer, 90, who found a
wealth of characters just outside door
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 11.
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I am a writer who came of a sheltered life. A sheltered life
can be a daring life as well. For all serious
</P>
<P>
   daring starts from within.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Eudora Welty,
</P>
<P>
   ``One Writer's Beginnings''
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. _ The curtains are open, the shades are up and a
light glows in a downstairs room of the house at 1119 Pinehurst St.
Someone has gathered dead leaves and branches and stuffed them in
black garbage bags that sit by the mailbox. Cats loll on the
concrete walkway. Across the street, the students of Bellhaven
College dart in and out of classes, their shouts softened by the
distance across the campus lawn.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine a living legend is just beyond the screen
door.
</P>
<P>
   Even without an exact address, it would be easy for Eudora
Welty's readers to recognize this house from her description of it
in 1983's ``One Writer's Beginnings'':
</P>
<P>
   ``The house was on a slight hill (my mother never could see the
hill) covered with its original forest pines, on a gravel road then
a little out from town, and was built in a style very much of its
day, of stucco and brick and beams in the Tudor style.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty has lived most of her life in this home, moving here with
her family as teenager, returning to it from New York at 22 to be
with her newly widowed mother and staying ever since. The road out
front is paved now, and the Bellhaven neighborhood, then new, is
being considered for a historic designation.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Welty's 90th birthday, which is Tuesday, the house
has become the writer's entire universe. Confined by poor health
alluded to only in the vaguest terms by her friends and family,
Mississippi's grande dame of literature and Jackson's most hallowed
resident is rarely seen these days. Round-the-clock nurses tend
her, and only close friends and relatives visit.
</P>
<P>
   Though she always liked the peace and familiarity of her
childhood home, Welty is not reclusive by nature. Until recently,
she had her daily routines in Bellhaven, and often she dined out
with friends or went to the theater. She traveled, visiting friends
and lecturing, and always getting to New York at least once a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eudora used to say she was underfoot locally,'' says Pearl
Amelia McHaney, a professor at Georgia State University who has
published the Eudora Welty newsletter for 22 years and edited a new
collection of essays, ``Eudora Welty: Writers' Reflections Upon
First Reading Welty.'' ``She might not have made a stir, but she
was always active.''
</P>
<P>
   She is missed around town. Yet, even as she is nowhere to be
seen, Welty is everywhere in Jackson. By choosing to stay here all
her life, Welty is in the air, palpable in her old haunts like the
lingering perfume of someone who just left the room.
</P>
<P>
   For Eudora Welty the woman, Jackson has been, quite simply,
home. For Eudora Welty the writer, Jackson has been what Oxford,
Miss., was to William Faulkner, a small but ample playground for
her imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Her characters were always here, waiting to be heard by the
woman with an uncanny ear for the cadences of small-town small
talk, and an almost eerie capacity to walk a spell in another's
shoes. Beauty parlor harpies and jazz singers, country folk and
city folk, black and white, freakish and all-too-normal, all were
Welty's fellow Mississippians. And the stories they inhabit _
masterpieces such as ``Why I Live at the P.O.,'' ``Powerhouse,''
``A Worn Path'' and her Pulitzer Prize-winning novel, ``The
Optimist's Daughter'' _ came into being by the light of her bedroom
window in the house on Pinehurst Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in Jackson has anchored her in the voices of the people
she's chronicled in her fiction,'' says William Ferris, chairman of
the National Endowment for the Humanities and a Mississippi native
who has known Welty since he was 12. ``These are the voices of
people she's come across all her life in the Jitney Jungle and in
the beauty parlor.''
</P>
<P>
   And the relationship is reciprocal. Unlike Faulkner, who was
tolerated at best by Oxford during his lifetime, Welty is loved
like an aunt and worshipped like a patron saint in Jackson. It is
as difficult to imagine Jackson without Welty as it is to imagine
Welty without Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's important where you set your story. The
important thing is to be so familiar with it that you don't have
stop and say, `what would be blooming there in July?' I know.
(Jackson) sets my stage and then I can push off from that base.''
</P>
<P>
   _From a 1984 interview in
</P>
<P>
   The Memphis Commercial Appeal
</P>
<P>
   What's it like to have a world-famous writer in town? The
residents of Jackson know. Eudora Welty has lived among them for 90
years, buying newspapers and groceries one day, receiving the
Pulitzer Prize or the French Legion of Honor the next.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Nobles, manager of Parkins Pharmacy in Bellhaven, used to
see her every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to come in here and buy her New York Times,'' says
Nobles. Now called MediStat since it was bought by a national
chain, it remains much as it was when it opened 75 years ago.
There's a post office window, a soda fountain and a lunch counter,
along with the usual aisles of greeting cards and toothpaste.
Nobles knows most of his customers by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, she used to come in here all the time, until she quit
driving,'' he continues. ``But a friend still comes in every day to
get her New York Times. She always wanted that New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   The pharmacy is next to the Jitney Jungle, where Welty would buy
her groceries. People used to shop at Parkins and the Jitney Jungle
just for the chance of catching a glimpse of Welty.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd get so excited over Miss Eudora,'' Nobles says. ``Not
the people of Bellhaven _ they were used to her _ but people from
other parts of Jackson or from out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers used to ask Nobles to get Welty's autograph for them,
but Welty asked him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not because she minded, but because she didn't want me to be
bothered with that,'' he says. ``That's just how she is.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty's sister-in-law, Mittie Welty, stops in to mail a letter.
She recalls fondly when the aging author was more active.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, she went everywhere,'' she says. ``She liked going out at
night with her friends. She liked the movies, and the New Stage,
the community theater here in Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite place was Bill's Tavern, a casual restaurant with
paper menus and crackers in baskets that serves fresh seafood and
Greek specialties. On her 85th birthday, one of many she celebrated
at Bill's, a belly dancer performed; she had ``Eudora Welty I Love
You'' written on her stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Welty's niece, Mary Alice White, remembers when she was too
young to know Welty was famous. She was simply the favorite maiden
aunt who took her on the train to New York to see Broadway plays
and drove in the carpool.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just a wonderful aunt,'' says White, admissions
director at Jackson Preparatory Academy. ``Then I'd open an English
book, and there would be my aunt's story to study.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it is with Welty in town. She is at once neighbor and
celebrity, aunt and literary legend, casual listener and
immortalizing chronicler.
</P>
<P>
   All around town are small shrines to Welty. The municipal
library is named after her. There is a bust of her at Lemuria
Bookstore, an independent bookseller. A Mississippi governor once
decreed her birthday to be ``Eudora Welty Day.'' Much of her life's
work is stored at the state archives, including her manuscripts,
the photographs she shot while at her first job as a publicity
agent for the Works Progress Administration and the war bond
newsletter she wrote in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   At Jackson Prep, a glass case in the library is filled with
photographs of Welty and first editions of her books. Diann
Arinder, librarian and English teacher at the school, recalls when
White's daughter, Welty's grandniece, invited her in 1996 to see
Welty receive the French Legion of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to meet Eudora Welty, and I thought I would just melt in
my shoes,'' Arinder says. ``She waved her long, delicate fingers at
me, and I couldn't believe those fingers had pounded on a
typewriter all these years _ and she preferred a manual.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty asked Arinder which books her grandniece liked to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that just like her to want to talk about someone else
besides herself?'' Arinder says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
