<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1007 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUDORA-WELTY11-2NDTAK     04-08 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUDORA-WELTY11-2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss: Arinder Says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lamar Life tower is overshadowed now, and you can no
longer read the time on its clocktower from all over town, as he'd
wanted to be possible always, but the building's grace and good
proportion contrast tellingly with the overpowering, sometimes
brutal, character of some of the structures that rise above it.
Renovators have sandblasted away the alligators that graced the
entrance. But the Company still has its home there, and my father
is remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   _From ``One Writer's Beginnings''
</P>
<P>
   Though the small town of 25,000 of Welty's youth has grown into
a small city of more than 200,000, many of the landmarks of her
childhood have endured.
</P>
<P>
   The Lamar Life Building, dubbed ``Jackson's first skyscraper''
in 1924, was Welty's father's pride and joy. He was an officer in
the insurance company and oversaw the construction of the building.
Today, it is dwarfed by New South architecture, but its white
marble facade and elaborate Gothic style hold their own in a city
increasingly made of steel and glass. A metal plaque at the
entrance says ``Home Office of the Lamar Life Insurance Company.
H.S. Weston, President; C.W. Welty, Vice President and General
Manager. Erected 1924.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a block or so from downtown, Welty's birthplace is still on
Congress Street, a dollhouselike Victorian home with a comfortable
porch and a small yard. A plaque marks the house as her birthplace
and says it was built in 1908 by Christian and Chestina Welty,
Eudora's parents. Now butter yellow, the two-story house has
offices in it, as do most of the homes on the street. Next door are
the headquarters for Lt. Gov. Ronnie Musgrove's race for governor;
up the street is Welty's elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Welty's presence has been invaluable to Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the foremost contribution in Jackson from a literary
perspective,'' says John Evans, owner of Lemuria Bookstore, where
Welty signed several of her books.
</P>
<P>
   Welty has brought people to Jackson who otherwise never would
have come, he says. Writers, journalists and just plain fans
trooped in and out of the house on Pinehurst Street for decades.
Henry Miller, Reynolds Price, Anne Tyler, The New York Times and
Vanity Fair, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has introduced writers, photographers, researchers and
journalists to Mississippi life,'' Evans says. ``And she has opened
the doorway for other writers from Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she is like compared with the other writers he's met
through the years, Evans becomes passionate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one more special, there's no one more gracious,
more genuine, more caring, and there may not be a more well-read
writer. And she has been so well-loved by the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewers love to ask Welty why she stayed, and her answer is
always simple. It is home, and it is familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved the place and the people, beginning with her
parents,'' says longtime friend Ferris. ``She felt a relationship
there that was unique and was wise enough to know that pull of her
heart was an instinct that should be respected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel awfully selfish living here alone, and I can't afford
to keep it up the way I should, but I can't imagine moving. And
it's home.''
</P>
<P>
   _From ``More Conversations
</P>
<P>
   With Eudora Welty''
</P>
<P>
   WELTY AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: April 13, 1909, in Jackson, Miss., daughter of Christian
Webb Welty, officer in an insurance company, and Chestina Andrews
Welty.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Educated: Mississippi State College for Women, 1926-27;
University of Wisconsin, bachelor of arts, 1929; attended Columbia
University Graduate School of Business, 1930-31.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  First published story:
</P>
<P>
   ``Death of a Traveling Salesman,''
</P>
<P>
   Manuscript magazine, 1936.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Career: Newspaper and radio writer, 1931-1932; publicity agent
for Works Progress Administration, 1933-1936; book reviewer,
1942-1984.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Selected prizes: Pulitzer Prize, 1973; National Medal for
Literature, 1980; Presidential Medal of Freedom, 1980; American
Book Award, 1981, 1984; National Medal of Arts, 1987; French Legion
of Honor, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   RECOMMENDED READING
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Optimist's Daughter.'' Winner of the Pulitzer Prize,
this slender, partially autobiographical novel tells the story of a
young woman named Laurel who had left the South but returns to New
Orleans as her father is dying.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Curtain of Green.'' First published in 1941, the stories
in Welty's debut collection are undiminished by time. Her best
stories are here: ``Petrified Man,'' ``Powerhouse'' and the most
celebrated of all, ``Why I Live at the P.O.,'' which writer Fred
Chappell once described as ``an extravaganza of ventriloquism,
dramatic irony and sheer slapstick.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``One Writer's Beginnings.'' This soft-spoken memoir of a
happy childhood and a writer's evolution grew out of a series of
lectures Welty delivered at Harvard University in 1983. It has
become standard reading for anyone aspiring to be a writer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``One Time, One Place: Mississippi in the Depression, a
Snapshot Album.'' During the Great Depression, as adept with a
camera as a pen, Welty traveled throughout her home state taking
photographs for Franklin D. Roosevelt's Works Progress
Administration. The 100 duotone pictures in this volume capture the
faces and scenes of a lost time.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB:
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Eudora Welty and links to other
sites, go to:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  arachnid.Gsu.EDU/(tilde)wwweng/ewn
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.interarc.com/welty/
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
