<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-GO09-COX     04-08 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-GO09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A spirited ride set amid raves, deals and, of course, Vegas
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go has the energetic, late-night delirium of a Chinese fire
drill. It's a whirl of wired young adults running in circles before
the traffic light turns green. The title comes from the word
mouthed by one character to another at a crucial point in the
story. It could just as easily derive from the film's headlong
momentum: ``On your mark, get set, go!''
</P>
<P>
   A three-part comedy-drama unfolding on a single Christmas Eve,
it's directed and shot by Doug Liman (``Swingers''). You could
think of it as a movie built on X's. We get Xmas, exhilaration,
exhaustion, excitement and the drug called ecstasy, better known as
X.
</P>
<P>
   The movie kicks off with grocery clerk Ronna (Sarah Polley)
trying to make some extra bucks to pay rent. When two strangers
named Adam (Scott Wolf) and Zack (Jay Mohr) ask her if she can, uh,
hook them up for a party that night, Ronna figures she can buy 20
hits of X from snarling dealer Todd (Timothy Olyphant) and sell
them back to the guys at a substantial markup.
</P>
<P>
   Things don't turn out as planned. The scenario escalates into a
tense encounter with the law, a wild rave, a drug overdose, some
gunplay and a hit-and-run accident. And that's only the first part
of the movie. The second follows Simon (Desmond Askew), a Brit who
works with Ronna, on a road trip to Las Vegas with three pals,
including Marcus (Taye Diggs). Their adventure includes a blazing
hotel room, a trip to a strip club (for the gratuitous T&AMP;A every
``hip'' moviemaker seems obliged to include), more gunplay, more
car disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Part 3 returns us to Adam and Zack, who turn out not to be the
people we thought. Their complex relationship is strained by dinner
with a policeman (William Fichtner) and his wife (Jane Krakowski).
Paced with the offbeat rhythms of a David Lynch movie, the
funny-creepy scene is charged with a sexual tension that playfully
turns out to be something else entirely.
</P>
<P>
   This segment solves the narrative threads dangling from the
first two parts. So, after all this, what have we learned? Not
much. But it's been fun, thanks to an engaging cast and
occasionally riotous touches. The funniest involves a hallucinating
kid, a house cat and subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   First-time screenwriter John August's script borrows the
wraparound chronology of ``Pulp Fiction.'' But it doesn't match the
high stakes of that movie or ask questions any deeper than ``Are we
having fun yet?'' It's more like a late-millennial ``American
Graffiti,'' with attitude replacing nostalgia. The movie's subtext
seems to be the aimless emptiness of the characters' lives, but
it's an idea that's never really addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go'' is basically a picaresque plot machine that sends its
characters spinning through misadventures. Though it wraps itself
in independent-film cachet _ it was a Sundance Festival hit _ the
movie is as calculated in courting its target audience as more
crassly commercial teen pics like ``She's All That'' and ``Wing
Commander.''
</P>
<P>
   The film writes its own description in the opening scene, as
another grocery clerk (Katie Holmes) tells a friend at a diner,
``You know what I like about Christmas? The surprises.'' That sums
up ``Go.'' It's a bright, shining package. And though it turns out
to be pretty empty, you can't help admiring how cleverly it's
wrapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sarah Polley, Scott Wolf, Katie Holmes and
</P>
<P>
   Jay Mohr. Rated R for strong drug content, sexuality, language
and some violence. 1 hour, 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Like the rave at its center, it's a blast while it
lasts, though you may feel let down when it's over.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
