<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1009 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POW-MUSEUM09-COX     04-08 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POW-MUSEUM09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National Prisoner of War Museum marks first anniversary
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDERSONVILLE, Ga. _ After 56 years, Marge Best remembers the
moment the telegram came ``like it just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw mother, and she was crying so,'' said Best, 71. ``We
knew what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The telegram said her father, Harold ``Pop'' Thomas, was missing
in action. Later, another brought the news he was a POW in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Best had come to this tiny, out-of-the-way Georgia town to visit
the National Prisoner of War Museum, a $5.8 million shrine to the
800,000 Americans held as POWs since 1776. The federally operated
museum opened a year ago today, and _ like the more famous and more
accessible Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington _ it has touched
thousands of veterans and their families, who walk slowly through
its grim corridors, full of relics that point out the unspeakable
horrors of POW life.
</P>
<P>
   Before last year, almost all visitors to Andersonville were
Civil War buffs who came to see the long rows of tombstones of
Union soldiers who died at the infamous Confederate prison. After
the museum opened, 6,600 more people a month are making the trek
through the rural countryside to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stories on the new museum were in papers all over the country,
on network news, and people of all ages were just taken with it,''
park Superintendent Fred Boyles said. ``People come now because
they realize we owe them, and all veterans, a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   An unexpected consequence has been the donation of 1,561 relics
and mementos by ex-POWs who salvaged eating utensils, hand-made
weapons, diaries and even German and Japanese flags that flew over
their World War II prison camps. The museum owns about 8,000
relics, 200 of which are on display. Some of the newly donated ones
will eventually go into glass displays designed to protect them
from light, humidity, heat and bacteria; for now they're being kept
in a climate-controlled warehouse at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Curator Eric Reinert is charged with taking care of all the
artifacts, and he's awed by what he's seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really something,'' he said, gingerly unfolding a huge
Nazi flag donated by Betty Hammel, 76, of Syracuse, N.Y. Hammel's
brother, the late Lt. John Hull, secreted the banner out of a
German prison camp. ``It's in great shape, kept folded in a closet
drawer all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   He dons white gloves, then opens a gray box containing a book
titled ``A Wartime log,'' in which Lt. Joseph Klingenberg of Villa
Hills, Ky., faithfully recorded his daily experiences in a German
camp after being shot down on Feb. 4, 1944. He donated the diary
along with a scrapbook kept by his wife, Aylyn, full of War
Department telegrams and censored letters the Germans allowed him
to send home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the best diaries I've ever seen,'' said
Reinert, thumbing through Klingenberg's log. ``The writing is
clear. He drew caricatures of friends. He recorded small details.''
</P>
<P>
   Klingenberg, 79, and a retired Xavier University chemistry
professor, said he realized as a scholar that the documents ``could
be used by students in the future to study the war.''
</P>
<P>
   His children didn't want the diary or scrapbook, he said. ``I
decided this is going to be a safe place. I know they'll take care
of it. And everyone needs to know what happened to us and what all
POWs endure, like those three young soldiers in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   With American World War II vets dying at a rate of 35,000 a
month, Klingenberg and his contemporaries are more willing to go
public with their memories than they used to be. ``After we got
home, we were too busy raising families,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He delivered the priceless books in person and his visit to the
museum impressed him. ``We need to make sure everyone is aware of
what we went through. It's too easy to put material like this in an
attic and let it waste away.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by others who've made donations, such
as Joseph Sturniolo, 75, of Sun City Center, Fla. He recently
handed Reinert a small lump of hardened brown bread. The bread came
not from his own experience in World War II, but from World War I,
when his late father, David Sturniolo, was held as a POW in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapped in newspaper, the bread was made from potato skins,
wheat flour and sawdust. His father had skipped his rations so he
could bring it home to show his family. The younger Sturniolo
didn't want the bread to get lost or deteriorate, and he feared his
children wouldn't appreciate its significance.
</P>
<P>
   Not all donors have delivered their relics personally to the
curator. Some have mailed them in, and at least one person left a
memento anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when the museum opened, somebody left a Japanese
flag _ just brought it in and left it on a table,'' Reinert said.
``No name, only this inscription: `Torn down by L.R. Scoggin and
Russell Rawlins.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some relics are from more recent conflicts. There are cigarette
pouches and a brick from the ``Hanoi Hilton'' in Vietnam, and the
flight suit of Lt. Col. Rhonda Cornum, an Army physician who was
wounded and held prisoner during the Persian Gulf War. Cornum also
donated casts wrapped around her broken arms by Iraqi doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But by far, most donations have been from the World War II-Korea
era.
</P>
<P>
   Captured at Anzio, Italy, on Feb. 22, 1944, Henry Kaufman, 78,
of Los Angeles, was held in several POW camps before the Germans
found out he was Jewish and sent him to the infamous Dachau
concentration camp. As German discipline fell apart near the end of
the war, Kaufman slipped into a Gestapo captain's bedroom one
morning, took the officer's pistol from the bedpost, killed him and
escaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so bitter with anger for him trying to kill me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman traveled to the museum to donate the pistol, its holster
and a full clip of bullets _ minus the one he fired into the
German.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the museum was packed with visitors, its parking lot
full of cars from more than a dozen states and several tour buses.
Men, women and even children dabbed at their eyes with tissues as
they viewed videotapes of POWs telling their stories or peered with
horror at duplicates of small cells in which captured men were
caged in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe the things those men went through,'' said
Zach Osterman, 12, of Atlanta, visting with his mother and
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bowers, 74, of Atlanta, was a crew member of a B-24
bomber, shot down on his first mission Sept. 27, 1944, and held
until war's end. He pointed toward the museum's entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children would never know about World War II if we didn't
have this,'' he said. ``People should know.''
</P>
<P>
   Marge Best, choked with emotion, said her father was 35 when he
was captured and is 91 now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still puts his hand over his heart when the national anthem
is played, and I know he'd like to come here. This museum is such a
wonderful memorial to all POWs, men who have lost their lives, to
all people who serve their country,'' she said. ``It's just
beautiful. He'd really appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I do.''
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   From Atlanta take I-75 south past Macon and Perry to the
Henderson exit. Go west on Ga. 26 to Oglethorpe, then south on Ga.
49. The National Prisoner of War Museum is on Ga. 49, nine miles
north of Americus. It and the Civil War cemetery, which is at the
same site, are open from 8:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily except
Thanksgiving, Christmas and New Year's Day. Admission is free.
Information: 912-924-0343.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
