<SLUG> BC-READER-CRITICS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You be the critic
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   `The Corruptor'
</P>
<P>
   This movie gives New York's Chinatown a bad name. Chow Yun-Fat
gives honest cops a bad name. And Mark Wahlberg gives acting a bad
name. There's plenty of action and violence but not much else. It's
not worth missing your supper to go see ``Corruptor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Schwartz, Chamblee (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   `October Sky'
</P>
<P>
   This is an inspiring story about the efforts of a group of
students who dared to dream of escaping the stranglehold gravity of
the mines. Based on a true story, it has such an authentic look
that I was transported back to the time that I too, at age 12,
looked up and saw that first artificial satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Depkin, Baltimore, Md.
</P>
<P>
   `Never Been Kissed'
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a slow and frighteningly boring movie proved
to be nothing more than that. The plot had its weaknesses,
including numerous scenes with an annoying Drew Barrymore crying
about her traumatic teenage years. The movie went on to prove that
it should have ``Never Been Made.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Stamm, Fairburn (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   `8MM'
</P>
<P>
   Besides being too dank and even more disturbing than David
Fincher's superior ``Seven,'' ``8MM'' is one of the most intriguing
thrillers of the past few years. It shows the porn industry with
probably more realism than ``Boogie Nights'' did and features a
fine performance by Nicolas Cage.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Skutle, Marietta (Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   We're looking for movie fans who want to add their opinions to
our film coverage. To qualify, send us a brief review, preferably
of no more than 50 words, about a recent movie. Send your review,
name, address and telephone number to:
</P>
<P>
   Reader Movie Response
</P>
