<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ WASHINGTON _ NATO allies said Friday they were
committed to continuing the air war against Yugoslavia, while hopes
dimmed for an early release of three American soldiers held
prisoner there. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AID _ RINAS AIR FORCE BASE, Albania - Relief workers had
planned to send in enough food for several hundred thousand ethnic
Albanian refugees on a temporary basis. Now, they find they must
feed up to 500,000 for the foreseeable future. That has left them
frantically searching for a way to keep pace with the growing
refugee problem. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHEMICAL _ WASHINGTON - NATO ground troops entering a
hostile Serbia could face the threat of chemical weapons, the
Federation of American Scientists said on Thursday. The former
Yugoslavia has four facilities producing toxins and possibly
rockets to launch them, which Serbian President Milosevic could use
as a ``trump'' card if NATO invaded. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CITRUS-CHINA _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Chinese
Premier Zhu Rongji announced that China was lifting its ban on the
import of citrus products from the United States. (Lipman, Cox News
Service) ATTN: Fla., Texas editors. Moving in international,
financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   VIRUS _ ATLANTA _ A tropical virus that has killed dozens of
people in Malaysia is the first of its kind and virologists are
stumped as to how it spreads, a CDC official in Atlanta said today.
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BUCHANAN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ History says Pat Buchanan can't
be elected president, but he can make life miserable for other
folks who want the job. In 1992, he scared then-President Bush in
the New Hampshire primary. In 1996, Buchanan knocked Texan Phil
Gramm out of the race and won the New Hampshire primary. Now,
Buchanan, who has promised to be nice to opponent GWBush, is
bringing his fire-and-brimstone campaign to the heart of Bush
country. Buchanan will campaign next week in Midland. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON -- Poverty in each state and the
nation as a whole would be much higher among the elderly _
particularly among elderly women _ if Social Security did not
exist, according to a study released Thursday by the Center on
Budget and Policy Priorities. (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Localized stories for Cox states have MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-TECH _ WASHINGTON - Students at historically black
colleges and universities have less access than other students to
the computer technology that is a key to today's cutting-edge jobs,
experts are saying at the annual conference of the National
Association for Equal Opportunity in Higher Education. (Mollison,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RECYCLE _ WASHINGTON _ Efforts to get Americans to recycle
leftover milk jugs, paper and and other trash are being hindered by
billions of dollars in tax subsidies to the raw material industries
against which recycled products must compete, recyclers and tax
reform groups declared Thursday. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   USDA-BEEF _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa. called
Thursday for an investigation into a Cox Newspapers report that
meat purchased for the federal school lunch program from a plant
with known safety violations sickened schoolchildren in Washington
state. (Montgomery, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMS _ WASHINGTON _ John Lewis joins Customs officials to
announce an independent investigation of racial profiling in
customs searches at Hartsfield and elsewhere. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DAYTONA _ Ruling expected as NAACP and several black college
students aska federal judge to stop Daytona Beach's plans to
restrict car access to city beaches during Black College Reunion
this weekend. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POW-MUSEUM _ Before the $5.8 million National Prisoner of War
Museum opened a year ago today in this tiny southwest Georgia town,
most visitors to Andersonville were Civil War buffs who came to
gawk at the 12,920 marble tombstones of Union soldiers who perished
at the Confederate prison whose name has become synonymous with
cruelty. But since last April 9, it's become a hallowed mecca for
tens of thousands of veterans, most wrinkled, limping on canes or
pushed in wheelchairs by aging sons and daughters through the dark
corridors of the grim museum, full of relics that point out the
horrors of life as a POW. Attendance skyrocketed more than 20
percent in just the first six months, and Park Superintendant Fred
Boyles expects 12-month figures to show a 40 percent jump over the
previous fiscal year. And an unexpected consequence has been the
donation of a flood of 1,561 relics by ex-POWs who salvaged eating
utensils, hand-made weapons, diaries and even German and Japanese
flags that flew over their camps when they were liberated.
(Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKCHURCHES _ The Interdenominational Theological Center (ITC)
will hold a press conference Thursday to announce the details for a
new think tank that will become a clearinghouse for the black
church. The ITC/Faith Factor will offer technical assistance and
research facilities for urban and rural black churches. ITC's
president, Robert Franklin, will talk about the new think tank as
well as other ITC programs. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NEWORLEANS-WARM _ NEWORLEANS _ As if it weren't bad enough that
New Orleans is the fattest city, the most heart-disease-ridden
city, now it's the city most at risk for global warming, according
to a new report. Because New Orleans is actually below sea level,
the Big Easy would become the Big Ocean if temperatures keep
climbing and the sea level rises. The solution? Money! Billions
would be needed to revamp the levees that keep the mighty
Mississippi from rolling over the city. The National Environmental
Trust issues the report, called ''Cities at Risk,'' in a telephone
news conference Thursday. (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   TEX-BUSH-TAXCUTS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Part of Gov. Bush's tax cut
plan clears a major hurdle as the Senate approves a variety of
sales tax cuts. (Elizondo, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-LANEY _ AUSTIN _ House Speaker Pete Laney is the last
of the big Democrats and could be the linchpin of the 1999
Legislative session. As the Senate sends bills to the House at a
fast clip, the unassuming Democrat from West Texas is in a unique
position to make or break legislation. But will he use his power?
Colleagues say that's not his style, but he could easily kill
legislation privately. We explain how. (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-TORT _ AUSTIN _ Tort reformers' key bill is expected
to be voted out of a legislative subcommittee on Thursday, but it
might be too late. The bill languished for at least three weeks in
a special subcommittee created by Lt. Gov. Rick Perry to handle all
tort reform legislation. The subcommittee is chaired by Perry's
boyhood friend, Troy Fraser, who has positioned himself as the key
tort reform champion this year. Yet, he was unable to quickly get
the bill out of his own committee. The bill relates to how juries
assess blame _ and monetary damages _ against employers for civil
liability. (McCarthy, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
