<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN CENTRAL BANK SLASHES INTEREST RATES
</HEADLINE>
   (ac) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Confronted with an economic slowdown across
Europe, the European Central Bank surprised almost everybody
Thursday by cutting interest rates to one of the lowest levels the
continent has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction in the central bank's benchmark rate, from 3.0
percent to 2.5 percent, came hours after a smaller cut by the Bank
of England. It reflected a growing alarm that growth is stalling
across much of Europe and needed a boost by lowering the cost of
borrowing.
</P>
<P>
   There had been some expectation that rates would be lowered
Thursday. But the European Central Bank's cut was twice as deep as
had been anticipated. The announcement at about 12:20 p.m. Eastern
time, which came after European financial markets had closed,
ignited a broad rally on Wall Street, and major market indexes all
closed at record highs.
</P>
<P>
   The rate reduction also appeared to be a measure aimed at
Europe's political leaders, many of whom have pressured the bank
for months to juice up economic growth as a way to reduce
joblessness, which averages more than 10 percent across the
continent.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they reduced borrowing costs to such low levels, bank
officials warned once again that in their view, the only real
solution to high unemployment is through reforming Europe's heavy
regulation and costly social welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monetary policy is not the cause of structural unemployment,
nor is it the solution,'' said Wim Duisenberg, president of the
European Central Bank. ``Now it will become demonstrably clear that
monetary policy is not the solution to those problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's move marks the first major policy decision by
Europe's new central bank, which assumed its powers with the launch
of Europe's new single currency, the euro, on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   It came after months of pressure from political leaders,
particularly in Germany and France, for lower interest rates. Until
recently, bank officials had only stiffened their resistance at
each new call for cheaper money.
</P>
<P>
   But a stream of bleak economic data had made it increasingly
clear that European growth has slowed much more dramatically than
that of the United States. At the same time, inflation has all but
evaporated and many experts have begun to worry about a
deflationary price spiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inflation is not a danger, which enabled us to pay more
attention to the second objective of the European Central Bank,
which is to support the economy,'' said Duisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   He said the bank, which is governed by a board that includes the
central bank presidents of all 11 countries in the euro-zone,
decided to act more boldly than expected in order to put an end to
the second-guessing about future rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were afraid that only a smaller move would have led to
expectations in the future of more small moves,'' Duisenberg. ``Now
you can be sure: this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England's decision to reduce its benchmark rate from
5.50 percent to 5.25 percent was done independently of the European
Central Bank and was the latest in a series of reductions over the
past half year. There is some expectation that the Bank of England,
which does not coordinate its rate cuts with the rest of Europe,
might reduce rates further.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Mayer, a senior economist at Goldman Sachs in Frankfurt,
said Duisenberg clearly intended to put new pressure on European
political leaders to push ahead with economic changes aimed at
stimulating growth and job creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw the ball back into the politicians' court,'' Mayer
said. ``From now on, they won't be able to put the blame on
monetary policy.''
</P>
<P>
   At least initially, the decision seemed to have no real impact
on the euro. The euro has fallen more or less steadily against the
dollar, from $1.17 at its debut in January to about $1.07 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Though a rate reduction can lower the value of a currency, the
euro essentially remained stable Thursday because investors had
already anticipated a cut of some sort. Indeed, in a display of
buying on the rumor and selling on the news, the euro climbed
slightly before the bank made its announcement and then eased back
again later.
</P>
<P>
   European political leaders quickly expressed their pleasure at
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This signal can only boost confidence among economic actors
and international partners in the European Union's ability to
return to strong growth,'' said the European Commission, in a
statement released Thursday evening in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   In France, a spokesman for Finance Minister Dominique
Strauss-Kahn praised the rate cut as ``part of a rebalanced
European policy mix more supportive of growth and employment.''
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg insisted that the bank had not capitulated to
political pressure or changed its basic approach, which places top
priority on price stability. While lower rates can invigorate an
economy, they also can increase inflationary pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to deny that in any way we switched our monetary
policy,'' Duisenberg said. With inflation stable at less than 1
percent a year, he said, the bank now had the ``leeway'' to
stimulate the economy by lowering rates.
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg also said he was not concerned by the euro's slide
against the dollar. Indeed, he said, based on the value of a
``synthetic euro'' _ a hypothetical currency made up of the 11
national currencies before the euro officially was introduced _ its
value is about the same as it was one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But most economists were skeptical that the rate cut will do
much to strengthen European growth, because the problems derive
more from structural issues within Europe, such as high taxes and
rigid regulations, and from declining exports to Asia, Russia and
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth here was not weak because of high rates,'' said Mayer
of Goldman Sachs.
</P>
</TEXT>
