A1020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHEMICAL09-COX     04-08 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHEMICAL09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUP CITES CHEMICAL WEAPONS RISK IN KOSOVO
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If U.S. and allied ground troops invade Kosovo,
they could face the threat of chemical weapons produced and stored
at facilities in Serbia, a scientific group warned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Federation of American Scientists said it has confirmed the
existence of four facilities currently involved in the research and
development of chemical toxins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises the concern as yet unreported in the press that
(Yugoslavian President Slobodan) Milosevic may be planning to use
or threatening to use, as a last resort, chemical weapons in Kosovo
or in greater Serbia, especially if NATO ground troops enter the
conflict, which is becoming increasingly possible,'' the federation
said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Pentagon said, ``we don't have any
knowledge'' of the chemical weapons plants beyond news reports.
</P>
<P>
   The group identified sites in the Serbian towns of Baric,
Lucani, Krusevic, and Potoci. It said that the plants were
producing toxins such as sarin gas, mustard gas, and the vomiting
agent BZ in a weapons research program that dates back to the
1960s, when the region was controlled by a communist regime. Most
of the material is thought to be stored at Lucani.
</P>
<P>
   The report cited a 1991 Yugoslav public document which claimed
that the Yugoslav army had warheads with chemical weapons, a rocket
launcher system, and thousands of rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch, an international humanitarian group, first
reported on the chemical weapons facilities a year ago and
complained that U.S. officials were covering up the danger.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kavanaugh, spokesman for the Federation of American
Scientists, said that his group followed up with an investigation
helped by intelligence sources, Bosnians and two technicians who
had worked at the weapons plants. He said that his group was
publicizing the facilities now because the risk has not been
included in the debate over NATO action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy situation, but with the talk of ground
forces, I'd like to see the government address it,'' Kavanaugh
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kavanaugh said allied bombers could try to destroy the
facilities, but ``I don't think it could be done safely.'' He said
that he was concerned that ``inadvertent bombing may cause the
chemicals to leak to the civilian population.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
