<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USDA-BEEF-0409-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWS REPORT ON SCHOOL LUNCH PROGRAM TRIGGERS CONGRESSIONAL
INVESTIGATION
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Montgomery and Elliot Jaspin
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service 1999
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Reports of possibly tainted food in the nation's
School Lunch Program have triggered a congressional investigation
into the Department of Agriculture's management of all federal
nutrition programs, Sen. Tom Harkin announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter, Harkin, D-Iowa, asked the General Accounting Office
to ``examine, with respect to the prevention of food borne illness,
the procurement practices and procedures used in acquiring meat and
poultry for these programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkin took the action after a Cox Newspapers investigation into
an elementary school E. coli outbreak revealed the meat suspected
in the illnesses was purchased by the Agriculture Department from a
plant with a history of food safety violations. The Agriculture
Department donated the meat to the school for the School Lunch
Program.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve students at Finley Elementary School in rural Washington
fell ill within days of eating a taco lunch for which the donated
meat was used. Four of them required hospitalization 200 miles away
at Seattle's Children's Hospital, and one spent days on dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   State and local health officials concluded that the school's
taco lunch caused the illness, though tests of unused taco meat
failed to provide conclusive proof.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials knew the meat had been purchased by the USDA
from Northern States Beef in Nebraska as part of the federal lunch
program. But they didn't know the plant had been cited by federal
inspectors 171 times for critical sanitation violations in the 18
months before the purchase. Or that it had been linked to an E.
coli outbreak in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for ConAgra, the agribusiness giant that owns
Northern States, said that without scientific proof the plant can't
be blamed for the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Still, federal regulations require that the Agriculture
Department ``take into account'' such things as a plant's
sanitation history before allowing it to sell commodities to
federal nutrition programs. The Cox investigation found no such
evaluation was done of Northern States.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Harkin called the revelation that a plant with a
history of contamination violations could sell meet to the School
Lunch Program ``shocking.'' He specifically asked the GAO to
investigate whether the Agriculture Department's purchasing system
``adequately takes into account'' histories of plants.
</P>
<P>
   USDA operates several nutrition programs that provide meat and
poultry to such things as the Emergency Food Assistance Program and
the Nutrition Program for the Elderly. In addition to providing
food for the needy, the programs also prop up commodity prices
because of the USDA's high-volume purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Solomon, a spokesman for the USDA, said the agency is proud
to provide the ``safest food supply in the world,'' and said they
look forward to the review to be done by the GAO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome any efforts to make it even better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
