<HEADER>
A1029 &Cx1f; tab-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-ADVISOR     04-08 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-ADVISORY-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATO bombings aren't likely to stop the civil war in Kosovo.
Why? Find out from Chris Hedges, a Nieman Fellow at Harvard
University, who was The New York Times' Balkan Bureau Chief from
1995 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ___ The following series, adapted from the forthcoming issue of
Foreign Affairs, has moved on the wire in the ``k'' commentary and
``a'' general news categories. ___
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part I: THE REBEL VOICE in KOSOVO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,400 words) Rising from the fetid hovels of Pristina and the
concrete-block family farms of rural Kosovo is the newest political
and military force to beset the Balkans _ the Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA). (slugged: BC-KOSOVO-ARMY-ONE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part II: INSIDE the KOSOVO LIBERATION ARMY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,500 words) ``On April 6, 1998, in the town of Jablanica, 30
miles north of Dakovica, I bumped into a group of surly KLA
fighters, dressed in a motley collection of uniforms and equipped
with an odd assortment of hunting rifles, pistols, automatic
weapons and hunting knives. Killings by Belgrade, and the
humiliation of 10 years of abuse, had left them seething with
resentment.'' (slugged: BC-KOSOVO-ARMY-TWO-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part III: KOSOVO BECOMES A POLITICAL TIME BOMB &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,500 words) The elements of a political time bomb, ticking
louder and louder while the world looked the other way, developed
over decades in Kosovo. In Serb jails, people were beaten and
tortured, usually while chained to radiators. Some simply vanished.
But the Serbs lived as if Kosovo were the raj, with all civil and
state jobs and a private police force to ensure their privileged
status in the birthplace of modern Serb nationalism. (slugged:
BC-KOSOVO-ARMY-THREE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Part IV: THE KLA IS WILDLY UNLIKELY TO HAND OVER ITS GUNS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,500 words) The Serbs have huge stockpiles of heavy weapons
they have yet to unleash, while the KLA probably has 30,000
automatic weapons, made available at bargain prices after Albanian
military arsenals were looted in the spring 1997 economic meltdown.
Settling in for a long fight, the rebels aim to acquire German
antitank weapons, heavy machine guns, sniper rifles and
rocket-propelled grenades. (slugged: BC-KOSOVO-ARMY-FOUR-NYTSF)
</P>
