<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT     04-08 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUG'S FIRST MOVIE 
10 THINGS I HATE ABOUT YOU 
EDTV
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug's First Movie
</P>
<P>
   An animated film based on the ABC Saturday morning series
``Disney's Doug'' &QL; 
with the voices of Thomas McHugh, Fred Newman, Chris Phillips,
Constance Shulman, Frank Welker, others.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Maurice Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Rated G.
</P>
<P>
   87 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Any movie that tries to link a Valentine's Day dance with a lake
monster has much ground to cover and this one bustles right along.
Doug Funnie, not so much a geek as a sweet guy, is sure he has
spotted something weird swimming around in Bluff Lake, the
principal body of water in the town of Bluffington and receptacle
for pollutants flowing from Bluffco Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Concomitant is the dance at the high school. Doug wants to help
plan the event as a means of getting quality time with the cute and
nice Patti Mayonnaise. A complicating element here is that Patti is
being pursued by Guy Graham, the breezily insolent editor of the
school paper, who is so cocksure of himself that he writes his
stories in advance of the events they report.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the monster turns out to be a cuddly big blue thing
grounded by the toxic soup. Doug names him Herman Melville and they
become friends. The media go crazy. Herman goes underground (or
under Doug's bed). Later he dons a blond wig and shows up as an
exchange student at school.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bluff, Bluffco's founder, chafes at the bad publicity and
determines to get rid of Herman. But Bill's weakness is his brash
daughter, Bebe. What Bebe says Daddy does, and later on little Bebe
will want Daddy to stop being such a jerk.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, though, Bluff enlists Guy Graham to help do in
Herman, but the editor telegraphs the plot by writing up the
results beforehand. Can Doug save his friend? And how is it going
with Patti?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: A robot acts up but none too scarily. ``Violence is
only for those who have run out of good ideas,'' Doug says.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   Ages 3-8. This is truly a film for the littlest ones. The
situations are drawn simply enough to hold interest and
consistently bring guffaws.
</P>
<P>
   10 Things I Hate About You
</P>
<P>
   Julia Stiles, Heath Ledger, Joseph-Gordon Levitt, Larisa
Oleynik, Andrew Keegan, Larry Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Gil Junger.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   94 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare can't get a rest these days. Here he's at Padua High
School, near Seattle, for the taming of a teen-age shrew named
Katarina Stratford (Ms. Stiles).
</P>
<P>
   Kat is actually a headstrong girl who speaks plainly and has
little use for adolescent banalities. That gets her kicked out of
class a lot and makes her anathema with schoolmates, especially
boys, who don't rank highly in Kat's estimation and wouldn't
approach her on a bet.
</P>
<P>
   At home her aversion to the opposite sex is a relief to her
father, Walter (Miller), an obsessively protective obstetrician who
craves, as he puts it, ``the deep sleep of fathers whose daughters
aren't out being impregnated.'' But his no-dating policy distresses
Kat's sweet younger sister, Bianca (Ms. Oleynik), who would just
like to enjoy her teen-age airheadedness in peace and see a boy now
and then.
</P>
<P>
   Walter thinks he's slamming the door on that notion when he
agrees to let Bianca date if Kat dates. How likely is that? Even
the slightest possibility interests Cameron (Levitt), who is deeply
smitten by Bianca. In developments too convoluted to detail,
Cameron teams with a vain model (Keegan) to buy the services of a
roguish fellow named Patrick Verona ( Ledger). Verona's job is to
soften up Kat to the point where she will go out with him.
</P>
<P>
   Verona is rumored to have set a state trooper on fire. Like Kat,
though, he's really a decent person who finally wins her with a
boffo rendition of ``Can't Take My Eyes Off of You,'' which he
belts out over a public address system while being chased around
the football stadium by security guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet love renew thy force,'' someone says. Kat composes a
sonnet for Verona and the Stratford girls head out on big dates.
``No ritual animal slaughters,'' Walter warns. But other treachery
is ahead.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: There's some scuffling at the prom but nothing
serious.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: The subject is often referred to, and in a couple of
instances people are on the verge of indulging.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: A good amount.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   Under age 9? No.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 10-12? The language may be objectionable, but the film is
good clean fun, or clean enough.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 13 and up? This is their movie.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT     04-08 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: their movie.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EdTV
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McConaughey, Jenna Elfman, Woody Harrelson, Sally
Kirkland, Martin Landau, Ellen DeGeneres, Rob Reiner, Dennis
Hopper, Elizabeth Hurley.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ron Howard.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ``The Truman Show'' opened the territory, but here's a
warmer, fuzzier comedy about taking an ordinary person and putting
his every move on television. Cynthia the programming executive
(Ms. DeGeneres) has the idea. ``Put a guy on TV and watch his head
roll down the highway,'' she says. He doesn't have to be any good.
In fact, it's better if he's bad.
</P>
<P>
   At first bad doesn't quite describe Ed Pekurny (McConaughey),
the good-looking if otherwise undistinguished 31-year-old video
clerk selected for the project. With cameras everywhere in his
life, Ed responds by scratching his erogenous zones when he wakes
up in the morning and recommending ``Smokey and the Bandit'' to
patrons at the store.
</P>
<P>
   The network is about to pull the plug. ``Yes, Whitaker, I know
they shoot horses,'' Cynthia tells her boss (Reiner). But hold on.
The country is getting hooked. Ed's loudmouth brother, Ray
(Harrelson), has a sensitive girlfriend named Shari (Ms. Elfman).
Soon she takes up with the gentle Ed, with cameras recording every
clinch.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the country doesn't like Shari, who gets a 71
percent disapproval rating in USA Today. Heartbroken, she removes
herself from camera range, or tries to.
</P>
<P>
   In parallel story threads, Ed's mother (Ms. Kirkland), her
companion (Landau) and Ed's estranged father (Hopper) get their
linen washed spectacularly before an enthralled nation. But Ed is
fed up and wants to quit. Trouble is, Whitaker won't let him.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: None.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Ed has a steamy tussle with a model (Ms. Hurley) on a
dining room table and there is some nudity.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: Much.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   Ages 3-9: Inappropriate for obvious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 10-12: The usual guidelines apply according to individual
rules and tastes. Keep in mind that for all the profanity and the
like, this is a down-to-earth movie about people who make some
interesting discoveries about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 13 And Up: Teen-agers are more than ready.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
