<P>
   The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The Yugoslav government asserted
Thursday that ``peace has been restored in Kosovo,'' declared an
end to its military offensive and urged all refugees to return home
while new political arrangements are negotiated for the province.
The government announcement said that under an accord between
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and the non-violent Kosovo
Albanian leader, Ibrahim Rugova, ``a process of return of displaced
persons from Kosovo, predominantly of Albanian nationality, has
been initiated.'' It appealed to all citizens of Kosovo to remain
home or to return there, and ``to live together and cooperate.'' By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO's military and civilian
authorities clashed publicly today for the first time in the 16-day
Kosovo bombing campaign, disagreeing whether Gen. Wesley Clark, the
alliance's American commander, had authority to bomb
state-controlled Serbian television off the air. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels, Belgium) _ President Slobodan
Milosevic's sudden decision to seal Kosovo's border took NATO by
surprise, and officials say they are now struggling to deal with
the consequences. With thousands of ethnic Albanians trudging away
from the border area, NATO needs to take special care to avoid
civilian casualities. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT (Washington) _ A look at Madeleine Albright, her
State Department and how they are weathering the crisis. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Dateline to kum, Albania) _ Serb forces were
positioning tanks and artillery along the Kosovo border Thursday as
the mystery deepened over the fate of tens of thousands of refugees
who vanished last night when the Serbs suddenly turned their
convoys back from the border. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ Even as the Yugoslav leadership
announced that separatist guerrillas in Kosovo were defeated, and
peace was being restored to the southern Serbian province, the
Kosovo Liberation Army reported heavy combat in several areas. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIEF (Washington) _ U.S. developments on refugee
relief. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VIETNAM (Hanoi) _ The Vietnamese, veterans of a U.S.
bombing campaign, excoriate the NATO attacks on Yugoslavia. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FAMILY (Dateline to kum, Albania) _ The saga of one
refugee family. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GENOCIDE (Belgrade) _ Aca Singer, a Jewish leader in
Belgrade and a survivor of Auschwitz who says he lost 65 family
members in the Holocaust, condemns all sides for use of word
``genocide.'' He said Auschwitz was genocide, not this. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHILDREN (Geneva, Switzerland) _ The head of the U.N.
Children's Fund says that increasing numbers of children fleeing
Kosovo are being found unaccompanied, and fears that the number may
rise substantially unless steps are taken to ensure families are
kept intact. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Defense Secretary Cohen visits
NATO bases at Aviano and Ramstein before returning to Washington.
By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
