<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Interesting proposition, but no sale  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Believing that one suit, one pair of shoes, one shirt and a
necktie are wardrobe enough for any practical man, I rarely darken
the doorway of a clothing store.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, though, I chanced upon a sale too attractive to pass
up. And it wasn't in a store at all, but right out in the open air.
</P>
<P>
   A man in a sidewalk stall was selling sleeveless shirts _ tank
tops, I believe they're called _ under a sign that said,
(ital)Exercise your constitutional right to bare arms.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``They're marked way down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How far down?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Drastically,'' he said. ``It's a Proposition B morning-after
special.''
</P>
<P>
   I held one up for size, though with tank tops one size pretty
much fits all.
</P>
<P>
   On the front was the outline of a human figure, with a
bull's-eye in the middle, and the admonition, (ital)Ask questions
later.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The printing on the back said, (ital)A machine gun means peace
of mind.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' I told the man. ``I'm not wild about the
color.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean you're against freedom?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' I said. ``But I really don't care to make a
political statement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen,'' he said, ``you can't sit this one out on the
sidelines. You have to take a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   I could tell from the funny little shine in his eyes that he was
a man I wouldn't care to aggravate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your position on trench mortars and shoulder-fired
missiles?'' he wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell the truth, I really haven't thought that one
through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And how do you see Charlton Heston?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was Moses, you know. In `The Ten Commandments.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. I saw it 30 nights in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You must have loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, actually, after about the third or fourth time I
(ital)hated it!(end ital) It was 40 years ago, and I was staying in
a cheap pension in a poor little town in Spain. They were showing
it outdoors on the wall of a building across from my room, and it
went until 1 or 2 o'clock every morning. By the time that month was
over I knew the whole sound track _ every line. In English and
Spanish both. It cost me a lot of sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Moses was no pushover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A (ital)non sequitur(end ital) perhaps, but I certainly
wouldn't argue with you,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moses was no pushover, and neither is Charlton Heston. He sees
the danger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That Janet Reno and her minions will come into our homes and
places of business and confiscate the weapons that we need to have
if we're going to maintain a well-regulated militia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's where we part company,'' I told him, as gently
as I could. ``I just don't see Janet Reno coming to take away my
hunting gun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How about her minions?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Them either.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So I take it you voted against Proposition B.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How I voted is my business. Let's just say I did my duty as a
citizen, as I saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, then,'' he said, ``what about turkeys?''
</P>
<P>
   The shift from Janet Reno to turkeys threw me a little
off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild turkeys,'' he said. ``Will you be out there after them
this spring?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, yes, of course. I never miss a season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then maybe we'll run into each other in the woods,'' he said,
proving that people can disagree, even about big things, and still
find common ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I won't sell you a shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all right. The color's wrong anyway,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   And walked quickly on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
