<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURANT OWNER IS HIGH ON `HOOF' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ When Rod Anderson acquired the Hereford House
in 1987, he issued five W-2 forms for each position at the
restaurant. That's an average of five persons filling a single job
in a year. That's a lot of staff turnover.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 440 persons filled 250 positions at the original
location and the newer Leawood, Kan., location _ less than two
persons for each position.
</P>
<P>
   His turnover turnaround lies partly in the acronym HOOF, short
for Helping Others Obtain a Future.
</P>
<P>
   Some background: Restaurants are notorious for high turnover.
Some people make restaurant work a career, but many others use it
as an interim job while in school or training. Turnover of 200 to
300 percent a year is common.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson wanted to reduce turnover by improving incentives for
long-term and transient employees. He improved health- and
life-insurance benefits and provided 401(k) investment
opportunities for employees 21 and older who worked at the company
at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Then he focused on the transient employees _ typically students
working their way through school.
</P>
<P>
   Through his plan, Anderson last year contributed $38,000 to help
at least 30 employees pay for their education. Tuition
contributions are based on the number of hours worked, and the
amount increases with each year the student works for the company.
Contributions max out at $600 a semester, or $1,200 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Burak, a University of Missouri-Kansas City history
major, joined the plan four months after taking a Hereford House
job. She said it was the reason she applied there, and the reason
she's still there after three years.
</P>
<P>
   Community college students are finding that HOOF contributions
can cover their full tuition costs, Anderson said. Students who
pursue more expensive education or training _ he's had everything
from chiropractic to barber students _ still have a valuable
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The company benefits, too. The HOOF expense pays for itself by
keeping experienced workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experienced servers sell more food. Their bills average $1
higher per visit than those of inexperienced servers,'' Anderson
said. ``If the experienced server has 150 visits a week, averaging
$1 more per check, it doesn't take long to see why keeping
experience pays.''
</P>
<P>
   HOOF also helps attendance, he said. Because it reimburses
tuition based on hours worked, students ``tend to come to work
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have turnover, sure,'' Anderson said, ``but this
helps keep workers at least for the duration of their education.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurateurs, like all service providers, compete for capable,
dependable help. Anderson thinks the program allows him to tap into
a pool of motivated student workers.
</P>
<P>
   Publicity has been word of mouth. But, as any business operator
knows, word of mouth is powerful. Five workers moved to the
Hereford House from another restaurant after one of them learned
about HOOF.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all in school and all still here,'' he said. ``When
they know they can get up to $1,200 a year from me, that counts for
something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
