<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPOSITIONS IN THE MICROSOFT CASE TO BE MADE PUBLIC  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The judge trying the antitrust case against
Microsoft Corp. is likely to find himself in the unusual position
later this month of reading articles about testimony in the trial
that has not yet been heard in court.
</P>
<P>
   That is one result of two orders Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
of U.S. District Court issued over the last week to comply with a
1913 law giving the public access to depositions taken in antitrust
cases.
</P>
<P>
   One order, issued on Wednesday evening, makes public transcripts
of more than 100 depositions taken by both sides over the last year
or so. Some have been entered into evidence in court, but many
others have not.
</P>
<P>
   These documents, tens of thousands of pages of testimony, will
be given to lawyers representing various news organizations,
including The New York Times, that petitioned the court for access
under the 1913 law. Copies of the depositions will also be given to
the government Printing Office, which will make them available to
those who pay a printing fee.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a second order issued on April 1 allows members of
the public, including members of the news media, to attend when new
depositions are taken in the coming weeks in preparation for
rebuttal testimony, which will be heard in court beginning next
month. That means news organizations will be able to publish
articles about the testimony before any of it is entered into
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It also means that Jackson, who is trying the case without a
jury, may read about statements made in depositions that the
lawyers trying the case would rather not use in court because the
statements do not help their cases.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Jackson has heard only the excerpts from depositions
that lawyers have found useful to show him. He has indicated that
he does read some news articles about the case. He has referred to
news articles in questions he has asked witnesses or lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, citing the 1913 law, several news organizations
asked to be allowed to attend when Justice Department lawyers took
a deposition from Bill Gates, Microsoft's chairman. Jackson
reluctantly agreed, but Microsoft appealed his ruling to the U.S.
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the appeals court upheld Jackson's ruling, and over
the following months the parties worked out the details of how the
depositions would be made public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1858EDT &QL; 
