A1057 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BEAVER-NAT     04-08 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BEAVER-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  AND THEN THERE WERE TWO: PARK SERVICE BLAMES A PAIR OF BEAVERS
FOR TREE DAMAGE
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, April 8, -- Call them the Bonnie and Clyde of the
Blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   The Tidal Basin terrorizing beaver who officials thought had
acted alone in eating through four of the beloved cherry blossom
trees, and nearly gnawing down four others, is now believed to have
an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   A National Park Service officer spotted the couple yesterday as
they went for a swim together in the Tidal Basin. The pair had been
lying low, causing no further damage Wednesday night, following a
day of intense publicity about the tree-toppling spree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a quiet night, but we are not out of the woods yet,''
said Julia Long, a National Park Service biology technician. ``Now
that we know there are two, which could mean the start of a colony,
we need to get them away from here and to a more appropriate
location.''
</P>
<P>
   The brazen beavers have eluded park officers for the last week
while enjoying a reign of terror on the celebrated trees at the
height of the Cherry Blossom Festival. The beavers have also eaten
through five white cedar trees -- one right in front of a National
Park Service office.
</P>
<P>
   Park Service officials yesterday hired Adcock Trapping Service,
a Maryland-based professional trapping service, for $1500 to
humanely trap the beavers, said park service spokesman Earle
Kittleman.
</P>
<P>
   The trappers will likely begin work Monday. Officials hope to
catch the beavers in a trap that looks like a suitcase opened on
its side, by luring them in with some branches -- not from cherry
blossom trees.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers typically mate for life, and start colonies, which
produce dams in waterways. They eat tree bark, and use the trees to
build their dams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about the trees and the beaver both,''
Kittleman said. ``The beavers are not adversarial, they just need
to be moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Park officials have been trying to discourage the beavers by
encasing the gnawed tree trunks in wire mesh, so they can't finish
the job. Each time a beaver topples a tree, it is quickly removed
and the stump is cut low. That way the beavers can't use the trees
to build a dam.
</P>
<P>
   To park service officials who have tried to balance the desire
to protect the trees and the wildlife, the beaver situation has
been particularly taxing.
</P>
<P>
   The trees, a gift from Japan in 1912, attract thousands of
tourists to Washington D.C., when the pink and white flowers
blossom in the Spring. The trees were at the peak of their full
bloom this past week, when the beavers struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beavers live near water and eat trees, which makes the Tidal
Basin an appealing and beautiful home,'' Long said. ``But the trees
happen to be cherry blossoms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-TECH-COST-ART-     04-08 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-TECH-COST-ART-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNOLOGIES SAVE LIVES BUT RAISE HEALTH INSURANCE COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Mich., Pa., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Managed health care plans and the Medicare program have had some
success slowing growth in spending for doctors, hospitals and home
care agencies. But managed care has been much less successful
reining in spending on new life-enhancing medical devices and
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Advances in technology _ from laser treatments to the latest
surgical procedures with miniature instruments _ are one of the
main reasons for the re-acceleration in the overall costs of health
insurance, after several years of slow or zero growth. Sales of new
medical devices in the United States rose 30 percent the last five
years, outpacing the 22 percent rise over all in health care
spending and all other categories except prescription drug sales,
which were up 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``About half the growth in real per-capita health costs is
associated with medical technology'' including advances in
procedures and drugs, said Mark Freeland, deputy director of the
National Health Statistics Group in the Health Care Financing
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Increased medical costs were cited Thursday by Humana Inc., a
managed care company with 6.2 million members, as it announced that
its first-quarter earnings would fall below Wall Street's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, many of the new procedures are promoted as
reducing costs: a $3 million laser device that provides an
alternative to brain surgery can pay for itself by reducing the
costs that surgical procedures and lengthy hospital recoveries
would have previously required. But health plans are finding that
over all, technology costs are surging, in large part because the
new procedures are more available or more attractive to more people
_ fostering a demand that insurers cannot stem.
</P>
<P>
   Patients who are hesitant about traditional open surgery, for
example, will eagerly agree to minimally invasive procedures with
miniature instruments to repair heart valves or remove defective
gall bladders.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern was clear at Health Partners, a big, nonprofit
Minnesota health maintenance organization. In only two years, from
1996 to 1998, the HMO counted double-digit growth in the number of
procedures for every thousand members in eight categories,
including some of the most expensive: brain and nervous system
procedures, heart and artery surgery, orthopedics like hip and knee
replacements and organ transplants. Premature infants were another
big-ticket item.
</P>
<P>
   At Children's Hospital in Minneapolis, where many patients are
tiny premature babies, ``there has been a technological explosion
and a tremendous increase in survival rates and the good news is,
we did not have an increase in extremely damaged children,'' said
Dr. Ronald Hoekstra. But with the advances, he added, costs are
bound to go up.
</P>
<P>
   One of Hoekstra's patients, Simon Hagman, a strapping 30-pounder
who celebrated his third birthday late last month, has already made
a personal contribution to the economics of high technology health
care. Health Partners, his family's plan, spent $1.2 million on
life-saving care for Simon, whose birth only 22.5 weeks after
conception was dangerously premature.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, born weighing 1 pound, 4 ounces and only 12 inches in
height, lived for 14 months in the neonatal unit at Children's
Hospital. With the help of sophisticated procedures and technology,
he overcame three heart attacks, several bouts of pneumonia and a
threat of blindness. He went home, with 24-hour nursing, still
dependent for a time on an oxygen system that augmented his
miniature lung power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miraculously, Simon survived without brain damage,'' said his
mother, Tracey Hagman.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen years ago, there would have been small hope for an
infant with Simon's precarious medical profile. For premature
babies with severe problems who did qualify for the less-advanced
treatments available then, the medical charges were about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The new drugs and procedures were welcomed as essential to
excellent care. ``It's the right thing to do, but it's very
expensive,'' said George Halvorson, chief executive of Health
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, our premiums are going to go up, and people are
going to have to pay more for care,'' he added. There were 345
cases in 1998 on which Health Partners spent $50,000 or more. That
was more than double the number in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While some experts say the spread of managed care will slow the
introduction of advanced devices, that is clearly not the case at
many HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extraordinarily difficult for HMOs to put up barriers
for care that is valuable,'' said Michael Chernew, a health
economist at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Most big managed care plans rely on advice from panels of
medical experts to recommend acceptance or rejection of new
technology. For example, a Blue Cross advisory panel endorsed a
number of new developments last year, but the group determined that
a heavily marketed new electron beam CT scanner was not as
effective in diagnosing heart disease as the older methods, said
Dr. Alan Garber, a professor of medicine at Stanford University who
is a member of the the panel. Such panels appraise the scientific
value of products and procedures; insurers typically weigh the
recommendations as well as cost-effectiveness in deciding whether
to approve the innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the advanced devices are big and complicated. Among the
most popular are stents, the tiny metal tubes that prop open
clogged blood vessels. In part because of new competition that cut
the price, sales of stents exploded last year to $1.4 billion, up
40 percent from 1997, said Vivian R. Wohl, a health care securities
analyst with Merrill Lynch. Sales of implantable defibrilators,
which shock faltering hearts, rose 20 percent, to $1.2 billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other new products are in demand: a roboticly assisted gamma
knife to attack tumors deep inside the brain, lasers to improve
vision by sculpting corneas, ultrasensitive blood oxygenators to
keep premature infants alive and inch-long metal spinal implants to
relieve back pain.
</P>
<P>
   And there is much more to come. Medical devices still being
tested include one to position a functioning heart in what is
called beating heart surgery; minimally invasive devices to thwart
blood clots and prevent strokes, advanced insulin pumps that
continuously adjust to changes in a diabetic's blood sugar; devices
that use microwaves, lasers or ultrasound to treat enlarged male
prostate glands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to see a flood of these things,'' Garber said.
``Most of these new technologies do contribute something to improve
health,'' he added. ``But the cost pressures are enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   Health care costs, to be sure, are rising for a number of
reasons, including an aging population. While the cost pressures of
many factors can be estimated with reasonable accuracy, technology
is a moving target, with some prices falling and the number of
sophisticated procedures rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the biggest impacts are not clear until years after a
procedure is introduced, as it gets better and physicians find more
uses for it,'' said Paul B. Ginsburg, president of the nonprofit
Center for Studying Health System Change in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And a new procedure can often be used by a larger pool of
patients than before, raising overall costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get better at doing a procedure, through experience,
you are willing to do it on older people and frailer people, as
happened with coronary bypass grafts,'' said Joseph Newhouse, a
health economist at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Bypasses were also improved in ways that made them more
expensive. ``The product in 1999 is not what it was in 1990,''
Garber noted. Defying expectations, the number of open heart bypass
surgeries kept on growing, even after a wildly popular alternative,
the angioplasty balloon-and-stent procedure to repair arteries,
took off, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking far out, there are some possibilities that new kinds
of technologies might be so powerful as to reduce the cost of
health care,'' said Stuart Altman, a Brandeis University professor
who is chairman of the Council on the Economic Impact of Health
System Changes, a nonprofit group supported by the Robert Wood
Johnson Foundation. ``But for the next 5 to 10 years, if not
longer, the general consensus is that technology will continue to
increase health care spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, however, studies have shown that some of the latest
drugs and devices can save money. Last month, scientists at the New
York University Medical Center said that patients who required
surgery for defective heart valves spent four fewer days in the
hospital after a minimally invasive procedure, compared with
traditional open chest surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And in brain surgery, 45 American hospitals and surgery centers
have purchased $3 million gamma knife systems, which use radiation
instead of a risky cutting procedure to zap tumors.
</P>
<P>
   One patient, Joseph Keenan, had put off surgery for years on a
tumor that was interfering with his hearing and balance. Keenan,
55, a professor of family medicine at the University of Minnesota,
finally had the procedure done about a year ago with a gamma knife.
</P>
<P>
   He checked into the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., at 5 a.m.,
had the procedure and was sent home by 10 the same morning. Two
days later, he flew to China for a long-scheduled lecture tour and
a round of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' Keenan said.
</P>
<P>
   At Health Partners, new devices are screened by expert
committees in each area, said Dr. George Isham, chief health
officer of the Minnesota HMO. The gamma knife reviewers, for
example, included a brain cancer specialist from Mayo, a radiation
oncologist and a brain surgeon from the University of Minnesota, a
brain surgeon from the Park Nicollet Clinic, a big Twin Cities
medical group, and a neurologist from Health Partners' own medical
group.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing scientific reports, the experts concluded that
the knife was effective. The HMO then decided to pay for the
procedures, Isham said.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center, which pioneered
gamma knife surgery in the United States, Dr. L. Dade Lunsford said
that studies had shown an ``enormous return on the initial
technological investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunsford, who is chairman of neurosurgery, said the gamma knife
was increasingly used to destroy hearing-nerve tumors like
Keenan's. Typically not cancerous, they are a problem for 2,000
Americans each year.
</P>
<P>
   Patients return to work in days instead of months, he said.
Complications are rare and the need for additional surgery has been
eliminated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total cost of traditional surgery was $30,000,'' he said.
The charge for Keenan at Mayo was $18,000, paid by Health Partners.
</P>
<P>
   As for Simon Hagman, the premature baby, he is ``very well
nourished and improving with time,'' said Hoekstra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can put a price on a life,'' Simon's mother
said. ``It was worth every dollar spent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
