<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AID-09-COX     04-08 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AID-09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    WESTERN POWERS RUSHING IN RATIONS FOR 500,000 EXILES WHO MAY
STAY IN ALBANIA
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS AIR BASE, Albania Nearly overwhelmed by refugees from
Kosovo, the Western powers and aid agencies on Thursday were
rushing in food to sustain up to half a million ethnic Albanian
exiles who they fear may land permanently inside this poor and
lawless country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I am down to a 36-hour supply of rations,'' said
Ramiro Lopes-DaSilva, the chief of logistics for the U.N. Food
Program, the main agency that is keeping the 280,000 Kosovo
refugees already in Albania from starving.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the U.N.'s stockpiled rations in Albania
dwindled toward exhaustion. Then at noon last Saturday, NATO
launched a military special operation from Ramstein Air Base,
Germany, aimed at airlifting hundreds of tons of ready-to-eat meals
to replenish the U.N. stockpiles before hunger set in.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 48 hours, NATO military transports and chartered
jets have been landing or taking off about every 15 minutes at this
former Albanian Air Force fighter base, hauling in 107 tons of
emergency rations from U.S. military depots in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Huge Albanian commercial flatbed trucks rolled onto the runway
every few hours and the crates were hoisted aboard by olive-painted
forklifts operated by U.S. troops from NATO bases in Europe. Most
of the trucks headed off for the 10-hour road trip to the largest
concentration of Kosovo refugees, spread out at a string of
makeshift camps near Kukes in northeast Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Lopes-DaSilva, a veteran of U.N. emergency refugee relief crises
from Rwanda to Angola, estimated that the 107,000 daily rations
flown in by NATO will feed the masses of Kosovo refugees in Albania
for only about 18 hours. More food is en route to Albania by ship
and air.
</P>
<P>
   With rain and lightning expected for the next three days, aid
workers were making emergency plans to rush supplies to a new
cluster of 14,000 Kosovo refugees who suddenly materialized
overnight in a remote border region of southern Albania, near the
town of Korce.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said they had been transported to Korce by
authorities in the neighboring Serb-majority nation of Macedonia,
whose politically shaky government has decided to close several
temporary transit camps rather than grant permanent sanctuary to
Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Another 20,000 Kosovo refugees were expected to cross on
Thursday into Korce from Macedonia, and the number from Macedonia
could ultimately reach ``just less than 100,000,'' Lopes-DaSilva
said.
</P>
<P>
   For several hours Thursday, three Swiss helicopters sat idle
next to a runway, with crates of American ready-to-eat meals
stacked on pallets waiting to be transported to Korce for the new
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In the early afternoon, U.N. officials were forced to scrub the
Korce flights, probably until Friday. Western officials at the air
bus said top Swiss military authorities in Tirana and Switzerland
had not approved a U.N. request for the flights and were checking
on the safety of flying to a potentially hostile border region.
</P>
<P>
   One source of unease about helicopter flights to Korce is that
the refugees were clustered very close to the Macedonian frontier.
A NATO colonel waiting by the runway said that the Korce landing
zone may be within the range of SA-7 and SA-14 shoulder-mounted
anti-aircraft missiles thought to be in the hands of Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   As the numbers in Korce swelled, another stream of terrified
ethnic Albanian refugees was entering Albania by crossing south
across the border from Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 refugees a day have been leaving Montenegro, the
semi-autonomous province of Serbia whose fragile democratic
government has been shaken by rumors of a military coup engineered
by Serbian leader Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always did expect some spillover from the conflict in
Kosovo, but the stocks have been depleted much faster than we
expected. Right now, we are working on a worst-case scenario of
having to feed half a million refugees here in Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, the UN Food Program had stockpiled enough food
in and near Albania to feed 200,000 Kosovo refugees for one month,
he said. But optimism surrounding the American-engineered
Rambouillet peace conference in February led the U.N. to slash its
stockpile dedicated to a potential Kosovo crisis. By the time the
Rambouillet talks collapsed, the U.N. Food
</P>
<P>
   Program had stockpiles to sustain just 60,000 refugees for one
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we got it all wrong, and our stockpile went
down much faster than expected,'' said Lopes-DaSilva.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Air Force Col. Clifford Bray, a military special ops
veteran who was dispatched here from Germany last weekend to
oversee the airlift, expressed apprehension Thursday that bustling
air traffic at this lightly defended air bus could attract the
attention of Serb commandos or anti-American terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albania is one of the highest terrorist threat environments in
the world,'' said Bray in an interview. ``We feel it is almost a
critical situation from a terrorist perspective, and we are taking
aggressive steps to increase security.''
</P>
<P>
   As food crates were being unloaded, U.S. Air Force troops were
also busy preparing to ring the air base with stronger fences,
obstacles against truck bombers and shields against snipers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is, among other things, a sizable criminal element in
some regions,'' said Bray. ``We have some evidence that they are
already observing us.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most tangible concerns, said one senior NATO officer
at the base, is that the Saudi revolutionary Osama bin Laden is
reported to have active affiliates in Albania's mafia-plagued
northern regions. Bin Laden is the accused mastermind of last
year's American embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby Albanian capital Tirana, meanwhile, international
aid chiefs also expressed worries about thousands of missing
Kosovar Albanians who had been fleeing Serbian police and military
actions inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 60,000 to 70,000 fleeing Kosovar Albanians had been
trapped in a no man's land in Kosovo, outside the Macedonian
border. After urgent pressure from NATO and from United Nations'
relief agencies, the Macedonians began transporting the refugees
into camps mostly in Albania on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can account for between 50,000 to 55,000 of these people,''
said Nicholas Morris, special envoy to the region for the United
Nations High Commission for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   His agency is investigating what happened to the missing
refugees and holds ``the greatest concern for anybody who was
actually expelled back into Kosovo,'' Morris said at a news
conference in Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day the border crossing in Kukes in northern
Albania was closed on Thursday, and relief officials have expressed
fears that fleeing refugees were turned back there to be used as
human shields to stop NATO bombing in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers correspondent Charles Holmes contributed from
the Montenegro-Albania border.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
