<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECYCLE-0409-COX     04-08 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECYCLE-0409-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAXPAYER SUBSIDIES SAID TO DISCOURAGE RECYCLING
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    With attached fact box
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The recycling movement in America is being hindered
by government subsidies and tax breaks for industries whose
products compete with recycled materials, a coalition of tax reform
advocates, environmentalists and recycling groups charged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And other taxpayers are picking up the tab to the tune of $2.6
billion every year, says a report issued by the GrassRoots
Recycling Network, Friends of the Earth, Taxpayers for Common Sense
and the Materials Efficiency Network.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``Welfare for Waste,'' called for elimination of tax
breaks and subsidies for the timber, mining and energy industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting these federal taxpayer subsidies for timber, mining
and energy will save taxpayers $13 billion over the next five years
and is essential to leveling the playing field for recycling
businesses,'' said Bill Sheehan, coordinator of the GrassRoots
Recycling Network, a group based in Athens, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Annual federal support for timber, mining and energy industries
totals $811 million, $496 million and $1.3 billion, respectively,
the report charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is real money to real people who pay taxes,'' the report
said. ``While the dollar level may seem relatively small, that kind
of preferential economic treatment is immensely significant when
compared to its potential impact on the much smaller recycling and
reuse industries.''
</P>
<P>
   The value of all used materials furnished to recycling
manufacturers has ranged from $16 billion to $19 billion a year for
several years, the critics of the subsidies and tax breaks said.
Thus, the purported $2.6 billion in subsidies to competing products
is worth roughly 15 percent of the value of the recycling
industry's feedstocks.
</P>
<P>
   The tax breaks and subsidies have been attacked for years by
environmentalists and taxpayer advocacy groups. They are defended
by the favored industries on a variety of grounds, including the
preservation of American jobs, maintaining energy independence and
protection of vital industries.
</P>
<P>
   The report released Thursday is the first to relate the
controversial provisions to efforts to encourage recycling in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing owners of timberland to pay capital gains taxes on
their timber sales, rather than the higher federal income taxes,
costs other taxpayers an average of $635 million a year, the report
said. In addition, so-called ``below cost'' federal timber sales
cost an estimated $111 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only slightly more than 40 percent of the paper discarded in
the United States is recycled,'' the report stated. If wood
products were not subsidized, recycled paper would be more
competitive, the four groups said.
</P>
<P>
   Recycled aluminum consumes 95 percent less electricity than
aluminum smelters. However every ton of newly smelted aluminum is
the beneficiary of a $200 government subsidy in cut-rate power that
the Bonneville Power Administration provides aluminum smelters --
and every other power customer in its service area.
</P>
<P>
   The report also charged that petroleum depletion allowances,
passive loss tax shelters, special tax credits for ethanol and
other ``alternative fuels'' and other government breaks give the
petroleum-consuming virgin plastics industry an unfair advantage
compared to recycled plastics.
</P>
<P>
   The report is available for free on the Internet (after 9 AM EDT
April 8th) at http://www.grrn.org, or in printed form for $10
(including shipping and handling) from the GrassRoots Recycling
Network, P.O. Box 49283, Athens, GA 30604-9283.
</P>
<P>
   (fact box follows)
</P>
<P>
   Targets
</P>
<P>
   Subsidies identified by the report's authors:
</P>
<P>
   Timber subsidies Yearly average cost to taxpayers (in millions)
</P>
<P>
   Timber tax breaks .......................$635
</P>
<P>
   Below-cost timber sales ................. $111
</P>
<P>
   Forest roads construction............... $31
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service salvage fund.............. $34
</P>
<P>
   Total .................................$811 million
</P>
<P>
   Hard rock mining subsidies
</P>
<P>
   1872 mining law............................$200
</P>
<P>
   Mining depletion allowance.................$269
</P>
<P>
   Tax write-offs............................ $27
</P>
<P>
   Total..............................................$496
</P>
<P>
   Energy Subsidies
</P>
<P>
   Depletion allowance........................$276
</P>
<P>
   Drilling costs deductions................ .. $9
</P>
<P>
   Passive loss tax shelter....................$38
</P>
<P>
   Alternative fuel credits.................. $543
</P>
<P>
   Enhanced Oil Recovery credits .............$245
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum electric subsidies................$200
</P>
<P>
   Total........................................$1,311
</P>
<P>
   Overall $2,618,000,000
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
