<SLUG> BC-NH-MLK-DAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. SENATE OK'S MLK HOLIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ New Hampshire has moved closer to joining the
other 49 states by honoring slain civil rights leader Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. with a holiday bearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 19 to 5, the Democrat-controlled state Senate
passed legislation Thursday that would add King's name to the Civil
Rights Day the state celebrates on the third Monday in January. The
bill now goes to the more conservative House, which has stopped
similar Senate bills three times.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, the measure's backers are more optimistic of
victory than at any time since the bill was introduced in 1979. In
1997, the move to add King's name to the holiday failed by one vote
in the 400-member House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on a one-vote loss two years ago and based on the
polling that's being done we think there's a majority,'' said
Arnold Alpert, president of the Martin Luther King Day committee
that has lobbied for the holiday for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Day became a federal holiday in 1986. In
1992, Arizona adopted the holiday, leaving New Hampshire as the
only state that did not celebrate it.
</P>
<P>
   That has brought nationwide attention. In 1996, a
Mississippi-based white supremacist group held a rally on the State
House steps to applaud the state for its solitary stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, when the Boston (sic) Patriots were thinking
about a new home, I called Bob Kraft in his office and talked to
him about moving his team to New Hampshire,'' Senate President
Clesson Blaisdell told his colleagues moments before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the questions he asked me was: `How, senator, do you
believe the black players on the Boston (sic) Patriots would like
playing in the state of New Hampshire, which doesn't recognize
Martin Luther King Day?'.'' Blaisdell said.
</P>
<P>
   The long fight has meant that the King holiday, if it comes,
will be even more meaningful, Alpert said. ``But as Jim Splaine,
the representative who first sponsored the bill in 1979 says, New
Hampshire won the race to be last, and now it will always have that
distinction,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1911EDT &QL; 
