<SLUG> BC-GREGG-BUSH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. GREGG PUTS IN A GOOD WORD FOR GEORGE W. BUSH JR. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush Jr. plans to visit New Hampshire as soon as the
Texas Legislature adjourns for the year, and will campaign with the
kind of personal interaction that every other presideneital
candidate must demonstrate in the state, according to New Hampshire
Senator Judd Gregg.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to show people he wants to win and is willing to
get in the fray and mix it up,'' said Gregg, who has taken a
leading role in the Texas governor's campaign in the Granite State.
``That means going out and meeting people on Main Street and
letting people ask him questions and hear his responses.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said he decided to endorse Bush earlier than usual.
Indeed, Bush has not formally announced that he is running for
president yet. But Gregg said the frontloaded primary process has
made New Hampshire more important than ever, and requires more
campaigning and organizing earlier than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize we're a good distance behind many of the other
candidates in the state,'' said Gregg, mentioning Patrick J.
Buchanan in particular. ``We're going to run a grass-roots effort
and we're going to run an aggressive campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Bush acknowledged that he is getting a late
start compared to many of the other Republican candidates. ``Yet
winning Senator Gregg's endorsement brings great credibility to my
exploratory effort,'' said Bush. ``I am greateful for his support
and I look forward to visiting New Hampshire early this summer once
I have completed my work in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Thursday said he has written to Republican activists
across the state urging them to elect Bush as president.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Gregg, the letter was signed by former governor Steve
Merrill, Executive Councillor Ruth Griffin, former Republican party
assistant chair Barbara Russell, and Rob Thompson, who was
grass-roots chairman for Merrill's 1992 campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
