<HEADER>
A1073 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-NY     04-08 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM 15 ACRES IN KOSOVO TO A NEW HOME IN TENT NO. 40
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MILITARY,
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-POLL, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-CONGRESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-TURKEY,
KOSOVO-ECON, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES, KOSOVO-POWS) 
(ac) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ The Bllaca family was dining on pasta and
beans when the masked Serbian policemen kicked in the kitchen door
of their home in Kosovo, jamming the butt of a rifle into Mehdi
Bllaca's head.
</P>
<P>
   All the neighboring villages had been emptied, so a sense of
foreboding had been hanging over their dinner table. Every 15
minutes, a Serbian patrol car glided ominously by their house, in
Dushanova. They could barely converse. When would it be their turn?
</P>
<P>
   The moment, when it came eight days ago, was rapid-fire. Blood
streamed down Bllaca's forehead, his elderly mother screamed, his
wife and children threw down their spoons and in minutes they fled
the land their family had lived on for 40 years. They were too
scared to take one final look back before the wooden house they had
built with their own hands burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to count the steps to the Albanian border, to see how
many it would take to get back home,'' Fatmira Bllaca, 25, said
Thursday. ``My brothers and sisters told me, `Let's save our lives
first. Let's go forward.' I stopped counting at 4,000. We walked
for 10 more hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Bllaca swept the dirt in front of her family's new home _
Tent No. 40 in the main refugee camp in Tirana _ with a brush
fashioned from pine needles. Under a brilliant midday sun, she laid
out a blanket for a lunch of donated bean soup and bread. And then
she summoned her parents, her grandmother, two sisters and three
brothers _ ``Lunch is served!'' _ to gather with plastic spoons
around a tin pot.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week's time the Bllacas (pronounced BLAH-tza), like
many others, have found the strength to adapt to their terrible new
reality. Their village, Dushanova, has reconstituted itself inside
the tent city; they have decorated their tent with blankets. It is
a far cry from their 15-acre property in Kosovo, from their
gardens, their cows and their family history.
</P>
<P>
   They have convinced themselves that their displacement is
transitory; within a month, they will be home, they said, or at
least back at the charred remains.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the Bllacas and their neighbors lined up to have their
photographs taken for new identity cards; their old ones were
issued by Serbs so they were glad to be rid of them, they said. The
men, sitting on army cots, sipped espresso from tiny china cups.
The children played soccer inside an empty, cracked swimming pool.
The women scrubbed clothes in a fetid fountain, gossiping.
</P>
<P>
   Seven days ago, Miss Bllaca trekked to the Albanian border,
fearful that the forced march would end in their slaughter. ``We
thought maybe our journey would end in a mass grave,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs who lined the road were pulling out young men and
roughing them up, so she and her sisters formed a human circle
around their brother, Miftar, 17, to hide him. It made the arduous
trip incredibly awkward, too.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, her freshly washed hair piled atop her head with a
bandana, Miss Bllaca read a novel by Ismail Kadare, a leading
Albanian writer. Her smallest brother, Valon, who is 10 and a
gifted artist, sketched by her side. She admired his effort: he had
really captured the tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel free today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Fatime, 47, said: ``For the last two years, we were
not free in our house or in our town. I was afraid every time my
oldest boy left home. The Serbian police would gesture to him,
twisting their hands, like they were ripping his head off.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Bllaca returned with news that clouded their
faces: no word yet about his oldest daughter, a university student
studying medicine, whose whereabouts are unknown. She was at school
when the family was chased from their town, and they do not know
where she is or if she is alive.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Outside their tent, just when they were starting to feel anxious
again, there were screams. ``A snake! A snake!'' people shouted. It
was the third one of the day, and the refugees smashed it dead with
rocks. In the Bllaca house, the uplifted mood was broken.
</P>
<P>
   Selvie Bllaca, who is 68 but looks much older, dropped her face
in her hands. ``What are we going to do?'' she moaned. ``Maybe God
will help.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only God and Clinton can save us,'' Bllaca said. ``All we have
now are our bare hands, and they are not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, the Bllacas lived a life firmly rooted in their
family land. They grew most of their own food and drank milk from
their cows.
</P>
<P>
   Bllaca had worked in a state shoe factory for 23 years, until
Kosovo lost its autonomy in 1989 and all the ethnic Albanians were
fired, losing their pensions. He started a small shoemaking
business, operating in his own house. All his neighbors became
similar businessmen, if they were clever enough.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 10 of the 800 families in their village were Serbian,
but the Serbs were the authorities. They taxed them for everything,
Bllaca said. They closed school buildings, and many of the Bllaca
children studied in makeshift schools organized by neighbors in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Bllaca became a seamstress, a ``housegirl,'' she said, who
was not nearly as independent as her older sister, the university
student. Miss Bllaca would never go to a discotheque, she said; she
was not educated enough, and the others would look down their noses
at her.
</P>
<P>
   Her younger sister, Shpresa, 19, had hoped to become a medic,
but the Serbs would not let Albanian students intern at the
hospitals or on ambulances, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bllaca's business proved successful. Two years ago, the
family built a new house, two stories with 10 rooms, wood-paneled
with wall-to-wall carpeting that was white with a floral border.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've done, all I've saved for in 30 years, was taken away
from me,'' Bllaca said Thursday. ``It's a huge disaster. What I
achieved I will never have again. I created a good situation for
everyone in the family. Every month, I gave my oldest daughter
money for school. Now I don't know if I have an oldest daughter
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, the family's life was oriented toward Albania. They
watched Albanian television, listened to Albanian radio, and read
Albanian newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always wanted to come to Albania, too,'' Miss Bllaca said.
``But not like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
