</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-LVMH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE FOR CONTROL OF GUCCI HEATS UP AS COMPANY REJECTS OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Gucci Group NV rejected a sweetened
takeover offer Thursday from LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the
French luxury-goods company, intensifying one of Europe's most
bitter takeover battles.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH, which is headed by Bernard Arnault, raised its offer on
Wednesday to $85 a share from $81, a 9 percent premium to
Thursday's closing price of 71.75 euros, or $78, in Amsterdam. But
Gucci, which is headed by Domenico De Sole, contended that the new
offer, worth $8.3 billion, was ``unacceptable'' because it would
undermine independent shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci's action sets the stage for a new round of court battles
in Amsterdam. Gucci is based in the Netherlands for tax purposes
but has most of its operations in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to remain free of Arnault and LVMH, Gucci sold a 42
percent stake last month to one of Arnault's biggest rivals,
Francois Pinault, head of Pinault-Printemps-Redoute.
</P>
<P>
   On March 22, an Amsterdam court ordered Gucci and LVMH to
negotiate. Arnault had not originally sought to acquire all of
Gucci, but after Gucci's deal with Pinault he came back with a bid
of $81 a share for the entire company.
</P>
<P>
   Now the fight amounts to a three-way struggle between Gucci,
LVMH and Pinault. In its latest offer, LVMH proposed offering $85 a
share for Gucci if the deal included the newly issued stock that
Pinault bought for $75 a share several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinault, who owns several luxury brands including Yves Saint
Laurent, does not want to sell and probably has enough shares to
retain effective control of Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, LVMH proposed that Gucci issue millions of new
shares that would essentially dilute Pinault's voting power. LVMH
executives argue that their offer is the only one that gives
ordinary shareholders a fair price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LVMH proposals would have enabled shareholders to access
the only control premium that has been proposed to them to date,''
the company said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole of Gucci, in an interview, insisted that he negotiated
in good faith with LVMH and simply wanted an ``unconditional''
offer for all the shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything we could to make this transaction fair for
LVMH, but we cannot accept a conditional offer,'' De Sole said. The
LVMH proposal would violate Gucci's agreement with Pinault, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault is now heading back to the Amsterdam court, which is
scheduled to review the entire situation once again on April 22. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
