   &UR; WORKPLACE PACKAGE &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; WAGE -  &LR; A look at the living wage campaigns like the one currently
under debate in San Francisco. In more than two dozen U.S. cities,
labor and community activists have convinced elected officials to
require companies with city service contracts to pay a
higher-than-minimum wage that ranges from $7 to $11. Companies
affected typically include ones providing janitorial services,
security services, and food services at city buildings. By Ilana
DeBare
