<HEADLINE>
N.H. HOUSE NEGOTIATES ANOTHER SCHOOL TAX PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N. H. _ Leaders of the 400-member N.H. House of
Representatives say they have reached bipartisan agreement on an
$825 million tax plan that will fund the state's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers, however, described the plan Thursday as a
starting point, something to bring to a negotiating conference
between the House and Senate. They do not see it as a final plan
likely to win approval from the Democratic Senate, Gov. Jeanne
Shaheen and ultimately the N.H. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Last December the court, in the so-called Claremont suit,
ordered the state to end its reliance on local property taxes to
pay for public education by April 1. The deadline passed and
lawmakers have yet to agree on a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fitch IBCA, an international bond rating agency,
Thursday placed $622 million in outstanding state bonds and $57.4
million in obligations issued by the city of Nashua on its
RatingAlert Negative list. The move is a warning that bond ratings
could be lowered, raising interest rates. Moody's Investor Services
made a similar move earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's plan, announced jointly by House Speaker Donna Sytek
and Minority Leader Peter Burling, relies on a smorgasborg of
unappetizing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes an increase in business taxes, a 2 percent tax
on all car sales, a 50 percent increase in the tax on the sale of
real estate, a 25-cent cigarette tax increase and the state's first
entertainment tax. That tax would be levied on everything from
video rentals and tickets to sporting events to golf greens fees
and health club memberships. Ski areas would be exempted.
</P>
<P>
   Critics are already predicting the plan will not pass. ``They
are willing to go anywhere just to get to a committee of
conference,'' said Rep. Frank Sapareto of Derry. ``There is
something in it for everyone to hate.''
</P>
<P>
   The House will hold hearings on the bill Friday, followed by a
vote early next week.
</P>
<P>
   If it fails, it will not have been the first. So far, the only
plans to have won any legislative approval have included what would
have been the state's first general income tax. With Shaheen
pledged to veto an income tax, however, it failed on its second
appearance in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Days later the House overwhelmingly rejected a plan that would
have raised money by, among other things, legalizing video slot
machines at race tracks and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Schools will stay open until the end of the school year,
although many districts are already unable to hire new teachers or
sign contracts with purveyors of school supplies, transportation
and other services.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Mark Joyce, a spokesman for the N.H. Association
of School Administrators said that if the fiscal impasse continues,
the state will violate a federal law that requires school districts
to make firm plans to provide summer programs for special needs
students by April 30. And that, said Joyce, could trigger a
class-action lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
