<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT HEARS CASE AGAINST MINISTER ACCUSED OF GENOCIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A federal judge said Thursday that an elderly
former pastor from Rwanda is likely innocent of genocide and crimes
against humanity stemming from a brutal ethnic feud in his central
African homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing before a three-judge panel of the 5th Circuit Court
of Appeals marked the latest round in a 2 1/2-year legal battle
pitting the Justice Department against former Attorney General
Ramsey Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Clark represents Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, 75, in his battle
against facing a United Nations war crimes tribunal in Tanzania
that is prosecuting suspects in the genocide in Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The case marks the first time the United States has arrested
someone on its soil to be turned over to an international tribunal
established by the U.N. Security Council, Clark told the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are setting a precedent that could be very dangerous,'' he
argued.
</P>
<P>
   He challenged the court to consider whether the United Nations
has the authority to establish a war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 71, the attorney general under President Lyndon Johnson,
said the tribunal was created illegally and that the United States
needed to have a congressionally approved treaty to warrant
surrendering his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tribunal itself is illegal,'' Clark said. ``We have never
extradited anybody without a treaty _ to do so would threaten
liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana, who has stomach and throat problems, would likely
die behind bars if he were tried, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 20 years of hearing cases, you develop some instincts
and radar,'' Appeals Court Judge Robert Parker said from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am persuaded the probability is great you (Clark) represent
an innocent man,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court panel isn't deciding Ntakirutimana's
innocence, but whether it is legal for the United States to hand
him over and whether there is reason to believe he committed a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides believe the precedent-setting case is headed to the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. tribunal charges that Ntakirutimana, the former head of
the Seventh-day Adventist Church in Rwanda, led attackers armed
with grenades, machetes and guns in April 1994 assaults on hundreds
of people who had fled into his church compound for safety.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rwanda was in the throes of a bloody feud between
the country's dominant ethnic groups, the Hutus and Tutsis, strife
that killed an estimated 500,000 and sent 2 million refugees
fleeing to neighboring nations. Most of those killed, including
those in Ntakirutimana's church, were Tutsis. Ntakirutimana is a
Hutu.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana was allowed to legally emigrate to the United
States later that year. He remains behind bars in Laredo, where he
has family, after his arrest by FBI agents in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors said the United States has an obligation to
enforce U.N. mandates and that there is more than enough evidence
to believe Ntakirutimana was involved in the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prosecute people who do terrible things,'' said Sara
Criscitelli, assistant director of the Justice Department's Office
of International Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a terrible thing,'' Criscitelli said outside the
federal courthouse in San Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
