<HEADER>
A1095 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-CARD-BILLING-S     04-08 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-CARD-BILLING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE TELEMARKETING CHARGES ON CREDIT CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE HADLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Read your credit card bill recently?
</P>
<P>
   You'd be wise to do so, say some Washington state consumers who
complain that their credit card companies are allowing businesses
to bill them without permission for goods they don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Credit card companies are providing key information they have
collected about you _ including your credit card number _ to
marketing firms.
</P>
<P>
   And savvy telemarketers are then using some of that information
to lure you into accepting ``trial memberships'' that many
customers don't realize they have agreed to until a $60 charge
shows up on their bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington state Attorney General's Office is so concerned
about the practice that it has begun an investigation of one
marketing firm _ BrandDirect Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers say the system has cost them money and, in some
instances, potentially their good credit rating.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Davis, a Vancouver, Wash., insurance agent, was surprised
recently when he opened his Traveler's Bank credit card bill and
found a lone charge of $59.95 for ``Outdoor Explorer Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Davis and his wife not recognize the club, they say
they never received any products or services from it.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle resident Dennis Petersen said in his complaint to the
Attorney General's Office that he was billed without his agreement
for Outdoor Explorer Club on his Chase Manhattan Bank Visa card.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never buy anything over the phone and certainly not
something like this that I'd never use,'' Petersen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both Traveler's Bank and Chase Manhattan Bank produced audio
tapes indicating that Petersen and Davis' wife apparently agreed to
sign up for trial memberships.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on?
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say, because the company that markets both clubs,
BrandDirect Marketing, of Shelton, Conn., does not record the
entire conversation with consumers it calls.
</P>
<P>
   And David Medine, associate director for financial services at
the Federal Trade Commission, says that without hearing the entire
conversation, it is impossible to know whether consumers have been
duped.
</P>
<P>
   Medine said telemarketing companies sometimes tape only the
portion of the conversation confirming the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the misrepresentations occur off the tape,'' he said.
``You have to see the full nature of the transaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State Attorney General Dave Horn agreed. He finds it
``suspicious'' when only part of the phone call is taped.
</P>
<P>
   Horn said if a company's practices are determined to be
deceptive, the company could be sued under the state's Consumer
Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan spokeswoman Charlotte Gilbert-Biro says that the
bank approves BrandDirect's telemarketing scripts and spot-checks
calls.
</P>
<P>
   But even if a transcript contains the correct words, a sales
pitch can still create a false impression with consumers in the way
it is delivered by trained telemarketers, Horn says.
</P>
<P>
   BrandDirect Marketing General Counsel Stephen Geissler said it
was the company's policy not to talk to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   The tape produced by Chase Manhattan included only the last part
of the conversation confirming Petersen's acceptance of a trial
membership.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, the telemarketer told Petersen that his membership
kit would arrive shortly and that he would receive ``quarterly
certificates worth $40 in gas at the station of your choice simply
for joining today.''
</P>
<P>
   The telemarketer continued, ``As I said, you'll have the next 30
days to use the service risk free. If you decide not to continue
your membership beyond the first 30 days, simply call our toll-free
number. Otherwise, we'll extend your membership privileges for a
full year and conveniently bill the $59.95 annual membership fee to
your Chase credit card account.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert-Biro, the Chase spokeswoman, said, ``It's a perfect
call. The offer was straight-forward. The customer clearly accepted
it. The rep didn't in any way pressure Mr. Petersen.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the transcript of the tape, a baffled Petersen
said, ``I guess I did OK it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Traveler's bank played the tape for Davis, he said it
sounded as if his wife had agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Why were these and other consumers so unaware of what they were
doing?
</P>
<P>
   The experience of one man who filed a complaint with the
Attorney General's Office provides one possible explanation.
</P>
<P>
   It suggests that the answer could lie in the ambiguous meaning
of ``trial membership'' and the fact that consumers haven't given
out their credit card number and therefore believe they haven't
agreed to be billed.
</P>
<P>
   What the consumers don't know is that BrandDirect Marketing
already has either their credit card number or the means to bill
their credit card without the number.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said when he called Traveler's Bank to inquire how Outdoor
Explorer Club could have billed his account without his agreement,
a supervisor there told him that ``Outdoor Explorer Club does
operate a little differently'' and as long as they ``make contact
with the home,'' they are allowed to automatically sign people up
unless people call to cancel.
</P>
<P>
   A ``trial membership'' that puts the burden on the consumer to
cancel _ known as a ``negative option'' _ is very lucrative for the
business offering it, said Gerri Detweiler, education adviser for
Debt Counselors of America, a non-profit Internet-based agency that
helps people get out of debt
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect this company as well as other companies make a lot
of money on people who didn't even realize they bought something,''
said Detweiler.
</P>
<P>
   The vendors who use negative option are correctly assuming that
many people will not notice the charge on their card or will not
remember to cancel it, Detweiler said.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that seemed to mystify and anger the complaining
consumers the most was how BrandDirect Marketing got their credit
card account numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan provides its cardholders' credit card numbers to
BrandDirect, Gilbert-Biro said.
</P>
<P>
   Traveler's Bank gives BrandDirect the name, address, and
telephone number of its cardholders, and after contacting the
cardholders, BrandDirect tells Traveler's which of those
cardholders are to be be billed.
</P>
<P>
   In its faxed response to inquiries from the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer, Exxon said it gives vendors ``a portion of the
cardholder file.''
</P>
<P>
   Most card issuers tell consumers when they sign up for cards
that they'll receive promotions from the issuer or affiliated
companies. Cardholders who fail to notify the card-issuer in
writing that they do not want to receive promotions may end up
doing business, wittingly or unwittingly, with companies like
BrandDirect Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert-Biro of Chase Manhattan said the marketing practice is
widespread and legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was able to have the charge taken off his bill.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon, Traveler's and Chase all said they carefully monitor
vendors and require them to follow the law. They stressed that if a
consumer wants a charge removed, it is to be promptly removed.
</P>
<P>
   Tips for avoiding unwanted credit card billings:
</P>
<P>
   -Check your credit card bill carefully each month and make sure
you know exactly what you're being billed for.
</P>
<P>
   -Pare down the number of credit cards you have. Eliminate cards
you rarely or never use. You must notify the card issuing company
in writing that you are canceling the card, even if it was never
activated.
</P>
<P>
   -Contact your card issuer to find out if any of your cardholder
information can be given to partners or affiliates of the card
issuer. If so, ask for the address to write to cancel this
authorization.
</P>
<P>
   -Be cautious about ``trial memberships.'' Refuse the offer if
you will be billed and later have to cancel if you don't like the
product. Recognize that even if you do not give out your credit
card number, you might still be billed.
</P>
<P>
   -Report unauthorized billings to the Consumer Protection
Division of the Attorney General's Office at 1-800-551-4636.
Complaint forms can be found at the Attorney General website at
www.wa.gov/ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
