<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CAPTIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CYPRIOT LEADER TRIES TO WIN FREEDOM FOR CAPTIVE SOLDIERS, U.S.
SAYS RELEASE MUST BE UNCONDITIONAL &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Cypriot leader Spyros Kyprianou tried Thursday to
win the release of the three American soldiers being held captive
by Yugoslav forces, but Serbia's vice premier threatened to try
them as terrorists unless NATO ends its bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said they hope Kyprianou's mission can
succeed if he is allowed as promised to meet Friday with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, NATO and U.S. officials continued to stress that
the soldiers' release must be unconditional. In the meantime, they
said the bombing of Serb military targets would continue until
Milosevic gives in to allied demands that he withdraw his forces
from Kosovo and accept the return of Kosovar refugees under the
protection of an international security force.
</P>
<P>
   Kyprianou flew to the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade on Thursday
aboard a Greek Air Force plane after NATO called a brief halt in
some of its bombing missions to allow for the aircraft's safe
passage. The plane returned to Greece last night, but Kyprianou,
who was told upon arrival that the Americans' release was ``out of
the question,'' stayed behind in anticipation of making a direct
appeal to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Kyprianou said he still hopes to win the Americans' freedom
during the long Orthodox Easter weekend, which began Thursday. In
return, he told reporters in Belgrade, ``NATO could reciprocate by
responding to the numerous international appeals for a cease-fire
at least over the Orthodox Easter weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said at the White House he would be ``for
anything honorable that would secure their release'' short of
ending the air campaign without Milosevic acceding to NATO's
demands.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appealed for their release, saying they ``never should
have been detained in the first place'' because they were in
Macedonia at the time of their capture last week and ``had nothing
to do'' with the NATO operation against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers _ Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smith Creek,
Mich.; and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas _ were
captured while on a reconnaissance mission along the
Macedonia-Kosovo border on March 31 as part of the NATO
peacekeeping force stationed in that country. They were reportedly
within Macedonian territory when a Serb patrol opened fire and
surrounded them.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials made it clear to Kyprianou before he left
Cyprus that he was not authorized to negotiate for the soldiers'
freedom. State Department spokesman James Rubin reiterated that
position in his daily briefing Thursday, telling reporters that
``any attempt to use the three as bargaining chips is both illegal
and immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would obviously welcome the release of the servicemen. But
let me be clear. We will accept nothing less than the unconditional
release of these servicemen,'' he said. ``We will not negotiate for
their release. We understand that Mr. Kyprianou is proceeding on
this basis as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen also made it clear that there
would be no concessions to Milosevic during a stop at Aviano,
Italy. Cohen addressed U.S. pilots and other military personnel
participating in the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Milosevic of illegally holding the Americans as
prisoners of war and said the Yugoslav leader would be held
accountable for their safety.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although it was unclear how Kyprianou's efforts would proceed
Friday, U.S. officials were making plans to fly the three soldiers
to Ramstein Air Base in Germany if Milosevic agrees to let them
leave Yugoslavia with the Cypriot leader. The three would likely be
flown out of Belgrade aboard a Greek Air Force plane to Cyprus,
where they would then board a U.S. plane for the trip to Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, they would be hospitalized for checkups and
debriefed. Plans were also being made to fly members of their
immediate families to Germany to meet them.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
