<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-TROOPS-BOS &LR;      04-08 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME TROOPS FOCUSED ON HUMANITARIAN MISSION  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Strapped into a seat inside a C-130 Air Force
cargo plane, Heather Byington headed into her first combat zone
Thursday, ready for war, clutching an M-16 rifle as the giant gray
aircraft took off from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the men and women around her, she blended into a wall
of camouflage.
</P>
<P>
   But as the plane headed toward Yugoslavia, there were no cracks
about Slobodan Milosevic _ no jokes, in fact, having to do with war
at all.
</P>
<P>
   These were the Air Force humanitarian assistance workers, the
ones assigned to the fringes to coordinate food and refugee aid,
more like missionary workers than GIs on a military mission. That
purpose was exactly why Byington and her Air Force colleagues said
they wanted to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to help people,'' Byington, 25, shouted over the roar
of the engine, smiling. ``I volunteered to go. I've been watching
CNN a lot, and I've been wanted to try and do something. I wanted
to be part of the humanitarian effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget comparing Kosovo to Vietnam _ at least around here.
Seated near Byington, stuffed between cargo loads of water, tents,
and power generators, every Air Force member on the trip described
a similar aspiration.
</P>
<P>
   To them, going to the border of Yugoslavia was not about
becoming a war hero, or killing the enemy. It was about feeding the
hungry and helping the poor _ as far from violence as possible.
</P>
<P>
   And in many ways, that is the changing mission of the military
itself, as the US takes on more and more peacekeeping roles and
humanitarian efforts worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Jess McGraw, 27, a senior airman, said he wanted to go because
he ``saw the need to help.'' Chris Ringland, 30, the plane's cargo
loadmaster, said the Air Force ``trained me for exactly this kind
of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergeant Kenith Franklin, 36, said he wanted nothing to do with
combat. He had been in Desert Storm and had ``been there, done
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the great misconceptions about us. We're not
here just for war,'' said Matthew Buchanan, 25, a senior airman
from Jacksonville Beach, Fla., before the plane departed from
Ramstein Air Force Base in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is better than Desert Storm. This, you don't get much
back, but it does make you sleep good at night, puts a smile on
your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Byington agreed, offering a reason why she and her colleagues
have become so averse to war. ``We're in the Air Force. Maybe our
mission isn't as combat-oriented as the rest of the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, before she had time to consider which military branch is
carrying out airstrikes against Yugoslavia, she curled up in her
camouflage uniform, leaned against the walls of the roaring plane,
and fell asleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
