</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN TANKS REPLACE REFUGEE CAMPS AT BORDER
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map showing refugee camps and displacement of the
Kosovar Albanian population is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-POLL, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-CONGRESS, KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-TURKEY,
KOSOVO-ECON, KOSOVO-WARCRIMES) 
(ac) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Serbian forces were positioning tanks and
artillery along the Kosovo border Thursday, just one day after tens
of thousands of refugees vanished when the Serbs turned their
convoys back from the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't know where they are or what is happening to
them,'' said Laura Boldrini, a spokeswoman for the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees, of the column of fleeing ethnic
Albanians estimated by aid officials to number some 80,000.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny handful of people _ not more than 30 _ who crossed the
border from Kosovo into Albania Thursday reported that the main
highway stretching north, which had been so clogged with the
slow-moving line of people on foot, in cars and in farm carts
pulled by tractors, was absolutely empty of refugees. Ms. Boldrini
said the few families who came across apparently had been let
across because the older family members had been born in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said there was a long, long queue of empty vehicles
burned and destroyed and no one around except the military
positioning guns,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On their side of the border crossing, Serb soldiers were seen
setting up mortars and laying mines in the trenches they dug on
Wednesday. Further back there is believed to be a battery of four
D-30 Howitzers, a light 122-millimeter field gun with a range of 10
miles.
</P>
<P>
   At the now-closed Qafr-e-Prushit border crossing in the rugged
mountains to the northwest, aid workers said they have seen the
Serbs gouging out berms with bulldozers to shelter T-55 tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs are digging in furiously all along the border,''
said Eugene O'Sullivan, the chief of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe observer team here.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the unknown fate of the tens of thousands of refugees
suddenly turned back at 3:30 in the morning on Wednesday that most
concerned aid workers here. They are worried that the refugees may
have been brought back to the larger towns that had been collecting
points for some sinister purpose, such as being used as human
shields against NATO forces. Perhaps even worse, they said, the
refugees might have been sent to wander the countryside, where
whole villages and towns have been looted and burned, on foot,
without food or water and at the mercy of Serbian gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   One theory for the sudden change in tactics, suggested
O'Sullivan, is that the Serbs might have decided that at the rate
they were going, they would totally empty Kosovo of its ethnic
Albanians, quite soon, leaving only Serbs, whom NATO might then
attack.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few days on the steep hillsides along the twisting
road from the border, lines of Albanian soldiers in ill-fitting
brown wool tunics that look like they date back at least to World
War I, have been carrying rusty rocket launchers into the crumbling
mushroom-shaped concrete bunkers the late dictator Enver Hoxha
scattered all over the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Albanian Army's weapons, up to and including tanks,
were looted from armories in a wave of civil unrest following the
collapse of a nationwide Ponzi scheme several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the flood of refugees cut off, the camps of people
squatting at the edge of town in farm carts covered with plastic
sheeting has diminished markedly. UNHCR officials say refugees are
being moved out of this remote area at the rate of about 20,000 a
day, and soon nearly all will have been sent down to Tirana, the
capital, and other areas where better care can be provided.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced aid workers who have been to many disasters around
the world have been increasingly stunned by the scope, the
meticulous organization and planning and the utter ferocity of the
Serbian campaign to drive out the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is going to stop this?'' asked Ms. Boldrini helplessly.
``This is a scandal. This is happening in Europe at the
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
