A1105 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALES-TAX-HNS &LR;      04-08 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALES-TAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$306 MILLION TAX BREAK FOR FAMILIES CLEARS TEXAS SENATE &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By KATHY WALT 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Senate approved a $306 million tax
break for families Thursday with a measure that would eliminate the
sales tax on diapers and some over-the-counter drugs and that would
suspend sales taxes on school clothing for a two-week period each
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting the sales tax on items like over-the-counter
medicines, diapers (and) school clothing makes everyday life more
affordable for many Texans,'' said Lt. Gov. Rick Perry. ``This tax
cut also puts some of the state's surplus back where it needs to be
_ back into Texans' pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure, Senate Bill 441, was approved without objection and
now goes to the House for consideration, where similar proposals
were approved by the House Ways and Means Committee a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas' sales tax rate takes the most from those who can least
afford it,'' said Sen. Rodney Ellis, a Houston Democrat and sponsor
of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Budget analysts estimate that the bill, which would take effect
Oct. 1 if passed, would cost state coffers $85 million in the first
year of the budget cycle and $166 million in the second year.
Another $55 million would be lost to cities, counties and other
taxing authorities during the two-year time frame.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is opposed by the Texas Municipal League because of its
effect on city revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales tax is as regressive as any tax we have and I think
people on the local level ought to be sensitive to that as well,''
Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is one of several tax-relief proposals working their
way through the Legislature. Gov. George W. Bush has proposed some
similar tax relief measures, including $330 million in sales tax
cuts for diapers, over-the-counter medicine, other health aids and
Internet access as a way to funnel part of a two-year $2.5 billion
budget surplus back to taxpayers. Although a tax exemption on
Internet access is not included in Ellis' bill, it is contained in
a separate bill that has yet to reach the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we are going to get some property tax relief,'' Bush
said Thursday. ``The good news is the House and the Senate appear
to be debating tax cuts. That is a very good start for someone who
wants to see tax cuts passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush added that while his whole package included sales tax,
business and property tax proposals, he strongly believes property
tax cuts are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we are going to get property tax cuts,'' he said.
``I also know we need to get sales tax cuts. I support a hefty tax
cut, and I look forward to working with the members of the House
and Senate.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Ellis bill would:
</P>
<P>
   Expand existing tax exemptions on prescription drugs to
over-the-counter medicines, such as children's cough syrup &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Exempt children's diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Exempt clothing and shoes selling for up to $200 per item from
sales tax during a 14-day period in August to help families buy
back-to-school clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that there are a lot of low-income families in Texas
who would prefer to go and buy one suit for their kid as opposed to
buying 20 pairs of jeans,'' Ellis said. ``I don't want to go in and
feel like I have to second guess what a low-income family wants to
do with that money.''
</P>
<P>
   The sales tax relief bills approved earlier this week in the
House committee would extend the back-to-school tax moratorium to
school supplies, while giving families a nine-day sales tax holiday
in August, rather than the two-week period specified in the Senate
bill. The House proposals also would limit sales tax exemptions on
school clothing to items costing no more than $75.
</P>
<P>
   The 6.25 percent state sales tax rate, which can be as high as
8.25 percent when local sales taxes are added, is one of the
highest in the nation, hitting poor families hardest, Ellis' office
said. His proposal would eliminate both state and local taxes on
the items approved Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander said families earning
less than $14,769 a year pay 6.9 percent of their income in sales
taxes, compared with those earning more than $74,357, which pay
about 1.5 percent of their total income on sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis' staff estimates that the back-to-school tax moratorium
could save a family with two school-age children at least $20. They
estimate that the diaper tax break alone would save a family with
one infant $6.60 a month, or nearly $80 a year.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
