<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1109 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIDS-CONFERENCE09-COX     04-08 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIDS-CONFERENCE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South remains SIDS problem, experts say
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia and other Southeastern states continue to be a
trouble spot in the national public health campaign to reduce
Sudden Infant Death Syndrome, say experts meeting in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1997, SIDS deaths nationally declined 43
percent but decreased in Georgia by 25 percent. While Georgia's
numbers represent an improvement (from 149 deaths to 115 deaths),
not enough Southerners are getting the message that babies should
only be put to bed on their backs, said Phipps Cohe of the SIDS
Alliance, a coalition of health department officials and parents
who've lost children to SIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Back to Sleep' campaign has spared about 2,000 babies a
year from dying of SIDS,'' Cohe said. ``So in seven years, we have
done a magnificent job. But we're finding there are still poc-
</P>
<P>
   kets of populations that need to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Of much concern are African-American babies, who are three times
as likely to die from SIDS, and day care centers where nearly
one-fifth of SIDS cases have occurred, Cohe said. Surveys have
found African-Americans are twice as likely to place infants on
their stomach, a sleep position that was once standard practice,
and a habit that may be tough for grandmothers and other older baby
sitters.
</P>
<P>
   But research led to the American Academy of Pediatrics' ``Back
to Sleep'' recommendation when it was found babies sleeping on
their stomachs and sides were in more danger of having their
airways blocked, and more at risk for SIDS.
</P>
<P>
   SIDS strikes, without warning or previous symptoms, in infants
under age 1. But why nearly 3,000 apparently healthy infants every
year from SIDS continues to vex doctors and scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are left with the coroner's report that says SIDS, but it
doesn't answer why,'' said Jim Morgan of Suwanee (GA.), who lost
his 94-day-old son, Nicolas James, to SIDS in 1997. He and his
wife, Cheyney Morgan, will speak Saturday on how the death affected
their older son, Joshua.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was only 6 years old at the time, but it was surprising how
he held up,'' Morgan said. ``He was the one who got me through the
funeral. We'd be crying, and he was the one saying, `Don't look (at
the casket.) It'll only make you cry.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For information: National Infant Death Syndrome Alliance at
1-800-221-7437 or Georgia's chapter at 770-795-0142.
</P>
<P>
   REDUCING THE RISKS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Place your baby on his or her back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Do not smoke around your baby.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use firm, flat bedding.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Do not have comforters, sheepskin or fluffy toys in the crib.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Avoid overheating your baby.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tell baby sitters, day care center workers and relatives not
to place the baby on his or her stomach or side when sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Communicate with your baby's doctor about changes in your
baby's behavior or health.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
