<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1110 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGA-LITERARY11-1STTAK     04-08 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-LITERARY11-1STTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Athens blooms as a literary center, nurtured by a three-way
coalition
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 11.
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Until 15 years ago, this lively college town was
better known as the home of the Georgia Bulldogs and R.E.M. than as
a literary hotbed. When Philip Lee Williams' first book, ``The
Heart of a Distant Forest,'' was published in 1984, he remembers
being the only novelist in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a book published then was so unusual, it was like
waking up on another planet,'' said Williams, 49, whose 10th book,
``Crossing Wildcat Ridge,'' was just published by the University of
Georgia Press. ``People were coming up to me on the street, asking
me questions, and I was supposed to have opinions on everything. I
didn't know how to act like a writer, and there was no one to tell
me.''
</P>
<P>
   All that has changed. The reasons for this literary blossoming
are tied to the University of Georgia, which established a creative
writing program and expanded its press into areas beyond academia.
It's also due to the ascendance of the Georgia Review under the
leadership of Stan Lindberg, whose reign at the
university-sponsored literary magazine has made it one of the
country's finest. And to the growth of the publishing scene: There
are now four imprints in town. Readings by local and visiting
writers, such as noted nature writer Terry Tempest Williams and
essayist Franklin Burroughs, are routine and well-attended.
</P>
<P>
   But the reasons also include Athens itself. It's a cheap,
low-key place to live, known for its musicians, artists and
tolerance for the offbeat, where you're just as likely to encounter
an award-winning writer as a millionaire musician at Blue Sky
Coffee House downtown or Jittery Joe's in Five Points. People come
here to college _ or just come to visit _ and never leave,
attracted by the lively cultural scene as much as the 19th-century
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have lived and written here have found willing
and interesting audiences of readers,'' said historian Tom Dyer,
55, whose ``Secret Yankees: The Union Circle in Civil War Atlanta''
was published by Johns Hopkins University Press in March. ``Athens
is on more of a human scale than Atlanta; it's smaller. You can
live here and get around and get to know people.''
</P>
<P>
   Poet Barbara Ras, 1998 winner of the prestigious Walt Whitman
Award and executive editor of the UGA Press, learned early on that
Athens' lit lovers are a more passionate breed. She still marvels
that more than 50 people showed up for a poetry reading she gave at
a downtown bar soon after she moved to town, when she knew almost
no one other than her colleagues at the UGA Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an astonishment to me to have that many people turn
out,'' Ras said. ``It showed that the community is hungry for
literary events and is willing to support them.''
</P>
<P>
   A place for like minds
</P>
<P>
   Literary events _ readings and signings _ are where you're most
likely to find a gaggle of those devoted to books and writing. But
because there isn't a front-list bookstore in town, or a place like
the late, lamented Old New York Book Shop in Atlanta's Midtown,
there's no single gathering spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real impediment is that there's no really good bookstore,
and everyone would like to see that changed,'' said poet Kevin
Young, who teaches creative writing in the UGA English department.
Locals long for a place like the Old Black Dog, an independent
bookstore that closed in 1996. During its 10-year run it became the
hub of local literary happenings. Judy Long, now editor of Hill
Street Press, was its manager.
</P>
<P>
   Squeezed into an old house in Five Points, near the UGA campus,
the Old Black Dog was packed stem to stern with books by local and
national authors. Veterinarian John McCormack, author of the
autobiographical ``Fields and Pastures New'' and ``A Friend of the
Flock,'' remembers that before Crown published his books, the Old
Black Dog carried ``Watch for a Cloud of Dust,'' a paperback
collection of columns he had written for a dairying magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Old Black Dog was a refuge from the world,'' said Judith
Ortiz Cofer, a UGA English professor and a native of Puerto Rico
who often writes about her life there, in New Jersey and in
Georgia. ``It was a place where good writing was valued. Such a
small space _ it offered an intimate setting that was unique.''
</P>
<P>
   At the store, Long and owner Melissa Tufts ``hand-sold books to
just about everyone in town who was interested in books and good
writing,'' said Julie Checkoway, director of UGA's creative writing
program. ``Judy didn't just sell books, she connected us to each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Long knew just about every writer, from McCormack, who had
treated Tufts' horses, to historian Emory Thomas, biographer of
Gen. Robert E. Lee, and UGA children's books expert Sylvia
Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   When Tufts closed the bookstore, Long worried that her
friendships might falter. But with a business called Byhalia Books,
which she calls ``a bookstore without walls,'' she has kept her
hand in the local literary scene, arranging readings, propping up
nervous authors and selling their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judy Long is the glue that holds the entire Athens literary
community together,'' said Checkoway. ``She knows everybody; she's
a human press release. Without her, it wouldn't be a community, it
would be a bunch of writers living in a town.''
</P>
<P>
   Some enchanted evening
</P>
<P>
   One literary gathering that Long hopes to stage involves retired
UGA English professor Coleman Barks, poet and the world's foremost
interpreter of the works of 13th-century Turkish mystical poet
Mavlana Jelaluddin Rumi. Long has heard Barks read Rumi's poetry to
musical accompaniment ``to packed houses in other cities, but not
in Athens,'' she said. So her goal is eventually to produce ``An
Evening With Coleman Barks'' in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Few people in town seem aware of Barks' international
accomplishments, largely because he doesn't tout his own works and
seems not to take himself very seriously. While Rumi is now the
best-selling poet in the United States (and is even in record
stores thanks to holistic healing guru Deepak Chopra's ``A Gift of
Love'' CD with celebrity poetry reciters Madonna and Demi Moore) _
and his Athens translator is almost a cult figure in California _
Barks remains relatively unknown locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I gave a reading in Athens, it would probably just be my
family who would come,'' said Barks, who punctuates his
self-deprecating barbs with a melodious laugh. ``No, that may not
be true. This is a very lively town, just the right size for me.
There's a literary community here, but we're all off in our own
place, working. People leave each other alone, and I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Barks said, he would meet ``on someone's porch''
with groups of other people who were writing, such as poet Paul
Zimmer, former director of the UGA Press; Cofer, who was sharing
stories that later went into ``The Latin Deli''; and Jim Kilgo, who
was just beginning to write the personal essays that make up his
first two books. They would read and then offer one another
criticism and comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were helpful and generous, especially Coleman,'' said
Kilgo. ``He was very supportive. He began taking my work seriously,
even before I did.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, poet Robert Bly, a friend of Barks', handed Barks a
scholarly translation of Rumi's works, telling him ``these need to
be released from their cages,'' Barks recalled. ``They were a
literal translation; they needed to be put in American English. I
had had a literary education, had studied at Berkeley and Chapel
Hill, and yet I had never heard of the great poet of that part of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   After two decades of collaborating with various Persian scholars
to bring Rumi to an English-speaking audience _ usually through his
own Maypop Books or with Threshold Books in Putney, Vt. _ Barks
recently obtained a contract with Viking giving him a six-figure
advance to produce a volume of Rumi's collected works. He said he's
both amazed and bemused at the idea of getting the country's
largest advance, ever, for poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I need? I guess it'll go to my grandchildren,'' he
said. ``And some for travel. I like to travel. I go out about two
times a month, reading.'' He said he finds colonies of Rumi lovers
wherever he goes, from Berkeley to Kalamazoo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
