<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1111 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGA-LITERARY11-2NDTAK     04-08 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-LITERARY11-2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga.: to Kalamazoo.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing support
</P>
<P>
   The UGA Press is a fixture of the local literary landscape.
Since it began accepting fiction in the 1980s, it has published
many Athens writers and has helped sponsor events and appearances
by national authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's extraordinary about the press is the range of its
publishing,'' said Ras, ``because it spans not only scholarly books
that are landmark works in history, civil rights, African-American
studies and environmental studies, but it also publishes fiction,
poetry and other significant works that contribute to the culture
of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina native John Miller, publisher of Orloff Press,
moved from California to Athens in 1997 to be with Karen Orchard,
who is the director of the UGA Press. A writer himself and the
winner of the 1996 California Book Award for ``Jackson Street,'' a
collection of short stories, Miller said he welcomed the arrival of
Hill Street Press last year, adding that ``anything which provides
an outlet for writers and promotes Athens as an arts-friendly city
is good for the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Georgia also sponsors the Georgia Review,
whose editor, Lindberg, is responsible for the quarterly's
``position on the cutting edge of contemporary literature,'' said
Rita Dove, a former national poet laureate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan Lindberg is a god,'' declared novelist Williams.
``Basically, he's the greatest literary magazine editor in the
country right now. Generations from now, people will remember him
as the greatest editor, ever, and the Review as the greatest
magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   With a circulation of 6,000, the Georgia Review has received
numerous prestigious awards over the years, including the 1986
National Magazine Award for fiction, when it beat out The New
Yorker, Esquire and Harper's. Since then it has been a National
Magazine Award finalist at least eight times. Pieces that it
publishes are routinely included in anthologies.
</P>
<P>
   Checkoway praised the Review for providing ``incredible
training'' for the students employed there as interns. They learn
how to edit and write, she said, often receiving advice from
Lindberg about their own work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mentoring in the true sense of the word.''
</P>
<P>
   The Review's associate editor, Stephen Corey, said the
notoriously selective magazine gets very few local submissions.
Novelist Terry Kay said he hasn't sent anything to the Review for
just that reason _ he doesn't want to put its editors in the
uncomfortable position of possibly rejecting and upsetting him.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Kay remains one of the biggest fans of both the
Review and Lindberg, whom he calls ``the pickiest person I've ever
met. This is the man who rejected John Updike and Robert Penn
Warren.'' But the Review has also published those well-known
writers, as well as Joyce Carol Oates, Eudora Welty, Robert Frost
and Harry Crews.
</P>
<P>
   Kay, who attended the ``Roots in Georgia'' literary symposium in
Athens in 1985 and the gathering of Nobel laureates during the
Cultural Olympiad in Atlanta, both of which were Lindberg's ideas,
said he was ``totally overwhelmed'' and convinced that Lindberg
wasn't receiving enough credit. So Kay and others have created an
award to honor the Review's editor, ``because he's done more to
acknowledge the literary efforts of this state than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsored by the Georgia Center for the Book, the Stanley W.
Lindberg Award will honor someone who has contributed
``substantially to the literary culture of Georgia through a
lifetime body of work,'' whether through publishing, editing,
writing or teaching. The first winner is Pat Conroy, who will
receive the prize April 24 at a black-tie event that's open to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Community comes together
</P>
<P>
   The Roots in Georgia conference is regarded as a benchmark event
both by its organizers and those who attended. ``It made us realize
there was a community here,'' said Lindberg. ``It was a coming
together of people in Athens, a recognition of them and the
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   It consisted of four days of literary readings, panel
discussions, films and lectures and brought to Athens such writers
and Georgia natives as Erskine Caldwell, Harry Crews, Olive Ann
Burns and James Dickey, along with Kay, Williams, Judson Mitcham
and Jim Peterson. Also attending was writer Raymond Andrews, a
Morgan County native who had recently moved from New York to
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Described by his many friends as incredibly generous, Andrews
``was somebody who was from the place, who believed in the place,''
said the Georgia Review's Corey. ``He was an extremely personable,
open kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews made everyone feel as if he was their best friend, said
Williams, and helped cement the writing community in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   All who knew him, including Barks, Kilgo, Long, Lindberg and
Williams, say they think of him ``almost every day'' since his
suicide in 1991 and miss him terribly, wishing he were here to
enjoy their successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd probably give me a hard time,'' laughed Barks. ``He was
pretty grounded in the here and now. He was a wonderful, unique
human being, and he can't be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca McCarthy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
