<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1114 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-08 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Pinochet Trial
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet could be held for trial in Britain on
charges of torture even if Home Secretary Jack Straw decides next
week that he cannot be extradited to Spain to face trial there, a
Crown Prosecution Service spokeswoman said. England's highest court
has ruled that only crimes alleged to have taken place after 1988
can be considered in the extradition decision.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth and Prince Philip will visit Australia only
months after it votes whether to keep her as head of state or
become a republic. The referendum is scheduled for November, and
the royal couple will travel there in the first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: IRA Firm on Arms
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein said the demand that its military wing, the Irish
Republican Army, must make a move toward disarmament before party
members take up their seats in the new Northern Ireland Assembly
was ``unacceptable.'' That demand emerged after 40 hours of talks
last week and will be the focus of new ones set to resume Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland: Global Child Abuse
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 40 million children suffer from abuse, the World
Health Organization said in Geneva. After studies in 19 countries
on children up to 14 years old, WHO said sex abuse was inflicted on
about 34 percent of girls and 29 percent of boys. In the United
States, WHO said it cost $12.4 billion a year for health services
for the estimated 2 million children injured by abuse.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela: A Threat of Emergency Rule
</P>
<P>
   President Hugo Chavez has threatened to declare a state of
emergency that would allow him to rule by decree. The threat came
after Congress refused to grant him enhanced powers he demanded
after taking office. Relations with Congress turned worse when the
son of a congressional leader was arrested on what he says are
trumped-up arms-smuggling charges. Chavez also said he might
dissolve Congress altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil: Legislator Expelled
</P>
<P>
   The lower house of Congress has expelled one of its members, who
is accused of ordering the murder of a political rival in order to
gain her seat in the Chamber of Deputies. Talvane Albuquerque has
been named by the police as the prime suspect in the killing of
Ceci Cunha, her husband and her in-laws. Immediately after the
action by Congress, Albuquerque was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Court: No Evidence Menem's Son Was Murdered
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court closed an investigation into a 1995 helicopter
crash that killed Carlos Menem Jr., the son of President Carlos
Saul Menem, saying there was no evidence he was deliberately
killed. Zulema Yoma, Menem's estranged wife, has long said that
Carlos Jr. was the victim of a murder plot, suggesting that
elements of organized crime were seeking revenge against the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Leftists Trade Barbs
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates for the presidential nomination of Mexico's
main leftist party traded angry public recriminations. Porfirio
Munoz Ledo, the party's congressional leader, said Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, the Mexico City mayor who is his rival, was to blame for
fraudulent party elections. Until Munoz provides evidence for his
charges, Cardenas shot back, ``he'll be seen as a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: ASEAN Membership on Way
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia will be admitted into the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations on April 30, Foreign Minister Hom Nam Hong said. The
association had delayed the step because of political turmoil in
the country. Cambodia will be the last of the 10 regional nations
to join the influential grouping, which comprises Indonesia,
Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore, the Philippines, Brunei, Vietnam,
Laos and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea: Democratic Blow to Kim
</P>
<P>
   The National Assembly members dealt a harsh blow to President
Kim Dae Jung by defeating a proposal to arrest a fellow lawmaker
for illegal fund-raising. In an unusual move for South Korea, a
budding democracy, more than 20 lawmakers crossed party lines to
vote against Kim.
</P>
<P>
   India: Two Key Officials Quit
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee has accepted the resignation
of two ministers, both members of the All India Anna Bravida
Munnetra Kazagham party, who quit when three of the party's demands
about defense matters were rebuffed. The resignations make a
reconciliation between the party and the government less likely,
which may soon leave Vajpayee without a majority in Parliament and
facing the prospect of a no-confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia: Prime Minister Hospitalized
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, 73, in hospital with what a
deputy said was a lung infection, has put off a national political
tour intended to counter what he has called ``intense propaganda''
by his opponents. The prime minister, speaking on national
television, said he hoped to return to work soon.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: TV Pornography Banned
</P>
<P>
   Releasing a new code of conduct, South Africa's Independent
Broadcasting Authority said material showing hard-core sex or
depicting ``excessive violence,'' especially against women, would
be banned from television. Television in South Africa was strictly
censored until the new constitution appeared in 1994, when
virtually all censorship vanished.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Absentee Voting Extended
</P>
<P>
   South Africans traveling abroad on election day, June 2, will be
able to vote at overseas embassies if they have registered to do
so, the Independent Electoral Commission said, but those who did
not register will not. South Africans living abroad have been
protesting the commission's unwillingness to provide absentee
ballots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
