<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-BEE _ MIAMI _ For 70 straight years, a U.S. citizen won
the annual national spelling bee. But last May, Jamaica's Jody-Anne
Maxwell became the first non-citizen to triumph. This year, though,
Jamaica is out. The island traditionally picks its winner in
August. But new rules disqualify any representative who wins her
regional spell-off before February. That's got a lot of Jamaicans,
as well as African-Americans, charging that racism is at work.
(Emling, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTO. MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CRONKITE-FAITH _ WASHINGTON _ Walter Cronkite presents his first
``Faith and Freedom Awards'' on Friday, one to a Baptist minister
who moderated suburban Atlanta schools after a court forbade
religious content in the curriculum. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-CONSERVATIVES _ WASHINGTON _ A powerful GOP group is
already attacking the voting records of conservative democrats in
the new Congress. Those on the hit list include Texans Chet
Edwards, of Waco; Max Sandlin, of Marshall; and Jim Turner, of
Crockett. All three represent conservative districts which could be
heavily targeted by the GOP in 2000. It looks like the battle to
control the House is underway _ a cool 18 months before the
election. And the excitement over a George W. Bush candidacy is
fueling GOP dreams of long coattails in conservative Texas
districts. (Moscoso, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   Boxes for Edwards, Sandlin and Turner - How conservative are
they? Ratings by conservative groups. And stats on the districts
they represent - what percent of their constituents voted for the
GOP in the last election. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This will be the CoxNet Focus page for this weekend. It is
part of the continuing yearlong series looking at the 2000th
anniversary of Christianity.)
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN _ On Oct. 31, 1517, Martin Luther tacked a
paper to the Palace Church door in Wittenberg, sparking a movement
that changed Christianity. But the church Luther founded finds
itself in deep trouble in Europe, where the Lutheran World
Federation reported a ``general reduction in numbers.'' And the
problem is even greater in Germany, the homeland of Protestanism,
where more than a million people have left the church rolls in
the1990s. (Gwhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 67. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANTS _ Most German Protestants spend little
time in the pews, but the history of northern Germany, the
birthplace of the Protestant Reformation, can be traced through
three churches: The Palace Church in Wittenberg where Luther nailed
the theses that started the Reformation; the Berliner Dom, or great
emperial cathedral, that survived the tremendous forces that shaped
20th century East Berlin; and, St. Michael's in Hamburg, a city
famous for its churches and its red-light district, where the
rebuilding of St. Michael's after World War II has become a major
point of pride for the city. (Gwhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-LUTHER _ Although Catholic monk Martin Luther never
intended to form his own church, millions of Christians around the
world are now in a family of denominations that bear his name.
Millions more are in other groups _ Reformed, Methodist,
Presbyterian _ that are part of the Protestant Reformation Luther
sparked. A brief bio of Luther. Photo. (Gwhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.5.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-BOX _ Although the government of Germany collects
funds for the Protestant and Catholic churches along with income
tax, many people have chosen to disaffiliate themselves from the
faith. And many of those who still pay money to the church seldom
attend. We take a quick look at the numbers. Gwhite. 7.4''
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND _ The Church of England has become a stodgy,
picturesque part of the British Isles, a place tourists visit, but
few Brits actually are involved with. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
20.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-CHART _ A country-by-country chart of European
religious affiliation. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution Art
Department). GRAPHIC
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-TIMELINE _ A detailed look at highlights of
Christianity through the Middle Ages. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution
Art Department). GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINENEW-CONTACTLENS _ Ciba, the contact lens
manufacturer based in metro Atlanta, is rolling out a new type of
lens and a marketing campaign aimed directly at consumers. (Kim,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   COSMOS _ The Hubble Space Telescope and other new instruments
for examining the space we live in have generated a flood of new
discoveries during the 1990s, the fastest accumulation of insights
about the Universe in history, scientists say. Yet, fundamental
questions still exist about science and religion. Was there a Big
Bang? Did something happen before it? Was there a ``before it?''
Did something ``cause'' it to happen? Are human beings the only
``intelligent creatures'' to live in the space that it seems to
have created and to wonder about these things? The American
Association for the Advancement of Science will bring together
scientists and religious scholars from universities in the United
States and Europe next week (April 14-16) to talk these questions
and others. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
