<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OLY-CONGRESS _ After a brief reprieve, the IOC bribery scandal
is heating up again, this time in the halls of Congress. A
congressional committee begins considering legislation Wednesday
that could cripple the IOC by denying it millions of dollars in
sponsorships. The legislation would strip the IOC's tax-exempt
status in the U.S, limit the amount of Olympic fees sponsors could
deduct and place U.S. TV rights fees _ the single biggest source of
Olympic income _ with the USOC instead of the IOC. The White House
was asked almost a month ago by the U.S. Olympic Committee to
include the IOC under the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, and an
answer is possible Tuesday. And the Justice Department and the FBI
also are investigating possible violations of federal fraud and tax
laws. (Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (s) Sports and (i) International categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-UTILITY _ MEXICO CITY _ Each morning, Josefina Cruz sets
up her produce stand on a Mexico City street in pitch dark. So she
can see what she's doing, she plugs a long cable she brings with
her into a electrical socket and clicks on a bare light bulb. The
socket happens to be on a utility pole, courtesy of electrical
workers who charged her to install it and come by once a month to
collect a fee. It's a scene out of Mexico's patchwork electrical
system, where jury-rigged hookups are commonplace. In February
President Ernesto Zedillo proposed privatizing much of this
state-run industry, hoping to bring in millions of private
investment to make it more efficient and expand its capacity.
Zedillo has run into lots of opposition, though. The privatization
of banks and highways has led to some disasters, making
privatization a dirty word in Mexico. (Ferriss, Cox News Service)
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Thursday in International and Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   COSMOS _ WASHINGTON _ The Hubble Space Telescope and other new
instruments for examining the space we live in have generated a
flood of new discoveries during the 1990s, the fastest accumulation
of insights about the universe in history, scientists say. Yet,
fundamental questions that occupy science and religion. Was there a
Big Bang? Did something happen before it? Was there a ``before
it?'' Did something ``cause'' it to happen? Are human beings the
only ``intelligent creatures'' to live in the space that it seems
to have created and to wonder about these things? The American
Association for the Advancement of Science will bring together
scientists and religious scholars from universities in the United
States and Europe next week (April 14-16) to talk these questions
and others. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE _ WASHINGTON _ Amazon.com and eBay may get most of
the ink, but the real money in electronic commerce is in
business-to-business transactions. Last year, business-to-business
revenue hit $43 billion against $8 billion for the consumer market.
A look at how the Internet is changing the way business does
business. (Regan, Cox News Service). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-GRAPHIC _ Data showing forecast for electronic
commerce revenue, business-to-business, and business-to-consumer.
(Cox News Service). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-BURDEN _ WASHINGTON _ The federal taxes paid are the highest
percentage of the nation's output of any peacetime in history. Are
American households feeling a bigger pinch as they mail in their
tax returns this month? Story will examine the total burden of
taxes, said to be 40 percent, and how they affect various income
groups. Which taxes are growing? Which ones are hidden? What
changes are in the works in Congress that could change the burden?
(Malone, Cox News Service). MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TAX-DATA _ Graphics material.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-SHARE-DATA
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN-FUND _ As he looks to his past race for sources of
money for his future race, Gov. GWBush doesn't have to go too far
down the list to find two supporters who have amassed fortunes in
Hispanic media. The top individual donor to Bush's re-election
campaign was Warren Tichenor of San Antonio, the latest generation
of a family that has grown mega-wealthy through ownership of
Hispanic radio stations. No. 2 on the list is Los Angeles
zillionaire Jerry Perenchio, whose resume includes head man at
Univision, massive political giving and residence in the Beverly
Hillbillies mansion. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   FREAKNIK-ATLANTA _ ATLANTA _ They are suposedly among the best
and the brightest, and at the very least they should know better.
But what is is about Freaknik that makes college students behave
radically different than they would at home or on campus. A look at
the psychology of crowds and anonyminity, and reaction from people
who have experienced the best and the worst of Freaknik.
(Suggs/Gibson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FREAKNIK-DAYTONA _ DAYTONA _ Live from Daytona, we look at the
activities of the Black College Reunion, with lots of color.
Looking for students who in the classic manner of freshman
composition classes, can ''compare and contrast'' the Daytona
experience with Freaknik. (Suggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
20.
</P>
<P>
   UTPRES-FAULKNER _ AUSTIN _ An elite group of students had
gathered to hear University of Texas President Larry Faulkner
deliver a hard sell on UT. It never came. Instead Faulkner flatly
told the students, ``This setting probably isn't the right setting
for every one of you.'' The scene was classic Faulkner: direct,
low-key, no-frills. In his first year heading the nation's largest
university, Faulkner is getting grades from A plus to incomplete.
Since taking office last April 13, Faulkner has faced ongoing
protests from staff over their pay, an overnight takeover of the
Main Building by angry students and the skepticism of
high-technology executives he wants badly to woo. We give readers a
sense of the job he is doing. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FAULKNER-QUOTES _ Faulkner comments through the year or on
specific topics. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-CREDENTIAL _ About one in five Texas public school
students are taught by teachers who lack proper credentials. And
nobody is required to tell their parents, many of whom have no idea
the problem is so pervasive. Educators have downplayed the problem
but an increasing body of evidence indicates that unqualified
teachers could be the driving force behind poor educational
performance. University of Texas data from the 1996-97 school year
shows that students with properly certified teachers pass the TAAS
at higher rates than their peers with uncertified teachers. The
study also shows that the most affluent schools are more likely to
have properly certified teachers. Uncertified teachers are most
abundant in bilingual education, English as a Second Language and
computer sciences _ three key educational areas in a state that's
increasingly Hispanic and increasingly computerized. (Brooks,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-CERTIFICATION _ Text box explaining what is teacher
certification? What does it entail? How do you get it? How do you
get in the classroom without it? (Brooks, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-UTILITY _ MEXICO CITY _ Each morning, Josefina Cruz sets
up her produce stand on a Mexico City street in pitch dark. So she
can see what she's doing, she plugs a long cable she brings with
her into a electrical socket and clicks on a bare light bulb. The
socket happens to be on a utility pole, courtesy of electrical
workers who charged her to install it and come by once a month to
collect a fee. It's a scene out of Mexico's patchwork electrical
system, where jury-rigged hookups are commonplace. In February
President Ernesto Zedillo proposed privatizing much of this
state-run industry, hoping to bring in millions of private
investment to make it more efficient and expand its capacity.
Zedillo has run into lots of opposition, though. The privatization
of banks and highways has led to some disasters, making
privatization a dirty word in Mexico. (Ferriss, Cox News Service)
WITH PHOTOS. Eds: Moving in International and Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEDTURNER-BISON _ No, it doesn't taste like chicken and it
certainly doesn't look like one. What we're talking about here is
bison, an animal that Ted Turner is trying to establish as a
culinary alternative to beef. It's an uphill fight but what else is
new for Turner, who helped establish the cable TV industry with his
TBS and CNN channels. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   GITOWN _ LEESVILLE, La. _ Despite its best efforts, this GI town
is no utopia. Eighty years after a group of Californians founded a
large commune here and promised members equal pay and equal social
opportunities, Leesville is a town in search of economic equality
with growing Southern communities. The New Llano commune lasted
just 20 years. A U.S. Army base has survived longer, but it has
never been particularly reliable. It opened and closed long often
enough to flood the town with soldiers preparing for World War II
and wars in Korea and Vietnam. Now, Leesville is struggling again.
Houses, bars, shops and a mobile home park are abandoned. There are
V.A. foreclosures for those who want them. (Kempner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS and MAP.
</P>
