<SLUG> BC-BOY-FINDS-GUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OFFICER AL'S' LECTURE BRINGS HAPPY ENDING TO GUN TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   METHUEN, Mass. _ The kids at the Maplewood Avenue bus stop were
pretty excited to find what looked to them like an old toy gun.
</P>
<P>
   That's why 11-year-old Christopher Beauchesne picked up the
handgun, after finding it while searching for a plastic action
figure he'd dropped while waiting for the school bus.
</P>
<P>
   So many parents in this neighborhood have imagined what might
have gone wrong from that moment. But disaster was avoided when a
first-grade girl remembered a lesson she had learned the day before
from ``Officer Al,'' the town's safety officer, who had visited her
classroom and lectured about handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Morganne Ackroyd began hollering loud enough for the whole block
to hear. ``I screamed: `Don't touch it because your arm will get
blown off,' '' she recalled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She was right: The handgun, which investigators suspect is the
weapon used in a triple homicide eight years ago, was still loaded.
And police believe it was the weapon used by a gunman who, after
killing three woman, later sought refuge in the home of coworker
Bob Beauchesne _ Chris's father.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Beauchesne said Thursday he thought immediately of the
triple-homicide. At the time, police had searched the area but
never recovered a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned back then becuase of all the kids around
here,'' Beauchesne said Thursday. But the killer, in the hours he
stayed with Beauchesne before turning himself in to police, ``told
me, `Don't worry about it, it's nowhere near here,' '' Beauchesne
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquim S. Alemeida, then 49, was sentenced to multiple life
sentences after the 1991 shootings.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, with Morganne Akroyd still shouting, the
eldest Akroyd girl, Kaitlynne, ran home to tell her grandmother,
who called the police.
</P>
<P>
   They recovered it still loaded with three cartridges. After
laying in the ground for years, the handgun, if fired, could have
easily exploded, police say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thank God it turned out this way,'' said Pattie Medore,
whose 11-year-old daughter was at the bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   Methuen oficer Al Torrisi noted he is only one of 35 ``safety
officers'' remaining in Massachusetts; many towns opt not to
finance them. The position is a law enforcement tradition left over
from the 1950s, when police would arrive in classrooms and tell
children not to talk to strangers and how to cross with the light.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Torrisi brings a display of handguns to school,
telling the children how many of them look like harmless toys, and
how dangerous they can be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
