<HEADER>
A1130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWORLEANS-WARM09-COX     04-08 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWORLEANS-WARM09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warming risky for Big Easy
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ More bad news for the Big Easy: If the fried
oyster po'-boys don't get you, global warming will.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans, already America's fattest city, now is the U.S.
city most at risk from the effects of global climate changes such
as floods, hurricanes and a rise in sea level, a new report says.
</P>
<P>
   The city lies 3 feet below sea level and is surrounded by the
Mississippi River, Lake Pontchartrain and wetlands. If temperatures
increase and sea level rises 10 inches in the next century, as is
projected, New Orleans would be flooded, according to ``Cities at
Risk,'' a report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the International Council for Local Environmental
Initiatives also says industries such as agriculture, shrimping and
fishing would be adversely affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life and property are at great risk in New Orleans from an
increase in the occurrence and severity of weather events such as
heat waves and hurricanes due to global warming,'' said Abby Young,
program coordinator for the Toronto-based council.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the scientific community thinks that human-produced
gases are disrupting the Earth's climate through the ``greenhouse
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that temperatures will rise 1.8 degrees to 6.3
degrees Fahrenheit in the 21st century, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Global warming is very much a local issue,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The council is working with 57 local governments to develop
strategies to reduce carbon dioxide emissions and gradual global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   A long list of bad circumstances earned New Orleans its latest
dubious achievement award. Besides being below sea level and
surrounded by water, the problems include:
</P>
<P>
   _ The loss of wetlands. For reasons unrelated to global warming,
Louisiana is losing its coastal wetlands at an alarming rate; more
than 1,500 square miles have been lost this century and 3,000 more
will go in the next century, said Gary Groesch of the Alliance for
Affordable Energy in New Orleans. The wetlands provide a vital
buffer when a hurricane hits. Losing them would leave New Orleans
more vulnerable to severe weather, Groesch said. In addition, many
species of wildlife would lose their habitats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Insects. Wetter winters and hotter summers mean more
mosquitoes, Groesch said. And the mosquitoes that carry dengue
fever, a devastating illness normally seen in tropical climates,
have been found in Texas already and will be in Louisiana in the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
   _ High energy use. Louisiana is the second-largest energy user
in the United States behind Texas. That's because the state sells
energy to industries at a massive discount, said Paul Temblet, a
professor of environmental studies at Louisiana State University.
By itself, Louisiana contributes 1 percent of the world's carbon
dioxide production, he said. That's more than many nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industries in Louisiana get their energy at 35 percent below
the national average,'' Temblet said. ``And the industries pay four
times less than Louisiana residents. They won't get more efficient
unless they have to pay more.''
</P>
<P>
   A bill to tax energy consumption was shot down last year in the
state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that we are the state most at risk from global
climate change and yet we are contributing the most to it of any
state,'' Temblet said.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans has assembled a task force to look at the problems
of global warming, said Jerald White, who works in Mayor Marc
Morial's office. The immediate goal is to reduce the city's energy
use by 20 percent and improve hurricane and flooding evacuation
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
