<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-700&AMP;ADD-N     04-08 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO OFFICIALS CLASH OVER PROPOSED BOMBING OF SERBIAN TV
FACILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-VIETNAM,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE, KOSOVO-CHILDREN,
KOSOVO-MILITARY.) 
(sw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO's military leaders vowed on Thursday to
bomb state-controlled Serbian television off the air, leading to a
public clash with the alliance's civilian officials, who have not
granted the generals the authority to strike the television
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance diplomats from three different countries said NATO's
supreme commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, had been pressing for
months for authority to bomb Serbian television and radio
transmission towers around the country because, as his military
spokesman put it on Thursday, they were ``an instrument of
propaganda and repression'' for the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Paris on Thursday morning about the French role in
the bombing campaign, Gen. Jean-Pierre Kelche, chief of the French
General Staff, accused the official Yugoslav press of disseminating
``hundreds of items of disinformation.'' He said the allies wanted
to start attacking Serbian television, RTS, which has been
broadcasting official propaganda and images of destruction said to
have been caused by the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to bust their transmitters and their relay
stations,'' Kelche said. ``We consider it an extremely dangerous
tool which is warping Serb opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   But, according to an authoritative official here,
representatives of NATO nations have not given the military command
permission to go after transmission towers that are regarded as
civilian rather than military targets.
</P>
<P>
   And the alliance's top civilian, Secretary-General Javier
Solana, said the only television towers that were being attacked
were those that were linked to military or police transmission
networks. Several such targets have been hit since the bombing
began March 24, but Serbian television screens have not been
darkened.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Kelche's remarks on Thursday afternoon, Air
Commodore David Wilby of Britain, spokesman for Clark, responded
with a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serb radio and television is an instrument of propaganda and
repression,'' he said. ``It has filled the airways with hate and
with lies over the years, and especially now. It is therefore a
legitimate target in this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If President Milosevic would provide equal time for Western
news broadcasts in its programs, without censorship, three hours a
day between noon and 1800 and three hours a day between 1800 hours
and midnight, then his television could become an acceptable
instrument of public information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he described the statement as ``a public announcement''
and said Milosevic could consider it ``fair warning.''
</P>
<P>
   But the alliance's civilian spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, quickly
moved to qualify the warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the television transmission towers are integrated into
the command and control communications transmission nodes of the
Yugoslav armed forces, and we have been attacking therefore those
military targets, which may have had as a secondary effect damage
or destruction to those TV towers,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   One participant in the alliance's daily decision-making meetings
in the North Atlantic Council later expressed surprise at the
announcement that the television transmitters would be hit.
``That's something General Clark started,'' he said. ``He's been
saying that television is an instrument of the Serb propaganda
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Another diplomat said that because the allies insisted on
keeping civilian casualties in Serbia to a minimum, the North
Atlantic Council had refused to approve Clark's requests to knock
television off the air despite its distortion of NATO's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sensitive issue, because a lot of the allies think they
are civilian targets,'' this official said.
</P>
<P>
   Silencing the adversary's propaganda machine was one of the
first things American, French and British planes did during the
Persian Gulf War in 1991, attacking Iraq's television transmitters
in the first hour of a bombing campaign far larger than the one in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But a European diplomat said on Thursday: ``This is not a war.
It's a limited, precise, use of force to paralyze a repressive
machine.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Serbian television has been particularly irritating for the
allies. Last week, it broadcast images of Milosevic happily
chatting with Ibrahim Rugova, a leading Kosovo Albanian political
figure, as if they both could not be happier despite the bombing
and the fury of the ``ethnic cleansing'' of Rugova's people in the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials say their military intelligence insists that
Rugova is in effect under house arrest, and they dismissed
Milosevic's announcement two days ago that Rugova had agreed to
negotiate a political settlement as part of a unilateral Serbian
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian television also broadcast the first images of the
American F-117A stealth fighter that was shot down on the first
weekend of the bombing, and showed the deaths and property damage
caused when a bomb fell 600 yards short of its target, an artillery
brigade headquarters, in Aleksinac.
</P>
<P>
   It has also claimed that allied bombing caused widespread damage
to Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, though Wilby said on Thursday
that the destruction had been done by marauding Serbian units, not
by NATO aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   CNN, the BBC and other Western television news organizations
have also rebroadcast Serbian television shots of bombs going off
at night around Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've used some of the Serb TV pictures, though we always mark
them very heavily,'' Vincent Ray, executive editor of BBC News,
said in a telephone interview from London. ``If they destroy
transmission facilities that Western media use, that would be an
interesting development.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a BBC correspondent, John Simpson, had a crew with him
in Belgrade that used Serbian television facilities to transmit
their own images. ``The problem is the Serbs won't let them go
around and see anything,'' he said. ``But we go to the transmission
facility to send only when we are pretty sure there won't be any
bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
