<SLUG> BC-CHINA-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE LEADER SEES ROOM FOR IMPROVEMENT ON HUMAN RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a startling addition to the usual Chinese line
on human rights, Premier Zhu Rongji said Thursday there is room to
improve human rights conditions in China and that he is impatient
with the pace of progress.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference with President Clinton, Zhu said neither
he nor President Jiang Zemin is aware of any efforts to steal US
nuclear secrets or to funnel money to Clinton's political
campaigns. He said he and Jiang have questioned Chinese military
leaders on the alleged espionage, and that they too deny any
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, who is extraordinarily animated and candid for a Chinese
leader, said China has agreed to cooperate with the US
investigation ``so long as you can provide some clues.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the two leaders were able to speak ``directly and
openly on matters where we have disagreements,'' and that ``it is
troubling that in the past year China has taken some steps
backwards on human rights'' by arresting people for their political
views. He also expressed regret that little progress has been made
in opening a dialogue between China and the Dalai Lama, the exiled
leader of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that during the talks Zhu agreed that China
would open markets to US citrus, meat products, and Pacific
Northwest wheat, and would direct all its government agencies to
use only licensed software. All these issues have been the focus of
trade frictions. He also said they struck a civil aviation
agreement which will double passenger and cargo flights between the
countries.
</P>
<P>
   However, the leaders acknowledged, agreement still eluded them
on the matter of Chinese entry to the World Trade Organization, a
primary goal of Zhu's visit. The Chinese leader said the gap
remaining between the two sides over what China must do to become
part of the international trading community is not great. The true
problem, he said, is American politics, which he believes is going
through an anti-China period.
</P>
<P>
   The press conference, held in the Old Executive Office Building,
lasted an hour and 45 minutes, one of the longest of Clinton's
presidency. Security was tight, and demonstrators for Tibetan
independence and greater human rights in China could be heard from
the entrances. But there were no incidents, and Zhu was as
good-humored as he was frank, his answers frequently evoking
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Before making his surprising comments on human rights, Zhu first
delivered the Communist Party line, stating his opposition to
American criticism of China's record at the United Nations Human
Rights Commission in Geneva, which he called unfair and ``an
interference in China's internal affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   He said differences in education and income levels also mean
people in the United States and in China have differences in their
definitions and priorities in the human rights area.
</P>
<P>
   ``So every country has its own approach.... One should not get
too impatient,'' Zhu said. ``But to tell the truth, I am more
impatient than you are in how to further constantly improve the
human rights in China.... I concede that there is room for
improvement in the human rights conditions in China.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Chinese are ``willing to listen to you (Americans),
and we are willing to have channels of dialogue on the human rights
question.''
</P>
<P>
   He said much of the rest of his visit to the United States _
which will take him to Denver, Chicago and New York, and will
conclude next Wednesday in Cambridge, Mass. with a speech and
discussion at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology _ will be
taken up with meeting and talking directly with Americans from many
walks of life to explain Chinese views and better understand
American views.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that only friends who say `yes' to you are good
friends,'' Zhu said. ``We believe that maybe the friends who are
able to say `no' to you are the best friends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
