<HEADER>
A1143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-STEM-CELLS-NYT &LR;      04-08 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STEM-CELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL DRAFTS RULES FOR HUMAN EMBRYO STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., N.J., Tenn.)  (mk) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ Federally financed scientists who wish to study
human embryonic stem cells, the primordial cells from which the
body develops, came a step closer to their goal Thursday as a panel
of biologists and lawyers drafted guidelines under which the
research may go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Use of the cells is contentious because they are derived from
human embryos and Congress has expressly forbidden federal funds to
be used for this purpose. But with enormous medical interest in
studying the cells, the general counsel of the Department of Health
and Human Services ruled in January that federally supported
researchers _ including most university-based scientists _ can
conduct research on the cells, as long as somebody else derived
them, using private money.
</P>
<P>
   But research cannot begin until the National Institutes of
Health, the chief disburser of federal medical research funds, has
issued guidelines drawn up by the director's advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's hearing, before a working group of the advisory
committee, the House Pro-Life Caucus and the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops objected strenuously to the decision to permit the
research. They echoed the position of a letter sent Wednesday by
Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., and eight other senators to Donna
Shalala, secretary of health and human services, saying that in
approving the research she would be sidestepping Congress' clear
intent by administrative fiat.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Shirley Tilghman of Princeton University, the chairwoman
of the working group, rebuffed the legal issue, saying that the
group's only task was to frame research guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Considerable discussion was devoted to arguments raised by
Richard Doerflinger of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
He accused Dr. Harold Varmus, director of the NIH, of playing with
words in defining the embryonic stem cells as ``pluripotent.''
Researchers have often called cells at this stage of development
totipotent, Doerflinger said. A totipotent cell, capable of forming
all human tissues, would be tantamount to an embryo, but a
pluripotent cell, able to make many but not all tissues, would be
something less.
</P>
<P>
   Doerflinger also said that researchers are on the brink of being
able to derive more specialized stem cells, or multipotent stem
cells, from the tissues of a patient's own body, and that these
would be more suitable than embryonic stem cells for
transplantation purposes because they would be compatible with the
patient's own immune system. Research on embryonic stem cells would
therefore be unnecessary as well as illegal, Doerflinger said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Brigid Hogan of Vanderbilt University, a member of the
working group, said that only the fertilized egg and cells from
stages preceding the blastocyst, or pre-implantation embryo, are
now regarded as totipotent. Human embryonic stem cells probably
cannot form the blastocyst's outer sphere of cells, from which the
placenta is derived.
</P>
<P>
   These cells, known as trophoblasts, are now believed to impress
an organizational structure on the embryonic cells which, if grown
by themselves, form a chaotic jumble of different tissue types, Dr.
Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Human embryonic stem cells grown in the laboratory form some
cells that have the characteristics of trophoblasts, Dr. Hogan
said, but even so did not develop into organized tissues like those
seen in a properly developing fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Human embryonic stem cells, the isolation and culture of which
was first described in November, can grow and divide indefinitely.
In principle, a single source could supply many researchers' needs.
For implanting the cells into patients, however, Dr. Hogan said a
bank of about 20 different cell lines would be needed, to include
cells compatible with the majority of human immune recognition
systems.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether embryonic stem cells or the more
specialized multipotent stem cells will prove best for
transplantation. Scientists hope that either type, when injected
into the right site in the body, would mature into the appropriate
cell type for that tissue. Stem cell research thus offers a broad
and novel approach to therapy, that of replacing diseased or worn
out tissues with brand-new source cells.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious application is in Parkinson's disease, caused by a
loss of dopamine-producing cells in the brain. Treatments involving
injection of fetal cells have shown some promise, but embryonic
cells would in many ways be preferable.
</P>
<P>
   The study of human embryonic stem cells is also important to
researchers seeking to understand the steps in human development
and how to prevent birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between totipotent, pluripotent and multipotent
stem cells may grow less significant as research proceeds. The
pluripotent embryonic stem cells mature into the multipotent stem
cells of brain, blood and other tissues under the influence of
certain growth factors, and the multipotent stem cells then
differentiate into the specialized cell types of the body. All
cells carry the same set of genetic instructions, however, and
there is likely to be no fundamental difference between them other
than the internal switch settings occasioned by the various growth
factors to which each class of cell has been exposed.
</P>
<P>
   The draft guidelines being considered by the working group would
permit federally funded research on human embryonic stem cells to
go ahead, subject to the cells being legally and ethically derived,
including having informed consent by the donors. The group's
recommendations require further approvals, including those of the
full advisory committee and the director of the NIH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
