<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1144 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHELL-BRUTUS-HNS &LR;      04-08 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELL-BRUTUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHELL TO GO AFTER 200 MILLION BARRELS OF OIL DEEP IN GULF OF MEXICO &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL DAVIS 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Shell Oil Co. will spend about $900 million to develop
a new deepwater Gulf of Mexico prospect named Brutus, estimated to
hold 200 million barrels of oil, the company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to proceed with development on a new field of this
size underscores the industry's stance that deepwater projects will
continue on schedule despite low oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Shell acquired the offshore leases for Brutus in 1985 for $15.5
million and has drilled three test and appraisal wells at the site
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deepwater projects don't come along every 90 days,'' said
Frank Knuettel, oil analyst with PaineWebber in New York. ``Just
because there has not been a major deepwater project announced in
some time does not mean anyone is backing away from their deepwater
plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Shell is forging ahead in the deepwater Gulf,
officials from Shell Oil's parent Royal Dutch/Shell Group told
analysts in New York Thursday that spending on oil production will
be about $5.7 billion in 1999, down from the $6 billion projected
three months ago and the record $8.3 billion spend in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Brutus will be the 17th Gulf of Mexico deepwater project in
which Houston-based Shell is the operator or has an interest. The
company has partners on many of its other deepwater prospects but
it holds 100 percent of the Brutus project.
</P>
<P>
   Brutus is on Green Canyon Block 158, about 165 miles southwest
of New Orleans. Production is expected to begin by late 2001, and
ultimately reach a peak rate of about 100,000 barrels of oil and
150 million cubic feet of gas per day.
</P>
<P>
   The project will be developed with a tension leg platform in
2,985 feet of water with installation scheduled for mid-year 2001.
It is not the deepest spot in which Shell operates an offshore Gulf
platform; that distinction still is held by Ursa which is in 4,000
feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Tension leg platforms float partially submersed and are tethered
to the sea floor. They are used in depths ranging from 1,500 to
7,000 feet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Brutus has been talked about for the better part of a year,''
said Rich Pattarozzi, deepwater division general manager for Shell
Exploration and Production Co. in New Orleans. ``We have been
working on the evaluation of the type of system we wanted and the
cost. We just recently got project approval and we are ready to
move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The design of the Brutus platform will be similar to that of two
of Shell's other deepwater platforms: Ram-Powell and Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of Brutus, however, will be about $100 million to $200
million less than those projects, largely because the design and
fabrication of Shell's deepwater tension leg platforms are becoming
more generic after four previous similar projects.
</P>
<P>
   Shell is the top oil and gas producer in the Gulf of Mexico with
daily output of 227,000 barrels of oil and 1.3 billion cubic feet
of gas. It is also the largest leaseholder, with an interest in
1,023 leases consisting of about 5.6 million acres.
</P>
<P>
   The $900 million price tag also includes the cost of building
pipelines to move the oil and gas from the Brutus platform to
existing pipelines in the Gulf which will then move the oil and gas
onshore.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
