<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1153 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-ART-2TAKES     04-08 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: official said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton and Zhu met in two separate sessions that, participants
say, was far more sober and businesslike than their public
performance later in the day. They discussed _ and disagreed on _
Kosovo Thursday morning in a small session attended by National
Security Adviser Sandy Berger, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, the cabinet member
who has most frequently encountered the Chinese premier. Chinese
leaders fear that the precedent of international intervention over
a rebellious province could easily be applied to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   At a larger meeting with other aides present, Zhu repeated his
vow not to devalue the Chinese currency, the yuan. Rubin and others
fear that a devaluation could re-ignite the Asian financial crisis.
They argued briefly on Clinton's plans to develop a missile defense
system in Asia, one ostensibly intended to protect American troops
from North Korean missiles, but a system the Chinese believe could
ultimately be used to defend Taiwan against Chinese missiles.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, veering into a discussion of Tibet, Zhu and
Clinton discussed the possibility of using the Vatican as a conduit
for discussions between Chinese leaders and the Dalai Lama, the
exiled religious leader of the Himilayan territory. In public, the
Dalai Lama is denounced as a religious fraud by Chinese diplomats;
the private conversation about opening a secret channel to him,
which White House officials refused to confirm Thursday night, was
calm and businesslike, according to several people familiar with
it.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday evening the main American negotiator on
the trade issues, U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky,
described China's willingness to open its markets in agriculture,
telecommunications, banking, insurance and other areas as ``very
sweeping.'' She suggested that final agreement was near _ but that
negotiators had simply run out of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that any of the remaining issues are
show-stoppers,'' she said. ``I would expect fairly rapid
resolution'' that would pave the way for China to join the WTO by
the time it hold a ministerial meeting in Seattle in November.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, executives of several companies said they were
surprised by the last-minute concessions that China made, some of
which are bound to open Zhu up to criticism that he is leaving
Chinese enterprises too vulnerable too soon to foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications agreement _ allowing foreign control of
cell phone networks, Internet providers and other ``value added
services'' _ came as a surprise. But while the business
opportunities for the likes of Motorola Corporation or AT&AMP;T _ along
with their Japanese and European competitors _ are obvious, such
accords usually run into myriad obstacles on the ground. And over
the years, the Chinese have shown that they understand that
Internet connections and a vast cell phone networks are a price of
joining the global economy, even if they dilute Beijing's ability
to control dissent and outside information.
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of the accord hint at a broadening of economic
freedom. China agreed to allow 100 percent foreign ownership of
commercial banks within five years _ almost all are now joint
ventures _ and they will be permitted for the first time to handle
individual Chinese accounts. That creates the possibility that a
worker in Xian would be able to deposit his savings at Citibank,
even if he would still face restrictions on moving his money
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are things that five years ago the Chinese wouldn't even
talk about,'' Robert Hormats, the vice chairman of Goldman Sachs
International, said Thursday morning, as Zhu and President Clinton
reviewed the military guard stretching across the South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese were unwilling to let foreign brokerages compete
for Chinese customers. They argue that an uncontrolled flow of
foreign capital worsened the Asian crisis, and they have no desire
to repeat the experience. But administration officials said they
believed China's reluctance had more to do with protectionism,
noting that they could keep in place strict rules on capital flows
in and out of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
