 (ATTN: Va.)  
 JURORS BEGIN DELIBERATING CONTEMPT CASE AGAINST SUSAN McDOUGAL 
 (rk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ A federal jury of six men and six women
began deliberating Thursday whether Susan McDougal is guilty of
criminal contempt and obstruction of justice for refusing to talk
to a grand jury about the Arkansas financial dealings of Bill and
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal's trial, now in its fifth week, is one of the
remaining loose ends in the once-sprawling Whitewater
investigation, now evidently winding down. She is almost certainly
the last person to go on trial in Arkansas in connection with the
investigation, which began with an examination of the Clintons'
role in the Whitewater real estate venture and eventually led to
the impeachment drama in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal has proved to be one of the most intriguing of
Whitewater figures, having already spent 18 months in jail for
civil contempt because of her unwillingness to testify before the
grand jury. She argued at the time, and then repeatedly at her
trial, that her refusal was principled, based on a belief that
Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, was determined
to prosecute the Clintons at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   In her trial testimony, she maintained that she had feared being
indicted for perjury as a result of any grand-jury testimony she
gave that did not implicate the Clintons in wrongdoing. She
compared Starr's tactics to those of the Nazis, a theme that her
lawyer, Mark Geragos, repeated in closing arguments to the jury on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as a witness at her trial, Ms. McDougal responded to the
very questions she had refused to answer, telling the jury she had
no knowledge of wrongdoing by the Clintons. Prosecutors tried to
turn this testimony to their advantage, arguing that she had
withheld information that would have helped the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what's absolutely reprehensible,'' Mark Barrett, one of
the prosecutors, told the jury. ``She had information that
exonerated President Clinton, and she kept that information from
the grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   In their closing arguments, Barrett and another prosecutor,
Julie Myers, offered a simple outline of their case. Ms. McDougal,
they noted, was given immunity from prosecution and then ordered by
a federal judge to answer questions from the grand jury, and she
refused.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant is a woman given to dramatic posturing, they
contended, and her refusal to testify had more to do with her
eagerness for public attention than with any point of principle she
professed to be making.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal and her husband, James McDougal, were partners with
the Clintons in the Whitewater venture, nestled in the Arkansas
Ozarks, when Clinton was governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Among other matters, Starr's prosecutors investigated whether
Clinton had improperly pressed for a federally guaranteed loan to
Ms. McDougal, part of whose proceeds were later used to help prop
up the failing enterprise. This was a chief issue that Ms. McDougal
refused to address before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   That grand jury, here in Arkansas, has already disbanded, as has
the Starr grand jury in Washington, which dealt primarily with the
president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Starr's aides have declined to say whether they are wrapping up
their work, but he has only one remaining grand jury, in Virginia,
and after Ms. McDougal the prosecutors are scheduled to bring to
trial only two other defendants: Julie Hiatt Steele, charged with
obstructing justice and making false statements in the Kathleen
Willey episode, and Webster Hubbell, charged with tax evasion in an
indictment that suggests he was paid to remain silent about his
knowledge of the Clintons' business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration of the McDougal case's secondary nature, the
prosecutors here suggested that they might not oppose leniency if
the defendant was convicted. Speaking to reporters, Barrett noted
that Ms. McDougal had already served a year and a half in jail for
civil contempt, as well as three and a half months on her 1996
Whitewater fraud conviction, a term that was cut short because of
her health problems.
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be ``totally appropriate'' to take those
punishments into account in determining a sentence other than
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the weeks of testimony and argument, the defense
strategy was to put Starr and his fellow prosecutors on trial with
arguments that they had abused other figures in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Judge George Howard Jr. allowed Geragos, Ms. McDougal's lawyer,
great leeway, even permitting him to call as a witness Ms. Steele,
who has been indicted because of her testimony that Ms. Willey
never told her of being groped by the president. Like Ms. McDougal,
Ms. Steele told the jurors, she has been victimized for not telling
the prosecutors what they wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end Howard told the jury that it was Ms. McDougal,
and no one else, who was on trial. He also instructed the jury that
she could not use as a defense that she had had a moral or ethical
reason for refusing to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors recessed Thursday evening and are to resume on
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
