<SLUG> BC-US-GUANATANAMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MAY DROP PLAN TO BRING REFUGEES TO GUANTANAMO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Days after pledging to take up to 20,000 Kosovo
refugees at the US naval base in Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, Clinton
administration officials said Thursday that the plan has been put
on hold and may be shelved.
</P>
<P>
   J. Brian Atwood, the head of the US Agency for International
Development and coordinator of the Kosovo refugee plan, said
Thursday that the transfer of refugees to Guantanamo has been put
on hold for at least this week because the Kosovo refugees don't
want to leave the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't walking back on the strategy,'' Atwood said. ``The
pressure to move people out...isn't as great. We know people would
prefer to stay in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that anyone in our government is that
enthusiastic'' about sending the refugees to the naval base, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, officials insisted the plan to send refugees to
Guantanamo had never been finalized and the initial stage of the
crisis was passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immediate crisis of them having food and some shelter, the
majority of that seems to be take care of,'' said Rear Admiral
Thomas R. Wilson, director for intelligence of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff. ``We'll start being more deliberate in where they move, and
the decision for them to go to Guantanamo has not been made yet.''
</P>
<P>
   These optimistic-sounding statements were made even as reports
from the Kosovo region showed that tens of thousands of refugees
are living in squalid conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Guantanamo plan had come under sharp criticism from human
rights advocates, including some who expressed their displeasure to
White House officials Thursday. Some human rights advocates have
said that the conditions at Guantanamo are comparable to a
low-security prison. They have also criticized the administration
for refusing to open US borders to the refugees and allow them to
apply for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration said the plan was being suspended
because the crisis had eased, some foreign policy analysts said the
reason had more to do with a realization by the administration that
the refugee transfer would be a public relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a horrible mistake'' to announce the Guantanamo plan,
said Sherle Schwenninger, senior fellow at the World Policy
Institute. He said US officials probably realized after announcing
the plan that it could be a replay of what happened when Haitian
refugees were housed at Guantanamo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you remember the images of refugees of Haitians behind
barbed wire, this would have been a PR nightmare,'' he said.
Schwenninger said the United States bears some responsibility for
the refugees crisis and has a ``moral responsibility'' to open US
borders to the displaced Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   In a closed meeting Thursday with administration officials, more
than 20 non-governmental organizations urged the White House to
reconsider its plans to use Guantanamo for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very strongly that they ought to stop in their tracks
and rethink this whole operation,'' said John Fredriksson,
associate executive director of the US Committee for Refugees, who
did not attend the meeting but was familiar with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that the Cuban government, while
condemning NATO military action against Yugoslavia, has no
objection to the use of Guantanamo as a refugee haven and also
offered to cooperate in providing assistance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tatsha Robertson of the Globe staff contributed to this report
from Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
