<SLUG> BC-CHINA-WHEAT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHWEST FARMERS `ELATED' OVER U.S.-CHINA WHEAT AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a major victory for Washington state's
struggling farmers, China yesterday agreed to drop its 27-year ban
on the importation of Pacific Northwest wheat.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and President
Clinton announced at a joint news conference, was greeted with
jubilation by Washington's wheat farmers and elected officials who
have been jealously eying China's 1 billion consumers as a
potential market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are elated over this,'' said Thomas Mick, chief executive
officer of the Washington Wheat Commission. ``This could mean a
real boon for our area.''
</P>
<P>
   Dropping its longstanding objections to Northwest wheat was one
of a series of trade concessions China made as part of its
thus-far-unsuccessful bid to win admission to the World Trade
Organization. China also agreed to relax barriers against the
importation of U.S. citrus and meat products, and agreed to take a
step toward cracking down on computer software piracy, an important
issue to Microsoft, Nintendo, and other Seattle-area companies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the moves ``an important agreement that will open
China's markets for U.S. exports of citrus, meat products, and
Pacific Northwest wheat, all highly important for our farmers.''
Zhu said the concessions ``will further promote the development of
friendship and cooperation between China and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The two countries plan in coming months to continue negotiations
over Chinese membership in the World Trade Organization, with the
White House hopeful of reaching a deal before WTO trade ministers
gather in Seattle in November.
</P>
<P>
   China in the past has refused to accept any wheat that comes
through ports in the Pacific Northwest because of the presence of a
disease-bearing fungus, or smut, called Tilletia controversa kuhn
(TCK), that affects wheat crops. U.S. officials have insisted that
the contamination is minor, could not spread to Chinese wheat crops
because of differing climactic conditions, and is harmless to
people.
</P>
<P>
   Under yesterday's agreement, China agreed to abide by the
findings of international scientists who have found that a low
level of TCK smut does not pose a risk to Chinese wheat crops or
consumers. U.S. wheat growers said they will have no problem
staying below the low level of TCK smut tolerance agreed to by
China.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese also agreed to reduce tariffs on U.S. wheat from 20
percent to 1 percent for the first 7.3 million metric tons.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat is Washington state's largest agricultural export, and
both of the state's U.S. senators have devoted considerable energy
to this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., has repeatedly tried to use her
friendship with Clinton administration officials and her belief in
constructive engagement with Chinese officials to push the issue,
while Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., has repeatedly hammered the
Clinton administration and China to do more to resolve the wheat
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This potentially means several hundred millions of dollars of
sales of our wheat to China,'' Murray said yesterday. ``Our wheat
farmers have really been hurt in the last several years because of
the Asian (economic) crisis, and this is a major boon for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton was effusive in his praise for the Clinton
administration, and in particular U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time when I've got to offer my congratulations to
the (Clinton) administration, because this is a major
accomplishment,'' Gorton said. ``This is about as good news as
Washington farmers have gotten in years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gorton warned removing barriers is only half the battle,
because the Chinese still have to decide to make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been occasions when the Chinese have nominally
removed trade barriers and nothing has taken place as a result,''
Gorton said. ``The real proof here will be with the first set of
orders.''
</P>
<P>
   China is a major producer of wheat, but it is also a large
consumer, and frequent weather woes have led it to import large
quantities of wheat in some years. Washington farmers believe that
the soft white wheat grown in the Northwest is particularly
suitable for a number of Chinese dietary staples, such as steamed
bread, a wrapping called suey gow, and various confectionery
products.
</P>
<P>
   Orders by China are likely to depend on many factors,
particularly the weather in China. Over the past decade, China has
imported anywhere from 2 million to 16 million metric tons of wheat
per year from such countries as Australia, Canada and France.
</P>
<P>
   According to Karen Fegley, the director of the Wheat Export
Trade Education Committee, U.S. growers should have a shot at
selling about 8 million metric tons of wheat to China a year.
Currently, wheat is selling for between $120 and $140 a metric ton.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal on software, reached on Wednesday, the Chinese
government agreed to order all government entities to use only
legally purchased software. The U.S. government issued a similar
directive in October 1998, and Paraguay, Thailand, Turkey, the
Philippines, Korea and Jordan have issued similar decrees in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is significant because China has one of the highest
piracy rates in the world _ 96 percent of software in China is
pirated _ and because governments are the largest users of
software,'' said Anne Gavin, spokeswoman for the Business Software
Alliance. Gavin said her group will be monitoring Chinese behavior
to see if the order is enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative, said the software
pact could have a trickle-down effect on the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a milestone in China's efforts to increase
intellectual property protection,'' she said. ``The Chinese
government's action ... sets an important example for the Chinese
private sector and for other national governments as well. The
Chinese decree is particularly significant given the size and rapid
expansion of the Chinese market for personal computers, now the
world's fifth largest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
