<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN RATE CUT SENDS U.S. STOCK GAUGES TO RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Europeans cut interest rates Thursday, igniting stock
markets in mid-session here, and all three major market gauges
climbed more than 1 percent to new records.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks were again among the pacesetters, but they were
joined by such recently lagging blue chips as Coca-Cola and
Minnesota Mining &AMP; Manufacturing, which have suffered from sluggish
European operations. Another standout was Wal-Mart Stores, which
jumped 4} to 102\, one of several retailers reporting very strong
March sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of the market seems to be coming from the bond
side,'' said Philip Orlando, the chief investment officer at Value
Line Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   Lower interest rates not only tend to make stocks relatively
more appealing but also reduce such business costs as carrying
inventory or investing in new machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was little reaction to an early rate cut by the
Bank of England, a larger-than-expected cut by the European Central
Bank shortly after noon galvanized investors and lifted prices
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   By the close, the Dow Jones industrial average had gained 112.39
points to 10,197.70, just over 11 percent higher than at the
beginning of the year. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose
17.09 points, to 1,343.98, and the technology-driven Nasdaq market
rebounded from Wednesday's slump to gain 28.96 points to 2,573.39.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices advanced along a broad front, with the bellwether
30-year Treasury issue rising 26/32 of a point to 97 5/32, to push
its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, down to a
six-week low of 5.44 percent from 5.50 percent Wednesday. Rates on
5-year and 10-year Treasury securities _ the latter a benchmark for
home mortgages _ eased even more.
</P>
<P>
   With inflation in this country remarkably benign in the ninth
year of an uninterrupted economic expansion, U.S. Treasury
securities offer some of the best rates of return among global bond
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Initially in Thursday's session, rates were little changed as
investors looked largely in vain for signs of cooling economic
growth. Another factor was Fannie Mae, which was tapping the market
for $3 billion. Dealers who had sold Treasuries as a hedge suddenly
were forced to scramble for cover as the market rallied on the
larger-than-expected half-point cuts by the European Central Bank.
Fannie Mae's 10-year notes were sold at a price to yield 5.716
percent, or about 59 basis points, or hundredths of a percentage
point, more than Treasury securities with a similar maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate cuts caught those who had set short positions leaning
the wrong way,'' said Daniel Antonellis, market analyst at
Briefing.com, an analytical firm in Menlo Park, Calif. But he added
that they ``gave the market much needed direction, particularly
with the Federal Reserve on hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the financial sector, which included gains of 3{ to 87~
for Chase Manhattan and 3 11/16 to 52\ for Republic New York, hefty
gains were widespread among drug and oil companies. Lilly, Abbott
and Pfizer all rose about 3 points, while Chevron jumped to a
record before closing at 93}, up 3 13/16 points for the day. Oil
prices have rebounded smartly in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's biggest gainer was Union Carbide, which surged 5{ to
51] on revived speculation that the chemical company may be
acquired. General Electric eased | to 113~ after an earnings report
that matched, but did not surpass, profit expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage stocks rose again but generally less than Wednesday.
An exception was a 10-point gain, to 84, for Knight/Trimark Group,
a market-maker in Nasdaq and other securities; it traded as low as
4{ six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest advance did little to remedy what Alan Ackerman,
market strategist at Fahnestock, called a bifurcated market in
which household names keep going up, while most others are ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big-cap stocks are in a bull market, while the small-cap
stocks appear to be in a bear market,'' he said. The S&AMP;P is now up
more than 9 percent so far this year while the Russell 2000,
composed of smaller companies, is down more than 5 percent. The
Russell rose 53/100 of 1 percent Thursday, less than half the 1.29
percent gain for the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange volume expanded to 850.56 million
shares from 816.41 Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
