<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMANA-MARKETPLACE-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMANA SAYS 1ST QUARTER PROFIT WILL NOT MEET FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Skedded as HUMANA-OUTLOOK on some early budget. See also
HEALTH-TECH-COST) 
(mk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Resurrecting concerns about whether managed-care companies do
much real managing, starting with their own businesses, Humana Inc.
said Thursday that its first-quarter profit would come in well
below forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The company said its operating profit would be 20 to 24 cents a
share in the quarter, down 30 percent from earlier projections.
Additionally, the company will take a $90 million charge for a
renegotiated contract with Florida hospitals and reserves to cover
future costs, which will probably lead to a net loss for the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The profit warning comes because underlying costs of care in
hospitals and doctors' offices are rising faster than expected,
faster even than the double-digit percentile increases in premiums
that Humana charged its customers this year.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it seemed like deja vu all over again, replaying
investors' nightmares dating to 1996 when, one after the other,
managed-care companies acknowledged mistakes in their cost
projections. One difference this time: Health insurance companies
are having better success in raising premiums. This year, Humana
raised rates by 11 percent to 12 percent for big health plans and
15 percent to 16 percent for smaller groups with fewer than 100
members. It plans to seek more increases before the year is out.
</P>
<P>
   But expenses are climbing even faster as patients use more
medical services and managed-care companies encounter growing
resistance to cutbacks on payments.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are consolidating, raising their ability to resist
demands for lower fee arrangements. Doctor groups are seeking
higher payments, and some are apparently making up for reduced
payments by seeing more patients more often. And health plan
members are demanding expensive drugs, stimulated by billion-dollar
ad campaigns by drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance companies themselves are increasingly reluctant to
say no to their members' requests for care, especially while
Congress considers patients' right bills that would open health
plans to medical malpractice lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Humana prides itself on knowing its business better than most.
Even so, it was surprised by a 20 percent surge in prescription
drug costs and substantial increases in the length of hospital
stays and visits to emergency rooms. Industry surveys point to
similar cost growth nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Wolf, the company's president and chief executive, said
it was hard to imagine that other managed-care companies would not
face similar problems. He noted that Milliman &AMP; Robertson, a
benefits consulting firm, recently said that health costs rose 8.5
percent in November, exceeding the 6 percent to 7 percent the
firm's actuaries had projected.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a survey by Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette found that
employers were ``already seeing significant medical cost
acceleration,'' Mimi Willard, a Donaldson vice president, said.
</P>
<P>
   On a day of rising stock prices, Humana led a broad decline in
managed-care stocks, plunging $5, or 33 percent, to $10.0625, a
52-week low, before rebounding to $12.1875, still a drop of 25
percent, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   United Healthcare was down $6 a share, to $44.6875; Pacificare
Health Systems fell $6.4375, to $61.3125; Wellpoint Health Networks
dropped $5.25, to $69.875; Cigna fell $4.4375, to $82.25, and Aetna
slid $2.4375, to $78.0625. But one company, Tenet Healthcare, rose
more than 20 percent even though it reported lower earnings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Humana may have been squeezed harder than most HMO companies. It
said that a new two-year contract with Florida hospitals of
Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. would add $50 million to expenses,
while a squeeze on government payments for Medicare HMOs would be
passed along to Medicare beneficiaries in reduced benefits next
year. Humana is one of the biggest operators of Medicare HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Many Columbia hospitals trace their origins to Humana, which was
able to negotiate below-market rates in the past, Wolf said. When
Columbia sold its hospitals in places like Louisville, Ky., Chicago
and San Antonio, the chain had less at stake in negotiations with
Humana, threatening at one point to ``walk away'' from its
contract, Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Walter, an analyst at Merrill Lynch, said that hospital
costs had been rising after several years of ``trending down.'' She
added that hospital companies could not reduce the days that
patients stay in a hospital beyond a certain point. ``There is only
so much you can squeeze out with managed care,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Humana, which was involved in merger and
acquisition talks last year, was still financially strong. Wolf
said Humana's modest 2.7 percent profit margin _ typical in the
industry _ would continue to deteriorate in the second and third
quarters before rebounding in the fourth. He said the company had
``terrific cash flows'' and a strong balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Albers, an analyst with Deerfield Partners, which manages
health care stock funds, said Humana's problems ``show what a lag
this industry has in trying to figure out what costs are.'' HMOs
collect premiums and set aside reserves that they hope will cover
costs when medical bills arrive later. She added: ``It's a
constantly changing picture. You really don't know the real answer
until six months after the fact, or even longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Sherlock, an independent managed-care analyst, said:
``Estimating medical reserves is like shooting a rocket to the
moon. If you're off by one degree, you end up shooting somebody
else's moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Abramowitz, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein, said the
managed-care companies would have to ``raise prices faster and do a
better job of managing costs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People get sick and technology gets created and drug companies
want more money,'' he added. ``The question is, when are HMOs going
to charge corporate America for what they want?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
