<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta plans to replace some flights with ASA
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines this summer will replace certain
flights in the Southeast with service by Atlantic Southeast
Airlines, the regional feeder in which Delta recently bought a
majority stake.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Delta will expand its own service on long-haul
markets between Atlanta and the western United States.
</P>
<P>
   The moves reflect Delta's plans to use the ASA acquisition to
more closely integrate the two carriers' operations.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta said ASA will add flights between Atlanta
and five Southeastern cities on June 1. Delta still will offer its
own flights on those routes but will reduce the number.
</P>
<P>
   Cities affected are Augusta; Montgomery, Ala.; and Daytona
Beach, Melbourne and Tallahassee, Fla. ASA will use 50-seat
regional jets for the flights, Delta said.
</P>
<P>
   ASA also begins regional jet flights between Atlanta and Islip,
N.Y., on Aug. 1, creating the only nonstop service to the Long
Island airport from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Delta is adding one additional flight to four
Western cities: Denver and San Antonio on June 1; San Francisco on
July 1; and San Diego, July 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``In more closely integrating ASA's and Delta's schedules at the
Atlanta hub, Delta takes advantage of the opportunity to reallocate
larger jets to long-haul markets'' that are often more profitable,
said Mark A.P. Drusch, Delta's senior vice president-network
management.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Delta rival AirTran said it will add a fifth
daily flight between Atlanta and Jacksonville, Fla., and a fourth
daily flight between Atlanta and Greensboro, N.C., on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
