<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta set to scrap 'Top of World' ads
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines is coming down from ``On Top of the
World.''
</P>
<P>
   The carrier is ditching its 2-year-old advertising slogan and
has put its agency to work on a new one that will debut this fall
in a fresh image-building campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can bury that tag line at this point,'' said Martin White,
recently installed as vice president for consumer marketing at
Atlanta-based Delta.
</P>
<P>
   He said the slogan, which sought to convey worldliness and
success, instead seemed vague and out of touch _ especially when
packaged in ethereal TV spots with chantlike theme music and
floating balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customers didn't understand it, and the employees didn't
buy into it,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ``On Top of the World'' TV spots will keep airing on
a limited basis until the new campaign is ready.
</P>
<P>
   The next tag line and campaign are being developed by Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi, the New York agency Delta switched to in 1997 after 51
years with BBDO South. The ``On Top of the World'' campaign was
Saatchi's first for Delta and was authorized by the carrier's old
management, much of which has been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   A preview of Delta's next advertising approach may be seen in a
print-radio campaign starting Monday for the airline's
BusinessElite cabin, which is replacing separate first- and
business-class sections on international planes.
</P>
<P>
   The BusinessElite ads carry no tag line and take a practical
tack. One shows a close-up of a tape measure, with copy touting
extra inches in the new cabins that mean ``52 percent more legroom
than British Airways and 28 percent more recline than American
Airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tone does reflect what we're aiming for'' in the fall
image campaign, said White, who came to Delta from US Airways. ``We
want it to be straightforward and not afraid of direct comparisons.
What we don't have yet is an overall theme.''
</P>
<P>
   While the ``On Top of the World'' campaign was seen as an
improvement over BBDO's widely panned ``Delta Marathon'' campaign
for the 1996 Olympics, Delta executives soon conceded its message
was vague. Even before White arrived, plans were being laid to give
customers more specific reasons to fly Delta.
</P>
<P>
   White said Delta's old ``We Love to Fly and It Shows'' slogan
was one of his favorites. He said the new fall campaign may have a
similar focus on employee spirit but added, ``Everything is still
on the table right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
