<HEADLINE>
BEAVERS MAKE MEALS OUT OF WASHINGTON'S FAMED CHERRY TREES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan, Texas, Va., Ky.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eating a leisurely picnic lunch Thursday under a
canopy of Washington's famous cherry blossoms, Mark Taylor suddenly
snapped to attention. Out there. In the Tidal Basin. Splashing
around. There he was: the beaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came up on his back, flipped over and went back under,''
Taylor said. ``I'm sure that was him.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it be? While several people have reported spotting a
beaver swimming in the Tidal Basin over the last few days, no one
has confirmed that Taylor's was one of those that have been
confounding the National Park Service for more than a week by
chomping away on some of the 3,700 cherry trees in the area, then
escaping into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Park Service officials, who originally suspected they were
dealing with one beaver, are now fairly sure there are two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a reliable sighting this morning, two of them in the
Tidal Basin,'' said Earle Kittleman, a spokesman for the Park
Service.
</P>
<P>
   As the pink-and-white cherry blossoms reached their full bloom
this week, park service officials were blaming the beavers for
felling nine trees _ four cherries and five white cedars _ and
damaging four others so badly they are not expected to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Teeth marks also have been found on 30 to 40 other trees,
leading park workers to wrap their damaged trunks with chicken
wire.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, as a sparkling sun and 80-degree temperatures greeted
thousands of visitors strolling along the Tidal Basin promenade,
the wired trunks at one spot across from the Jefferson Memorial
drew quite a crowd of people. Some people wanted to know what the
beaver gnawed, and when did he gnaw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize we were at beaver ground zero,'' said Cliff
Lowell, pointing out shredded bark and teeth marks to his wife,
Kerry Koller, and their two young children. ``I'm impressed. You
can tell it's fresh chewing. But if he's trying to dam up the Tidal
Basin, he's in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Other visitors saw sinister forces at work, raising the
possibility of a wag-the-beaver scenario. Sheri Polis of
Alexandria, Va., suggested that the Clinton administration had set
loose the beaver as a way to deflect attention from other problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised this didn't happen during Monica Lewinsky,'' Ms.
Polis said. ``I'm a Democrat, but I'm willing to believe
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily Copening, a sightseer from Louisville, Ky., expressed
sympathy for the beaver. ``I want them to transfer him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer him? To where, she was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm just a tourist,'' she said. ``I don't know what's
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Park Service officials are trying to figure out how to capture
the beavers, which first damaged some of the cherry trees last
year. Kittleman said the task is especially challenging now, one of
the city's busiest tourism weeks of the year. Many visitors come to
Washington just to see the blossoms on the cherry trees, which were
a gift to the United States from Japan in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a crowded area down there,'' Kittleman said. ``I
don't want to say exactly what we're going to do. Anyway, we're
still trying to figure it out, what method to use, what kind of
lure, how to make sure we have a successful relocation.''
</P>
<P>
   Advice is pouring in. The Park Service has heard from
naturalists, wildlife organizations and the National Zoo, as well
as from individual citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Bob Moore's take on things. A tourist from
Sugarland, Texas, who professed to know a thing or two about
beavers, Moore postulated that a beaver was chewing up the trees
because they suited his diet.
</P>
<P>
   To catch the beaver, he said, ``They need another beaver. Or a
fake beaver. Put it near a tree. He might spot it and come up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
