<HEADER>
A1172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTRALIA-COKE09-COX     04-08 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-COKE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke stock up despite snags in Cadbury deal
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. posted its first gain on Wall Street in
nine days Thursday, despite an Australian ruling that blocks part
of its $1.85 billion acquisition of Cadbury Schweppes' beverages
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There also was a report Thursday from Germany that antitrust
regulators there will block the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Competition and Consumer Commission said the
purchase of Cadbury brands in that country would result in a
substantial reduction in competition as Coca-Cola melds its
powerful brands with Cadbury's Dr Pepper, Canada Dry and the
Schweppes line of mixers. The proposed deal would increase
Coca-Cola's share of the Australian soft drink market to 75
percent, from 65 percent, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies, however, said they have negotiated revisions to
the deal they hope will meet regulatory muster in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies had positive discussions with the ACCC earlier
this week regarding the amended proposal and believe that real
progress has been made towards a successful outcome,'' Coca-Cola
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based beverage giant plans to buy Cadbury brands in
120 countries, excluding France, South Africa and the United
States. Of the 20 or so nations that require regulatory approval,
five have already given it.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies may face antitrust obstacles in about 10
countries.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the daily newspaper Handelsblatt reported regulators
there will block the sale. And in Mexico, the deal also could be
challenged when regulators meet there soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulatory process is a long one,'' said Coca-Cola
spokesman Robert Baskin. ``There are a number of countries that are
reacting to initial proposals. If and when the reactions in
isolated cases are negative, that doesn't mean we can't appeal or
submit another proposal. These are ongoing discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said they do not expect the regulatory
challenges to kill the deal.
</P>
<P>
   John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage Digest, believes
the Australian takeover eventually will be approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were laying odds, I would bet the deal goes through, but
in a different configuration from what was originally proposed,''
Sicher said. That could mean Coca-Cola would sell off some of
Cadbury's Australian brands, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, Sicher added, Coca-Cola's key bottler there, Coca-Cola
Amatil, also may sell local brands to win regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   The overall deal in 120 countries is important to Coca-Cola for
two reasons, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   First, it increases the company's sales by 600 million cases a
year. What's more, Cadbury's brands would be distributed through
Coca-Cola's superior network.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means an acceleration of growth for the Cadbury brands
even more in the years to come,'' Sicher said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's stock rose $1.93 3/4 Thursday, closing at $60.87
1/2. It had been losing ground since closing at $65.87 1/2 on March
25.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term buyers saw it below $60 and said things will get
better eventually,'' analyst Caroline Levy of Schroder &AMP; Co. said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley analyst Andrew Conway expects trading to be in
the $57 to $62 range until the second half of the year when, he
said, sales and earnings growth will accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, we believe the worst is over for Coca-Cola,'' Conway
wrote in a research report published Thursday, referring to the
company's problems overseas.
</P>
<P>
   His year-end price target for the stock remained at $75.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Conseil d'Etat, France's highest court, said it
will hear Coca-Cola's appeal today against the French government's
rejection of the company's effort to buy Orangina.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for a ruling on Coke's $830 million bid for
the flavored drink.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
