<SLUG> BC-CONCOURS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amelia Island Concours d'Elegance a classic in the making
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After four years, the Amelia Island Concours
d'Elegance in Florida has grown to be much more than just another
car show.
</P>
<P>
   It now encompasses three days of activities and is generally
recognized as one of the top events of its kind in the country.
Weekend activities included a road rally, a golf tournament and
social events.
</P>
<P>
   The crown jewel of the weekend was the concours with honorary
chairman Carroll Shelby, a legend in the American automotive
industry. His accomplishments include production of automobiles
such as the 289 and 427 Cobras as well as the Peter Brock-designed
Daytona Coupe. Those cars shared the spotlight with 206 exceptional
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the event's ambience was Packard, this year's featured
marque. On display were Packard cars ranging from a 1904 Graywolf
owned by Atlantan Jim Kaufmann to a 1954 Packard Panther.
</P>
<P>
   The cars were exquisite, but don't expect to see any of them at
next year's concours. A car may be displayed only once, and all
cars are presented by invitation only.
</P>
<P>
   One participant from Pennsylvania commented, ``What I really
like about Amelia Island is that it is more about cars and less
about the social scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the grounds were filled with models strolling in period
costumes that complemented the cars, families with dogs and
children in tow, and guests of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   This year's event had more than 9,000 people attending the
charity functions, which raise funds for Hospice Northeast, based
in Jacksonville, Fla., and serving patients in northern Florida and
southern Georgia. It was originally organized by Bill Warner of
Jacksonville, whose father was cared for by the hospice.
</P>
<P>
   The grandfather of all concours in this country is Pebble Beach,
Calif., which is in its 49th year, followed by Meadow Brook, Mich.,
in its 21st season. Next year's Amelia Island concours is scheduled
for April 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
