u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHWIRE09-COX     04-08 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHWIRE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southwire selling metal-making unit
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southwire, one of the world's largest cable and wire
makers, is selling its metal manufacturing business, including
smelters in Carrollton and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Southwire is getting out of the metal business to focus on its
cable and wireless business, Mallard Holliday, a Southwire
spokesman, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company will use the money from the sale to upgrade its
factories and expand its cable and wire manufacturing businesses,
he said. No buyer has been named.
</P>
<P>
   Southwire, which has annual sales of $1.4 billion, employs 4,500
people, 2,300 in Georgia. Southwire operates 15 factories, six of
them in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Southwire sold factories in Texas, Malaysia and
England to Knoxville-based Dura-Line. The factories, which made
polyethylene conduit used to protect telecommunications lines,
operated under the name Integral.
</P>
<P>
   The refinery is the United States' largest recycler of scrap
copper, Holliday said. The 380 workers there make 138,000 tons of
sheet copper a year. The copper is used in cable and to wire homes,
businesses and factories for electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The company is amid a $125 million expansion of its aluminum
smelting plant, located in Hawesville, Ky., an Ohio River town
southwest of Louisville. The factory makes more than 200,000 tons
of aluminum a year. The near-pure metal is used in cable and to
transmit electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The smelter, running since 1969, employs about 800 people, half
of whom were hired to replace 400 United Steelworkers who went on
strike in June.
</P>
<P>
   Holliday said Southwire's decision to close the factories is not
based on labor issues or metal prices, which are near historic
lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad they didn't reach this decision when metal prices
were higher and would have supported better prices for these
assets,'' said Thomas Van Leeuwen, a research analyst with Credit
Suisse First Boston. ``Metal prices are at absolutely abysmal
levels. It puts tremendous profit pressure on all smelters
worldwide. Inventories for both copper and aluminum are
accumulating. There is more metal there than people need.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has operated the Hawesville smelter, which makes
ingots and bars, with managers and replacement workers since the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   The union offered March 2 to return to work unconditionally, but
Southwire kept the replacement workers and put the strikers on a
waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
