<SLUG> BC-SHARP-COLUMN-CONCOURS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Being a judge at Concours is like picking the best diamond
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This was my fourth consecutive year attending the
Amelia Island Concours d'Elegance, and I have developed a real
fondness for the event. The first year, I didn't even really know
what a concours d'elegance was until I got there.
</P>
<P>
   It is an exceptional display of exceptional cars restored in
many cases to better-than-new condition. It is something that
anyone who has a soft spot in their heart for things automotive, or
who just happens to appreciate beautiful cars, can get into.
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine my surprise when Amelia Island Concours Chairman
Bill Warner called to invite me to be a judge. Astonished, I
replied, ``I'm really honored, but I don't think I'm remotely
qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would put me ``with some other big-name judge'' and I
would do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   It was my impression that judges were automotive gurus who knew
things like what were the appropriate options, proper paint colors
and a host of other details not common knowledge to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to look like an idiot, I sought out some scholarly
advice from Jonathan Stein, editor of the collectors' publication
Automobile Quarterly. He said judging was basically a process of
intelligence, common sense and good taste.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, I attended the judges brunch. Across the table
was Tom Bryant, editor of Road &AMP; Track magazine and part of my
judging team. Also there were David E. Davis from Automobile
magazine and automotive designer Peter Brock.
</P>
<P>
   I also was the only woman in the room, except for honorary
Chairman Carroll Shelby's wife, Cleo. Nope, no pressure here.
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that they gave me a book on how to judge a
car. There are four basic categories: exterior, interior, engine
compartment and presence. The first three are self-explanatory. The
fourth is a polite way of saying ``How much do you like this car?''
There are a couple of options for tie-breakers.
</P>
<P>
   Each car begins with a perfect score in each category, and you
deduct points at your own determined rate for ``flaws.'' As I
progressed down the line of 32 cars we had to judge, I quickly
found I needed to do continual adjustments because each one seemed
to look better than the last.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness for the ``presence'' category. It covered a
multitude of sins.
</P>
<P>
   When we had all arrived at our opinions, we assembled as a group
to compare numbers. To my pleasant surprise, about 95 percent of my
numbers were in line with the rest of the judges'.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow judge Brock Yates quizzed, ``How'd you do?''
</P>
<P>
   My reply, ``This isn't so tough. It's just like going to the
jewelry store and trying to decided which diamond you really don't
care for.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp's column is written exclusively for Cox News
Service. Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
