<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE CIRCULAR FIRING SQUAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Sentence in bold should be set in italics.)  
(DW) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boy, I sure hope the Clinton team loses this war in Kosovo,
because if it wins, there will be no one to pick up the Nobel Peace
Prize. If I read The Washington Post, New York Times and Wall
Street Journal correctly, everyone in this administration already
has blamed everyone else in this administration for failure in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the front pages, one finds that the Joint Chiefs blame
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright for dragging them into a
morass. The State Department blames the Pentagon and the NATO
allies, the CIA says it predicted the war would go badly, the vice
president is worried that it's going to sink his election chances,
the Congressional Democrats want to dump the whole Clinton foreign
policy team for failing to anticipate Serbian behavior, and the
Republicans don't know what they want but they all agree it's Bill
Clinton's fault.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about turbo finger-pointing. You don't even have to leave
this administration and write your memoirs to betray it _ now you
can do it on the job. If the Clinton team were half as good at
targeting the Serbian tanks in Kosovo as it is at targeting its own
members in the press, we would have won this war already.
 &UR; Yo, boys and girls, can we do this later?  &LR;  If this war goes badly,
you're all sunk, and we're all sunk. You have to hang together,
both in appearance and reality, because in this information age,
everyone is watching _ most importantly our allies and Slobodan
Milosevic. If the allies see everyone on the Clinton team blaming
everyone else, how long do you think NATO will stick behind
America?
</P>
<P>
   How is one supposed to conduct a long-term campaign in such an
environment? I guess one should not be surprised. It is scary how
we have seamlessly moved from O.J. to Monica to Kosovo, and treat
each one as just another partisan spectacle. CNN has shamelessly,
and shamefully, aired a steady stream of interviews with every
relative of the three captured U.S. GI's _ as if their fate were
the central issue of the day, as if they were not soldiers sent to
fight but high schoolers abducted while on a picnic in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   This is war, not infotainment. We're not up against JonBenet
Milosevic. We're up against a ruthless dictator who has made
500,000 people homeless. It is going to require ruthless, brutal
staying power to succeed here. Maybe the air war will not be enough
to pressure the Serbs into accepting the minimum diplomatic outcome
we need _ which is that the refugees be allowed to return to their
homes in Kosovo, and run their own lives, protected by
international peacekeepers. But two weeks of bombing is far too
early to determine that.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a perfect analogy, but I was in West Beirut during
the summer of 1982 when the Israeli Army decided not to enter that
city with ground troops to evict the PLO but to rely instead on
air, sea and artillery bombardments. For the first two months there
was solidarity between the Beirut Muslims and the PLO, in the face
of the Israeli siege. But as the summer wore on, as the economy
ground to a halt, the Muslim leadership in West Beirut finally
called Yasser Arafat and said, in effect: ``Yasser, we can't take
this anymore. We said we'd be with you `till the last dog dies.'
Well, it just died. It's time for you to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratislav Grubacic, one of the most prominent Serbian
journalists, puts out a daily Internet news report from Belgrade,
Yugoslavia. Here's an excerpt from Tuesday, April 6: ``The prospect
of a prolonged bombing campaign is making people depressed and
nervous. However, even if the air strikes stop soon, the reasonable
part of the population fears that living in a devastated and
isolated country without fresh money and help from abroad will be
like living in a concentration camp.''
</P>
<P>
   If the United States wants to return the Albanian refugees to
Kosovo _ without using ground troops _ NATO is going to have to
intensify both its diplomacy and its bombing of Serbia, with no
holds barred.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, to emerge with an acceptable outcome, the Clinton
team is going to have to steel itself for accusations of engaging
in both military ``overkill'' and diplomatic ``appeasement.''
</P>
<P>
   Managing such a tense endgame will require a cool head and a
tight-knit team with a mean streak and steady nerves _ not a group
marching forward while looking over their shoulders at each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
