<SLUG> BC-VIRUS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pig-borne virus is a killer that baffles experts
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An outbreak of a deadly virus among Malaysian
residents who raise, handle and transport pigs is stumping health
experts who say it does not resemble any known virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen this virus before. But that doesn't mean it
hasn't been there all along,'' said Dr. Pierre Rollin, a virologist
with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, which has sent
eight specialists to Malaysia to investigate. ``It's probably been
there all along waiting for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Of 229 suspected cases reported in Malaysia and Singapore, 111
people have died; 100 in Malaysia and 11 people who handled the
imported pigs in Singapore, the CDC reported Thursday. Most are
adult men who have had close contact with pigs or pig farming, a
mainstay of the country's many rural villages.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts said they believe the virus is not spread from
person to person, but from pigs to humans. ``It starts out with
nonspecific symptoms like the flu but quickly develops into
neurological symptoms,'' Rollin said. ``It's a rapid onset. Within
two to three days, a person can go into a coma and require
respiratory assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The virus first sickened and killed hundreds of pigs in October,
then spread to workers, killing 15 of them, CDC officials said.
Malaysian health officials initially said the deaths were caused by
the Japanese encephalitis virus, which is transmitted by
mosquitoes. But in late February, villagers and farmers in the
hog-rearing district of Bukit Pelandok in the central Negeri
Sembilan state began dying at an alarming rate, prompting health
officials to seek further help.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lam Sai Kit, from the University of Malaysia's department of
medical microbiology, discovered adults and pigs were succumbing to
the disease. Japanese encephalitis usually affects children.
</P>
<P>
   Despite intense aerial fogging of the hog farms, about 70 people
died within a month, including pig farmers who received
encephalitis vaccines. Lam suspected another virus at work.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysian virologists flew to the United States on March 17 with
samples. Lab analyses quickly proved the virus wasn't encephalitis.
Instead, it resembled a rare Hendra virus, first detected in
Australia in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms are the same for both viruses _ high fever, aches,
eventual coma and death.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC finding plunged Malaysia into further confusion. Pig
farmers deserted their homes after police cordoned off their
villages. To curb the outbreak, soldiers dressed like astronauts
swept through a half-dozen pig-farming districts in an attempt to
slaughter a targeted 1 million pigs.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
