<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1184 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RELIEF-NYT     04-08 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RELIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES WILL BE KEPT IN ALBANIA, NOT CUBA, SAYS ADMINISTRATION
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-VIETNAM,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE, KOSOVO-CHILDREN,
KOSOVO-MILITARY.) 
(ac) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bowing to pressure from refugee groups and aid
organizations, the Clinton administration has suspended plans for
an airlift of Kosovo refugees from Macedonia to the U.S. naval base
at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba. Instead the United States will build
refugee barracks for them in Albania, according to administration
officials.
</P>
<P>
   While emphasizing that the United States will retain the option
of flying up to 20,000 refugees from Macedonia to the base in Cuba,
a top Clinton administration official said that ``we don't have a
first flight planned'' to the base.
</P>
<P>
   The airlift option grew out of the Macedonian government's
urgent request last week to NATO to assume responsibility for more
than 100,000 Albanian refugees, saying that Macedonia's delicate
ethnic balance would be destroyed by these newcomers. NATO's
response was to offer to airlift them out. Most NATO nations then
offered to accept certain numbers for temporary or permanent
asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The Macedonian government took matters into its own hands on
Tuesday, swiftly deporting an estimated 45,000 refugees, about
9,500 of them to Albania, in an overnight operation conducted
without informing refugee workers. Many refugees reportedly were
removed against their will and were not told their destinations,
and hundreds of families were separated in the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian government had repeatedly volunteered to take in
refugees as long as Western countries agree to house them and
provide supplies for them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the chief opponents to the Guantanamo idea was the office
of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, which argued
against the base ``with its flavor of a detention camp'' but also
against the legal restrictions the United States would place on the
refugees once they arrived in camps, refusing to give them any
right of asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea of moving the refugees out of asylum near their
homes is bad, moving out of the region is worse and Guantanomo is
the worst of all,'' said Karen Abu Zayd, the UNHCR representative
here.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. airlift of refugees could also cause a logistical
nightmare in the middle of the airwar campaign. But a Pentagon
official said, ``We're making preparations to receive the first
several hundred refugees at the base if we get to that stage.'' He
added, ``But if the refugees would prefer to go to Albania rather
than Guantanamo, I think we will fill up Albania first.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States joined nearly a dozen other countries in
offering to accept refugees when Macedonia asked for immediate
help, a gesture all the relief agencies applauded, even though they
opposed the selection of Guantanamo. But two days ago a group of
American refugee organizations wrote to President Clinton opposing
the Guantanamo base. They said ``the inhospitable, isolated,
prison-like environment is inappropriate and would exacerbate the
trauma and suffering they have already experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   While saying that the president understood these concerns, an
administration official who asked not to be named said that the
changing situation on the ground and the desire of the refugees to
remain close to their homes was the reason the Guantanamo airlift
had been put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be a voluntary decision by the refugees and if
they do not want to go that far we will accommodate them,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo have wanted to
stay as close to home as possible in the hope of returning, if only
to learn what happened to other family members. Many men did not
accompany their families, either because they wanted to stay and
fight or because they were held back by the Serbs. Many are
presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   But refugees are accepting some offers of asylum. Thursday,
German planes flew out 1,000 refugees who voluntarily agreed to
leave Macedonia for Germany. Others were flown to Norway and
Iceland.
</P>
<P>
   According to the UNHCR, Albania is now housing 303,000 refugees,
Macedonia has 117,000, and Montenegro 59,000.
</P>
<P>
   By volunteering to take in thousands of additional refugees,
Albania, one of the poorest nations in Europe, would benefit from a
big public works program that would provide roads and sanitation as
well as housing.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official estimated that the United States was
prepared to spend $1 million a day to house 20,000 refugees in
Guantanamo for at least six months, or $180 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That money would go a long way to rebuilding Albania and at
the same time give the refugees the homes they want,'' said the
official who favored the Albanian option over Guantanamo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased that they're not rushing forward with
Guantanamo and that the priority is now clearly preserving
protection for the refugees in the region and getting supplies into
the region,'' said Bill Frelick, senior policy analyst for the U.S.
Committee for Refugees who attended the meeting. ``The logistics
required, spending the time and resources to evacuate these people
half way across the globe at the height of the refugee crisis would
be an absolute mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Atwood, the administration's coordinator for the Kosovo
relief effort, said in a telephone conference call with reporters
Thursday that the administration was reconsidering Tuesday's
decision to use the Guantanamo base for temporary asylum because
living conditions in the camps in Albania and Macedonia are
beginning to improve and because the Serbs have temporarily closed
the border, preventing more Albanians from fleeing their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep people in the region,'' Atwood said. ``We want
to prepare the people to return to their homes. It will be a lot
easier to undertake that if they are in the region.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
