<HEADER>
A1186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUSTOMS09-COX     04-08 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOMS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New panel to probe claims of customs bias
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Customs Service created a special
commission Thursday to investigate allegations that black
passengers are being unfairly targeted for drug inspections because
of their color.
</P>
<P>
   ``If bias exists, whether perceived or real, it is paramount
that we find its cause and eliminate it,'' said Commissioner
Raymond Kelly. ``Bias is not a part of customs policy. We cannot
afford it to be part of our practice.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kelly is not the only chief of a federal law enforcement
agency concerned about officers singling out potential suspects
because of the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said her department is investigating
whether police officers are using racial profiling in traffic stops
and other questioning of citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so very important that we address the feelings of
Americans who feel that police officers are stopping them because
of race,'' Reno said on Thursday. ``Let's address it, let's hit it
head-on.''
</P>
<P>
   If police officers deny that they are using racial profiling,
stand behind them, said Reno, adding, ``but stand behind them with
hard facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cities are already gathering those facts, said Reno, citing
San Diego as an example. In San Diego, police officers are
recording the race of everyone they stop in an effort to compile a
statistical picture of whether or not there is an ``inappropriate
reliance on a racial profile,'' Reno said. She called on other
police departments to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is investigating allegations of racial
profiling by the New Jersey State Police in traffic stops and by
police agencies in Eastpointe, Mich., and Orange County, Fla. The
department provides racial sensitivity training to local police
elsewhere, Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the four-person customs commission comes less
than two weeks after Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) requested that
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin conduct a federal investigation
into whether blacks were being unjustly singled out for inspections
at Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis requested the investigation after customs inspectors told
reporters that the unwritten rule at Hartsfield is ``to go after
blacks.'' Lewis said he was moved to act after WAGA-TV news
reported that 90 percent of the individuals sent to hospitals to be
X-rayed for drugs were African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good first step,'' said Lewis, appearing at press
conference with Kelly to announce creation of the commission.
``Something is happening out there, and we have to address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield is not the only airport where allegations of racial
bias have been raised.
</P>
<P>
   At Chicago's O'Hare International Airport, 100 black women have
come forward alleging in a lawsuit that they were unfairly singled
out for inspections because of their race and gender.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the complaints about discrimination, the number of
people actually searched at customs is relatively small when
compared with the total number of passengers passing through the
nation's airports.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, customs inspectors searched 50,892 of some 71.5
million passengers. Drugs were found in 2,116 of those searches,
which were conducted by frisking, patdowns, partial strips or
X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   Constance Berry Newman, undersecretary of the Smithsonian
Institution, will chair the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Also named to the commission were Robin Renee Sanders, the
National Security Council's director for Africa, and Ana Marie
Salazar, deputy assistant secretary of defense for drug enforcement
policy and support.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sanders, who is black, and Salazar, who is Hispanic, said
they have had personal experiences with customs officials during
border crossings. A fourth person will be named at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
