<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-09-COX     04-08 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO INTENSIFIES ATTACKS AS TALKS ARE SET ON THREE CAPTIVE
AMERICANS
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 750
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON U.S. and allied pilots pressed a withering,
around-the-clock air campaign directly on Yugoslav troops and
police early Friday, targeting forces on the ground, tanks on the
road and heavy artillery in the field.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he was hopeful that a Cypriot statesman
would be able to secure the release of three captured American
soldiers during talks in Belgrade scheduled for Friday. The
Pentagon insisted, however, that it would not barter away NATO air
strikes in exchange for the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Explosions rocked the suburbs of Belgrade early Friday, in the
17th straight day of NATO bombing. The state-run Tanjug news agency
reported separate strikes on a fuel depot in the town of Smederevo,
to the south, and explosions also in the southern industrial city
of Kragujevac.
</P>
<P>
   The first four U.S. tanks were flown into Albania to support 24
Apache attack helicopters and 18 battlefield missile launchers. The
Apaches, expected to begin arriving in Albania late next week, are
fast and low-flying gunships that would add an aggressive new
element to NATO's efforts to strike Yugoslav troops and tanks in
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Escalating the image war for public opinion, NATO officials said
they would target state-run television broadcast facilities in
Belgrade unless those outlets agree to air uncensored Western media
reports.
</P>
<P>
   The threat came a day after Serb television reported that NATO
bombs not Serb troops and police had reduced much of the Kosovo
provincial capital of Pristina to an abandoned wasteland of smoke
and ash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serb radio and TV is an instrument of propaganda and
repression. It has filled the airwaves with hate and with lies over
the years, and especially now,'' said NATO air commodore David
Wilby. ``It is therefore a legitimate target in this
</P>
<P>
   campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said NATO would take those stations off its target list if
Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia, would
allow uncensored Western media reports six hours a day split
between afternoon and evening broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Serbian television was used as a proper tool of free
speech, as opposed to a propaganda machine, then it would be
considered, as other media broadcasts, very much acceptable,'' said
Wilby.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic wasn't expected to embrace the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Spyros Kyprianou, speaker of the Cypriot parliament, traveled to
Belgrade aboard a Greek airplane Thursday and was scheduled to meet
Friday with Milosevic to discuss the possible release of three
American soldiers captured last week near Macedonia's border with
the Serb province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be for anything that would honorable that would secure
their release, obviously,'' Clinton said at a White House press
conference with Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   But Pentagon spokesman Capt. Michael Doubleday said NATO would
not halt its air strikes to secure the soldiers's release.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is immoral to use them as any kind of bargaining chips,''
Doubleday said, ``and we are certainly not going to negotiate in
any way for their release.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials showed extensive video and still
photography on Thursday, pointing to mounting success in targeting
Yugoslav troops, police and equipment in the south and west of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two weeks of air strikes focused on fuel depots,
ammo dumps, roads, bridges and command and control facilities,
troops inside Kosovo are showing signs of isolation and depletion,
said Rear Adm. Thomas Wilson, intelligence director for the U.S.
Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're feeling the impact among their deployed forces,'' said
Wilson, citing fuel shortages that appear to be slowing military
operations across Kosovo. He said direct strikes on troops and
tanks have forced some units to disperse and hide their vehicles in
abandoned buildings and beneath foliage.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said repeated attacks on Yugoslavia's two refineries and
more than a dozen large oil storage facilities had destroyed
one-fifth of the country's petroleum stocks. Additional strikes
have targeted oil loading docks and distribution routes, forcing
widespread fuel shortages across the country and limiting the
army's ability to resupply tanks and trucks in the field.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Serbs forced thousands of fleeing refugees to turn
back and march into southwestern Kosovo, Wilby said it still isn't
known where those civilians have gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are obviously very concerned about where those people will
be moved to,'' said Wilby. There were scattered reports that Serbs
have used ethnic Albanians as human shields to try to confound
allied attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have anecdotal rumors and reports of human shields, which
we have not been able to verify,'' said Wilson. ``It is a miserable
tactic for anybody to use in a wartime scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 24 hours from Wednesday night through Thursday, NATO
forces struck two dozen targets across Serbia. Seeking out Serb
forces in broad daylight, a pair of British Harrier jets destroyed
a compound of military vehicles in southwest Kosovo with
armor-piercing cluster bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon showed video footage of laser-guided bombs
destroying a Serb armored personnel carrier typically such vehicles
carry a dozen or so troops and crew as it moved along a road in
southwest Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other Pentagon images showed:
</P>
<P>
   A Maverick missile destroying a bridge in Kosovo after being
fired by an A-10 Thunderbolt jet flying under heavy anti-aircraft
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Another A-10 attack on a convoy aborted under heavy
anti-aircraft fire.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction of the Raska bridge, a large highway bridge five
miles north of Kosovo, by F-15 warplanes dropping 2,000 pound
laser-guided bombs.
</P>
<P>
   An attack with similar bombs dropped by F-16s on an ammunition
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting on activities over the past several days, Wilson also
said NATO forces had tracked down and bombed a group of combat
vehicles and forces at a rendezvous point at Istok, ten miles north
of Pec in western Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A similar attack south of Pec, near Decani, killed troops and
destroyed tanks, trucks, anti-aircraft guns and heavy artillery
that Serbs had used to shell nearby cities as part of a wider
campaign of terror targeting ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The allies also reported hitting a convoy of troops either Serb
army or special police near the city of Djakovica, scene of some of
the most intensive anti-Albanian repression.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Air Force Gen. Charles Wald, vice director of strategic
plans and policy for the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said strikes
against fielded forces would continue to intensify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are flying day and night missions. And some of the day
packages are what we would consider large packages,'' said Wald,
referring to the grouping of several types of combat aircraft and
protective craft assigned to a specific mission. ``I would tell
Milosevic that ``If you don't understand we're committed by now,
you probably ought to start reading tea leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
