<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-08 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERN MOUNTS OVER YUGOSLAVIA'S HANDLING OF REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Concerns grew within the NATO alliance Thursday
that Yugoslavia was halting the exodus of Kosovo Albanian refugees
for a second day both to turn them into human shields and to
complicate NATO's intense bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials said the refugees were returning voluntarily
from the border with Macedonia, and US officials admitted they had
no hard evidence that the hunkered-down Serbian forces in Kosovo
were hiding behind civilians. Still, US officials described the
border closing possibly as part of an ``evil design'' by
Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic to force refugees home and
into harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to try to ascertain what the evil design
is of this terrible business,'' said State Department spokesman
James P. Rubin. ``Clearly, by closing the border and trying to send
people back, he is not allowing the Kosovar Albanians out of
Kosovar.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO bombed targets in the suburbs of Belgrade Thursday
night, Air Marshal Sir John Day said at a British military briefing
that NATO forces would ``take every precaution'' to avoid bombing
targets inside Kosovo where refugees might be. ``At the end of the
day, the responsibility is Milosevic's,'' Day said.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   --Kosovar refugees will not arrive at a US naval base in Cuba
until next week at the earliest, and US officials suggested few
Kosovars may ever volunteer to relocate there.
</P>
<P>
   --US and UN relief officials said they believed most of the more
than 40,000 Kosovar refugees who vanished overnight Wednesday from
a rough camp on the Kosovo-Macedonia border had been accounted for
in Macedonia, Albania, and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO announced the launch of ``Operation Allied Harbor,'' a
deployment of 8,000 multinational troops to Albania by the end of
next week to provide humanitarian relief to the 300,000 refugees in
11 camps.
</P>
<P>
   --President Clinton, asked by reporters if he believed NATO's
campaign against Yugoslavia would succeed without the use of ground
troops, said: ``I believe our present strategy will work if we can
keep the allies with it.'' New polls show increased US support for
troop deployment.
</P>
<P>
   --European Union foreign ministers, meeting in Luxembourg, gave
strong support Thursday to NATO airstrikes and said Serb leaders
they blamed for atrocities in Kosovo should be brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, expectations for a quick release of the three US
soldiers held by the Yugoslavs since March 31 fell Thursday when a
meeting between a Cypriot diplomat and Milosveic was delayed until
Friday. Spyros Kyprianou, acting president of Cyprus, arrived in
Belgrade Thursday after NATO arranged for the safe passage of his
aircraft into Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kyprianou said the Americans might be freed during the long
Orthodox Easter weekend that starts Friday, and he suggested NATO
could then ``reciprocate by responding to the numerous
international appeals for a cease-fire.'' But the hardline Serbian
vice premier, Vojislav Seselj, told reporters that would be
unnecessary since freeing the three was ``out of the question,''
and that the soldiers should be tried as terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he hoped Kyprianou's mission would
succeed. ``We would like to see the servicemen released because
they never should have been detained in the first place,'' Clinton
said. ``And I would be for anything honorable that would secure
their release, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials insisted Thursday they would not negotiate with the
Serb-led government of Yugoslavia or halt the NATO bombing campaign
to free the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, NATO's air campaign against targets in Belgrade and
Kosovo continued in mostly good weather and with great intensity.
NATO officials in Brussels said its planes flew 400 sorties
Wednesday night, with US Navy fighters from the USS Roosevelt
aircraft carrier in the Adriatic Sea joining the campaign for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with films and detailed explanations of what they said
were NATO hits on Serb targets in Belgrade and Kosovo, spokesmen at
NATO headquarters in Brussels and at the Pentagon said the bombing
campaign was inflicting heavy damange on Serb military
installations and degrading their capacity to make war and
terrorize civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our operations are ongoing with even greater success against
fielded forces,'' said Air Commodore David Wilby of the British
Royal Air Force, a spokesman for NATO. ``Our operational tempo and
effectiveness continues to increase. I believe that our momentum is
building with encouraging pace.''
</P>
<P>
   The alliance spokesmen denied Serb charges that its bombing in
the Kosovo capital of Pristina was the cause of widespread
destruction and 10 deaths. They accused the Serbs of destroying
civilian buildings and homes themselves to make it appear that NATO
had bombed the sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't rule out that some of the damage _ two nights ago, we
attacked the telephone exchange (in Pristina) _ was not done by air
attack,'' said Rear Admiral Thomas Wilson, director of intelligence
for the Joint Chiefs of Staff. ``But the rest of the damage being
shown in Pristina was done by the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that NATO's policy is to ``do all it can to avoid
collateral damage,'' but officials were clearly concerned that the
return of the refugees from the closed border could put them in
danger of NATO airstrikes, even if they could not prove Serb intent
to make them human shields.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a continuing humanitarian concern about the fate
and well-being of the 10,000 ethnic Albanians who had been turned
back at the border on Wednesday. Some had been separated from
families who had made it into Macedonia; many were without food,
water, or warm clothing, refugee workers said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandako Ogata, the UN's High Commissioner for Refugees, arrived
in Albania Thursday to assess the ``enormous task'' and figure out
what had happened to the Kosovars who had been denied passage at
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what happened to them, and I'm very very
worried,'' Ogata said. ``I hope it was not stopped by force. But
right now, I really have no information.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Brian Atwood, the US coordinator of refugee relief, said
conditions are becoming critical in Kukes, an Albanian town where
many of the 140,000 Kosovar refugees are suffering from trauma and
increasing medical problems, including respiratory ailments and
diarrhea. The food needs there alone, he said, are 125 tons a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never seen a group of refugees so traumatized by what
they have been through,'' said Atwood, who is administrator of the
US Agency for International Development. ``What do you do for a
9-year-old child who watched three of his brothers be executed and
his house be lit on fire with his 2-year-old sister inside?''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said because the refugee flow is slowing, more camps are
being set up in Albania and Macedonia, and the ethnic Albanians
don't want to leave the region, using the US naval base at
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, may be unnecessary, at least in the short
term.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said he and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton would
travel to Dover Air Force Base in Delaware Friday to meet with the
crew members helping coordinate an airlift of relief supplies. Mrs.
Clinton is also going to be featured in an administration
advertising campaign to encourage Americans to donate to the
Kosovar relief, Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
