<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-SAFETY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGHER RULES FOR FISHING INDUSTRY URGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A new Coast Guard report urges that a series of tough
rules _ from boat inspections to crew licensing _ be imposed on the
dangerous and largely unregulated world of commercial fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has gone down this road before. Agencies
from the National Transportation Safety Board to the National
Research Council have made many of the same recommendations in the
past 10 years, only to have an industry opposed to regulation
defeat them.
</P>
<P>
   What also hasn't changed is that commercial fishing is a
dangerous pursuit, according to the report, ``Dying to Fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen are 16 times more likely to die on the job than
firefighters or police officers, the report noted, and eight times
more likely to die on the job than truck drivers and others who
operate motor vehicles for a living.
</P>
<P>
   A fishing safety law passed by Congress in 1988 has cut deaths
by 20 percent, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, where much of Washington state's fleet works, deaths
have fallen from about 36 a year to 18, according to the Coast
Guard in Juneau. Thirteen lives and 32 vessels were lost last year.
</P>
<P>
   The number of vessels lost in Alaska has not changed much.
</P>
<P>
   The 1988 law, by requiring emergency equipment such as survival
suits and life rafts and the ability to use them, largely focused
on how to survive accidents, not how to prevent them.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard, for example, has a voluntary program to inspect
fishing boats. But fewer than half the nation's boats participate
in the program, and the inspections themselves focus on safety
equipment, said Coast Guard Cmdr. Mark Prescott, vice chairman of
the task force that released the report this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't tell a guy, `Hey, the hull looks like it's in poor
condition,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It would be like requiring flight crews to carry parachutes but
not requiring them to prove their competence to fly or that their
planes are airworthy, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to use Prescott's own analogy, if people keep falling off a
cliff, ``you park an ambulance at the bottom instead of building a
fence at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force of Coast Guard officers and representatives of
other government agencies was formed in January after a series of
fishing boat accidents off the New Jersey coast. From late December
to mid-January, four boats sank in the mid-Atlantic, and 11 people
died.
</P>
<P>
   The sinkings sparked an interest in fishing vessel safety all
the way to Secretary of Transportation Rodney Slater, Prescott
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also has received special emphasis from an assistant
commandant of the Coast Guard, Rear Adm. Robert North. He has
ordered an industry group that advises the Coast Guard on fishing
safety to meet next week in Washington, D.C., to consider the 50
recommendations the task force made.
</P>
<P>
   Some, including mandatory boat inspections, would require the
authorization of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard could adopt other recommendations simply by
adopting new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations would have the biggest effect on operators
of smaller fishing vessels. Skippers of large boats, for example,
already must have licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be overly optimistic if I thought fishermen would welcome
more regulation,'' Prescott said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he said the fishing industry might be receptive to
equitable regulations that are ``not creating a standard someone
already in the business can't meet.''
</P>
<P>
   The fishing industry probably isn't going to be receptive to a
long list of new regulations, said Jim Herbert, a fisherman and
technical college instructor from Seward, Alaska, who heads the
fishing industry group that advises the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's business as usual,'' Herbert said. ``But then the oil
industry never requested double-hulled tankers, and the auto
industry never requested seat belts.''
</P>
<P>
   The climate may have changed enough, he said, that the industry
may be willing to accept some of the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the task force's recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   -Require safety inspections of fishing boats and ensure that the
inspections are a prerequisite for fishing permits and vessel
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   -Make operators of fishing boats have a license, apply drug and
alcohol testing to crews, and require crew members to hold a
competency certificate.
</P>
<P>
   -Require larger boats to meet stability requirements, make sure
boats have emergency lighting and smoke detectors in interior
spaces and force crew members to wear personal flotation devices in
some locations on deck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
