<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FAMILY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAMILY GUY' IS CLEVER, FUNNY - AND INSULTING 
</HEADLINE>
 GUY-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Husband and wife are in bed. Wife suggests hanky-panky. Clueless
husband misses the signals. It's as much a comedy cliche as the
single parent.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Family Guy,'' which targets everything we love and loathe
about TV, it is still a cliche. But when served with a twist of
sublime, cliches are so much easier to swallow. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   Lois Griffin says to her husband: ``You should spend some time
with our kids, Peter. And with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Griffin replies: ``Whoa. What could me and you do
together?''
</P>
<P>
   Lois laughs coquettishly, bats her eyelashes.
</P>
<P>
   Peter recoils: ``Lois, you've got a sick mind!''
</P>
<P>
   Lois continues: ``Peter, I'm talking about making love.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter, relieved, says: ``Oh, I thought you wanted us to murder
the children and harvest their organs for beer money!''
</P>
<P>
   In politically correct precincts, ``Family Guy'' will offend. In
places where subversive humor is embraced and cherished, it will be
hailed for what it is: a wry observation of behavior that is not
becoming, yet becoming more prevalent in a polarized society. The
funniest character is a 1-year-old baby named Stewie, whose goal is
world domination and the elimination of anyone who stands in his
way, parents included. Stewie has two older siblings, ages 13 and
16, and there's a family dog who puts on airs and drinks too much.
</P>
<P>
   It's all raucous nonsense, but the debate will rage as to
whether ``Family Guy'' contributes to, or merely reflects, the
demise of civility. As with most TV fare, it's doing a little of
both, and it's doing it with a sharp eye for detail.
</P>
<P>
   After a post-Super Bowl presentation in January and a
rebroadcast Tuesday night, ``Family Guy'' settles into its regular
slot at 8:30 p.m. Sunday with a riotously irreverent,
laugh-out-loud episode.
</P>
<P>
   Series creator Seth MacFarlane mined his New England origins to
create the Griffin family and the clammy enclave of Quahog, R.I.,
where life is amazingly derivative. Shoot, the baseline of ``Family
Guy'' is so similar to ``The Simpsons'' that it's amazing Fox put
it on at all.
</P>
<P>
   But not all imitations have to be pale ones. Grounded a bit more
in reality, ``Family Guy'' is clever,
</P>
<P>
   funny, insulting to just about every interest group imaginable _
and far from a carbon copy.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the principal character is a plain-speaking oaf of
white-bread America, quick with an impolitic comment or an
offensive barb. But Peter Griffin actually understands that he has
family obligations, where Homer Simpson understands nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Peter even tries to get the family to stop watching so much TV
by planning other activities. The family goes along for a while,
but soon returns to the blandishments of the tube, causing Peter to
say, ``But I thought we were having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Daughter Meg, supine in front of the television, replies: ``We
were, but now it might be nice to watch other people have fun. Or
get killed. You know, whatever's on.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Seth MacFarlane is hoping to connect with just that
sort of discriminating audience.
</P>
<P>
   Family Guy. Half-hour animated comedy series about a family of
five (plus dog) living in the suburbs. Voices by Seth MacFarlane,
Alex Borstein and Seth Green. Premieres in its regular time slot
Sunday on Fox. Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
