<SLUG> BC-BEIJING-TRIAL-DELAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER U.S. REQUEST, BEIJING DELAYS TRIAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese officials have postponed the trial of a
democracy advocate, which was scheduled to start this week, after
the U.S. Embassy here urged them to drop or postpone the case.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Beijing courts said the trial of the advocate, Fang
Jue, on charges of fraud and illegal business activities would
begin on Tuesday. That was the day set for the start of Prime
Minister Zhu Rongji's official visit to the United States, which is
intended to patch up growing conflicts over human rights, trade,
missile defenses and charges of Chinese nuclear espionage.
</P>
<P>
   On learning of the trial date, the U.S. Embassy urged China to
release Fang and drop the charges, an embassy official said. ``If
they couldn't do that, we noted that the timing was very
inauspicious,'' said the official. If a trial does occur, the
embassy told the Chinese, it would like to observe the proceedings
firsthand, something that has never been permitted in a political
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Fang, 44, was formerly a government planner in the southern
province of Fujian but broke off to start his own trading company.
He had never been openly involved in dissident activities, but in
early 1998 he distributed to foreign journalists a manifesto
calling for democratic government, negotiations on autonomy for
Tibet and other changes. He said the document reflected
conversations among many younger government and Communist Party
officials, though he refused to name any.
</P>
<P>
   Exiled dissidents in New York championed his report, and he was
detained last July. Eight months later he was told of the charges
against him, relating to alleged acceptance of company payments
while he was still an official in 1995. He has denied the charges
and his sister says they were fabricated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
