u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GARCIAPARRA-BOS &LR;      04-08 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA DAY-TO-DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Nomar Garciaparra, who had been vague about
his elbow this spring, made no attempt to downplay how his left
hamstring felt Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts quite a bit,'' said Garciaparra, who strained the
muscle high in his left leg in the ninth inning of Wednesday
night's 6-0 win over the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who was on first base after a fielder's choice,
scored on Mike Stanley's two-run double, but on his way from third
to home felt the muscle grab. He remained on his back for a few
moments after sliding across the plate, then got up and gingerly
made his way back to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   He said that night he hoped it would feel better by the time he
came to the park Thursday afternoon, but that wasn't the case. He
was scratched from Thursday night's game here against the Royals,
is unlikely to play this weekend against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
on the artificial surface of Tropicana Field, and ackonwledged the
possibility he'll have to go on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no bruising or blood, which is good,'' he said.
``It's one of those things you have to take day by day to see
exactly how it feels. Hopefully, it won't be too long...I don't
know whether that (placing him on the DL) is going on, but until we
know how it is, we're going to have look at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams, who used Donnie Sadler in Garciaparra's
place, said that for now, he's considering Garciaparra's
availability on a day-to-day basis. But Williams usually prefers to
err on the side of caution, especially with an injury like a
hamstring, which can be easily aggravated.
</P>
<P>
   Just the fact Garciaparra allowed for the possibility he'd have
to go on the DL is a measure of how much it hurts him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give you any timetable,'' Garciaparra said. ``I
definitely know I did something with it, and we'll just go from
there. A hammy's something you've gotta really watch. It can feel
good some time, and you think it's OK, then it gets you
again...What I might not be able to do today I might be able to do
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra sounded like he'd just as soon not take any chances
on the artficial surface in St. Petersburg this weekend. ``You've
got to watch that, too,'' he said. ``It's a factor. It's different
playing on turf than other surfaces.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra said he has not had problems with his hamstrings. In
1996, while playing for Pawtucket, Garciaparra tore a tendon behind
his left knee and was out for nearly three months. Technically,
that was a hamstring muscle as well, but in an entirely different
area from his current problem.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Garciaparra missed 14 games at shortstop after
straining the flexor muscle in his throwing elbow. Concerns that
the tendinitis he was experiencing could flare up again is one
reason the Red Sox kept Sadler on the big-league roster.
</P>
<P>
   And it was in Kansas City last May 9 that Garciaparra separated
his right shoulder diving for an eighth-inning groundball with the
Sox ahead by eight runs. His rookie season, 1997, he missed four
straight games with a sore ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' Garciaparra said of this spring's injury woes.
``Maybe it's just one year to get them all out of the way. I don't
get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
