</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELS SAY THEY CONTINUE TO FIGHT DESPITE BEING HIT HARD BY
YUGOSLAV FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: In the quotation in the 9th graf, the parentheses around
`particular' should be replaced by brackets, which do not transmit
over all wires.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-VIETNAM,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE, KOSOVO-CHILDREN,
KOSOVO-MILITARY.) 
(sw) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army,
who have been waging a war of independence for the Serbian
province, told foreign diplomats Thursday that they have been hit
hard and that Yugoslav forces have pushed them into the hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are pretty weak, they have been badly hit and have taken
casualties,'' said one Western diplomat here. ``They are running
out of ammunition and have lost vehicles and headquarters areas. It
will take time for them to re-equip, they are not going to be much
of a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he added, the Kosovar rebel leadership remains coherent,
and has retained command of its troops. It is even sporadically
engaging the Serbs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A rebel commander, a member of the general staff who goes by the
name of Drini, insisted in an interview that ``The KLA is a good
force. In the last two weeks we have only had 16 casualties from
all units, so it means we are not destroyed or even hurt.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the Yugoslav government announced that peace was
being restored to Kosovo on Thursday, the rebels reported heavy
combat in several areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are reporting heavier fighting today than the last two
days,'' said the diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``There was heavy shelling east of Mitrovica and in the Drenica
region.''
</P>
<P>
   The two areas he named, in northern and central Kosovo
respectively, have been heavily contested throughout the one-year
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yugoslav generals said they would finish off the rebel
force in four days, but they are still there,'' said another
Western military observer who was part of the mission in Kosovo run
by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They remain potentially an effective force,'' he added. ``They
do not threaten the Serbs in the way they did before, they cannot
threaten to break major arteries but they can threaten them in a
(particular) place.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels reported fighting on Thursday in Kachanik, in
southern Kosovo on the main road to Macedonia. The guerrillas
seized part of the town several days ago and appear to be holding
their own. Fighting has flared back and forth, and Serbian MiG
fighters and helicopters attacked Kosovar positions on Thursday,
the rebels reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have gained a lot of territory over recent weeks but
have not tried to hold it, the foreign observers said. They tend to
occupy villages, burn them and then pull out. Often, the villages
are then reoccupied by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav military strategy has been to break up the guerrillas
by surrounding them and pounding them with artillery fire. ``They
try to wear them out in the hope maybe they will give up,'' the
Western diplomat said. ``And then when they are weakened they will
send in the special operations units,'' referring to Yugoslav
commandos who finish off the battle.
</P>
<P>
   That could happen in the next few days. Yet there are signs that
NATO air strikes on Yugoslav armor and bases in Kosovo are
relieving the pressure on the rebel force. Drini, the Kosovar rebel
commander, said NATO planes hit a Serbian armored convoy driving
into northern Kosovo with reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   They also destroyed an armored artillery unit near the village
of Rogovo in southern Kosovo, he said. The previous day, NATO
bombing dealt heavy blows to artillery bases near the town of
Mitrovica in northern Kosovo and south of Klina in the west.
</P>
<P>
   All of the attacks have considerably eased the pressure on the
rebels and reduced the heavy shelling of their positions, the
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA has sounded more relaxed,'' the diplomat said. ``I
could hear in their voices. A couple of days ago I was talking to
someone near Klina, and I could hear the incoming shells exploding.
He held the phone out and said, `You can hear it.' Today he said
`It is quiet, we are sleeping at night.' ''
</P>
<P>
   NATO bombing in Kosovo appears to have taken out artillery bases
and hit a large number of tanks and artillery pieces in Decine, in
western Kosovo, Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian police and army now seem to be moving their forces
constantly, and transferring some forces northwards, allowing the
Kosovars more room, Drini said. He said the rebels were filtering
back into territory previously lost.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the rebels have ordered a general mobilization
and are actively recruiting fighters in Albania. Their force is
estimated at some 8,000 to 10,000 men and morale appears to be
good.
</P>
<P>
   Drini railed at reports likening the Kosovar rebels to the
Taliban, the militant Islamic fundamentalist movement in
Afghanistan, or to Communist guerrillas. ``We are just fighting for
a decent life, we just want peace. It is just a question of
survival. We have nothing to lose,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
