<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS STAYS COOL, DESPITE TRIPLE BOGEY ON EIGHTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Tiger Woods was smiling. He had committed the one
faux pas on a golf course that he had promised himself he would
never commit again. But he was relaxed. He had scored a triple
bogey on the so-easy-for-him eighth hole, a very birdieable par-5.
</P>
<P>
   Woods seemingly couldn't have been more pleased. He had been
forced to draw that snowman on his scorecard _ that big, fat ``8''
_ but he hadn't fallen apart. He hadn't become unglued. He hadn't
lost his patience. He had come back. He had settled down. He had
responded as only the best respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in good shape,'' Woods said of his even-par round of 72
that ordinarily might not be satisfactory. ``I'm even par, right
where you want to be. I'm very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   And well he should be.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was 1 under and in control of his tempo and game when he
badly hooked his tee shot at the eighth, his ball landing in the
woods that separate the eighth and second fairways. ``The blunder
came on the tee shot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the pine cones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to try and hit a 6-iron between two trees,'' Woods said,
``but I had some pine cones right against my ball which I couldn't
move. I tried to play it through the trees but I just caught one
tree and the ball flew into the flowers (actually a bush) between
No. 8 and No. 2. I had to take an unplayable lie and I had to take
it back to the (previous) spot. But this time there were no pine
cones.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods finally got out of the woods, but then flew the green and
could not get up and down. He had his snowman, that triple bogey
Woods had said time and again this week the new-and-consistent
Tiger Woods would avoid at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, when I would be 2 over, I would try and be
aggressive right away,'' Woods said of the defining moment of his
round. ``Now I say to myself, `Be patient. I have a lot of holes
left. I have 64 holes left.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So Woods waited his turn and at Amen Corner he played his wedge
on the 155-yard 12th hole to 8 feet and made birdie. Then, on the
par-5 13th, a 3-wood and 6-iron put him on the green and he
two-putted from 30 feet for birdie. On 14, he carded his third
consecutive birdie, this one from 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   So even though he would give a stroke back on the 17th, when he
flew the green, Woods was happy. Two years ago, he overwhelmed
Augusta National, but that happens perhaps once in a lifetime
because Augusta is too canny and cunning. The patient must outwit
this course; the impatient are devoured.
</P>
<P>
   ``My patience definitely was rewarded,'' said Woods. ``You've
just got to hang in there and stay patient and understand that
you're going to get some mistakes and you're going to have some bad
bounces. Especially here. You're going to hit some good shots that
end up in bad places.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods had hit a bad shot into a bad place and hadn't fallen
to pieces. Seldom has a 72 been so pleasing. Smiles abounded. Woods
just may be on his way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
