<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLDRAFT-DEFENSIVEENDS09-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long reach increases ends' odds
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Because outside pass rushers are so difficult to find,
NFL personnel directors reach for prospects every year, hoping they
mature into players who can knock down quarterbacks regularly.
</P>
<P>
   For this year's draft, however, their arms had to be extra long.
</P>
<P>
   The talent scouts had to reach all the way to the savannas of
Ghana and the well-manicured lacrosse field in Charlottesville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia end Patrick Kerney, who over the past month has become
the top prospect at the position, originally was recruited as a
lacrosse player. Ebenezer Ekuban of North Carolina, a player with
raw physical skills but little experience, was born in Ghana and
began his Tar Heels career as a tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Both started at end for only two seasons and are examples of the
way the league pursues prospects with ability to rush the passer
from the outside or anchor against the run. It is true this year,
because even the best players at defensive end and tackle come with
deficiencies. ``Probably more than at any other position, you're
betting on the (future), when it comes to defensive linemen,'' San
Diego Chargers general manager Bobby Beathard said. ``It's a
position where people are willing to roll the dice, because demand
is so great and the supply is so thin. Sometimes you hit the
jackpot, and sometimes you shoot snake-eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until Kerney stopped shooting at lacrosse goalies two years
ago did he develop into a solid player. His first two years at
Virginia, Kerney was a nondescript second-line player splitting his
time between the sports. But in 1997-98, he totaled 22 sacks and 31
tackles for losses.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Peach Bowl game, when he took advantage of injured
Georgia tackle Matt Stinchcomb, catapulted him into national
prominence.
</P>
<P>
   His pass-rush skills aside, Kerney still carries plenty of
question marks. At 6 feet 5 5/8, 266, he needs to gain weight, and
he must improve against the run and stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban, an engaging young man whose enthusiasm for the game is
obvious, needs to mature technically. In limited exposure at end,
he had a dozen sacks and 126 tackles. He looks as if he grew up on
a weight machine but still lacks football instincts.
</P>
<P>
   He switched from offense to defense after dropping a sure
touchdown pass against Syracuse in his sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 15 yards behind everyone, and it hit me right in the
hands,'' Ekuban said. ``A week later, the coaches asked if I might
consider going to defense. From the tone in their voices, I knew I
didn't really have a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
