<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SIDE-TIGER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disaster in the woods
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ The tee shot on No. 8 hooked left, and Tiger
Woods jerked his head in disgust. Only he didn't really know how
bad his drive was until he got to his ball, which rested under a
tree and was nestled between two pine cones. Not good.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the line to the fairway was thin between trees. Really
not good. Daring shot-maker that he is, Woods used a 4-foot-wide
stance and tried to blast through the cones and trees. Instead, the
ball hit a tree and bounded about 10 feet behind him and into a
gathering of azaleas between the eighth and second holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unusual situation,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. He could not strike the ball from the flowers, so he
took a one-shot penalty, returned to the cite of the original
second shot and dropped. ``This time there were no pine cones,''
Woods noted.
</P>
<P>
   And so, lying three on the par 5, he blasted out across the
fairway. ``Probably one of the best shots I hit all day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods ended up three-putting and getting a triple-bogey 8,
leaving him at 2 over and sending him to a front-nine 38. ``At
worst, I should have made a double bogey,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He could have lost it right there, been so frustrated over a
good round gone bad that he could not recover. But this wiser
version of Tiger Woods instead called on self-control.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, when I'm 2 over I would try to be aggressive
right away,'' Woods said. ``Now, I say to myself, `Be patient. I
have a lot of holes left.' I'm trying to be more patient now.''
</P>
<P>
   He benefitted from said patience. He parred the first two holes
on the back nine and birdied 12, 13 and 14 en route to a closing
34. He finished at even-par 72, still in the mix _ a major
accomplishment considering the disaster on No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooting even par in a major is always a good way to start,''
he said. ``You have to keep hanging in there and grind it out.
Unfortunately, I hit a couple of loose shots.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited an 2-iron mistake off the tee on No. 2 and a 3 iron
over the green.
</P>
<P>
   After getting to 1 under, Woods pulled a tee shot on 17 into the
left rough. It cost him a shot as he made his only bogey of the
back nine. When he parred the final hole, he accepted the round of
72. Had he scored the birdie expected on No. 8, Woods would be tied
for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   But he knew he had gutted out a day when he did not have his
best stuff and remained within striking distance of the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It was similar to his first round in '97, when he followed a
front-nine 40 with a closing-nine 30. He went on to win that year
with a record 18 under.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just made a couple of mistakes,'' he said. ``I'm playing
really well and just trying to stay patient. I have 64 holes left.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
