<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROPES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This week, players' families are treated like family
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ While Stewart Cink tries to figure out the right
club to hit in the swirling winds on Augusta National's 12th hole,
and just how to slink a putt down one of the wickedly sloping
greens, the really tough decisions in his household this week
belong to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   She decides who gets the Masters badges and she wasn't happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got these eight golden passes,'' she said. ``I don't like
being the one who decides who gets to go. It's hard when friends
want to come, and even family. And we have to pay for the tickets
on top of that, which I don't understand because if it wasn't for
the players, the tournament wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the voice of stress behind this week's clubhouse badge.
Golf's first major places huge pressure on the 96 players here, and
it quickly seeps to their families. This week is like no other they
face all year.
</P>
<P>
   Pros' families usually stay in hotels; here, they rent houses.
Normally, they entertain a few friends and family; here, they are
besieged with well-wishers and long-lost acquaintances. Most weeks,
they leave their kids in the PGA Tour's nursery; here, they must
get used to new care-givers hired by the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   For the families, the Masters is a big green fishbowl. They know
exactly what's at stake, and the anxiety grows as they inch to the
course, like everyone else stuck in Washington Road traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do something good here, it follows you the rest of your
life,'' said Cink, who drove over from Smyrna with her two boys,
ages 5 and 2. ``Usually, I'll just catch Stewart on the back nine,
but here I want to watch every shot. I'll probably be more nervous
than usual, especially if he's doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kathy Perry, the tension started building months ago, when
husband Chris began seeking advice on the course from everyone from
fellow Ohioan Jack Nicklaus to former champ Fuzzy Zoeller. It
increased when she pulled her son out of kindergarten for a week;
she doesn't do that for just any event.
</P>
<P>
   Then Perry arrived on Magnolia Drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of awestruck when we drove in the entrance and saw
all this history,'' she said. ``Because this is so historical, I
don't even know what words to use. There's just a mystique or aura.
I don't know if I could lay my finger on it.''
</P>
<P>
   That atmosphere is exactly what the club's members try to create
for players' families. She and Chris attended a reception for
Masters rookies this week at the Eisenhower Cabin, where the
tournament's special treatment of its players was made even
clearer: If the familes needed anything, the Augusta National
members would take care of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that extra little touch,'' Kathy Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Debbye Watts, meanwhile, is still getting accustomed to the
absence of Jumbo Ozaki posters all over the place. Her husband,
Brian, has played in Japan for six years; this is his first season
in America, and it's a lot easier ordering food in Augusta than in
Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Jenna Elfman lookalike had to find her way around,
and didn't know where the ninth green was when she arrived with son
Jason, almost 2. He darted under a gallery rope and she scrambled
to pull him back as he let out a scream.
</P>
<P>
   That's not something Watts tolerates at any tournament, and she
planned to take him to the new day care. The new arrangement didn't
worry her, as it did other Tour wives. ``I can't imagine anything
at the Masters not being nice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing better for the families than coming here once is
getting the chance to return each year, and that's what Gary
Player's wife, Vivienne, has done for 41 years. This year she broke
that streak because her daughter just gave birth to the couple's
10th grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes right down to it, her son Wayne said, ``Nothing's
more important than family.'' Not even the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
