<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: What's All the Fuss About Internet Sites That Give
Away  Stocks? 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Is there anything fundamentally wrong with fledgling Internet sites
that offer shares of their companies to people who sign up on their
Web sites?
</P>
<P>
   Not really. There doesn't appear to be any tangible downside for
consumers who hold the shares, except that they may never be worth
the paper on which they're printed.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the response to earlier Street Smarts columns on
Internet stock giveaways, some readers are asking: ``Why all the
fuss, if the shares are essentially for free?'' The trouble,
according to critics and federal regulators, is that the practice
smacks of excessive promotion.
</P>
<P>
   And in the once starched-shirt world of investing, promotion is
a dirty word. What's more, with the proliferation of Internet chat
rooms, where sources of information are quite anonymous, the
age-old practice of stock hyping seems to have migrated from the
telephone-filled ``boiler rooms'' of old to today's virtual chat
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that Internet firms that offer stock to site
users are engaging in such activities.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that the SEC wants to make sure that the Net's
worldwide reach at warp speed doesn't breed new problems.
</P>
<P>
   Most Web site stock distributions are usually
``micro-offerings''_ small batches of shares with low valuations _
which most investment pros are leery of in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Such little-known stocks used to rely on word of mouth and tiny
brokerages for marketing. But now the Internet has filled that
void, meaning that micro-cap stock propaganda can reach more people
faster than ever before. And that presents a fertile environment
for fraud and deception.
</P>
<P>
   As mentioned in previous columns, the SEC is clamping down on
Web sites that have not told the SEC that they are issuing stock.
Seems sensible to me. All companies, whether they are widget-makers
or Web sites, need to abide by fundamental securities laws.
</P>
<P>
   And one fundamental tenet of a stock offering is telling the
truth. A glaring problem with the Exit23b Web site, which was
featured in an earlier column, was that one of its e-mails
promoting a stock giveaway made false claims. It stated that Yahoo
once gave away free stock, which is nothing but a bald-faced lie.
That's the kind of stuff that the SEC is trying to snuff out.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Exit23b, which apparently is based in Washington
state, has a Web site under construction that indicates the company
plans to be an electronic commerce operation selling home
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Also, speaking of stock giveaways, some readers have asked about
Ecompare, a comparative shopping Web site, which was offering free
shares. Judging by the message on its Web site, it seems likely
that Ecompare is in the process of trying to meet regulatory
requirements for issuing stock.
</P>
<P>
   `` E-Compare's free stock distribution has been voluntarily
suspended pending clarification of SEC _ Security Exchange
Commission (sic) _ rules on the matter,'' states a posting on its
site. Perhaps a good place to start in making amends with
regulators would be to get the name of the agency right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE'RE NO. 14: &LR;  If NationsBanc Montgomery Securities hopes to
crack the top five bulge-bracket (full-service) investment banks in
the not-so-distant future, which it says it wants to do, the bank
has a tough row to hoe.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco investment banking unit of BankAmerica of
Charlotte, N.C., apparently still needs to improve its status among
its peer group.
</P>
<P>
   Because if you look at the list of 13 underwriters selected by
Goldman Sachs to manage its initial public offering, Montgomery
Securities isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Published by TheStreet.com, the list consists of almost every
major investment house on Wall Street _ including Goldman, which is
acting as its own lead manager. Topping the list are Donaldson
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   As an underwriter, these investment banks will have allotments
of Goldman shares to sell to their best customers during the
initial offering, which is slated for the first week of May.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman plans to sell 69 million shares at about $50 per share,
which would raise about $3.45 billion in what likely will be the
largest IPO of the year. At that price per share, Goldman would be
valued at about $23.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Montgomery wasn't the only Bay Area investment bank
not invited to Goldman's coming-out party. All other regional
banks, such as BancBoston Robertson Stephens and Hambrecht and
Quist, were also left off the list.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAKING CREDIT: &LR;  During Vice President Al Gore's recent
presidential fund-raising swing through Silicon Valley, he made the
usual boilerplate speech at the tony Woodside residence of Janina
Pawloski, founder of E-Loan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore rifled through his well-rehearsed list of talking points,
such as the Clinton-Gore administration's commitment to education
reform, its righteous decision to send troops to Kosovo, and its
recognition of California and technology as a cog in the nation's
fine-tuned economic engine. As expected, each line received its
fair share of polite applause from the sea of dot-com name tags.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until Gore pointed out that the Dow Jones
industrial average soared from 3,000 to 10,000 during the
Clinton-Gore reign that the options-laden crowd began to cheer in
earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market's performance definitely received the biggest
applause of the night,'' noted one fund-raiser attendee.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the administration's original agenda of gay rights,
health care and jobs for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
