u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      04-08 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIM AND GRUESOME TIMES FOR FALDO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ When it was finally done, this grim, gruesome and
horrible round, Nick Faldo emerged from the scorer's tent behind
the 18th green and spotted 15 or so of the media, all but one
English.
</P>
<P>
   No inquisitors this day.
</P>
<P>
   Mourners.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes were averted, as mourners avert their eyes. Voices were
soft, as mourners soften their voices. The tone was sympathetic, as
mourners try so hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   A mere three years ago, Nick Faldo charged past Greg Norman on
the final round here at Augusta National and won his third Masters.
Nick Faldo was atop the golf world. Now, Nick Faldo's golf game is
dead as he has slid down that horrible golf abyss that Australian
Ian Baker-Finch and Britain's Sandy Lyle had slid down in the last
decade, landing at true bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Achh,'' Faldo began in disgust, after one of the mourners had
mumbled something soft to him, hopefully to get the words started.
``I had two bad drives (on) one and two ... then I hit three iron
shots off-line ... for 80.''
</P>
<P>
   That was it. The coroner's self-cause of this latest golf death.
Strange and sporadic explanation, two bad drives to start, three
bad irons somewhere in the middle and then that horrible final
number, ``80.''
</P>
<P>
   The mourners understood. Words didn't have to be spoken. Any
human with two eyes could see that Nick Faldo's golf game had
deconstructed, that Nick Faldo's golf game is in pieces -- little
pieces, at that -- and that this golfer is at rock bottom. Atop the
world three years ago, 167th in the world now ... and still
falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every iron shot was right at it or right over it,''
Faldo went on, his mind seaching for even a jot of confidence.
``You know .. I couldn't ... I just couldn't get up and down when I
needed to or when I had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bits and pieces of thought, just as his game is in those tiny
bits and pieces now. On the course, Faldo is the living, breathing
and, really, terrifying example of an athlete who lets his mind
think too much. There is no confidence. His mind races. There can
be no confidence. His mind races from one magic solution to the
next.
</P>
<P>
   There is none.
</P>
<P>
   On the 17th fairway, Faldo stared at his approach shot some 145
yards from the green for the longest of times. Finally he stepped
to the ball. Finally he swung that horrible piece of metal in his
hand. The ball flew the green. Right over the stick, true, but also
right over the green.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo didn't move toward the green. Instead, he remained in
place, deconstructing his golf swing once again, for maybe the
millionth time. Faldo would take his practice swing back a fifth of
the way ... and stop ... and study exactly where his hands and
shoulders were. Then he would take his next practice swing back a
bit further, perhaps halfway back, and stop ... and study. Then he
would take his swing back to the top ... and stop ... and study
this newest angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like ... it keeps hitting me,'' Faldo would say later, in
another of those pieces of thought, when the mourners had gathered
around. He had run his hands through his hair just as he had said
those words, maybe the third or fourth time he had run his hands
through his hair. He is at wit's end when it comes to golf.
Clearly.
</P>
<P>
   A girlfriend was waiting nearby, a new blonde girlfriend. The
story was that his last blonde girlfriend, Brenna Cepelik, had
taken a 9-iron to Faldo's Porsche last summer or a 5-iron to
another car as Faldo dismissed her.
</P>
<P>
   She had been a coed at the University of Arizona when they found
each other early in 1995, and the affair was so well-disguised that
it took the British tabloids 8 months before their telescopic
lenses were prying into classrooms in Arizona. When Faldo had won
the Masters in 1996, he had hugged Brenna. Publicly. His wife was
gone.
</P>
<P>
   David Leadbetter, Faldo's golf guru, also was gone as of last
summer, about the same time as Brenna. Leadbetter and Faldo had
spent endless moments and months and years together, Leadbetter
deconstructing every piece of Faldo's swing, much like a golfing
Walt Hriniak, and for years it had been good. But, in the last two
years, it had been horrible. So the one guru was replaced by a new
guru.
</P>
<P>
   No difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were only three shots that happened to miss the green
... you know, off-target,'' Faldo went on, yearning to find some
good in the bad. Faldo then was asked to go through a few shots,
and he tried, and when one of the mourners tried one last bit of
empathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had a good finish coming in? (birdie-par-par).''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``How close were you on 16?'' Faldo had tapped in his only
birdie on the 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What club did you use on 16?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven-iron.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Faldo has missed the cut at Doral, missed the
cut at the Honda Classic, been disqualified at the TPC (when he
failed to identify his ball that became lodged in a tree before
dropping a new ball), tied for 33rd at one event and then tied for
55th last week in the BellSouth Classic in Atlanta. In his
lifetime, Faldo has earned $4,553,613 on the golf courses of the
world; this year the total is $30,650.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours earlier, another once-broken man, broken by life and
alcohol and not golf, had stood in the same spot as Nick Faldo had
stood. John Daly had been ready to implode when he hit his approach
shot into the creek in front of 13, but he had stepped into the
water and splashed the ball onto the green and rescued a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that if you shot a 72 here, you were
discouraged,'' said a now-sober Daly. ``The year that Faldo won, I
was 4-under going down 18 (on the first day) and I doubled to start
the (tournament) 2-under. But the fans are great here. They are
behind me, most of them. It's really special.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a light in John Daly's eyes as he spoke his hopeful
final public words of his day. There was no light in Nick Faldo's
eyes as he said his last words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to take a look at the takeaway,'' Faldo began
another sporadic string of throughts. ``A few little bits ... you
know ... it's the same old story ... close but not close enough ...
come back tomorrow, I guess. Al right?''
</P>
<P>
   The golfing corpse turned on his heel. The mourners filed away.
Sadly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
