</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 When Physical Stature Makes It Hard to Find a Job
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I'm a 26-year-old man who has had some unfortunate
problems in dealing with employers due to my stature. I have what
doctors refer to as infant-adult condition. At 3 feet and 55
pounds, I have the bone mass and muscle tissue of a small child.
I'm having trouble finding work with a real estate brokerage in my
town. One broker said she could not hire me because I would be
viewed by potential buyers as ``a small infant'' (her words) and
would not be able to gain the respect necessary to represent the
company. How can I find a brokerage that will see me as more than
just a little person?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  That broker who said you won't be able to gain
clients' respect is simply ignorant. If you do good work, clients
will quickly focus on the homes or offices you're showing them
rather than your height. In fact, you may even be able to turn your
unusual appearance into a marketing advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Van Etten, a Florida legal writer and lawyer who is of
very short stature, initially was advised by law firms to seek
behind-the-scenes work in a government office because clients might
not have confidence in her abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't have been more wrong,'' said Van Etten, who
persevered and became a successful trial lawyer. ``New clients
would come into the office who couldn't remember my name, but who
remembered seeing me in court. They'd say, `Is this the office
where the little lady works?'''
</P>
<P>
   That broker's comments to you pretty clearly violated the
Americans With Disabilities Act. So one of your options is to find
an experienced civil rights lawyer and file a discrimination
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   But frankly, if your main goal is launching a real estate
career, I'd avoid getting into a legal battle right now. Instead,
focus on your job search.
</P>
<P>
   Start by networking with people who you know are supportive of
disability rights. Your town might have a chapter of Little People
of America: Check their Web site at  &LR; www.lpaonline.org. &LR;  Or it may
have a Center for Independent Living or other disability-rights
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Ask members of those organizations for names of real estate
brokers they've used. Their first impression of you will be as a
``friend of a client'' rather than as some oddity.
</P>
<P>
   Also, do some conventional networking through your local chamber
of commerce or Board of Realtors. Show the people you meet that you
are professional, reliable and sharp _ a great potential employee,
regardless of your height.
</P>
<P>
   If a prospective employer still has doubts, you can offer to
prove yourself. ``I would think it's pretty low-risk for the
brokerage since they pay on a commission basis,'' said Van Etten,
who chairs the access committee of Little People of America. ``He
could say something like, `Let me work out of your firm's office
for three months. If I don't sell anything, then I'll move on. ...'
He has to show he has the personality for sales _ that he's
positive and not easily rebuffed.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding Startup Jobs
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you direct me to some good sources for jobs with startups
or companies that have recently gone public? Are there recruiters
who specialize in startups? I work in the area of corporate
facilities/ real estate. The work I perform probably wouldn't be
needed by very recent startups, but might be helpful to those that
are starting to expand.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: There definitely are recruiters who focus on startups.
But there's no easy way to find all of them: Most directories tend
to list recruiters by their geographic area or industry, not by the
size of their client firms.
</P>
<P>
   You might thumb through a resource like the Directory of
Executive Recruiters (Kennedy Publications) and contact recruiters
for industries like biotech or software, which tend to have a large
number of emerging companies.
</P>
<P>
   Roger King runs a Sausalito recruiting firm called TechSearch
that does a lot of work for startups. He suggests some other
job-search tactics: Check newspapers like The Chronicle that run a
regular listing of local firms that have gone public. And seek out
organizations or events that draw people from the startup world.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Silicon Valley Association of Software
Entrepreneurs is chock-full of startup executives. And the Marin
Technology Venture Forum, to be held May 6, will draw both startup
entrepreneurs and venture funders. (See  &LR; www.marinventure.com &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   Last but certainly not least, there's the Internet. Betsy
Collard of the Career Action Center in Cupertino suggests that you
check out a site called  &LR; www.venturerex.com,  &LR; which lists more than
7,000 jobs at 800 startups across the country. Upside magazine also
offers startup job listings at  &LR; www.upside.com.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Want more ideas for researching jobs at startups? Check with the
Career Action Center at (408) 253-3200.
</P>
<P>
   Murky Bonus System
</P>
<P>
   Q: Part of our pay is based on a bonus system. The bonus is
calculated at the end of each month based on performance during
that month, but the money isn't distributed until the end of the
quarter. Recently, the company adopted a new policy saying that in
order to receive a bonus, employees must be working for the company
at the time the money is distributed. This means deserving people
lose their bonuses if they quit before the end of the quarter. Is
this legal?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: It sounds not only legal, but pretty common.
</P>
<P>
   Labor law treats bonuses differently from regular wages. Your
company can't refuse to pay wages for time you've worked if you
happen to quit before the end of a pay period. But it  &LR; can &LR;  make
bonuses conditional on folks remaining employed through a certain
date _ in your case, the end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The labor code is focused principally on wages and doesn't
give the same protection to bonuses,'' said Alan Exelrod, a San
Francisco attorney who represents employees with Rudy, Exelrod,
Zieff &AMP; True.
</P>
<P>
   Consider yourself lucky in one respect: At least your bonuses
are paid out each quarter. Many companies don't hand out bonuses
until the end of the year. Their employees may work for nine or 10
months, meet all their performance goals and yet be denied a bonus
because they quit before year's end.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
