<SLUG> BC-MA-AIDS-LAYOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS AGENCY LAYS OFF 19 WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a sign of the nation's battle fatigue in the fight
against AIDS, the largest AIDS agency in Massachusetts laid off 19
workers Thursday, nearly one-fifth its staff, in an effort to make
up a nearly $1 million shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   The first major layoff in the 16-year history of the AIDS Action
Committee of Massachusetts comes largely in response to a steep
dropoff in money from the annual AIDS Walk, its primary
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS Action's fund-raising crisis reflects a nationwide trend
affecting organizations from New York to Seattle, as the public has
come to think the epidemic is less urgent because of new drugs and
the drop in deaths, say AIDS advocates.
</P>
<P>
   However, the urgency is even greater as more people with AIDS
live longer and require more services, and as the rate of new
infections continues unabated, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very bittersweet time here,'' said Larry Kessler,
executive director of the Boston-based agency, in an interview.
``Here we are at this point now, we've got some better drugs and
some really good news. At the same time, we know it doesn't equal
cure. We're worried about prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the agency said the staff downsizing would be
accompanied by a shift in focus toward more intensive HIV
prevention and health-promotion programs, to more effectively stop
the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of AIDS Action clients who die each year has
dropped from more than 300 in the mid-1990s to fewer than 100 last
year, the number of registered clients receiving services has
jumped from about 1,300 to more than 2,000 in the same time frame,
according to the organization's figures.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 242 people died from AIDS in 1997, down from 609 in
1996, according to the latest mortality figures. About 25,000 to
30,000 Massachusetts residents are estimated to be infected with
HIV, said Jean Maguire, director of the state's AIDS bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, while the number of people who died from AIDS
dropped 47 percent in 1997, about 40,000 Americans a year continue
to become infected with the virus that causes the incurable
disease, according to US figures.
</P>
<P>
   That estimated infection rate has ``been unchanged for the past
few years,'' with minorities, women, and young people making up a
growing share of those now being affected, said Daniel Zingale,
executive director of a Washington-based national network of AIDS
agencies. Based on the current demographics of infection, Zingale
said, ``Every hour, two Americans under the age of 25 are becoming
newly infected with HIV.''
</P>
<P>
   All day Thursday at the AIDS Action offices on Clarendon Street,
department heads met with each of more than 100 staffers, letting
them know whether they were being laid off, staying or having their
duties changed, Kessler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everybody has been crying at every level, from the top
down. It's very sad,'' Kessler said. ``It gets triggered by a
look.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19 being laid off effective April 22 have been with the
agency from one year to 10 years, and did such jobs as secretary,
bookkeeper, and case manager. They will each get six weeks' salary
as severance, three months' health coverage, plus any accumulated
vacation time, Kessler said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, two of the more than half-dozen who had been
told they were being laid off by then said they would come back as
volunteers, Kessler said. ``I cannot describe for you why they're
such special people. They're real givers.''
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS Walk, which began 13 years ago, raised more than $3
million at its peak, in 1993, but its gross revenues have
consistently dropped since then _ most sharply after 1996, the year
that the drugs known as protease inhibitors made headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, AIDS Action had hoped to raise $2.6 million from the
walk, but grossed only slightly more than $2 million. This year,
with more pessimistic expectations, the agency plans on only $2
million from the June 6 walk, but would love to raise $2.4 million
or $2.5 million, Kessler said. The AIDS Walk has been the single
biggest private source of funding for the $10 million a year
agency.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, AIDS Action and many other AIDS agencies have
seen other private donor sources shrinking, with corporate mergers
and competition from other good causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of `donor fatigue' out there,'' said Anne Marie
Silvia, executive director of the Boston AIDS Consortium, a private
non-profit organization that focuses on AIDS planning, policy and
advocacy in the greater Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   But state and city public health officials and other AIDS
advocates applauded AIDS Action's attempts to do more with less by
creating new programs to intensify its efforts to prevent HIV and
keep people who are already infected as healthy as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The new AIDS Action programs are a neighborhood mobilization
project to prevent HIV; case management of infected clients to
reduce transmission of the virus; and promotion of health among
HIV-infected people.
</P>
<P>
   With the ``breathing room'' that the new drugs now provide, and
with the new programs focused on prevention, ``We're turning our
guns on those areas that are fueling the epidemic,'' Kessler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are closing in on 20 years, and it's still here in
more ways than one. The epidemic says it's not going away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
