<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWJONES-LIBEL-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS RECORD LIBEL CASE SHOULD BE RETRIED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., N.Y., Texas)   (rk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The case that resulted in the largest libel verdict in history
was tainted by the deception of the plaintiffs, a U.S. District
Court judge said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the case, which pitted a Texas brokerage firm
against The Wall Street Journal's parent company, should be
retried.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is the latest twist in a case that won widespread
attention in 1997 when a Texas jury awarded the plaintiffs, MMAR
Group Inc., a record $222.7 million, an amount that exceeded the
total annual earnings of Dow Jones &AMP; Co., The Journal's parent
company, and shocked media companies in its severity.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Ewing Werlein Jr. of the Southern District of Texas,
had already reduced the original award to $22.7 million,
eliminating $200 million in punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was on appeal when a former employee of the company
approached Dow Jones lawyers 14 months ago to say that MMAR's top
officials had hidden and destroyed evidence that might have
buttressed the allegations made in the 1993 Journal article that
prompted the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Laura Jereski, the article said that MMAR had gained
its power and reputation by selling mortgage-backed securities, but
described the company's dealings with clients as reckless. A
central point in the article was that MMAR mishandled the
investment portfolio of the Louisiana state pension plan, costing
that client $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   MMAR officials had contended in court that the article, and
resulting lawsuits and investigations, destroyed its business.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the verdict, the former MMAR employee, William
Fincher, contacted one of Dow Jones' lawyers through an
intermediary, who told the lawyer that MMAR executives had hidden
or destroyed internal tape recordings before the trial. Some of
these, Fincher asserted, supported the article's descriptions of
irregular handling of the Louisiana pension account. Dow Jones
attorneys had sought all such evidence during the pre-trial phase
of the case.
</P>
<P>
   According to legal papers Dow Jones lawyers filed with Werlein
seeking to overturn the libel verdict, Fincher had been put in
charge of reviewing hundreds of hours of internal tape recordings
about the time MMAR filed its libel suit in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dow Jones' motion to have the original verdict set
aside, Fincher ``disclosed that MMAR had withheld crucial evidence,
including audiotapes and transcripts, and engaged in a scheme to
erase damaging portions of conversations recorded on the `master
reels' of its telephone taping system.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fincher, the legal pleadings said, had made copies of
crucial tapes. Last summer, while he was providing further evidence
to Dow Jones attorneys, Fincher died in the crash of a small plane
while on a Central American vacation.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments on the case Thursday, Werlein wrote that ``The
tapes contain significant evidence to suggest that MMAR had engaged
in mismarking'' the documents that listed the value of pension
fund's mortgage-backed securities. ``This evidence,'' the judge
continued, ``went to the heart of one of the most damaging
statements in the article.''
</P>
<P>
   The material, Werlein wrote, ``would have provided potentially
fruitful, if not dramatic, new avenues of cross-examination during
the trial, and would have provided substantial evidence from which
to argue to the jury that the mismarking statement was true.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the newly revealed taped conversations, which occurred
a few months before The Journal's article appeared, MMAR's chief
financial officer is discussing the Louisiana state pension
portfolio with the head of the company's trading desk. ``But, I
mean, what did we do? Except for mispricing?'' the officer asks.
</P>
<P>
   The top trader responded, ``That's what we _ well, that, which
is pretty major. And we sold them all this (expletive). It was
probably _ could be considered unsuitable by certain people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reached early Thursday evening, MMAR's attorney, Kenneth M.
Morris, said, ``If we need to retry the case, we will.'' He added
that he had not received a copy of the judge's ruling, but ``a new
trial procedure would be a disappointment but certainly not a
defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I think those tapes can be fully and fairly
explained. I do not think those tapes show that MMAR mismarked''
any listings ``to hide any losses because there were no losses to
hide'' in the pension plan's portfolio. ``I'm confident that the
jury will find that that statement remains false and defamatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the case is on appeal to the circuit court, Werlein cannot
not immediately order a retrial until the higher court sends him
back the case.
</P>
<P>
   Paul E. Steiger, the Journal's managing editor, said Thursday,
``We are very pleased with the court's decision, and are quite
optimistic as this case returns to the district court. We've long
maintained that we did not cause MMAR's collapse, but merely
chronicled it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
