A1227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-BUSH-TAXCUTS09-CO     04-08 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-BUSH-TAXCUTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate supports consumer tax cuts
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Though they rejected similar proposals two years
ago, Senate Republicans on Thursday helped pass more than $300
million in consumer sales tax cuts, a key part of Gov. George W.
Bush's legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats in 1997 urged Bush and fellow lawmakers to
exempt over-the-counter medicines and children's school clothing
from the sales tax. At the time, Senate Republicans, backing Bush's
1997 call for property tax cuts, voted against the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a likely candidate for the Republican presidential
nomination, again has called on lawmakers to cut property taxes. He
also wants consumer sales tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad the see the governor and some of our other colleagues
have jumped on the bandwagon,'' said Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos.
Barrientos (D-Austin) peppered the Senate with comments about
Republicans fighting the issue two years ago before the Senate
approved the bill by an unrecorded voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``How come we didn't pass these very same tax cuts last
session?'' he asked Sen. Rodney Ellis (D-Houston), sponsor of the
bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   No Republicans voted for the amendments last session, though not
all Democrats supported them either.
</P>
<P>
   As approved by the Senate, Texans would not pay the state's 6.25
percent sales tax or the local option sales taxes of up to 2
percent on over-the-counter medicine specifically formulated for
children. They also would not pay sales taxes on diapers. Those
exemptions, which would begin Sept. 1, 1999, would cost the state
$101 million during the next two budget years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the permanent exemption on diapers and children's
medicines, Senate Bill 441 would establish a 14-day sales tax
holiday during which no sales taxes would be collected on most
clothing and shoes that cost less than $200. That would cost the
state about $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals would cost cities, counties and other taxing
authorities, like transit authorities, another $54.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Because recent state income has been higher than expected,
lawmakers and Bush are talking tax cuts for the next two budget
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a real tax cut for families that they can
understand,'' said Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have criticized a $1 billion property tax cut passed
in 1997 and Bush's proposed $2 billion property tax cut this year.
They say property tax cuts do nothing for people who don't own
homes or businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A House committee late Wednesday approved its version of
consumer tax cuts. That plan, including House Bills 209, 2280, 2371
and 2372, would eliminate the sales tax on diapers, most school
supplies, children's over-the-counter medicines. The House
committee plan also would create a nine-day moratorium on sales
taxes on children's school clothing that costs $75 or less.
</P>
<P>
   The committee now will have to decide whether to take up the
Senate version of the proposal, make changes to its version on the
House floor or debate the issue with senators in a conference
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
