<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR GRUNFELD, FUTURE RIDES ON KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the bleeding doesn't soon stop, Ernie Grunfeld
surely knows where this is going because he has already been there,
eight years ago, in one of those fancy sky boxes atop Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   He was alongside Al Bianchi one winter night in 1991 when
Bernard King returned like a vengeful ghost to haunt the faltering
Knicks with 49 points, and a crowd of 14,227 erupted with inspired
chants of ``Al Must Go.'' If it was painful for Grunfeld to sit
there while his boss, the general manager, was derided, it was
worse for Bianchi, who finally turned to him and said: ``They booed
Holzman, DeBusschere and Reed. I guess I'm in good company.''
</P>
<P>
   Bianchi was fired soon after, just like Red Holzman, Dave
DeBusschere and Willis Reed. Grunfeld slid into the general
manager's seat, and up another notch to team president after Pat
Riley slithered south to Miami, and Dave Checketts climbed from the
Knicks' presidency up the corporate ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld, out of Forest Hills High School, has outlasted
Bianchi, the man who hired him, for almost a decade. He has had a
good front-office run, but history and common sense tell us it will
end if the Knicks don't reverse field and at least last into the
second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld will be out, and his recent pronouncement of job
security for the coach, Jeff Van Gundy, will be moot. Even
Checketts, caretaker of the entire Garden, may have to explain _ 60
percent to Charles Dolan and the other 40 to Rupert Murdoch, if I
understand the latest shuffling of ownership _ why the hundreds of
millions in basketball and hockey salaries have produced such
insipid results.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts, Grunfeld and Van Gundy, whom you never mind bumping
into in the Garden corridor, obviously have their public-access
allies, who, unfortunately, have sounded more like spokespeople
these last turbulent weeks. All warring camps should by now at
least be in agreement that, barring a miracle of biblical
proportion, there will be no championship in the Patrick Ewing era.
Whoever is in charge next season had better come up with one heck
of an exit strategy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if this management team didn't have the time and
resources to win the franchise's first title in over a quarter of a
century. Eight years in the front office is an eternity these days,
and after several spending sprees, Grunfeld has somehow assembled a
team that doesn't pass or rebound well enough to create high
percentage shots, a team with no custodial presence that was
foolishly built around a 36-year-old center with a worn, cranky
body.
</P>
<P>
   On this latter subject, Ewing's public defenders should stop
whining about how maligned he is. The argument that Ewing is no
longer a title-caliber leading man _ if he ever was _ is an
indictment of the front office, not him. For the money Checketts
and Grunfeld spent, as well as the prices they charge, they had to
do better than they have.
</P>
<P>
   Some recent moves by Grunfeld have been the confused or
desperate maneuverings of a man trying to make up for mistakes. The
Knicks didn't want to pay an aging Charles Oakley free-agent money,
so they surrendered their interior soul, turned around and handed a
$28 million, four-year deal to Chris Dudley, 34. They compounded
the Chris Childs mistake by overpaying Charlie Ward. They knew
Latrell Sprewell could score and paid little mind to how he would
fit.
</P>
<P>
   So much costly redecorating, in the interests of ``winning one
with Ewing.'' This is the weight on the shoulders of every player
who has walked through the locker room door. Not to mention the
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Before anyone screams bloody murder in Van Gundy's defense,
please note that 23 coaching changes have been made since he
relieved Don Nelson late in the 1995-96 season. Van Gundy is
knowledgeable and prepared, but labels come cheap these days. I
suppose if Allen Iverson, who hasn't been in a playoff game, can be
called a great player, then Van Gundy, as his worried supporters
have been lining up to say, is a great coach.
</P>
<P>
   If he goes, frankly, he'll live, and probably with a lucrative
deal someplace else. Any sympathy I have for fired coaches is
reserved for guys like Butch Beard and Eddie Jordan, the
African-American aspirants who wait years to coach a bad team for a
short time, on the way back to being an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   For Knicks fans, the reality is that they're better off if this
team bottoms out right here and now. The illusion of contention
will finally be shattered. The paying customers can start chanting
that someone, or everyone, must go. The corporate head hunters will
fill in the blanks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
