A1232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NUHN09-CO     04-08 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NUHN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love `the quietest No. 3 in history'
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA , Ga. _ The breakthrough for Davis Love III was supposed
to have come at the PGA in 1997 when he won his first major. Now,
the theory went, the pressure was off and the majors would start
rolling in like clouds in front of a low pressure system.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Just like after Tiger Woods won the Masters by 12 shots in 1997,
there was no follow through.
</P>
<P>
   Golf is funny that way. It will lure you into thinking you've
figured it out, then it will knock on your front door late at night
and leave a burning sack of putters on your porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here last year thinking I had a good chance,'' Love
said. ``To not really contend in any of the majors was
disappointing. All I did was hang around in a couple of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanging around can be profitable in this game.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus made a pretty fair career out of it. He hung
around, made a birdie here or there, saved a par from someone's
porch, had the nerves of a cliff-diver, watched the men around him
turn to jelly and won 70 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   But if you don't do any or all of those tricks that Nicklaus
perfected, you end up seventh or eighth and people are asking you
questions like this one from a USA Today writer on Thursday:
``Someone asked me last night, `Why doesn't Davis Love win more?'
and I'm like, `I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   This was after Love had goosed a 3-under-par 69 at Augusta
National Golf Club to tie for the first-day lead at the
storm-interrupted Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Love's quick-draw answer: ``He doesn't shoot low enough
scores.''
</P>
<P>
   And then this more reflective response: ``I've been wondering
that a lot this year. I do feel I should win more, but I bet
there's 100 guys playing this week who feel they should win more,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not 100, but plenty. This is a Tour of should-haves,
would-haves and might-haves. And every major _ except the one Tiger
swallowed whole _ ends with a half-dozen guys muttering that it was
theirs for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   Love was one of them in 1995, the year Ben Crenshaw won with his
late teacher, Harvey Penick, whispering to him from the grave.
Penick died the Sunday before the Masters, Crenshaw was a
pall-bearer at the funeral on Wednesday, and then came the classic
finish.
</P>
<P>
   Love nailed a 6-under-par 66 on Sunday and led by a shot. But
Crenshaw, playing with memories of Penick ripping him apart,
birdied 16 to tie, birdied 17 to lead and then two-putted for a par
on 18 to win, after which he doubled over and let out a week's
worth of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Love finished at 13-under 275, which would have won 16 of the
previous 18 Masters (and tied the other two), yet he left Augusta
that night as empty as an Arizona ghost town.
</P>
<P>
   Love flew home to Sea Island, Ga., then phoned Crenshaw, who was
eating his Champion's dinner in the clubhouse here. Best of
friends, the two congratulated each other on a battle well fought.
``Then I told Ben, `The only way I could feel good about finishing
second was that you won,''' Love said, ``and that's how I still
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   He shot 32 on the backside Thursday after wrestling a 37 out of
the front, then addressed his status as No. 3 in the world golf
rankings. ``I'm the quietest No. 3 in history,'' he said. ``I came
in here and talked to one or two people, hit some balls, and that
was it. It's nice not to be in demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand is a fickle beast. You're only in demand if you've left a
footprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to be in demand next Monday,'' Davis Love
decided.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
