<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAM-SUCCESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAGRAM'S ONLINE PLANS BOOST STOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. -- Internet mania has hit Seagram Co.,
parent of Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram's decision to launch an online music business goosed the
stock by 13 percent in the past two sessions for a pair of all-time
highs. It gained $4.0625 Wednesday and an additional $3 on Thursday
to close at $62 a share after hitting $65 during the session.
</P>
<P>
   The price rise represents a validation of Edgar Bronfman's
strategy to transform Seagram from a beverage concern to an
entertainment conglomerate. Seagram shares had been depressed last
fall, dropping under $30 at one point, over concerns about its film
business. But the shares recovered on optimism about the
acquisition of Polygram NV and remained at the $47 level in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   The stock began rising last week on rumors of a major Web
alliance. Seagram and German media giant Bertelsmann confirmed
Wednesday they will pool resources for online sale in the most
extensive such move by major music companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction is an overreaction except that anything related
to the Internet is getting a great response these days,'' said
Barry Hyman, an analyst with Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum. ``This is a
good partnership because music is heading in this direction. We
bought the stock at $32 when it was one of the cheapest
entertainment companies in the universe so right now I would
consider it fairly valued but I will think it will continue
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Bannister of Edward Jones, who recently upgraded Seagram
from hold to buy, said the price surge reflects not just Wall
Street's lust for Internet stocks but also its satisfaction with
how the company is positioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seagram is being viewed much more now as an entertainment
company,'' she said. ``The stock was significantly undervalued, so
the discount is not there anymore, but there's a lot of potential
for them to benefit eventually from downloading music from the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
