<HEADER>
A1236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES09-CO     04-08 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confidence not lacking in Perez, 20
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today is the big day for Odalis Perez, who makes his
first major-league start when the Braves open a three-game series
with the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   And no, the left-hander who beat out Bruce Chen for the No. 5
starter's job is not especially nervous. But Perez, 20, is glad
today is finally here.
</P>
<P>
   To pass the time Perez said he has been ``just relaxing,
watching TV, watching the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his confidence comes from his personality, some from his
successful spring. In his two spring starts, Perez dominated the
two best lineups in the American League. In a split-squad game
against the New York Yankees, Perez struck out seven in four
innings and gave up two runs. Against the Indians, Perez pitched
five scoreless innings, allowing one hit and striking out six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will go there and do well, like I was doing in spring
training,'' Perez said. ``I will try to do my job and be focused,
approach the hitters one at a time. I'll just throw all my pitches
and let them work.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez said he hasn't been studying the Arizona lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a good team,'' Perez said. ``It doesn't matter the kind
of lineup they're going to have there.''
</P>
<P>
   One advantage Perez does count on is the Diamondbacks'
unfamiliarity with him. Perez, who was used exclusively as a
reliever last season, faced the Diamondbacks only once. He saw two
batters and got them both out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have a big surprise,'' Perez said. ``They
don't know who I am. There might be two or three guys who remember
who I am. Most of the guys don't even know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker ready
</P>
<P>
   The day after striking out the side in the ninth inning to cap
off a 4-0 Braves shutout, John Rocker said he wasn't counting on
having the closer's job, but was ready for it either way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they'll give (Mark Wohlers) as many chances as they
think he deserves to reclaim his closer's job,'' Rocker said. ``If
he gets back to where he was two years ago, I'm sure they'd be
thrilled to death to have that. ... Better (for me) to be prepared
and have it not happen, than not prepared and have it happen and
say `What do I do now?'''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan on the move
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of reasons why Brian Jordan has been eagerly
attempting stolen bases in his first several games as a Brave: One
is he wanted to get his first stolen base behind him. And secondly,
he's not trying to protect Mark McGwire anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got freedom,'' said Jordan, who was 17-for-22 last year
in stolen bases. Jordan, who is 0-for-2 in steals, said one of
those attempts came after he misread a sign, where he thought he
was supposed to go instead of just having the option to go. Also,
Jordan is nursing a sore hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel fast at all,'' Jordan said. ``I don't have that
explosion. ... I'm not going to give up trying. ... You've got to
be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
