<HEADER>
A1238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELISSA-VIRUS-NYT &LR;      04-08 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELISSA-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER LIKENS MELISSA VIRUS TO GRAFFITI
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEHOLD, N.J. _ The 30-year-old computer programmer accused of
creating the fastest-spreading computer virus in history made his
first appearance in court Thursday, and afterward his lawyer
suggested that whoever wrote the virus should be considered a sort
of graffiti artist rather than ``an international cyberterrorist.''
</P>
<P>
   The programmer, David L. Smith, was arrested a week ago after a
global search and charged with writing and sending out the Melissa
virus, which has infected more than 100,000 computers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Edward F. Borden Jr., said Thursday that Smith would
most likely plead not guilty if indicted by a state grand jury. The
programmer, who lives in Aberdeen, N.J., will not have to enter a
plea on the five counts he faces until his arraignment, which has
not yet been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's hearing in state Superior Court in Monmouth
County, Judge John Ricciardi advised Smith of his rights and
explained the legal process that will ensue in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a tall, broad-shouldered man, wearing a plain black suit,
nodded repeatedly as the judge spoke to him, but remained silent
except for an occasional ``Yes, sir'' or ``No, Sir.'' After the
brief hearing, he walked without a hint of emotion through the pack
of reporters waiting for him outside the courthouse and was driven
away by Borden.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to speak with reporters, Borden described Smith as a
bright young man who had been wrongfully vilified by the state.
``David was making his way in the world just fine until a few days
ago,'' he said. ``He's very upset and has been affected by this
very profoundly.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that Smith, who worked until a few days ago
as a consultant for CGS, a computer company based in Iselin, N.J.,
wrote the virus and named it after a topless dancer he had
apparently met in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He is charged with three counts relating to the interruption of
public communication, as well as theft of computer services and
wrongful access to computer systems. The charges carry a maximum
penalty of 40 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 26, when it was first uploaded to the Internet news
group alt.sex from a stolen America Online account, the Melissa
virus has spread like a cancerous chain letter by penetrating a
computer user's e-mail system and sending itself to as many as 50
correspondents in the user's e-mail address book.
</P>
<P>
   By replicating and transmitting itself so quickly, the virus
backed up and at times incapacitated computer networks at about 300
corporations, experts have said.
</P>
<P>
   While Borden said he could not dismiss the virus as a ``harmless
prank,'' he said it did not delete any files or severely damage any
computers. He also refused to say whether Smith had anything to do
with creating the virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question,'' he said of whoever wrote the Melissa
virus, ``is whether we're dealing with someone more akin to a
graffiti artist or to an international cyberterrorist.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Loriquet, a spokesman for the New Jersey attorney general's
office, which is prosecuting the case, said a grand jury would soon
convene in Trenton, but would not say exactly when.
</P>
<P>
   Smith remains free on $100,000 bail and is staying with his
family, Borden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
