<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1246 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES09-C     04-08 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big-hitting McCarron likes lengthier course
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Everyone has claimed the changes made to Augusta
National favor the long hitters. They certainly favored co-leader
Scott McCarron, considered one of the PGA Tour's longest drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the course does set up real well for me,'' said
McCarron, a 33-year-old Californian, after his five-birdie,
three-bogey round. ``For some reason, I get here and start relaxing
and feel comfortable. I drive the ball farther and feel more
powerful. It's kind of a mystical place for me.''
</P>
<P>
   His 69 marks the first time he's broken 70 in three Masters, but
that is a bit misleading. He finished 10th in 1996 with rounds of
70-70-72-74. Crowd washed away
</P>
<P>
   The storm that blew through Augusta National late Thursday
afternoon turned the first round of the Masters into two
tournaments. The first was as hot as summer and jammed with crowds.
After the rain, a cool breeze and strange hush fell over the course
as the few-hundred lingering fans watched lightning dance in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting a sand shot on 18 close enough for a tap-in par
and 83, Arnold Palmer said he thought the small necklace of
spectators around the last green was the fewest he'd seen in 45
Masters. A few minutes later, everyone could easily see Mark
O'Meara hole a 3-footer for birdie, which would have been
impossible if he had finished a few hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Franco stumbles after fast start
</P>
<P>
   It would have been a fairy tale if Carlos Franco could have
stayed on the leaderboard. A 33-year-old Masters rookie who grew up
in Paraguay, a country with only three golf courses, he got to 4
under after 11 holes.
</P>
<P>
   But disaster struck on the par-5 15th when Franco struck a hard
5-iron from 202 yards that bounced off the green as if from a
tabletop. The ball came to rest on the bank of the pond behind the
green _ a lucky break. But Franco skulled his next shot into the
front pond and he made a double bogey en route to a 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``One moment I was first,'' he said through an interpreter after
his round. ``The next moment I had an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Rough start
</P>
<P>
   When honorary starter Byron Nelson was introduced as the winner
of 11 consecutive PGA tournaments Thursday morning, one fan
wondered, ``Isn't David Duval working on that record?'' Sort of.
He's won 11 _ out of his past 34. Nelson, 87, topped his drive
left. But he wasn't the first to find the new Augusta rough. That
distinction belonged to Gene Sarazen. The 97-year-old ``Squire''
took a smooth whack at a ball that never reached the fairway, but
who cared?
</P>
<P>
   Felled by heat
</P>
<P>
   The medical trucks were busy Thursday because of the heat. About
the time the temperature crested at 90 degrees, one woman who had
been sitting without shade watching drives on No. 11 keeled over in
her chair, and medical personnel carried her away on a stretcher.
With summer-like conditions predicted through the weekend, those
headed to the course should pack a few essentials along with that
badge: a brimmed hat, light-colored clothing, sunscreen and
rubber-soled shoes. Golf spikes will just make it hotter.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles flying high
</P>
<P>
   Jumbo Ozaki's eagle at the par-4 10th was the fifth on that hole
since the tournament began in 1934. Tom Lehman's eagle on the 13th
hole is his fourth at Augusta, second on that hole. Nick Price's
eagle on No. 2 is his third at the Masters. Other eagles: Lee
Janzen holed out a wedge at No. 2, and Jose Maria Olazabal
recovered from a bad drive at No. 13 with a 4-iron to 25 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Par-3 jinx lives
</P>
<P>
   Joe Durant's 5-under 22 to win Wednesday's Par-3 tournament came
back to haunt him Thursday. He made four double-bogeys in his last
four holes on the way to an 87, keeping intact an infamous record:
Nobody has ever won the Par-3 and the Masters in the same year. ``I
guess there must be something to that Par-3 jinx,'' said Durant,
making his first Masters appearance after a win in last year's
Motorola Western Open. Semi-Colin?
</P>
<P>
   After an opening 70, it was noted to Scotland's Colin
Montgomerie that his name and scores were not on the big scoreboard
near the 18th hole. ``Of course, my name's not up there,''
Montgomerie said. ``I'm the wrong nationality.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Glenn Sheeley contributed to this notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
