<SLUG> BC-NUKE-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S PRIME MINISTER DENIES SECRETS WERE STOLEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See also CHINA-U.S., CHINA-U.S. SCENE)  
(DW) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Spicing his denials with humor and compliments to
his American hosts, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji asserted Thursday
that China had never stolen nuclear secrets from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to make a very solemn statement here that I have
no knowledge whatsoever of any charge, of any allegation, of
espionage or the theft of nuclear technologies,'' Zhu declared.
``And I don't believe such story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the policy of China to steal so-called military
secrets from the United States,'' Zhu continued through an
interpreter, even though he speaks excellent English. ``And I don't
think there can be such problem, given the tight security measures
in the United States and advanced technology.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the sound system malfunctioned momentarily. ``It
seems that the technology with regard to this microphone is not
that advanced,'' the premier remarked to accompanying laughter.
</P>
<P>
   With President Clinton standing nearby and flags of both
countries on display behind the leaders, Zhu said, ``As a senior
engineer, I've been in charge of the industry in China for more
than 40 years, and I have never known any of our most advanced
technology came from the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing remarks he made last month amid suspicions that China
had been able to obtain American nuclear-weapons secrets from U.S.
laboratories during the course of joint scientific programs, Zhu
said, ``I hope you don't underestimate your own ability to keep
secrets, and don't underestimate the capability of the Chinese
people to develop their own technology.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, American intelligence experts have been
investigating the possible acquisition by China in the 1980s of the
designs of the United States' most modern nuclear warhead. While
acknowledging the seriousness of the allegations, administration
officials have taken comfort in noting that the thefts, if any,
were not committed on their watch.
</P>
<P>
   But The New York Times reported Thursday that some American
intelligence officials now believe that a second theft of data
occurred. They suspect that Chinese agents stole secrets related to
the neutron bomb, which kills with enhanced radiation, from the
United States in 1995, during the Clinton presidency. Several
agencies are investigating the possible thefts, although
administration officials say they have found no evidence that China
has produced an improved neutron bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Thursday that he would continue to decline to
comment on specific intelligence reports. But he said he had raised
the espionage issues with Zhu on Wednesday night, when the prime
minister arrived in Washington on an official visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, China is a big country with a big government, and I
can only say that America is a big country with a big government,
and occasionally things happen in this government that I don't know
about,'' the president said. ``I think it's important that we
continue the investigation and do our best to find out what
happened, and I asked for his cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Zhu said he had been asked at a welcoming luncheon
in Los Angeles how his country would celebrate the 50th anniversary
of Communist rule this fall. With a grand military review, the
prime minister replied, and perhaps the missiles will bear signs
``that they are made in China, not from the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
