<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUGUSTA CUTS WOODS DOWN TO SIZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Tiger Woods scored another first Thursday at
Augusta National Golf Club. A landmark moment, it was not. It was
more like a land mine.
</P>
<P>
   In 14 previous trips around the course, Woods never had posted a
score worse than a double bogey. That all changed when the
23-year-old stepped to the par-5 eighth tee and pulled his drive
into the pine trees standing sentry on the left side of the
fairway.
</P>
<P>
   The ball came to rest between two pine cones, making his second
shot tricky. Woods tried to punch the ball out into the fairway
with a 6-iron, but it hit a tree and ricocheted into a clump of
azaleas some 15 yards behind where he stood, speechless.
</P>
<P>
   Upon retrieving his voice, Woods muttered, ``This is how you
lose (expletive) golf tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, in 1997 Woods shot a 4-over-par 40 on the front nine
and went on to win the Masters, the first of golf's four majors, by
a record 12 strokes. He managed to better that horrible halfway
number by two on this day, but it was a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a one-stroke penalty for an unplayable lie, Woods'
fourth shot on eight found the fairway. He flew the green with his
fifth shot, then chipped to 15 feet and two putted for a
triple-bogey 8.
</P>
<P>
   So much for taking advantage of his prodigious length on the
hole, which Woods had played in 6 under par in four other Masters
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of getting mad, Woods went 2 under on the remaining 10
holes to salvage an even-par round of 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to hang in there and be patient,'' Woods said. ``In
the past when I was 2 over par I'd try and be aggressive right
away. (Today) I told myself to be patient, that I had 64 holes
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, wielding his putter like a wand, Woods made those
three extra strokes he was carrying courtesy of No. 8 disappear
with consecutive birdies at the par-3 12th, the par-5 13th and the
par-4 14th. A bogey 5 at 17 was his only hiccup on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   On pins and needles: If the players felt like they were trying
to land their approach shots on the head of a pin, there was a good
reason. The first-day pin placements were so tough, Agoura Hills
resident Steve Pate felt fortunate to escape the sixth green with a
bogey 4 after hitting what he considered a really solid tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   The pin was in the back right quadrant of the green, tucked some
10 feet behind a mound that created a waterfall effect for balls
hit with any hint of a backspin.
</P>
<P>
   Pate's tee shot landed about five feet in front of the hole and
rolled all the way down to the right front part of the green.
Pate's first putt also rolled back down to within an inch of where
he had struck it. His third stroke stayed above the hole and he
made the comeback putt for his only bogey in a round of 1-under-par
71.
</P>
<P>
   Pate was in the second threesome sent out on the course. His
early tee time was a decided advantage insofar as he was able to
finish before the sun had thoroughly baked the greens until they
were as hard as crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Great Scott: The fourth time was a charm for former UCLA golfer
Scott McCarron. In his 13th competitive round at Augusta National,
McCarron broke 70 for the first time. His 3-under-par 69 was good
for a share of the lead with Brandel Chamblee and Davis Love III.
</P>
<P>
   His play made a prophet out of former champion Fred Couples, who
had said earlier in the week that he believed McCarron had the game
to do well here.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Freddie to say that is an honor,'' said McCarron, who made
seven straight cuts to start the 1999 season before missing the two
leading up to this week. ``I'm really relaxed here and am enjoying
the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing sick: Amateur Matt Kuchar, who wowed the crowds with his
play and his personality in his 1998 Masters debut, opened with a
77. That's five shots higher than his first-round score of a year
ago but not bad for someone who had to rise from his hospital bed
to make it here.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar, 20, who has been battling influenza, spent Tuesday at a
local hospital being treated for dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I had a lot more fun and I was playing a lot
better,'' Kuchar said. ``I was in more of a fairytale world. This
year, being sick kind of took the fairytale out of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
