<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PAR AT THE MASTERS FOR THE PARAGUAY PRO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA , Ga. _ With birdies on the third and fourth holes,
Carlos Franco's name went up early on the Masters leader boards,
but it was a new name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is Franco?'' voices in the gallery were asking.
</P>
<P>
   Not many knew that Franco, with a bandit's mustache and a sturdy
swing, is No. 46 in the World Golf Ranking and No. 54 on the PGA
Tour money list with $221,320, mostly because of a tie for third in
last month's Honda Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Not many knew that the 33-year-old Franco halved Phil Mickelson
for the International team that routed the American pros in the
Presidents Cup matches in Australia last year, or that he had
defeated Sam Torrance in the 1993 Dunhill Cup at St. Andrews when
little Paraguay shocked Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   But of all the golfers in Masters history, the 5-foot-9-inch,
165-pound Franco of Asuncion, Paraguay, was perhaps the most
unlikely to tee off at Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   One of six sons of the greenskeeper at one of only three golf
courses in Paraguay, he grew up in his family's one-room shack with
a dirt floor and no plumbing. But he and his brothers could play
the Asuncion Golf Club course at off hours. They now are six of
only 28 golf pros in all of Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   As a barefoot youngster, Carlos was shooting par when he won a
pair of golf shoes at age 14 in a caddie tournament; he earned $3 a
loop. He fished golf balls from the ponds. He used rusted irons
until a friend gave him a set of Hogan clubs when he was 18. By
then he was watching the Masters on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Jack Nicklaus win in 1986,'' he said. ``He was an
extraordinary golfer, very aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   In a touching moment here Tuesday, Franco, practicing alone, was
on the tee of the 155-yard 12th hole when Nicklaus, riding in a
golf cart to ease his recuperation from hip surgery, stopped and
asked for Franco's 6-iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, give me the 5,'' Nicklaus said.
</P>
<P>
   With that familiar swing, the six-time Masters winner lofted a
ball onto the green. Franco applauded, then took his 8-iron and
lofted his ball onto the green.
</P>
<P>
   When Franco walked to the 12th tee Thursday after a birdie 3 at
the 11th hole to go to 4 under par, he was suddenly leading the
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew,'' he was saying now through an interpreter. ``I was
very happy. Not nervous. I was proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco had been advised by Seve Ballesteros, the two-time
Masters winner from Spain, to aim for the middle of Augusta
National's slick greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried,'' Franco said, ``but it's not that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   After a bogey 4 at the treacherous 12th hole, he was still tied
for the lead. After a good drive at the 500-yard 15th, he had a
chance for a two-putt birdie if he hit his 5-iron on the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure if it was 4-iron or 5-iron,'' he said. ``I hit
5-iron. Hit it perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't enough club. His ball splashed into the pond in
front of the green. ``One moment, excellent,'' he said later with a
shrug. ``Next moment, accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco took a double-bogey 7 there, then bogied the short 16th
hole and finished his round at even-par 72, three strokes away from
the leaders, but the only Masters golfer to shoot the first three
letters of his country's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence,'' he said. ``I think I can
surprise here.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco has won 29 tournaments worldwide, mostly in South America
and five on the Japan tour where he earned more than $2.7 million
in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   He owns a spacious home in Asuncion for his wife, Celsa, and
their two sons, Carlos and Ramon. He also supports many family
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the PGA Tour here is much more competitive than Japan,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Franco earned his PGA Tour card by one stroke at last year's
Q-School, using his driver to putt on the five closing holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I putt with driver,'' he has said with a laugh, ``to
get people to know me.''
</P>
<P>
   In introducing himself to the Masters galleries Thursday, Franco
putted with his putter, but no introduction was necessary in
Paraguay where he was seen on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor people in Paraguay,'' he said, ``they need to see
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco referred to the recent outrage in Paraguay over the
assassination of its vice president, Luis Maria Argana, which
forced President Raul Cubas Grau to resign and flee into exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope what I do here will give the poor people in Paraguay
something to give them hope,'' Carlos Franco said. ``The poor
people need that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
