<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1252 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-WHITMAN-POLITICS-2     04-08 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-POLITICS-2TAKES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. GOVERNOR SAYS SHE WILL RUN FOR U.S. SENATE IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs to add 2nd take)   (bl)  
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman said Thursday that she
plans to run for the U.S. Senate next year, raising the prospect of
a rematch with the man she ousted from the State House six years
ago, Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the state constitution forbids her to run for a
third term, Whitman said that a seat in the U.S. Senate would give
her the opportunity to continue promoting her moderate Republican
agenda, only on a different stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would give me a voice,'' Whitman said during a news
conference in Trenton. ``A place where I could keep talking about
the need for lower taxes, limited government and the fact that all
the answers don't necessarily come from Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, she announced that she was forming a
fund-raising committee to begin collecting the $10 million to $12
million needed for a statewide campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Whitman's nationwide prominence as a moderate,
tax-cutting Republican, her announcement was greeted with
enthusiasm among Republicans in Washington, who feel that she
offers the party a strong chance to pick up a seat that has been
held by a Democrat, Frank Lautenberg, for nearly two decades.
</P>
<P>
   National party leaders also said that having a well-known
candidate on the ticket next year would bolster support for the
Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she had not expected to decide whether to run for
the Senate until later in the year, but she sped up her
decision-making process after Lautenberg unexpectedly announced his
retirement in February.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she would remain in office throughout the campaign.
If she wins, state Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, a
Republican from Scotch Plains, would become acting governor for the
final year of her second term. DiFrancesco plans to run for
governor in 2001, and the role of acting governor would likely
strengthen his bid.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lautenberg's decision to retire prompted several
Democrats to consider the race, most of the attention so far has
fallen on Florio, who was defeated by Whitman by a narrow margin in
the 1993 gubernatorial election. Florio has already announced his
plans to seek the Democratic U.S. Senate nomination and has been
raising money and trying to build support for his political
comeback. But he has yet to win the support of many party leaders,
who worry that the $2.8 billion tax increase he sponsored while
governor will hurt him in a race against Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Republicans have also considered running for
Lautenberg's seat, but most are expected to step aside for Whitman.
Even so, she is expected to face a primary challenge from Murray
Sabrin, who ran for governor as a member of the Libertarian Party
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said that she made the decision after she became
convinced that she could complete her second-term agenda in three
years instead of four. She noted that the state Legislature has
already agreed to move forward with her property tax rebate plan,
her initiative to preserve one million acres of farmland and other
open space, roll back auto insurance rates and deregulate the
energy industry.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Whitman filed papers Thursday formally creating a
campaign committee, she said that she would not begin actively
campaigning or talking about broader issues until sometime next
year.
</P>
<P>
   But Florio, firing his first salvo at the newly announced
candidate, said he had already begun to outline his positions and
that he would expect the governor to begin presenting her views to
voters as well.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by reporters whether she was worried about a possible
rematch with a candidate as well known as Florio, Whitman laughed
and said, ``I certainly look forward to comparing our records about
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats who have expressed interest in the seat include
Rep. Frank Pallone; Goldman Sachs co-chairman Jon Corzine; former
state party chairman B. Thomas Byrne and Cherry Hill Mayor Susan
Bass Levin.
</P>
<P>
   After her election as governor in 1993, Whitman rose to national
prominence by delivering on her campaign pledge to cut income tax
rates by 30 percent. She was occasionally mentioned as a possible
vice presidential or presidential candidate, and in 1994 was
selected to deliver the Republicans'
</P>
<P>
   televised response to the State of the Union address.
</P>
<P>
   But her prospects for national office were diminished after the
1994 congressional elections, when conservatives seized control of
the Republican Party and Whitman's support for abortion rights put
her at odds with some party leaders. Those prospects seemed to dim
even further after she nearly lost a re-election bid in 1997. And
in recent months she has said emphatically that she had no interest
in running for national office.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two months, as she decided whether to run for
the Senate, Whitman received a pledge from the National Republican
Senatorial Committee to help her campaign, she said. Those promises
were important to Whitman, her campaign aides said, because during
her 1990 challenge to Sen. Bill Bradley, Whitman received similar
promises, but the help never materialized and she lost a
surprisingly close race.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is a costly and complicated arena for statewide
campaigns because candidates need to reach voters by advertising in
two expensive media markets, New York and Philadelphia. Most
political analysts predict that each major party candidate will
need up to $12 million to run a competitive campaign. As an
incumbent governor, Whitman is not expected to have much difficulty
raising funds.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman is likely to share the political spotlight in the region
next year with a fellow Republican, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, who is considering a U.S. Senate bid in New York. The
mayor and the governor have recently clashed on a issues ranging
from garbage to sports franchises, but met for dinner this week at
the New York mayoral residence in an effort to smooth their
differences as they plot their next political moves.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's run for Senate seems a natural progression for a woman
whose family was so steeped in Republican politics that she
attended her first national political convention at age 9. Each of
her grandfathers served as chairman of the New Jersey Republican
finance committee. Her parents, Webster Todd and Eleanor Schley,
were one of the New Jersey's most wealthy and politically connected
couples and became patrons for centrist Republicans like Thomas
Dewey, Nelson Rockefeller and Wendell Wilkie.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman was active in Republican politics while attending
Wheaton College, where she received a degree in government. She
married John Whitman, the grandson of former New York Gov. Charles
Whitman, and worked briefly for the federal Office of Economic
Opportunity and the Republican National Committee. Whitman then
left the workplace to raise her two children, Kate and Taylor, and
did not re-enter public life until they were old enough to attend
school.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman first ran for office in 1982, when she was elected
freeholder in Somerset County, the affluent countryside where she
still lives on the family's 205-acre estate, known as Pontefract.
In 1988, she was appointed president of the Board of Public
Utilities by Gov. Tom Kean, and used it as a base to build her own
statewide support. After forming Republicans for Choice, a group
that supports abortion rights, Whitman made her first attempt at
statewide office in 1990 by unsuccessfully challenging Bradley for
his U.S. Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Whitman barely averted political disaster when she won
a slim victory over a little-known challenger, Woodbridge Mayor Jim
McGreevey. McGreevey surprised many political analysts by running a
focused campaign that blamed Whitman for the state's high auto
insurance rates, and came within 25,200 votes of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, Whitman has restored some of her
national standing by making frequent fund-raising appearances for
moderate Republicans across the country. But she is still
considered more popular nationally than within New Jersey, and in
fact has never received more than 50 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In her announcement Thursday, Whitman gave a preview of her
campaign themes, touting her record of tax cuts and taking credit
for the state's robust economy and low unemployment rate. She also
sounded a populist note, saying that the federal officials need to
hear the pragmatic perspective of someone who has experience
running a government outside the Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that I can make a real contribution as a former
governor to help determine that federal policy,'' she said. ``To go
there with an understanding of just what it takes to deliver. What
it takes to balance a budget in a state and deliver services to all
the people who require it. What those federal regulations _ a
slight change in a `but' or an `and' _ can mean in terms of
literally tens of thousands of dollars to needy people in our
states.''
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic leaders said they consider Governor Whitman a
formidable opponent, but welcome the chance to challenge her
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the name recognition and financial resources, but I do
believe she's vulnerable,'' said Thomas Giblin, chairman of the
state Democratic Party. ``Her record on property taxes, HMOs,
profiling by the state troopers, car insurance. When she decides to
marry up to the Republican platform, which is run by
arch-conservatives, she's going to be taking money from folks whose
philosophy is opposed to what her personal beliefs are. That ought
to be interesting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
