<HEADLINE>
CONCERN GROWS THAT SERBS WILL USE ETHNIC ALBANIANS AS HUMAN SHIELDS &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Allied officials expressed concern Thursday that
Yugoslav forces will use ethnic Albanians trapped in Kosovo as
human shields to deter NATO's stepped-up bombing campaign against
Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said the regime of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic may have closed border crossings out
of Kosovo because he planned ``to use people as human shields in
case the alliance's military action is concentrated more on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serb government urged refugees to return home Thursday,
saying peace had ``prevailed'' in Kosovo and the fight against
separatists was over.
</P>
<P>
   The developments made it harder for NATO strategists to pick
bombing targets as unsettled weather returned to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look at the circumstances at the time, and we'll make
sure that before we carry out our attacks that we can carry out
those attacks without collateral damage ... particularly innocent
civilian lives,'' NATO air chief David Wilby said at alliance
headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials acknowledged reports that Serb forces were
planting land mines along the Yugoslav border with Albania and
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's repeated contentions that ground forces were not
under consideration was brought into question by the assertion of
Canada's defense minister, Art Eggleton, who said Western military
officials were ``looking at other options as to where ground troops
might be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Eggleton acknowledged the original NATO plan was to use ground
troops only after a peace deal was struck with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if that's not going to be possible, and I think as we see
with each day the Milosevic government is not indicating they're
favorable to doing that, then certainly NATO has to look at other
options,'' Eggleton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration insisted that a turn to ground troops
was not in the plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe our present strategy will work if we can keep the
allies with it,'' Clinton said during a news conference with
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen expressed a similar view on
a quick trip to Europe, telling pilots at the Aviano air base in
Italy: ``We will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now starting to see this air campaign really take root
and start to go after those who are on the ground inflicting the
kind of suffering we've seen upon the Kosovar Albanians,'' Cohen
said in an NBC interview. ``So it will go on as long as
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, who met Wednesday with representatives of the 19 NATO
nations, said: ``They are solid and determined to carry this
mission out to its completion. ... This resolve has only been
strengthened by the exposure of Mr. Milosevic's barbarity.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO air assault drew strong support from European Union
foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the face of extreme and criminally irresponsible policies
... the use of the severest measures, including military action,
has been both necessary and warranted,'' the ministers said in a
statement adopted during a meeting in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   The latest turn in the Serb oppression of Kosovar Albanians came
Wednesday when, after weeks of driving displaced families toward
the border, Milosevic's military started to seal off crossing
points.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rear Adm. Thomas Wilson told a Pentagon briefing about
``anecdotal rumors and reports of human shields which we have not
been able to verify. It's a miserable tactic for anybody to use in
a wartime scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, a planning director for the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, said that more than a half-million ethnic Albanians
remain in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, as we do our planning, mission planning, that is always
put into the calculus of everything we do,'' Wald said.
</P>
<P>
   Laying out the bombing campaign is made more difficult because
allied strategists are uncertain where the Kosovar Albanians headed
for the border have gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what has happened to these people who seem to
have been forced back inside Kosovo,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea
said. ``We do not want to see a second humanitarian crisis inside
Kosovo itself with all of these displaced people without shelter,
food or any kind of assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, spokesman Jamie Rubin said Serb forces
``appear to be denying them the opportunity to cross the border and
receive humanitarian assistance and (are) trying to force them back
into a wasteland with virtually no food, water or shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said NATO forces flew almost 400 combat missions over
Yugoslavia on Wednesday, with all allied planes returning to base.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wilson cited ``strong evidence'' of Serb supply problems and
fuel disruption.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal Milo said his nation has
granted NATO authority to operate from its territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave to NATO ... all the rights to use our harbors, our
airspace and to control everything in Albania,'' Milo said in a
EuroNews interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration announced a new shipment of 51 metric
tons of food rations for Kosovo refugees in Macedonia and Albania.
The shipment, organized by the U.S. Agency for International
Development, will contain enough high-protein biscuits for 647,000
meals.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
