<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT &LR;      04-08 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THREE TIED FOR THE LEAD IN THE MASTERS, EVERYTHING'S COMING UP
AZALEAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ The first round of the Masters was everything
that Brandel Chamblee imagined, everything that Scott McCarron
hoped for, everything that an experienced major winner like Davis
Love III expected.
</P>
<P>
   For those three players, who were the clubhouse leaders at
three-under-par 69 when play was suspended because of darkness,
Thursday was a pleasant stroll through the azaleas, a comforting
way to start the year's first major.
</P>
<P>
   But they were fortunate. For many others, playing Augusta
National Golf Club was even more of a mind game than usual. The pin
placements were difficult, more like Sunday than Thursday. There
was a 90-minute rain delay that broke the momentum of 33 players
who were still on the course. There was just enough of a breeze to
alter some shots. There was the unknown of playing a different
Augusta, a course that has been lengthened on three holes and
toughened with 1]-inch-high rough to test the skill, patience and
strategy of the world's greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that mission accomplished. Only 17 of the 84 players
who completed the first round broke par, and many took nose dives
on the back nine. David Duval, cruising at three under par through
nine holes, made bogeys at No. 12, No. 13 and No. 14. When the
normally unflappable Duval becomes undone, you know this is not a
picnic. While Duval (one under par through 17 holes) and Tiger
Woods (par 72) remained in contention on a tightly bunched leader
board, by the time this Masters ends, many players may feel more
suited for a straight jacket than a green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting 69s and avoiding costly mistakes that sabotaged many
rounds, Love, Chamblee and McCarron were atop the leader board when
play was stopped because of darkness. First-round play will resume
at 8:15 Friday morning. Twelve players were unable to finish the
first round, including Nick Price, who was three under par through
17 holes. Meanwhile, seven players were at 70, just one stroke off
the lead - defending champion Mark O'Meara, Justin Leonard, Jose
Maria Olazabal, Jeff Sluman, Lee Janzen Andrew Magee and Colin
Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   While Love and Price are tested veterans, sitting atop the
leader board at the Masters was new territory for Chamblee and
McCarron. Chamblee is playing in his first Masters, but he handled
his first round like a relaxed tourist, soaking up the atmosphere
and hitting superb shots along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard horror stories about how much the course changed from
practice rounds to tournament rounds, so I didn't know what to
expect,'' said Chamblee, a 36-year-old tour veteran who won his
first event at last year's Greater Vancouver Open. ``I didn't know
how I was going to handle the first day.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee handled it just fine. He laughed about his first visit
to the course on Saturday, when he drove down Magnolia Lane for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up on Washington Street and almost went past the
entrance,'' Chamblee said. ``I had my PGA money clip and started to
show the guy. He said, `I don't need to see that.' He didn't ask
for ID. I thought, `Man, I'm going to ask my buddies to give that a
shot.'''
</P>
<P>
   Love and Price do not need identification at Augusta, but
neither player has ever won the Masters. Love has come close,
finishing second to Ben Crenshaw in 1995. But after winning the
Professional Golfers Association Championship in 1997, Love
faltered in majors last year, including a tie for 33d at last
year's Masters. Love came into this season determined to be a
factor in majors again. Thursday was a good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was especially anxious for this one,'' said Love, who shot a
37 on the front nine, then recovered to shoot 32 on the back, with
birdies at No. 10, No. 11, No. 16 and No. 17. ``I haven't been
playing as well as I would like, but there's a lot of reasons. We
could talk about it for a long, long time. But I do feel like I
should win more. But I bet there's 100 guys who feel they should
win more, too.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron, whose last victory was at the 1997 BellSouth Classic,
is only in the field because he finished 16th at Augusta last year,
and the top 24 finishers earn spots for the following year. But
something about the Masters brings out the best in McCarron, whose
worst finish in three starts is a tie for 30th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a mystical place for me,'' said McCarron, a
33-year-old native of California, who took advantage of his length
off the tee to make five birdies, offset by two bogeys. ``For some
reason, I get here and drive the ball farther and feel more
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   But some players seemed powerless to avoid making costly
mistakes, including Woods, who made a triple-bogey 8 at the par-5
No. 8. The rough made it harder to spin some shots into the green,
but the famous ultra-fast greens at Augusta were the major problem,
coupled with difficult pin placements that made it dangerous for
players to attack.
</P>
<P>
   The back nine was particularly treacherous. Phil Mickelson, who
was two under par through 12 holes, hit into the pond at No. 15,
which led to a double-bogey, followed by bogeys at No. 17 and No.
18 that left him with a bitter 74. Even Duval, the world's
top-ranked player and pre-tournament favorite with four victories
this year, was not immune. After a bogey at No. 12, he pulled his
tee shot at No. 13 into the creek, then after the rain delay, he
missed a putt for par at No. 13, followed by another bogey at No.
14. A great approach shot at No. 17 led to an easy birdie putt that
seemed to get Duval back on track, and he will finish No. 18 on
Friday, followed by a second round that promises to be interesting,
with so many top players near the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are an awful lot of good players out there apart from
Duval and Woods, and they know that as well,'' said Montgomerie, an
excellent player still in search of his first major. ``It will be
interesting to see who's up there at the end. Very interesting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
