<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1269 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKET-RIDES-HNS &LR;      04-08 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKET-RIDES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR PASSENGER ROCKET SPUTTERS &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By MARK CARREAU 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A businessman has given up a two-year effort to offer
the first commercial spaceflights aboard a passenger rocket
designed to be launched from Gulf waters off Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   The bid included creation of a Civilian Astronauts Corps whose
members would pay $100 each and could then purchase rides on the
proposed six-passenger rocket for $5,500. Plans for the first
flight of what came to be billed the Mayflower expedition slipped
from July 4, to October to early next year as efforts to raise
funds to build the rocket through advanced ticket sales and
advertising flagged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've decided to close things up. It just wasn't working,''
Harry Dace, director of the Civilian Astronauts Corps, said
Thursday. ``We just simply were not getting enough participants and
enough responses from potential advertisers to keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, he began returning the nearly $200,000 collected
from 62 potential passengers and placed in an escrow account, Dace
said. Some had paid all and some only part of their $5,500. He's
also returning $12,000 in membership dues collected from 120 people
who joined the civilian astronauts but had not pre-purchased a
seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is getting every penny back,'' Dace said.
</P>
<P>
   Dace recruited Jim Akkerman, a retired NASA propulsion and space
systems engineer, to design a passenger rocket through a company
called Advent Launch Services. When they unveiled their plan in
early 1997, they envisioned development costs of $8 million to $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   Dace planned to raise the funds for a seven-story, reusable
rocket fueled by natural gas and liquid oxygen through the sale of
2,000 memberships in their astronaut corps with passenger
privileges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the idea was so good that people would love it and
come running to jump on board,'' Dace lamented. ``How wrong we
were.''
</P>
<P>
   The project received prominent news coverage in Houston, and
ultimately was featured in national and overseas stories. Though
meager, the passenger pool included adventurous souls from a dozen
countries, including Sri Lanka, New Zealand and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The two men believed they could raise the funding they needed in
18 months, then spend another year producing and testing their
rocket. But no hardware was ever fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   Their plan was to duplicate for civilians what the late Alan
Shepard, America's first space traveler, did in 1961. Shepard's
Mercury capsule soared to an altitude of 115 miles atop a Redstone
rocket before separating and parachuting to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Dace hoped the plan would capture the $10 million X Prize, an
international competition intended to foster space travel and
tourism. The prize will go to the first private citizens who manage
to launch three passengers to an altitude of at least 62 miles and
repeat the feat within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been as excited about a program as I was about
this. I've been running on adrenaline for two years,'' Dace said.
``I've done everything possible to make this work, but it's not in
the cards.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
