<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGIA-JUDGES-ART-NY     04-08 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-JUDGES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA GETTING READY TO REPLACE MOST OF ITS JUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBILISI, Georgia _ In one of the most sweeping attacks on
corruption in the former Soviet Union, most of Georgia's judges are
to be forcibly retired next month and replaced by new ones chosen
by competitive examination.
</P>
<P>
   Like many former Soviet republics, Georgia is plagued by
corruption, which has crippled attempts at political change and led
to widespread complaints that things were better under Communism.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers who support President Eduard Shevardnadze fear that
this resentment could lead to gains for pro-Communist parties in
parliamentary elections set for November.
</P>
<P>
   So they have taken a series of radical measures. In December
they hired an American company to distribute electric power here in
the capital, taking over from a state agency widely viewed as
corrupt. They plan to turn the tasks of the customs service,
traditionally a rich source of bribes and kickbacks, over to a
foreign company. All senior officials have been required to file
declarations of their net worth.
</P>
<P>
   But none of these steps is as potentially important as the move
on the judiciary. Most of the country's nearly 350 judges were
named in the Communist era. Few have a grasp of new legal codes
modeled after those in the United States and Europe; all are widely
seen as part of a system ruled by favoritism and payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a new commercial code, new civil procedure laws, new
criminal laws, new tax laws and a whole new structure for our legal
system,'' said the minister of justice, Lado Chanturio, a former
law professor whom Shevardnadze appointed last year to direct the
overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't put this system into effect with judges who are in
many cases ignorant and corrupt. Our new judges will be educated
and qualified, which is something very new and unusual in this part
of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the government invited lawyers who aspired to judicial
careers to take an examination composed of essay and
multiple-choice questions. It was drawn up with the help of the
American Bar Association, printed in California and shipped to
Tbilisi in a German diplomatic pouch to assure security.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 lawyers took the exam, and 270, many in their
early 30s, passed. Most sitting judges either refused or failed the
exam.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the 270 new judges, along with several dozen
incumbents who passed, took their oaths of office and a second oath
pledging never to take a bribe. And Mikhail Saakashvili, the former
New York lawyer turned majority leader of the Georgian Parliament,
who helped design the new system, said that the judges' salaries,
which start at about $350 a month, will soon be tripled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to create an island of totally uncorrupted
people who can serve as an example to all of society,'' Saakashvili
said. ``Even before the new system goes into effect, we can see
that it's working, because lots of people are not going to court
and waiting for the new judges to take office.''
</P>
<P>
   The new judges are to begin work on May 15, but some outgoing
judges say they will refuse to vacate their offices. Several
citizens' groups, however, have threatened to physically remove
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecutors will be our next target,'' Saakashvili said.
``They're already organizing resistance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
