<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/08/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) MINOR LANE HEIGHTS, Ky. -- April 8, 1999 --
KY-AIRPORT-RELOCATE-2, 4-08 -- Mayor Fred Williams of Minor Lane
Heights on the 287-acre site where residents will move into new
houses over the next few years. To honor the residents' request to
stay together, Louisville airport authorities set up a special
program with a $10 million grant, which the airport matched, to
help pay for a new site near the existing city. (Mark Lyons/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) MINOR LANE HEIGHTS, Ky. -- April 8, 1999 --
KY-AIRPORT-RELOCATE-1, 4-08 -- Rather than break up lifelong
friendships, residents of Minor Lane Heights told the Louisville
airport authorities that they would agree to be moved out of the
path of jet noise only if they could stay together. ``We've never
encountered this big a deal, a community making a decision to move
this way,'' says Stan Lou, an FAA official. (Mark Lyons/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) TIRANA, Albania -- April 8, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA-3,
4-08 -- The Bllacas in their tent. From left, Fatmira, her parents,
Fatime and Mehdi, her brother, Sami, her sister, Shpresa, and
grandmother Selvie. They have convinced themselves that their
displacement is transitory; within a month, they will be home, they
say, or at least back at the charred remains. (Rina Castelnuovo/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- April 8, 1999 -- RAC-KRONE-RETIRE, 4-08 --
Julie Krone, signing a whip at Aqueduct on Thursday, announced
officially that she was retiring as a jockey at the age of 35. ``I
have nothing more to prove, and, well, I don't want to get hurt
again,'' says Krone who, at 4-foot-10 and 100-pounds has won nearly
$80 million in purses and is the only woman ever to win a Triple
Crown race, the 1993 Belmont Stakes. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) DENVER -- April 8, 1999 -- HISPANIC-UNINSURED-2, 4-08 --
Some of the Hispanic uninsured in Denver seek out community health
centers like the Tepeyac Clinic, where Sylvia Garcia brings her
daughter, Darling, for a recent physical. The lack of professional
health care here sustains a thriving, informal system of
alternative care built on religion, tradition and home remedies.
Often it works. But just as often, it delays and impedes crucial
care. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) DENVER -- April 8, 1999 -- HISPANIC-UNINSURED-1, 4-08 --
Some of the Hispanic uninsured in Denver turn to folk remedies like
those sold at this specialty store. While Hispanics - 64 percent of
whom are of Mexican origin - appear to be gaining in economic and
political strength, their lack of insurance coverage and ready
access to professional care is costly in both the demands they
eventually make on emergency rooms and in public health. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- April 8, 1999 -- DEECEE-BEAVER, 4-08 --
Don't be fooled by that air of insouciance: Beavers, like this one
in the Tidal Basin on Thursday, are harming Washington's cherry
trees. Park Service officials, who originally suspected they were
dealing with one beaver, are now fairly sure there are two. ``We
got a reliable sighting this morning, two of them in the Tidal
Basin,'' says Earle Kittleman, a spokesman for the Park Service.
(Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11 --
CANBY-THEATER, 4-08 -- David Hare making his debut as a
professional actor playing himself in his own play, ``Via
Dolorosa,'' at the Booth Theater. Nothing Hare has done before
prepares you for the production and its discoveries, including the
demonstrated fact that he can be such seriously invigorating
company. But, then, there are no exact precedents for what he is
doing here. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11 --
OPERA-FLANIGAN, 4-08 -- The soprano Lauren Flanigan during
rehearsals for a new production of Richard Strauss's ``Intermezzo''
at the City Opera. Her career has been one of the most dynamic,
unpredictable and tumultuous of the last decade. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11 --
WAR-KIDS-THEATER, 4-08 -- Ken Leung in rehearsal for ``The Road
Home: Stories of Children of War,'' to be staged next week at the
Asia Society in Manhattan. The production dramatizes interviews
with survivors of war and social conflicts from Bosnia and Cambodia
to America's inner cities. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11 --
GUARE-THEATER, 4-08 -- John Guare, right, at a rehearsal of his new
play, ``Lake Hollywood,'' with the cast members Ralph Waite and
Betty Miller. In the world according to Guare, the more things
change, the more they, well, don't change. ``The person I was 40
years ago, I am still today,'' says the 61-year-old playwright.
(Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SHIMLA, India -- April 8, 1999 -- INDIA-LOVERS-2, 4-08
-- Reshma, left, the mother of the slain man, and Gansahi, the
mother of his lover. Desh Raj, 23, was beaten to death by the
girl's family, along his lover, 17-year-old Nirmala, for breaking a
local marriage taboo that a husband and wife must come from
different villages. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) SHIMLA, India -- April 8, 1999 -- INDIA-LOVERS-1, 4-08
-- Since his son, Desh Raj, was slain, Mawasi Ram, who is nearly
blind, has taken to sitting at the spot where the killing took
place and blood is still on the wall. Desh Raj, 23, was beaten to
death, along his lover, 17-year-old Nirmala, for breaking a local
marriage taboo that a husband and wife must come from different
villages. (Barry Bearak/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BOJANE, Macedonia -- April 8, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-2, 4-08 -- Ethnic Albanian refugee women from
Kosovo in a Macedonian refugee camp - which they are not allowed to
leave - in the mountains on Thursday. The Kosovo Liberation Army,
guerrillas that have been waging a war of independence for the
Serbian province, told foreign military authorities Thursday that
they have been hit hard and that Serbian forces have pushed them
into the hills. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) STANKOVEC, Macedonia -- April 8, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-1, 4-08 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo
push and shove each other in an attempt to officially register with
camp authorities. Even as the Yugoslav leadership announced that
separatist guerrillas in Kosovo were defeated, and peace was being
restored to the southern Serbian province, the Kosovo Liberation
Army reported heavy combat in several areas. (Alan Chin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) TIRANA, Albania -- April 8, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA-2,
4-08 -- A bundle of blankets being unloaded Thursday in Tirana from
a Boeing 747 by workers for Virgin Atlantic Airlines, who are
assisting in the relief efforts for the masses of ethnic Albanian
refugees fleeing Kosovo. Virgin delivered two planes full of
blankets and kitchen kits. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KUKES, Albania -- April 8, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA-1,
4-08 -- An aerial view of ethnic Albanian refugees receiving goods
from a relief truck Thursday. Although the crowds have lessened,
those in Kukes seem to be settling in with hopes of returning to
their homes in Kosovo. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) APPLE VALLEY, Minn. -- April 8, 1999 -- POEM-AUTO, 4-08
-- Students wax poetic at Greenleaf Elementary School in Apple
Valley. The Catch the Poetry Bug Campaign is sending three VW
Beetles to 30 schools in April, each with about 1,500 words on
magnetic stickers, like refrigerator magnets, that can be arranged
to make poems. Todd Boss, a spokesman for the campaign, says the
poetry bug is ``a virus for learning the language arts.'' (Steve
Woit/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- April 8, 1999 -- CHINA-U.S., 04-8 --
President Clinton and Prime Minister Zhu Rongji of China during a
formal welcoming ceremony at the White House on Thursday. The two
leaders held wide-ranging talks aimed at repairing strained
U.S.-China relations. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BOSTON -- April 8, 1999 -- BOSTON-TRAILS-2, 4-08 --
Boarding the trolley that goes on the Literary Trail of Greater
Boston. Modeled in many ways on the city's venerable Freedom Trail,
a walking tour of notable American Revolution sites like Bunker
Hill, the literary trail is also the first creation of the Boston
History Collaborative, an alliance of historians, tourism
professionals, business people and government officials. (Michael
Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- April 8, 1999 -- BOSTON-TRAILS-1, 4-08 -- Jim
Feeney, a librarian at the Boston Athenaeum, speaking to visitors
on a tour led by the Literary Trail of Greater Boston. The tour
visits sites in the Boston area associated with New England
writers. But it is important to remember that it is a work in
progress, not yet subject to easy description or judgment. (Michael
Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- April 8, 1999 -- ICEMAN-THEATER-REVIEW-2,
4-08 -- Robert Sean Leonard, left, as Don Parritt, and Tim
Pigott-Smith as Larry Slade in the new revival of ``The Iceman
Cometh,'' which opened Thursday night at the Brooks Atkinson
Theater. The finest achievement of this slightly rough but always
engrossing production is its complete evocation of the appeal of
its characters' pipe dreams, of illusions nourished and sustained
by alcohol. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 8, 1999 -- ICEMAN-THEATER-REVIEW-1,
4-08 -- Kevin Spacey, foreground at left, as Hickey, and James
Hazeldine as Harry Hope in the new revival of ``The Iceman
Cometh,'' which opened Thursday night at the Brooks Atkinson
Theater. Hickey is a preacher of the gospel of self-knowledge,
given shimmering, scalpel-edged life by Spacey, who turns everyone
he touches from a fluttering ghost into a truly dead soul. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 8, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 4-08 -- Jim
Norton as the feisty character Jack in ``The Weir.'' Norton says he
had found inspiration for the role in memories of his Irish uncles
and friends. In fact, a photograph hanging on the wall of the set
is of his grandparents and his uncle. ``Whenever I get nervous, I
look over at that picture,'' says Norton, 60. ``Compared to those
people, I have it easy.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ATLANTA -- April 8, 1999 -- DOG-BAKERIES-COX, 04-08 --
Flynn, a 10-month old Soft Coat Terrier, chooses his own ``Bake and
Fetch'' cookies at the Three Dog Bakery, while his master, Jeff
Abeson, gives him a boost. Three Dog Bakery is one of a growing
number of treateries in Atlanta and elsewhere that cater solely to
dogs. (Renee Hannans/Atlanta Journal-Consitution Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MEXICO CITY -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11
-- MEXICO-UTILITY-2-COX, 04-08 -- Like countless other street
merchants, tropical fish vendor Miguel Morales carries his own
cables (called ``diablitos,'' or little devils) so he can siphon
electricity directly from transformers. Morales also taps into
homes and pays a fee to residents so that he can run his fish tank.
(Susan Ferris/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MEXICO CITY -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11
-- MEXICO-UTILITY-1-COX, 04-08 -- A household electrical plug on a
Mexico City utility pole illustrates the extent of this country's
often jury-rigged electrical service. For a fee, which was probably
pocketed, utility workers installed this plug so street vendors
could have access to electricity. (Susan Ferris/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ROSSLYN, Va. -- April 8, 1999 -- WOMAN-EDITOR-COX, 03-29
-- On May 1, Karen Jurgensen will replace the retiring David
Mazzarella as editor of USA Today. ``I'm not out to make this a
woman's newspaper,'' says the soft-spoken Ms. Jurgensen. ``I hope
that everybody will pick up the paper and think it's relevant to
their lives.'' (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HAMBURG, Germany -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SAT. APRIL
10 -- MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANT-1-COX, 04-08 -- Corinna Meyer-Esche and
her daughter Antonia, 7, share a moment during Sunday Mass at St.
Michael's church. Corinna has been a member for 10 years and
Antonia was baptized there. ``The Michel,'' as Hamburgers
affectionately call it, is the most famous of the churches whose
towers define the skyline of the city. (Jean Shifrin/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BERLIN -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SAT. APRIL 10 --
MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANT-1-COX, 04-08 -- A man fishes in the off a
bridge In the shadow of the Berliner Dom. The stained glass windows
that were destroyed during WWII have recently been replaced.
Described by a guidebook as an ``ostentatious symbol of monarchical
power,'' the structure was completed in 1905 as the cathedral of
the last German emperor, William II. (Jean Shifrin/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WITTENBERG, Germany -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SAT.
APRIL 10 -- MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN-3-COX, 04-08 -- One of Wittenberg's
signature monuments is a statue of Martin Luther, the father of the
Protestant Reformation. Many hope that Luther's heritage will
transform this village on the northern bank of the River Elbe into
a destination for tourists, pilgrims and scholars interested in
Protestant history. (Jean Shifrin/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BERLIN -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SAT. APRIL 10 --
MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN-2-COX, 04-08 -- The Rev. Uwe Hollm, 68, is a
retired administrator of the state church in Berlin. A Hitler youth
from age 9, he was devastated when he learned of Adolf Hitler's
suicide and further disturbed when he began to realize the horrors
of the Holocaust. He associated himself with Christianity because
``I saw a living, vibrant community of Christian people,'' he says.
(Jean Shifrin/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WITTENBERG, Germany -- April 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SAT.
APRIL 10 -- MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN-1-COX, 04-08 -- The twin towers of
the Protestant Parish Church of St. Mary dominate the skyline of
Wittenberg. Martin Luther often gave sermons in this, his favorite
church. (Jean Shifrin/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
