<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1273 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     04-08 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOU'VE HAD ENOUGH OF THE TRUTH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Try to answer the following False or False Quiz, as gleaned from
the Fake Facts column _ now there's a clue _ of the New York
Observer:
</P>
<P>
   _ Actress  &UR; Meryl Streep &LR;  wears a men's size 14 shoe. FALSE.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Yankees owner  &UR; George Steinbrenner &LR;  spent a year in
the Peace Corps, building water-supply systems in Indonesia. FALSE.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR;  is nine years older than  &UR; Rudy Giuliani &LR; .
FALSE.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phone sex is not exactly new. In the 19th century, U.S.
railroad employees were known to engage in telegraph sex. FALSE.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cottage cheese is a French invention (original name: fromage
du cottage). FALSE.
</P>
<P>
   _ The common farm chicken is native to what is now Malaysia.
FALSE.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1978, an ordinary roll of Scotch tape sold for as much as
$79. FALSE.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cruise ships are the most dangerous form of travel. FALSE.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Paul Newman &LR;  has donated $250,000 to Catholic Relief Services
to help refugees from Kosovo, reports the New York Daily News, and
 &UR; Roberto Benigni &LR;  is said to be helping to pay for a shelter for
Albanians in Bari, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ernestine Schlant Bradley &LR; , a professor and teacher of modern
German literature at Montclair State College in New Jersey, will
lecture Monday night at the Jung Institute in San Francisco on
``The Language of Silence: West German Literature and the
Holocaust,'' which is the subject of her new book. The reason for
this rather scholarly item is that the scholar is the wife of  &UR; Bill
Bradley &LR; , the tall guy who may be running for president.
</P>
<P>
   _ California Lawyer reports that plaintiffs and defendants on
the ``Judge Judy'' show are guaranteed, before they agree to go on,
that no matter what the judge rules, ``the show will pay the
loser's judgment cost, to a maximum of $5,000.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ewan McGregor &LR;  is ``the only name mentioned'' to play
 &UR; Michael Caine &LR; 's role in a remake of ``Alfie,'' says the Express of
London.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE ULTIMATE INSIDER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dominick Dunne &LR; , Vanity Fair's man inside every important place
_ Hollywood, Fifth Avenue, Washington _ writes in the latest issue
about his many links with people brushed by the
 &UR; Lewinsky &LR;  scandal, and all the dinner parties he attended with
them. He was steered around Washington, he writes, by  &UR; Dee Dee &LR; 
 &UR; Myers &LR; , former Clinton press secretary and Lewinsky commentator for
`` &UR; Larry King &LR;  Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Would you like to have dinner with  &UR; Jamie Rubin &LR;  of the State
Department?' Dee Dee asked,'' he writes. ```He's  &UR; Madeleine &LR; 
 &UR; Albright &LR; 's assistant, and he's married to  &UR; Christiane Amanpour &LR;  of
CNN.' Sure, I said. We ordered ostrich, at Jamie's suggestion.
Right from the start, I had a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THOSE ADORABLE YORKIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Duchess of York &LR;  is going to be the face of Wedgwood in the
United States, according to reports in London newspapers. She won't
appear in British ads for the company because that might anger the
royal family.
</P>
<P>
   The duchess will continue her activities for Weight Watchers,
logically linked to her new job as purveyor of plates.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile,  &UR; Prince Andrew &LR; , the Duke of York, has begun Royal
Insight, a monthly online magazine to be found at www.royal.gov.uk,
the royal Web site. Among its features is a  &LR; q &LR; uestion-and- &LR; a &LR; nswer
section that solicits questions and shares the answers to past
ones.
</P>
<P>
   For example: Does the queen watch TV? ``Yes,'' says this
informative site, ``as do other members of the Royal Family _ it is
an important way of keeping in touch with current affairs and other
subjects. People often wonder whether The Queen has a favourite
television programme. This is difficult to answer as it would be
unfair to promote any particular programme or television channel,
by singling out The Queen's personal choices.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can have a straight-on relationship with the average woman
on the street here. No one's mad at me and no one wants what I've
got.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sharon Stone on the benefits of living in San Francisco,
gleaned by Jeannie Matteucci from W.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
