<HEADER>
A1281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORMORANT-KILLERS-700     04-08 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORMORANT-KILLERS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
9 MEN PLEAD GUILTY TO KILLING HUNDREDS OF BIRDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)   By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine men from sport-fishing communities along the eastern shore
of Lake Ontario pleaded guilty Thursday to charges stemming from
killing more than 1,000 federally protected birds last summer,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings, which killed hundreds of double-crested
cormorants _ both adults and nestlings _ and left dozens of
nestlings to starve to death, are considered by the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service to be one of the largest mass killings ever of a
species protected by federal laws.
</P>
<P>
   A 10th man pleaded guilty to being an accessory to the crime by
hiding shotguns used to kill the birds. The plea agreements,
negotiated over the last few weeks, were entered in U.S. District
Court in Syracuse, said Thomas J. Maroney, the U.S. attorney for
the Northern District of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The five men who pleaded guilty to the most serious charges
agreed to serve six months of home confinement, monitored with
electronic ankle bracelets. They each agreed to pay a $2,500 fine
and to contribute $5,000 to the National Fish and Wildlife
Foundation, a private group, which will use the money to restore
wetlands around Lake Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   But several of the men, who are professional fishing guides,
have said all along that they believed they were justified in
shooting the fish-eating birds to save their livelihood. They feel
vindicated, they say, by the state's recent decision to cull the
cormorant flock to protect sport fish.
</P>
<P>
   James R. McGraw, a defense lawyer in the case, said the state
plans proved that the killing of the birds was appropriate. Several
of the defendants were reached by telephone, but declined to be
interviewed until their final sentences are handed down in August.
</P>
<P>
   The cormorants are not endangered, but are protected by the
81-year-old Migratory Bird Treaty Act, which prohibits hundreds of
species that migrate across international borders from being killed
or harassed.
</P>
<P>
   Their numbers have risen sharply in recent decades, and the
birds, which can each gulp several pounds of fish a day, are
considered pests by anglers in the Great Lakes and catfish farmers
in their winter range along the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Before the shootings last year, several of the defendants in the
case had threatened to cull a fast-growing colony of the birds on
Little Galloo Island, which is about five miles from Henderson, a
lakeside town where dozens of charter boats dock and eight of the
10 defendants live.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the community blamed the cormorants for a recent
sharp decline in stocks of smallmouth bass, a popular game fish.
The economy of Henderson, which is largely built on bass fishing by
tourists, has seen a simultaneous downturn, as anglers have headed
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   A study released in December by New York environmental
scientists confirmed a link between the growth in the cormorant
colony and falling fish stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors and federal and state wildlife officials said
Thursday that there was no excuse for the outburst of violence
against the birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vigilantism, and especially this kind of cruel killing by
individuals, has no place in resolving a complex population
issue,'' said Craig A. Benedict, an assistant U.S. attorney who
helped prosecute the case.
</P>
<P>
   The pleas filed in court described the systematic nature of the
shootings: On July 27, the five men facing the most serious
punishments, David McCrea, Ronald Ditch, Mitchell Franz, Louis Cook
and John Kabot, took McCrea's boat to the island, where they split
into groups and began shooting birds from the boat and the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Ditch and McCrea are guides whose families have made a living
from sport fishing for several generations. Cook owns a marina.
</P>
<P>
   After the July 27 shooting, according to the plea agreements,
the men handed their shotguns to Rex Allen, who was in another boat
and who did not shoot any birds. Several of the guns were later
hidden by another man, Angelo Aversa.
</P>
<P>
   The mass shooting was discovered when state biologists visited
the island two days later as part of a continuing study of the
birds' diet. They found dozens of fledglings starving to death,
sitting among piles of carcasses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the same plea agreement, Aversa and Ditch's three sons _
Andrew, David and Thomas _ admitted to shooting cormorants in
separate incidents last year along with the other five men. They
have agreed to serve three months of home confinement and pay
smaller fines. Allen, who never shot at the birds, will pay a fine
and be placed on probation.
</P>
<P>
   McGraw, a lawyer for Ditch and his sons, said they stood by
their actions, but were willing to accept punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they got involved, they knew there was going to be a
consequence,'' McGraw said. ``They weighed the good and the bad and
decided it was appropriate to do. When the bureaucracy sits back
and lets a community die and an industry die, I don't think that's
vigilantism.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Department of Environmental Conservation is
planning to go ahead with its own culling of the Little Galloo
Island colony, under a permit that is expected to be issued by
federal wildlife officials in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   State biologists plan to trap and kill 300 adult birds and dip
the cormorants' eggs in mineral oil and return them to nests. This
practice suffocates the embryos, but the parent birds continue to
roost and thus are not prompted to breed a second time. The goal is
to reduce the colony from 6,000 nesting pairs to about 1,500 in
five years, according to the state proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The men are to be sentenced Aug. 11 by Magistrate Judge Gary L.
Sharpe, and will not be confined to their homes until September.
They are not prohibited from fishing on the lake this summer, said
Benedict, the assistant U.S. attorney.
</P>
</TEXT>
