<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BLUEGRASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODDSMAKER HAS A FIELD DAY FOR THE BLUE GRASS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Fla., La., Dubai)   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ The 75th running of the Blue Grass Stakes, the
Eastern finals for the Kentucky Derby, drew one of its most closely
matched fields Thursday when eight colts were entered led by
Wondertross, Vicar and Cat Thief.
</P>
<P>
   They were so close that five of the eight horses were rated at
odds between 5-2 and 9-2 in the early line set by Mike Battaglia,
the oddsmaker at Keeneland Race Course. They will run a mile and
one-eighth for a purse of $750,000 and a chance to advance to the
Kentucky Derby three weeks later against the best in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Grass will be the centerpiece of a racing tripleheader
on Saturday, with 26 horses competing in three stakes at three
tracks: eight in Kentucky in the Blue Grass, 11 in the Wood
Memorial at Aqueduct in New York and seven in the Arkansas Derby at
Oaklawn Park. The best of the bunch will move on to Churchill Downs
to contest the Kentucky Derby on May 1 against other prime
3-year-olds, led by General Challenge and Prime Timber, who ran
first and second in the Santa Anita Derby last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be favored, but it doesn't put you in the
winner's circle,'' said Jerry Bailey, the leading jockey in the
country and the rider of Wondertross. ``He made a tremendous effort
in the Florida Derby, made up 15 lengths and lost by a nose. But
that's Nick Zito's style. He keeps improving them up to the
Kentucky Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito, the winner of the Kentucky Derby in 1991 with Strike the
Gold and in 1994 with Go for Gin, observed that ``horses seem to
thrive in Kentucky in the springtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Wondertross, he said: ``His coat is shiny. He seems happy.
He's a great horse. But Vicar beat him in the Florida Derby by a
nose, and Vicar can go forward, too. My hope is that Wondertross
stays the same as he is now, and he'll be at his peak for the
Kentucky Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``horses don't know the odds.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds were so close on the morning line that fractions made
the difference. Wondertross, a son of Chief's Crown and owned by
William J. Condren and George Steinbrenner, was made the favorite
at 5-2. But on his mathematical heels at 3-1 was Vicar, who nosed
him out in the Florida Derby. Cat Thief, third in the Florida
Derby, and Menifee were at 4-1, with Lemon Drop Kid at 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberlite Pipe, who took the Louisiana Derby last month, and
Pineaff, who outran Menifee in the Tampa Bay Derby two weeks ago,
were both quoted at 15-1. At 30-1 is Prado's Landing, the first
arrival from the stable of horses owned by Sheik Mohammed
al-Maktoum of Dubai on the Persian Gulf. If Prado's Landing were to
run a strong race, he would lend instant credibility to his Dubai
stablemates, Worldly Manner and Aljabr, who are booked into the
Kentucky Derby without a prep race.
</P>
<P>
   In the draw for the Blue Grass, not much importance was being
placed on geography. Pineaff drew the rail with Vicar to his
immediate right. In the middle came Kimberlite Pipe in the No. 3
slot, then Prado's Landing and Lemon Drop Kid. On the outside, Cat
Thief will start in the No. 6 hole in the gate with Wondertross in
No. 7 and Menifee in the last stall.
</P>
<P>
   As for East-West rivalry, D. Wayne Lukas has cast a vote for Cat
Thief, a son of Storm Cat, who has been running second or third in
the major Florida stakes recently and has done everything except
win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
