<HEADER>
A1289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-ANALYSIS09-     04-08 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-ANALYSIS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Researcher: As growth rises along Florida cost, so will costs of
hurricane damage
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Andrew was in living color.
</P>
<P>
   The great storms from earlier this century are found only in
fading snapshots, fading clippings, the fading memories of elderly
survivors from a more sparsely developed Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But if those storms were to strike today, they would hammer a
Florida of 15 million people, gleaming megalopolises and coastlines
packed shoulder-to-shoulder with luxury high-rises.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusting for how Florida has changed, those storms would do
damage on the order of Hurricane Andrew, an unnerving prospect for
the future, hurricane researcher Christopher W. Landsea told the
National Hurricane Conference on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers studied the economic impact of the century's most
ferocious storms as if they had hit the United States today.
Adjusting for inflation, growth and increased property values, they
found that seven of the 11 costliest storms and 13 of the top 30
were storms that hit Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list: the great 1926 storm, which would cause an
estimated $80 billion in damage today. It was almost as strong as
Andrew and as big as Hugo. And unlike Andrew, which made landfall
in Homestead, the 1926 hurricane hit downtown Miami head-on.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew was second. It cost $26 billion when it hit in 1992. Just
seven years later, its impact would be $36 billion, the study
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The 1928 hurricane, which drowned up to 3,000 in the Glades, was
ranked seventh, at $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Colorado State University hurricane soothsayer
William Gray on Wednesday updated his annual forecast by saying
he'll stick to his December prediction of 14 named storms _
tropical storms or hurricanes _ with nine of those becoming
hurricanes, and four becoming major hurricanes, with winds of more
than 111 mph. Gray never says where or whether storms will strike
land, although he has said the odds of a hurricane hitting the U.S.
East Coast, including all of Florida, is three times above normal
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing awareness and preparation, better building codes and
the advent of mass communications have dropped hurricane deaths
from thousands per year at the turn of the century to 100 a year
now, but property damages have risen sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, people continue to migrate to America's coastline,
especially Florida's, Landsea told weather researchers and
emergency managers.
</P>
<P>
   Applying his formula to history, Landsea contended the United
States has a one-in-six chance of suffering a storm with more than
$10 billion in damages, and every year, ``the stakes rise due to
inexorable coastal population growth and development.''
</P>
<P>
   Already about 110 million people _ nearly half of all Americans
_ live in a 5-mile-wide coastal strip that accounts for only 10
percent of the nation's mass. It's expected to rise to
three-fourths of Americans during the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   More people live in Miami-Dade and Broward counties, according
to the 1990 census, than lived in all 109 coastal counties from
Texas to Virginia in 1930, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Major hurricanes make up only one-fifth of all tropical storms
but account for 85 percent of the damage. And while peninsular
Florida experienced seven major hurricanes from 1944 to 1950 and
only three since, it is the increasingly-valuable property in their
path that will mean more costly storms in the future, Landsea said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are causing hurricane disasters,'' he said. ``It is only a
matter of time before the nation experiences a $50 billion or
greater storm, with multibillion-dollar losses becoming more
frequent.''
</P>
<P>
   Landsea, a hurricane researcher at the South Florida-based
Hurricane Research Division of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, parent of the National Weather Service and the
National Hurricane Center, conducted his research with Roger A.
Pielke Jr. of the National Center for Atmospheric Research in
Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
