<HEADER>
A1302 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATHOME-SFCHRON &LR;      04-08 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHOME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AT&AMP;T Grasp on AtHome Slips a Bit
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
AT&AMP;T Corp. will lose a bit of control over Redwood City's AtHome
Corp. because it failed to sign up enough customers for AtHome's
high-speed Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   AtHome, which provides fast Internet connections over cable TV
lines, said yesterday that AT&AMP;T will no longer be able to control
decisions made by AtHome's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T acquired a 71 percent voting stake in AtHome when it bought
TCI, the cable company that originally had the deal with AtHome.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has three seats on AtHome's board of directors. Until now,
the 11-member board needed only three votes to take any action.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the board will require a majority of votes before
taking any action, which dilutes AT&AMP;T's power.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, &UR;  &LR; Cox Communications, Comcast Corp. and Cablevision Systems
Corp. _ four of the largest U.S. cable TV companies _ have a stake
in AtHome and agreements to sell AtHome's Internet service to their
cable customers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of those agreements, AtHome included a clause saying
that if AT&AMP;T's TCI subsidiary did not sign up a certain number of
customers by June 4, 1999, the other cable partners could drop
AtHome as their exclusive Internet access provider.
</P>
<P>
   Since AT&AMP;T does not expect to sign up enough subscribers _ the
number was not disclosed _ Cox, Comcast and Cablevision could drop
AtHome altogether and sell another company's Internet access
product to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox and Comcast agreed not to end their exclusivity
agreements with AtHome &UR;  &LR; in exchange for AT&AMP;T giving up some of its
hold over the AtHome board.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission yesterday, AT&AMP;T said AtHome's board could not take any
action without the approval of Comcast or Cox. AT&AMP;T also agreed to
increase its target subscriber levels to an undisclosed number.
</P>
<P>
   AtHome has 331,000 subscribers across the country, said AtHome
spokesman Matt Wolfram said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Rimer, who follows AtHome for Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, said
TCI's failure to attract the agreed-upon number of customers was
not a surprise. ``One of the reasons that TCI sold itself to AT&AMP;T
was because it could leverage the deep pockets of AT&AMP;T to grow at a
much more accelerated level than it could as an independent
company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects the subscriber levels to grow now that AT&AMP;T
has assumed control of the cable company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIRCUS-ANIMAL-TRAINER     04-08 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-ANIMAL-TRAINER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL BRINGING OUT THE ANIMAL, AND ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Fla.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There once was a time that children followed the
circus dancing when it came to town. But these days the children
are more likely to be given coloring books by the animal rights
advocates that feature a circus elephant weeping, and the trainer
might be singled out on a Web site for abuse. This drives Gunther
Gebel-Williams, the legendary animal trainer, nominally retired,
nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the allegation that a baby elephant died
over a year ago at Ringling Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey because it
was forced to perform when it was sick. The circus ultimately
settled with the government, but Gebel-Williams, now 64, a part
owner, says they were simply trying to do right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not let a 2-year-old elephant stay in back, away from
the other elephants, when he doesn't feel good,'' says the
German-born trainer, in heavily accented English. ``A 2-year-old
elephant is a child. The performing, it was just pushing around a
ball. Still to this day I don't know why the elephant died.''
</P>
<P>
   When he starred in the center ring of the Ringling show,
strutting with his unnatural white blond hair, his beloved leopard
Kenny (now an honored throw rug in his Florida home) in a signature
sling around his shoulders, Gebel-Williams had something that was
not touted in the posters, though the ladies didn't need a program
to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women were so good to me,'' Gebel-Williams says. ``It was
always so easy! It was a tough life for Sigrid'' _ his wife _ ``but
family was always No. 1. I never promised any of them anything.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife cannot be happy about this. ``She's not happy, but
there is only one Gunther,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He remains a physical guy. He has an arm around your shoulder
and is patting your knee moments after he meets you, which can turn
a girl's head until you realize it's the same way he pats the
elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Gebel-Williams retired from performing nine years ago. But he
still trains the animals and performs occasionally. He trains the
animals the way he always has: positive reinforcement, meat on a
stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think I hurt the animal with this?'' he says, backstage at
the Garden where the elephants are chained at the foot, knocking an
elephant's side with an elephant hook, and you realize, with some
concern, that not all the elephants are shackled.
</P>
<P>
   One, with pink speckled ears and a dusty hide, is walking
unfettered, responding to Gebel-Williams' hand signals and voice.
As Gebel-Williams stands against the elephant's front leg, she
bends her head down and wraps her trunk around him, and envelops
him in a full body hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``My lover,'' Gebel-Williams says.
</P>
<P>
   The lore of the circus is that one runs away to join it. Gunther
Gebel, raised in wartime Germany, is of the other tradition, which
was the domain of the malformed or unwanted _ he was dumped.
</P>
<P>
   His father was a carpenter who drank and beat his mother. His
mother, a seamstress, beat Gunther. When he was 13, Gunther's
mother contracted with the Circus Williams to hire him as an usher,
informing her son after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried so much,'' Gebel-Williams says. ``I never get it. My
son is 28. I look at him, I think how? I think the war did
something. I raised my family close.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child Gebel-Williams bonded with the animals. Eventually,
he took the circus' name, a marriage of sorts. He also married
Sigrid, a former model. She, their son and daughter all went into
circus work. Mark Oliver Gebel now performs his father's act.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to showtime. Mark Oliver Gebel is in the center ring with 12
Bengal tigers, inside a mesh cage, carrying two whips and a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Gebel-Williams places a small black satchel containing raw meat
outside the cage. As his son works, he rewards and distracts the
animals, reaching through the bars to pat a tiger or skewering a
piece of meat on a stick and slipping it to the animal. A few
minutes into the act he runs to the sidelines, grabs the reporter's
hand, and takes her to the side of the ring to show how his son
uses the whip only to signal.
</P>
<P>
   Now a 500-pound Bengal tiger is on its hind legs, walking
forward toward Gebel, towering over him.
</P>
<P>
   Is Gebel-Williams scared watching his son like this?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not scared,'' he says, ``but I worry. If he did something
else, if he flew planes, I couldn't be there every day, but here I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Now only one tiger is the cage. Gebel moves it onto a wide
swing, then steps behind it, the only control the leash in his
hand. Suddenly, the cage collapses, leaving the reporter, beside
Gebel-Williams, 6 feet from the tiger. The presence of a stranger
is a first and a surprise to everyone but Gebel-Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Gebel-Williams laughs, and offers the reporter a piece of raw
meat on a stick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
