<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1310 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN     04-08 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVILL FINDS NEW GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Art Nevill was tired of racing on shorter tracks at slower
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he tested a Speed Challenge Truck, built by a San
Bernardino company, at Willow Springs Raceway in Rosamond, liked
the vehicle so much that he bought one on the spot and used it to
win the series' second season championship.
</P>
<P>
   `` I wanted to go race superspeedways,'' the Acton resident
said. ``I didn't want to race just (the) Legends (class) anymore. I
wanted to go to Phoenix and to bigger road courses.''
</P>
<P>
   The 26-race series will make its 1999 debut at Irwindale
Speedway tonight, where the trucks will race the track's half-mile
oval 16 times this season. The series, which now has 24 trucks,
then moves to the Orange Show in San Bernardino on Saturday night.
Also racing tonight, starting at 7:30 p.m., will be NASCAR Late
Models, Grand American Modifieds and street stocks. On Saturday
night, starting at 7 p.m., racing will be for NASCAR Super Late
Models, Super Stocks and American Race Trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Nevill, who won the title despite being the ``Old Man'' of the
series at age 53, already has had success at Irwindale, winning the
Legends main feature last weekend. He said he hopes to win both
titles this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of devoted to racing,'' said Nevill, a two-time
Legends champion who began racing karts in the '80s, dropped out of
racing and then returned to the sport in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The Chevrolet trucks have 330-horsepower engines with 1999 S-10
bodies. The intake manifold and timing cover have been sealed to
prohibit drivers from altering the truck's power. Pre-race
inspections also prevent altering of the engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're low maintenance and if they don't break, catch on fire
or if you don't crash, they don't cost that much,'' Nevill said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevill, who averaged 92.31 mph in testing at Irwindale last
month, said the car's chassis is what makes this series so special.
He said he did so well in the session that he has yet to change the
set-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as good as any late model touring car,'' he said of the
chassis. ``It's really stable. I've had some Winston West drivers
look at the chassis and they tell me how good it is and I say, `I
agree.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nevill says he learned chassis set-up from friend Donnie Johnson
when they raced together at Saugus Speedway. He said Johnson taught
him shocks, staggering and chassis and it's a reason why he did so
well last year. He won three races and finished in the top three
most of the season. He did it without benefit of a pit crew; his
wife won't watch him race after he broke his back in a 1995 crash.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Steiner, who won the series inaugural title in '97, will
also be racing tonight after racing in a different series last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting younger drivers, but guys with experience, who
have raced midgets and modifieds,'' Nevill said. ``It's going to be
real competitive, yet, we hardly ever have any yellow flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just show up at the track by myself and say, `beat me.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
