<SLUG> BC-BBO-HANKAARON09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A long wait for a perfect hero: Hank Aaron
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like that night exactly 25 years ago, it was cloudy
with threatening rain. But it was cold at Atlanta-Fulton County
Stadium the night Hank Aaron swung his way past Babe Ruth, a cold
that had nothing to do with the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little out of sorts 25 years ago. We didn't know
what was going to happen,'' said Billye Aaron, the slugger's wife.
``And while we were anticipating the breaking of the record, it was
an odd kind of feeling of what will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's work done that night was properly _ and finally _
completed before the Atlanta Braves played Philadelphia on
Thursday. As part of the season-long anniversary salute to Aaron's
715th home run, Major League Baseball formally presented the new
Hank Aaron Award that will go annually to the game's leading
hitters. With monies raised at his birthday tribute Feb. 5, Aaron
was presented a $1 million check for his Chase the Dream
Foundation. An Atlanta crowd once more stood to cheer him.
</P>
<P>
   But far beyond the material, Aaron's reaffiliation with the game
he felt had long shunned him seemed all but complete. Following the
video tributes shown on the scoreboard, following the address by
commissioner Bud Selig and the songs sung by Kenny Rogers, Hank and
Billye Aaron took a long slow cart ride around the park. While the
public appreciation for Aaron was palpable, more subtle was Aaron's
appreciation for how different this night was from April 8, 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say I was nervous, like I am tonight,'' he recalled.
``This is tremendous to have an award named after you in
perpetuity. It's going to be around as long as baseball. When I'm
no longer here, my grandchildren and great-grandchildren can go and
remember this thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous feeling. I'm very grateful for this.''
</P>
<P>
   If it seemed that baseball was trying to make amends, it was.
Selig, the other half of a long and sincere friendship with Aaron,
has spearheaded the Aaron project after confessing to worrying
about Aaron and his legacy. There was plenty that blighted Aaron's
breaking the record _ MLB's indifference, Ruth die-hards, racist
threats _ and Selig could not explain why the game had not yet done
anything in lasting tribute to Aaron's accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the appropriate time,'' Selig said.
``Twenty-five years later, fortunately everyone is in good health.
It's something that should have happened a long time ago but didn't
happen. Should have, could have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now. And Hank can enjoy the award and the recognition.
Like a lot of things in life, I'd wished they'd had a better
experience and I wish a lot of what happened hadn't happened. It
was unexcusable and unexplainable. Baseball can only do now what it
can do. And so I'm proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The night was not lost upon the Braves, many of whom were in
diapers when Aaron went deep off Los Angeles' Al Downing. If the
game is now played before a more tolerant world, the way Aaron
endured is still an object lesson in any clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He set a standard I don't think anyone can achieve,'' said
Braves right fielder Brian Jordan, who was 7 years old the night
Ruth's record fell. ``You look back as a black baseball player now,
what he had to go through to achieve what he did _the death
threats, people not wanting to see him do it because the color of
his skin _ he blocked all that out and remained focused to achieve
what no one else in baseball accomplished. That's a role model.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cast of characters were there. Downing sat with the
dignitaries. Ralph Garr, Aaron's teammate who physically picked up
Aaron's foot and placed it on the plate as he brought No. 715 home
that night, was there. Andy Young, the man who would be mayor, was
at the pre-game press conference taking pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (former Mayor) Ivan Allen understood what bringing a
major league team here meant at the time,'' Young said. ``One of
the reasons he worked so hard to get us a stadium and a team was
that he was trying to hold Atlanta together while the rest of the
South was pulling apart. And Hank was the perfect hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron was asked about his ownership of the 755-homer record and
he replied that Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr., is a perfect candidate,
both in talent and deportment. Like it's even close. At age 29,
Griffey is still 404 short of the Hammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been mine long enough,'' Aaron said. ``I believe in
sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is just what he did Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
