u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-LEDE09-CO     04-08 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-LEDE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love joins two atop Masters
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It was a long, tiring first day at the 63rd
Masters. It began at 8 a.m. with a ceremonial first shot struck by
97-year-old Gene Sarazen and, well, it never ended.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a 1-hour, 30-minute rain delay from a late-afternoon
storm Thursday and a 96-player field already slowed down by
threesomes, 12 players must complete play today at 9 a.m. before
the start of the second round at Augusta National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   That just made Davis Love III's round all that more precious.
</P>
<P>
   With a 3-under-par 69 completed by midday, when 90-degree
temperatures and firm greens were the obstacles, Love, of Sea
Island, Ga., shared the top of the leaderboard with two other
strangers to such a lofty spot _ Scott McCarron and Brandel
Chamblee.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, after a late birdie at the 16th hole, needs only a
par at the 18th this morning to complete his 69 and join the
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everywhere you looked, there was major championship
success.
</P>
<P>
   Love, the 1995 Masters runner-up, took the 1997 PGA
Championship. Price has won two PGAs and a British Open. Among
seven players one shot off the lead at 2-under 70 were defending
champion Mark O'Meara, 1997 British Open champion Justin Leonard,
1994 Masters winner Jose Maria Olazabal and two-time U.S. Open
champion Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   McCarron tied for 10th in his first Masters in 1996, but
Chamblee has never been here before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm pleased with a 3-under start,'' said Love, who
birdied the 16th and 17th holes for a back-nine 32. ``The course
played pretty difficult. I got away with not getting anything going
on the front and then I got something going on the back. A good
start, but there's a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at 70 stood Colin Montgomerie of Scotland, Andersen
Consulting Match Play Championship runner-up Andrew Magee and Jeff
Sluman, the 1988 PGA champion.
</P>
<P>
   With a surprising first round considering his recent troubles,
Australian Greg Norman, 44, a two-time British Open champion, was
the unexpected name at 71, two strokes off the lead. He was joined
there by twice U.S. Open champion Ernie Els, who double-bogeyed the
18th hole; Steve Pate, Bob Estes, 1991 Masters winner Ian Woosnam
of Wales and 1988 champion Sandy Lyle of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good day's work,'' said Norman, who is playing with a
different shoulder than the one that missed the cut the past two
years. ``It was a fairly stable, good, solid and consistent round.
Anytime you get off to a good start, it's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Favorite David Duval, the world's No. 1 player, also is at
1-under with the 18th hole remaining after suffering bogeys on the
12th, 13th and 14th. Stewart Cink, who found the water at the 15th
hole, also is at 1-under with three holes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, the 1997 Masters champion and the favorite before
Duval won 11 of his last 34 events, settled for even-par 72 after
botching the par-5 second hole with a triple-bogey 8.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar, struggling with a virus, had a 77.
</P>
<P>
   Not very popular when the day began, the decision to use
threesomes became an even sorer subject when combined with the rain
delay. Those players able to finish had to do it in diminishing
light on greens of varying firmness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Threesomes made it all the more difficult,'' said O'Meara.
``Normally ,you cruise around here, but today with the rain you're
looking at a 6 and a half hour round. Mentally and physically, it's
taking a lot out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman missed a four-foot birdie putt at the 18th, failing to
climb within a shot of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Jumbo Ozaki, who had eagled the 10th hole to go 3-under,
finished with two straight bogeys for a 71.
</P>
<P>
   Els double-bogeyed the 18th hole to lose his chance at a share
of the lead. He drove into the fairway bunker, hit a 7-iron into
the greenside bunker, blasted our and then 3-putted from 35 feet.
</P>
<P>
   England's Nick Faldo, with three green jackets, continued his
mysterious slide with an 8-over 80.
</P>
<P>
   As the day unfolded, playing conditions changed. Depending on
the time of day, you had breezeless and hot, or breezy and cooler.
Without Thursday's rain, the greens would have been severely baked
out by today.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Couples, one of the pre-tournament favorites, managed a
2-over-par 74 and did nothing to promote confidence for a
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a long way to go tomorrow,'' Couples said. ``I putted
like a 12-handicapper. A lot was because I was just too far away
from the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   For Love, who has two seconds and a third this year on the PGA
Tour, it was a confidence-boosting beginning. The world's No. 3
player, Love said, ``It's nice to get started. After coming off the
PGA (in 1997), you think you're going to come in with a lot of
confidence and get going. But to not contend in any of them last
year, just kind of hang round in a couple of them, was kind of
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
