<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SIDEDUVAL09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval's human side: back nine
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Who was this guy, anyway? The top button of his
shirt was uncharacteristically unbuttoned long before the turn. His
sunglasses were gone by the 13th tee, just when things suddenly
grew really dark for David Duval. Yet for all his recent dominance
and seeming perfection, Duval knew this opening round of the
Masters would be nowhere near as one-sided as his past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``A round of golf doesn't involve nine holes,'' Duval said. ``It
involves both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides of David Duval were evident Thursday, including that
rarest of views: A most human side. After turning in 33, tied for
the lead at 3 under and looking every bit the most prohibitive
favorite since, well, Tiger Woods a year ago, Duval looked very
human in _ and then coming out of _ Amen Corner.
</P>
<P>
   He bogeyed No. 12. Then, after play was suspended because of
weather for 90 minutes, he bogeyed No. 13. Then, he bogeyed No. 14.
Back-to-back-to-back bogeys? When was the last time that happened?
Surely, long before Duval began ruling the game in October 1997,
when his run of 11 victories in 34 tournaments began.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, when play was suspended again, this time because
of darkness, Duval had finally righted himself with a birdie at 17.
That left him 1 under, two off the lead, with No. 18 left to be
played at 9 a.m. today before he, Nick Price and Bob Tway tee off
for the second round at 10:27.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 18 holes involved,'' said Duval, who actually had just
17 holes of involvement. ``On a course like this, you're going to
run into some bad stuff. You just try to outweigh it with some good
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The good stuff came early for Duval, who saved par on No. 1 with
a nice 15-footer, then looked like the guy who'd won two
consecutive tournaments (The Players Championship in his hometown,
then the BellSouth Classic last week at Duluth) and $2.5 million.
Duval made birdie at Nos. 2 and 3 to go 2 under. Never mind a bogey
at No. 5. Consecutive birdies at No. 7 and 8 moved him to 3 under
and into a share of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   But after starting the back side with two pars, Duval suddenly
gave the gallery a peek behind those shades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a poor decision on one hole,'' he said, ``a bad swing
on another. On 14, the wind kicked up and got us. That's the three
bogeys.''
</P>
<P>
   On No. 12, his tee shot stayed dry, but long and left of the
green. He chipped on, but short, then dropped his putter in
disbelief when a 10-footer to save par didn't drop.
</P>
<P>
   At 13, Duval snapped his drive high into a pine at the bend in
the dogleg. The ball dropped down into the creek. Duval was clearly
flustered. For nearly five minutes, he talked to an official,
gesturing toward the pines, walking back and forth. Finally, he
took a drop, hit out nicely and knocked his approach shot 9 feet
below the hole before play was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   When it resumed, Duval missed the putt for another bogey. After
a great drive on No. 14, with the wind gusting and the pines
swaying back and forth, Duval stepped away from his ball once, then
finally left it short. The ball hit the mounds on the front of the
green and rolled back off. He chipped on but barely up to the crest
of a ridge, where the ball stopped. A miss from 18 feet left Duval
with a third consecutive bogey and at even par.
</P>
<P>
   Two pars later (he just missed a 10-foot birdie at 16), Duval
finally found his form again. His approach on No. 17 stopped 3 feet
from the hole. He made the birdie, then walked back to the
clubhouse, with one hole left to finish this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard,'' Duval said of the course. ``The greens are
pretty fast, pretty firm.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the pace of play with threesomes: ``It's not exactly
quick. We expected that, but it's hard to keep your rhythm. We were
out there about four hours when the (first) horn sounded.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for finishing the first round this morning, Duval said,
``If you want to win this event, you've got to find a way to deal
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
