<HEADLINE>
GALAXY COACH DISAPPOINTED IN FAILED DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano voiced his
disappointment over the Galaxy's failure to come to terms with the
Rose Bowl and build the Los Angeles franchise a practice facility
next to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Galaxy president Tim Leiweke cancelled plans to build
the site on the stadium grounds after learning the Rose Bowl raised
its price an additional $200,000, bringing the total cost to an
estimated, $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The last two seasons the Galaxy trained either at Occidental
College or on the Rose Bowl's parking lot grass. With the season
two weeks old, Zambrano's not sure where his team will train next.
</P>
<P>
   A lingering question in Zambrano's mind is why the deal to build
the site didn't happen when money never seemed to be an issue
during the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the only thing I can think of is that maybe the fact
there is a football team coming to L.A. -- that had some impact and
made our ownership rethink certain things,'' Zambrano said. ``That
is a guess, speculation on my part. If that's not the case then for
sure our guys have been filled with broken promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this happened it was hard for me to address the guys
because it was almost like here we go again. I still think the
commitment of our ownership is strong towards getting us a
facility, but certainly now that we have this factor (of an NFL
team possibly) coming to town, I guess we can't ignore it.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Paul Caligiuri said the team was looking forward
to the new training facility after talk of the plans since October.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had been at Azusa Pacific or at Mount San Antonio
(College) like we orginally planned everything would be fine and
constantly flowing,'' Caligiuri said. ``Now this is a blow, we're
scrambling. We relied on something that was never finalized. We
heard it was getting better and better, but in reality, we're back
to square one again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) Following tonight's match the Galaxy is off for more
than a week before visiting Chicago April 17 to take on the MLS
champion Fire. Chicago swept the Galaxy in the Western Conference
finals last season.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles returns to the Rose Bowl April 24 to take on San
Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
