<HEADER>
A1317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTARCTIC-EXHIBIT-2ND     04-08 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTARCTIC-EXHIBIT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: no shelter.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crew built a leaky hut by overturning two of the boats and
laid sodden sleeping bags onto a freezing, stinking, wet bed of
stones covered with penguin guano. This wouldn't do for long. For
one thing, no one would ever find them there. Shackleton's only
option was to seek help in the third boat, which he had christened
the James Caird (after the expedition's main sponsor). The Caird's
rigging consisted of threadbare clothes and rotted bags. The crew
had a single sextant and a chronometer of unknown reliability.
</P>
<P>
   So with five men, Shackleton set sail again, this time to try to
get back to South Georgia Island, 800 miles to the east, skirting
the Drake Passage, the worst stretch of ocean anywhere. Winds gust
over 100 miles an hour. Temperatures are subzero. The Cape Horn
rollers, as they're called, swell to 100 feet and move at speeds
close to 40 knots. No one had ever done anything vaguely like this.
Since Shackleton, no one else has.
</P>
<P>
   At the museum, sure to please the crowds, is a clever video
simulation of the experience of the passage (along with the Caird
itself, freshly painted, alas, so it looks anonymous), although the
effect doesn't come close to recreating the rise and fall of the
big rollers. The museum realized that to do so would make visitors
sick.
</P>
<P>
   Every few seconds, after all, the Caird, as Shackleton recalled
in his memoir, would soar 50 feet or so, then dive headlong, the
sails going slack because the troughs were so deep, before another
giant wave loomed, threatening to drown the crew. This happened
thousands of times each day.
</P>
<P>
   The men were forced to huddle on a floor of rocks, used for
ballast, under a flimsy canvas flap in soaked reindeer sleeping
bags. The bags shed so much hair that when a man managed to fall
asleep, which was possible only from sheer exhaustion, he woke up
choking. The hair clogged the makeshift pump and spoiled the meager
rations.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly bad gale began to blow when the Caird got to sea,
and it lasted for days on end, among other things often making it
impossible for the crew to fix its position securely. If they
miscalculated their direction by a degree, they would miss South
Georgia. Then it was another 3,000 miles to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Worsley was Shackleton's captain. Fortunately he was a
genius. To read about Shackleton's expedition (the classic account
is Alfred Lansing's 1959 book, ``Endurance'') is to encounter more
than a few quiet, brave men who seem to belong to another era,
another species even. Worsley, whose memoir, ``Endurance: An Epic
of Polar Adventure,'' will be republished this month, was maybe the
most impressive. Somehow he guided the battered Caird to South
Georgia in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But their troubles still weren't over. The rocks made it nearly
impossible to land. Agonizingly close to their goal, the men
suffered through more days in a storm trying to get ashore, and at
one point they came very close to crashing into a huge cliff.
Worsley later wrote that he recalled feeling piqued when he
believed they would die off South Georgia because ``no one would
ever know we had got so far.''
</P>
<P>
   They did land. But there was yet another huge hurdle: They were
on the opposite side of the island from the whaling station and
unable to sail around to it. This side of South Georgia was
uninhabited and uncharted. They had to trek 22 miles over
unexplored glaciers and snowy mountains. No one had ever made this
trip, and all they had for equipment was a carpenter's adz and 90
feet of rope.
</P>
<P>
   To get a sense of what they accomplished, you might remember
that in 1996 a young, well-trained, well-fed team of British
marines, stationed on South Georgia on winter patrol, set out with
mountain skis, aerial maps, superlight gear and electronic
equipment to break Shackleton's record for crossing the island
overland and only barely beat his time.
</P>
<P>
   It took 36 harrowing hours on a near-suicide march before
Shackleton and his men finally straggled into Stromness, their
faces blacked with soot and hidden behind matted beards, their
bodies dead white from soaking in salt water and covered in boils.
It was May 20, 1916. Shackleton, unrecognizable, asked to see the
station manager, Thoralf Sorlle, whom he knew. It had been nearly
two years since Shackleton had left the island and, especially with
the distraction of the war, his expedition had pretty much slipped
from people's minds. Everyone assumed he was dead. One familiar
account of the meeting with Sorlle comes from a Norwegian whaler in
his broken English:
</P>
<P>
   ``Manager say, `Who the hell are you?' And terrible bearded man
say very quietly, `My name is Shackleton.' Me _ I turn away and
weep.'' The other Norwegian whalers at Stromness, who knew the
Drake Passage better than anyone, could not believe the Southern
Ocean had been crossed in the Caird. They held a dinner for the men
and silently, one by one, they lined up and shook the hands of
Shackleton and his crew. He later said it was the greatest tribute
ever paid to him.
</P>
<P>
   As for the men on Elephant Island, it took Shackleton four
desperate trips and another three months, until Aug. 30, 1916,
before he could get through the ice to retrieve them. When he first
got to Stromness, he wired the British Admiralty for a rescue ship.
But Britain was fighting a war, and the Admiralty didn't have much
sympathy for him anyway, so he was compelled to appeal to another
country for help. Chile agreed and sent a tug, the Yelcho.
</P>
<P>
   When the men spotted the boat offshore, they hurriedly tried to
hoist a flag to signal their position, but the flag got stuck half
way up the post. Shackleton was devastated. He thought it signaled
that someone had died.
</P>
<P>
   But every man survived. Shackleton wrote to his wife: ``I have
done it. Damn the Admiralty. Not a life lost and we have been
through hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley had not been on the Caird or crossed South Georgia, so
his photographs tell only part of the story, although he did take
some pictures on Elephant Island with a vest-pocket camera he had
salvaged. Mostly he recorded the experience of the Endurance and
life on the floes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
