<HEADER>
A1318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTARCTIC-EXHIBIT-3RD     04-08 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTARCTIC-EXHIBIT-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the floes.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He went to technical lengths to set up dozens of cumbersome
lights in the dark to get stunning nighttime shots of the ship's
rigging, like spun-sugar candy, against blackness. He climbed to
the crow's-nest for pictures of the Endurance casting shadows on
the icy sea, amazing images that organize and give depth to an
essentially impossible white-on-white vista by projecting the
linear geometry of the ship's mast against it. And he took
beautiful, melancholic color photographs of the ship marooned in
ice.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Alexander, who put the exhibition together and wrote
the accompanying book, describes the pictures Hurley took later in
his career as bland color postcard snaps. The photographs here have
a calm, abstract beauty. Perhaps the immensity of the subject
tempered his inclination to melodrama. He made decent portraits but
did not photograph images of individual suffering or despair.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the photographs are mostly of groups, the individuals
anonymous, reflecting the character of an expedition whose members
depended so completely on each other for their lives. We see
clothes hanging on lines to dry in the camp, and the men, like sled
dogs, hauling their boats over ice, black silhouettes against empty
whiteness. Many pictures simply show boredom and inaction, men
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The best pictures have an extraordinarily modern quality, a
reduction and irregularity of geometric forms that can even put you
in mind a bit of Calder or Ellsworth Kelly. A few photographs also
come out of Romantic landscape painting, staged but exquisite: a
stunning panorama of snowy South Georgia, for instance, that mimics
Friedrich. Worsley and another crewman are atop a cliff,
overlooking the island, with the Endurance in the harbor below.
</P>
<P>
   After the expedition, Hurley went to photograph the war at
Ypres, Belgium. He made a popular film of the Shackleton
expedition, which has recently been restored and released on video.
He spent most of the rest of his life in Australia, photographing
in the South Pacific, and died in 1962, at 76, on assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the crew enlisted immediately upon their return
to England. Having lasted two years with Shackleton, Tim McCarthy,
a seaman, was killed at his gun in the Channel a few months after
he got back. Alf Cheetham, one of the officers on the Endurance,
drowned when a German submarine torpedoed his minesweeper just
before the armistice.
</P>
<P>
   Lionel Greenstreet's war service began when the Yelcho landed in
Chile. He took command of a tug returning to Britain. He was the
last survivor of the expedition, dying in 1979, at 89, as Ms.
Alexander points out, an explorer from the era of masted ships who
lived to see the public become indifferent to moon landings.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton returned to a world that had endured too much death
and dying to glorify a frivolous adventure without reservation. He
was embraced, up to a point. But he was undeterred. He cooked up
several more wild schemes, until in 1922, back at South Georgia,
with plans to hunt for Captain Kidd's treasure, he had a heart
attack and died. He was 47.
</P>
<P>
   His wife declined an offer to have his body returned to England,
and at her request, he was buried in a small graveyard for
Norwegian whalers on South Georgia.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Endurance: Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic Expedition''
opens Saturday at the American Museum of Natural History, Central
Park West at 79th Street, (212) 769-5000, and is there through Oct.
11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
