</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-UNINSURED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANICS LAG FAR BEHIND OTHERS IN HEALTH INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to replace 5th through 7th grafs with 5 grafs rewritten for
clarity and balance.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Erica Aguilar, a Mexican-American born in Denver, is 21
years old and has three children, ages 4, 2 and 8 months. The
children have Medicaid, and for them she uses Denver's La Casa
Family Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Aguilar herself has no health insurance. She works 26
hours a week as a sales clerk at Montgomery Ward for $6.50 an hour,
and as a part-timer, she is ineligible for insurance even if she
could pay her share of the premium. Yet she earns too much to get
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   So for herself and sometimes her children, she uses home
remedies. ``I go by what my grandmother tells me,'' she said. She
douses her eyes with sugar and water to cure eye irritations. To
cure colic, she rubs the baby's stomach with warm oils.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aguilar's story is emblematic of a striking disparity in the
nation's health care. For reasons that are largely economic, but
also cultural, 34 percent of the nation's 31 million Hispanics have
no health insurance, compared with 22 percent of blacks and 12
percent of non-Hispanic whites. Overall, 43 million people in the
nation are without insurance, up from 31 million a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Hispanic people appear to be gaining in economic and
political strength, they disproportionately lack insurance coverage
and ready access to professional care. That is particularly true
for the three-quarters who are from Mexico and Central America.
Cuban-Americans tend to be older and wealthier and to have
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The social costs of the uninsured come with the dangers of
untreated contagious diseases and an eventual reliance on emergency
room care, according to the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has a vast Hispanic population, making up a quarter of
the city's half-million residents compared with 11 percent
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic residents here are mostly young and mostly from Mexico
and Central America, and as in many cities their lack of
professional health care sustains a thriving system of alternative
care built on religion, tradition and home remedies. Often it
works. But just as often, it delays and impedes crucial care.
</P>
<P>
   Health system officials and community leaders here say the
menial jobs for relatively young and uneducated Hispanic workers
make health insurance unlikely for them. But the disparity in
coverage is worsened, the officials say, by cultural and
bureaucratic barriers and a political climate that has darkened for
immigrants, both legal and illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tend to be poor,'' said Ann Zuvekas of the George
Washington University Center for Health Policy Research, the author
of several studies of minority health. ``They tend to work for
small employers, in low-wage jobs, cleaning buildings and
gardening, in car washes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are cultural differences and language barriers,'' Ms.
Zuvekas added. ``And a number are immigrants. Public policy has
been to make sure that many immigrants don't get insurance.'' Under
the overhaul of the welfare system three years ago, for example,
legal immigrants must wait five years to apply for Medicaid, the
health insurance program for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the $48 billion, 10-year program that Congress and
President Clinton enacted two years ago to expand government
insurance to all groups of poor children, little has been done to
treat the gap in the Hispanic population's coverage. ``We are being
lobbied to improve our children's care,'' said Richard Allen,
director of Colorado's Medicaid program. ``But regarding Hispanics?
No.''
</P>
<P>
   Some who do qualify for programs like Medicaid still won't
enroll for fear that doing so will encourage politicians to use
rising enrollments of immigrants to argue for slowing future
immigration, including relatives of immigrants already here
legally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're frightened,''said Dr. Richard Wright, chief executive
of Community Health Services of Denver Health, the city's nonprofit
health care system. ``They think, `If I enroll, that will work
against me as an immigrant.'''
</P>
<P>
   For most uninsured Hispanics, the disparity in coverage arises
from erosion of job-based benefits. Only half of all Hispanics are
covered through employment, compared with two-thirds of
African-Americans and three-quarters of white workers.
</P>
<P>
   When employers do offer insurance, usually asking their workers
to pay a share of the cost, Hispanic workers are the most likely to
refuse it because they earn less than other workers and have more
mouths to feed on their slimmer wages.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau says that in 1996, Hispanic men earned a
little over $16,000, about $10,000 less than non-Hispanic white
men. And 27 percent of Hispanic families have five or more members,
compared with 12 percent of other families.
</P>
<P>
   While economic reasons dominate, issues of culture also emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``People rely on faith a lot,'' said Luz Collins, who was born
in Mexico and manages the Westside Family Health Center, one of 11
Denver Health clinics. ``They wheel and deal with God. You call it
home medicine. It's our actual medicine. A lot of it's hidden
because we realize it's not accepted by the majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Some home medicine tends to be harmless, as in the case of Irene
Chavez's 2-year-old granddaughter. Recently, Ms. Chavez lovingly
displayed a framed photograph of the toddler with her deep happy
dimples and wavy black hair. ``She's a beautiful granddaughter,''
Ms. Chavez says, ``so beautiful that people just can't believe
she's real.'' The beauty, she contends, was the child's undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Whether from spite, envy or admiration, Ms. Chavez said, someone
gazed overly long at her granddaughter and in so doing marked her
with the evil eye, or ``mal de ojo.'' A day or two later the child
fell ill, with vomiting, diarrhea and a high fever. Doctors said
she had a virus. ``They said, `Stop being paranoid,''' Ms. Chavez
said. ```There's nothing wrong with her.'''
</P>
<P>
   Unconvinced, the family called in Louise, their 77-year-old
neighborhood curandera, or healer. Chanting prayers, the woman
rubbed an unbroken egg over the child, tracing signs of the cross.
Then she broke the egg, put it in a cup, placed a cross made of
twigs in the yolk, and put the cup under the head of the child's
bed. By morning the child was well. The egg, Ms. Chavez said, had
exorcised the curse.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But when such efforts fail and patients belatedly show up at
doctors' offices, says Dr. Alicia Vazquez, the primary care
physician at Denver Health's La Casa de Salute clinic, they have
been drinking cocktails of exotic herbs or using cheap,
under-the-counter prescription medicines that bodegas smuggle in
from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 32-year-old female comes in with a five-day history of sore
throat, runny nose and a cough and reports that she's been taking
an antibiotic from Mexico because that's all she could get,'' Dr.
Vazquez says.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vazquez takes a culture of the patient's mouth to see if she
has strep throat. It proves negative. ``But is that because she
does not have strep throat, or is she partially treated?'' she
said. Not knowing which, she said, leaves the doctor with the
choice of treating a condition the patient may not have or waiting
to see if the conditions worsens.
</P>
<P>
   Even the act of going to a clinic is novel to some Hispanics.
``In Mexico, there are so many things around for curing yourself
that you don't go to the doctor,'' said Juvenica Acevedo Flores, a
hearty widow who is 4 feet, 4 inches tall and 87 years old.
</P>
<P>
   She has Medicare but rarely used it until a few years ago when
she was found to have diabetes. Now her daughter takes her to the
Westside clinic for checkups. ``It's necessary,'' Ms. Acevedo said
with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Brodsky, a clinic manager whose grandmother was a
curandera, said the whole notion of insurance could be foreign.
``The culture isn't one to ask for help outside the family,'' she
said. ``Then when something really bad happens, you turn to the
family for money'' to pay for professional care.
</P>
<P>
   Language is also a barrier, both in efforts to get patients to
enroll in health care programs and in communicating with them once
they sign up.
</P>
<P>
   At Denver Health's Community Health Services, which oversees the
clinics and serves a predominantly poor and Hispanic clientele, 83
percent of the 80 physicians are non-Hispanic whites. So are all
eight senior social workers and 84 percent of the 97 registered and
advanced-practice nurses.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, said Ms. Collins of the Westside clinic, ``A
Hispanic is given heart medicine and it's not well-explained. They
end up taking it when they have a chest pain, not every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Sanchez-Martin, director of the Center for Community and
Behavioral Health at the Denver branch of the Latin American
Research and Service Agency, says the problem is one of ``cultural
competence,'' not just language. Relations between men and women,
for example, clash with American norms.
</P>
<P>
   At the private, largely church-funded Tepayac Clinic, husbands
sometimes stop their wives from having pap smears. ``If the
doctor's a man,'' said Jim Garcia, chairman of the clinic's board,
``the husband says no. The idea of another man touching his wife is
beyond comprehension.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So we try to relieve that,'' said Susan Gallo, a psychologist
and the clinic's executive director, ``by having a female attendant
in the examining room _ a chaperone.''
</P>
<P>
   Barriers like these reinforce Denver's unofficial safety net.
One strand is the neighborhood curandera, and another the bodegas
and four or five botanicas and yerberias that dispense herbs, teas,
incense, powders, charms, sprays and oils, some with proven
medicinal value and often prescribed by curanderas.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rick Padilla, a family physician at Westside, estimates that
100 to 200 curanderas serve the city, nearly all working from their
homes and known only by word of mouth. In a random survey of 405
adult Hispanic patients, he found that 29 percent had sought a
curandera's intervention at least once in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Some charge nothing, Padilla said. Others accept a meal, or a
donation ranging from $5 to $100. ``They're not very well
regulated,'' he said, ``and there's a lot of potential for abuse.''
But when he feels that Hispanic patients' fears and suspicions
obstruct their care, he refers them to a trustworthy curandera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Latin people think their diseases are related to someone
having put a hex on them,'' said Toni Palma, a Hopi Indian married
to a Mexican and a counselor to the elderly at Westside. A woman
might say she has been cursed and made sick by another who wants
her husband.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the disparities in insurance coverage do not
translate into conclusive evidence of a sicker population.
Nationwide, the average Hispanic is a first-generation immigrant,
26 years old _ 10 years younger than the rest of the population _
and less likely to have contracted the diseases that develop later
in life.
</P>
<P>
   Still, among the three largest population groups _ white, black
and Hispanic _ statistics from the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention show that Hispanics have the highest rates of diseases
like mumps, tetanus, whooping cough and German measles. They have
lower levels of HIV infection, diabetes and tuberculosis than
blacks but about twice the levels of whites.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight percent of Hispanic children are uninsured, the
journal Health Affairs reports, compared with 18 percent of black
children and 12 percent of white children.
</P>
<P>
   But once Hispanic immigrants have lived in America for a decade
or two, physicians here say, their diets begin to shift from beans,
grains, fruit and vegetables to fast and processed foods.
</P>
<P>
   So once they are settled, said Robin Weinick, social scientist
at the federal Agency for Health Care Policy and Research,
``Hispanics tend to be in poorer health.'' And, she said, ``They
have the poorest access to care of any population we measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright of Denver Health said, ``We've got to learn. We've got to
talk to people in the community. We've got to have a dialogue so
our system and their beliefs can be more in sync.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
