purchase information see end of text. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is a menu for this week's New America News
Service:
</P>
<P>
   THE LANGUAGE EXPERTS WILL BE LISTENING. Language and its power
to distort meaning to prop up political or ideological agendas
concern more people than elected officials, reports columnist Bill
Maxwell. It concerns scholars in the graduate program in rhetoric
and composition at the University of South Florida (scholars
everywhere place USF's program among the top five in the nation).
``They study language, especially the ways that words and sentence
structure map our thinking, values, emotions and actions at given
times on specific subjects,'' he writes. USF Professor Lynn Worsham
told him, ``I try to introduce students to the idea that language
shapes the world and that what we say matters.''
</P>
<P>
   DIVORCE IN THE FEDERAL GOVERNMENT. The most corrupt part of the
federal government, the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
must be split apart. An agency, half corrupt, half inefficient,
cannot stand, insists columnist Raoul Lowery Contreras. ``If
reorganization does not occur soon _ splitting apart the law
enforcement and the naturalization departments, problems will
worsen. There will be more illegals; legal immigrants will be
caught up in a tangled bureaucratic web while trying to become
citizens; and millions of dollars will be spent with nothing to
show for them,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS USED AS MASCOTS IS OFFENSIVE! IS THAT SO HARD TO
UNDERSTAND? The word Indian women today find so degrading _ squaw _
was derived from the Algonquin language and may have just meant
`woman' way back when. But since then the interpretation and
association of the word ``squaw'' by white men was ``whore,''
explains columnst Tim Giago. A North Carolina high school teenager
was recently seen on national TV expressing her pride at being
called a `squaw' _ the name of her school athletics team. ``But
this is only one of hundreds of examples of Indians being used as
mascots,'' he writes. ``Why is it so hard for people to understand
this is really offensive to Indians?''
</P>
<P>
   VIOLATIONS OF `DON'T ASK, DON'T TELL' CONTINUE. Five years into
the Clinton Administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy on
gays in the military, the number of gay discharges (1,149) in 1998
is the highest in a decade _ up 86 percent since 1993, representing
a total cost to the American taxpayers of $130 million dollars,
notes columnist Chuck Colbert. What's more, he adds, anti-gay
harassment surged 120 percent _ up from 182 incidents of anti-gay
harassment in 1997 to 400 incidents in 1998. ``This doomed policy
is far too costly _ in terms of dollars spent, servicemembers
discharged, and careers ruined,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW FACE IN FITNESS. Like many of her sixth-grade girlfriends,
Ceci Gonzalez turned to sports and exercise to relieve the boredom
of growing up in Brownsville, Texas. There was one important
difference, however, writes Cary Cardwell in Hispanic Business
magazine. Ceci was the only girl lifting free weights with the boys
at St. Joseph Academy High School. Now this Latina has made her
mark in an industry dominated by Anglos. Recently winning the Ms.
Fitness USA crown, she wants others to follow her lead.
</P>
<P>
