<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVIDED-IMMIG-DEPT:CONTRERAS-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVORCE IN THE FEDERAL GOVERNMENT
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno announced that she will not add
another 1,000 officers to the Border Patrol. This has shocked the
anti-immigrant cabal that seeks to negatively frame the entire
immigration issue. Doris Meisner, Commissioner of the Immigration
and Naturalization Service (INS), announced that Border Patrol
officers are to be reassigned to the border from the American
hinterland.
 &HT;    Finally, it seems, we won't have the specter of armed Border
Patrolmen chasing children through school yards in Nebraska and
spiriting them away to the border to kick them out of the country
without even notifying the schools or their parents. Scenes like
this have become common since Congress authorized the Patrol to
expand from a few hundred officers to 9,000 today.
 &HT;    When the expansion started, I appeared on a radio show with T.J.
Bonner, head of the Border Patrol union (San Diego), and he
conceded that the Patrol would never absorb such numbers, so
quickly. But, nonetheless, it has come to pass. The Border Patrol
is full of incompetent, untrained officers. Would another thousand
incompetent officers staunch the flow of illegals from Mexico and
Canada? No. Instead, they would be a waste of money.
 &HT;    Why, then, with hundreds of millions of dollars to spend, has
the INS not figured out some way to keep track of visitors planning
to overstay their visas? They can't keep them from crossing the
border, nor can they keep track of them or find them once they've
overstayed their legal visits. They also are unable to handle
applications for citizenship within a period of two years, or so.
What can the INS do right? Not much, it seems.
 &HT;    What, then, should we do with the INS? It must be split into
parts that are specialized:
 &HT;    _The law enforcement part, including the Border Patrol and the
investigative sections of the INS, should be transferred to the
Justice Department with its long history of running law enforcement
agencies, such as the FBI and the U.S. Marshall's Service.
 &HT;    _The Naturalization part must be made part of the State
Department. It must be separate from enforcement in any
reorganization _ and reorganization MUST occur.
 &HT;    If reorganization does not occur soon, problems will worsen.
There will be more illegals; legal immigrants will be caught up in
a tangled bureaucratic web while trying to become citizens; and
millions of dollars will be spent with nothing to show for them.
 &HT;    Both the attorney general and INS commissioner should be pushing
such a project, as they should for a larger guest worker program.
Let's face it, 9,000 Border Patrolmen can't seem to catch many
illegals _ unless they're children _ so something must change.
Either they throw up their hands and give up or they should seek
out positive methods of working with the problems of immigration.
 &HT;    Let me be clear in that I do not say immigration is a problem,
but there are problems in immigration. There are long waiting
periods for citizenship processing, sometimes into years upon
years. There is massive corruption of federal employees (The New
York Times had a five-part report naming the INS as the most
corrupt agency in the federal government). And, there are hundreds,
if not thousands of violations of civil rights that cost the
government hundreds of thousands of dollars.
 &HT;    Some of the violations occur across the border in Mexico. Yes,
Border Patrol bullets shot from inside the United States by
trigger-happy Border Patrolmen wounding boys _ unarmed boys _ in
Mexico. The shootings are punishment for throwing rocks. One Border
Patrolman murdered a Mexican, threatened his Patrol partner to keep
quiet, then walked out of court a free man because he ``feared for
his life.'' The Mexican victim was, of course, unarmed, shot in the
back and allowed to bleed to death.
 &HT;    Critics would destroy immigration and impose an immigration
moratorium, but that is senseless and doesn't fix the problems; it
only spreads them out over fewer people. Critics maintain that
there is some sort of national emergency with high immigration and
some illegal immigration. They are wrong. There is a national
emergency on the horizon, but it isn't immigration, it is the
graying of America. An old America that can't feed itself, that
can't replenish itself, that is unproductive and an America living
off of government checks.
 &HT;    Given proper administration by the government, the present
immigration system is a boost to America and will keep it on top of
the world in technology, social and political systems. The critics
of immigration must be stopped in their tracks before they place
the country in irreparable harm's way.
 &HT;    Proper administration starts with pruning the Border Patrol and
divorcing it from the INS. Ms. Reno, Ms. Meisner: do something
before it is too late. Border Patrol officers chasing children
through schoolyards in America is unacceptable.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
