A1347 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-MASCOTS:GIAGO-     04-08 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-MASCOTS:GIAGO-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS USED AS MASCOTS IS OFFENSIVE! IS THAT SO HARD TO
UNDERSTAND?
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is CEO of book publishers Lakota
Times Publishing, Inc., located in Sioux Falls, S.D. His Indian
name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SIOUX FALLS, S. D. _ I do not recall ever writing a column that
could be considered as Rated R, but this one might come close.
 &HT;    It is pretty certain that the word Indian women find so
offensive _ squaw _ was derived from the Algonquin language and may
have just meant woman way back when. But, over the years, the most
common interpretation and association of the name ``squaw'' by
white men was ``whore.''
 &HT;    As the pioneers moved west and came across many other Indian
tribes who did not speak in the Algonquin dialect they still called
the Indian women they encountered ``squaws.'' It was not uncommon
for white men to say, ``I'm going to get me a little `squaw'
tonight.'' And they did not mean the size of the woman. Eventually
the word `squaw' took on all of the vulgar slang now used to
describe the private parts of a woman. All educated American Indian
women know this, hence their resentment of the word.
 &HT;    This came home to me as I watched the evening news on CNN and
saw a blonde, high school cheerleader from Erwin High School in
Asheville, N.C. stand in front of the camera and say, ``I'm proud
to be called a `squaw,''' which is the mascot name of the girls'
athletic team at this school.
 &HT;    Can you imagine any knowledgeable teenager standing in front of
a camera conveying her image internationally saying, ``I'm proud to
be called a `whore.''' And yet, to most of the Indian women
watching this newscast, this is exactly what the young white girl
was saying.
 &HT;    I have been writing about the use of Indian people as mascots
for more than 20 years. Over this period, 600 schools have dropped
the use of Indians as mascots, but nearly 2,500 have not.
 &HT;    I do not write as often about mascots as I once did. I only
write about it now because it is once more in the news and I hope I
can help to educate and change minds by giving an Indian point of
view.
 &HT;    The University of Illinois with its ``Chief Illiniwek'' is a
classic example of educated ignorance. Most of the student body,
faculty and alumni honor and cherish the ``fake'' Indian they use
as their mascot, but have venomous hatred for the ``real'' live
Indians who show up each year at homecoming to protest this racism.
Their fake mascot symbol is now more important to them than the
living race of people they once chose to honor and now dishonor.
 &HT;    There are no more Gaels or Norsemen and the Fighting Irish are
mostly African Americans. There are no teams named to honor the
Chinese, Mexican Americans or African Americans. There are no
Blackskins, Yellowskins or Brownskins, but there are Redskins. A
high school in Illinois called themselves the ``Chinks'' not too
long ago, but the school changed it because it was too racist. I
wonder why. Do you suppose the Chinese couldn't stand the honor?
 &HT;    It is true the Cleveland Indians were named for an Indian man
named Sokalexis who played for their team for about 18 months, but
would Sokalexis approve of the hideous caricature of a bucktoothed,
grinning Indian now used as a symbol on their ball caps? Reminds me
of the gruesome caricature once used to grace the walls and signs
of the infamous Sambo Restaurants. What ever happened to them? Much
too racist even to the hardcore bigots? But hey, the ugly Indian on
the hat of the Cleveland team is all right because it is meant to
honor Indians. Right? Some honor!
 &HT;    The Justice Department is now investigating the use of Indian
mascots at Erwin High School. They are questioning whether the
symbols create a racially hostile environment for the Indian
students attending that school. One argument by those favoring the
continued use of the mascots, the warriors and the squaws, has been
that the school population is only marginally Indian. If only one
Indian attending Erwin High finds the mascots degrading and
offensive, that should be reason enough to change them.
 &HT;    It should go without saying that a brand new high school,
college or professional team would never choose Indians, braves,
warriors or chiefs as mascots today. They would know these names
can be used to demean Indians and that Indians find them to be
insulting.
 &HT;    Most Indians choose not to be mimicked and ridiculed at sporting
events and all Indian women find the word ``squaw'' very offensive.
Again I ask; why is this so hard to understand?
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago 
