<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1348 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DON'T-ASK-DON'T-TELL:     04-08 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DON'T-ASK-DON'T-TELL:COLBERT-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLATIONS OF `DON'T ASK, DON'T TELL' CONTINUE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By CHUCK COLBERT 
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert is a founder of the Gay and Lesbian Alumni of
Notre Dame/St. Mary's College, and serves on the board of directors
of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Five years into the Clinton Administration's ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy on gays in the military, the number of gay discharges
(1,149) in 1998 is the highest in a decade _ up 86 percent since
1993, representing a total cost to the American taxpayers of $130
million dollars.
 &HT;    What's more, anti-gay harassment surged 120 percent _ up from
182 incidents of anti-gay harassment in 1997 to 400 incidents in
1998. These incidents included not only verbal gay-bashing, but
also death threats.
 &HT;    This major finding and numerous other anecdotal accounts
document hundreds of routine violations of ``don't ask, don't
tell,'' according to a report recently released by the Washington,
D.C.-based Servicemembers Legal Defense Network (SLDN), a legal
advocacy and watch dog organization that represents gay men and
lesbians.
 &HT;    It is not supposed to be this way. Established in 1994, the
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy permits gays and lesbians to serve
in the military, but prohibits them from saying they are homosexual
or engaging in homosexual acts.
 &HT;    ``We will not witch hunt. We will not chase. We will not seek to
learn orientation,'' said Gen. Colin Powell, then chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, testifying in 1993 on behalf the new policy.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, ``our report concludes that lesbian, gay, and
bisexual service members face daily threats to their physical
safety and well-being _ not from enemies but from Uncle Sam,'' said
C. Dixon Osburn, SLDN's co-executive director.
 &HT;    Former Army Pfc. Joshua Jones experienced anti-gay harassment
first-hand in Fort Hood, Texas and ``feared for his safety when a
dead fish head was nailed to his barracks door, which in his unit
signified that the recipient would be beaten up. A note on the door
stated, `For you faggot,''' according to the SLDN report.
 &HT;    ``Military leaders have been AWOL when it comes to stopping the
anti-gay harassment. Service members have nowhere to turn inside
the military when their peers and supervisors harass and threaten
them,'' said Michelle Benecke, SLDN's co-executive director.
 &HT;    Perhaps the most disturbing trend documented by SLDN is the
growing link between asking questions and anti-gay harassment.
``Hostile commanders, supervisors, colleagues and investigators
hound service members with constant questions about their sexual
orientation and conduct. Sometimes they question the individual
directly. Many times, they question service members in front of
their peers. Lesbians, gays and bisexuals experience the
questioning not only as asking, but harassment, intimidation, and
hostility,'' states the report.
 &HT;    ``The Pentagon has officially held no one accountable for asking
or harassing a service member in violation of the policy,'' the
report continues. ``As a result more service members are disclosing
their sexual orientation in response to the asking and harassment
as the only means to protect themselves.''
 &HT;    That's what one ensign, a Naval Academy graduate, had to do:
``Living in forced isolation, in constant fear of investigation and
inadvertent disclosure is harmful to gay service personnel. Each
day I am witness to unprofessional, anti-gay comments and
attitudes. The Navy takes no action to stop this improper and
outrageous behavior on the part of its best and brightest officers.
My witness to this unfortunate anti-gay climate, and the direct
harm it causes me, forces me to disclose to you that I am gay,'' he
wrote in a letter to his commanding officer.
 &HT;    Pentagon officials have yet to respond to the SLDN report. Two
months ago, however, the undersecretary of defense for personnel
and readiness stated that 87 percent of gay discharges resulted
from voluntary statements.
 &HT;    But SLDN found that heavy-handed tactics forced many
``voluntary'' statements. Such ``statements'' include ``disclosures
made to psycho-therapists; in personal diaries; in response to
direct questions about their sexual orientation; in anonymous
on-line profiles; and those coerced out of service members due to
fear, intimidations, assaults, death threats and threats of
criminal prosecution,'' the reports states.
 &HT;    Ironically, it is the military's own heavy-handedness that is
ultimately undermining the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy. The
latest 1998 Gallup poll showed 77 percent of American adults
support letting gays serve in the military. A recent poll of Army
males showed a big drop in strong opposition to gays in the
military _ down from 63 percent in 1993 to 36 percent in 1998.
 &HT;    Even the architect of don't ask, don't tell, Professor Charles
Moskos of Northwestern University, has stated that ``heavy-handed
enforcement ... will inadvertently undermine the ... policy.''
Continuing, ``It is these kinds of actions by the military, rather
than lobbying by homosexual-rights advocates, that pose the
greatest threat to the efficacy of the policy ... '' he said.
 &HT;    The sooner the more likely it is for ``don't ask, don't tell''
to implode. This doomed policy is far too costly _ in terms of
dollars spent, servicemembers discharged, and careers ruined.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Chuck Colbert 
