<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MS-FITNESS-USA-NU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW FACE IN FITNESS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material is for use only by
arrangement with New York Times Syndicate/Special features. For
purchase information see end of text. 
 By CARY CARDWELL 
 c. 1999 Hispanic Business 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Like many of her sixth-grade girlfriends, Ceci Gonzalez turned
to sports and exercise to relieve the boredom of growing up in
Brownsville, Texas. There was one important difference, however.
Ceci was the only girl lifting free weights with the boys at St.
Joseph Academy High School.
 &HT;    ``It was pretty much just me and the football team in the weight
room,'' she recalls with a laugh. Some of her girlfriends may have
snickered, but her track coach assured her that strength training
would help her excel outside the weight room _ in track,
gymnastics, and later in her career.
 &HT;    Now age 24, Ceci Gonzalez Evans credits her continued interest
in strength and fitness training for helping her succeed. She
earned a track scholarship to the University of Houston as a
sophomore in 1990, and most recently was crowned Ms. Fitness USA
1999 during a national competition in Las Vegas.
 &HT;    ``When I graduated from U of H, I still had a competitive drive
and needed an outlet. I was still into lifting weights, but I
didn't want to go into body building. I didn't want to get big,''
she says. ``I heard about a fitness competition at the U of H the
next month, and I went to it and decided it was for me. It was high
energy, perfect for someone like me with a dance and gymnastic
background.''
 &HT;    Fitness competition for women is a growing trend, with events
pulling in major sponsors such as Bally Total Fitness and MET-RX, a
nutritional supplement. It differs from body building by
emphasizing body shaping as opposed to building muscle mass.
 &HT;    ``The look the judges want is like a model with muscles,''
Gonzalez Evans
 &HT;    says. ``You have to look lean and feminine. It's not that
`ripped-to-the-bone' look of body building. They want you to look
feminine but defined, with muscles.
 &HT;    ``It's like a beauty pageant with muscles,'' she says of the
contests, which include evening gown and talent competitions as
well as a swimsuit event that reveals muscle tone. ``It's the same
sequence as a real beauty pageant, but it focuses more on the
feminine side of body building.''
 &HT;    Gonzalez Evans, who met (and later married) her coach, Tommy
Evans, while he was playing football and she was performing as a
heptathlete for the University of Houston, says she would like to
see more Hispanics take up strength and fitness training.
 &HT;    She recently returned to Brownsville as a guest of her cousin
Frank Trevino, a counselor at Vela Middle School, where she talked
to at-risk teens. She pointed to Selena as an example of the energy
and grace that can come from fitness and strength training.
 &HT;    ``I got a lot of my ideas from her, and used Latin routines to
set myself apart from the other girls (contestants), most of whom
were doing hip-hop and funky dance routines,'' Gonzalez Evans says.
 &HT;    She spoke to about 100 kids, who eagerly responded with
questions and requests for autographed pictures. ``When we left, my
cousin told me that many of those boys I had been talking to were
gang members, but I had touched a side of them you usually don't
see, because they have to act tough all the time. These kids just
need something else to put their energy into.''
 &HT;    It took Gonzalez Evans three years of competition to win the Ms.
Fitness USA crown. But she says exercise routines aren't just for
those at the competitive level. With women's sports on the rise at
both the amateur and professional levels, she says this is a
perfect time for women of all backgrounds to set goals and work out
_ especially Hispanics.
 &HT;    ``Maybe there aren't that many into it because you don't see
many Latinos on television doing the fitness stuff,'' she says.
``But I could have shied away from it or gone with it. And I went
with it. Somebody's got to break those barriers. Right now, it's an
industry that's pretty, blond, and blue-eyed _ and that's got to
change.''
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Hispanic Business 
