scarcely daring to breathe. When was the last time you heard that
kind of hush in a theater? That this one occurs four hours into the
performance of ``Iceman,'' which officially opened April 8, is a
testament to the abiding potency of Eugene O'Neill's great,
lumbering barroom metaphysics lesson of a play and to the hypnotic
pull of this production. By Ben Brantley.
