<HEADER>
A1360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-PROFILING-780&AMP;     04-08 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-PROFILING-780&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE PROFILING DEBATE: ACTING ON EXPERIENCE, OR ON BIAS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Conn., Fla., Ill., Ind., Mass., Md., Mo., Ohio,
N.J., N.Y.,   Pa., Texas, Va.)   (rk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The police consider it a crucial crime-fighting tool based on
street savvy. Critics contend it is a potentially fatal weapon that
betrays deep institutional racism.
</P>
<P>
   Profiling _ the use of race and ethnicity as clues to
criminality _ is at the heart of federal and state investigations
into police behavior in New Jersey and New York City. It is the
subtext of the outrage over the fatal shooting two months ago of
Amadou Diallo, an unarmed West African immigrant, by four white New
York officers in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   It is the subject of bills pending in Congress and a dozen state
legislatures, and the U.S. Customs Service announced Thursday that
it would examine allegations of profiling by its inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Determining when and how the police should use race or ethnicity
to assess suspects and situations, though, is a complicated
balancing act of public safety and civil liberties. Law enforcement
experts insist that effective police work depends upon quick
analysis, and that skin color is one factor among many _ like dress
or demeanor _ that officers must consider.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing chorus of community leaders see a presumptive
linking of minorities to crime that has caused intolerable
humiliation and physical abuse of innocent citizens _ even Diallo's
death.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the aggressive policing strategy that has helped
reduce crime in New York and around the nation, officers often cast
a wide net in hopes of turning up illegal drugs and guns.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the profiling debate is the question of whether to
focus, for example, on the 9,500 arrests made over the last two
years by New York's Street Crime Unit, or the 35,000
stop-and-frisks officers reported that turned up nothing. How many
innocent people must be inconvenienced to keep streets safe?
</P>
<P>
   Several studies give credence to the complaints of black and
Hispanic citizens that compared with whites, they are so frequently
stopped on highways and frisked on city streets that only racial
profiling can explain the pattern. But African-American and
Hispanic people are also overrepresented among those charged with
major crimes _ especially murder and robbery _ and in the nation's
prison population.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers often use those statistics to justify profiling,
while critics question whether it has become a self-fulfilling
prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening is law enforcement begins to use blackness as
the proxy for propensity to be involved in crime,'' said David
Harris, a law professor at the University of Toledo who is writing
a report on profiling for the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stop more blacks because more of them are in jail,'' he
said. ``When we stop them more, we'll find more stuff on them,
we'll arrest more of them proportionally, we'll convict more of
them proportionally, there'll be more of them in jail, and around
the circle we go.''
</P>
<P>
   Police chiefs acknowledge that some officers focus
inappropriately on African-American and Hispanic people, and say
that they are eager to address that fact through discipline and
retraining.
</P>
<P>
   But some are worried about overreaction: in rejecting a measure
that would have allowed troopers to stop motorists for not wearing
seat belts, Virginia lawmakers worried that officers would unfairly
concentrate on black drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cops are profiling all the time, your good cops;
unfortunately, now that's developing a bad name,'' said William J.
Bratton, former police commissioner of New York City. ``Whether
they call it profiling, or street smarts, awareness _ whatever the
names might be _ profiling is essential.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratton recalled a summer when he was a rookie patrolling in
Boston. There was a rash of stolen Lincoln Continentals, so
officers began looking twice when Lincolns passed. White
businessmen who seemed likely to own such vehicles were allowed to
keep driving, while black teen-agers were often pulled over, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   They found a lot of stolen cars, he recalled. What they can
never know is how many of the white drivers were car thieves as
well.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, officers in Illinois learned that trucks from
Texas were being used by drug couriers, according to Ronald S.
Neubauer, the police chief in St. Peters, Mo., and president of the
International Association of Police Chiefs. Troopers quickly
stopped four trucks with Texas plates; all four were driven by
Mexicans, all four were loaded with drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean they're racially profiling Mexicans? I don't
think so,'' Neubauer said. ``We train our officers to be wary of
suspicious circumstances. I don't want my officers to act out on
bias, I want them to act out on their training and experience.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   New York City police cadets typically receive about six months
of training in the academy, including at least one seminar focused
on diversity and racial sensitivity. But most experts acknowledge
that the more important training comes once police officers hit the
streets, often at the hands of their veteran partners.
</P>
<P>
   There, officers develop what they call their ``sixth sense,''
the instinctive ability to sniff out situations or isolate
individuals who seem potentially unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is as simple as noticing a person out of place _ a
shabby youth in a tony suburb, for example, or a pinstriped suit in
a gritty ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is informed by a known criminal pattern, like
Bratton's Lincolns or Neubauer's Texas trucks. Often, though, it is
as vague and subjective as a furtive look or an uneasy gait,
something officers know as well as their own shield numbers, but
cannot precisely name.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a thin line between appropriate behavior and
inappropriate behavior,'' said James J. Fyfe, a former New York
officer who teaches criminal justice at Temple University in
Philadelphia. ``A person's characteristics are one of the things
upon which police officers base their actions; the problem is when
it becomes the primary thing, or the only thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The police have broad discretion in whom to stop. The legal
standard justifying a stop-and-frisk, the maneuver that has become
the controversial hallmark of New York's Street Crime Unit, is
``reasonable suspicion,'' a fuzzy concept. On the highway, evidence
of a traffic infraction is required to stop a car, but studies have
shown that so many drivers commit such offenses that it is largely
a matter of discretion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cops work on an exception principle: they learn what's normal
in a neighborhood, and things that are abnormal draw their
attention; quite often, that involves issues of race,'' Fyfe
explained. ``Their whole frame of reference in approaching them is
framed by their experience. It's a police application of what we
all do.''
</P>
<P>
   Neubauer said: ``If you didn't stereotype in your life every
day, you'd have total confusion. We seem to have singled out the
law enforcement arena as the target to try and cure.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is because police officers have broad powers to
abridge individual rights. Some blame Diallo's death in a hail of
41 bullets on profiling; the four officers who have been indicted
in the case were searching that night for a black rapist.
</P>
<P>
   Most incidences of profiling are much subtler, but critics
contend that the increasing perception that the police mistreat
members of minority groups could have a corrosive long-term effect
on public safety that overshadows the short-term benefit of a crime
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every prominent black politician, athlete and businessman
_ not to mention urban teen-ager _ seems to have a personal story
of being stopped and searched, harassed and harangued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the impact of those stories, as they permeate those
communities, that causes problems for effective community-police
relations,'' said Karim Ismaili, a criminal justice professor at
St. John's University in New York who taught cultural sensitivity
seminars at the New York Police Academy last fall. ``There's this
spiral of fear and mistrust; this affects both the officer and the
citizen and the public in general.''
</P>
<P>
   At Citizens Opposing Profiled Police Stops (www.copps.org), they
hear complaints not only from black and Hispanic men, but also from
Grateful Dead fans and white kids with baggy pants, long hair and
tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Brown, the African-American sports agent who helped found
the group last year, said it has happened to him several times,
including a particularly painful incident while on a family
vacation in Florida. Officers pulled him over on the highway, told
him he ``fit a profile'' and asked to search his car. Finding
nothing, he recalled, they suggested he have a nice day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stuff is all over the highway. Have a nice day?'' Brown
said, angered anew. ``My wife's panties, her personal items _ they
went all through the stuff. How do you have a nice day?''
</P>
<P>
   There have been no nationwide studies analyzing the rate of
stops and searches by race, but several narrower surveys have
turned up results that Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., called ``too
outrageous to be a mere coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, the state police agreed as part of a court
settlement to track the race of drivers that troopers stopped and
searched on a stretch of I-95. Only 17 percent of the drivers on
that road were black, but more than 70 percent of those searched in
the first 20 months were African-American.
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey judge found in 1996 that troopers had an illegal
practice of making targets of minority drivers, citing a ``stark''
disparity in which blacks were 4.85 times as likely to be stopped
as whites.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers is expected to introduce a bill in the coming weeks that
would require all police officers in the country to record the
race, among other things, of every person they stop on the highway.
Similar legislation passed the House last year but died in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, parallel measures are pending in at least a dozen
state legislatures, including Connecticut's and New Jersey's, and
police chiefs in Philadelphia, San Diego and San Jose have recently
decided to collect such data independently.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney general, Janet Reno, called Thursday for the
collection of information on police stops to examine ``the feelings
of Americans who feel that police officers are stopping them
because of race.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of profiling say the practice grows out of aggressive
policing strategies, like New York's, that stress statistics and
reward officers who make the most arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an organized tactic where we cast an extremely broad net
and we hope we're going to catch one or two drug runners,'' said
John Crew, the San Francisco lawyer who runs the ACLU's police
practices unit. ``If you're doing stops based on hunch, it's also
inevitable that both conscious and subconscious racism will creep
into those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew said it was not enough to attack explicit statements like
those in a manual used by the Public Agency Training Council in
Indianapolis, which suggests stopping all cars with ``Jamaican
paraphernalia, bumper stickers or slogans.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if a police supervisor just told his troops, ``What we're
really trying to do is target drugs coming up from Tijuana,'' it
could be problematic, Crew said, because officers might interpret
it as: Stop Hispanic drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves the law enforcement question: how to take aim at
drugs coming up from Tijuana?
</P>
<P>
   ``They once asked Willie Sutton why he robbed banks, and he
said, `Because that's where the money is,''' said James Savage,
acting president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association in New
York. ``Why do you send people into minority or high-crime
neighborhoods to look for guns? Because that's where the guns
are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
