<DOCNO> NYT19990408.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1388 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZHU-HNS &LR;      04-08 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZHU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR TRADE DEAL ELUDES CLINTON, ZHU &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENNIFER DAY 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a distinct chill in Sino-U.S. relations in the
air despite the warm spring day, President Clinton and Chinese
Premier Zhu Rongji failed to reach a major trade accord Thursday
but spoke out on issues including allegations of Chinese espionage
and human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   At a joint news conference, Zhu admitted his country has some
work to do in the area of human rights, long a major concern among
U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I concede that there is room for improvement in human rights
in China,'' the premier said.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, who is thought by many to be a moderate force, is visiting
the U.S. capital during his nine-day trip, the third in a series of
high-level exchanges between Washington and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   On a topic that has dogged the Clinton administration, Zhu said
he and Chinese President Jiang Zemin knew nothing about allegations
that China stole U.S. nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pressed the premier to cooperate with a U.S. Department
of Justice probe into those allegations as well as other charges
that a high-ranking Chinese military intelligence chief may have
donated $300,000 to the president's 1996 campaign through a Los
Angeles Democratic fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major items on the two leaders' agendas was to
produce a long-awaited agreement on China's membership in the World
Trade Organization, which enforces international trade rules.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton reported negotiators had made progress,
particularly in the areas of agriculture, no agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Before Zhu and Clinton met in the Oval Office to discuss several
issues beyond human rights and trade organization access, a crowd
of about 100 gathered in a park opposite the White House to protest
over human rights issues, particularly in Tibet, and missiles aimed
at Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the red-carpet welcoming ceremony when the
rousing music and gun salute stopped, faint echoes of the
protesters' chants could be heard.
</P>
<P>
   T. Kumar, Amnesty International's advocacy director for Asia,
said Zhu's statement was a step in the right direction but that it
had to be followed up by action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome that statement, but we want him to match the words
with deeds,'' Kumar said. ``When (Chinese leaders are) in the U.S.
and looking for access to WTO, they will make statements like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu said that he also believes different countries have
different standards for what constitutes human rights, a claim
Kumar rejected on the grounds that China has signed two
international covenants on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The premier also needled the president a bit, saying a friend of
his had come to him with examples of human rights violations in the
United States and told him to ask Clinton about them during his
visit.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhu did not, he said, ``because I trust you are able to
resolve your own problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not respond to the comment, but earlier in his
opening statement said there is still disagreement between the two
countries on the meaning and reach of human rights. He also said he
regrets that China has failed to open talks with the Dalai Lama,
the exiled spiritual leader of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I am convinced that greater freedom, debate and
openness are vital to improving China's citizens' lives as well as
China's economy over the long run, it is troubling that in the past
year, China has taken some steps backwards on human rights in
basically arresting people basically for seeking to express their
political views,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent crackdowns on democratic activists have been one of many
factors to anger U.S. legislators in recent months. Reports that
China stole nuclear secrets have also spurred criticism of China
and of Clinton's handling of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Zhu's denial of any episodes of espionage,
Clinton said it is possible it could have occurred without
high-ranking officials knowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is a big country with a big government, and I can only
say that America is a big country with a big government, and
occasionally things happen in this government that I don't know
about,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Several legislators have said they could not trust any agreement
made with China, including one on World Trade Organization
membership, in part, because of the spying allegations. Rep.
Christopher Cox, R-Calif., is heading a panel investigating
technology transfer.
</P>
<P>
   He said Thursday on CNN's ``Moneyline`` that he believes the
United States must continue talks with China, as all nations must
continue to communicate effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to sell and import Beanie Babies, provided
they're not made with slave labor,'' Cox said. ``It's another thing
entirely to have a Wal-Mart for our nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton said he hopes soon that both countries will ratify the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty to end all nuclear testing and
encouraged China to settle its differences with Taiwan peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks on Taiwan came after Zhu said he could not
rule out aggression against the island, which for many years was
recognized by the United States as the legitimate government of
China after Communists seized control of the mainland. Under
Clinton, however, U.S. policy has shifted to support Taiwan's
reunification with China.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu said he could not rule out force ``because if we were to
make such a pledge, make such an undertaking, then I'm afraid
Taiwan would be in a perpetual state of separation from the
motherland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
