<HEADER>
A1486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-BUCHANAN09-COX     04-08 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BUCHANAN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buchanan brings vote-rocking views to Bush's turf
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Pat Buchanan, who history says can't win the
presidency but can make life miserable for others who can, is
heading into the heart of Bush country.
</P>
<P>
   The third-time GOP candidate is bringing his fire-and-brimstone
campaign to Midland-Odessa next Wednesday for a town meeting
centered on what can be done to shut the valve on ``cheap foreign
oil.'' Buchanan campaign manager Jay Townsend said Thursday the
Texas trip is targeted at an issue, not a foe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our message is that we have disagreements with the White House
and some people in our party over U.S. trade policy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about George Bush,'' Townsend said. ``The time for
that discussion will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Buchanan is a long shot for the GOP nomination, the
eventual winner will have to go through him in New Hampshire's
first-in-the-nation primary. In 1992, Buchanan picked up 37 percent
of the New Hampshire vote in running second to then-President
George Bush, offering the first hint that the incumbent was in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Buchanan won the New Hampshire primary, throwing a
major scare into eventual nominee Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's 2000 campaign already is heavy on evidence that he
and Bush are headed for major disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not born to vast wealth or a famous political dynasty,''
Buchanan said in a fund-raising letter. ``In this campaign, we will
be facing candidates who enjoy these advantages.'' On issues, Bush
and Buchanan differ in approach and philosophy. Both oppose
abortion rights, but Bush says he does not believe the country is
ready for a constitutional amendment banning the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan fired back by saying, ``I think leadership requires you
to stand up and say `This is wrong, and our goal is to end abortion
in the United States.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's early campaign rhetoric also is heavy on the
isolationism that marked his previous races and puts him on a
collision course with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no vital American interest in fighting over whose
flag flies over Pristina,'' Buchanan said when the bombs started
flying in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, after hours of briefings with foreign policy advisers, has
stuck to a carefully worded stance on the Serbian conflict. He said
Thursday that it is in the United States' best interests to
preserve a ``stable, peaceful Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that a thug like Milosevic, if left unchecked,
can set a bad example for other ethnic cleansers,'' said Bush,
adding he is concerned about ``whether or not the bombing campaign
is being done with ferocity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Buchanan also disagree on the North American Free Trade
Agreement. To Buchanan, it's a deal that ``sold out America's
workers, ravaged our manufacturing base and caused disruption in
our small towns and farming communities.''
</P>
<P>
   To Bush, NAFTA is ``an enormous success.''
</P>
<P>
   The foes also differ on China, a foreign policy issue that Bush
tackled publicly Thursday for the first time, calling for dealing
with China ``in a very firm and consistent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we ought to have trade with China. I also believe
that free trade with China will help develop the entrepreneurial
class in China,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Dead wrong, says Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first myth is the Utopian belief that peace descends on
the wings of trade,'' he said in a San Francisco speech on Monday.
``As long as we trade with China, it is said, we need never
confront China. History, however, reveals this notion to be bunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, and only at a reporter's urging, Bush on Thursday
delved into the differences between himself and Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not subscribe to protectionism, isolationism,'' he said.
``I think it would be a big mistake for America to retreat during
this era when we have got a chance to influence the world in a
positive, constructive way. At home, I know that walling off Texas
from Mexico would be an unmitigated disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan puts his name on the idea, promising to ``lengthen the
`Buchanan Fence' on the southern frontier, repatriate illegals and
repair the great American melting pot.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious differences, Buchanan has said he will keep
his rhetoric against Bush to a minimum, at least for now. Buchanan
has promised to give Bush and Elizabeth Dole ``a decent interval''
to lay out their agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Bush picked up a major political plum Thursday
when New Hampshire Sen. Judd Gregg, who wields the state's best
political machine, signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Former state GOP Assistant Chairman Barbara Russell and Rob
Thompson, a businessman and former top political aide to former New
Hampshire Gov. Steve Merrill, will be co-chairs of the Bush
campaign in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's point person in New Hampshire is Shelly Uscinski,
chair of the state's Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush promises to do no out-of-state campaigning until
after the Texas Legislature adjourns on May 31, he took advantage
of satellite technology Thursday evening to talk directly from
Austin to New Hampshire voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to come up to New Hampshire and begin a grass-roots
campaign,'' he said in a live interview on WMUR-TV of Manchester.
``I understand that New Hampshire is retail politics and I look
forward to coming up there to shake as many hands as I can, look
people in the eye and tell them where my heart is.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
