u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-TORT09-COX     04-08 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-TORT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tort reform bill passes committee
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A specially created Senate subcommittee handling
all tort-reform bills this session passed a key civil justice
reform measure Thursday, but senators, lobbyists and the House
committee chairman who would get the bill say it may be too late to
pass it for the session.
</P>
<P>
   Senators and lobbyists say the subcommittee passage of the
tort-reform bill illustrates a strategic miscalculation by Lt. Gov.
Rick Perry and by the subcommittee chairman, state Sen. Troy Fraser
(R-Horseshoe Bay) one of the Legislature's foremost tort-reform
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Perry called the miscalculation allegation ``bad information''
and said bringing up the bill for a Senate vote next week should
not harm its chances.
</P>
<P>
   Failure of the third-party liability bill _ a top priority for
Texans for Lawsuit Reform and its principal backer, Houston
developer Dick Weekley _ would mark the third session the proposal
died. The bill would limit how much businesses might pay for
injuries when they are not the sole cause of the harm.
</P>
<P>
   Perry had referred the third-party liability bill directly to
Fraser's subcommittee instead of to the full Economic Development
Committee in a rare move that bypassed the committee's chairman,
Sen. David Sibley.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's bumpy ride brought to the forefront _ again _
Fraser's awkward relationship with Sibley (R-Waco), who authored
the tort-reform bill. Sibley had been the point man for tort reform
measures in past sessions, but Perry has tried to give the lead to
Fraser, a longtime friend.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser's subcommittee on technology and business growth approved
the bill by a 3-0 vote, with two senators absent.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the legislation had been conducted March 18. Fraser
had tried to refer the measure to the full committee without a
subcommittee vote, but withdrew that effort after several
colleagues criticized the effort as an extraordinary breach of
Senate procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser said Sibley had offered the motion. But Sibley said he
signed the motion, as the bill's author, at Fraser's request.
</P>
<P>
   If it had worked, the bill might have reached the Senate floor a
week earlier, perhaps increasing its chances for passage.
</P>
<P>
   Senators and lobbyists close to the tort-reform effort say
Weekley was ``livid'' and ``went berserk'' about the delay in
getting the bill to the Senate floor. But Weekley denied that
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed,'' Weekley said. ``But I'm thrilled to
death that it got out today.''
</P>
<P>
   The delay does not mean the bill is dead, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill stalled in what had been considered a sympathetic
five-member subcommittee, widely assumed to have been created by
Perry to benefit Fraser. But one Republican Sen. John Carona of
Dallas, who has been supported by Weekley's group, would not commit
to the legislation after hearing predictions of higher worker
compensation insurance rates for business owners.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would allow juries to allocate fault in
personal-injury lawsuits in two ways that could reduce damages paid
by businesses. Carona was concerned about one that would allow
juries in personal-injury cases to calculate damages against an
employer and another company when both had liability for an
on-the-job injury.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee heard testimony that the bill might lead to
higher worker's comp rates for employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Trial Lawyers Association, one of the chief opponents
of the bill, contends injured employees would be forced under the
legislation to lose money they might have recovered in full from
the second company.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Carona was lobbied hard over the long Easter
weekend by tort-reform groups. Carona would only say that he told
Fraser last Friday that he would vote the bill out of the
subcommittee. State Rep. Fred Bosse (D-Houston), House Civil
Practices Committee chairman, said the delay in getting Sibley's
bill to the House would dim its prospects. Bosse said he did not
favor the legislation but intended to give it a full hearing, if
possible, considering as many as 70 bills awaiting hearings in his
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one I intend to put on high priority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
