<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWJONES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE THROWS OUT DOW JONES LIBEL RULING &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ED ASHER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A federal judge on Thursday threw out a $22.7 million
libel ruling against Wall Street Journal publisher Dow Jones &AMP; Co.,
saying the plaintiff, a now-defunct Houston investment firm, had
withheld important evidence.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Ewing Werlein said he will void an
earlier judgment in favor of MMAR Group Inc. and give Dow Jones a
new trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``From clear and convincing evidence, the court finds that MMAR
obtained its favorable verdict through its own misconduct and
misrepresentations,'' preventing Dow Jones from ``fully and
fairly'' presenting its defense, the judge said in his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Paul Steiger, managing editor of The Wall Street
Journal, said: ``We are very pleased with the court's decision and
are quite optimistic as this case returns to the District Court.
We've long maintained that we did not cause MMAR's collapse but
merely chronicled it.''
</P>
<P>
   MMAR attorneys could not be reached for comment late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   MMAR, a brokerage firm that bought and sold securities for
customers, sued for libel after the newspaper published a highly
critical story by reporter Laura Jereski on Oct. 21, 1993. The
company claimed the story had caused it to go out of business in
mid-November 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal wrote that MMAR had mispriced the market
value of some securities by 10 percent or more to hide portfolio
losses. Such procedures, the story also said, may have been a
factor in a $50 million loss by the Louisiana State Employees
Retirement System.
</P>
<P>
   A jury found in favor of MMAR in 1997, awarding it a stunning
$222.7 million in damages, the largest amount ever awarded by a
jury in a libel case.
</P>
<P>
   Werlein later struck the $200 million in punitive damages but
allowed $22.7 million in compensatory damages to stand.
</P>
<P>
   After the trial, Dow Jones attorneys contended that they had
found out that MMAR had withheld, destroyed and altered evidence
that was central to their defense.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, the judge said a former MMAR employee, William A.
Fincher, told the paper's attorneys in July 1998 that the brokerage
had failed to turn over damaging tape recordings and that he had
copies of some of those tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Fincher also said that MMAR Chief Executive Officer Cory Miner
had pressured him in 1995 to erase portions of the tapes, which he
said he had declined to do.
</P>
<P>
   Fincher died July 8, 1998, when his private plane crashed in
Belize.
</P>
<P>
   Werlein wrote that several of the audiotapes, taken from an
``extensive tape-recording system,'' contain conversations that
would have been ``extremely helpful'' to Dow Jones, particularly in
its defense against one of the most damaging allegations in the
article: that MMAR hid a portfolio's losses by ``mismarking''
securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mismarking'' is misrepresenting the value of securities, that
is, by telling a client that a stock, bond or other security is
worth more than it will bring on the open market.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The judge cited one conversation between Miner and Chuck Ramsey,
a former MMAR officer and salesman and the unnamed source Jereski
used to report the mismarking allegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Miner, apparently suspicious that Mr. Ramsey had been a
source for Ms. Jereski, recorded the conversation by using a
microphone concealed in what appeared to be a pen,'' the judge
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The two discussed the mismarking reported in Jereski's article,
the judge said, and Ramsey is heard on tape saying, ``I heard Rich
Evans, (not identified, but presumably an MMAR employee) stand
there day after day, talk about (expletive deleted) trying to get
that position in line. So if you don't think he was mismarking that
position? I know (profanity deleted) good and well he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Another conversation between MMAR officers leaves ``a reasonable
inference'' that securities were mispriced or mismarked, Werlein
said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said three tapes, ``in the aggregate, and each
individually, contain significant evidence to suggest that MMAR had
engaged in mismarking'' securities that Jereski had written about.
</P>
<P>
   Werlein continued, ``The evidence submitted in connection with
(Dow Jones' motion for a new trial) is clear and convincing that
MMAR engaged in serious misconduct during the pretrial discovery
phase of this case, and that MMAR's misconduct prevented defendants
from fully and fairly presenting their defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge concluded that MMAR's verdict was unfairly obtained
because of its ``misrepresentations and misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
