<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCO PLAYS THE LONG SHOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ You don't pull yourself out of poverty by being
passive. That much, Carlos Franco knows for sure. From a barefoot
caddie in his native Paraguay to a card-carrying member of the PGA
Tour, Franco has overcome odds more lopsided than Augusta National
Golf Club's severe, undulating greens.
</P>
<P>
   There were times during the opening round of the Masters on
Thursday when Franco admittedly would have been wise to back off
his attack. He came at Augusta National so boldly, lopping four
shots off par in the first 11 holes, you just knew it was just a
matter of time before the course struck back.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, she exacted her revenge on the 15th hole, a
beguiling 500-yard par-5 that dares you to ignore the water in the
front and back of the green and go for the flag in two. Franco, who
is as long as the list of professional golfers in Paraguay is
short, did just that.
</P>
<P>
   After crushing his drive, he took a 5-iron and flew his second
shot over the green and into the creek. A one-stroke penalty, a
chip and three putts later, Franco had registered a double-bogey 7
and relinquished his share of the lead, at minus-3.
</P>
<P>
   He'd give another stroke back on the next hole, a 170-yard
par-3, and miss by inches a birdie putt on 18 to finish at even-par
72.
</P>
<P>
   From all alone in first at 4-under par to tied for 21st (12
golfers weren't able to complete their rounds before play was
suspended because of darkness), it was a precipitous fall. Franco,
though, emerged from the experience unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Standing under the shade of an old oak tree near the clubhouse,
he described himself as ``(begin ital)muy contento(end ital).'' No
translation was necessary; Franco's beatific expression rendered
the interpreter's words redundant:
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he is very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Franco broke par for the first time before he ever
broke in a pair of golf shoes. He was 14 when he first played a
round with proper footwear and 18 before he owned his first set of
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at the age of 33, Franco is a proud PGA Tour Qualifying
School graduate, Class of 1998. He is paid handsomely to use one
company's clubs and he never wants for shoes and his family wants
for absolutely nothing. Let other people count the strokes he
squandered; Franco would prefer to count his blessings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one moment I was first, in another moment I had an
accident,'' he said, shrugging. ``I'm not very concerned about it.
He who doesn't risk anything doesn't win anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco went for broke as a youngster, because then he didn't
have much to lose. He and his six siblings (including five
brothers, all of whom are excellent golfers) grew up in the
Paraguayan capital of Asuncion. Their father was a greenskeeper at
Asuncion Golf Club, one of only three courses in the South American
country of 5 million. Home was a one-room shack with no indoor
plumbing and no television.
</P>
<P>
   Franco was 18 when he saw his first Masters telecast. Two years
later, he watched Jack Nicklaus win the 1986 tournament at the age
of 46 and a dream took root.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked Jack Nicklaus because he is aggressive like
me,'' Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   One day, he decided, he would play Augusta National like Jack.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now it's not a dream,'' said the man who reminds his peers
of someone not named Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a Dalyesque golf swing,'' said first-round co-leader
Brandel Chamblee, alluding to the PGA Tour's Long John. ``He's very
talented. All the guys out here know who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   And anyone who doesn't ``will know about him soon enough,'' said
former Masters winner Larry Mize, who was paired with Franco in the
first round (Jeff Sluman rounded out the threesome).
</P>
<P>
   Franco, who finished tied for third at the Honda Classic last
month, is exalted in his homeland. There are no Paraguayan
reporters here, but the tournament is being televised live in
Asuncion. His wife Celsa and two sons, ages 10 and 8, are ensconced
there, in a two-story, five-bedroom house.
</P>
<P>
   Franco's family is safe and secure, but his country is not. Late
last month, Luis Maria Argana, the vice president of the coalition
government, was assassinated, a sober reminder of just how tough
and tenuous a transition it is from a military dictatorship to a
democracy, even 10 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy because I'm playing golf,'' said Franco, a 1998
member of the international President's Cup team who spent five
years playing on the Japanese tour before coming to the U.S. ``But
when I think of the poor people, I am very concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   In seven PGA Tour starts, Franco has made four cuts and earned
more than $220,000. That's about a hundred times more than his
deceased father made in a year. No question he has earned this
flight of fancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the leaderboard and saw my name and it was a nice
feeling,'' Franco said. ``I feel very confident. I think I can
create something here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
