<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hammerless: Braves shut down by Byrd
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thursday was Kevin Millwood's first night on his new
job as the Braves No. 4 starter, but it was Paul Byrd who had the
bigger point to prove to Atlanta's front office.
</P>
<P>
   The former Brave pitcher, who lost his job with Atlanta last
August, showed his former team a little of what he's been doing
since the Phillies claimed him off waivers last August. With a
little help from Rico Brogna and Scott Rolen, who each had solo
home runs, Byrd beat the Braves 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd held them scoreless through the first six innings before
the Braves started making some offensive noise with a total of
three runs in the sixth and seventh innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies needed four relief pitchers to hold the Braves down
in the eighth inning _ with no help from a pair of fielding errors
_ but did when Jeff Brantley struck out Andruw Jones with the bases
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings in, Brogna took Millwood deep over the wall in left
center, just out of the grasp of a climbing Jones for a 1-0
Phillies lead. It took Millwood three batters to gather himself
before he drew a soft fly ball from Desi Relaford for the second
out.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he had runners at first and second after walking
Bobby Abreu and Mike Lieberthal (Lieberthal after having him 0-2)
and he still wasn't out of the woods. Byrd fought back from 0-2
down to run the count full before Millwood struck him out looking
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood struggled a little bit more with his control in the
next inning but Rolen bailed him out of a runner-at-first, one-out
situation by popping up a 3-0 pitch on the infield. Millwood
retired seven of the next eight hitters before Rolen got a home run
of his own in the sixth inning with a shot to the left-field seats
for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves spotted Millwood 5.1 runs per game on his way to 17
wins last year. Thursday they were struggling for the .1.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, who won five of eight starts after the Phillies claimed
him off waivers from the Braves last August, allowed only three
base runners through the first six innings on two walks and a
Millwood hit.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd was coasting right through the Braves lineup until he faced
Millwood in the third inning. Millwood, who had only four hits last
season, doubled just inside the third-base line. But he was
stranded there when Otis Nixon struck out.
</P>
<P>
   The second Braves baserunner _ Brian Jordan on a walk in the
fourth _ fared no better as Javy Lopez struck out looking at an
off-speed pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
