u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-2NDLD     04-08 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL, AMMUNITION LINES TO YUGOSLAV TROOPS HAVE BEEN CUT, ALLIES
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change ``Joint Chiefs of Staff'' to ``Joint Staff'' in 9th
graf. No other changes.) (See also: KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-ASSESS,
KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-RELIEF,
KOSOVO-VIETNAM, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-GENOCIDE, KOSOVO-CHILDREN) 
(Eds: More to be filed) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT With STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's air campaign has effectively cut fuel and
ammunition supply lines to 40,000 Yugoslav army troops and police
fighting in Kosovo, allied officials said Thursday in providing the
first details of damage to support their claim that the 16-day
bombardment was taking a steep toll.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Pentagon officials noted that Yugoslav armored
forces had stopped maneuvering and were hunkering down, they
conceded that the strategy to starve the Yugoslav war machine might
be too late. The Yugoslav army, they said, may have already
achieved its goal of defeating Kosovo rebels and expelling hundreds
of thousands of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   And after four days of clear weather _ ideal for bombing _ rain
and fog rolled in again Thursday night, forcing several
fighter-bomber missions to turn back to base. Pentagon officials
said the forecast called for bad weather for much of this week.
</P>
<P>
   NATO missions were also complicated by the unexpected return to
Kosovo of huge numbers of ethnic Albanians who were turned back at
the Macedonian and Albanian borders when Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic abruptly closed the borders. Though the
whereabouts of these refugees were not immediately known, NATO
officials acknowledged that they could put new limitations on
targeting.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Thursday that Yugoslav forces were
responsible for killing ``thousands'' of Kosovar Albanians and
creating ``hundreds of thousands of refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, said, ``In 1998
alone, the death toll was 2,000.'' Moreover, he said, ``there are
growing numbers of credible reports of innocent people being killed
in the last two or three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said information on the killings was initially obtained
from monitors of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe and was later supplemented by accounts from refugees and by
``all available means'' of intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   As administration officials sharpened their rhetorical attack on
Milosevic, senior military officers said Thursday that Yugoslavia's
two main oil refineries had been knocked out of operation, and that
the main rail lines and roads leading into the besieged province
had been destroyed or severely damaged. Fuel shortages were
reported throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to see strong evidence of supply problems and
fuel problems plaguing these Yugoslav forces in a number of
different areas and among a number of different units,'' said Rear
Adm. Thomas Wilson, the director of intelligence for the military's
Joint Staff.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO warplanes again flew more than 400 missions, attacking
22 targets across Yugoslavia, including air defenses, fuel depots,
bridges and tanks in the field, allied intelligence reported that
the Yugoslav army was hunkering down, and hiding in abandoned
buildings and forests, curtailing its campaign to drive ethnic
Albanians out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unilateral ceasefire declaration by Milosevic,
Yugoslav forces continued to engage remnants of the Kosovo
Liberation Army. Allied officials said there was evidence that
Yugoslav forces were conducting mop-up operations, particularly in
the northern part of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials said the air campaign would intensify. Defense
Department officials said Thursday that they expected Gen. Wesley
Clark, the NATO military commander, to request at least half a
dozen A-10s and a dozen F-16 ground attack planes, bolstering an
air armada of 600 aircraft already involved.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Defense Secretary William Cohen have said that
whatever requests Clark makes to conduct the air campaign will be
honored. Cohen said Thursday that he was considering a request for
additional F-15E strike fighters, as well as aerial refueling
craft. The fighter can attack with precision weapons from high
altitudes, making it less vulnerable to anti-aircraft fire.
</P>
<P>
   As American officials geared up for a protracted air campaign
that could last several more weeks, lawmakers traveling this week
with Cohen to Brussels, Belgium, and Italy, to meet with NATO
officials and American troops, indicated that the administration
must consider additional measures.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member bipartisan delegation of House and Senate members
intend to send the president a letter on Friday urging him and the
leaders of the other 18 NATO countries to begin at least the
planning for ground troops, said congressional officials.
</P>
<P>
   While political pressure may be building here for considering
ground forces, NATO officials remain adamant that no such option is
under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   As the air campaign entered its 16th day, allied officials here
and in Brussels denied claims by Yugoslav authorities that NATO
bombing had caused widespread damage within Pristina, the
provincial capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters who toured the city as part of a visit arranged by
Yugoslav officials filed reports on Wednesday describing the
damage. But U.S. officers said Thursday that most targets around
Pristina were in lightly populated suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Only two targets in the city itself were hit, a telephone
exchange used by the military and a police headquarters building.
While the officers acknowledge that the bombing might have caused
some damage around the telephone building, they denied the Yugoslav
claims, and said Yugoslav forces were responsible for the
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collateral damage is being done by the Serbs,'' Wilson
told reporters at the Pentagon. ``Towns and villages have been
damaged primarily by fires set by the Yugoslav forces as they've
gone through, as well as by shooting them up with artillery and
tanks and those kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than two weeks of air and missile strikes, Pentagon
and NATO officials say they have inflicted significant damage to
Yugoslavia's armed forces, but Clark said in an interview that many
targets remain, and he vowed to continue striking them.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and NATO have left vague the exact
military objectives of the attack, saying the aim was ``to
degrade'' Yugoslavia's military and paramilitary police forces.
Senior Pentagon officials concede the standard was set so that the
attack could end at virtually any point and be considered to have
met that objective.
</P>
<P>
   Ending the strikes soon, however, could leave Milosevic with a
weakened but functioning military and considerable special police
forces, which he relies on to stay in power.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that
Clark, as well as the leaders of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, wanted
to be able to continue to attack Yugoslav military targets for at
least a couple weeks more, if not longer, particularly since the
initial phases of the operation were hampered by foul weather.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday a senior Pentagon official said the general hoped to
escalate around-the-clock bombing, rather than limiting most of the
air raids to nighttime. The prospect of a significant diplomatic
initiative could force a halt to Clark's plans to escalate the
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   At Aviano Air Base in Italy, the nexus of NATO's air war against
Yugoslavia, Cohen's remarks to troops Thursday clearly underscored
a hardening of the Pentagon's view, leaving little prospect for a
deal with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic, as you all have seen, has carried all of us
into the heart of darkness,'' Cohen told an assembly of pilots and
airmen. ``It is a place where the law of rule drives its heel and
boot over the rule of law and where justice amounts to nothing more
than a bullet in the back of the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, military briefers described in the greatest
detail to date specific targets attacked and estimates on the air
war's effectiveness against certain kinds of targets.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warplanes, for instance, successfully bombed a refinery at
Pancevo that produces nearly two-thirds of Yugoslavia's oil. But
Wilson acknowledged earlier in the week that the Yugoslav troops in
Kosovo had at least a couple of weeks' fuel with them when the air
war started, and while many forces showed signs of running low,
tanks and armored vehicles were not yet stopping in their tracks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
