<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1501 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-KRONE-RETIRE-ART-     04-08 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-KRONE-RETIRE-ART-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE RACING'S TINY GIANT REACHES THE FINISH LINE
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: La., Mich. Texas) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a glance, one might think she's still a
schoolgirl, still the small high school kid who began racing 20
years ago at age 15 on Michigan state and county fair tracks near
her Benton Harbor home, and who grew up to be the best female
jockey ever and, yes, one of the best jockeys, period, of our time.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Krone says that the love of racing, the love of horses,
the love, even, of the barns and stables ``is still in my blood, in
my bones, in my heart.'' But Thursday Julie Krone, now 35 and
married, and who had endured the numerous physical and emotional
joys and hardships of her ``roller-coaster'' profession, as she
termed it, announced that she was retiring as a professional
jockey.
</P>
<P>
   She appeared in the press room of Aqueduct, the little girl
grown into a woman _ still small in size at 4 feet 10{ inches and
100 pounds _ but with the strong hands and, as she proved many
times over a spectacular career, the stout heart of a standout
athlete.
</P>
<P>
   After all, she rode the sleek, half-ton thoroughbreds to 3,500
victories, including the 1993 Belmont Stakes _ the first and only
woman to win a Triple Crown race.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Krone wore a light-blue pants suit, her blond hair was
cut short enough to expose a pair of silver earrings, her blue eyes
were expressive and her smile matched her various moods, from
pensive to playful.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the number of reasons for her decision were as
many as the stars in the sky. ``They'd fill up a constellation,''
she said. But a few reasons were brighter than others. ``I'm 35; I
wanted to go out on top,'' said the woman who recently rode five
winners in one day at the New Orleans Fair Grounds. ``I have
nothing more to prove, and, well, I don't want to get hurt again.''
</P>
<P>
   She is close to $80 million in career earnings. She was the top
money-earning female rider, from 1986 to 1996, with a career high
of $9.1 million in 1992. She was the third-leading rider in the
nation, in regard to races won, in 1989, with 368 victories; and
fourth in 1988 and sixth in 1987. On Aug. 20, 1993, she became only
the third jockey in history to win five races in one day at
Saratoga, joining Angel Cordero and Ron Turcotte.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But racing is hardly all winner's circles and the sweet mists of
the early morning on the backstretch. Krone has been in myriad
spills on the track, perhaps the most serious occurring on Aug. 30,
1993, at Saratoga, closing day at the races there, and just 10 days
after she had scored that sensational five-victory tour. She went
down hard, suffering a severely fractured right ankle, which
required two plates and 14 screws to reconstruct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lying in the hospital bed before my surgery,'' she
recalled, ``when a friend brought in my five-win picture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the ultimate,'' she said. ``It was the very best of
racing, and the very worst of it. It was everything in the world,
and nothing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   She endured several other bad spills, breaking her hands at one
point, and sometimes, for a forgettable period, her spirit.
</P>
<P>
   She had fought through the discrimination of not getting mounts,
and then not getting good mounts, but now she had psychological
problems about being in a race, the pounding for position with
other tough jockeys and determined horses, fighting for the lead,
for the wire.
</P>
<P>
   She used to ride hard on the rail, now she seemed to be avoiding
trouble by sliding to the outside. And then, as she willingly
discusses, she met a psychologist and her therapy sessions with him
helped make her strong again.
</P>
<P>
   She got so involved with psychotherapy that Krone _ a high
school dropout who later earned her degree _ has taken
correspondence courses from Empire State College in Saratoga, a
division of the the State University of New York system. She says
she plans to pursue a Ph.D. in psychology. She also says that money
is no problem with her _ ``I've been earning and saving since I was
17 years old'' _ and that she likes art and television, and may try
her hand at broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also going to spend a little time just sitting on the
grass and looking at the sky,'' she said. ``I think I'm going to
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In mid-February, in the starting gate at the Fair Ground, a
fractious horse she was riding caused her to smash against the iron
side. For the next few days her ankle ``was on fire,'' and her
thoughts of quitting all this because of the pain endured _ and the
creeping fears of more injuries _ made her come to the decision to
end her riding career.
</P>
<P>
   She will ride her last race at Lone Star Park outside Dallas on
April 18, unless she gets a mount for the Kentucky Derby on May 1,
which she doubts.
</P>
<P>
   She was asked if she plans to have children. ``I once heard
Katherine Hepburn say that there should always be a little
mystery,'' said Krone, with a smile. ``So I'll leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the her place in history, she said that there were
moments of deep gratification for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most rewarding moments,'' she said, ``have been when
little girls, 10 and 11 years old, would run up to me and say
things like, `I played soccer with the boys and I was the best
goalkeeper out there.' This has happened hundreds of times. They'd
say that they read about me in a newspaper or magazine, or saw an
interview on television, and that they admired what I had
accomplished and how I had overcome adversity. If I had made even a
little difference with girls like that, if I had made some little
girl more brave than she had been, then that's what's been
important for me as far as being a female athlete is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after her news conference, Julie Krone left Aqueduct,
not on a horse but in an automobile, riding off happily, if a bit
wistfully, into the sunset.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
