<HEADLINE>
F-16 FIGHTER ENGINES CRACKED: SERIOUS FLAW FOUND IN 17 LUKE AFB
JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BARRETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENX _ An inspection of jets at Luke Air Force Base has
revealed cracks in at least 17 engines, a discovery that may point
to the cause of a recent Arizona crash that led to the grounding of
400 F-16s nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. John Barry, the base commander, told ``The Arizona
Republic'' that the cracks were not discovered in previous
maintenance checks because the base did not have the equipment to
detect them.
</P>
<P>
   Since the March 26 crash, maintenance crews have found cracks up
to an inch long in the augmentor ducts of 17 engines. About 50 of
Luke's 200 jets have not yet been inspected.
</P>
<P>
   An augmentor duct helps provide thrust for the engine by forcing
air out of the engine's nozzle. Barry said the cracked ducts have
the potential to cause a crash and were pulled from the engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty concerned about it, obviously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Five F-16s from Luke have crashed in the past six months _ three
in the Valley and two near Gila Bend _ at a cost of about $20
million each. One was caused by pilot error, but initial reports
indicate the rest were caused by engine problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ After the March crash, Air Force officials grounded 400
fighter jets nationwide that use the Pratt and Whitney 220 engine
involved in the Arizona crashes. Half of the grounded planes are at
the Glendale base.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 500 maintenance and support personnel have been trading
off eight-hour shifts day and night to inspect the grounded planes.
The Pentagon also sent five inspectors and provided new inspection
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Using an enhanced dye and blacklight provided by the Pentagon,
maintenance inspectors were able to spot hairline fractures in 17
of the Pratt and Whitney 220 augmentor ducts.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Burris, director of communications for Pratt and Whitney,
said his company also has sent inspectors to Luke, but he added
that many of the augmentor ducts were delivered in 1991 or earlier
and some use technology developed more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Luke's planes represent nearly one-fifth of all aircraft using
the Pratt and Whitney 220 engine. Although all F-16 aircraft are
manufactured by Lockheed Martin, the engines and some components
are made by both Pratt and Whitney and General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Burris defended his company's engine, saying that before a Luke
fighter jet crashed in December, it had been nearly two years since
the model 220 had been blamed for an accident. None of the F-16s
using the 220 engine is flying in the NATO mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Barry has requested more money from the Pentagon to replace the
ducts and other engine parts cited by crash investigators.
Officials also have singled out problems with the engine turbines
and fan blades.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barry wouldn't give the exact cost of replacing those parts,
but it would be in the tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., is backing the funding request. If
approved, it could mean more money for parts within the next few
months, as well as an additional lump sum in the 1999-2000 fiscal
year, which begins in October.
</P>
<P>
   Those funds would be in addition to the $225 million allocated
in the 1999-2000 budget to pay for spare parts for engines and the
$257 million Air Force officials asked for earlier this year for
spare engines.
</P>
<P>
   While the base waits to learn whether it will receive the funds,
Barry is allowing a limited number of the jets back in the air
after they have passed a grueling inspection.
</P>
<P>
   The Glendale base began flying 90 daily sorties Monday _ about
half the normal number. Barry does not expect the base to resume a
full training schedule until July.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen jets that use a newer engine model began flying a
few days after the most recent crash.
</P>
<P>
   Luke already had boosted maintenance checks, as well as the
criteria for passing inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Barry said personnel at the base have done ``everything humanly
possible,'' but he acknowledges that may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only manage risks with inspections to a point, and then
no more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When training resumed Monday, Barry was the first pilot to fly a
sortie. &QL; 
Jennifer Barrett can be reached at (602) 444-7113 or at
jennifer.barrett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
