<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-BUSINESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JUDGING MILSTEIN'S MILLIONS, AND HIS MANNER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORKK _ Howard Milstein will not say if he is frustrated or
incensed at the NFL for erecting the obstacles that forced him to
withdraw his application to buy the Washington Redskins for $803
million.
</P>
<P>
   He will not say if he feels the league's finance committee
judged him solely by the financing plan that he was told contained
too much bank debt and too little cash _ or by his character.
</P>
<P>
   He will not say if the league compelled him to get out by
forcing him to make so many changes to his financing you would have
thought he was providing a bailout loan for the government of
Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   And he will not say if facing approval by the NFL was like going
before the ultimate co-op board, which can spurn you if it doesn't
like your shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very simple,'' Milstein said Thursday by telephone, one
day after he, his brother, Edward, and Daniel Snyder, a Bethesda,
Md., businessman, bowed out of the bidding for the Redskins when
faced with certain rejection. ``If you play in the big leagues, be
prepared for big wins and big losses.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm disappointed. We thought we presented the
strongest possible financial structure.'' He insisted that he did
not have to be persuaded to withdraw. ``I'm not a quitter,'' he
said. ``I'm resourceful. I can get across the goal line. But I was
not prepared to go down a path where the fans and team would be
hurt by a controversy that would paralyze the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing his bid was doomed, Milstein may have relished suing the
league. But the prospect of a tumultuous and nasty federal lawsuit
ended when the league assumed responsibility for recouping the $30
million that Milstein paid the estate of Jack Kent Cooke when his
group agreed to buy the team on Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   What remains a mystery is why the league objected so much to
Milstein's initial bank financing plan for the Redskins, which was
identical to what he proposed to buy the the expansion Cleveland
Browns last year. The league knew plenty about the Milstein
financial empire and his proposed bank financing.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL thought he was worthy enough to proceed to the Final
Jeopardy round of Browns bidding and got him to provide a $45
million letter of credit, or 10 percent of his $450 million offer.
Had he bid $550 million _ $20 million more than the winner Al
Lerner bid _ would Milstein's money have looked as green?
</P>
<P>
   Was his money right then but wrong now? To satisfy the league,
Milstein made the financing of the Redskins strong enough so that a
$125 million loan from his father carried no interest and would
have insulated him, the team and Jack Kent Cooke Stadium from a
lawsuit if it were not paid after 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   League concerns over the the liquidity of Milstein's real estate
assets never told the full story. Was he the wrong millionaire? Was
he too headstrong, too political? Had he made mortal enemies during
the Browns' auction?
</P>
<P>
   Or was he not one of the NFL family, having no ally but the
Cooke estate? The league failed to get the Cooke estate to show it
a $680 million bid from John Kent Cooke, the late owner's son. The
estate said no. Why seek out a much lower bid? Cooke is a known
quantity, an under-the-radar club member.
</P>
<P>
   Funny. Milstein did not rule out trying to break into the NFL
elite again. ``You never know what tomorrow brings,'' he said. But
he might be better off learning how to become a quarterback and
become a top draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   How many tomorrows the Milstein family will share with the
Islanders, whom they bought in February 1998, is uncertain. The
legal and on-ice miseries of the Islanders under the ownership of
the Milsteins and Steve Gluckstern served as a negative model for
some owners of how he might run the Redskins. That Gluckstern has
been a NHL governor is irrelevant; only Milstein was buying the
Skins.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, they want out of the Islanders. Buyers may be in short
supply without a new arena to replace Nassau Coliseum in sight.
Clearly, Milstein thought he'd get one when he bought in. Although
selling may be a mere formality to end this saga, Milstein would
not reveal what his get-out-of-Uniondale strategy is.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should call my brother,'' he said. Recently, Howard
transferred his part of their 45 percent stake in the team to
Edward.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Milstein did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
