<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA TRACES LINK SUSPECT TO 17 RAPES, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ DNA evidence has linked a Bronx man to 17 rapes in
the Bronx, upper Manhattan and Westchester County, police officials
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The police believe that Issac Jones, 34, was responsible for
raping or robbing as many as 51 women at gunpoint in 39 attacks
since 1993, the largest rape pattern in recent memory. The victims
ranged in age from 13 to 53, and in some cases several women were
attacked at once. In one case, the police said, a woman was raped
in front of her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was ordered held without bail on Thursday after he was
arraigned in Bronx Criminal Court on four counts of rape and
charges of burglary, robbery, menacing, possession of stolen
property and weapons possession.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was arrested on Tuesday afternoon when he and his
girlfriend went to a Bronx pawnshop to try to sell some jewelry he
is accused of stealing from a victim, the first deputy police
commissioner, Patrick E. Kelleher, said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As he was being interrogated, police officials said, Jones
confessed to raping four women, and he was arrested. But the police
also took a DNA sample from Jones to see whether it matched DNA
evidence that was recovered at the scenes of 17 attacks.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Kelleher said, the test results came back positive.
``In each of the 17 DNA samples,'' he said, ``we found a match to
that of Issac Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   More charges will probably be filed against Jones based on the
DNA evidence after a grand jury hears his case, police officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The four counts of rape Jones was charged with yesterday stem
from three attacks that took place in the Bronx in 1994, 1997 and
1998, according to the criminal complaint. In the last attack of
the three, the complaint charges, he raped two women after he broke
into their basement apartment, pointed a handgun at them and robbed
them of cash and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who worked as a floor polisher at the General Motors
Building in midtown Manhattan, lived in a basement apartment at
2001 Story Avenue in the Bronx with his girlfriend, the police
said. He was previously convicted of sodomy in 1983 and robbery in
1989, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rapes began in 1993, the police did not recognize a
pattern until 1997, police officials said. Then they began working
backward, adding cases that fit the pattern: rapes that took place
after midnight in certain neighborhoods by a man wearing a mask and
armed with a handgun. When they compared the DNA evidence collected
at the scenes, they had further confirmation that the attacks were
linked.
</P>
<P>
   The last attack took place early on Feb. 14 in the Washington
Heights section of Manhattan, when two women were raped in their
apartment building minutes after they were dropped off at the front
door by their boyfriends in a taxi cab, the police said. Several
pieces of jewelry were stolen in that attack.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives distributed pictures of the jewelry around the city,
and began to focus on two shops that sold similar jewelry. Then,
for seven weeks, they conducted surveillance outside the shops from
7 a.m. to 7 p.m., six days a week. On Tuesday afternoon, the police
said, Jones was picked up after he and his girlfriend showed up at
one shop, in the Bronx, to sell some of the jewelry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
