<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WHITMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WHITMAN LOOKS TO THE SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, April 9:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey is planning to run for the
Senate in 2000. Her announcement that she is setting up a
fund-raising committee is as positive a declaration of candidacy as
is seemly from a sitting governor who must convince voters she
intends to stay focused on the state's business for the next year
and a half.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of adding a Republican woman of Whitman's stature to
the Senate will excite many people, and to the rest of the nation
she probably seems an odds-on favorite. She defeated the incumbent,
Jim Florio, in 1993 and presided over a growing New Jersey economy.
Like her neighbor, George Pataki of New York, she has identified
herself with two popular issues _ tax cuts and environmental
protection. Right now the leading Democratic candidate is Florio,
who left office identified with tax hikes, a concept that elicits
something less than universal enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman's entry does not mean she is an automatic winner.
New Jersey has not elected a Republican senator since 1972, and the
state seems to have trended Democratic in recent years. Whitman
herself has never gotten more than 49 percent in any state
election, including her surprisingly weak showing against State
Sen. James McGreevey in the last gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   A contest between Whitman, one of a large crop of successful
Republican governors, and Florio, who had to run the state in far
less prosperous times, would make for interesting debates. But some
Democratic leaders, still smarting from the fact that Florio's tax
plan cost their party control of the state legislature, are hunting
for another candidate. Others worry that a primary would leave any
Democratic nominee in a weakened condition to run against Whitman,
but that is not necessarily true. The winner of a primary often
simply comes out looking like a winner.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem on everyone's mind is, as usual, campaign
funds. A tough Senate race is expected to cost more than $10
million. Whitman's fund-raising drive is going to be led by Lewis
Eisenberg, who has already been rewarded for past money-raising
efforts on her behalf with the post of chairman of the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey. The Port Authority is a
troubled organization, and Eisenberg might do better to hand over
his job to someone else who does not have to worry about the state
of Whitman's war chest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
