<SLUG> BC-SOAP-OPERA-CHANNEL-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC PLANS A 24-HOUR SOAP HOUR CABLE CHANNEL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Texas)  (rk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the second move this week that pitted the
interests of a broadcast network against those of its affiliated
stations, ABC announced Thursday that it would create a 24-hour
soap opera cable channel. The decision means that for the first
time in broadcast history, a network's entertainment programs will
be repeated on a different channel in the same day.
</P>
<P>
   The affiliates opposed the channel, saying its reliance on
repeats of ABC's four daytime soap operas would undercut their
exclusive rights to ABC programming. They said the channel could
also have an impact on the ratings of both the original broadcasts
of the programs during the day and on some of the ABC programs that
will compete with the soap opera channel in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by ABC, which is owned by the Walt Disney Co., came
one day after the Fox network unilaterally reclaimed more than 20
percent of the prime-time commercials formerly controlled by its
affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the decisions by ABC and Fox represent what Pat
Fili-Krushel, the president of ABC, called ``a message that the
network business has to change.'' Struggling to be profitable, the
broadcast networks are seeking to reorganize their relationships
with the local stations, many of which are extremely successful.
</P>
<P>
   Networks have previously placed repeats of programs they own on
cable channels that they also own. NBC, for example, uses repeats
of its ``Dateline: NBC'' on its MSNBC channel. But no network has
decided to reuse entertainment programs in this way before.
</P>
<P>
   David Barrett, the head of the ABC affiliate board, and the
executive vice president of Hearst-Argyle Television, the largest
owner of ABC-affiliated stations, said the affiliates had been
prepared to accept ``some measure of the repurposing of ABC
programs'' in negotiations with the network. ``But those talks
ended last week,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Just over a week ago, ABC broke off negotiations for a
comprehensive new agreement that would have provided ABC with
financial help from the affiliates for its expensive rights fees
for NFL games, in exchange for some specific terms on when ABC
programs might be used on other channels.
</P>
<P>
   In that deal ABC had offered the affiliates a financial
participation in the soap channel. But the affiliate board refused
the offer, mainly because ABC sought the right to match any change
in the network-affiliate relationship that one of the other
networks put into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fili-Krushel said that the affiliates had been informed that
ABC would go ahead with plans for the soap channel without them. It
did so Thursday. ABC executives have also said they will now seek
deals both on program exclusivity and NFL rights with affiliates on
a case-by case basis.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said that affiliates had anticipated the ABC move. ``It
was no surprise'' he said, ``I don't rule out still accomplishing
the goal of working out a comprehensive agreement with ABC, though
Michael Eisner might not agree with that optimism.'' Eisner is the
chairman of Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ABC plans to start up the channel, which has yet to be named, in
January 2000. Anne Sweeney, the president of Disney/ABC cable
networks, said she hoped the new channel could achieve the same
initial distribution level the company reached when it began the
Toon Disney channel last year, 5 million cable homes. That channel
now reaches 12 million homes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC conceived the channel as a way to draw additional revenues
for its soap operas, which are expensive to produce and are not
repeated. Ms. Sweeney said the network had taken note of the
cultural changes that have affected the largely female soap opera
fan base, with many more women now working outside the home.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The network conducted tests of the channel last year in two
cities, Houston and Chicago and Ms. Sweeney said the network was
encouraged by the results. She said they showed overall increases
in interest in the soap operas when viewers could see episodes they
had missed the same night.
</P>
<P>
   But other ABC executives acknowledged that the tests did show
some cannibalization of the audience for the daytime broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said he doubted that any ABC affiliates would react by
pre-empting the ABC soap operas on their channel ``at least in the
short term.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sweeney said that ABC was in a singular position to create a
soap opera channel because it owns all four of its daytime soaps,
``General Hospital,'' One Life to Live,'' ``All My Children'' and
``Port Charles.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
