<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS EXCITED ABOUT FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Williams _ remember him? _ is on the line, and the 1990
graduate of Long Beach Poly High and 26-year-old professional
heavyweight boxer is oozing with enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just so great and exciting for my career,'' says
Williams, who earlier this week signed to fight the fearsome Ike
Ibeabuchi for $150,000 on June 19 in a HBO televised match that
will be a co-feature with Michael Grant and Lou Severese either at
Madison Square Garden in New York or in Atlantic City. ``After I
beat Ibeabuchi, I'm going to be destined for some very high-paying
fights. And I will beat this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what?
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Williams will beat Ike Ibeabuchi, the lethal-punching
Nigerian who recently dealt Chris Byrd his first loss by stopping
him in five rounds and also conqueror of another Top 10 fighter,
David Tua, the chiseled 240-pounder who's being heralded as another
Sonny Liston?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, and Slobodan Milosevic is on the verge of being named
commanding general of the NATO forces and Bill Clinton is a role
model for connubial bliss and I soon will purchase a chopped-up
Harley and join up with the ``Hell's Angels'' after festooning my
anatomy with ``Born To Raise Hell'' tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Jeremy Williams possesses fistic skills and a potent
punch he has a 34-2 record with 31 knockouts but his chin has come
under severe scrutiny since it betrayed him terribly one sweltering
summer evening three years ago in Indio when it failed to withstand
a withering right hand launched by Henry Akinwande.
</P>
<P>
   Since suffering that unfortunate knockout, Williams has fought
infrequently and stayed in the shadows of his sport, scoring a few
victories over nondescript opponents and shifting his promotional
allegiance from Dan Goossen's America Presents to Dino Duva's Main
Events.
</P>
<P>
   His name recently appeared often in articles in the New York
newspapers before the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis fight because
he served as Lewis' top sparring partner for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Lewis people first called me, I said, `No way. I'm no
sparring partner,''' recalls Williams. ``But then I got to thinking
how Larry Holmes, who later would become a great heavyweight
champion, sparred with Muhammad Ali before the `Rumble in the
Jungle' fight with George Foreman. So I decided to do it to find
out how I'd fare against someone like Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   According to all reports, including ones not as biased as the
one given by Williams, he handled himself well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox Lewis hit me right on the button with two of his best
right hands and I did not go down,'' relates Williams. ``He sparred
with me like he fought Holyfield throwing a few punches and then
grabbing and holding. I actually got mad at his tactics a few times
and threw him to the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I did the sparring with Lennox. What it has done for
me is give me the confidence that I can hold my own against anyone.
Let's face it, Lennox Lewis beat Evander Holyfield, and he's the
true heavyweight champion. I wasn't scared of him when I sparred
with him, and I know I did pretty well. Why should I be scared of
Ike Ibeabuchi?''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Williams won't be scared, but this will be the first time
in his professional career when he enters the ring with no one
expecting him to emerge victorious.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people don't realize is that I'm a much better fighter
now than I was three, four years ago when I still was going through
the adjustment of going from being a light heavyweight to a
heavyweight,'' says Williams, who says he now weighs 220. ``I also
was younger and more immature and thought I knew everything. I
always had a good offense, but I never had a defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``My new trainer, Ronnie Shields, who has trained Evander
Holyfield and Meldrick Taylor, has taught me so much about defense,
about rolling my shoulders with the punches, about feinting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Ike Ibeabuchi is unbeatable. Who's he beaten in
his career? Chris Byrd? Good fighter, can't break an egg. David
Tua? He only has one punch a left hook. That's all. All you have to
do to beat David Tua is keep your right hand up high to block his
hooks. He can't move a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going down to Vero Beach, Florida next week, and train for
eight weeks. Remember, I trained one day for Henry Akinwande. That
was all. I'm going to surprise a lot of people in this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jeremy Williams wins, he will. ...
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's silly macho credo don't dare lend a hand to an
opposing player when he seeks a foul popup on the lip of your
dugout was responsible for Mo Vaughn winding up with a badly
sprained left ankle the other night against Cleveland. At least one
Indian player could have stood up and kept Vaughn from tripping
over the steps and into the dugout. But everyone on the Cleveland
team remained seated when Vaughn took his tumble, even though it
could have resulted in Vaughn enduring a far more serious injury
like a broken leg, or ravaged knee than he did. This is one sacred
rite the baseball players should scuttle. ...
</P>
<P>
   I sometimes wonder if Kurt Rambis actually knows what he's
doing. ...
</P>
<P>
   The cruelest emotion is rejection, and now Dennis Rodman at
least will have a valid excuse for his bizarre behavior in the wake
of his getting dumped by Carmen Electra. ...
</P>
<P>
   Is George Steinbrenner aware that Don Zimmer made some of the
dumbest strategic moves in baseball history during his failed days
as a manager? Zim's a nice old guy, but Bobby Cox is a tactical
genius next to him ...
</P>
<P>
   I always thought men were the only miscreants who made fools of
themselves by talking shop into their cell phones at the bar, but I
actually saw a lady doing this insufferably phony bit the other
night at a joint on Pine Ave. ...
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Pine Ave., its two-fisted pioneer, John (Don't Tread
On Me) Morris, is expecting a galaxy of celebrities, including
David Letterman, to show up at Mum's during next weekend's Toyota
Grand Prix of Long Beach. ...
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, I'm reading Emile Zola's ``The Debacle.'' It's
about the 1870 Franco-Prussian war, and not about the war NATO is
now conducting against the Serbs in Yugoslavia. ...
</P>
<P>
   My old pal Larry (Smiley) Kahn is doing a bang-up job on the
Angel pre- and post-game shows on KLAC (570 AM). When are the
Angels going to let Kahn do some play-by-play, which he does best?
...
</P>
<P>
   I have to laugh when they say Dusty Baker does it with mirrors
in San Francisco. No doubt Baker is one of the best managers in
baseball, but he does happen to have a fellow on his team named
Barry Bonds. ...
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Williams, a film patron, tells me he yells, ``Shut the
(expletive deleted) up!'' when some loudmouth is talking
incessantly in a movie theatre. I'd like to do the same, but
Williams is slightly more equipped to back up his threatening words
than I am. ...
</P>
<P>
   Who's more overweight, Shaquille O'Neal or Mo Vaughn? ...
</P>
<P>
   I'm afraid to phone my pal of 31 years, Jerry West, these days.
If it's painful for me to watch the Lakers' bumbling antics, how do
you think a perfectionist like West is taking it? ...
</P>
<P>
   It's so reassuring to know that people in the Balkans are now
being killed to save them from death. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
