<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMERON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-SCHOOL CANCER VICTIM'S PALS FIGHT TO MAKE SCHOOL LET HIM
GRADUATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LORI BAKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Ariz. _ Cameron Schmidt, who has battled cancer to
come within three credits of earning his high school degree, now is
fighting for the right to walk with his classmates at their
graduation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Mountain Ridge High School in Glendale say they
won't bend the rules to let him do so. No diploma, no commencement,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   But friends are backing Schmidt. Some of his classmates have
said they won't take part in the ceremony if he can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schmidt Walks'' is the demand on petitions signed by more than
700 Mountain Ridge students.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan also is inscribed on T-shirts being worn by many
students today (April 9) at school. It's also being circulated on
fliers, in letters and in e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   Principal Connie Harris told Schmidt, 18, that he can't walk
with the other 526 seniors in the May 20 ceremony because he's
three credits shy of the 22-credit requirement to graduate in the
Deer Valley Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known many of these kids for the past four to seven years
and to be able to walk with them would mean the world to me,''
Schmidt said. ``I've felt like an outcast for the past couple years
because of my cancer. To be able to be a part of this graduation
ceremony will make me feel like a normal kid again.''
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman, Schmidt had a B-plus average and was on the
basketball and football teams. In the middle of his sophomore year,
he fell ill and was diagnosed with Hodgkin's disease, a potentially
fatal form of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He worked to keep his studies up while recuperating from a bone
marrow transplant, chemotherapy and radiation treatments. He's
maintained a B average by studying at home and taking some classes
at school.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't able to earn credits fast enough to graduate with
the Class of '99.
</P>
<P>
   Harris wouldn't discuss Schmidt's particular case, which is is
being appealed to the district's Governing Board. But she said his
request is not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several students each year who lack the credits but
want to walk with their class,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, girls who have left school early because of a
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan Stefan, a Mountain Ridge student who has known Schmidt
since the fifth grade, said his friend's situation is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school district says, `Where do we draw the line?' '' he
said. ``If a girl gets pregnant, she was responsible for that. It's
not Cameron's fault that he got cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, who hopes to be a marine biologist or firefighter, has
been cancer-free for 10 months. His hair is growing back and his
strength is increasing.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't expect to get a diploma until he earns the rest of
his credits in the fall, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His father pleaded with Deer Valley board members March 23 to
let his son go through commencement.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Deer Valley administrators nor board members have
responded to his request. Next week, Schmidt and many of his
friends will ask the board again.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Susan Burke, who is chief of the state's Office for
Children With Special Health Care Needs, said she will support
Schmidt if the board votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deal with very sick kids all the time, so I know what
Cameron has been going through,'' she said. ``I think it's a
reasonable request to let Cameron walk with his friends. When you
have rules, you have to consider extenuating circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Board Vice President Richard Eng said he also would vote to
allow Schmidt to walk. But fellow members David Cantelme and Joan
Bennett worry about setting a precedent. Board President Ted
Carpenter could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Valley administrators plan to meet next week to find out
whether other students are in a similar situation and to discuss
whether exceptions to the policy should be made.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt hopes his friends won't have to decide whether to
boycott the ceremony because of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anyone to miss out on a once-in-a-lifetime
event,'' he said. ``I understand they want to make a point.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Robbins, a senior who said she wouldn't go to
commencement if Schmidt can't, said that allowing him to take part
in the ceremony is the humane thing to do. &QL; 
Lori Baker can be reached at (602) 444-7120 or at
lori.baker(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
