<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE HEAVEN FOR TV FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER 
Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're around the age of 40 or older, then you remember a
time when Walter O'Malley held as a tight a fist on Dodger
television exposure as Slobodan Milosevic holds on Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dodgers' first years here, the only games televised were
road games at San Francisco. In the early '60s, the schedule was
expanded to include games with pennant race implications. In the
'70s, the Dodgers flirted with televising home games for the first
time on a subscription TV service known as ON TV. And as cable
exploded in the '80s, the team eventually expanded their road
schedule to 75 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in year two of Fox's stewardship of the team, you can't
turn on a television set without seeing the Dodgers. They're on the
tube as often as that insidious Tae Bo infomercial.
</P>
<P>
   By seasons' end, at least 149 Dodgers games will be televised in
1999, including at least 75 of their 81 home games. The menu: 80
games on Fox Sports West 2 (52 home, 28 away); 50 games on KTLA (16
home, 34 away); three ESPN national appearances (two home, one
away); and eight Fox Saturday telecasts (five home, three away).
</P>
<P>
   There are also four games which might be carried on ESPN's
non-exclusive Wednesday package, and four Saturday dates in
September that Fox may air depending on the pennant races. There
are also five Sunday evening games that could find their way on air
depending on changes in ESPN's Sunday night schedule.
</P>
<P>
   About the only games you can definitely scratch off your TV
calendar are five midweek day road games and two Tuesday road games
in April. Otherwise, it's Dodger Blue Heaven for those attached to
their couch.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that was presumably losing money in the last years of
the O'Malley era and has since blown its payroll into the
stratosphere, the increased viewing seems a strange byproduct. On
the day the Dodgers gave Kevin Brown baseball's first $100 million
contract, Dodger President Bob Graziano said the team needs to grow
its attendance well beyond the comfortable 3 million, to 4 million.
</P>
<P>
   It seems odd on the surface to think the Dodgers can put that
many fans in seats when the product is being given away on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano says it's a matter of marketing two separate items.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely diverging from the past,'' he said, ``but
things are so different now than they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at attending games and watching them as two different
experiences. We want to create an experience for those coming to
the games that you can't get from the living room, create a sense
that fans who watch at home are missing something by not coming to
the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we've found that televising a game early in a
homestand gets people interested in coming out to a game later in
the homestand. We have so many promotions this year that any night
at the park is going to give the fan something new to think about
or take home.''
</P>
<P>
   Those promotions this year run from the usual, Hollywood Stars
Night and cap day, to the current bean bear promotion the first
week, plus a few postgame concerts and a Brooklyn Dodger cap
giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much is driven by television these days,'' said Brent
Shyer, the Dodgers' director of broadcasting and media relations.
``That's the biggest change from Peter (O'Malley) to the Fox Group.
They bought the team in part because of the TV inventory, and they
know its value.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers are as successful all season as they have been
the first week of 1999, the TV exposure could launch more fans to
the park and perhaps even create some new ones. If not, then fans
will watch other teams chase playoff spots, if they watch at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are hardly the one baseball team trying to make this
dual experience work. Most teams now televise 100 or more games a
season through some combination of over-the-air networks (like
KTLA) and cable (FSW2).
</P>
<P>
   In year two of Disney's operation of the Angels, the Orange
County team will be on television at least 110 times. The Angels
will televise 50 games on Fox Sports West (46 home, 4 away) and
another 50 on KCAL (six home, 44 away). There will also be four
exposures on ESPN's national package and six Saturday games on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels could wind up appearing another four times on Fox in
September and as many as eight times on ESPN's non-exclusive
Wednesday package.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of success is to obviously put a winner on the field
and hope everything grows together. And in today's baseball
environment, where teams can be built up or torn down in a matter
of months (i.e., Florida Marlins, San Diego Padres), the hope for a
winner is never too far away.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's certain: We'll know if the theory works simply by
tuning into the wall-to-wall TV coverage and seeing if there are
fans in the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW THE NEWS (AND SOME GOSSIP):
</P>
<P>
   CBS televises the Masters for the 44th consecutive year, meaning
more verbal linguistics by Jim Nantz
</P>
<P>
   and crew to paint the prettiest picture possible of Augusta
National. Consider the downside of gentle analogies and the
avoidance of anything controversial the price you pay for only four
minutes of ads per hour, the only tradition at Augusta worth
embracing. Saturday's third round airs at 12:30 p.m., and Sunday's
finale at 1 p.m. ... NBC's steady NBA diet LAKERS LAKERS LAKERS!!
continues Sunday with the Lakers-Seattle game on at 3 p.m., the
second half of a doubleheader which will send Houston-Utah here at
12:30 p.m. Through 18 telecasts, NBC is earning a 4.5 Nielsen for
the NBA, slightly down from last season's Jordan-enhanced rating of
4.6. Part of NBC's success has come from airing more games into
prime time, when viewing usage is higher. ... In a clearly paranoid
reaction to Fox Sports News' increasing national profile, ESPN has
launched a new 10 p.m. PST version of SportsCenter to run opposite
Fox Sports News. ESPN will still air a separate 11 p.m.
SportsCenter. ESPN hopes to keep looky-loo sports fans from jumping
around the dial and getting lost on some other network. Fox Sports
West took a Nielsen quickie survey Tuesday, the night ESPN's 10
p.m. debuted, and beat it 1.69 to 0.21 ... NBC has re-signed former
NFL coach Joe Gibbs
</P>
<P>
   as an analyst but not for football. He'll be an analyst on a
NASCAR event later this year ... ESPN will debut an enhanced
version of Bat Track (the speed of a swinging bat) Sunday (5 p.m.)
when the Angels visit Texas ... Irv Kaze
</P>
<P>
   's KIEV talk show Saturday (5 p.m.) features Long Beach Grand
Prix majordomo Chris Pook
</P>
<P>
   ... Veteran sports talkers Fred Wallin
</P>
<P>
   and Peter Vent
</P>
<P>
   are in negotiations to start their own sports talk show on an
as-yet named station ... Congratulations to Newy Scruggs
</P>
<P>
   and Dave Denholm
</P>
<P>
   , KXTA's drive time hosts, on being named best talk show hosts
in Cleveland. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
