<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: POLICE POLITESSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, April 9:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's effort to create a more polite police
force deserves less of the sophisticated cynicism that we enjoy so
much in New York City and more celebration about the civilizing
possibilities. As Dennis Walcott of the New York Urban League has
been saying for some time, good police manners could do for
community relations what fixing broken windows does for crime
rates. Just as mending windows and pursuing small infractions
appears to keep down serious crime, so small courtesies between
police and public might yield better community relations on a
deeper level.
</P>
<P>
   New York's sharp-tongued mayor, whose pleas last year for a more
civil city provoked as much parody as praise, predicted the same
dismissive reaction this week as he passed out new palm cards on
manners to the police. The cards order officers to address each
person as ``,'' ``Ms.,'' ``sir'' or ``ma'am.'' The reminder tells
officers to ``respect each individual'' and ``his or her cultural
identity'' and requires police to explain courteously what they are
doing and apologize for inconvenience. The police are still there
to catch criminals, of course, but they should not leave a
community seething.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has also suggested that citizens should be polite to
police. That's fine, except for his oddly excessive idea that the
public should address an officer by rank. What mere civilian could
be expected to know which rank gets the gold leaf or who wears the
gold eagle? In such stressful situations, a simple ``officer''
should do.
</P>
<P>
   Since the police shooting of an unarmed West African in
February, residents in minority neighborhoods have made it clear
that they need more humane law enforcement. The mayor and Police
Commissioner Howard Safir have launched reforms in training and
recruitment and have revamped the Street Crime Unit. By contrast, a
few thank-you's may look like sugar dusting from on high. Still, as
long as it is not a substitute for the hard repair work that is
needed, a little more street diplomacy couldn't hurt.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-08-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
